<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-CLAUS-FUNERAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRESIDENTIAL SANTA' GETS LOVING TRIBUTE FROM CELEBRITY MOURNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Robert George, Santa Claus to eight presidents,
was remembered at his funeral by family and friends -- including
Pat Boone, Casey Kasem and former President Carter -- as a man
utterly devoted to the role he played for nearly 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   George, a suburban Sun Valley resident, began acting as a
full-time Santa in 1949 in Nebraska and was first appointed
Presidential Santa in 1956 by President Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he also distributed toys with Los Angeles
firefighters. At his funeral, a contingent of Fire Department
officials honored his work by serving as pallbearers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Wolfgang Krismanits of Sonora, Calif., who met George
in 1995, said that although he ``sat with so many presidents . . .
the people he really loved were the children.''
</P>
<P>
   A nephew, Larry George, recalled seeing his uncle in action once
in the San Francisco Bay Area. ``There was no one that wasn't
doubled over with laughter by the time they got off that sleigh,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   George died July 1 at a doctor's office in suburban Burbank. He
was 74 and had been suffering from health problems tied to heart
disease and diabetes, said his wife, Stella.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's home has been decorated year-round with Christmas
decorations -- a habit that had created a dispute with neighbors
and city officials when the Georges lived in suburban Glendale in
the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But Boone and the other approximately 125 people attending the
morning funeral at the Church on the Way in suburban Van Nuys
remembered George especially for his generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few days, the Lord has called Roy Rogers and Santa
Claus to heaven,'' Boone told the mourners. ``There's something
going on up there,'' he added, to laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Boone said he saw a television news story a few ago about George
being hospitalized in Burbank after a heart attack. He went to see
George, who he didn't know, and invited him to join his church, the
Church on the Way.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Robert and Stella George became front-row fixtures
at the church's 9 a.m. Sunday service.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just brought joy to our lives,'' said Boone. He later
sang a hymn, joined by mourners, some of whom closed their eyes and
stretched their arms upward.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, a congregant at the church, Rick Segall, sang ``Have
Yourself a Merry Little Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gary Abke read a condolence letter he said Stella
George received from former President Carter, the president with
whom Robert George became closest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rosalynn and I and our entire family are deeply saddened.''
Carter wrote. ``We cherish the relationship we have shared with
Santa.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview outside the church, radio personality Kasem said
he'd known George since the early 1980s, when he featured him on a
television show called ``The Top 10 Christmas Hits of All Time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody could be more devoted,'' Kasem said. ``There's an old
saying that service to others is the rent we pay for a room in
heaven. Robert deserves a suite.''
</P>
<P>
   George was buried at San Fernando Mission Cemetery in suburban
Mission Hills.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
