<HEADER>
A4806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     07-08 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, July 8.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ The International Monetary Fund and the
Yeltsin government are negotiating an aid package that may produce
less money than foreign investors say is needed to help ease
Russia's financial crisis. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ASSESS (Undated) _ With the abrupt death Tuesday of
Nigeria's most prominent civilian politician, Moshood K.O. Abiola,
Nigeria has suddenly lost in the space of only one month the two
leaders whose rivalry has locked this country in a costly four-year
stalemate. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-MISSING (New York) _ An investigation into the disappearance
of the owner of an opulent Upper East Side townhouse has led the
police to two unusual suspects: a mother-and-son con artist team
that is also being questioned in the recent murder of a wealthy
86-year-old man from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES-FIGHTING (Washington) _ Forest fires can be pinpointed
by satellite now, and broadcast nationwide by cable television, but
fighting them is still the same as it has been for half a century,
with shovel and chainsaw, clearing all possible fuel away from a
fire break, and praying for rain. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SURPLUS (Sacramento) _ After years of battling over budget
shortfalls, the California legislature has found that it is just as
painful to fight about a budget surplus. Republicans want to cut
the high costs of car registration; Democrats want the money to go
to services. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BONDS _ The Clinton administration plans on Wednesday to
introduce a new form of savings bond that is indexed to inflation.
The bonds, which are aimed at small savers and range in value from
$50 to $1,000, are to be announced by Vice President Al Gore, as
part of a carefully planned effort to burnish his credentials on
economic issues. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OIL-ROUGH-NECKS (Abilene, Texas) _ Many ``rough necks'' _
laborers on oil rigs _ lost their jobs when oil prices hit bottom
in the late 1980s. When prices strengthened several years ago, the
oil-service companies suddenly found that a whole generation of
workers had vanished, and they have been scrambling ever since to
catch up. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ A month-long strike by the United
Auto Workers against General Motors Corp. is starting to drain the
cash reserves of both sides and is prompting GM in particular to
begin reviewing ways to save money. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   DATEK-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Datek Online, one of the United
States' fastest-growing online brokerage firms, has postponed its
initial public offering amid investigations into whether the firm
engaged in illegal trading practices and participated in a
money-laundering operation, according to people close to the firm.
By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients. Photo
[NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   ANTISMOKING-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The next phase of an ambitious
anti-smoking campaign, created for and in part by teen-agers, is as
audacious as any tobacco-company advertisement featuring
anthropomorphic animals, fit and healthy athletes or models who
flash sparkling white teeth. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-MATISSE (New York) _ During his 60 years as a dealer,
Pierre Matisse exhibited some of the greatest artists of this
century in his gallery in the Fuller Building at 41 East 57th St.,
including modern masters like Miro, Balthus, Chagall, Dubuffet,
Tanguy, Mondrian, Giacometti, de Chirico and his own father, Henri
Matisse. Pierre, a pack rat who was intensely devoted to promoting
his artists, hardly ever parted with a scrap of paper, and by the
time of his death in 1989, he had amassed files stuffed with
correspondence from all the artists with whom he had worked. These
archives, which document nine decades of 20th-century art in New
York, have been given by the Pierre Matisse Foundation to the
Pierpont Morgan Library. They will be available for study in
January. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   FREUD-EXHIBIT (New York) _ A much-criticized exhibition on Freud
is to open at last. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT5) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ When all is said and done, writes
Maureen Dowd, Bill Clinton's biggest legacy may not be in politics,
but in letters.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich comments on the CNN nerve gas
story.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE (Paris) _ A strange thing has happened on
the way to the World Cup final: this fractious country, never in
agreement about anything, eternally divided, deeply skeptical, has
united around a soccer team that is now lauded by workers, women,
and even intellectuals. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-CROATIA (Paris) _ Advance on the Croatia-France
semifinal. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WASH-CHERRIES (Zillah, Wash.) _ These are happy days in the
orchards of the Yakima Valley, the nation's premier cherry-growing
region. Last year's crop, over 90,000 tons, was the largest on
record, and the experts are predict that as young trees come into
production crops of 110,000 tons and more are possible over the
next five years. Still, the day before the harvest begins is a
tense time. Hundreds of thousands of dollars hang in the balance. A
rain storm, even a few unexpected gusts of wind, could wipe out the
work of a year in a matter of hours. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   NY-BRUNCH (New York) _ When the weekend arrives and the city's
daytime motor shifts into idle, New York prepares to greet its
favorite meal. It is called brunch, and it is weird. A linguistic
and culinry hybrid, brunch is a breakfast that begins with a
cocktail. Or a lunch that's organized around a stack of buckwheat
pancakes. It's neither fish nor fowl nor good red herring, although
all three can wind up on the same plate. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT4) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-CARIBBEAN (Miami) _ On a blistering South Florida
afternoon whose heat approximates a restaurant kitchen's, Norman
Van Aken, dressed from chin to cuffs in his white chef's outfit,
looks refreshed and cool as he cuts a path through sweaty shoppers
inside the Palacio de los Jugos market. It looks less than regal,
but for Van Aken, the fresh fruits and vegetables shipped here
daily from the Caribbean, Latin America and other tropical lands
represent the raw material for dishes fit for gastronomic royalty.
Van Aken is the head chef and partner in Norman's in nearby Coral
Gables, which is widely considered the best restaurant in South
Florida. A pioneer in the Florida-Caribbean fusion cooking that he
calls New World cuisine, Van Aken is perhaps the best known of the
Miami chefs collectively called ``The Mango Gang.'' By Jon
Nordheimer.
</P>
<P>
   ALLENDE-COOKING (Undated) _ The morning sun that flooded Isabel
Allende's kitchen was as innocent and unblemished as a perfect egg
yolk. It slid across the hand-painted ceramic tile counter, warmed
her back and made her dangling silver earrings sparkle. But the
56-year-old Chilean novelist was, for the moment, immune to the
poetry and the pleasure of the spring sun. Bent in her own shadow,
calibrating the flame under the omelet pan on her stove, Ms.
Allende, had surrendered to an atavistic ritual of the kind that
might have made a scene in one of her novels. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
