<HEADLINE>
FERRARO'S CAMPAIGN MANAGER QUITS; BOTH DENY TENSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Democratic strategist running Geraldine Ferraro's
Senate campaign announced he was quitting Tuesday, saying only that
he wanted to move on and that he still believed Ms. Ferraro could
defeat Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato in November.
</P>
<P>
   The strategist, David Eichenbaum, said that Ms. Ferraro had not
asked him to leave his job as campaign manager, but that she agreed
it was time for him to go. People close to the campaign said
Eichenbaum had complained privately in recent weeks that Ms.
Ferraro, a former representative from Queens, was not heeding his
advice. Eichenbaum said that was not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the right decision for me at this time,'' he said
Tuesday afternoon. ``I have discussed it with Gerry, we have agreed
on a course of action that is best for both of us, and we are doing
it in a friendly way.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Eichenbaum, who has been working for Ms.
Ferraro since late last year, came on the heels of several
potentially damaging incidents for Ms. Ferraro, who is the best
known of the three Democratic Senate candidates and has a strong
lead in most polls.
</P>
<P>
   In a debate last week, one of her rivals, Mark Green, questioned
her judgment in accepting a $20,000 speaking fee from a tobacco
company last year. Ms. Ferraro defended the fee, but the next day
announced that she would donate the money to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, she called Green and her other Democratic rival,
Rep. Charles Schumer, ``liars'' for denying they had strong-armed
delegates at the Democratic state convention. And in May, when Ms.
Ferraro accused D'Amato of pushing breast cancer legislation that
served ``the interests of the insurance companies,'' she riled
breast cancer victims and several female lawmakers who supported
D'Amato's legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Eichenbaum insisted his decision had nothing to do with the
recent incidents. But other political strategists, who said his
departure had been rumored for weeks, said it was the strongest
sign yet that Ms. Ferraro's campaign was adrift.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Ms. Ferraro dismissed such criticism
and said that Eichenbaum's departure would not ``impact one way or
the other on the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are saying the campaign is adrift don't have a clue
about what is going on with the campaign,'' Ms. Ferraro said. ``I
get really annoyed at that. We are talking issues, we have great
things going, we are still 20 to 30 points ahead in the polls and
we are not adrift.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro said her new campaign manager would be Beth Scully,
who joined the campaign in March and has been working as its
operations manager.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several strategists said that Ms. Scully, who also worked on Ms.
Ferraro's unsuccessful 1992 Senate campaign, has been close to Ms.
Ferraro for years. She is relatively unknown compared with
Eichenbaum, who was communications director for the Democratic
National Committee in 1996 and ran the successful 1994 re-election
campaign of Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mr. Eichenbaum said he had been planning his departure
for several weeks, he said he did not have any immediate career
plans. He said he had waited until July, traditionally one of the
slowest months for political campaigns, to announce his departure
because he wanted to shepherd Ms. Ferraro through last week's
debate, the first of the primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a September primary, it made sense not to wait any
longer,'' Eichenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, the chairwoman of the State Democratic Committee,
predicted that although Eichenbaum's departure would create a buzz
in political circles, it would not hurt Ms. Ferraro because voters
do not care about the inner workings of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters don't know who David Eichenbaum is,'' she said. ``I
think this is of no consequence in the larger picture of retiring
Al D'Amato in November.''
</P>
</TEXT>
