<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC LIVES: E.R. SHIPP, BUDDY GRECO, MOVING ART DISPLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BARRON with GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keeping Her Eye On the News &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ E.R. Shipp, who won a Pulitzer Prize as a columnist
for The New York Daily News, has been named ombudsman for The
Washington Post. She replaces Geneva Overholser, who left The Post
last month after three years in the job, which is independent of
the paper's news-gathering operation and comes with a weekly column
and the responsibility to act as an in-house critic. Or, as
executive editor Leonard Downie Jr. put it, ``We can't control her,
and she can't control us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shipp, who is 43 and worked as a reporter and editor at The
New York Times for 13 years, will start at The Post on Oct. 1. She
will take a leave of absence from Columbia University, where she is
an assistant professor of journalism, and move to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few weeks we've seen ample evidence of the need
for the ombudsman,'' she said, referring to an article on Chiquita
Brands International that The Cincinnati Enquirer said was based on
stolen voice-mail messages, a story on nerve gas that CNN and Time
magazine concluded was not supported by CNN's reporting and columns
that The Boston Globe said had been fabricated. ``But,'' Ms. Shipp
added with a laugh, ``I'd like to be an
ombuds-something-other-than-man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beat Goes On &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Greco, who rose from being a singing pianist with Benny
Goodman's orchestra to a solo career on the club, cruise ship and
casino circuit, has become the Cal Ripken of cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night at the Algonquin Hotel, he gave his 10,000th
performance as a professional entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been performing at local clubs and strip joints in South
Philadelphia when I was 16,'' said Greco, who was also a child star
on the radio in Philadelphia when he recorded ``Oh, Look At Her,
Ain't She Pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The record sold over a million copies,'' Greco said, ``but I
made pennies.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1949, he was hired by Goodman for $250 a week. He went
on to record nearly 70 albums and compact disks and more than 100
singles.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tony Bennett, Greco has an autobiography in the works; his
is in the hands of the writer Janet Berliner. In poring over his
scrapbooks, reviews and letters, he calculated that his 10,000th
performance would occur during his 12 days at the Algonquin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' he said. ``It only feels like 9,000. But
I've been doing it such a long time. I'm 70. If I do 30 weeks a
year on average, it sounds like a lot, even to me. Too many
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving Pictures &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime Tuesday, a lot of art went on display on the Upper
West Side. Then some of it was packed in a trailer for a 12-city
tour.
</P>
<P>
   The trailer departed from Broadway and 64th Street. It belonged
to the Children's Television Workshop, the producer of ``Sesame
Street'' and other acclaimed shows, which marked its 30th
anniversary by filling the trailer with paintings by celebrities
like Carly Simon, Katie Couric and Tony Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety minutes later and a couple of blocks away, at Tavern on
the Green, Leroy Neiman showed off the official poster of the
Goodwill Games, which begin July 19. ``There's never been anything
like this in New York,'' he said, ``so I did New York.'' Or more
precisely, the Manhattan skyline.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the only symbol of New York that he has worked on
recently. He painted Joe DiMaggio. ``Then,'' he said, ``we sat down
and signed the print. First time I ever co-signed a print with
another person. I think it's, I'm not going to say degrading, but
unnecessary for another person to sign it besides the artist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
