A4817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MIDTOWN-SURVEY-NYT     07-08 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MIDTOWN-SURVEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTING HEADS (AND POTENTIAL WALLETS) TO HELP SELL MID-MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anyone walking through the intersection of Seventh
Avenue and 34th Street can see that there are a lot of other people
in the area. But how many? The answer is important to retailers,
who look at pedestrian traffic and see potential shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   To measure the crowds, officials of the Grand Central and 34th
Street Business Improvement Districts sent staff members to 14
major intersections to count the number of people passing by at
different times of the day.
</P>
<P>
   What they found were wide variations in the volume of pedestrian
traffic, even in locations that are close together.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the morning rush hour in April, an average
of 2,406 people walked along the southeast corner of Seventh Avenue
and 34th Street. During the same period, an average of 9,834 people
passed the northwest corner of the same intersection, most likely
because of the nearby exit from the Long Island Rail Road.
</P>
<P>
   The evening rush was even more congested, with an average of
11,856 people streaming by the northwest corner of the intersection
and 4,335 passing the southeast side.
</P>
<P>
   The size of those crowds is good news not only for retailers but
for real estate investors as well. Vornado Corp. chairman Steven
Roth cited streets ``teeming with people day and night'' as the
reason why his company has bought more than $1 billion in office
buildings, a hotel and retail properties along Seventh Avenue
between 31st and 34th Streets. With Madison Square Garden in its
midst, he said, Vornado hopes to develop the area into an urban
version of a suburban entertainment-retail shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   With its dense concentrations of relatively well-paid office
workers, real estate executives said, Manhattan presents new
opportunities for retailers who have developed their businesses in
the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Research has found that New Yorkers are walkers, willing to
tramp longer distances than people in other central business
districts to shop for what they want.
</P>
<P>
   They are also far more likely to walk to any destination, be it
work or shopping, than their counterparts in other parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of Manhattan, like the heavily residential Murray
Hill ZIP code, more people walk to work than arrive by subway, bus
or taxi, according to the BID study. Accustomed to walking, they
will go farther during lunch breaks to go shopping.
</P>
<P>
   N. David Milder, the president of Danth Inc., a consulting
concern that studies the relationship of pedestrian traffic to
retailing decisions, wrote that ``because of the amount of economic
activity found in the midtown area, its geographic density and the
propensity of New Yorkers to walk significant distances, one can
reasonably expect that retailers in the Grand Central district can
tap a much larger captive employee market than retailers in other
downtowns or suburban locations.''
</P>
<P>
   Milder said studies had shown that office workers in New York,
on average, were willing to walk 2,250 feet, or 0.43 miles, to do
midday shopping, compared with under 1,000 feet in other cities.
Discussions with researchers ``produced a general consensus that
people in Manhattan do walk twice as far as people in other
downtowns and that this is probably because of midtown's huge range
of retail choices and the large stretches of continuous retail
space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two BIDs have been doing pedestrian counts since 1995, said
Dan Pisark, director of retail improvement for the two business
districts, which are centrally managed. ``The retail companies are
quite interested in them, and the store leasing industry is
interested as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers want pedestrian counts, said Benjamin Fox, a partner
in New Spectrum Realty Services, a retail brokerage concern,
``especially in midtown where people are likely to shop in spurts,
because that will help them plan their staffing levels.''
</P>
<P>
   But although the counts are a useful tool, said Alan Victor, an
executive vice president of Lansco Corp., they do not show how much
people are spending. ``That's a question we get asked all the
time,'' he said. ``Retailers want to know what other people's sales
volumes are and who else is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with their limitations, pedestrian counts are popular with
retail brokers and store operators, Pisark of the business
districts said. The counters, he said, chronicle the passing throng
in the morning from 7:45 a.m. to 9:15 a.m., at midday from noon to
1:30 p.m. and in the evening from 5 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. They also
record the peak traffic at each site, regardless of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The counts are conducted during what are considered normal
operating times in the city, like April and October, when the
streets are least likely to be thronged by visitors and tourists.
``We never count during Thanksgiving or Christmas,'' he said.
``It's too crowded then; a counter could not stand at a place like
42nd Street and Vanderbilt Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   With rush-hour counts of more than 7,000 people an hour at that
location, Milder of Danth Inc. concluded that more than 2 million
people a year pass by that corner during the one-hour evening rush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
