<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    69th All-Star Game is one NL would like to forget
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Denver _ A classic it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Then again the All-Star Game is rarely a game to remember.
</P>
<P>
   In a game that seemed to last forever, where pitchers that
normally rely on control couldn't find the plate, where fielders
dove and came up with little, where Big Mac couldn't get the ball
out of the infield, the American League knocked off their brethren
from the senior circuit 13-8 before 51,267 at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   The game, the 69th version of this gathering of two leagues,
came down to the sixth inning, an inning that Montreal Expos closer
Ugueth Urbina and Atlanta Braves catcher Javier Lopez would like to
forget.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The National League had a one-run lead, thanks to a three-run
homer by Barry Bonds in the top of the inning. But when Urbina
finally was able to get three outs, the AL had scored three runs,
two on a wild pitch and passed ball. They also had stolen four
bases.
</P>
<P>
   But it was that kind of game.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching was for the most part awful and for more reasons
than just the fact that Coors is a hitter's park.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Urbina, the biggest culprits were Braves lefthander
Tom Glavine and Indians righthander Barolo Colon.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine turned a 2-0 NL lead into a 4-2 deficit in the fourth
inning. In the fifth, Colon turned a 5-3 AL advantage into a 6-5
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, then Urbina gave it right back and the AL pitchers
finally settled down to close it out, their second straight win
though the NL still leads the series 40-28-1.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that focused on power, and three homers were hit,
the first by Alex Rodriguez and then Bonds ripped a three-run homer
in the sixth off Colon before Roberto Alomar went deep in the
seventh. Mark McGwire, who had trouble in the home-run hitting
contest the night before, went hitless, as the only ball he put in
play in three plate appearances was a slow roller to short. Braves
first baseman Andres Galaragga did put a scare into the AL when
with two runners on in the sixth he drove a ball deep to center. At
first, the crowd, which adores the Big Cat, thought it was gone,
but it fell just short of the 415-foot sign in center field.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that focused on Braves shortstop Walt Weiss, whose
3-year-old son has been so sick but miraculously got better in time
to be at the game. And Walt didn't disappoint Brody, going 2-for-3,
scoring a run and driving in another.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that focused on Alomar, the Baltimore Orioles'
second baseman who is not expected to be with the club much longer.
Scouts are watching his every move, and he certainly didn't
disappoint, going 3-for-4 with a stolen base and the homer. Where
will he land next?
</P>
<P>
   And it was a game that focused on the city of Denver as a great
baseball city. It did a marvelous job hosting the game and showed
why this place is packed every game despite their team not being
very good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
