<HEADER>
A4820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-CHARTER-NYT &LR;      07-08 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CHARTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ABUSING THE CHARTER PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 8:
</P>
<P>
   Any pretense that New York City has an urgent need to rewrite
its charter evaporated Monday when Peter Powers, chairman of the
Charter Revision Commission, released a memo to the commissioners.
Powers told Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's hurriedly created commission
to limit their revisions to ``what can be attained'' in time to
make the November ballot. Translated, the urgency here arises from
the mayor's political need to get a charter item on the ballot in
place of Council Speaker Peter Vallone's referendum on Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani and Vallone are rivals, they have jointly
elevated their power struggle ahead of two civic questions that
deserve unhurried deliberation. The first is whether public funds
should be used to move Yankee Stadium to Manhattan. The second has
to do with what, if any, changes are needed in the structure of
city government.
</P>
<P>
   The commission scheduled its first public hearings over the July
4 holiday season, when many people are on vacation. It clearly does
not have time to draft a reasoned revision of the city's charter.
It exists to block Vallone's stadium referendum. Under election
rules, a charter referendum on this November's ballot would
automatically bounce Vallone's stadium vote (or any other
referendum) until the next election.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor opposes the Vallone referendum for a variety of
reasons, including the fact that it could boost Vallone's campaign
for governor. This page has argued repeatedly against the Vallone
referendum, which among other things would let the City Council
dodge rather than think its way through the stadium problem.
Nevertheless, reforming the charter to checkmate a political
mistake like the Vallone referendum is a hazardous business. The
charter commission should put its civic duty ahead of loyalty to
Giuliani and stop trying to restitch city government on the fly. If
Vallone really is gubernatorial material, he can show it by
shelving his politically tainted referendum.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to look responsible, Powers has suggested that the
commission take aim at campaign finance reform and consider
nonpartisan elections and full-time council members. The latter two
subjects are so weighty they they require more than two months of
debate by a limited group.
</P>
<P>
   As for campaign finance reform, it can be accomplished without
changing the charter. In fact, Vallone last week proposed an
excellent bill to plug the holes in the city's 10-year-old campaign
finance system.
</P>
<P>
   It would be refreshing to see the mayor and Vallone unite behind
a law the city needs rather than unnecessary referendums erected as
monuments to their political egos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4822 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLSTAR-SIDE-COX     07-08 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine, All-Star game just don't mix
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ It wasn't nearly as bad as 1992, when he gave up nine
first-inning hits and five runs.
</P>
<P>
   But the All-Star Game and Tom Glavine just don't jibe.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing teammate Greg Maddux, Glavine was able to escape the
third inning without any damage but not the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   He was tagged for four runs, never getting out of the inning and
for a while it appeared he might end up being the losing pitcher
but was let off the hook on the three-run homer by Barry Bonds in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, now with 13.50 ERA in four All-Star appearances (he has
made six teams), had some control problems. To open the third he
walked Kenny Lofton and then gave up a one-out hit to Griffey as
Lofton went to third. But major-league RBI leader Juan Gonzalez
failed again, pushing a ball up in the air to short right which
second baseman Craig Biggio ran down and Lofton could go nowhere.
Then Glavine got Jim Thome to hit a flyball to left.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine's offense was another story. In the bottom of the
inning, Glavine came up to the plate and bunted Larry Walker to
third and Walt Weiss to second, the two scoring the first runs of
the game. Glavine, however, had trouble in the fourth, giving up a
two-run double to Ripken which tied the game. Damon Easley followed
with an infield single, but Glavine was able to get Lofton to
ground back to him for an out. Ripken never moved off third.
Glavine then walked Alomar and Griffey, a run coming home, and he
was replaced by Florida's Kevin Brown, who would let in a run
charged to Glavine on a flyball hit by Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   However, the other Braves players did fare better than Glavine:
</P>
<P>
   _ Maddux immediately found himself in trouble as Lofton opened
the game with a single, stole second and went to third on a bunt
single by Alomar as the relay from Mark McGwire to Maddux at first
was late. But then Maddux became Maddux again. He was able to get
Ken Griffey Jr. to foul out to McGwire. Then Gonzalez, desperately
trying to take the ball to right field, got jammed and rolled a
ball back to Maddux, who looked Lofton back at third and threw to
first for the out. Maddux worked the count full to Jim Thome and
walked him before striking out Alex Rodriguez on three pitches, the
last one a great fastball that stunned the Mariners shortstop who
was looking for something offspeed. In the second, Ivan Rodriguez
led off with a single before Cal Ripken hit into a double play and
the inning ended with David Wells grounding out to second.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chipper Jones hit into a double play on his first at-bat and
walked in the fourth, hustled to third base when Lofton bobbled a
ball in center and would score on a single by teammate Walt Weiss.
Jones grounded out to second in the fifth and was replaced at third
base by Vinny Castilla.
</P>
<P>
   _ Weiss went 2-for-2, scoring a run and knocking in Jones.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andres Galarraga came on for Mark McGwire in the sixth and hit
a ball to deep center that was caught.
</P>
<P>
   _ Javier Lopez came on for Mike Piazza in the sixth and had
trouble behind the plate. Lopez was charged with a passed ball that
let in a run, and in the inning the AL tied an All-Star record by
stealing four bases. He also struck out to end the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
