A4832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-HOMERUNS-NYT &LR;      07-08 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HOMERUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HOME RUN FEVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 8:
</P>
<P>
   Baseball aficionados are savoring this summer's three-man
assault on one of the game's most celebrated milestones, the
single-season home run record. At midpoint of the season, Mark
McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals, Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs
and Ken Griffey Jr. of the Seattle Mariners are hitting long balls
at a pace that, if sustained through September, would vault them
past Roger Maris' mark of 61, set in 1961. McGwire, the leader, has
already hit 37.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of computerized record keeping, when it is possible to
determine which left-handed hitter in history knocked in the most
winning runs in the bottom of the ninth inning, the home run title
is the gold standard for power hitters. Because it was invented and
long owned by Babe Ruth, who hit 60 home runs in 1927, Maris has
always seemed an interloper to some. By 1961, the season had grown
by eight games, clouding Maris' achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Now come two proven sluggers, McGwire and Griffey, and a late
bloomer, Sosa, to tantalize fans with the prospect of a new record.
The question, however, is whether their power hitting is memorable
or the pitching they face is miserable. With the addition of two
new teams, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays and the Arizona Diamondbacks,
major league pitching staffs are thin. Yet even suspect pitching
shouldn't diminish the excitement of the chase.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one home runs do not sound like that many for a six-month
season with 162 games. Sosa hit 20 in June alone, a new one-month
record. But what often looks plausible in June seems unattainable
by September, after heat and fatigue have taken their toll. The
psychological pressure can be wilting as well. Maris was a nervous
wreck by the time he cracked the Ruth barrier.
</P>
<P>
   There is sure to be an exacting analysis of the parlous pitching
if the record is approached, but at least there ought not to be a
churlish debate about whether Ruth's record is the one that counts.
The time may just be right for a new mark. Ruth's record stood for
34 years. More time than that has elapsed since Maris exceeded it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-NYT &LR;      07-08 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN LEAGUE TRIUMPHS, 13-8 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr., the leaders in the
pursuit of Roger Maris' home run record, did not hit any home runs.
Juan Gonzalez, who drove in 101 runs before the break, did not get
a hit in four times at bat with a total of nine runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez did drive in a run with a sacrifice fly, and it
contributed, sort of, to the American League's 13-8 victory over
the National League on Tuesday night in the highest-scoring
All-Star Game. An A.L. single by Rafael Palmeiro in the ninth
inning drove in the run that eclipsed the previous highest-scoring
game, the Americans' 11-9 victory at Cleveland in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   This game, which lasted 3 hours 38 minutes, also surpassed that
game as the longest nine-inning All-Star Game. The game in 1954
took a mere 3 hours 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the star All-Stars did not hit home runs, that did not
mean Coors Field was big enough to hold all of the baseballs within
the playing field. Alex Rodriguez and Roberto Alomar, who was named
the most valuable player, slugged bases-empty home runs for the
A.L., and Barry Bonds whacked an impressive three-run blast for the
National.
</P>
<P>
   If the 51,267 fans, the largest to watch a game at the routinely
sold-out Coors Field, were disappointed that McGwire, the major
league home run leader with 37, did not hit one, he said he was
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm realistic about things,'' said McGwire, who did not add to
his total of home runs in the last five games before the break. ``I
can't do it every day at bat, can't do it every week. You go
through streaks where you hit some, get in a nice groove, then you
go in a streaks where I hit one every week or so.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the teams combined for a record-tying 31 hits, the
tying run and the tie-breaking run, the one that gave the A.L. a
lead it never surrendered, were scored in the sixth inning without
a hit driving them in. The first came on a passed ball by Javier
Lopez, the second moments later on a wild pitch by Ugueth Urbina.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationals threatened to disturb the A.L. lead in the eighth
when Greg Vaughn of San Diego lined a two-run single to left field
and Devon White of Arizona followed with another line single to
left. But when the Brewers' Fernando Vina tried to score from
second base, the Yankees' Paul O'Neill threw him out, firing a
perfect throw to Sandy Alomar Jr., who tagged Vina on the left knee
as he slid home.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gordon then induced the dangerous Andres Galarraga to ground
into an inning-ending double play. The Americans then added three
runs to their advantage in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   According to an ages-old baseball maxim, good pitching is
supposed to stop good hitting. But the notion that the All-Star
Game pitchers would enforce that view was dispelled in the middle
innings. Instead, the Coors Field maxim prevailed _ that is, when
at Coors, hitters beat up pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine, Greg Maddux's sidekick in Atlanta, suffered the
worst beating, allowing the A.L. four runs in the fourth inning for
a 4-2 lead. Maddux himself encountered a little trouble in the
first two innings, but he escaped unscathed by throwing a third
strike past Alex Rodriguez with two out and the bases loaded in the
first and inducing Cal Ripken Jr. to ground into a double play in
the second.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine had no such luck with Ripken, holder of the longest
playing streak in history, at 2,566 games. After Alex Rodriguez and
Ivan Rodriguez began the fourth with successive singles, Ripken
ripped a fly ball to right field that missed the stands by inches.
It went for a double instead and tied the score, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Damion Easley of Detroit then batted for Roger Clemens, whose
pitching produced the N.L.'s two runs in the third inning, and got
an infield single. Glavine made a good play on Kenny Lofton's
bouncer to the third-base side of the mound for the first out, but
he did not pitch well to the next two batters.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander walked Roberto Alomar and Griffey, the first
loading the bases, the second forcing in the tie-breaking run.
Kevin Brown became the new pitcher after that flurry of
uncharacteristic wildness, and Gonzalez hit a fly to center field,
driving in the fourth run.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn, the perennial N.L. batting champion, drove in his
team's two runs in the third with a bases-loaded single. Alomar
dived for the tantalizing up-the-middle bouncer, but the ball
deflected off the heel of his glove. The Yankees' David Wells, he
of the perfect game, had pitched two hitless and scoreless innings
as the A.L. starter.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss of Atlanta, who singled against Clemens in the third,
singled again in the fourth against Brad Radke of Minnesota,
driving in Chipper Jones after Mike Piazza of the Mets singled him
into scoring position. But Alex Rodriguez restored the A.L.'s
two-run lead by leading off the fifth inning with a home run
against Andy Ashby of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The A.L., however, did not retain that lead for long. With
Bartolo Colon of Cleveland pitching in the N.L. half of the fifth,
White lashed a leadoff triple to left-center field and McGwire
walked. Bonds, who before the game was nursing a bad headache, then
swatted the ball high in the air toward the right-field stands, and
it crashed into the San Francisco Giants sign on the facade of the
third tier.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first home run in eight All-Star Games and 20 at-bats
for Bonds, who with his father, Bobby, joined the Griffeys as the
only father-son team to hit All-Star Game home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The blow put the N.L. ahead, 6-5, but what else? The lead did
not last long. Only until the next inning, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   And what an ugly inning it was. Alomar and Griffey started the
problems for Urbina, Montreal's closer, by beating the ball into
the ground and getting cheap singles. Alomar's caromed off Craig
Biggio's glove near second, and Griffey's barely went beyond the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Urbina struck out Gonzalez, but after the runners executed a
double steal, he walked Jim Thome, loading the bases. With Derek
Jeter batting, Lopez of Atlanta lost control of an Urbina pitch,
and Alomar scored the game-tying run on the passed ball, the other
runners also advancing a base each.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter struck out on the next pitch, but Urbina's second pitch to
Ivan Rodriguez was wild, and Griffey scored the tie-breaking run.
Rodriguez then singled home Thome with the third run of the inning
and gave the A.L. an 8-6 lead. Alomar made the score 9-6, slugging
a two-out home run against Trevor Hoffman of San Diego in the
seventh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
