<HEADER>
A4839 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI     07-08 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT GOES UP AS BASEBALL RECORD CHASERS GO BACK TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sometime during the All-Star Game festivities, the
standard baseball cliches _ ``Good pitching beats good hitting''
and ``Pitching and defense wins games'' _ were apparently replaced
with something telling about what's to come in the second half
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Major league baseball's new foolproof slogan?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, now, everybody knows it gets awfully hot in August.''
</P>
<P>
   What that means for baseball fans falling in love again with the
game formerly known as the national pastime is that in St. Louis,
where slugger Mark McGwire must toil under the shadow of the arch
and the Midwest summer sun, and in Texas, where RBI machine Juan
Gonzalez must battle flying insects the size of The Alamo and
body-numbing heat the likes of which no Swedish sauna could ever
produce, baseball's biggest records seem safe and sound.
</P>
<P>
   August is where good intentions for baseball immortality go to
die.
</P>
<P>
   Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   While none of the 1998 All-Stars spent a moment here making any
bold, Joe Namath-like predictions about what's going to happen in
the second half, no one exactly disputed the entertaining notion
that records could fall.
</P>
<P>
   And fall with a media-crushing, fan-frenzied thud that will make
Cal Ripken's breaking of Lou Gehrig's Iron Man record in 1995 feel
like high tea with the Queen.
</P>
<P>
   The high-octane performances of the first half have only served
to fuel gargantuan expectations for the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``(McGwire) is the big thing now in baseball. I'm trying to
drive in my RBIs, you know,'' said Gonzalez, whose 101 RBIs at the
break have been the envy of his All-Star peers, except maybe Ken
Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (`It's not really Juan that's impressive, it's the guys in front
of him. Those guys getting on base, being in scoring position,
that's what's impressive. He's only had 26 home runs but he's
driven in 101. The guys batting one, two, three, they're on base
all the time,'' Griffey said.)
</P>
<P>
   As for Gonzalez, he was optimistic great things could happen in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is to stay healthy all season. There's a good chance
at breaking the home run record. I'm in the race for the RBI
record, too. You know, I never pass in my mind any (thought) about
the record. I'm trying day by day, one at a time,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Even for those of us with wildly hyperbolic imaginations, it's
difficult to believe that the luster of baseball's first half could
sustain itself for another 80-plus games.
</P>
<P>
   However, while watching Tuesday night's All-Star Game, somewhere
between the time Roger Clemens hit Houston's Craig Biggio with a
wild pitch and Montreal right-hander Ugeth Urbina heaved a few
one-hoppers past catcher Javy Lopez (total elapsed time: four
innings, two hours), an exciting thought did occur:
</P>
<P>
   Why not hurry up this high-scoring little Mid-Summer Classic and
let the record-chasing boys go back to the work of re-creating
history?
</P>
<P>
   (And, by the way: If Urbina can get a spot on Jim Leyland's NL
All-Star squad, what's the matter with the Cubbies' rookie
strikeout phenom Kerry Wood? OK, fine, Urbina has 20 saves this
season _ fifth best in the NL and roughly 100 times as many saves
than the entire Mariner bullpen. But, Mr. Leyland, ``We The
People'' wanted Kerry Wood pitching to Griffey and Cal Ripken and
Jim Thome.)
</P>
<P>
   What are the grand records up for grabs in the second half of
'98?
</P>
<P>
   A) Hack Wilson's 1930 record of 190 RBI, which Gonzalez is
attacking.
</P>
<P>
   B) Roger Maris' 1961 record of 61 home runs, which McGwire,
Griffey and Sammy Sosa are chasing with steamroller-like pace.
</P>
<P>
   C) The Cubs' 1906 record of 116 wins, which the red-hot Yankees
could approach, should their second half mirror their first.
</P>
<P>
   And, if Boston shortstop Nomar Garciaparra had not had his
consecutive-game hitting streak stopped at 24, Joe DiMaggio's
awesome 56-game hitting streak could have been on the line, too.
</P>
<P>
   The mind almost reels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you imagine someone sitting on 50? Everyone's going to
want to know; `Can he get to 56?''' said catcher Mike Piazza,
himself trying to set a record for number of teams an All-Star
catcher has played for in one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure would drive you nuts. You would have to be put in
an insane asylum. You would have to pull every TV out of the house,
every radio out of the car, just to try and block out all the hype
and attention. It wouldn't be easy, not in this age of instant
information when you can watch 10 games on satellite TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is right. It won't be the heat of August that will wilt
the hard-charging All-Stars in their pursuit of the record book. It
will be the crush of media and the unbridled mania of the fans that
could worse jeopardize the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to finish the season without any gray hairs in my
goatee,'' McGwire said Tuesday night before heading back to
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is all gray, then it's a sign the pressure got to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   No one wants Big Red to turn gray, but everyone is rooting for
big things come September. If the Mariners are beyond salvage and
the pennant races everywhere except the NL West pose little hope,
baseball still holds a crushing ton of promise.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
