<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRENCH TOUR WITH NO TIME FOR BRAKES 
BY DAN GIESIN
</HEADLINE>
 DE FRANCE-SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the warm-up act is about to end, France is ready to go
all out for its annual showstopper, the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   As a concession to the World Cup, which concludes Sunday in
Paris, this year's Tour will begin a week later than usual and a
10-hour ferry ride away from the shores of Brittany. Even though
the peloton will spend three days in Ireland, beginning with
Saturday's opening prologue in Dublin, don't expect any blarney in
this year's Tour.
</P>
<P>
   It could be one of the most hotly contested races in recent
history.
</P>
<P>
   The '98 Tour will be a much more competitive affair than last
year, when Jan Ullrich, the brash young Telekom team rider who
became the first German in the 94-year history of the race to win
the Tour, shredded the field in the two time trials and kept pace
with the climbers in the mountains to seize the title by more than
nine minutes over runner-up Richard Virenque of France.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich, 24, since has gained a ton of weight hitting the
offseason rubber-chicken circuit after last year's victory,
ballooning to 185 pounds on his six-foot frame (one wag said
Ullrich will do his military service as a blimp).
</P>
<P>
   And the winter-long la dolce vita showed in the early-season
races, when Ullrich was more of a threat to the integrity of his
bike frame than to the top riders in Europe's spring classics. Even
though team officials insist Ullrich is rounding into shape, the
excess baggage could weigh him down.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Ullrich expand must be sweet revenge for Virenque, who
dominated in the Pyrenees and Alps and had nothing to show for it
but his fourth straight polka-dot jersey signifying the top climber
on the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   But the 28-year-old Festina team leader, who finished the '96
Tour in third place, is not a lock to overtake his lumbering German
rival because he is only a better-than-average time trialist.
</P>
<P>
   This ``race of truth,'' as the great Bernard Hinault, the last
Frenchman to win the Tour (1985), called the individual race
against the clock, is where a rider either can make up time or put
distance on a rival, and Virenque does not figure to do either in
the 361/2-miler on July 18 or the 321/2-miler on August 1, the
penultimate stage of the Tour's 21 stages.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, look to the shaven-headed ``Pirate'', Marco Pantani, to
be wearing the yellow jersey when the riders make their final
parade down the Champs-Elysees on August 2. Pantani, whose elfin
physique belies his enormous heart, won last month's Giro d'Italia,
which he says gives him a huge psychological lift going into the
Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giro is great preparation for the Tour,'' he told VeloNews
last month. ``I'll go into the Tour this year with a team
(Mercatone Uno-Bianchi) entirely at my disposal, something I've
never had before. ... The most important thing now is that I raced
for three weeks (in the Giro) without having a bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Pantani, who finished third in the Tour both
last year and in '95, showed the world during the Giro that tough
conditions in the mountains do not faze him _ he is easily the
purest climber among the 189 riders in this year's Tour, Virenque
notwithstanding _ and his time-trialing ability has steadily
improved.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latter quality that will serve Pantani well in this
year's Tour _ the half-dozen mountain stages are not the toughest
routes the Alps and Pyrenees have to offer. (Virenque has said they
are not demanding enough.) Thus the two races against the clock
could settle the matter.
</P>
<P>
   And with Ullrich's fitness and Virenque's time-trialing
questionable, Pantani should be able to capitalize and slip into
the yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as with any race covering 21 days and 2,392 miles,
something unexpected could happen, so do not be surprised to see
Bobby Julich, perhaps the United States' best cyclist now that
Lance Armstrong is working back into shape after a bout with
testicular cancer, slip into contention.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Julich, a native of Glenwood Springs, Colo., and
co-captain of the French-based Cofidis team, finished 17th in his
Tour debut, and he could be ready for a top-10 finish.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the San Francisco-based U.S. Postal Service team, the only
American-sponsored squad among the 21 Tour teams, could cause a
stir in its second Tour de France with Frenchman Jean-Cyril Robin,
a strong climber who finished 15th last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
