<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN LEAGUE STOPS NL, 13-8, IN ALL-STAR GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ They talked much here the past two days about Mark
McGwire's power, Ken Griffey Jr.'s sweet swing and Juan Gonzalez's
pursuit of Hack Wilson's RBI record.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody paid much attention to the possibility that Rangers
catcher Ivan Rodriguez might become the first American League
catcher to ever win a batting title.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, hitting .350 for the season, reminded people of that
last night. Rodriguez had three hits in four at-bats, helping spark
the American League to a 13-8 victory against the National League
in the 69th annual All-Star Game before 51,267 at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles second baseman Roberto Alomar also had three hits,
including a home run, to steal most valuable player honors away
from Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an effort by the whole team,'' Alomar said. ``We wanted
to win this game, and we came out playing aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players were pivotal in the three-run sixth inning that
allowed the American League to take the lead for good. Alomar led
off the inning with an infield hit, and Rodriguez finished it with
a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are great pitchers, but I just concentrated on hitting
the ball hard,'' Rodriguez said. ``You know that I'm an aggressive
hitter. It's a good feeling to get three hits in an All-Star
Game.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as missing out on MVP honors, Rodriguez said, ``I was
just having fun. I'm happy that Roberto won. He did a great job,
also. It could have been either one of us. It could have been a lot
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Coors Field has a reputation for being a hitter's paradise, and
the All-Stars confirmed that. The combined 21 runs set an All-Star
Game record while the American League tied a record with 19 hits.
The 31 hits by both teams also tied a record.
</P>
<P>
   The balls didn't exactly go flying out of Coors Field. There
were only three home runs hit, the most memorable one being a
three-run blast by Barry Bonds in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, both sides took advantage of another Coors Field factor
that makes it a great place for hitters. Coors Field has some of
the deepest dimensions of any ballpark in baseball, a concession to
the high altitude, that force outfielders to play deep. As a
result, 26 of the 31 hits were singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch baseball on television, you always see a lot of
runs scored in Denver,'' Alomar said. ``This was a little bit
different of an All-Star Game, but in this ballpark, that's what
you expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers outfielder Juan Gonzalez, who batted four times with a
total of nine men on base, couldn't take advantage of the American
League's offense, going 0-for-3 with a sacrifice fly for his only
run batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers reliever John Wetteland pitched a scoreless inning, but
Aaron Sele didn't get in the game. Hargrove was saving him in case
the game went into extra innings, but the AL pulled away in the
later innings.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' three-run homer, a 451-foot blast off the front of the
third deck in right field, gave the National League a 6-5 lead. But
the American League rallied with three in the sixth when the
National League got sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar reached on a single off second baseman Craig Biggio's
glove, and Griffey bat out a broken-bat roller past pitcher Uegueth
Urbina. Gonzalez struck out, but then the AL pulled off a double
steal. After Jim Thome walked, Alomar scored on catcher Javier
Lopez's passed ball. Griffey scored on Urbina's wild pitch, giving
the AL the lead, and Rodriguez scored Thome with a sharp single to
left.
</P>
<P>
   The AL defense was much sharper in the eighth when the NL,
trailing 10-6, threatened to tie it. Greg Vaughn's bases loaded
single off reliever Tom Gordon scored two runs, but AL left fielder
Paul O'Neill threw out Fernando Vina trying to score on Devon
White's single to left. Shortstop Omar Vizquel then made a slick
grab of Andres Galarraga's chopper up the middle to start an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``O'Neill's play was the best of the game,'' Alomar said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
