r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-08 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL BY THE NUMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball at the break has more than a literal meaning for once.
Baseball is getting a break from fans who, for the first time since
baseball's suicide attempt in 1994, truly seem interested in what's
happening in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has stat freaks to thank, because we're waist-deep in
relevant numbers. It should also thank its tradition now there's a
concept because without Roger Maris, Hack Wilson and the 1954
Cleveland Indians, none of these numbers would mean anything.
</P>
<P>
   That said, here's a look at what's to come, by the numbers:
</P>
<P>
   190 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Before we get to Juan Gonzalez, one needs to explain how a guy
named Hack (Wilson) had 190 RBI and why this record is more
significant than 62 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was a product of his time, a high fastball hitter of the
mid-20s-to-30s, when everyone in baseball was following Babe Ruth's
power lead. For example, the batting average for the entire
National League in 1930 was .303.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had one of the all-time bad bodies. He was 5-6, weighed
195 pounds, and wore a size six shoe. His career was short, 12
seasons and 1,348 games. The 1930 season was his best, with 56
homers (the N.L. record) and 190 RBI. Stat man extraordinaire Bill
James wrote in his Historical Baseball Abstract that if Wilson were
alive today, scouts wouldn't bother sending in a report.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is not chasing Wilson as much as an entire era. Home
runs are romantic, but they're not new. Sixteen of the 23 50-homer
seasons in baseball history have come since World War II, and six
of them in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   A player has finished a year with 162 or more RBI in a season
only 16 times, and the last time it happened was 1938. That's 61
years. Wilson's 190 has often been placed in the same untouchable
territory as Johnny Vander Meer's back-to-back no-hitters and Joe
DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   If Gonzalez gets anywhere near 190, he'll deserve the A.L. MVP
award regardless of how many homers Ken Griffey or any one else
hits. This is a record for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   62.
</P>
<P>
   The home run race is always spoken in terms of how many homers
Mark McGwire (37), Griffey (35) or Sammy Sosa (33) have. But it's
more relevant when you flip the numbers around.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire only needs 25 home runs in his remaining 76 games to get
to 62. Rather than focus on whether he gets to 62, one might want
to chart whether he'll get 61 by Game 154, which would also one-up
Babe Ruth's 60 homers in 1927. It was Ruth's mark in eight fewer
games which led baseball to put an asterisk alongside Maris' 61 in
1961.
</P>
<P>
   If Las Vegas were to install a betting line on McGwire and they
will, if they haven't already it should include a proposition for
injury. He's played with back problems since 1989. Last year (156
games) was his first season since 1991 that he didn't miss a
significant part of the season with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   756.
</P>
<P>
   While we're homer happy, now is as good a time as any to suggest
that we're ringside to mid-assault on Hank Aaron's career record of
755 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   In nine-plus seasons, Griffey, 28, has hit 329 home runs. At the
same stage of his career, and a year older, Hank Aaron had
approximately 320 home runs. The DH allowed Aaron to extend his
career sum, as it will Griffey, and I doubt if baseball will do
anything to impact offense in the seeable future.
</P>
<P>
   122.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees check in at 61-20, a .753 percentage. If they
continue to win at that pace, they will finish the year 122-40,
which would break the A.L. record of 111 wins in a season, set by
the 1954 Cleveland Indians, and the major league mark of 116 set by
the 1906 Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Now would be a good time to inform the Yankees that both of
those teams lost in the World Series. The Indians were swept by
Willie Mays and the New York Giants, and the Cubs lost to the White
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   2.
</P>
<P>
   Throw out the 1996 season and the Angels have won two more games
over the last four years than the Dodgers. Even with the '96 season
included, the Angels are 281-273 the last four seasons despite
pitching best described as desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Al l things considered, the Angels have been impressive lately.
There is no shame in losing to the talented 1995 Mariners. Last
year, the Angels finished six games over .500 despite injuries to
Chuck Finley, Mark Langston and Mark Gubicza and a patchwork
pitching staff that featured a rookie (Jason Dickson), an import
(Getting-Shiggy-With-It Hasegawa) and a knuckleballer (Dennis
Springer).
</P>
<P>
   They're doing it again this year, with injuries to Ken Hill,
Allen Watson and Jack McDowell and the likes of a rookie (Jerrod
Washburn), a retread (Omar Olivares) and a knuckleballer (Steve
Sparks) holding them up.
</P>
<P>
   On spec, the Rangers look like the better team, but then someone
always does. The Angels have four everyday players hitting over
.300 and six with 40-plus RBI if you combine the totals of rotating
catchers Matt Walbeck and Phil Nevin.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Indians are 1-2 in the A.L., but who's to say
the Angels aren't No. 3? And would it be too much to ask of Disney
to find Terry Collins an arm?
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) 13{ and 14. (end bold) That's how far the Dodgers
trail San Diego in the N.L. West, and the number of players left
from the opening day roster.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these numbers will increase. The only person who thinks
the Dodgers will close the standings gap ironically is the guy most
likely to pad the other, interim-for-life G.M. Tommy Lasorda, who
is making one last attempt to get Randy Johnson from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   It won't shock anyone if the only Dodgers left from Opening Day
at season's end are Raul Mondesi and Tom Prince, in which case you
can start calling them ``The Franchise Formerly Known As The
Dodgers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
