<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-GAYBASHERS-GA-7     07-08 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-GAYBASHERS-GA-750&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK RACISTS ACCUSE WHITE GAYS OF NEIGHBORHOOD `TAKEOVER'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Atlanta)   (This ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent newspaper in
London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 750; TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,100
WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA, GA. _ Jonathan Huff and Randy Brazee knew they had a
problem when someone hurled a brick through the window of their car
outside the house they own together in the Atlanta neighborhood of
Kirkwood.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapped around it was a note with a curt message. It read:
``Move out of Kirkwood now, snowflakes!'' Snowflake, they later
discovered, is a derogatory term some black Americans use for white
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   That was in March. Not long afterwards, Jonathan, a computer
systems manager, was listening to a radio show while at work at
Georgia Tech in downtown Atlanta. What he heard stunned him.
</P>
<P>
   Someone called Amos Moore, a black minister of the Baptist
Church, was accusing whites, and especially white homosexuals, of
invading Kirkwood and trying to take it away from its mostly black
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan, 28, understood at once. Months before, he and his
longtime partner Randy, 30, had successfully sued a black neighbor
for selling cocaine and other drugs out of her house, and this was
payback time.
</P>
<P>
   But something else was going on. This minister, whom he had
never heard of, was clearly trying to stir a black campaign to oust
all whites, gay and straight, from Kirkwood.
</P>
<P>
   The suburb remains at least 80 percent black. Of the whites who
have moved there, about half are homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Moore was airing a noxious mix of grievances. Among
them was his claim that the few gay households in Kirkwood _ there
are about 20 _ were setting about recruiting black youths to the
gay lifestyle by flying rainbow flags outside their homes, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   They were importing AIDS into the area, he went on, and by doing
up their houses they were driving up property prices and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This last point may have had some legitimacy. Just to the east
of the center, Kirkwood is an unassuming neighborhood of modest
turn-of-the-century homes that for decades has been almost entirely
populated by low-income blacks.
</P>
<P>
   A slow influx by prosperous young whites over recent years has
begun a gradual process of gentrification. An active neighborhood
association of blacks and whites has made strides in driving out
litter and crime. Rapidly rising house values have been an
inevitable consequence.
</P>
<P>
   But the notion of an anti-white, anti-gay hate campaign was much
harder to stomach. Atlanta is a proud symbol of racial integration,
a city where almost all the political power lies with blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Jonathan and Randy and many friends were themselves
the victims of prejudice and discrimination by blacks _ a classic
case, it seemed, of the oppressed turning into the oppressor.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Moore has not gone away. In recent weeks, he has twice
distributed leaflets to black homes, asking them to rallies. ``Save
Our Neighborhood,'' the first once screamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are concerned about the `white takeover' of Kirkwood,
come meet with us...to discuss how we can put an end to the
homosexual and lesbian takeover of our neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   A second leaflet called for an end to ``apartheid'' in Kirkwood
and declared: ``Don't let AIDS take over our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy, who works for a mobile-phone company, says it is the
racism that upsets him most, even more than the gay-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just in awe that this is happening in 1998. What he is
saying is just perpetuating racism and it's just plain scary.''
Jonathan adds: ``If his stance were a religious one, I wouldn't
care. But for him to viciously and publicly say these things is
frightening, and it's just wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Atlanta is appalled too. ``This city is what it is
because of all the people who are here, including straights and
gays,'' declared the city council president, Robb Pitts. ``We are
grateful and thankful to the gay community for their
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's defunct community relations board is to be
resurrected specifically to seek ways to defuse the tension in
Kirkwood.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, meanwhile, a special town meeting on the issue
was held at City Hall. At the meeting, Moore was unrepentant,
saying: ``The Bible says homosexuality has no place in the kingdom
of heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the gathering, he was heckled by Jimmie Scott, a gay man
who is black. ``How can you call yourself a man of God and preach
hate?'' he wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate you, because God hates you,'' the Reverend replied. ``I
don't have to condemn you, because God condemns you.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Moore's outbursts have helped to feed another debate
now getting widespread attention in the U.S. It is about the
alleged unwillingness of the black community generally, and
especially black churches, to come to terms with homosexuality and
to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   While inclusion of homosexuals has been vigorously discussed by
predominantly white denominations, it is not on the agenda of any
of the mainstream black churches.
</P>
<P>
   The head-in-the-sand attitude to gay sex and AIDS in most black
churches comes at a time when new statistics show that 57 percent
of new HIV infections in America are among black people, whether
caused by homosexual or heterosexual contact or through drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Black Americans account for only 13 percent of the whole
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception is that homosexuality is not a reality in our
church,'' said the Rev. Tim McDonald of Atlanta's Concerned Black
Clergy. ``That's a problem that white folks have.'' If there are
black ministers in denial about homosexuality, the Rev. Moore is
surely among them. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moore and his poisonous rhetoric will surely fade in time. If
there are many supporting him, they are not showing themselves: at
the City Hall meeting, there was barely a handful at his side.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could I find anyone in Kirkwood willing to speak up for him.
``It doesn't bother me at all,'' said Agnes Langston, 51, when
asked about the new gay households.
</P>
<P>
   A black resident in Kirkwood for 30 years and a close neighbor
of Jonathan and Randy, she celebrates their court action that
forced the closing of the crack house on Kirkwood Road. She has no
desire to meet the Rev. Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Langston also agrees that since the whites started coming in,
the area has become more pleasant. ``It's calmer, there's no more
litter and no more drugs.'' But she also acknowledges the potential
downside of gentrification. ``Those taxes,'' she says. ``Someone's
got to fix that.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
