<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESLIE'S BIRTHDAY PRESENT: A VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks breathed a big sigh
of relief Tuesday night as they snapped a losing streak at five
games with a 86-79 victory over the Eastern Conference-leading
Charlotte Sting.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika converted two crucial 3-pointers in the final two
minutes and Lisa Leslie celebrated her 26th birthday with 24 points
before 5,927 at the Forum. Tamecka Dixon had 19 points and Penn
Toler and Mabika had 15 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really were prepared,'' said a happy Sparks coach, Julie
Rousseau. ``Two days of practice really helped out. We can do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (3-7) found a way by reducing their turnovers (they
had 14) while being aggressive offensively and defensively. They
shot 52 percent from the field, had 12 steals and scored 20 points
alone on the Sting mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks held the lead from early in the first half, but the
Sting (8-3) tied the score twice in the final minutes. Andrea
Stinson (21 points) made a 14-foot jumper to give Charlotte its
last tie, 74-74, with 3:07 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie grabbed her own miss to regain the lead (76-74) and
Mabika hit a 3-pointer with 2:03 on the clock to make it 79-75. She
made another long one with 32.5 seconds left. Then the Sparks broke
the Stings' press, Sandra VanEmbrics made a layup and that was
that. The Sting scored two baskets in the last three seconds, but
it was too little and way too late.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a while the Sparks were in control in the
first half, leading 42-37 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few lapses, they were effective defensively, making
steals and creating problems for the Sting. And the Sparks got
better offensive production from their leaders with Leslie scoring
14 points, Dixon 10 and Toler nine.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks gained the lead for good on a Leslie free throw with
11:35 left. They were ahead by was many as 10 twice in the last two
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, if we can put two halves together, we can win,''
Toler said. ``I thought everybody played great, even off the bench.
I thought that was a great, great team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sparks note: Mabika was fined $350 by the WNBA for throwing
an arm at Utah's 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
