<SLUG> BC-BBO-SMITH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COORS FIELD STEALS A BIT OF SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ It takes a mile-high amount of hype for a ball park to
push its way to stardom among a host of major league All-Stars.
Coors Field did just that on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Strange things were happening a mile above sea level. And when
they occurred, it certified the troubles the home team Rockies have
seen since they set out to prove that major league hitters can be
contained no matter how thin the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   That things are different here was never more apparent than when
Baltimore's Roberto Alomar hit an opposite-field home run off of
San Diego's Trevor Hoffman in the sixth inning, this after
appearing to bail out on the pitch and swinging with his heart and
his back foot practically in the on-deck circle.
</P>
<P>
   As Alomar circled the bases and helped the American League flex
its muscles all the more in a 13-8 victory, his teammate, Cal
Ripken Jr., could be seen laughing in disbelief in the visitors'
dugout. The homer was the highlight of the night, not only for
Alomar, the most valuable player, but also for a ball park that
chopped down offensive record after record.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a different kind of All-Star Game, with a lot of
scoring,'' said Alomar, owner of three of the record-tying 31 hits
and scorer of 2 of the record 21 runs in the game. ``In this ball
park, it's what is expected.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager and an A.L. coach, was
thinking as much as he watched the runs pile up. For it was Torre
who aptly described just what kind of baseball this is when losing
many a game here while managing the Cardinals. ``Arena baseball,''
he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   The last Ping-Pong shot over the fence usually decides the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland of the Marlins, who managed the National League
All-Stars, seemed to sense just that during the game when he could
not define his strategy, simply saying, ``In this park you never
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Hargrove of Cleveland, the American League's
manager, who once managed a mile high while with a Colorado Springs
farm club, knew what might come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It played pretty much as I expected,'' Hargrove said. ``The
one thing that I had forgotten is how deeply the outfielders play
to make up for the thin air.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Baylor, the manager of the Rockies for all their six years
in the majors, learned those Coors Field nuances long ago. He has
also watched the track meet of scorers rounding the bases without
end. Once earlier this year, his Rockies scored 7 runs in a game _
only to lose by 11. On Tuesday night, Baylor, a coach for the N.L.
squad, watched the home team All-Stars score a half dozen runs by
the fifth, but still trail by four heading into the bottom of the
eighth in what would become the highest scoring All-star Game,
surpassing the record set in 1954 when the A.L. won, 11-9.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez had three hits, a record for a catcher in an
All-Star Game. And the Texas Ranger played only six innings.
</P>
<P>
   And as always in Coors Field, the carnage could have been much
worse. For the A.L. stranded 11 runners, the N.L. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The fans love this kind of ball when Rockies' hides are not on
the line. So they came primed for action. No 2-0 games would do, as
Chicagoans had to settle for when the All-Star Game was played in
that other hitters' park, Wrigley Field, in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The record Coors Field crowd of 51,267 cheered the approach of
every notable home run hitter, especially those chasing Roger
Maris' single-season record of 61.
</P>
<P>
   The masses groaned when Ken Griffey Jr. popped out with runners
on first and third and no outs in the first inning. They booed when
Mark McGwire was walked with a runner on third and no outs in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   They wished for heroics when the former local favorite Andres
Galarraga flied to the warning track in the sixth, just missing a
three-run home run. Even a reviled Rockies rival turned the cheers
around when Barry Bonds of the Giants hit his first All-Star home
run, becoming only the second son, after Griffey, to join his
father in the roll call of All-Star home run hitters.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of offensive mayhem that has sent pitchers
scurrying from the N.L. West club as quickly as they could and
caused observers to question the sanity of any pitcher who comes
here voluntarily. (Darryl Kile, what were you thinking?)
</P>
<P>
   Andy Ashby knows. An All-Star from the Padres, he had his nerves
worn here as a member of the original Rockies. When asked before
the game if he knew how to pitch well here, Ashby laughed and said,
``I didn't know when I was here.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys headed for the Hall of Fame didn't seem to have much of
a clue either. Roger Clemens of the Blue Jays was rocketed for two
runs in one inning. The usually unflappable Tom Glavine of the
Braves walked in a run, an unheard-of slip by one of the legion of
Cy Young pitchers from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Leyland could only lament and commiserate with the
full-time residents of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a Coors Field game,'' the Marlins' manager
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 0153EDT &QL; 
