<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-ALOMAR-NY     07-08 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-ALOMAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MVP STAYS IN THE ALOMAR FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ For the first time, two brothers have not only earned
the most valuable player trophy in the All-Star Game, but they have
done it in consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   With a home run and two singles, Roberto Alomar, the Orioles'
second baseman, was voted the mvp on Tuesday night in the American
League's 13-8 victory. A year ago in Cleveland, his older brother,
Sandy Alomar, the Indians' catcher, hit the game-winning homer in
the A.L.'s 3-1 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a tough moment; our grandmother had just passed
away, and Sandy got the trophy,'' Roberto Alomar was saying now.
``This year, I won it.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a disappointing season for the Orioles, who were
considered a challenger to the Yankees in the A.L. East. But with a
38-50 record, they have dropped 26{ games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Their owner, Peter Angelos, has talked of trading several
Orioles later this season. One possibility is that Roberto, who
will be a free agent after the season, will join his brother in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a dream for me to play with Sandy on the same
team,'' Roberto said, ``but we don't know if it's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the A.L. starters, Roberto Alomar stayed in the game the
longest. Mike Hargrove, the A.L. manager, explained that Ray
Durham, the White Sox second baseman, and Scott Brosius, the Yankee
third baseman, were two of his most versatile backups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to keep Ray out as long as I could,'' Hargrove said.
``Having Robbie Alomar in a ball game for a long time doesn't hurt
a winning effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar beat out a bunt in the first inning, popped out in the
third, walked in the fourth, singled off second baseman Craig
Biggio's glove in the sixth and soon stole third base and scored on
a passed ball, then hit a home run off the Padres' Trevor Hoffman
in the seventh for a 9-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to be prepared to come and play the whole
game, especially when you're playing in a National League ball
park,'' Alomar said. ``You have to leave some guys behind, just in
case it's a tied ball game at the end. I was surprised I played
eight innings, but I was ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar was not surprised by the highest-scoring game in All-Star
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always watched baseball on TV,'' he said. ``When you
watch the scoring in Denver, you're always seeing big numbers, 13
to 6, 13 to 7. This was a different kind of All-Star Game, a lot of
scoring. But in this ball park, that's what you expect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
