<HEADER>
A4892 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALLSTAR-SPI &LR;      07-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALLSTAR-SPI </SLUG>
  
 AL rains hits in record All-Star slugfest  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ When neither All-Star team scored in the first two
innings at Coors Field Tuesday night, you began to wonder if good
pitching still stops good hitting at a mile-high altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   Although the anticipated longball extravaganza never
materialized, the American League used homers from Mariner
shortstop Alex Rodriguez and Baltimore Orioles second baseman
Roberto Alomar, a barrage of singles and record number of stolen
bases to defeat the National League 13-8 in the highest-scoring
All-Star game ever.
</P>
<P>
   Also the longest.
</P>
<P>
   The 69th Midsummer Classic took an American League-like three
hours and 38 minutes to play. That is 28 minutes longer than the
July 15, 1954, game that also had been the previous
highest-scoring, nine-inning game.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, an Alomar won the MVP trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto picked up where his older brother, Sandy, left off last
season. Roberto's three hits, including a home run, earned him the
award Tuesday. Sandy won it last year in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back brother MVPs was a first, but just one of
several strange happenings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   How unusual was this game?
</P>
<P>
   The AL had more stolen bases (5) than home runs (2).
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Indians pitcher Bartolo Colo surrendered a three-run
homer to San Francisco Giants outfielder Barry Bonds in the fifth
inning and still was the winning pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' 451-foot blast remarkably hit the ``SF'' logo on the
upper-deck facade in right-center field, right next to a ``Hit it
Here'' sign. A hit there would have made one of the 51,267 fans an
instant millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   But in a game that produced 31 hits and 21 runs, a throw from
left field might have been the key play.
</P>
<P>
   The National League, trailing 10-6 entering the eighth inning,
loaded the bases off Boston Red Sox closer Tom Gordon. The
right-hander, who leads the AL in saves with 25, found himself in a
bases-loaded, none-out predicament after Moises Alou singled, Edgar
Renteria reached on third baseman Scott Brosius' error and former
Mariner Fernando Vina walked.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hitter Greg Vaughn slapped a two-run single to left and
Devon White also singled to left field. Vina chugged from second to
third and was waved home by third-base coach Rich Donnely.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, who normally plays right field for the Yankees,
charged the ball in left and came up throwing. Vina was nailed at
the plate for the inning's first out, and former Rockies star
Andres Galarraga bounced into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   The blown opportunity to get back in the game stunned the
capacity crowd.
</P>
<P>
   And the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't talked to him (Donnely) about it,'' NL manager Jim
Leyland said. ``It might have been a situation, to be honest with
you, where he thought the ball might go to second base because of
the score. But (he) got burned by it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said Vina may have been fooled on the ball White hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a ball that was a sure hit, and I'm sure the guy
(Vina) had to hold up a little bit. When I got the ball, I saw that
he wasn't around third, so I figured I had a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just threw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vina, who played for the Mariners in 1993 and eventually matured
into an All-Star second baseman with the Milwaukee Brewers, was
tagged out at the plate by Sandy Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   Being too aggressive backfired for the NL. It worked fine for
the AL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into the game with the idea that we would be as
aggressive as we could be if we could get people on base,'' AL
manager Mike Hargrove said. ``We felt that if we could get our guys
like (Kenny) Lofton and (Roberto) Alomar on base early, steal some
bases and put on some pressure, we might have a better chance of
carrying it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Lofton singled and stole second in the first inning; Alomar and
Ken Griffey Jr. singled and pulled off a double-steal in a
three-run sixth; Ivan Rodriguez singled and swiped second in the
sixth; and Brosius singled, stole second and scored in the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The previous All-Star stolen base record, four, was shared by
the AL in 1990 and NL in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The game's prophet turned out to be AL starter David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference on Monday, the Yankees' perfect game
left-hander said he envisioned a high-scoring game, but not when he
was pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Wells tossed two hitless innings before the game became a
slugfest. But so did NL starter Greg Maddux, who worked out of a
bases-loaded situation in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, Atlanta Braves teammate Tom Glavine, worked one
inning and didn't work out of trouble. The AL scored four runs in
the third inning to erase a 2-0 deficit and never trailed again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 03:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-ALLSTARGAME-BOS     07-08 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
NO MARTINEZ, BUT AL STARS SHINE
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-ALLSTARGAME-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Gordon Edes 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Skipped over as the American League's starting pitcher,
Pedro Martinez went to AL manager Mike Hargrove before Tuesday
night's 69th All-Star Game and said that if Hargrove didn't need
him, he'd rather not pitch.
</P>
<P>
   A fit of pique, or a minor knot in his shoulder, as Hargrove
told a national TV audience during the game? It wasn't a knot,
Martinez said afterward, but judging by his frolics in the AL
dugout, clowning with teammates and bantering with fans, Martinez's
snit over not starting was a minor one.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Red Sox ace had a foreshadowing of what was to come
in Coors Field, already a proven vineyard of bitter wine for those
who pitch for a living and no different Tuesday night, when
offensive records fell by the fistful in the American League's 13-8
win over their National counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather wait and take the real rest and go to Baltimore for
the second half,'' Martinez said. ``If I had been the starter, I
would have taken it ... But I'm not upset.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a couple of innings for them to warm up, but hitters on
both sides seized the occasion, treating double-digit winners on
the mound as if they had just arrived on the Pawtucket shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles second baseman Robbie Alomar gave the Alomar brothers
back-to-back MVP trophies, by hitting a home run, beating out a
bunt single, and reaching on an infield hit, and executing a double
steal with Ken Griffey in the sixth inning, when the AL Stars took
the lead for good, 8-6, with three runs scored on a passed ball,
wild pitch, and Ivan Rodriguez's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not quite as dramatic as brother Sandy's game-winning home
run on his home turf in Cleveland a year ago, but it will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' said Robbie Alomar, who is the subject of
trade rumors because of the Orioles' dreadful season and could have
a new address by the end of the month. ``I didn't come here to win
an MVP. I came here to play the game of baseball, to have fun, and
to try my best to help this team win. It's a great surprise. I'm
going to take the trophy home.''
</P>
<P>
   The AL Stars, beating the NL at their own game, stole a record
five bases, homered twice, and collected 19 hits before a Coors
Field record crowd of 51,267 that witnessed the longest nine-inning
game in All-Star history. It started at 8:42 p.m. Eastern time, and
ended at 12:20 a.m., 10 minutes before the late-night talk shows
were signing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Coors Field type game _ you saw some balls bloop in, freak
hits, guys had to play deep, and then they hit some balls out of
the ballpark,'' said National League manager Jim Leyland, whose
team last led after Barry Bonds's three-run home run off
Cleveland's young fastballer, Bartolo Colon, in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland's team appeared on the verge of regaining the lead in
the eighth inning against Red Sox closer Tom Gordon until Rich
Donnelly, Leyland's third base coach in Florida, waved home
Fernando Vina on Devon White's base hit, even though there were no
out, two runs already in, and Gordon reeling from allowing five
straight base runners to reach on three singles, a walk, and an
error.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee outfielder Paul O'Neill, playing out of position in left,
made a strong throw to the plate to cut down Vina, and Cleveland
shortstop Omar Vizquel, whose selection meant Nomar Garciaparra had
to stay home, turned the kind of acrobatic double play that led
Hargrove to pick Omar over Nomar in the first place, preserving the
AL's 10-8 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I played left field? Seemed like about 20 years
ago tonight,'' O'Neill said. ``I didn't come in on the ball real
well because I wasn't real comfortable. But as soon as I got it, I
had a little momentum going to the plate and I basically threw it
as hard as I could. It ended up in the right spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams broke the record for most runs in a game scored by
both clubs, which was 20. The AL Stars tied their own record for
most runs in a game, 13, which they did twice before, the last time
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The only surprise offensively was that the expected long-ball
duel did not materialize. Only three home runs were hit, two by AL
Stars (Alomar, Seattle's Alex Rodriguez), one by the NL (Bonds).
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cy Young Award winners (Tom Glavine, Roger Clemens) nor
commoners were spared the offensive onslaught. Both starters, Greg
Maddux and David Wells, emerged unscathed, Wells having the easier
time of it while Maddux pitched out of a first-and-third, one-out
jam in the first. But after Clemens gave up two runs on Tony
Gwynn's two-run single in the third, Billerica's Glavine was raked
for four runs in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar touched off the AL's deciding rally against Montreal
reliever Ugueth Urbina in the sixth with an infield hit off the
glove of Houston second baseman Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey followed with a broken-bat bleeder that barely cleared
the pitcher's mound for an infield hit, and on an 0-and-2 count to
RBI king Juan Gonzalez, Alomar broke for third and easily beat Javy
Lopez's throw to the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who came to the plate with nine runners on base but
delivered just one with a sacrifice fly in the fourth inning,
struck out, but Cleveland strongman Jim Thome walked to load the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   The tying run came across when Urbina's fastball ticked off
catcher Lopez's glove for a passed ball, and Urbina's wild pitch
made it 7-6. Texas catcher Rodriguez, who came into the game second
in the AL in hitting with a .351 average, then lined an RBI single
to left, his third hit of the game, to make it 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar's home run off San Diego reliever Trevor Hoffman, the
brother of current Dodger manager and former Sox infielder Glenn
Hoffman, made it 9-6 in the seventh, and three straight singles in
the eighth, the last by Sandy Alomar Jr., made it 10-6. The AL
salted the game away with three runs in the ninth on three singles,
an error, and a sacrifice fly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 0306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
