<HEADER>
A4901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-BOS     07-08 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN BREAKS OFF TALKS WITH RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Gordon Edes 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Just as with Roger Clemens, who has gone to two
All-Star Games since leaving the team as a free agent, the Red Sox
apparently are prepared to take negotiations down to the zero hour
with first baseman Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's agent, Tom Reich, said here Tuesday night that talks
have broken off until after the season with the Red Sox regarding a
new contract for his client but added, ``the door is still open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment whatsoever other than the fact that we
talked,'' said Reich, who refused to confirm that the Red Sox had
made the first baseman an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Club spokesman Kevin Shea would not confirm that talks were even
held here, with CEO John Harrington and general manager Dan
Duquette both in town.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was scheduled to participate in the game after being
selected an All-Star for the third time, but he bowed out because
of a strained right hamstring and remained in Boston. He said
before the All-Star break that he planned to work out at Fenway
Park before the team leaves Wednesday for Baltimore and a start of
a four-game series with the Orioles Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald, without citing sources, reported that the Red
Sox had offered Vaughn a four-year deal worth around $37 million.
That would be a substantial increase over the last offer the Red
Sox made this spring, a two-year deal in the neighborhood of $20
million, but well below what Vaughn's representatives consider
market value for premier first basemen.
</P>
<P>
   The average value of $9.25 million a year, if accurate, is less
than the reported three-year, $30 million offer the Red Sox made to
Vaughn last December, an offer he said he was close to accepting
until the team signed pitcher Pedro Martinez to a six-year, $75
million deal, whose average value of $12.5 million is the highest
given any player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed,'' Reich said Tuesday night. ``The door is
still open. No other talks are planned until after the season. I am
not going to participate (publicly) with what's going on. It would
not have been productive in the first half of the season and it
won't be productive during the second half for the same reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Another first baseman who knows Vaughn as a friend and a rival,
Baltimore's Rafael Palmeiro, was asked before the game whether he
thought it possible that the Red Sox would not re-sign Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a mistake,'' said Palmeiro, who is also in his
free agent year and dealing with considerable speculation that the
Orioles will not re-sign him. ``I think Mo Vaughn is the Boston Red
Sox. He's one of the best players in the game and one of the most
colorful personalities. They would miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who has said he would like to stay in Boston, will have
15 days after the season to file for free agency. The Sox then
would have about another month to negotiate with Vaughn before
losing that right. The Clemens negotiations went down to the
December deadline before he said he had signed with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door's always been open and the door will stay open, but
that's it,'' Reich said. ``Mo is bound and determined not to let
contract decisions intrude into the second half. There aren't going
to be any further discussions until after the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
