<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5133 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV14-     07-08 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DON'T HAVE TO ALL STAND ALIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday July 14)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I knew a man who wore a tiny flag pin in his lapel. The pin was
to show that he was all-American. And he was, in his way.
</P>
<P>
   When he spoke of his country you'd think his heart would burst
with pride. But his heart didn't have enough room for all
Americans. He didn't like Mexicans or Jews or African-Americans, a
term he refused to use. He didn't care that much for Catholics,
either.
</P>
<P>
   But even bigots have a right to pin on the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, a Fallbrook teen-ager is in trouble for
refusing to say the pledge of allegiance. She said by refusing to
stand with her class in the morning ritual, she is protesting a
violent society and a corrupt government.
</P>
<P>
   You haven't heard about kids doing that in a while. Recently I
talked to some high school juniors and asked what cause would move
them to march in the street and none of them could come up with
anything. They're focused on mainly getting through high school.
</P>
<P>
   Political protest is kind of out of fashion in 1998. The
15-year-old, whose pulled back hair and wire rimmed glasses make
her look a little like pictures of the very young Hillary Clinton,
is rare in her willingness to stand alone on behalf of her
convictions. She had to know her act would be viewed as
disrespectful and draw the predictable heat, although it's
surprising how much national furor it's caused. It makes you wish
her issues about violence and corruption could whip up passions as
much as her simple protest.
</P>
<P>
   Those of the old ``Love it or leave it'' school were quick to
point out that there are countries far more violent and corrupt
than the United States, as if that somehow absolves us of our
slighter ills.
</P>
<P>
   I always wonder why those who want to banish dissenters to
another country don't just do the moving themselves. They'd fit
right in at a place that demands blind loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's flag burning. It would be hurtful, probably even
enraging, to see someone burn up an American flag. Personally I
think one of the best ways to show passionate disagreement in this
country is to share it in a letter to the editor, but some demand
more drama.
</P>
<P>
   That's one annoying thing about a democracy. You have to protect
the free speech of some pretty zealous ducks, including flag
burners, neo-Nazis and even the guys in suits who knock on the door
at dinnertime and want to save your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Free speech is always easy to defend when you happen to agree
with it. The real test of being an American is tolerating those
things you don't personally like.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States you can ban noisy leaf blowers, but you can
do nothing to stifle the garbage sounds made on hate radio. Except
turn off the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Some people's words are really revolting, but we can only
control so much, or the precedent comes back to muffle all of us.
Celebrities seek stringent laws to keep the paparazzi away and this
seems reasonable. So do limitations on pornography. But
``reasonable'' leads to ``unreasonable.'' We already have school
boards banning Toni Morrison's words.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the 15-year-old who protested the pledge say she has
offended those who went to war to fight for her right to free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what's the good of fighting for something if people don't
use it?
</P>
<P>
   One of the most patriotic things I've heard recently was when
Oprah Winfrey triumphed over the cattlemen who sought damages for
her show on mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment rocks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If people really want to get heated up on behalf of those who
protect freedom, they ought to consider how our military abandoned
Gulf War soldiers on the battlefield. Remember the flag-waving back
when they went to war?
</P>
<P>
   Flags and pledges and national anthems deserve our respect, but
they are just symbols. They don't make you a better American.
Refusing to say the pledge of allegiance doesn't make you a traitor
any more than wearing a flag pin makes you a patriot.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartzpressdemo.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
