two-mile Maroon Lake Scenic Trail, which is accessible by bus from
the Rubey Park transportation center in town. Information: Aspen
Chamber of Commerce, (970) 925-1940.
 &HT;    Rafting on the area's rivers is a fast-growing recreation sport.
Among the rafting companies in the area are Inland Drifters, (970)
963-7438, which charges $45 a person a half day or $75 for a full
day, and runs class 1 through class 4 rapids (6 is the most
difficult), and Blazing Adventures, (800) 282-7238, which charges
$65 to $78 for class 1 through 5.
 &HT;    Children enjoy exploring Ashcroft, a semirestored ghost town on
Castle Creek Road, 30 minutes from downtown. The Aspen Historical
Society gives free tours at 11 a.m., 1 and 3 p.m. every day but
Monday.
 &HT;    On rainy days, tours of Aspen's two silver mines, Smuggler and
Compromise, offer instructive insights into the city's origins (but
children must be 5 or older).
 &HT;    At Smuggler, visitors walk a quarter-mile into a mountain that,
in 1894, provided the world's largest silver nugget: 1,840 pounds.
Admission is $20, $15 ages 5 to 12. The Compromise tour, offered
only on Saturday after July 11, involves a Jeep ride to the mine,
then a rail ride into Aspen mountain. Fee: $30 and $20.
Reservations required: (970) 925-2049.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    Among Aspen's several luxury hotels, two Victorian red-brick
standouts are on Main Street, the Jerome at 330 East Main, and the
Sardy House at 128 East Main.
 &HT;    Built in 1889, at the height of the silver boom, the Jerome
boasted the first elevator west of the Mississippi. Painstakingly
restored a decade ago, this central Aspen landmark is one of 16
city buildings listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
 &HT;    With a fire in the parlor fireplace, elk heads on walls and
cherry wood throughout, a visitor feels like a silver baron. For a
night in one of its 93 hotel rooms, the Jerome's nightly charges
vary in the summer from $295 to as much as $1,190, for a suite;
(800) 331-7213, fax (970) 925-2784.
 &HT;    Two blocks down Main Street, half-hidden by towering pines,
stands another Victorian gem, Sardy House. This quiet hotel of 20
well-appointed rooms has a small heated swimming pool in the
garden. Summer room rates, including breakfast, vary from $180 to
$440; (970) 920-2525.
 &HT;    For a resortlike setting in town, the Aspen Institute has 98
guest rooms and suites on its 40-acre riverfront campus on the west
end of town. Guests can use the institute's six tennis courts,
gymnasium and outdoor lap pool, and have golf privileges at the
Snowmass Lodge and Club. Summer room rates are $195 to $395; (970)
925-4240.
 &HT;    Budget: The Limelite Lodge at 228 East Cooper Ave., was the
cradle of the 1950's folk group The Limeliters when it was a
nightclub. Now, it is a family-oriented hotel, with 72 rooms, some
with kitchens, starting at $98 in summer; (970) 925-3025.
 &HT;    The Boomerang Lodge at 500 West Hopkins Avenue has 34 sun-filled
units, each with a private balcony or terrace offering a view of
Shadow Mountain. Rooms in summer start at $131, including
Continental breakfast; (970) 925-3416.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    Aspen's nearly 100 restaurants have spruced up their summer
menus and honed their service in anticipation of the Food and Wine
Magazine Classic, taking place this weekend. Among them is Pinons,
105 South Mill St., where entrees include sauteed Colorado pheasant
breast and elk tenderloin. Dinner for two, with wine, is about
$120; (970) 920-2021.
 &HT;    The Little Nell, in the hotel of the same name, at 675 East
Durant Ave. is a personal favorite. In the elegant dining room or
sunny courtyard, diners enjoy mustard crusted trout or
honey-soy-seared salmon. Dinner for two with wine is around $150;
Hours: 7 a.m. to 10 p.m.; (970) 920-6330.
 &HT;    Outdoor dining with a view of Aspen Mountain can also be found
down the block, at Ajax Tavern, 685 East Durant. On a terrace near
the ski area's gondola as well in the dining room, diners can eat
local foods like free range chicken and Colorado lamb. Dinner for
two with wine costs about $100. Lunch and dinner served; (970)
920-9333.
 &HT;    A midpriced standout is Campo di Fiori, 205 South Mill St., an
earthy grotto with well-prepared Northern Italian dishes, a strong
Italian wine list and rapid-fire service. Try the arugula salad and
the risotto giardinera (asparagus, tomato, spinach and bell
peppers). Open for dinner daily. Dinner for two with wine costs
about $80; (970) 920-7717.
 &HT;    On the second floor of a bookstore at 221 East Main, Explore
Bistro offers vegetarian meals _ breakfast, lunch and dinner _ on a
sundeck or inside. Dinner for two with a drink is about $40; (970)
925-5338.
 &HT;    La Cocina, 308 East Hopkins Ave., a local hangout with
Southwestern cuisine, draws everyone from ski lift operators to
Hollywood types. Margaritas, blue corn tortillas and chocolate
velvet, a mousselike cake, add up to about $35 for two; (970)
925-9714.
 &HT;    Woody Creek Tavern is a timeless joint held together with
cigarette smoke, country music and old wallpaper five miles out of
town, in Woody Creek. The burger of local Limousin beef goes for
$6.95 and the chicken fajitas are $8.95. No credit cards. Don't ask
for espresso; (970) 923-4585.
 NIGHT LIFE  
 &HT;    After serving surprisingly good cabaret food, the waiters and
waitresses at the Crystal Palace, 300 East Hyman Ave., transform
themselves into a hilarious satirical revue.
 &HT;    During their annual spring break, they undoubtedly wore pencils
to the nub reworking fresh material supplied from our nation's
capital. Dinner and one-hour show are offered Thursday through
Saturday for $49.50 a person. For reservations, call (970)
925-1455.
 &HT;     (James Brooke is chief of the Denver bureau of The New York
Times.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 James Brooke  
