<SLUG> BC-PALM-SPRING'S-LURE-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: 
 SIZZLING SUMMER SAVINGS AROUND PALM SPRINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    From the days of Al Capone through the glittery era of Frank
Sinatra, Bob Hope and Dinah Shore, we mature travelers have been
bedazzled by stories of Palm Springs, Calif. But who can afford
that kind of playground except movie stars?
 &HT;    Today, little has changed in classy Palm Springs and its
neighboring communities in the Coachella Valley, which is about 120
miles east of Hollywood in the desert _ little, that is, except the
cost of having a good time.
 &HT;    Play golf for $20 a round on uncrowded courses? Stay at a resort
for $49 a night? Eat at outstanding restaurants and get pampered in
the spas? Find discounts at almost every attraction without waiting
in line?
 &HT;    Yes, it's true.
 &HT;    Indeed, mature travelers who shop around, do their homework and
pick the proper season can experience the joys of Palm Springs for
about $100 a day per person. That season is summer. The downside:
the heat.
 &HT;    No longer does Palm Springs shut down between June and
September, as it used to when resident celebrities fled to cooler
climes. One marketing executive at a local resort explained it this
way: It is less expensive for restaurants, hotels and other travel
vendors to stay open during the summer than to have to lay off
staff as the heat approaches and hire new, green help in the fall.
 &HT;    The result: During the summer, there are restaurants with more
waiters than customers, rooms with good rates and golf tee-times
almost anytime you want.
 &HT;    Many of Palm Springs' bargains, in fact, stay in place through
mid-December.
 BEATING THE HEAT  
 &HT;    We visited Palm Springs and the Coachella Valley for a few days
late last June, when daytime temperatures were already over 100. We
played lots of golf, swam almost every afternoon, enjoyed some fine
naps under misters in the shade, took evening walks and did our
sightseeing _ mostly to air-conditioned places _ in the early
afternoon.
 &HT;    Our formula for enjoying the Palm Springs heat is to plan ahead
and move slowly.
 &HT;    Our early morning tee times meant we were able to enjoy the
benefit of a comforting breeze and, as a bonus, we learned that the
desert is prettiest at the beginning of the day.
 &HT;    If it got too hot for us to finish 18 holes _ at only $15 to $30
a round _ we simply quit the course and cooled down in the
clubhouse.
 &HT;    We started at 7:30 one morning at Del Webb's Sun City Palm
Desert (760-772-2200 for tee times). A few golfers were on the
course ahead of us, but there was never a wait to play. At that
course, visitors pay $80 a round in winter but only about $30 in
summer.
 &HT;    The next day, with a 6:30 a.m. tee-off, we played the
championship course at Marriott's Rancho Las Palmas resort
(760-862-4551). It costs $109 a round in winter, $48 in summer. We
finished 18 holes before noon, beating the heat again.
 &HT;    Several great courses have summer ``twilight'' rates: $20 for 18
holes after 10:30 a.m. at Rancho Las Palmas before the heat or
darkness get to you.
 &HT;    Darkness doesn't blanket Palm Springs until about 7 p.m., which
means golf fanatics can play late into the evening. However, our
original plan to play nine holes in the early morning and another
nine just before dark didn't work. Frankly, it's too hot in the
early evening _ coolness comes to the desert at night.
 &HT;    On getaway day we started to play at about 8 a.m. at Tommy
Jacobs' Bel Air Greens (760-322-6062), an easy nine-hole course
that is almost entirely shaded.
 &HT;    Last June, it cost $15 a round. If we had waited a month,
between July and September, Bel Air would have charged $14 a round
_ and handed out two-for-one passes.
 LODGING DEALS  
 &HT;    This year, summer specials at Palm Spring's hotels may not be as
spectacular as last year due to increased occupancies. (Seems more
people are realizing the benefits of vacationing in the desert!)
But mature travelers can still find spectacle savings if they shop
wisely.
 &HT;    Last June, our $69 room at Marriott's Rancho Las Palmas in
Rancho Mirage (800-909-6019) _ one of the leading resorts _ cost
$179 or more last winter.
 &HT;    One of the best lodging deals we found was a $49-a-night
weeknight summer special at the Palm Springs Spa Hotel &AMP; Casino,
operated by the Cahuilla tribe and located right in downtown Palm
Springs. That price included a room for two, a spa session, dinner
two-fers and $10 in casino chips. January through mid-June, those
rooms cost up to $159 without the extras.
 &HT;    Public transit around the valley is practically useless to
tourists, and most summer visitors rent autos or bring their own.
 &HT;    We spent early afternoons touring in cool places: the
air-conditioned Palm Springs Desert Museum; the well-shaded,
outdoor Living Desert Wildlife Park; and the new Palm Springs Air
Museum. All give senior discounts of up to 50 percent.
 TAKE A TOUR  
 &HT;    Celebrity Tours' (760-770-2700) 2 1/2-hour trips show you where
the stars live and include a pickup in an air-conditioned
motorcoach at your hotel. Mature travelers get $2 off the regular
$17 tour price.
 &HT;    The easiest way to beat the heat is to ride the Palm Springs
Aerial Tramway (760-325-1449) to the top of the 12,000-foot Mount
San Jacinto. Bring a jacket _ it's 30 degrees cooler high above the
desert floor. Mature travelers get $3 off $17 tram tickets.
 &HT;    The Palm Springs Desert Resorts Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau
operates centers in Rancho Mirage and at the Palm Springs Regional
Airport. For more information, call (800) 417-3529, or write 69-930
Hwy. 111 201, Rancho Mirage, Calif. 92270.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    _______ 
 &HT;     (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 The Mature Traveler Newsletter  
