<HEADLINE>
HAPPY (SKI) TRAILS IN SOUTH AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    For passionate skiers, the season doesn't end when the mountain
bikes come out in Colorado and Utah. Summer is the time to get on a
plane and head south to Chile and Argentina.
 &HT;    North America may be enjoying hot weather, but south of the
border you'll find snow falling in the rugged Andes.
 &HT;    ``Last year was a great year for snow down there,'' explains
Gary Nicoll, manager of Ski Vacation Planners. ``We're hoping for
the same this year.''
 &HT;    The resorts of Chile and Argentina promise challenging runs,
glorious mountain scenery and a laid-back Latin lifestyle. The
resorts usually open in mid-June and close around the first week of
October.
 &HT;    There are daily direct flights from Miami to Santiago and Buenos
Aires. Remember that this is a good time to use frequent-flier
miles for both tickets and upgrades.
 &HT;    The flights may be long _ about eight hours from Miami to
Santiago _ but the good news is that jetlag, the bane of many
European ski vacations, is minimal for North Americans heading
south.
 &HT;    In Chile, the major resorts to consider are Portillo, Valle
Nevado, Termas de Chillan.
 &HT;    Portillo, about 92 miles from Santiago, has spectacular
surroundings, including the 23,000-foot Cerro Aconcagua, the
highest peak in the Americas.
 &HT;    There is plenty of beginner and intermediate terrain here, as
well as enough expert terrain, including chutes, to keep advanced
skiers busy for a week.
 &HT;    Just 37 miles from Santiago is Valle Nevado, a vast resort with
over 40 miles of groomed runs, with all skiing above the treeline.
 &HT;    Skiers can also access two adjacent areas, La Parva and El
Colorado.
 &HT;    Valle Nevado has a village not unlike that at the Canadian
resort of Whistler. The skiing is varied, with plenty of
intermediate and expert terrain.
 &HT;    Termas de Chillan, located about 300 miles south of Santiago,
has emerged as one of the most popular ski resorts in the country.
 &HT;    A hot springs resort that dates back to the 17th century, it has
a vast amounts of terrain, including one run that it is 6.8 miles
long.
 &HT;    In July of 1997, the Gran Hotel Termas de Chillan opened, the
first five-star deluxe hotel at the resort.
 &HT;    Las Lenas, San Carlos de Bariloche and Chapelco are the primary
areas in Argentina.
 &HT;    Las Lenas has some of the most challenging terrain on Earth,
with over 40 miles of trails. It is the choice for expert skiers
and for powder-hounds looking for some of that fabled Andes snow.
 &HT;    San Carlos de Bariloche is the only town in South America with a
traditional ski culture. Picturesquely located on the shores of
Lake Nahuel Huapi, it long ago earned the moniker ``Little
Switzerland.''
 &HT;    The ski mountain, Cerro Catedral, is about 12 miles from town.
There is so much terrain here that both intermediates and advanced
skiers have plenty of opportunity to explore.
 &HT;    Chapelco is located 12 miles outside of the lakeside resort town
of San Martin de Los Andes. It offers tree-skiing and steep chutes
for experts only. The resort is accessed via an air connection from
Bariloche.
 &HT;    High season in Chile and Argentina, which runs from mid-July to
mid-August, is based on South American school holidays and should
be avoided. Both prices and crowds can be nearly double what they
are in low-season.
 &HT;    Mid-August is generally regarded as the best time for North
Americans to go while ``spring'' skiing arrives in early September,
with a season's worth of snowfall and lodging discounts everywhere.
 &HT;    Anyone shopping around for a South American ski vacation should
look to a specialist, such as Ski Vacation Planners (545 Cedar
Lane, Teaneck, N.J. 07666; 800-822-6754) or Adventures on Skis (815
North Road, Westfield, Mass. 01085; 800-628-9655).
 &HT;    Both companies have established reputations in planning such
trips and can easily arrange add-ons in Santiago or Buenos Aires.
 &HT;    Here's a selection of packages. Prices are per person and are
based on double occupancy in mid- to late-August.
 &HT;    Adventures on Skis offers a package to Las Lenas that includes
round-trip airfare between Miami, Buenos Aires and Malargue,
round-trip airport transfers, seven nights' lodging at the Hotel
Escorpio, daily lift tickets, as well as daily breakfast and dinner
for $2,575.
 &HT;    In Chile, they have Termas de Chillan in late August that
includes round-trip airfare from Miami to Santiago and round-trip
airfare from Santiago to Concepcion. Skiers also receive transfers,
seven nights' accommodation at the Grand Hotel Termas de Chillan, a
weekly lift ticket, breakfast and dinner daily. The price starts at
$2,170.
 &HT;    Ski Vacation Planners has a deal to Portillo that starts at
$1,315 for seven nights' accommodation at the Hotel Portillo, four
meals daily, eight full-day lift tickets for $1,315, land only.
Round-trip airfare from Miami to Santiago is $954. Transfers are
extra.
 &HT;    In Argentina, they can offer Bariloche for $1,497, land-only, at
the Club Hotel Catedral, at the base of the mountain. The price
includes seven nights' accommodation, daily breakfast and dinner.
Lift tickets and transfers are extra. Airfare from Miami to Buenos
Aires to Bariloche is $1,321.
