<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Between flames, Citrus plant auction a success
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When a federal judge orders a bankruptcy
sale, it takes more than last week's brush fires to delay it.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart auctioneer Karlin Daniel, 47, belted out his rap _
``Sixty-five hundred there! Do I hear 7,000?'' _ for four hours
recently at a Brevard County citrus packing plant, despite heat,
smoke and ash from brush fires burning out of control several miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   A federal bankruptcy judge in Orlando had ordered the sale of
the items owned by the Mims Citrus Growers Association, Daniel
said. The growers' cooperative filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy on
Feb. 6 and closed in late March after the federal court declared
its finances unsalvageable.
</P>
<P>
   The auction had even greater attendance than Daniel usually gets
for such auctions because Brevard County sheriff's deputies were
coincidentally directing traffic toward the auction from a detour
due to the fire. Just east of the packing plant, the deputies had
blocked U.S. 1 at State Road 46 to give firefighters further north
room to battle the brush fires.
</P>
<P>
   The 500 people who attended the auction were not in an affected
area and were not in any danger, a sheriff's spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, however, deputies evacuated about 200 bidders
inspecting auction items at the packing plant.
</P>
<P>
   The co-op's assets _ including a 14-acre citrus grove close to
but spared by the fires, an 11,500-square-foot packing plant and 58
citrus trailers _ raked in nearly $1 million for creditors, Daniel
said. Successful bidders picked up their prizes in Mims on Friday
and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun,'' Daniel said. ``In retrospect.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
