A5169 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-ANIMALS09-COX     07-08 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-ANIMALS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Animals routed by fire still scared, confused
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUNNELL, Fla. _ These animals don't have to talk. Their terror
and confusion are all too plain, in the eyes peering out of small
cages, the burned and bandaged feet of a puppy, the way horses
quietly place their heads against owners' chests, as if asking to
be held.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't over for the pets, livestock and wild animals routed by
fire. Some are still out in the smoking woods, cut off from their
homes, hiding in culverts, drainage ditches, under cars or in
garbage cans, disoriented and traumatized.
</P>
<P>
   Chaos still had the upper hand at times around the animal
control shelter at the Flagler County fairgrounds, as groups and
volunteers tried to reconnect scores of animals and owners
separated by fire and evacuation. Besides the dogs, cats, birds and
rabbits on hand, loads of horses, pigs, goats and other animals had
been farmed out to shelters in Jacksonville, Gainesville and
Palatka and were due back by nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, the problem changed from finding shelter space to
caring for abandoned, lost and injured animals.
</P>
<P>
   Animal control officers told horrifying stories of how people
fleeing the fires left dogs chained to trees and fences, in yard
kennels or in houses with no food and water. And the miracles of
their survival.
</P>
<P>
   At one address in Palm Coast, officer Rick Kinard found the
house and two vehicles burned to the ground. In a sandy spot in the
back yard, a terrified Rottweiler and bulldog were huddled
together; in a cage attached to the only part of the wooden fence
that didn't burn was a little Pekingese.
</P>
<P>
   At another house in Palm Coast, officers found an elderly, weak
and bedraggled miniature poodle and a young Dalmatian, both without
food or water. By day's end, Kinard had found the owner and filed
cruelty charges against her.
</P>
<P>
   There were worse accounts, such as the sheriff's deputy who used
his nightstick to try to bash open the chains holding three dogs,
was attacked and had to leave them as the flames moved in. But the
most gripping story was one of danger, heroism and mother's love.
</P>
<P>
   A matronly female hound and her 3-month-old pup had run from
who-knows-where through smoldering ground that burned the pup's
tender paws. She stopped, dug a deep hole in the dirt for the puppy
to lie in and stood guard over him.
</P>
<P>
   She stood her ground against the well-meaning people who first
tried to help them. But Kinard and his wife, Darlene, also an
animal control officer, gradually won her trust. Tired, hurt and
trusting, she lay down and let them carry her and the pup to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   The pup, with his singed feet covered by bright orange
``socks,'' has become a media star and shelter celebrity. Volunteer
Paul Borruso is pretty sure an owner will show up to claim the two,
but if it doesn't happen by Friday, he's volunteered to be a
``foster'' owner. Borruso and his wife, Connie, recently moved to
nearby Ormond Beach from Boca Raton, where he was with IBM.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles south on U.S.1 at Eagle Rock Ranch, Pam Cochran
waited for all her boarding horses to come home from various places
and recalled the night of panicked evacuation. She and her husband
and two daughters had gotten eight horses to the shelter, including
two thoroughbreds picked up along the highway, only to find they
were gone and nobody could tell her where they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was called The Mad Lady,'' by the shelter staff, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The horses had been sent to Palatka to stay at the fairgrounds
there, then to Jacksonville. The confusion left Cochran and other
owners realizing they need a disaster plan for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle fared reasonably well in Flagler County, where most are
kept in vast, cleared pastures that served as firebreaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They's a lot of fences burned,'' said cattleman Leslie Tucker,
``but everything else is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers' herds may be mixed up, but that's all right, Tucker
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody around here pretty much knows their own cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
