r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILNER-COLUMN09-COX     07-08 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOOKREVIEW: Folklore from the largest State
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Texana books collectors must love the University
of North Texas Press and the people who operate it. They're always
coming out with books that remind us of our diverse and rich
heritage in this big state.
</P>
<P>
   For example: ``Boardin' in the Big Thicket'' by Wanda A Landrey.
Some call this a history book with recipes and some call it a
recipe book with a lot
</P>
<P>
   of history in it. Either way you label it, this is a book worth
having, and the UNT Press has recently released a paperback
edition.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Leon Hale, the Houston Chronicle columnist and
I-don't-know-what-all, wrote about it when it came out the first
time in hardback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wanda Landrey causes me to remember a special day, long ago,
when I ate sweet potato pie at the Bragg Hotel in the Big Thicket.
This book makes me
</P>
<P>
   hungry, not just for the boarding house dishes Wanda describes,
but also for a time in Texas culture that is gone forever.''
</P>
<P>
   A reviewer in the Bloomsbury Review had this to say, among other
things: ``Pioneers in southeast Texas found a little Eden in the
Big Thicket...The
</P>
<P>
   woods were filled with delicacies like nuts and wild fruit...The
commerce that crisscrossed the region created a network of boarding
houses, with a
</P>
<P>
   unique cooking style that took advantage of the bounty of the
land.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, with the acquisition of a batch of Encino Press
books, all Texas Folklore Society publications still in print are
now available from
</P>
<P>
   UNT Press. A few of those include:
</P>
<P>
   ``Aunt Puss &AMP; Others, Old Days in the Piney Woods'' by Emma
Wilson Emery. Published in 1969. Emma Wilson Emery spent her
childhood in the Big Thicket
</P>
<P>
   piney woods with many interesting relatives. She later lived in
Nacogdoches and worked as typesetter for the Daily Plaindealer. She
graduated from
</P>
<P>
   nursing school in 1911 at Shreveport and became poet laureate of
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's Going On?'' (In Modern Texas Folklore), edited by F.E.
Abernethy. Publication of the Texas Folklore Society XL, published
in 1976. This
</P>
<P>
   collection of essays from the 1970s describes the customs,
traditions, songs, and stories by which future anthropologists will
analyze the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The rodeos and chain letters and bumper stickers, Neiman Marcus
and fat stock shows, gospel conventions and underground newspapers,
CB radios and
</P>
<P>
   university ghosts, backwoods beer busts and the folklore of
marijuana, Jack Ruby and the Kennedy assassination. This book also
looks at zydeco, Western
</P>
<P>
   Swing, gospel music, Texas country music, and the rise of
redneck rock. ``Texas Folk Medicine'' by John Q. Anderson.
Published in 1970. The list of
</P>
<P>
   ``cures'' from acne to whooping cough will bring to mind your
grandparents' methods for removing warts, stopping hiccups, or
relieving the aches of
</P>
<P>
   rheumatism.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these folk medical practices are older than scientific
medicine. Some reflect a belief in magic. Seldom written down, this
oral lore has been
</P>
<P>
   passed down from generation to generation from the time of the
first settlements in this country. Science has shown that many have
no therapeutic
</P>
<P>
   value, but some do and the power of suggestion was enough for
others. John Q. Anderson taught folklore at Texas A&AMP;M and the
University of
</P>
<P>
   Houston. He is a past president of the Texas Folklore Society.
</P>
<P>
   If your friendly local bookstore isn't stocked with one of the
above and you'd like to have it, you may order any of them from:
University of North
</P>
<P>
   Texas Press, P.O. Box 311336, Denton, Texas 76203-1336.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
