<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-READY-FOODREVIEW09-CO     07-08 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-READY-FOODREVIEW09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ready Food Review
 &HT;    By Jim and Barbara Maggard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Precooked Montgomery Inn Ribs, $10.99 for 1-pound slab. Sauce
included. Cooking instructions: Grill or broil for 4 minutes, turn
and cook an additional 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   E CONVENIENCE: The ribs are sizzling after just 7 minutes under
the broiler; it's certainly a quick meal.
</P>
<P>
   E QUALITY: Yep, the meat is literally falling off the bone of
these baby back ribs. However, the meat has the pronounced
``leftover'' taste associated with oven-reheated meat. The
sweet-as-ketchup sauce helps disguise it.
</P>
<P>
   E VALUE: Just a couple more dollars buys side dishes and service
at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   E OVERALL RATING ON A 10-POINT SCALE: 5
</P>
<P>
   E WOULD YOU BUY AGAIN: No. I like ribs with some chew and sauce
with some heat.
</P>
<P>
   E COMMENTS: Fans of Montgomery Inn ribs, and there are many,
might want to fix these at home rather than drive to Cincinnati.
But they don't have to do that either; Montgomery Inn ribs are
available for carry-out at the Englewood Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller Food Editor
</P>
<P>
   E CONVENIENCE: Thunderstorms made our decision to broil the ribs
instead of grilling them. Cooking time listed was right on the
money.
</P>
<P>
   E QUALITY: While the sauce easily earns a 10 rating and was a
sufficient amount, the tasters commented on the musty ``aged-meat
taste'' and questioned the lack of a sell-by date on the package.
</P>
<P>
   E VALUE: A bit pricey at $10.99 for the actual amount of edible
meat in the package.
</P>
<P>
   E OVERALL RATING ON A 10-POINT SCALE: 7.
</P>
<P>
   E WOULD YOU BUY AGAIN: Not the ribs, but we have bought and used
the sauce before.
</P>
<P>
   E COMMENTS: Not a sensible buy for a family, but a lone diner
might choose this entree on a rainy Saturday night over a trip to a
restaurant or another ``carryout'' meal.
</P>
<P>
   Jim and Barbara Maggard are retired Daytonians.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
