<SLUG> BC-TX-INSTITUTIONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Federal funds frozen at school for mentally ill
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ First, a mentally retarded woman drowned at Abilene
State School. Next, retarded residents at Richmond State School got
sick after drinking bottles of pear-scented body spray and
mouthwash. Then, Austin State School failed to report sexual
activity among residents to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, all three institutions have had their
federal money frozen because of serious health and safety problems.
</P>
<P>
   The three sanctions may signal growing trouble with Texas'
ability to keep free from harm the 5,300 mentally retarded people
living in state institutions. Safety inspectors routinely cite the
institutions for insufficient staffing and poorly trained workers.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, federal money has been frozen nine times at
various retardation institutions because the residents' health and
safety were jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   With money from the Medicaid program being halted every three
weeks on average, the Texas Department of Mental Health and Mental
Retardation soon could surpass the record number of 11 freezes
placed on Medicaid money in 1997 at retardation institutions.
Between 1993 and 1996, Medicaid money was halted a total of 10
times.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicaid money, which at large institutions can amount to
$69,000 a day, provides as much as 85 percent of the budget at each
of the 11 state retardation institutions. The money will be
restored when state Department of Human Services inspectors decide
the problems have been corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Brunette, director of state mental retardation facilities,
said he's concerned about the incidents but that perspective is
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people at our facilities, the vast majority of them, go
through every day, all day long, well-cared for, well-supervised,''
he said. ``It's these exceptional things that occur that are going
to require our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   More Medicaid sanctions have occurred over the past two years,
Brunette said, because federal Health Care Financing Administration
officials have imposed stricter Medicaid standards on retardation
institutions, much as the federal government has tried to get tough
on nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said the agency is having a hard time hiring and
retaining enough qualified workers. As the Texas economy soars,
workers are turning away from caring for disabled people toward
jobs in fast-food and other businesses that pay more than the
state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   An average state retardation worker, who provides direct care
such as bathing and feeding, earns about $7 an hour. Last year,
four of every 10 direct-care workers quit, compared with three of
every 10 just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor contributing to the problems at state schools is
the growing concentration of residents with severe behavior and
medical problems as more moderately retarded people move to group
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The June 18 drowning of Anita Gaye Kelley, 54, at Abilene State
School occurred after the institution failed to closely supervise
the woman. She was left alone to climb into a bathtub full of
water, inspection records show.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors found that a replacement worker had not been told of
Kelley's need for close supervision at bath time. Several workers
complained that too few workers are available at the institution,
forcing workers who may not know the residents to float from dorm
to dorm to cover vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   At Richmond State School, regulators found similar complaints
from employees. ``We need more staff,'' one worker told state
inspectors. ``We have tried to tell the supervisors that we can't
do our jobs without more staff, but no one listens. Then, if the
clients leave the dorm unsupervised, we get in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 19, a retarded woman with a history of ingesting
inedible liquids was left unattended at Richmond State School. She
drank a bottle of pear-scented body spray and required
hospitalization in the institution's infirmary, inspection records
show. Just the day before, a retarded man in a different dorm drank
a bottle of mouthwash and had to be treated in a local emergency
room, records also show.
</P>
<P>
   At Austin State School, the institution was notified recently
that its Medicaid money is frozen because it failed to tell state
regulators about several incidents of fondling among male
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Jim Armstrong said his staff did not realize such
incidents must be reported to authorities. ``Hereafter, though, we
will report it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rising number of Medicaid sanctions comes after the state
cut $13.2 million from the retardation institutions' budgets last
fall because their populations are declining as more residents move
to community-based homes. The cuts resulted in layoffs at some
institutions, including Austin State School.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
