<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: At least they didn't play the Bee Gees
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ The disk jockey came up to me right after
the Class of 1978 reunion party started and said he was glad I was
there, since he hated being the oldest person in the room. He
walked off before I could hasten to explain that although I was too
old to be a member of that class, I was certainly too young to be
in his graduating class.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he played K.C. and the Sunshine Band's ``That's the Way I
Like It.'' The late 1970s might have had something to recommend it
(though I can't remember what it would be at the moment), but it
sure wasn't musical taste. In less than 10 years the songs at the
top of the charts went from the
</P>
<P>
   Beatles and Jefferson Airplane to the Bee Gees and the Village
People. Yeech.
</P>
<P>
   This is my running buddy's graduating class of Nacogdoches High
School. I've never been to a reunion party of a class to which I
didn't belong. I've
</P>
<P>
   only been to one of my own, and that was 15 years ago. I thought
Longview High would have a 25-year reunion this summer, but
apparently nobody had the energy to organize it. Or I wasn't
invited, which would be a distinct possibility given my rather
spotty record back then.
</P>
<P>
   It's strange going to someone else's class reunion -- lots of
inside jokes, old stories and such that you don't get. I did a lot
of standing around, smiling and shuffling while strangers peered in
vain for a yearbook picture encased in plastic and pinned to my
shirt. Aaah, a spouse, they would finally realize, and introduce
themselves. I was sorely tempted to borrow a name tag of a
non-attendee and wear it. That'll mess 'em up, as they look at the
20-year-old photo of someone who looks vaguely like you, meaning
the same gender and race, and try to connect that memory with the
person standing in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't all strangers. A goodly number of the Class of 1978
still live here, running small businesses, teaching, working at a
bank, etc. I
</P>
<P>
   know several of them. A surprising number of the class,
including the contractor, was involved in building our house.
</P>
<P>
   My running buddy has a circle of girlfriends who still keep in
touch, most of whom still live here or come back often to visit.
They've stuck together
</P>
<P>
   through kids, divorces, death and other assorted disasters.
These women in the past 20 years have gone on countless road trips
together, crashed on
</P>
<P>
   each other's couches when marriages went south, and still call
each other, usually late at night, to laugh and gossip into the wee
hours. When they all
</P>
<P>
   got back together at the reunion, cutting up and reminiscing,
they reminded me of ``Thelma and Louise'' -- except there were more
of them. You could
</P>
<P>
   picture them all piled up in a convertible, hurtling down the
road somewhere, radio going full blast, looking for an ATM machine.
</P>
<P>
   The few members of her gang that I hadn't met examined me, the
new husband, closely. I felt as if I was a piece of livestock with
an uncertain
</P>
<P>
   pedigree -- not all that far off the mark. I passed examination,
apparently: teeth OK, hasn't lost all his hair, a bit short
perhaps, but relatively
</P>
<P>
   unobnoxious. No criminal record, either.
</P>
<P>
   My running buddy took a great deal of ribbing from classmates
she hasn't seen in years about no longer dressing exclusively in
cowboy boots and hat.
</P>
<P>
   Her penchant for rodeos and dressing like Annie Oakley passed
long before I met her, thank the Lord. Other classmates had ditched
their Afros or
</P>
<P>
   bouffaints, or acquired some extra baggage around the middle. A
few have passed away, and their yearbook photos hung on a piece of
poster board on
</P>
<P>
   which someone had scrawled 'In Memoriam.'
</P>
<P>
   After the reunion party, about two dozen or so folks showed up
at our house, since it was close by. A classmate who plays music
professionally
</P>
<P>
   brought out his saxophone. My step-son lugged his electric
guitar and amp outside, and and jammed with the sax player for a
good while, followed by
</P>
<P>
   another classmate. It was great fun, but I hope the neighbors
were sleeping soundly.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pleasant ending, the ceiling fans stirring the finally
tolerable air on the back porch, the stars blinking weakly above.
Everyone finally
</P>
<P>
   left by 3:30 in the morning, which meant I wasn't worth killing
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness reunions don't come around but every 10 years or
so. I just remembered something memorable about 1978. It was the
year my
</P>
<P>
   oldest daughter was born. Maybe I am getting old.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
