<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One good . . .
 &HT;    By Staffwriters
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONE GOOD WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   I f you're already in a burger rut at the grill, check out the
ideas on the Web at the University of California at Berkeley's
``101 Ways to Make Burgers'' site. The possibilities range from
Louisiana-style Spicy Blackened Burgers to Fajita Burgers. Point
your browser to soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/burgers/indexall.html.
</P>
<P>
   ONE GOOD IDEA
</P>
<P>
   I f the idea of keeping cool in the kitchen appeals to you, a
new book may expand the possibilities. Joie Warner's No-Cook Pasta
Sauces (Chronicle, $17.95) goes beyond everyone's staple of
uncooked tomato sauce and comes up with 75 recipes. Some rely on
leftover chicken and seafood from a night out or prepared foods
such as eggplant caponata from a jar, but most are prepared from
scratch. Example: a no-cook meat sauce made with diced prosciutto
and Black Forest ham.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry tomatoes hint at what's ahead
</P>
<P>
   Though a few truly home-grown tomatoes are available at farmers
markets, most of us are waiting for the sun-warmed backyard variety
that are still weeks away. Stem tomatoes at the supermarket remain
the best choice at the store . Now they are available as cherry
tomatoes, and one variety labeled Towingo is as pretty as a piece
of art. Look for a good selection at Meijer stores.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
