 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE THURSDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Thursday, July 9, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   TX-INSTITUTIONS _ AUSTIN _ In the past three weeks, three Texas
institutions have had their federal money frozen because of serious
health and safety problems. The three sanctions may signal growing
trouble with Texas' ability to keep free from harm the 5,300
mentally retarded people living in state institutions. (Gamino,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GUINESS-CARDS _ A nun in New York had six bags of cards
hand-made by children, ready to send to the young boy with an
inoperable brain tumor who wanted to hold the world record for the
most get-well cards received.
</P>
<P>
   But that young, ailing boy has recovered and grown up. He set
the world record _ at 33 million cards _ back in May 1991. And it's
about time that it stopped, Children's Wish Foundation officials
say. (Lee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/7.
</P>
<P>
   STINKY-FLOWER _ Despite the buildup, the celebrated stinking
flower of Atlanta _ the gigantic Amorphophallus titanum, blooming
at the Atlanta Botanical Garden _ didn't rank with the rankest
scents you've ever whiffed. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED 7/7.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When a federal judge orders a
bankruptcy sale, it takes more than brush fires to delay it. Stuart
auctioneer Karlin Daniel, 47, belted out his rap _ ``Sixty-five
hundred there! Do I hear 7,000?'' _ for four hours recently at a
Brevard County citrus packing plant, despite heat, smoke and ash
from brush fires burning out of control several miles away. (Bhatt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PAMPERS _ It's here and it's huge: The first plus-sized
disposable diaper for full-figured babies and toddlers. Noting a
trend toward later potty training (big-name pediatricians recommend
waiting until a kid is ``ready,'' which can be late in
toddlerhood), Proctor &AMP; Gamble brings out a larger Pampers for kids
weighing more than 35 pounds, sort of a bridge model between the
old Pampers and Depends. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-ANIMALS _ BUNNELL, Fla. _ The trauma isn't over for the
pets, livestock and wild animals routed by Florida fires. Some are
still out in the smoking woods, cut off from their homes, hiding in
culverts, drainage ditches, under cars or in garbage cans,
disoriented and traumatized. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   CONWAY _ At the age of 20, Texas-born Gordon Conway became an
illustrator for Vanity Fair and an accomplished fashion artist.
This was the 1920s, and she was the New Woman. Raye Virginia Allen
revived interest in Conway with her University of Texas Press book
that grew out of work at UT under Bill Goetzmann. Book signings are
planned for fall and several exhibits on Conway are scheduled
around the country. (Staff, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   MILNER-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Texana books collectors must
love the University of North Texas Press and the people who operate
it. They're always coming out with books that remind us of our
diverse and rich heritage in this big state. (Milner, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   COOKBOOKS _ Trendwatchers and publishers agree that increased
sales of instructional cookbooks as opposed to recipe books is
fueled by a generation of people who grew up with convenience foods
rather than home cooking, and who want to make up for lost time.
Not only are they reading more about the basics of American home
cooking, they're watching cooking shows and taking classes like
never before. Many cookbook authors are thrilled with the trend,
because they get to teach the lesson they've wanted to all along _
that fine cooking is not in the recipe but in the accumulated
skills of the cook. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PEAS-MAIN _ Through the ages, Southern field peas have been a
comfort to old and young alike, a ritual of summer as constant as
corn, okra and tomatoes. Though there are innumerable ways to cook
a field pea _ from soups and stews to pilaus and pea cakes _ any
Southerner will tell you that his way is the only way: Pick a mess
with the dew still on them. Shell them carefully. Wash them gently.
And simmer them slowly with a hunk of ham or pat of butter. (Brock,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PEAS-RECIPE _ Recipe page to go with story on Southern peas
centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PEAS-TIPS _ A guide to picking, shelling, cooking and storing
Southern peas. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Broccoli casserole . (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN _ A visit with restaurant employees to enjoy the
meal they are served _ which is different but just as good as what
the paying customer gets. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   READY-FOODREVIEW _ Precooked Montgomery Inn Ribs, $10.99 for
1-pound slab. Sauce included. Cooking instructions: Grill or broil
for 4 minutes, turn and cook an additional 3 minutes.
(Maggard/Maggard, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ONE-GOOD _ I f you're already in a burger rut at the grill,
check out the ideas on the Web at the University of California at
Berkeley's ``101 Ways to Make Burgers'' site. The possibilities
range from Louisiana-style Spicy Blackened Burgers to Fajita
Burgers. Point your browser to
soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/burgers/indexall.html. (Staff, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-VIAGRA _ Poor men are not going as wild over Viagra as
state officials had feared. So the state Medicaid's $12
million-a-year projection for the impotency drug is shrinking to $3
million to $5 million a year. That sounds like a lot of money, but
it is just a blip in Florida's $7 billion yearly Medicaid budget.
(Warejcka, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
