<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED: Silence of the Lambs . . .)
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the status of HR 3008, the Notch Fairness Act, that
was introduced in Congress the latter part of last year?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Notch babies'' is a term some retirees use to refer to
themselves because, they believe, they are receiving lower benefits
than other Social Security recipients with comparable earnings born
earlier. According to an analysis by the American Association of
Retired Persons, the problem is that these ``notch babies'' are
comparing themselves to those born from 1912 through 1916 who are
receiving higher benefits than intended. According to AARP, the
benefits that ``notch babies'' receive are actuarially correct.
</P>
<P>
   The ``notch baby'' situation is a long-simmering issue. Since
1981, members of Congress have introduced 118 pieces of notch
reform legislation. None of these initiatives, however, has been
passed into law. The latest bill, HR 3008, sponsored by Rep. Mark
Neumann (R-Wis.), would give the ``notch babies'' the option of
receiving lump-sum payments totaling $5,000, or increased monthly
benefits, through the year 2002. It was referred to the House
Committee on Ways and Means and to the Committee on the Budget Nov.
7, 1997, but has yet to be acted on. Staff of the Ways and Means
subcommittee on Social Security is reviewing the bill's provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does the expression ``caught red-handed'' come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: In ancient times, ``to be taken with red hand'' was to be
caught in the act, like a murderer, with his (or her) hands red
with the victim's blood. The use of ``red hand'' in this sense goes
back to 15th-century Scotland and Scottish law. Sir Walter Scott's
``Ivanhoe'' has an early use of ``taken red-handed'' for someone
apprehended in the act of committing a crime. Not long afterward,
the expression became more common as ``caught red-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a big fan of Rosie O'Donnell. How can I get tickets to
her show in New York?
</P>
<P>
   A: You'll have to be lucky, and persistent. And you must plan
well in advance. Even then, there are no guarantees. You can send a
postcard (or letter with stamped, self-addressed return envelope)
to be entered into a lottery for tickets for the 1998-99 season.
You'll be notified by postcard if your name has been chosen. The
address: NBC Studios, The Rosie O'Donnell Show, 30 Rockefeller
Plaza, Suite 800E, New York, NY 10112.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can take a chance at getting standby space for tapings
Monday throughThursday each week. Standby tickets are available on
that same day only at 8 a.m. outside the 49th Street entrance to 30
Rockefeller Plaza. Standby holders must return no earlier than one
hour prior to a taping on the 50th Street side of the NBC lobby.
</P>
<P>
   A further complication: Even if you get a regular or standby
ticket, you're still not guaranteed admittance. And taping
schedules are subject to change, sometimes without notice.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the houseboat in Miami where Andrew
Cunanan committed suicide? Was any connection ever determined
between Cunanan and a German businessman, I think it was, who owned
the houseboat?
</P>
<P>
   A: The houseboat, named the New Year, was condemned by Miami
Beach officials in January after it had settled on the shallow
bottom of Indian Creek and its German owner, identified as Torsten
Reineck, missed a deadline to refloat and repair it. It then was
demolished. Cunanan, the suspected serial killer of fashion
designer Gianni Versace and four other men, committed suicide on
the houseboat in July 1997 before police could capture him.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were unable to prove any previous link between
Cunanan and Reineck. That was among several questions the
investigation was not able to answer, such as how Cunanan ended up
on the houseboat, and what he did between Versace's slaying and his
own suicide. As Miami Beach Police Chief Richard Barreto said when
the probe was closed officially on Dec. 31, 1997, the answers to
many questions ``went down with the ship, so to speak, when Andrew
Cunanan committed suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find the Powerball winning numbers on the
Internet? I travel frequently, and it would be handy when I buy a
ticket in a Powerball state. The only site I could find has not
been updated in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A: Try a website for a lottery in one of the participating
states, such as Wisconsin. Here's the address: www.wilottery.com/
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did the Mississippi River get its name, since it starts
in Minnesota and ends in Louisiana and borders many states?
</P>
<P>
   A: The book ``Why Do They Call It Topeka'' explains that the
Mississippi, the longest river in North America, derives its name
from the Algonquin words mescha (meaning ``great'') and cebe
(water). The state was named after the river.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 paperback, subtitled ``How Places Got Their Names,'' is
a wealth of information about how places (towns, states, rivers,
mountains) got their name. It's by John W. Pursell. If it isn't in
stock, bookstores should be able to order it. It's a Citadel Press
book, published by Carol Publishing Group ($9.95; ISBN
0-8065-1588-0).
</P>
<P>
   Q: The release of the new ``X-Files'' movie, and the popularity
of Gillian Anderson in the role of Agent Scully, has me wondering:
When did the FBI start permitting women to serve as agents? And
what thoughts did J. Edgar Hoover have on this subject?
</P>
<P>
   A: The FBI's first female agents were Joanne E. Pierce of
Niagara Falls, N.Y., and Susan Lynn Roley of Long Beach, Calif.,
who joined on July 17, 1972. FBI spokeswoman Celestine Armstead
said the agency can't respond about Hoover's beliefs on female
agents because ``that would be speculation as to what someone else
thought, and we're not going to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the CIA gift shop have a mail order catalog?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Furthermore, the gift shop doesn't sell to the public. A
spokesman said the gift shop, operated by the CIA's Employees
Activity Association, is private and not government-run. It sells
such items as golf balls, baseball hats and beer mugs with the CIA
logo, but only to CIA employees.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a retail outlet not affiliated with the CIA
that does sell many such items to the public. Ship's Hatch Inc.,
has outlets in Arlington and Fairfax, Va. ``Tourists love the CIA
stuff,'' said Mary Beth Cox of the Arlington location. Numerous
items with the CIA logo are available, including coffee mugs,
T-shirts, hats, patches, cigarette lighters and shot glasses, she
said. Specialty items such as Navy hats (from any Navy ship, past
or present, Cox said) also are available.
</P>
<P>
   Items can be obtained in person (or by mail order) from Ship's
Hatch, 1677 Crystal Square Arcade, Arlington, VA 22202
(703-413-6289); or by telephone order from the Fairfax location
(703-691-1670). Information also is available on the stores'
website: www.shipshatch.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the name Atlanta derived from Atlas, the god in Greek
mythology? Or is it from the Atlantic Ocean?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you want to take an indirect route, it's from Atlas. But
the more direct source is Atlantic, from a railroad that took part
of its name from the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The place that was to become Atlanta was incorporated under the
name Marthasville on Dec. 23, 1842. The post office also recognized
it by that name. In 1845, J. Edgar Thompson, chief engineer of the
Georgia Railroad, was asked by his boss to suggest a new name for
the depot, the southern terminus of the Western &AMP; Atlantic
Railroad. The book ``Georgia Place Names'' said Thompson came up
with Atlanta as a feminine version of Atlantic. Although the town
still was called Marthasville, freight coming in was marked
``Atlanta,'' and it wasn't long before the new name stuck. Atlanta
was incorporated as a city Dec. 29, 1845.
</P>
<P>
   The names Atlantic and Atlas are directly related. The ancient
Romans named the Atlantic Ocean after the Atlas Mountains of North
Africa, which marked the western limit of what was then the known
world. The Atlas Mountains were named for Atlas, son of the Titan
Iapetus and the sea nymph Clymene, in Greek mythology.
</P>
