 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 393 - JULY 8, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 393 -- July 8, 1998 We are offering
the following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. ANTONIO BANDERAS TAKES A STAB AT 'ZORRO' Spanish actor
Antonio Banderas talks about the new movie ``The Mask of Zorro,''
the enduring appeal of the swordsman, why his own children may not
like the movie and how he coped with the scandal of his romance
with Melanie Griffith, for whom he left his wife. By Ian Spelling.
1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
SOMETHING ABOUT MATT DILLON Matt Dillon has spent a decade making
movies, and gone from flavour-of-the-month teen idol to respected
Hollywood leading man. His latest film, ``There's Something About
Mary,'' is the zany, slapstick face he says he's always wanted to
make. Dillon talks about the new movie, what it was like to co-star
with his longtime girlfriend Cameron Diaz, how he reacted to
criticism of his recent, super-steamy erotic thriller ``Wild
Things,'' and why he thinks there isn't enough sex in today's
movies. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
BEN AFFLECK'S NEXT FRONTIER At precisely the moment when Hollywood
wants to label him ``hunk'' or ``genius,'' actor Ben Affleck sees
the danger of being mythicized into something unreal. So he's
playing the Hollywood kind of Russian roulette young talent has
always played, dancing with the system, but also dancing away from
it. In this interview Affleck talks about the summer's big action
movie, ``Armageddon.'' By Jay Carr. The Boston Globe. 2,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________4.
WILD ABOUT HARRY Family comes first for Harry Connick Jr., the
father of two young girls and husband of former Victoria's Secrets
model Jill Goodacre. He tries to guard his privacy at home but it's
hard with two successful careers : he's an in-demand musician whose
love of traditional jazz and funk has struck a chord with millions,
and an in-demand actor whose career took off in the blockbuster
sci-fi film ``Independence Day.'' He now has a starring role in
``Hope Floats,'' a romantic comedy with Sandra Bullock. By Steve
Morse. The Boston Globe. 1,100 words.
_______________________________________________________________5.
THE SECRETS OF LOREENA MCKENNITT Loreena McKennitt's star has been
gently rising in the new-age and world-music fields for more than a
decade. She has had gold albums in America and sells well in other
parts of the world. The Canadian singer-songwriter-harpist is
comfortable with both ancient tribal instruments and computers. In
this interview she calls her soothing style ``eclectic Celtic,'' --
it has a Celtic basis and a wide range of world-music influences
including Middle Eastern and Russian, that sounds as if it sprang
from the mystical Dark Ages. By Jim Sullivan. The Boston Globe.
1,600 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
ERNIE HUDSON AT A CROSSROADS Ernie Hudson starred in the two
``Ghostbusters'' hits, and has a score of other films to his
credit. Now in his 40's, Hudson admits that his dreams of being a
big-screen leading man may be over. The actor, frustrated but
determined, talks frankly about mistakes he has made, the downside
of money in Hollywood, and his new dream : surviving on his own
terms. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
ROSEBUD REDUX : ORSON WELLES IS HOT AGAIN Towards the end of his
life, Orson Welles - a proud, defiant artist and arguably the
greatest director America ever produced - was reduced to appearing
in wine commercials to earn a living. Meanwhile, his cherished
projects were left unseen. ``When I die,'' Welles said, ``they'll
be picking over my creative bones.'' Nearly 13 years after his
death, Welles is now at the centre of a major revival. Critics
lament that his quintessential works are being made by other
directors. By Patrick Z. McGavin. From The Hollywood Reporter.
2,300 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
FRANCES MCDORMAND TAKES A SHINE TO MADELINE Frances McDormand won
an Oscar for her ``Fargo'' role as a pregnant sheriff who gets
tangled up in a violent kidnapping case. She's been a regular in
the weird films of the Coen brothers, and is even married to Joel
Coen. So it's a change for her to be bright and bubbly in
``Madeline,'' based on the beloved classic children's book and
filmed in Paris. By Jean Oppenheimer. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
EXPLORING SPACEY The man who has made a career out of playing
psychos is really just a nice, normal, cultured guy. Kevin Spacey
broke out of the crazed mould in a British production of ``The
Iceman Cometh,'' and on the movie front, he stars in ``The
Negotiator.'' Interview by Merle Ginsberg. W magazine. 1,500 words
+ 2 photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
EDWARD BURNS INTERVIEW Actor Edward Burns wowed the Sundance Film
Festival for his debut film, ``The Brothers McMullen,'' which was
shot for a tiny $25,000 but grossed more than $10 million.
Hollywood is already buzzing about his starring role in Steven
Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan'' (Spielberg cast him without an
audition.) By Julie L. Belcove. W magazine. 1,500 words + photos.
</P>
