<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, July 8, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VINYL-CHLORIDE (Lake Charles, La.) _ Thousands of previously
secret documents suggest that major chemical manufacturers closed
ranks in the late 1950s to contain evidence of the toxic effects of
vinyl chloride, which is used to make one of the world's most
common plastics. The documents present a deadly scenario: That the
companies subjected at least two generations of workers to
excessive levels of a potent carcinogen that targets the liver,
brain, lungs and blood-forming organs. By JIM MORRIS. (Photos and
graphic available on New York Times photo service; for weekend
release.)
</P>
<P>
   AGE-DISCRIMINATION (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Gov. Pete
Wilson must chose this week between protecting middle-aged workers
and helping California's corporate interests in a bill that would
significantly strengthen anti-discrimination laws for workers older
than 40. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   CREMATION-COMPLAINTS 9San Francisco) _ A Martinez, Calif.,
crematorium is struggling to dispose of several bodies after it was
temporarily shut down by fire officials last month and then closed
while the state Department of Consumer Affairs investigates
customer complaints. By ROBERT SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (San Antonio) _ Melissa Barela should be planning
her wedding instead of making her fiance's funeral arrangements.
Ricardo Salinas, a 24-year-old Border Patrol agent in San Benito,
Texas, was shot and killed in a gunbattle that killed another agent
and a 53-year-old woman and her 31-year-old daughter. By NATHALIE
TREPANIER.
</P>
<P>
   MOLESTER (Santa Rosa, Calif.) _ Apparently depressed by being
identified as a high-risk sexual predator in a flyer distributed to
his neighbors, Michael Allen Patton hanged himself. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BANK-MERGER (San Francisco) _ Most bank mergers are dry, routine
affairs. But a political firefight is flaring in California over
the proposed $60 billion acquisition of BankAmerica Corp. by
NationsBank Corp. of Charlotte, N.C. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAXES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Once thought to be a problem only
for the rich, estate taxes are now challenging middle Americans.
Work for a few decades, pay off a mortgage, buy some life insurance
and invest your savings, and boom, you could have a more sizable
estate than you had ever imagined. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   ROOFING-BOOM (San Francisco) _ A vigorous economy in the Bay
Area coupled with torrential El Nino rains explain the rising tide
of work for the roofing industry. Clearly, it is their best year in
a decade or more. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SONDHEIM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Following well-received
biographies of several key 20th-century artists (painter Salvador
Dali, architect Frank Lloyd Wright, composer Leonard Bernstein),
Meryle Secrest has turned her attention to Stephen Sondheim,
indisputably the most important composer and lyricist in
contemporary musical theater. By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BATHING-EXPERIENCE (Albany, N.Y.) _ You don't just hop in the
bathtub anymore for a quick bath. With today's whirlpools and deep
soaking tubs, it's a ``bathing experience.'' And to accommodate
older houses, manufacturers are making deeper tubs that fit in many
of the tight enclosures of bathrooms. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Finally, it happened. A woman
confessed she didn't have sex with President Clinton. Former Time
magazine White House reporter Nina Burleigh says she would have
gladly had sex with Clinton after she supposedly caught him
admiring her legs during a game of hearts on Air Force One. She
wrote that she didn't feel harassed. Instead, she swooned for the
First Dude. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LARIAM-MALARIA (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ A recent column by San
Francisco Examiner reporter Scott Winokur on the perils of Lariam
is the first ever aimed at a general audience. Otherwise, you would
need to subscribe to special-interest publication to learn about
this toxic anti-malarial drug. By B. MEREDITH BURKE.
</P>
<P>
   PMS (San Pedro, Calif.) _ I am in the throes of a major bad mood
and my husband is not home and my kids are at summer classes.
Hormone-induced for sure, this blasted bad mood. But still, I know,
someone is going to receive the sharp edge of my temporarily
contorted psyche. By GLADYS ALAM SAROYAN.
</P>
