<SLUG> BC-CPT-PACKARD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Packard Bell NEC Names Groupe Bull Exec as CEO  
 By Jamie Beckett   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Packard Bell NEC moved quickly Saturday to name Alain Couder
president and CEO following the abrupt resignation of its founder.
</P>
<P>
   Couder, a top executive of Groupe Bull, a major stakeholder in
Packard Bell NEC, replaces Beny Alagem, 45, who decided to leave
the PC maker Tuesday because of ``fundamental differences'' with
its shareholders, Groupe Bull and NEC.
</P>
<P>
   Couder said Alagem had not resigned under pressure from the
company's board of directors, but he wouldn't say more. Analysts
speculated that Alagem was ousted because he was unable to stem
losses, and one analyst said that health problems prompted Alagem
to leave. Alagem would not elaborate on his prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Couder, 52, is chief operating officer at Groupe Bull, a French
hardware and software-maker that owns 13 percent of
Sacramento-based Packard Bell NEC. NEC Corp. of Japan owns 49
percent of Packard Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The executive change comes as the company, known for its
low-cost personal computers, is trying to shore up its slipping
market share against rivals Dell, Compaq and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the privately held company cut 400 jobs nationwide to
pare costs. Although company officials did not disclose figures,
they said Packard Bell has been losing money for ``a couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, the market share of Packard Bell, the world's
fifth-largest PC-maker, has fallen to 4.8 percent from 7.6 percent
in 1995, according to Dataquest, a research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The company sells Packard Bell consumer PCs at retail stores and
NEC business PCs primarily through distributors and direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   There was some confusion about when the new CEO will start work.
Couder, a French citizen who now lives in Paris, said he will
assume the role of president and chief executive of Packard Bell
NEC as soon as his visa is issued.
</P>
<P>
   But board members, who also appointed Couder to chair the
executive committee of the board, said in a statement they expect
Couder to start work by October 1, at the latest. The board did not
say who would run the company in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   ``One goal is to be profitable,'' Couder told reporters and
analysts during a conference call. Speaking in a heavy French
accent, he declined to be specific about his plans or when he
expected to get the company into the black.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants Packard Bell to be able to provide consulting
services along with its PC sales _ as its competitors do. He would
not discuss how he plans to build the services business, other than
to say he plans no acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Couder also was unable to say when an initial public offering _
planned for later this year _ would occur.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Couder's operational experience at Groupe Bull,
which sells to business customers, could help Packard Bell as it
shifts its emphasis to the commercial market.
</P>
<P>
   But they worried about his ability to build a vision for the
company. For example, other PC companies, such as Apple Computer
and Dell, benefit from a top executive who is seen as a visionary
and who can inspire workers. Couder, though, is a relative unknown
to U.S. analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is the spark, the excitement for Packard Bell NEC going
forward?'' asked Bill Schaub, a PC analyst at Dataquest in San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Alagem and his co-founders remain shareholders of Packard Bell
and currently own 25 percent. He will have no management role in
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Bell was founded in 1986, when Alagem and two partners
bought rights to the name from Teledyne Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Alagem was given a chance by NEC and Groupe Bull to stay on as
chairman but declined. ``I decided I'd be happier in my own
venture,'' Alagem said in a statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company has not named a new chairman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-05-98 1848EDT &QL;
</P>
