 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 An Epiphany Brings Former Top KMPG Exec to Silicon Valley  
 By Tom Abate   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A chauffeur used to drive Roger Siboni from his New Jersey home
each morning to his mid-Manhattan office, where he worked as chief
operating officer of the prestigious KPMG accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays Siboni is driving himself around Silicon Valley. Chalk
it up to the fact that at age 43, Siboni reached an Epiphany _
that's the name of the Palo Alto software firm he joins this month
as chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trading salary and the trappings of power for equity,''
Siboni said.
</P>
<P>
   Epiphany sells a $250,000 software package that can extract
customer information from any database and pour it into a Web
browser. The idea is to let marketing people spot occasional
customers and turn them into big spenders.
</P>
<P>
   Using software to pump up sales is a top priority for
corporations like Charles Schwab Corp., which has been using
Epiphany since November.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing on the market that I'm aware of that is as
powerful and as easy to use, and is also Web-accessible,'' said
Mary Kelley, vice president for database marketing at Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   Credit for making Epiphany powerful and simple goes to
co-founders Ben Wegbreit and Steve Blank, and lead programmers Greg
Walsh and John McCaskey.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to Siboni to sell this startup to the Fortune 500 by
drawing on personal relationships built up during two decades as a
high-profile KPMG consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Siboni is no stranger to the Valley. He started KPMG's high-tech
consulting practice in 1975, advising ancient firms such as
WordStar.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, while COO at KPMG, Siboni took sides in the ``browser
wars'' when he handed a huge contract to Microsoft despite a
personal sales pitch from Netscape CEO Jim Barksdale.
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch in Palo Alto, Siboni said he's run into Barksdale
since then, and their cordial exchange convinced him that the
Netscape CEO hasn't held a grudge.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Barksdale's such a big man, he probably doesn't mind
that Epiphany just hired Karen Richardson as its vice president of
sales, luring her away from a similar post at Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's only business in the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Conspicuous absence: &LR;  House Speaker Newt Gingrich led a
delegation of congressional Republicans on a meet-and-greet tour of
Silicon Valleythis week, but local Representative Tom Campbell,
R.-Campbell, was not a member of his party.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be the hometowner was snubbed because he was on the
losing side of last summer's attempted Republican coup against the
Speaker? Whatever the cause, Campbell finds himself temporarily
frozen out of the GOP's effort to make sure Vice President Al Gore
doesn't walk away with Silicon Valley votes _ or money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to pay more attention here, and ask in return for more
attention to be paid to us,'' said Representative Bob Goodlatte,
R-Va., who accompanied Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Goodlatte, who has spearheaded encryption legislation favored by
high-tech firms, was tapped by Gingrich to head a new Technology
Leadership Group that will bring Republicans in Congress together
with industry leaders like Cisco Vice President Judy Estrin,
Merrill Lynch investment banker Scott Ryles and Kleiner, Perkins
venture capitalist Floyd Kvamme.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; AOL's slippery slope? &LR;  Last week America Online shut down the
Web site of a member who had parodied several passages from the
Koran.
</P>
<P>
   The shut down was publicized by the Freedom Forum, a Virginia
foundation dedicated to newspaper and First Amendment issues. The
Forum said the site drew strong objections from Muslim academics in
Egypt and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley-based AOL watcher Dave Cassel said members at large
hardly noticed the flap. But Cassel questioned AOL's censorship
policy in light of the fact that a Texas Ku Klux Klan chapter has a
long-standing AOL page that advises visitors to prepare ``for the
coming disorder that will test the very survival of the White race
... (against the) jack booted Zionist Occupational Government.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL spokeswoman Tricia Primrose said her firm received more than
1,000 complaints about the Koran site, and closed it after decided
it ``defamed a religious group.''
</P>
<P>
   She said AOL had received some complaints last year about the
KKK site last year, and AOL requested some changes to the page at
that time. But this year AOL has not heard any objections from
members and therefore has not taken any action against the page.
</P>
<P>
   The page is maintained by the Klan group that marched in Jasper,
Texas, last week, the town where a black man was killed by being
dragged behind a truck allegedly driven by several white men.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-05-98 1847EDT &QL;
</P>
