<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-LUCENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Lucent Plans Bell Labs Unit In Silicon Valley  
 By Jonathan Marshall   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Laboratories, the research arm of Lucent Technologies, is
opening a new branch in Silicon Valley, in part to foster Lucent's
local venture investments.
</P>
<P>
   The labs will house as many as 130 people at a new facility to
be completed next year in Stanford Research Park and will focus on
data networking, semiconductors, communications software, wireless
communications and optical networking.
</P>
<P>
   It also will supply expertise to Lucent Venture Partners, a $100
million fund the company announced in February to back startups
that complement Lucent's own development efforts. Many major
technology companies, including Microsoft and Intel, have similar
venture arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Labs will help identify and evaluate promising new
technologies,'' said Lucent spokesman Gary Bonham. ``The point
isn't simply to gain an equity position, but to have a hands-on
involvement to move the technology along. We'll give the startups
access to our business units and distribution channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Venture Partners already has funded at least four new
companies, said John Hanley, its managing partner. He declined to
name the companies or report the level of investment.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanley said the fund is working closely with half a dozen
other venture funds, including Accel Partners in Palo Alto and
Mayfield Fund and U.S. Venture Partners in Menlo Park, to identify
investment candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Fong, a general partner at Mayfield Fund, said Lucent
might use its venture fund to promote commercial development of
technology dreamed up at Bell Labs. And it could further attract
promising startups in the networking industry because Lucent is
widely viewed as a counterweight to networking goliath Cisco
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent also said yesterday that Lucent Technologies Foundation
will contribute $2.6 million to endow a professorship and two
graduate fellowships at Stanford University to promote research and
teaching on communications networking.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has made several major acquisitions in the Bay Area
independent of its venture unit. Last year, it bought Octel
Communications, a Milpitas firm that makes unified messaging
software for corporate networks, for $1.8 billion. It also
purchased Livingston Enterprises in Pleasanton, a networking
company, for $650 million in stock. In February, it announced plans
to buy a wireless technology division of Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bell Labs group will be led by Bill Coughran, head of
Lucent's Internet software research team, and Ron Schmidt, who left
the board of Bay Networks in April. Bay announced last month that
it was being acquired by Northern Telecom, a Lucent competitor in
the telecommunications equipment industry.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the new Bell Labs group will be housed with Lucent
Venture Partners on Sand Hill Road in Menlo Park, before both move
to the Stanford Research Park next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-05-98 1847EDT &QL;
</P>
