<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5227 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CLARK-SFCHRON &LR;      07-08 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CLARK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Tech's High Flier Soars Again  
 By Jon Swartz   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Clark already has founded two billion-dollar high-tech
companies, and if his latest startup takes off, he could make
Silicon Valley history.
</P>
<P>
   But on a recent morning, he hardly looks like an executive at
the pinnacle of the corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   His voice raspy from a nagging allergy and his gangly body
dulled by a late night of libations, Clark _ who co-founded
Netscape Communications Corp. and Silicon Graphics Inc. and who
currently is shepherding another Internet company with big-time
potential _ is late for an interview and uncharacteristically
reserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon, let's get some coffee,'' he says, forcing out each
word. ``I need to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   But after a latte at a Menlo Park cafe, he's as animated as some
of the splashy graphics that SGI brought to high-powered
workstations. Opinions and pronouncements rattle out like chat room
conversations on the Internet, the global communications network
which Netscape technology helped popularize.
</P>
<P>
   In a far-ranging, three-hour interview, the tall Texan expounds
on the Internet phenomenon, takes digs at former SGI chief
executive Ed McCracken (``an egomaniac who never looked me straight
in the eyes''), recounts his childhood in Plainview, Texas (``I
grew up in black and white''), discusses academia and politics, and
describes the art of the startup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impatience is a virtue,'' Clark said, explaining his
businessphilosophy. ``Entrepreneurship is about not being satisfied
with the way things are done and changing it. And (potential
entrepreneurs) better be interested in making money. If you're just
interested in passion, then go to your playpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 54, quit high school at 16 to join the Navy after a
series of hijinks _ including an unsuccessful attempt to smuggle
whiskey on a band trip _ got him suspended &UR; .  &LR; After hauling wheat
in Kansas and generally kicking around, he started college at 20
and eventually earned a doctorate in computer science from the
University of Utah in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   He took a job teaching computer science at theUniversity of
Santa Cruz but found it a disappointment. ``I thought it would be
an idealistic place to teach and walk in the redwoods,'' he said.
``Instead, there was a noses-in-the-clouds attitude that drove me
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a more down-to-earth school, he went to teach at
Stanford University, met some computer science students and formed
SGI in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began one of the more remarkable hot streaks in the
high-tech business. In 1984, Clark brought in McCracken as CEO and
the Mountain View company went on to reshape computer-generated
graphics. Its workstations were used to create the special effects
in such movies as ``Jurassic Park'' and ``Terminator 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite SGI's early roaring success, Clark's strained, 10-year
relationship with the stoic McCracken resulted in some awkward
moments. Clark recalls one SGI executive meeting:
</P>
<P>
   ``My adolescent daughter couldn't pronounce his name, so she
used to call him Ed `McCrackle' or Ed `McMuffin,' Clark says. ``I
mentioned this, but Ed didn't find it amusing. He said, `It's not
funny to make fun of one's last name.' Meanwhile, everyone around
the table is trying to suppress their laughter.''
</P>
<P>
   McCracken says he doesn't remember the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim is a really special, brilliant guy whom I respect a lot,''
said McCracken, who now is chairman of Prasad Project, a South
Fallsburg, N.Y., organization that provides health-care services to
low-income U.S. neighborhoods and developing countries. ``He's an
extrovert, and I'm a lot quieter. But differences are what make
great companies. SGI grew from nothing to a Fortune 500 company.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the strengths of a good company like SGI is that you
have brilliant people who are on the edge,'' McCracken says in a
measured tone. ``That makes the pot more turbulent, and from
turbulence comes brilliance and good ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   McCracken got most of the credit for SGI's success and took most
of the blame for its recent problems.
</P>
<P>
   Embittered by his clash with McCracken, Clark quit as SGI's
chairman in 1994 and sold all his stock in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, the self-described ``serial entrepreneur''
hooked up with browser whiz-kid Marc Andreessen to start Netscape,
which opened up the Web to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the right startup at the right time,'' Clark said.
``The Internet was just taking off, and we blew out the doors with
our timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Within 18 months of its founding, Netscape went public amid much
hoopla and Clark's stock options were worth more than $1 billion.
He currently owns 16 million shares of Netscape stock, worth more
than $570 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim's genius is looking at the intersection where the
technology is going and where the market will be in several
years,'' Andreessen said. ``On two occasions,he has gone from a
standing start to creating billion-dollar businesses. What's
interesting is how many more companies he has in him.''
</P>
<P>
   While remaining chairman of Netscape, Clark also is the
financial and intellectual force behind Healtheon Corp., which some
observers including Andreessen think could become Clark's third
multibillion-dollar startup.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara company, rumored to be going public in the fall,
makes software that lets consumers manage their health benefits
online. The two-year-old company already has enlisted a long list
of health care providers, hospitals and pharmacies to adopt the
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online health care (management) will emerge as one of the
low-hanging fruit industries on the Internet, along with selling
books and PCs,'' said analyst Mary Meeker, of Morgan Stanley in New
York. ``This is a market with huge potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark has invested $16 million of his own moneyin Healtheon,
which is backed by Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, the same Menlo
Park venture-capital company that helped launch Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm the only one to start two or more major companies
nationally,'' Clark said. ``Wayne Huizenga did it (with Waste
Management Systems and Blockbuster Entertainment). I can't think of
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's Midas touch has paid off handsomely. He estimates his
personal worth at $500 million to $750 million, give or take a few
million depending on the fortunes of Netscape stock.
</P>
<P>
   Clark also is penning a book, ``Netscape Time,'' which recounts
the launch of the Internet company, and is spending more time with
his family. He has two daughters, ages 33 and 28. He and wife,
Nancy Rudder, a journalist, divide their time between Palm Beach,
Fla., and Atherton, where Clark rents a house from his
grandchildren, ages 2 and 1, who own it.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Healtheon becomes viable, Clark's formidable
energies are shifting to yet another firm: Seascape Communications,
which he houses in a few hundred square feet on top of a Jenny
Craig Weight Loss Center in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   The small software outfit is developing technology for his
latest ``passion'' _ a 156-foot sailboat, dubbed Hyperion, that
could redefine high-tech transportation. When completed in October,
the software program will control the boat's basic functions from a
bank of a dozen onboard computers.
</P>
<P>
   The luxurious boat is chock-full of amenities such as state
rooms, espresso machines, wine storage areas, library and
movie-viewing lounge. Clark said the price tag was in the ``low
eight figures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love creating companies,'' Clark said as he was noodling
with a software program he created for the boat. ``I come up with
an idea and then I let someone else run them.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, he is running late for a helicopter lesson.
``Gotta go,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, you get the impression that Clark, an ardent flier,
will be a world-class helicopter pilot in no time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-05-98 1846EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
