<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEBMENTORS-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
WebMentors turn tables, tutor own teachers 
By Mark Fisher  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Throughout the summer, University of Dayton
professors are inviting a select group of University of Dayton
students into their offices for lengthy, one-on-one instructional
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Listen closely and you'll hear the usual professorial lecturing
about the importance of thorough understanding of the subject
matter coupled with quiet reassurances that there are no dumb
questions.
</P>
<P>
   But wait . . . these personal tutorials have a twist. The
students are the teachers, the teachers the students.
</P>
<P>
   UD wants to make sure all of its professors develop enough
computer know-how to be able to build and maintain their own World
Wide Web pages as the school prepares to wire up its students,
faculty and staff into what it calls a ``Learning Village.'' And
who better to teach its teachers than Web-savvy UD students who
have grown up with computers?
</P>
<P>
   Thus the ``WebMentors'' program was born. Seven students adept
in the intricacies of the Internet and Web have trained 50 UD
faculty and staff since last fall. The university pays the
WebMentor students for their efforts but does not charge UD
employees for the training.
</P>
<P>
   WebMentor Bill Rombach, a 21-year-old accounting and finance
student, said he was a little worried about whether faculty members
would be reluctant to take instruction from a student.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the way it has turned out, a lot of the faculty are
completely eager to learn,'' Rombach said. ``It's refreshing to see
professors excited about learning from students.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no hand-holding, Rombach said. ``We put our hand on
their shoulders, but we let them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Rombach's pupils, Father John McGrath, S.M., assistant
professor of religious studies at UD, recognizes the benefits of
the new technology. During a recent session between the two, the
conversation focused on icons, HTML directories, Netscape software
and double-clicks-versus-single-clicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one more way to reach students and help them
learn,'' McGrath said after his training session. ``There is an
element of creativity to it that makes it exciting and leaves a lot
to students' own initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   The role-reversal aspect of the WebMentors program carries its
own benefits for faculty members, McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for us,'' he said. ``We get a better understanding
of how students feel.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath and his colleagues who receive training agree to three
conditions: they must be willing to learn, keep their Web sites
fresh and updated and share their Web knowledge with colleagues.
McGrath, who has worked with a computer in his classes for eight
years, says he's eager to get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only I had this when I prepared my doctoral thesis. . . ``
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-06-98 2002EDT &QL;
</P>
