<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY07-COX     07-08 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY07-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
TechnoBuddy: Cyber-friends aside, don't forget virtue of real
friends 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sweet and single Teresa is really a burly truck driver
named David from Montana, married, with tattoos and kids. And the
wealthy neurosurgeon you met last night is a lonely schoolteacher
in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Let's chat about chat and the people you meet there.
</P>
<P>
   Chat is a feature you'll find in several forms on the Internet.
Most Internet veterans who like to chat online use IRC -- Internet
Relay Chat -- to have typed conversations with strangers. There are
also chat programs that run directly on Web pages and need no
special software. But the idea behind all the various ways of
chatting is to be able to have a conversation using the Internet
instead of the telephone or two rocking chairs on the front porch.
</P>
<P>
   I started using chat almost as soon as it became available on
the Internet. And I met some nice people there, folks who became
real-world friends. I'm glad I met them and that sort of thing is
still possible. But the Net was a smaller and friendlier place back
then. I hate to sound elitist, but -- as the Internet has grown
--there's been a dumbing down. It's no different than the way
broadcast television progressed. In the Golden Age of television,
the screen was filled with classic variety shows, intelligent
comedy and original plays. There has been an inevitable lowering of
taste to fit the lowest common denominator both on television and
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of frightening stories about really scary people
-- criminals of various types -- who use the Internet to meet their
victims. That threat of physical harm is an important reason to be
careful on chat and with e-mail acquaintances. But, that's not the
topic for today. Instead, let's talk about some real concerns I
have about chat that have more to do with the threat it can pose to
your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I'm not saying chat is evil, or the people
you meet there are somehow lesser humans than the folks you'd find
hanging around the community swimming pool or sitting at the tables
of your favorite coffeehouse or bar. But I am saying that -- unlike
the people you meet in the real world -- there are fewer ways to be
able to use your common sense and intelligence to judge how worthy
David or Teresa is to be a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go back to my example of the people you'd meet at the
community swimming pool. Let's say you pull up a chair in the shade
and strike up a conversation with the people sitting nearby. Right
away, you're able to tell how old they are, what sex they are, and
just get a general impression of how they act. Almost certainly, if
you talk longer than five minutes, you'll learn their names and
perhaps where they work.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's talk about how chat works on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, unlike on ``Cheers,'' nobody knows your name. You
use a nickname. And since there are no controls over what nickname
you choose, David can become Teresa if he decides that would be
fun. All of a sudden things are very much like they'd be if
everyone you meet at the swimming pool is wearing a disguise and a
mask.
</P>
<P>
   Humans being human, this anonymous world tempts a lot of people
to indulge in some fantasy. Not all of it is bad or even harmful. A
bald middle-aged guy like me can become a 22-year-old soccer player
with curly blond hair. An unemployed person can briefly become the
chief technical officer for a large corporation. Who's to know?
And, if you don't take the folks you meet in the chat areas
seriously, what does it matter anyway?
</P>
<P>
   That's just my point and the thing that I most dislike about
chat. At best, most of what you do there really doesn't matter. You
may spend hours a week chatting with Ben72 or MaryBeth98, get to
know them and even get to care about their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But try calling up ole Ben72 some morning when your car won't
start and ask him for a ride. With rare and wonderful exceptions,
the people you meet there are cyber-friends. They'll hold your hand
electronically or listen to your troubles with a keen ear. But,
when the real world intrudes, often as not they aren't around and
don't want to be.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm suggesting that most people who spend hours a week making
cyber-friends would have happier and better lives if they put the
same amount of time and effort into making real-world friends.
Friends in the real world can be inconvenient and aggravating.
</P>
<P>
   These friends don't come with on/off switches. And that, to me,
is their virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-06-98 1040EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
