<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE05-COX &LR;      07-08 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE05-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Cyberscene: There's always someone to talk to 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So you'd like to have a little chat?
</P>
<P>
   Lots of people use the Internet as a way to make friends and
have typed conversations with them using one of the many chat
services there. You'll find plenty of do's and don'ts about
chatting with strangers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But, other than to say that it's just common sense not to tell
anonymous strangers your name, telephone number, address or any
personal information, this article isn't about the right and wrong
of chat. Instead, it'll guide you to places where you can get the
software you need, sites that offer instruction on how to use chat,
and even offer a brief course in chat etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start at one of the best Web sites for basic chat
information. It's not a commercial site and that makes the complete
information and terrific links all the more impressive. The start
page is called Internet Relay Chat and can be found at
http://hoga.wwa.com
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)edge/irc.html.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a beginner, you'll find the Newbie section especially
helpful. In simple language, you'll be able to cover topics such
as: How to get Hooked up, Servers and How to Connect, Join Channels
and Communicate with Others.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've learned what to do and why you might like to do it,
you'll need the computer programs that let you reach some of the
Internet Relay Chat areas. That's another nice feature of this
page: It also has links to downloads for the chat programs. You'll
be able to download the programs free and the page offers software
for almost any computer platform you can name (and some you
probably have never heard of) including Unix, Windows, DOS,
Macintosh, OS/2, VMS, Amiga and X-Windows.
</P>
<P>
   There are several choices for most platforms. My favorite
software programs for Windows and Macintosh chatting are both
available from this site. I'd select a program called mIRC for
Windows and IRCle 2.1 for Macintosh computers. But, since these
programs are free, you may want to download a couple and find
something that suits your own tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Once you're connected and online with other chatters you'll
notice that a lot of abbreviations and special terms are used. If
you want to sound like you've been around for a while, you may want
to drop in on a page called Chatter's Jargon Dictionary at
http://www.tiac.net/users/scg/jargpge.htm. You'll soon learn that
if someone is ROFL they're ``rolling on the floor laughing'' or if
they tell you something IMHO, it's ``in my humble opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   So far we've talked about the type of chat that is known as IRC.
But there is a new breed of chat on the Net that goes beyond
typing. It's called virtual worlds. In most of these Web-based chat
services, you'll be able to see a cartoonish representation of the
person you visit with.
</P>
<P>
   There are way too many virtual chat services to list them all.
If you want to explore that type of chat, there's an excellent
collection of links from the Yahoo search engine at 
http://www.yahoo.com/Recreation/Games/Internet(underscore)Games/Virt
 ual (underscore)Worlds/3D(underscore)Worlds/.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you who are only casually interested in chat and do not
want the trouble of downloading chat programs may want to check out
some of the Web-based chat services. In most cases, you need
nothing more than your Web browser to chat there. Again, there are
literally dozens, maybe hundreds, of Web chat services. So you
should start with another group of Yahoo sites at 
http://www.yahoo.com/Computers(underscore)and(underscore)Internet/In
 ter net/World(underscore)Wide(underscore)Web/Chat/.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Check it out. We'll chat more later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-06-98 1039EDT &QL;
</P>
