<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5291 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BATHING-EXPERIENCE-HN     07-08 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATHING-EXPERIENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN FEATURES TURN BATHING INTO AN EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ You don't just hop in the bathtub anymore to take
a quick bath. With today's new line of whirlpool and deep soaking
tubs, it's referred to as a ``bathing experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that experience can fall short in many of today's
postwar houses, which haven't been remodeled and still feature the
original shallow, 14-inch-deep tub. These tubs are so shallow that
the water barely covers an adult's legs, let alone providing much
room for stretching for those over 5-feet-2-inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no real thought to comfort and the lumbar support
back then,'' said Martha Kerr, a designer with Neil Kelly
Designers/Remodelers in Portland, Ore. ``Today, there's a trend
toward deep tubs, where the water comes up to your chest, and
there's an angled end to comfortably support your back.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, whirlpool and tub manufacturers are making deeper
soaking tubs that fit in many of the tight enclosures of older
postwar bathrooms. These tubs also come in a variety of affordable
prices, depending on how many options you desire.
</P>
<P>
   A standard 14- to 17-inch deep, cast-iron tub that's 32 inches
wide by 5 feet long holds 20 gallons of water and sells for
approximately $310 to $400. Compare that to a cast acrylic
whirlpool that is 21 inches deep, takes 40 gallons of water and
costs approximately $720, said Tim Rose, a sales associate with
Central Plumbing Bath &AMP; Kitchens in Scotia, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool manufacturers have realized the majority of us can't
fit one of those megasized tubs into our small, narrow baths and
are therefore making models that can replace older tubs in cramped
quarters of up to 60 inches in length.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you have the room, such as converting an extra
bedroom into a bath, whirlpools come as large as 7 feet by 5 feet
and 24 inches deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are seeing a more compact construction of whirlpools,
because getting in and out of them where they were sunken into a
large tile surround has become a safety issue,'' said Kerr, who
also teaches bathroom programs for the National Kitchen &AMP; Bath
Association in Hackettstown, N.J. ``You're now seeing fewer steps
or decks surrounding the whirlpool. Albeit, they looked grander
with the big surround and steps leading to them, but they weren't
very practical.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of whirlpool shapes to choose from, including
rectangles, ovals, novelty and corner shapes.
</P>
<P>
   You can even attach shower doors to some whirlpool models. Some
whirlpools, called body spas, include a shower with massage jets
that recirculate 80 gallons of water per minute, according to Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   Within a whirlpool, you can choose various decorative features.
The water and air mixture jet systems come in brass, chrome or the
same color finish as your tub. There are standard power jets,
hydro-jets that feature individual flow control and pulsating
massage jets. Jets even come with an air volume control, allowing
the right mixture of air and water to create a gentle to vigorous
pulse. Don't worry about getting an electric shock, as a pneumatic,
nonelectric control switch allows you to turn the jets on and off
while in the tub.
</P>
<P>
   Many models feature molded-in head or armrests, or both. With
some models, you even have the option of a molded seat. You can
even get mood lighting with a dimmer control and five
interchangeable colored lenses to see the bottom of the bath.
</P>
<P>
   Most of today's new tubs are made of cast high-gloss acrylic,
which is resistant to stains and scratches. Acrylic also holds the
temperature longer than cast iron, according to Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are numerous colors to choose from, Kerr said
that off-whites, such as bone or almond, collectively sell as well
as white, still the most popular color.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When restoring a house, some people replace a modern tub with a
resurfaced claw-and-ball-foot tub, some in whirlpool-style.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an increased interest in maintaining the
architectural integrity of a home,'' Kerr said. ``Therefore, bath
fixtures with a more traditional look are desirable. You can even
get a claw-and-ball-foot tub with whirlpool jets. To hide the motor
and pipes, the tub has a double wall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Refinishing an existing claw-and-ball tub or other cast-iron
tubs should only be done if it is to be used in the guest bedroom,
where it will only be used occasionally,'' Kerr added. ``That way
it could hold up for the next 25 years. But I don't recommend it
for a tub that you'll be using every day. A refinished tub isn't
resurfaced under the same conditions as the original surface. If
you use it every day, it will only last about one and a half to
five years at the most before it begins to break down.''
</P>
<P>
   Other style baths have made their niche, or are doing so now.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese soaking tubs have been around for about 15 years. These
are large, deep tubs with a drain in the middle of the floor, that
you can stand in or sit on built-in areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soaking tub is just that and used in the traditional
way,'' Kerr said. ``You take a shower before getting into it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear from designers around the country that a soaking tub is
preferred more than the whirlpool,'' Kerr said. ``People want the
oversize tub, but not necessarily the noise of the jets. Even
though the jets have an on/off button, just about every
manufacturer now makes a deep soaking tub, which costs less than a
whirlpool.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the soft look of a bath, Kerr said the newest
looking tub to surface at a recent national bath show was a wooden
tub sealed with a poly glaze to protect it from temperature
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years we have seen several wooden tubs come on the
market,'' she said. ``It's a most intriguing material, but the
amount of care is beyond the norm. When you drain the water from
the tub, you may end up with staining, depending on the chemical
composition of your water. Therefore you have to thoroughly dry the
tub each time you use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A chemical water wear line can also occur, if you tend to soak
in the tub for an hour or more each time ... sort of a ring-wear
stain line around the tub.''
</P>
<P>
   Bath specialists warn against using abrasives of any kind, such
as scrub sponges to cleansers, on any tub, even cast iron, as they
will eventually cause the surface to break down and become abrasive
itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
