<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5360 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-08 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMS OF DOING IT WITH THE FIRST DUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Finally, it happened. A woman confessed she
didn't have sex with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Former Time magazine White House reporter Nina Burleigh wrote in
a Mirabella magazine essay that she would have gladly had sex with
Clinton after she supposedly caught him admiring her legs during a
game of hearts on Air Force One. She wrote that she didn't feel
harassed. Instead, she swooned for the First Dude.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is, he didn't have sex with her. I don't know if
this is a first for Clinton, but it is a new low in the already
sinking field of journalism: A no-kiss-and-tell article.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the worst of it: Burleigh wrote that she would have
been happy to have oral sex with Clinton ``just to thank him for
keeping abortion legal.''
</P>
<P>
   This is truly weird stuff. Please tell us, oh no-kiss-and-tell
reporter, what in heck does oral sex have to do with abortion?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to become a little sympathetic toward the
president after all the dirt that's been dumped on him. If things
keep on like this, his presidential library will have buck-a-peep
windows.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to have complete sympathy for presidential
spokesman Mike McCurry. This is the kind of day he had with the
Washington press corps on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It started with a grilling on Clinton's threats to get tough
with health care providers who don't provide, and went on to
questions about the Indonesian army shooting protesters. Then came
this:
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``Mike, is there any plan to send a representative to
the ceremony of the burial of Czar Nicholas II's remains?''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry: ``I'd have to check with our embassy in Moscow to see
if there are. I'm not aware of any.''
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``How about Roy Rogers?''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry: ``Probably.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we do know Roy's song, but not in Russian. McCurry has to
put up with this kind of stuff day in and day out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a state test, graduates of bilingual programs in San
Francisco and San Jose out-scored native English speakers in most
grades and subject areas. Sean Walsh, the spokesman for Gov. Pete
Wilson, said it was remarkable, adding: ``The governor has never
been flatly against programs that help kids transition into
English.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing kids might learn in a bilingual program, unless
they're taking Bureaucratese as a Second Language, is that
``transition'' isn't a verb.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Berkeley, Mayor Shirley Dean is trying to downgrade the crime
of public nudity to the level of a traffic ticket, to make it
easier to prosecute all the naked people running around there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are performance artists,'' said one of them, X-plicit
Player Marty Kent. ``We don't feel what we are doing is a trivial
matter on the level of a parking ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, performance artists, like mimes, deserve capital
punishment. But it wouldn't be right. By the way, where do you put
the traffic ticket on a nude guy? It might not be a trivial matter
at all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
