<SLUG> BC-PMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING TO SURVIVE THAT TIME OF MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GLADYS ALAM SAROYAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO, Calif. _ I am in the throes of a major bad mood and
my husband is not home and my kids are at summer classes.
</P>
<P>
   Hormone-induced for sure, this blasted bad mood. But still, I
know, someone is going to receive the sharp edge of my temporarily
contorted psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Hark, who goes there! Why, none other than the handyman who is
here to install the blinds and block the sun that dares enter my
living room.
</P>
<P>
   I am standing cross-armed with a twisted mouth and a frown that
pulls my face tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not straight,'' I can hear my voice barking.
</P>
<P>
   He is not fazed by this shrew of a woman who wears the oldest
sweatshirt she could find.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said, ``I haven't put them up yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   I stomp out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   I throw some water on my face, look piercingly into my
reflection, and order that angry-for-no-reason face of mine to stop
this descent into bedlam.
</P>
<P>
   I am back in the living room, and all the blinds are firmly hung
already. The handyman glances at me and picks up his tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not straight,'' I tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He pokes the blinds lightly, pulls them up, moves them down.
``There,'' he says to me, ``all straight now.''
</P>
<P>
   I am feeling lousy. This monster within me won't leave me. And I
know that if the man in front of me was the man I married who is
now safe in his office, he would have thrown his arms up in the air
and with a pained look on his face headed to the nearest bakery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This weather is driving me crazy,'' I tell this guy who, by
the way, is named Guy. But I know that La Nina has nothing to do
with this time-of-month storm that rages through my body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmm,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' I tell Guy, ``if the blinds are not straight, my
husband will blame me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmm,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he is a nice guy, but crooked blinds drive him crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmm,'' Guy edges toward the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not me,'' my voice has reached its highest pitch. ``I am very
reasonable when it comes to straight lines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell you what,'' says Guy, who seems no stranger to strange
suburban ladies. ``Let your husband take a look at the blinds and
have him call me.''
</P>
<P>
   I muster the last remnants of my sanity. I bid Guy adieu. I even
remember to sign the check.
</P>
<P>
   There, all is well, I am sure the weather will change for the
better. And, thanks to Guy, I have managed to seek some relief by
rattling someone else's sanity.
</P>
<P>
   How do I know? The poor guy left all his tools in my living
room. I doubt he will be back soon.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gladys Alam Saroyan is a free-lance writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
