u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-KIDNAPPER-BOS &LR;      07-08 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-KIDNAPPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE A SYMBOL OF MEXICAN CRIME RUNNING RAMPANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Where is Daniel Arizmendi Lopez?
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several weeks, police officers and army troops
have scoured Mexico City and its surrounding states in hopes of
nabbing the elusive reputed kidnapper who has become this country's
most notorious criminal. But Arizmendi, 39, known as
(itals)cortaorejas,(unitals) or ``ear cutter'', for the way he
allegedly mutilates his hostages to get families to pay ransom,
remains at large, and a living, if unseen, symbol of Mexico's crime
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the massive search for the drug lord Amado Carrillo
Fuentes a year ago _ which ended when he died during botched
plastic surgery in Mexico City _ have Mexicans seen such a
concentrated hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The search has become a national saga. Headlines about the hunt
for him and his accomplices have rivaled coverage devoted to the
World Cup soccer tournament and to the continuing struggle between
the government and guerrillas in the southern states of Chiapas and
Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many kidnappings are attributable to the
Arizmendi ring. Estimates from officials range from 18 to 200 over
the past eight years. In an interview Arizmendi granted last month
to a Mexico City newspaper, he admitted to 20. Observers believe he
has netted more than $40 million in ransom.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, authorities raided a half-dozen of Arizmendi's
homes in Mexico City and Cuernavaca, about 40 miles south in the
state of Morelos, in hopes of catching him. Although police and
army troops arrested Arizmendi's wife, son, daughter, and
daughter-in-law and seized $5 million, they missed their target,
who reportedly slipped away in a stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Arizmendi's younger brother, Aurelio, allegedly a
major figure in the kidnapping ring, was arrested in a southern
Mexico City neighborhood following a car chase and a daylight
sidewalk shootout. Officials said they had been tailing Aurelio for
five days.
</P>
<P>
   From his hospital bed where he was taken after being shot during
the capture, the younger Arizmendi gave candid and grisly accounts
of how the kidnappings were carried out and of how victims were
beaten and their ears cut off with scissors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daniel was the chief, Daniel cut the ears,'' Aurelio said in
television and newspaper interviews. ``We never had regrets. We
never thought about that. It was all about work.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidnappings have become widespread in Mexico and in other Latin
American countries over the last few years. In Mexico City, for
example, where many abductions are cases in which taxi drivers take
passengers hostage at gunpoint and rob them, police report nearly
2,000 cases in three years, though many say the actual number is
higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizmendi ring has hit mostly Mexican and Spanish
business-people. Aurelio said in the interview that there have been
eight ear cuttings and that two people have died.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnappings are often seen as a relatively low-risk and
high-profit crime, especially during bad economic times. And weak
criminal justice systems encourage police and prosecutors to become
accomplices, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   The rash of abductions and assaults in Mexico, once considered
among the safest of Latin American countries, has spawned a rapidly
growing industry in private security and kidnapping insurance. Many
executives, for example, have resorted to riding in bulletproof
cars with tinted windows and surrounding themselves with
bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the perception of impunity, that criminals can
commit these crimes and get away with them,'' said Arturo
Valenzuela, director of the Center for Latin American Studies at
Georgetown University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   To halt the tide of abductions, the Mexican attorney general
formed an antikidnapping unit late last year. The force includes
about three-dozen police officers who receive higher pay and three
months of special training.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe Arizmendi, a former chauffeur and state
police officer in Morelos who reportedly turned to crime as a
small-time car thief in the 1980s, began his kidnapping spree in
Mexico City's working-class neighborhoods. Eventually, the ring
began working almost exclusively in the financial districts and
affluent areas.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi kept several rank-and-file as well as top police
officials on his payroll, investigators say. These officers either
helped carry out kidnappings, authorities say, or have given
Arizmendi tips to avoid capture.
</P>
<P>
   Both Arizmendi brothers have denied receiving protection from
law enforcement officers. But several top officials _ including the
former chief of the antikidnapping police unit in Morelos, a
federal agent, and a prosecutor _ have been arrested and charged
with helping the ring. Morelos Governor Jorge Carrillo has also
resigned because of the scandal, although he has denied any
involvement with Arizmendi.
</P>
<P>
   Police agencies and media outlets say they receive calls daily
from witnesses claiming they've spotted Arizmendi. Late last year,
Mexico's attorney general offered a $625,000 reward for his
capture.
</P>
<P>
   On one television broadcast last week, an anonymous caller said
Arizmendi and his associates were eating in a restaurant in the
posh neighborhood of Polanco on the city's north side. Armed
officers and TV cameras rushed to the scene but found he wasn't
there.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi himself added to the drama last month when he
reportedly called the Mexico City newspaper Reforma and gave an
extensive interview. When asked what his message was to the police
who are searching for him, Arizmendi responded: ``Well, nothing,
except that I wish them luck, and hopefully, the day they find me,
they catch me and kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the interview, Arizmendi admitted to being addicted to
money and alcohol, adding, ``I believe I'm going to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if police capture Arizmendi, many experts and residents in
this city of 20 milllion people agree that it would be a symbolic
but small victory in the struggle against rampant crime. Already
this year, there have been a record 100 bank robberies in Mexico
City. And although record keeping is erratic, one government
estimate reportedly shows that homicides here were up 50 percent
from 1990 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until the economic situation here improves will things
change,'' said Alfonso Pasapera Mora, a professor of criminal law
at the Universidad Iberoamericana in Mexico City. ``I believe
people prefer to take these criminal risks so long as they find
themselves in desperate economic situations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe assistant Lorena Zarate contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRANSPORTATION-URBAN-     07-08 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPORTATION-URBAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG-TICKET TRANSPORTATION ITEMS REQUIRE BIGGER BACKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cities must build. But should government pay for big projects,
or should they be left to the private sector, which, after all,
stands to benefit?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is reasonably clear, concluded some professionals and
academics who recently focused on the question: Government should
build the transportation links _ the highways, the tunnels, the
railroads _ because they pay off big-time. But the stadiums and
convention centers have more uncertain economic returns and should
be looked at skeptically.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are caveats and exceptions. Obviously, there are the
roads and transit lines to nowhere, plotted only to create a few
temporary jobs and (sometimes named) to support a politician's ego.
Forget those.
</P>
<P>
   And there are cities, according to Heywood T. Sanders, professor
of urban administration at Trinity University in San Antonio, that
are established ``destination'' cities and for which big public
investments can make sense. You know which ones they are. There's a
good chance you've been to them: Las Vegas, Orlando, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Boston? No easy answer there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a somewhat peculiar place,'' said Sanders. ``It's a
good visitor destination, but it's got some problems.'' The
downside includes location, far from the growing population centers
of the American West and Southwest; weather (enough said); access,
which refers particularly to the fact that Logan Airport is close
but one frequently can't get there; and hotel costs, among the
gougiest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders spoke last month at a seminar &UR;  &LR; in Boston called
``Evaluating Infrastructure Projects: Concrete Lessons for Policy
Making.'' The session was organized by the Pioneer Institute, a
market-inclined think tank that occasionally pays academics and
consultants to assess potential projects like Boston's new
convention center. Or those under way, like the controversially
priced, $10.8 billion Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking of the panelists, such as Alan Altshuler, director
of the Taubman Center for State and Local Government at Harvard
University, was that transportation links have generally returned
more than they cost in economic benefits. Altshuler was secretary
of transportation under Governor Frank Sargent in the 1970s, when
Sargent, a Republican, was perhaps the first prominent politician
in the country to say no to another big urban stretch of highway
like those that had crushed myriad neighborhoods nationwide. It was
the so-called Inner Belt that would have pushed Interstate 95
through Boston and Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Zuk, director of the Big Dig, formally known as the
Central Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel project, of course defended the
effort and, in general, ``the grand idea'' of transportation
megaprojects.
</P>
<P>
   Highway projects that used to cost a mere million dollars a mile
and were obviously good investments have turned into those like the
Big Dig, which at eight miles and almost $11 billion is _ well, you
figure it out. It takes a while to get a payback on an investment
like that, no matter how many commuters and delivery trucks it
speeds through Boston at rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   The United States spends a small portion of its gross national
project on infrastructure, Zuk said, adding ``That is a very
important deficiency.'' He named the Suez and Panama canals,
Brooklyn Bridge, and interstate railroad and highway systems as
transportation links, often controversial, that now are economic
pillars.
</P>
<P>
   Take even the $4 billion Denver airport, which Taubman Center
assistant director David Luberoff noted was so far from population
centers ``you're more or less in Kansas.'' Said Zuk, ``Denver may
be an airport built in a place where nobody is today ... but in 20
years it won't be,'' and he suggested building every new airport
``just far enough away that people will accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stadiums and convention centers, though, are another matter,
said Sanders, who was pessimistic a year ago about the return on
spending hundreds of millions of public dollars in Boston and said
he is even more so now. He recently compared what he says were the
convention industry's own projections for the last few years to
reality. To put it in academic jargon, the curves don't occupy the
same space on the chart. And the trends are in opposite directions
_ predictions optimistic, actual number of conventions declining.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are inevitably oversold,'' says Sanders, author of
``Convention Center Follies,'' an article in the Summer 1998 issue
of the journal Public Interest. And bad public dollars get thrown
after good ones. The attitude is: ``If it doesn't work, build some
more hotels next door.''
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, Atlanta, Milwaukee, Cleveland, and other cities
trying to prosper, says Sanders, ``The answer lies in the grand
idea. The grand big-fix idea is alive and well and charming.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sanders blames not only politicians but also business
people for wasting increasingly scarce public funds. He cites ``the
astonishing political strength and persistence of large-scale
business interests in big cities,'' the same groups that
shortsightedly pushed for interstate highways through urban
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, powerful Boston and state business interests
led by the Artery Business Committee crushed a sputtering effort to
remove tolls from the Massachusetts Turnpike and harbor tunnels, in
a court victory that ensures a big source of Big Dig funding.
</P>
<P>
   The leanings of academics aside, there is an emerging public
attitude in the wake of the counterculture '60s and the perhaps
excessive '80s that business is as business does, and big-project
plans should be judged on a case-by-case basis, not based on who is
for and who against.
</P>
<P>
   And in politically alive locales like Boston, projects are going
to be critically considered whoever is behind them, to avoid
perpetual regrets like the elimination of the city's West End
neighborhood, a victim of urban renewal. The Massachusetts Port
Authority's combined stadium and convention center idea for South
Boston was dashed in part because Boston _ unlike some less
desirable cities _ doesn't need to pay wealthy team owners to come
to town.
</P>
<P>
   According to Luberoff, the question of whether the federal
government should engage in huge building projects with public
money was debated from the nation's beginnings but never officially
answered. So the debate devolved to the states, with the same
inconclusive result, and then to the cities. Only with the Great
Depression did public works come alive.
</P>
<P>
   History repeated in the 1950s, with federally funded
urban-renewal programs. And the business community was supportive,
Sanders contends, because spending public money meant that land
values stood to increase.
</P>
<P>
   No project ever represented that principle better than the Big
Dig. Not only will scores of businesses downtown, formerly faced
with an elevated eyesore of a highway, eventually abut inviting
open space. But a new city neighborhood has been opened up on the
South Boston waterfront, largely because of the Ted Williams Tunnel
connection to the airport, and eventual direct access to the
turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is going to really reap the benefits'' of the Big Dig and
the convention center? asked Luberoff. Both are being paid for with
your taxes. A healthy economy will benefit all, as the nation is
fortunate enough to experience now. But being situated next to
these gleaming new projects is the equivalent of being personally
handed another big check.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Boston, the Turnpike Authority and the state want to
start talking about a means by which those who benefit will pay
more of a share of the considerable cost of maintenance and upkeep.
So that the taxpayers who paid in the first place won't just keep
on paying.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas C. Palmer Jr. covers transportation issues for the
Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
