<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-EXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EXES' MARKS THE SPOT OF ROCK 'N' ROLL DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE EXES 
By Pagan Kennedy 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23, 203 pp., $23 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever wanted to play in a rock band? Go on tour in a
beat-up van and sleep on the cold floor of someone's
ex-girlfriend's apartment? Practice night after night for months in
order to perform for 13 people? And all so that sometimes on some
nights you will connect so fully with the right combination of
melody and volume that you and your bandmates move like one
creature and mesmerize everyone listening?
</P>
<P>
   Author Pagan Kennedy's second novel, ``The Exes,'' is for anyone
who has ever dreamed of dominating rock 'n' roll clubland _ and for
everyone who has ever spent a night there. This good-humored and
often sly book creates a fictional band and lets it loose in the
real and gritty world of the Boston scene. Told in four parts, by
the four band members, it gives us a loosely related tale of how a
rock group forms, makes some kind of name for itself, and then
teeters on the brink of disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   The band of the title, the Exes, comes into being when
singer/guitarist and sometime art student Lilly conceives of a
group in which everyone once went out with another band member. Her
idea appeals to Hank, her ex-boyfriend, largely because he realizes
that his attraction to Lilly's wildness, her desperation to become
famous, is more of a ``musical crush'' than a personal one. When
they win over Shaz, a bisexual bassist who proves the most
musically adept of the group, and her unstable ex, Walt, a former
graduate student still raw from a psychiatric hospitalization, the
band _ and the setup _ are complete.
</P>
<P>
   Before long the Exes encounter a modicum of success, but it
takes a while longer for its members to get used to not losing.
Lilly, who grew up poor and socially outcast, learns that what
makes her different _ her ``stink,'' as she calls it _ is also her
creative germ. Shaz keeps trying to reconcile her family-oriented
Islamic upbringing with her sexuality. Walt is just trying to hold
himself together, and Hank, seemingly the most normal Ex, secretly
suspects that his calm suburban upbringing has left him without a
soul. In some way, all four have been outsiders, and at first their
new popularity shocks them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lilly grew used to these guys with their never-to-be-shot
movies and their never-to-be-organized benefit concerts. They
wanted to lay claim to you, if only in some imaginary way. For they
had seen something magical glinting out of you when you were up
there on stage, and they wanted credit for having such good
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens next is sometimes obvious (to anyone who has ever
been in a band) and also very funny. Egos interfere with
songwriting as they once did with dating. Secret alliances form,
and stale resentments heat up. Cold romances rekindle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all these complications are human ones, rather than
musical. And that's what helps this sharp little novel transcend
its setting. The band setup is not only a hip device, replete with
enough name-dropping to appeal to scenesters, it's also a lovely
pressure cooker of emotions. Throw four people into one basement
practice room night after night and see what develops. Add late
hours, liquor, and an occasional motel room, and watch the
combination ignite.
</P>
<P>
   The use of a few only mildly disguised characters and places in
``The Exes'' is a point of interest, but ultimately irrelevant.
Kennedy knows her stuff _ she published her own basically
autobiographical fanzine, called Pagan's Head, for years, turning
the experience into the book ``'Zine: How I Spent Six Years of My
Life in the Underground and Finally Found Myself ... I Think.'' And
yes, local rockers will get a kick out of recognizing the local
music fanzine The Noise (or The Source, as Kennedy calls it) and
wondering if the Satanistas are really the Satanics. But what makes
this book so enjoyable is its author's eye for detail, from the
sweet smell of Cambridge's Necco Factory to the rush of playing
music: ``Suddenly when all the factors are right you suddenly click
in. You're there. You aren't playing the music anymore _ it's going
through you, like electricity. ... You could kill a person by
hitting him with just enough sound at just the right frequency. ...
And sometimes you want that. You want to find the one perfect note
that will shatter everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy roots her people in a real place and time, and works the
humor and in-jokes inherent to these. But she also portrays the
loneliness and aimlessness that come to young adults starting life
in the city. Hip as they are, her people connect and disconnect
like any others, and ``The Exes'' has their beat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
