<HEADLINE>
AS ASIAN ECONOMIES TUMBLE, SO DO INVESTORS' PORTFOLIOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Asia's biggest economies text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Collapsing currencies and sinking economies cascaded from
Indonesia to South Korea, robbing US mutual fund investors in Asia
of as much as one-fourth to one-half of the value of their
investments in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second disaster in nine months for investors in Asian
mutual funds. US funds invested in Asia were already pummeled by a
collapse in Asian economies _ and stock markets _ that started a
year ago when Thailand's currency, the baht, plunged.
</P>
<P>
   Only Japan's stock market seemed to float above the pandemonium
_ the Nikkei stock index dipped only slightly in the second
quarter. But the resilient Nikkei masked a severe downturn in the
island country.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for Southeast Asia to fully recover, the Japanese must yank
the world's second-biggest economy out of a deflationary spiral fed
by a weak yen, a sinking banking system, and shaky consumer
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The region's entire economy is intricately bound to Japan's
fortunes. Japan buys one-fourth of China's exports. Japanese banks
lend to businesses all over Asia. Malaysian plants owned by
Matsushita, the Japanese electronics giant, produce 5 percent of
Malaysia's income. Global fallout could be severe if the Japanese
yen plunges further and China is forced to devalue its currency,
the yuan. If the yen declines, Chinese exporters would be less able
to compete in world markets with lower-cost Japanese goods.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan only last month was declared officially in recession,
and policy makers have barely begun to deal with a crisis in its
banking system that could drive its _ and possibly the world's _
economy down further.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Gendreau, an investment strategist for Salomon Smith
Barney in New York and a specialist in emerging markets, said he
fears that Asia's economic slump may be the worst globally since
the Great Depression of the 1930s. ``I see very few signs of a
turnaround on the horizon,'' Gendreau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two or three years are going to be awful years for
the economies of the Asian region _ there's no doubt about that,''
said Mark Madden, who travels to Asia as manager of a $200 million
emerging markets fund for Pioneer Funds in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But Madden predicted investor confidence would grow as
governments tackle banking crises and corporate bankruptcies. When
that begins, investors will ``begin to anticipate an improvement
and a bottoming of things.'' Madden is most optimistic about South
Korea, Thailand, Singapore and, perhaps, Indonesia. China and Hong
Kong ``are much further away,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Investors could not bear a repeat of the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, rioting over rising prices for rice and fuel
forced President Suharto to resign in May. South Korea's finance
minister was arrested and charged with the ``crime'' of bringing
the country to the verge of collapse and its financial system to
insolvency. Recipients of aid from the International Monetary Fund
_ Indonesia, Thailand, and South Korea _ are suffering from tight
credit. Malaysia's resilient economy is strained. And the condition
of China's banks is in question.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil was disastrous for US investors. After gaining
between 2 percent and 5 percent in the first quarter, all four
major types of Asian funds tracked by Lipper Analytical Services
Inc. in New York declined in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   China funds had the biggest loss among all categories of equity
funds, falling 28.34 percent. Funds invested in the Pacific Rim _
excluding Japan _ dropped 26.93 percent. Funds with diverse Asia
stocks declined 15.95 percent _ their losses were softened by
holdings in Japan. Japan-invested funds declined just 1.18 percent
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the worst-performing funds were single-country funds
invested in Malaysia, South Korea, and Singapore. The WEBS Malaysia
fund managed by Barclays Global Fund Advisors in San Francisco lost
46.01 percent in the second quarter and 73.96 percent over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   The plunge in Asia funds in the fourth quarter of 1997 was
slightly worse: China funds were down 29.41 percent, according to
Lipper: Pacific Rim funds, excluding Japan, were down 28.26
percent; regional funds, down 23.44. Only Japan funds fared much
worse last fall, declining 16.17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn has been a big lesson for American investors.
Though some dipped their toes in Japan as early as the 1950s, they
did not become adventurous in emerging markets until the 1990s. US
investors now have $10 billion in nearly 200 such funds.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some who see &UR;  &LR; bright spots amid Asia's gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Farrell, head of Asian investments for Guinness Flight
Investment Management Ltd. in London, &UR;  &LR; predicted ``more normal''
economic conditions in Hong Kong, the home of Asia's third-largest
stock market (after Japan and Taiwan). Most important for Hong Kong
and China are continued growth in the United States and Europe,
which fueled recent export growth in the two Asian markets. In
South Korea, he is encouraged by efforts to start the ``painful''
restructuring of the &UR;  &LR; chaebol trading groups, such as electronics
giant Samsung. Malaysian plantations that produce palm oil are
doing well, too.
</P>
<P>
   But he hesitated to predict when a regionwide recovery would
lift the most troubled economies _ Indonesia, Thailand, and South
Korea. Said Farrell, in a moment of frankness: ``Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ASIAN GDPS &QL; 
Percent change, gross domestic product, of Asia's biggest
economies. &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997 ! 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   actual ! forecast &QL;
</P>
<P>
   China ! 8.8% ! 6.0%  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia ! 7.8% ! -2.5% Singapore ! 7.8% ! 0.9% Taiwan ! 6.8% !
4.8% South Korea ! 5.5% ! -6.5% Hong Kong ! 5.3% ! - 2.0%
Philippines ! 5.1% ! 0.8% India ! 5.0% ! 5.6% Indonesia ! 4.6% !
-14.7% Japan ! 0.9% ! -2.1% Thailand ! -0.3% ! -8.7%  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   United States ! 3.8% ! 3.4% &QL; 
SOURCE: Salomon Smith Barney &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
