<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE LANDSCAPE WAS THE STAR OF THE MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONUMENT VALLEY, Utah -- In 1924, Harry Goulding and his wife,
Leona, opened a trading post here and lived simply with their
Navajo neighbors amid the stark remoteness of this beautiful
valley. But in the Depression of the 1930s, ochre rock and
vermilion dust fed no one, so amid deepening poverty, Goulding
sought help in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   He heard that United Artists was scouting locations for a new
Western. Goulding camped at the studio until he could show a
portfolio of black-and-white photographs by Josef Muench to the
director, John Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Born Sean Aloysius Feeney to immigrants from Galway in Cape
Elizabeth, Maine, Ford had never seen such sights, not even on the
screen of the Dreamland Theater in Portland. In Hollywood, where he
changed his name to John Ford, he eventually directed 136 movies,
34 of them westerns, the most memorable of which he filmed in
Monument Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the cameras rolled for ``Stagecoach'' 60 years ago, making
a star of the actor who played the Ringo Kid, a Midwesterner who
also changed his name, from Marion Morrison to John Wayne.
``Stagecoach'' was a box-office hit for Ford, Wayne, and Monument
Valley. Producer Walter Wanger hired Navajo riders to play Apache
warriors and a few weeks' work on ``Stagecoach'' earned tribesmen a
total of $48,000, a hefty payroll in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can say that the real star of my westerns has
always been the land,'' Ford once said. The modern director who
follows that philosophy is Robert Redford. In ``A River Runs
Through it'' and ``The Horse Whisperer,'' Redford's Montana is the
star.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford-Wayne collaboration flowered as vividly as the
cliffrose and purple sage in Monument Valley. In Paris, ``The
Searchers'' is studied nearly every day at the Sorbonne; Left Bank
bookshops sell solemn tomes on the existential odyssey of Ethan
Edwards, the ornery cowboy played by Wayne in the 1956 film.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, a cavalry trilogy portrayed Wayne posed against higher
command. In ``Rio Grande'' and ``Fort Apache'' the Duke battles and
curses the Army's bureaucracy. ``She Wore A Yellow Ribbon,'' his
first cavalry epic in Technicolor, also stressed Ford's elegaic
longing for frontier values. Next to Goulding's Lodge stands a
movie-set stone cabin, a shrine for Duke fans, which housed Wayne's
character, Captain Nathan Brittles, a cavalry officer on the verge
of retirement who faces one last patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Among visitors here is one whose faulty recall evokes ``A
Child's Christmas in Wales'' by Dylan Thomas, who could ``never
remember whether it snowed for six days and nights when I was 12 or
for 12 days and nights when I was 6.'' In a vanishing American
demographic, many a moviegoer can not remember whether he saw ``She
Wore A Yellow Ribbon'' 10 times when he was 8 or eight times when
he was 10.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne once said that ``For the big screen, for the real outdoor
dramas, you have to do it where God put the West.'' The 30,000
acres of majestic buttes and mesas have attracted other movies,
from ``Easy Rider'' to ``Thelma and Louise.''
</P>
<P>
   A mile above sea level, the austere land where Arizona and Utah
converge with Colorado and New Mexico attracts tourists who gaze at
the pictographs, painted images, and petroglyphs, carvings, left in
the caves of nearby Mystery Valley by the Anasazi, called ``the
ancient ones'' by the Navajo.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur and professional photographers arrive daily, drawn by
the architectural splendor of the brooding monoliths. Don Imus and
Fred Imus, raised in Arizona, followed Muench's trail and published
in 1997 the results of their Nikon-and-Hasselblad forays in ``Two
Guys, Four Corners.'' A stunning sunrise portrait of the valley is
captioned: ``The Southwestern equivalent of the New York City
skyline minus anything with Donald Trump's name on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid its towering cathedrals, formed by millions of years of
dust and wind, the place where God put the West has no room for
Mammon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
