<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5428 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PORNOGRAPHY-BOS &LR;      07-08 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PORNOGRAPHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ADULT' SHOPS, BARS BRACE FOR NYC CRACKDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any day now, city inspectors are going to march into
Billy's Topless, a Manhattan bar where women have been dancing
bare-breasted for a quarter-century, and order its current crew of
young ladies to slip into something a little more decent.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors are going to be marching all over town that day,
enforcing a zoning law that bans ``adult establishments'' within
500 feet of a school, church, residence, or another adult
establishment. It is a restriction that spells doom for all but a
couple of dozen of New York City's 155 strip joints, porn shops,
peep shows, and XXX video salons.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation was passed by the City Council more than three
years ago, but legal challenges invoking the First Amendment's
guarantee of free expression have kept it holed up in the courts
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, a federal appeals court, like all the state
courts before it, ruled the measure constitutional. Soon the
appeals court will issue a technical document, called a mandate.
Then, city officials say, enforcement will be quick and decisive.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Anthony, the 78-year-old owner of Billy's Topless, stood
behind his bar the other day, taking a long drag on another
cigarette and shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing about this,'' he said of the new law, ``is
that Mayor Giuliani made a deal with Disney that they'd clean up
42nd Street. I have no objections to that. I applauded that _ 42nd
Street was a whole bunch of sleaze. But don't say the whole city
has to do the same. You'll put a lot of people out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony has been running Billy's, on the corner of 24th Street
and Sixth Avenue, a rather undeveloped section of Chelsea, for 22
years. (The original Billy died in 1979, shortly after selling him
the place.) For 10 years before then, he was an agent who provided
the dancers to Billy's and several places like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I got into this profession was I used to make
costumes,'' he said. ``One day, a girl comes in and says, `Can you
make me a two-piece go-go outfit?' This was more than 30 years ago,
so I say, `What's that?' Turns out she worked as a go-go dancer for
an agent, he started coming up to my shop, I got interested in what
he was doing, and that's how it started.''
</P>
<P>
   He slapped his right hand on the bar, exposing a tattoo on his
knuckles _ a devil with a halo over its head. ``I got that 52 years
ago in Panama, on my way back from World War II,'' he said. ``I
call it `The Good Devil.' It's me.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked up. ``I mean, what's wrong with this business?'' he
asked, spreading his arms to encompass the place. ``This is a
neighborhood bar. People come in here, have a drink, enjoy
themselves. We don't have any hookers, we don't have any drugs,
nobody's hustling anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   When the law takes hold, Anthony will not have to shut down. He
could relocate to some site in a city-specified ``manufacturing
area,'' ``but that would put me way over on 12th Avenue,'' he said
dismissively. ``Who's going to go over there?''
</P>
<P>
   Or he could have the dancers put on a few more square inches of
clothing. The law is anatomically explicit on what areas of the
body have to be covered for a place like Billy's to stay in
business. Basically, ``Billy's girls,'' as a sign in the bar calls
them, would have to put on something akin to bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's what I'll do,'' Anthony said with a shrug. ``I'll
comply. I don't plan on retiring, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The law provides similar escape hatches for the XXX video
arcades. If they adjust their stock so that pornography takes up
less than 40 percent of the floor space, then they can stay where
they are.
</P>
<P>
   Herald Price Fahringer, the lawyer who is representing a
consortium of adult establishments in the court battles over the
zoning law, said last week that most of his clients will probably
make the adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   One Fahringer client, the owner of Manhattan Video, a triple-X
palace in midtown, just down the street from a Lord &AMP; Taylor
department store, put it like this: ``Hey, they want me to sell
violence and horror instead of sex? OK. I'll sell violence and
horror.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 1, 1996, authorities shut down all 38 of the porn
stores that dominated 42nd Street between Broadway and Eighth
Avenue. Since then, the Street and the whole Times Square district
have undergone a transformation few had thought possible _ from a
din of drugs, crime, and prostitution to an urban theme park of
comparative wholesomeness.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup was accomplished through the bluntest of
instruments. A state agency condemned the whole block as a
``disaster area,'' took title to the properties, and evicted the
tenants and owners, reimbursing them with a modest estimate of
``fair market value.''
</P>
<P>
   This tactic would have been too costly to apply to the whole
city. So, like several other cities, New York moved to control the
rest of the porn industry through zoning laws. The Supreme Court
had ruled that regulating porn shops is not unconstitutional as
long as it can be demonstrated that their current locations affect
crime, commerce, or safety. City lawyers, business organizations,
and neighborhood action groups set out to make the case.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the inspectors make their move, the controversy will
not be over. Fahringer is still hoping the federal appeals court
will consider his petititon for another rehearing on the issue. If
that fails, he will take the case to the US Supreme Court. ``We've
already prepared our papers for that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Legal issues could spin out for years or decades. For example,
if an inspector finds that a video shop carries more than 40
percent pornography, the owner could challenge the finding, arguing
that some portion of the tapes are not pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute doesn't delineate clearly,'' Fahringer said,
adding with a chuckle, ``We'll have a lot of fun in compliance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
