<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5430 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARINGS-BOS &LR;      07-08 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH DRAMA TO LOW FARCE, MOB CASE EVOLVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the astounding allegations of Stephen Flemmi first
made headlines last summer, a skeptical public weighed the word of
the veteran gangster against that of the FBI, which Flemmi accused
of unethical, even criminal, conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The gangster lost _ at first.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom held that Flemmi's most startling claims _
that he and his criminal sidekick, James J. ``Whitey'' Bulger, had
paid off an FBI supervisor and were tipped off to investigations
during their years as the bureau's marquee informants _ simply
couldn't be true.
</P>
<P>
   A terse, two-sentence statement issued by the head of the Boston
office of the FBI last June reminded the public that those claims
were made by ``an individual who is a co-defendant in a pending
federal racketeering case.'' That seemed to speak for many within
and outside of the law-enforcement community.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after months of federal court hearings sparked in large
part by Flemmi's allegations, most of what initially seemed
unimaginable has been supported by a first-hand source: former FBI
supervisor John M. Morris, who ran the bureau's Boston organized
crime squad in the late 1970s and early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mark L. Wolf has suspended the hearings until August
without hearing from Flemmi or the mobster's longtime bureau
contact, former special agent John Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi is expected to testify. But Connolly _ who unlike Morris
has not been given immunity from prosecution _ invoked his Fifth
Amendment right against self-incrimination when called as a
witness.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Still, in interviews and through his lawyer, Connolly has
denied key points of Morris's testimony, including his alleged
involvement in funneling money to Morris and telling Bulger and
Flemmi about investigations or indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Connolly has acknowledged that Bulger and Flemmi were given
permission to continue their gambling and loan-sharking operations
while working as FBI informants.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Flemmi or Connolly, the hearings have had moments
of high drama and low farce:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Morris admitting that he told Connolly an informant had
implicated Bulger and Flemmi in a murder, fully expecting the
information would get back to them. The informant wound up dead.
</P>
<P>
   Morris's wife ordering him to throw out a silver ice bucket, a
gift from Flemmi. Morris and two other agents planting a fake bomb
under the car of a reluctant witness. &UR;  &LR; FBI agents welcoming Bulger
and Flemmi as dinner guests _ and Flemmi's elderly parents
reciprocating. And Bulger's brother, Billy, then the state Senate
president, wandering next door to the Flemmis just as one party was
breaking up.
</P>
<P>
   But the most stunning testimony came from Morris, who retired
from the bureau in 1995 and who now lives in Tennessee. During
eight days on the witness stand in April, Morris admitted that he
had alerted Flemmi and Bulger to an investigation targeting
bookmakers in 1988 and had asked a federal prosecutor to keep them
out of a 1979 indictment for fixing horse races.
</P>
<P>
   Morris had taken $5,000 from Bulger during one of the cozy
``get-togethers'' Flemmi described in an affidavit, plus $2,000
that Flemmi hadn't mentioned _ $1,000 Morris asked for to pay for a
rendezvous with his girlfriend in Georgia and another $1,000 hidden
in a case of wine.
</P>
<P>
   But Morris denied that he alerted Bulger and Flemmi to the 1995
extortion and racketeering indictment that landed Flemmi in jail
and sent Bulger on the run. And the former agent said he never told
the pair they were free to commit any crime as long as they didn't
kill anyone, as Flemmi claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, more than three months of hearings suggest the FBI wasn't
eager to lock up its prized snitches.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Nearly 200 documents, many of them from Bulger's and Flemmi's
previously secret FBI files, and the testimony of FBI agents and
supervisors suggest a hands-off policy, or at least a willingness
to look the other way.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for example, the alleged shakedown of a South Boston
real estate agent by Bulger and two associates in the late '80s,
complete with threats at gunpoint and chilling references to body
bags.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The alleged victim agreed to secretly record meetings and to
testify against Bulger and the others, but later backed away after
the FBI says the threats stopped. There is nothing in the FBI files
on the case, even though the realtor was interviewed at least
twice, according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   And three or four years before a 1990 indictment charging 51
people with running four major South Boston cocaine rings, the FBI
had been told that Bulger was extorting money from drug dealers. A
year before the raids, an FBI agent submitted a report on one drug
dealer paying ``tribute'' to Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   But when the indictments were returned, the only mention of
Bulger was a quote in the indictment from a defendant. Unless
Bulger got his cut, the defendant said, ``You didn't deal drugs, or
you ended up dead.'' Attorneys for Flemmi and his three
codefendants in the 1995 case, including reputed New England Mafia
boss Francis P. Salemme, argue that the FBI ignored Bulger's and
Flemmi's crimes because they had been promised immunity in exchange
for information they provided on their criminal rivals _ especially
those in the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, equating the FBI's inaction with a formal pledge of
immunity remains a tough case to make, legal experts say. There is
no document to prove such a pledge, and a string of FBI agents and
supervisors have denied they ever gave Bulger and Flemmi permission
to commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a stretch,'' said Rosanna Cavallaro, an associate
professor at Suffolk University Law School. ``I don't think the
fact that they turned a blind eye is the equivalent of a promise of
immunity. That's a leap for a judge to make.''
</P>
<P>
   To do so, she said, would create ``a pretty troubling
standard,'' in effect transforming ``a good-buddy relationship into
a kind of de facto immunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Said one former federal prosecutor, ``Even if the FBI looked the
other way for 10, 20, or how many years doesn't mean they can't go
after him in the 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   But defense attorney Robert Sheketoff, who has represented
organized crime figures and whose law partner, Kimberly Homan, has
assisted in Flemmi's defense, sees it differently. ``I think what
matters is if there was an agreement, implicit or explicit,'' he
said. ``People ... can share the same mental state without any
piece of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheketoff says the hearings have provided a valuable public
service in exposing ``the seamy side of law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that the general public and the legal community
understand that there's a lot of dishonesty in this business,'' he
said, ``and it's not just the criminals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
