<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-MERGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY GROUPS POISED TO QUESTION MERGER OF NATIONSBANK,
BANKAMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Most bank mergers are dry, routine affairs. But
a political firefight could erupt in California over the proposed
$60 billion acquisition of San Francisco's BankAmerica Corp. by
NationsBank Corp. of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Community groups fear the merger will lead to poorer banking
service and less money invested in California's low-income and
minority neighborhoods, charges denied by both banks, which claim
strong records of community lending.
</P>
<P>
   The debate will heat up Thursday and Friday during a public
meeting in San Francisco of the Federal Reserve Bank. At least 200
people who support or oppose the bank deal are scheduled to appear,
said Fed spokeswoman Carol Eckert.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have jumped into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress _ including California Democrats
Barbara Lee and Maxine Waters, both members of the House Banking
Committee _ sent a letter Tuesday to NationsBank Chairman Hugh
McColl, expressing concern about the impact of the merger on
banking services to low-income and minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Association of Bay Area Governments held
a hearing last month to study the economic impact of the merger.
And the Los Angeles City Council recently passed a resolution
calling for public hearings on the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers can't stop the planned merger, but they can pressure
federal regulators, such as the Federal Reserve Board and the
Treasury and Justice departments, to look more closely at the
acquisition. They could also rally public opinion against a
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can up the ante and put a lot of pressure on NationsBank if
we're not satisfied with their response,'' said Kate Emanual,
legislative director for Rep. Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Calif. ``I
would hope they would want to do the right thing, and not just blow
off congressional concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent wave of bank deals has drawn congressional attention,
but politicians appear to have little influence on the process.
Last year, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and other powerful lawmakers
objected strongly to the $16 billion sale of Philadelphia's
CoreStates Financial Corp. to First Union Corp., another Charlotte
bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed approved the merger anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether political pressure might delay or sway the outcome
of a merger application, Fred Bagwell, a Fed vice president in
Richmond, Va., said: ``The comments of local political leaders will
be taken into consideration, along with all other comments.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger between NationsBank and BankAmerica, announced in
April, would create the nation's second-largest bank with $570
billion in assets and 29 million customers. The new bank would keep
the name of the venerable San Francisco bank, but its corporate
headquarters would be in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Bank executives hope that regulators will approve the merger by
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Reinvestment Act of 1977 requires banks to make
loans in all neighborhoods in which they have branches. If a bank
has a poor community lending record to minority and low-income
areas, regulators can kill a merger proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the NationsBank-BankAmerica merger proposal, bank
executives announced a $350 billion, 10-year commitment nationwide
in community development loans and other investments. The plan
includes $180 billion for small businesses, $115 billion for
affordable housing, $25 billion for economic development and $30
billion for consumer loans.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, BankAmerica has had a good reputation for
banking in low-income and minority areas. Community groups and
politicians fear that NationsBank may neglect or abandon its
community investments in California.
</P>
<P>
   But NationsBank executives defend their record of community
lending.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has made more than $25 billion in community investment
loans over the past five years, including $5.2 billion in mortgage
loans to minority and low-income borrowers, according to
NationsBank spokesman Scott Scredon.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also has built 14,000 affordable homes for $300 million
and invested another $340 million in 10,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who do business with us know our record is very
strong,'' said Catherine Bessant, president of NationsBank's
community investment group. ``We're the unknowns in California, but
we believe over time we'll build the kind of credibility that we've
enjoyed in other markets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
