<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5436 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GHOUL-POOL-BOS &LR;      07-08 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHOUL-POOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTORS ON THE NET MAKE A SPORT OF DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, the very idea _ gambling on famous people dying _ seems
sick. The players themselves admit it. Macabre, morbid, all that.
And yet, death comes to us all. So why not get a bet down on who'll
go 10 toes up?
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't wish for anybody to die,'' says Jake
Maruby, who runs ``Dying for Dollars,'' a popular ``death pool'' on
the Internet. ``But nothing we do is going to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grim Reaper harvests on his own schedule, but who says you
can't indulge in a bit of spectral speculation? If you were one of
the shrewd bettors who figured that Chris Farley or Princess Di
might be on the 1997 list, or Roy Rogers on the 1998 list, you hit
the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   If you had Wendy O. Williams or Tammy Wynette or Sonny Bono this
year, you chalked up big points. Frank Sinatra? Dr. Spock? Who
didn't have them? And everybody always has the Pope. He's what they
call a ``perennial.''
</P>
<P>
   Death pools have been around since at least the 19th century.
``It's a game, a very amusing game that they play in every
drawing-room in Paris whenever an `Immortal' passes on,'' Georges
Duroy says to Madame Walter in Guy de Maupassant's novel ``Bel
Ami.'' ``The game of Death and the Forty Old Men.''
</P>
<P>
   The game of Death has gone cyber now, and it includes anyone who
might ever have rated a page in People or 30 seconds on ``ET.'' At
least a dozen death pools with names like Celebrity Death Pool, A
Date With Charon Dead Pool, Derby Dead Pool, and Dead! are now on
the Internet, abetted by master lists like the Dead People Server
and You're Outta Here! that keep track of who's still living and
who has joined the choir invisible. (James Mason is dead; Jackie
Mason is alive.)
</P>
<P>
   While pools differ on format, most involve submitting a list of
up to 50 people ``marked for death'' in the upcoming calendar year.
The more prescient the pick (like rapper Tupac Shakur in 1996), the
more points.
</P>
<P>
   Some pools come with modest cash payoffs; others merely provide
bragging rights and 15 minutes of cyberfame. ``Of course we're not
rooting for these people to die,'' Ron Frey says on his site, The
Death Pool. ``We just want the points.''
</P>
<P>
   Morbid or not, death pools are undeniably intriguing. ``People
will tell me `That's sick,''' says Ray Markey, a New Jersey
computer net-worker who runs the Philadelphia Dead Pool. ``Then
they say, `Well, can I see the list?' Then they say, `You know who
you don't have?' Then they say, `How do I get in?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghoulpooling'' is, as Maruby concedes, a guilty pleasure.
Still, betting against the living is as American as the
Constitution. Why else did the Founding Fathers dream up the idea
of a vice president, who is frequently described as being ``a
heartbeat away'' from the Oval Office? Why else would we have life
insurance?
</P>
<P>
   ``People take out policies against death and dismemberment,''
says Melody Rutherford, a San Francisco computer worker who's been
involved with the Celebrity Death Pool since the early '70s.
``You're betting that you're going to die before you pay up. And
the company is betting that you won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's not as if the players are bumping people off to
move themselves up in the standings. That was the plot of ``The
Dead Pool,'' the 1988 Dirty Harry movie in which death pool
celebrities were mysteriously turning up dead. ``We frown on
that,'' says Rutherford. ``You wouldn't get any points if you
killed somebody. You'd be disqualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Death pools may be macabre, but they do have rules. Decedents
must be notable (or notorious) enough to have their passing
mentioned on television or in a major newsmagazine. They must be
certifiably dead (not just presumed) and must have been human. No
cartoon characters or animals.
</P>
<P>
   There are also rules that govern betting on (okay, against) the
living. Nobody on death row. Nobody whose government has put a
price on his head (though author Salman Rushdie is fair game, since
he's on a religious hit list). And nobody who's just received a
artificial major organ. ``No ba-boon hearts,'' says Maruby.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, anyone from Madonna to the Queen Mum is fair
game. Actuarial strategies abound. Most ghoulpoolers choose ``the
old, the feeble, the overweight, the addicted.'' Others ``chase
ambulances,'' picking celebrities who've had strokes (Gene Kelly),
developed cancer (Frank Zappa) or contracted AIDS (Randy Shilts).
</P>
<P>
   Others do ``lifestyle analyses'' and select healthy people with
unhealthy tendencies (``the young and the restless''), like rock
stars who snort coke and drive Porsches at 120 mph. Still others
pick totalitarian dictators with bloody hands (the ``live by the
sword, die by the sword'' theory) or violent types due for ``karmic
payback.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be Vincent Price to play the most extreme (and
endless) game of all. Organizers say most ghoulpoolers are between
20 and 40 and that as many women play as men. ``They're the people
next door,'' says Maruby, who has more than 80 players in his Dying
for Dollars pool, which costs $25 (``just pennies a day'') to
enter. ``They just have a different slant on things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghoulpoolers pore through newspapers and magazines and watch
``ET'' for hints that someone famous might be heading for a ``dirt
nap.'' Street rioting in a Third World country whose ruler has been
propped up by the CIA since the '70s. A punk rocker who's off to
Hazelden for his third detox. An actress who's back on chemo. An
ex-ballplayer who's too frail to make it to his Hall of Fame
enshrinement.
</P>
<P>
   They check the Noted Nonagenarians and Centenarians Web site for
anyone on borrowed time. They consult the Dead People Server to
make sure it was James Earl Ray and not James Earl Jones who
crossed the Styx. And they're scrupulous about keeping up with the
obits. ``First thing every day, they log on to the CNN Web page and
search for the word `dead,''' says Ray Markey, who has 153 members
in his Philadelphia Dead Pool and 250 more who want in for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Non-poolers usually recoil in disgust at the idea of marking
people for death. ``They pause and they say, `That's really sick
and morbid,''' says Maruby, who lives outside of New York City and
works for a publishing company. ``Then they stop and say: `What
about Milton Berle?'''
</P>
<P>
   Berle _ Great-Great-Granduncle Miltie by now _ is 89, after all.
Most ghoulpoolers have chips on his number. They're also betting
against Muhammad Ali, Fidel Castro, Kirk Douglas, Robert Downey
Jr., Rev. Billy Graham, Katharine Hepburn, Bob Hope, Saddam
Hussein, Richard Pryor, Ronald Reagan, Elizabeth Taylor, Strom
Thurmond, and Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Betting on ``perennials'' like Hope and Reagan, though, is like
betting on favorites at the race track. It's brainless and,
usually, fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hawking, the author-physicist with Lou Gehrig disease,
has already lived more than three times longer than medical tables
say he should have. ``Keith Richards,'' Maruby says. ``People have
been losing money on him for years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Teasers'' who keep eluding their demise (remember the endless
``FRANCO TAKES TURN FOR WORSE'' headlines?) drive ghoulpoolers
crazy. So connoisseurs would rather score big with an exotic bet on
someone like Pol Pot, whom most folks had forgotten was still
alive.
</P>
<P>
   John Wayne Gacy, Les Aspin, Herve Villechaize, and Lee Atwater
all carried heavy points when they booked passage with Charon. This
year's long shots include James Brown, Bob Dylan, Hugh Hefner,
Jerry Lewis, and Frank Perdue.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, betting humans as though they're Preakness entrants can
require some soul-searching. ``Am I ready to put aside that
puritanical side of me that says this is disrespectful of the
living, not to mention exploitive of the dead?'' Ron Frey muses on
The Death Pool.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of ``harvesting stiffs'' may be macabre, but graveyard
humor goes back at least as far as Lazarus. Shakespeare has dying
Mercutio cracking wise (``Ask for me tomorrow and you will find me
a grave man.'') and Hamlet holding poor Yorick's skull as though it
were a cantaloupe. So what's wrong with a decedents derby?
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Oh my God, that's terrible,''' says Melody
Rutherford. ``Then they say: `Bob Hope.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
