<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC SCHOOLS SUPPORTER MAKES CASE FOR EDUCATION WITH VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Catholic educators and their supporters were elated last month
when the Wisconsin Supreme Court ruled that government-funded
vouchers for private religious schools were constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Catholic educators see a small crack in the door
between public and private schools that has been firmly shut for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Groome, a theologian and one of the country's foremost
authorities on Catholic education, also sees cause for optimism.
But Groome, a professor at Boston College, argues that the country
is poorer for failing to understand why Catholic education is so
appealing to Catholics and non-Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, as a system of education, there probably is no
more successful system in the history of humankind,'' said Groome,
author of a recently released book, ``Educating for Life: A
Spiritual Vision for Every Teacher and Parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Groome noted that there is plenty of empirical evidence showing
that Catholic schools outperform public schools, particularly when
it comes to educating children in some of the country's most
impoverished neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote his latest book to make the case that what ails public
schools is a lack of precisely what Catholic education emphasizes _
the education of the whole student, including nurturing the soul
and shaping character.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church has been in the business of education for
nearly 2,000 years and so, Groome believes, has a place in any
serious discussion of how to educate the nation's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced there isn't a value or virtue or core curriculum
taught in a Catholic school that couldn't be taught in a public
school,'' said Groome, whose writings have had a significant
influence on Catholic school curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Groome said, any mention of values in the same breath
as public education too often leads immediately to the belief that
advocates are trying to push religion into the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   But Catholic education, when true to its historical roots, isn't
about proselytizing or forcing dogma on students, Groome said.
``The Catholic tradition stands roundly and soundly in favor of
critical reasoning and getting people to think and to think for
themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Catholic education's success, Groome believes, is
its embrace of the ``humanizing'' function of education, an idea
that can be traced to ancient Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest Greek philosopher, Plato, described teaching as
`turning the soul' of learners, and he meant touching and shaping
their innermost `being' _ their identity and agency,'' Groome
writes in his book. ``For Plato, we become and act most humanly as
our souls are turned toward the true, the good, and the beautiful,
and education is a crucial catalyst in this `turning.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is what good teachers have been been able to do: Go beyond
just filling students' brains with facts, to reach to their core,
to touch their heads and hearts. Catholic education has succeeded,
Groome argues, by focusing on seven R's: reading `riting,
`rithmetic, reverence, respect, rhetoric and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Groome also makes a clear distinction between religious and
spiritual values. While religious values may concern a specific
faith tradition, the spiritual values are broader. ``Spirituality
is that which appeals to the depths of the human soul'' and that
need not be bound by any traditional faith systems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He dismisses arguments that spiritiual values in education are
incompatible with the separation of church and state. ``When you
look at the Constitution, at the Declaration of Independence, they
presume great spiritual values,'' Groome said. ``The founding
fathers presumed that the educational system would be grounded in
great spiritual values.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the philosophy that permeates public education today,
Groome asserts, promotes a, ``narrow kind of individualism,
consumerism, a deep materialism, and very often a dangerous kind of
selfishness and parochialism.''
</P>
<P>
   What is needed is a more holistic educational philosophy, one
grounded in spiritual values. ``There is still false liberalism
that paralyzes us into believing we cannot impose values on our
children,'' Groome said. ``And that's just baloney. It's
irresponsible and it's disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Jeff Smith, who has achieved national fame as the ``Frugal
Gourmet'' and who is an ordained Methodist minister, has reached a
settlement with several men who accused Smith of sexually
assaulting them as teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the settlement are confidential.
</P>
<P>
   By settling, Smith avoided a civil trial scheduled to begin next
week in Tacoma, Wash. Smith had vowed to fight the allegations,
charging that his accusers were ``bloodsuckers'' and ``crooks''
bent on ruining his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   One of the plaintiffs, George Heitman, said he was unhappy with
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dissatified with the terms of confidentiality of the
agreement,'' he told reporters. ``In fact, I'm kind of dissatified
with the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting as a university chaplain and then a restaurateur in
Tacoma more than 30 years ago, Smith went on to become a national
TV personality and a best-selling author. His ``Frugal Gourmet''
cooking show at one time reached more than 7 million households
through syndication on local public television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasts of his last series of shows were suspended last year
following the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Six men accused Smith of sexually molesting them when they
worked for him at his Tacoma restaurant, the Chaplain's Pantry.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has not been charged with any crimes. It is not clear yet
what the impact of the allegations and the settlement will be on
Smith's television career.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
