<HEADLINE>
WHERE JOURNALISM IS A LIFE-AND-DEATH MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, England -- Like Alka-Setzer after a leaden meal, a
change of scenery can bring blessed relief from even the japeries
of jaded journalists.
</P>
<P>
   After a season of navel-gazing and breast-beating over the
career wrecks of assorted miscreants in US journalism, it was
refreshing to sit in on a panel discussion about journalism that
matters.
</P>
<P>
   There are still life-and-death decisions made by editors and
reporters in many parts of the world, as the toll of slaughtered
journalists attests each year. Less fatal, but no less threatening,
are the subtler pressures meant to remind the truth-teller that
one's job, promotion or longterm economic prospects can be dashed
by an overly-aggressive presentation of unpalatable facts.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian financial crisis has produced a series of challenges
to the journalists of those countries ranging from Indonesia to the
Philippines that were nearly capsized by the Japanese tailspin.
Malaysia, Thailand, South Korea, and the other smaller players have
been rocked.
</P>
<P>
   And at a Reuters Foundation reunion of journalism fellows from
the past 15 years at Oxford University, the tensions of
contemporary journalism were described by editors who get death
threats, intimidating hints from superiors, and heavy-handed
treatment by their governments.
</P>
<P>
   The trivial pursuits of American journalism's infatuation with
the ongoing sitcom cast of Bill-Monica-Linda-Kenneth-Paula-Hillary
were hardly raised. You can't very well horn your way into a
discussion of death threats, career loss and being blamed for a run
on the bank your publisher owns, by raising the weighty issues of
Zippergate.
</P>
<P>
   In too many other countries, they don't shoot the piano player,
they shoot, stab or toss acid in the face of the journalist for
pointing out connections that malefactors of power would prefer
left in the shadows. And I came away from a recent morning's earful
about Asia with the sinking feeling that Asia's economic turmoil is
deeper and more perilous for us than I'd realized.
</P>
<P>
   If what I heard is correct, and it rang with truth for me, then
the extent of rot in the economic timbers of Asia is greater than
we comprehend. In country after country, bureaucrats and bankers
conspire _ sometimes in the belief they are defending national
interests _ to cover up the extent of the weaknesses in their
currencies, banking structures and statistics of real wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Asian journalists are constantly pressured to help the
government save face, by accepting unchallenged some patently
inflated government numbers, or by refusing to print or highlight
rumors of impending bank collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's anemic government offers the worst example of a
bureaucracy that cannot summon the will and nerve to confront its
banking collapse head-on. The successive pronouncements in Tokyo of
this bid to prop up the yen, or that tax cut, or of still another
public works program, do not convince the hard-eyed speculators who
lay in wait to ambush the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's weak political system cannot yet come to grips with the
banks' refusal to come clean about the extent of their
nonperforming loans. And as Aaron Zitner spelled out in Sunday's
Globe, bank-owned stocks have fallen by half over 10 years, as
property values plummeted 70 percent. Rare is the banker who wants
to admit his assets are halved, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's visit to China was a nine on a scale of 10
for a number of reasons, including atmospherics, domestic political
fallout in both countries, and a chance to change the topic from
you-know what. But the extensive and deftly executed state visit by
Clinton and his thousand-or-so camp followers reset
Chinese-American relations on a much more solid _ and much more
necessary _ footing.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's swoon has effectively taken the world's second-largest
economy off the board, at least until the lame Japanese political
system can face the harsh realities. That puts the great Chinese
giant much higher in the economic scheme of things, because 1.2
billion people will drink a lot of Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have stuffed $87 billion in foreign mutual funds to
take advantage of the run-ups that have occurred over the last
decade. But political turmoil (Indonesia, South Korea), oil price
drops, hostile weather for some crops, and the vagaries of the
economic cycle have hammered many Asian investments. Funds
concentrating on Europe went up 28 percent in the last two qarters,
while Chinese funds were down 26 percent, and Latin America's
dropped 18.
</P>
<P>
   The average Pacific-Japanese fund was off 24 percent so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Because their government is cowering in advance of upcoming
local elections, there is not much confidence that the carping of
the US and other powers will hound the Japanese into plugging the
leaks in their banks. So you'd have to guess it will get at least a
little worse before it gets a little better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
