<HEADLINE>
MILITARY DOUBLE STANDARD CHARGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sergeant Major Gene McKinney, once the Army's top
enlisted man, was court-martialed last year for sexual misconduct.
Lieutenant Kelly Flinn, the Air Force's first female B-52 pilot,
was discharged in 1997 for having an affair with a subordinate's
husband. But in the swirl of allegations of sexual offenses by one
of its generals, the Army allowed Major General David R.E. Hale to
resign in February with full honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the old boys protecting the old boys, that's what it
smacks of,'' said Susan Barnes, a Denver lawyer who represented
Sergeant Major Brenda Hoster, one of six women who brought charges
of sexual harassment against McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   A day after disclosure of a scathing report from the Pentagon's
Inspector General finding evidence that Hale behaved improperly or
committed adultery with the wives of four officers under his
command and lied about it, the question for the Pentagon Tuesday
was whether it applies a double standard for punishment based on
rank, race, or gender.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokeman Kenneth Bacon denied the brass played
favorites or gave special treatment to Hale, who was the Army's
deputy inspector general when he retired. Hale has denied the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Double standards are always very tricky, and it's easy to use
the term,'' Bacon said Tuesday. ``When the facts are known here,
people will see that it's not a double standard.''
</P>
<P>
   On orders from Defense Secretary William Cohen, the department's
general counsel is reviewing whether Hale's retirement request was
handled in a ``fair and adequate'' way, Bacon said. He emphasized,
however, that the review will not focus on the role of the Army
chief of staff, General Dennis Reimer, in allowing Hale to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Pentagon, that decision was viewed by some as at
least a mistake and at worst as one more sign that the
male-dominated military still ignores criticism of its often clumsy
handling of sexual misconduct cases and its well-documented culture
of sexual discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``For General Reimer to have let Hale go out the door with his
stars intact looks very suspicious,'' said Elaine Donnelly,
president of the Center for Military Readiness, a Pentagon watchdog
group. ``I disagree that he should not be the focus of an
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Olympia Snowe, Republican of Maine, thinks so, too. She
has summoned Reimer for a meeting to get details of why he allowed
Hale to retire while allegations of misconduct were outstanding and
a Pentagon investigation was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the ``Today'' show in May, Reimer denied as
``absolutely untrue'' accusations that he made ``special promises''
to Hale, and he defended his decision as one ``based upon the facts
available to me at that particular point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the reports the Pentagon was probing, Reimer acknowledged,
was that Hale was being ``stalked'' by Donnamaria Carpino, a
military wife who had filed a criminal complaint against Hale in
January. Carpino charged that Hale had blackmailed her into having
sex by threatening to bring adultery charges against her husband,
an Army colonel under Hale's command at the NATO base in Izmir,
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   According to the inspector general's report, which the Pentagon
released Tuesday after it was circulated on Capitol Hill and
leaked, Hale had a consensual, sexual relationship with Carpino
from March to June 1997, while Hale was married and was the
commanding officer of Carpino's husband. The report said the affair
violated good order and discipline and the military's code of
justice, which prohibits adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the report said, Hale lied about why he had approved
Pentagon-paid travel for Carpino to the United States. The two met
in Boston while Carpino was supposed to be visiting an ailing
mother in Connecticut. Hale, 53, also allegedly lied to
investigators that he was single when he met Carpino. In fact, his
divorce did not become final until the summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which has become the basis for a criminal
investigation by the Army, asserts that Hale romanced and had
``inappropriate relationships'' with wives of subordinate officers
during postings in Hawaii and Turkey. ``Witnesses told us that
(Hale's) actions created a command climate that was `ugly,'
`uncomfortable' and ... `a Peyton Place,''' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Army spokesmen insist Hale could be returned to active duty to
face formal charges and even a court-martial. It's an issue with
the Army because McKinney, who is black, had vigorously argued that
high-level officials similarly charged but part of the military
network had been allowed to retire without penalty, while he was
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney retired with full benefits after being acquitted of 18
counts of misconduct. He was convicted of one count of obstruction
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the civilian world, the military has strict prohibitions
against adultery because it can undermine order and discipline.
Flinn's case drew protests because the female flier seemed unfairly
singled out for punishment. In fact, her fraternization with the
spouse of a subordinate, and her lying about it, made her a prime
candidate for a court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force General Joseph Ralston, on the other hand, was not
punished _ though he lost his bid to be chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff _ when it was revealed that he had a lengthy affair
in the 1980s with a civilian woman.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, the lawyer who represented one of the women who brought
charges against McKinney, said that too often the Pentagon hides
behind a charge of adultery when the more serious issue is military
leaders who abuse power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
