<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-BOSCOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC IRISH PROGRAM INCLUDES COUNTRY'S DYNAMIC PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ The Jesuits founded Boston College in large part to
educate the children of Irish immigrants who fled the famine of 150
years ago, and so it is no surprise that BC has one of the oldest
and best Irish Studies programs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But while many American universities have programs dedicated to
the more traditional disciplines of Irish history and literature,
BC is carving out its own niche by marrying the study of
traditional Ireland with modern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Academics and students have long been fascinated by Ireland's
history and the writings of Swift, Synge, Joyce, Yeats, Beckett,
and a legion of others. But modern Ireland is being defined by its
business acumen as much as its continued ability to produce prose
as compelling as Roddy Doyle's and poetry as timeless as Seamus
Heaney's.
</P>
<P>
   As Ireland has become Europe's most dynamic economy in the
1990s, the skills of Irish business magnates Michael Smurfit and
Tony O'Reilly are as worthy of study as the writing of Edna O'Brien
and John Banville.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Friday agreement in Northern Ireland, meanwhile,
signals that politics is a growth industry on the island. Political
leaders, both established and emerging, want to impart and absorb
lessons on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   If revisionism is all the vogue in Irish history, the Irish
Institute at Boston College is leading the way to revising what it
is to use Ireland as a subject of study in higher education, and to
equip tomorrow's leaders on the island in both the private and
public sector. It is also a way for a university founded on the
backs of Irish immigrants to give something back.
</P>
<P>
   Sean M. Rowland, the Institute's director, explains the change
this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``BC has always been strong in Irish studies, especially history
and literature,'' he said. ``What we've done is take it campus
wide. Our political science department is working with political
parties here. Our education department is working with the Irish
government's Department of Education. Our business studies have all
sorts of links with the corporate sector here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been an interest in Ireland in higher
education. But a sentimental interest is one thing. A
business-rooted interest is entirely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said academia tends to consider itself above politics,
but the Institute has deliberately cultivated strong and high-level
political support from the American, Irish, and British governments
because it sees such support as crucial to its efforts. It gets
funding from those governments, including a $1 million grant from
the US government it has received each of the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary goals are to promote peace and economic
development through education and job creation,'' Rowland said. To
do so, he says, political support at the highest levels is
essential.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute is politically connected. The Irish prime
minister, Bertie Ahern, presided over its official opening last
December at Chestnut Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an academic side to the political links. For
example, Mary O'Rourke, the Irish Cabinet minister in charge of
trade and enterprise, has been lecturing MBA students at BC for the
last decade. O'Rourke, who has held more senior positions in
government than any other Irish woman, is an expert on European
Union affairs, and is a veteran of many a domestic political
battle.
</P>
<P>
   At a Dublin Castle dinner to wrap up a higher education
conference sponsored by the Institute last month, the head table
included the BC president, the Rev. William P. Leahy; Irish
President Mary McAleese; US Ambassador Jean Kennedy Smith; and
Irish Education Minister Micheal Martin.
</P>
<P>
   McAleese, an academic who left her job as law professor and vice
chancellor at Queen's University in Belfast to become the first
native of Northern Ireland to serve as Ireland's head of state,
said the partnerships created by BC with Irish businesses and
government agencies are ``yielding very tangible results in the
numbers of young people equipped with the leadership skills to
carry this island forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economic and cultural renaissance is no accident or
coincidence,'' said McAleese.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said the evolving relationship with Ireland ``goes to the
very roots of Boston College. We'd like to think we're at the
cutting edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said the Institute has been given the room to expand
``because of the commitment of Father Leahy and Frank Campanella,''
BC's executive vice president. Campanella's interest in all things
Irish might not be obvious from his last name, but three of his
grandparents were born in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who splits his time between Boston and his native
Ireland, said corporate support is essential for the Institute's
ability to mount a trans-Atlantic presence. IBM, for example, whose
worldwide education manager is BC grad Sean Rush, helped underwrite
last month's three-day conference in Dublin. The Ireland Funds, the
International Fund for Ireland, and the Irish American Partnership
also lend financial support.
</P>
<P>
   In its previous incarnation as the Center for Irish Management,
the Institute began humbly in 1988 offering a program that brought
20 entrepreneurs from Northern Ireland for three-month internships
in Boston. This year, the Institute administered 21 programs. More
than 250 people from Ireland, north and south, plus hundreds of BC
students, will take part in education, political leadership, and
business management programs put on by the Institute.
</P>
<P>
   As the Irish economy booms, meanwhile, the traffic is no longer
one-way.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s, our biggest worry was how do we get enough visas
for the Irish kids to get into America,'' said Rowland. ``Now we
have all these American kids who want to get in here. It just shows
how much things have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the programs is one aimed at marketing tourism in both
parts of Ireland, which reflects one of Ireland's traditional
economic strengths, and one on corporate child care that highlights
an emerging need in an economy where only recently have large
numbers of both parents or single mothers worked. The child-care
program is aimed not only at those in the private sector who want
to develop child-care businesses but those in the Irish government
who will regulate this emerging industry.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said the Institute is developing closer links with
British institutions. Taking a page from the Good Friday agreement
that created new political machinery to reflect new relationships
between the islands of Ireland and Britain, and within those two
islands, Rowland wants to ``bring young political leaders from
Ireland, Northern Ireland, England, Scotland, and Wales to BC.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to develop some programming to bring Ireland,
Northern Ireland, and the United Kingdom together,'' said Rowland.
``The old, anti-British stuff isn't helpful to anyone anymore. BC
is very much at the fore of forging ahead, of building new
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland believes the ``new'' Irish studies complement the
traditional Irish studies program. He said the Institute draws on
those traditional strengths. Among lecturers at last month's
conference were historian Kevin O'Neill, co-director of BC's Irish
Studies program, and Robert K. O'Neill, director of the John J.
Burns Library at BC, an internationally recognized expert on rare
books and special collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a Kevin O'Neill and a Bob O'Neill opens doors in the
world of higher education,'' said Rowland. ``They are known at
every university in Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the auspices of the Institute, Thomas O'Connor, BC's
professor emeritus of Irish history, is developing a research
project that will identify the migration trends of the Irish
diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   BC obviously sees the old and the new working together. Last
month, it moved the Institute and the traditional Irish Studies
programs into the same mansion house on Hammond Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' says Rowland, ``we're all under the same roof.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
