<HEADER>
A5451 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-VAUGHAN-BOS &LR;      07-08 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VAUGHAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHAN REDISCOVERS JOY IN THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jimmie Vaughan last put out a solo record, he was hurting.
His brother, the blues giant Stevie Ray, had died in a helicopter
accident in 1990, causing Vaughan to retreat from the business.
After a few years, he finally poked his head out to release
``Strange Pleasure,'' an album that paid tribute to Stevie Ray and
was suffused with spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dealing with a lot of things on that album. There was a
lot of emotion,'' says Vaughan. ``But for the new record, it's like
I'm back on the other side of the street. It's bluesier, dirtier,
more raw.''
</P>
<P>
   The new disc, ``Out There,'' is a return to Vaughan basics: the
stinging yet svelte guitar tone, the warmth of a Hammond B3 organ,
and a reliance on blues shuffles that hook you whether you want to
be hooked or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my last record was spiritual, I'm back to being a wino,''
Vaughan says, with a self-deprecating laugh. ``But, you know, it's
so hard to describe music. Thank God, I can play it.''
</P>
<P>
   He plays it adeptly on ``Out There,'' with the dean-of-the-blues
chops that date back to his days with the Fabulous Thunderbirds. He
also wrote the songs _ except for ``Like a King,'' by Nile Rodgers,
and ``Motorhead Baby,'' by one of his idols, Johnny ``Guitar''
Watson. For any bluesman to write most of his songs, however, is
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing a lot better,'' Vaughan, 47, says of his emotional
state. ``I did the tribute record and I thought that was important
for acceptance and closure. Then I said, `OK, I've done this, and
I've got to start a new phase.' I'm really doing my own thing right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   For Vaughan, that means mixing his blues guitar with the more
streamlined sound of a hired vocal group and with the naturalistic
``wood and tubes'' sound of a Hammond B3. He is a purist _ and long
may he feel that way, because it works for him.
</P>
<P>
   He also sings with surprising assurance, since he didn't start
singing lead vocals until he was 40. His debut as a lead singer
came on the album he made with Stevie Ray, ``Family Style,'' which
was released shortly after the helicopter accident.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan, the older of the two, has made great strides as a
vocalist. He was shaky on his last solo disc, but, like Eric
Clapton, he has honed himself into a fine singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting better. It's just from doing it more,'' he says.
``I have a long way to go, but at least when I do sing, it actually
sounds good to me now. I go into my head and say, `What would you
like to hear?' And then the song comes pretty fast, but I can't do
it on command. It has to twirl around in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to sing in a natural way. Some people can sing
amazingly, but I'm more of a feel singer. Hopefully, that's enough
for me to express myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Vaughan shows a malleable voice, using it as an
instrument, rather than an afterthought, in a new love song
``Astral Projection Blues.'' He also shines vocally on the smooth,
Claptonesque soul of ``Lost in You,'' which he co-wrote with New
Orleans legend Dr. John. It has a groove that won't let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people just like blues,'' says Vaughan. ``When
they hear it, they like it.''
</P>
<P>
   They like it when it's done this well. Vaughan has crafted a
stylistic, signature sound, while nodding to his other idols such
as B.B. King and Buddy Guy, both of whom joined him on the epic ``A
Tribute to Stevie Ray Vaughan'' live album in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still listen to those guys,'' Vaughan says of King and Guy.
``What can I tell you? I'm still learning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
