<SLUG> BC-MA-TAXACHUSETTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BAY STATE VOTERS, IT'S NOT A TAXING ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GEETA ANAND  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass. _ If there's one message percolating up from
voters around the state, it is this: They don't think they live in
Taxachusetts any more.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Acting Governor Paul Cellucci and the Legislature debate
tax-cut proposals on Beacon Hill, with Cellucci pouncing on news of
the state's $1 billion surplus to demand an even larger cut this
year, the people of Massachusetts seem far from convinced that the
state should return extra revenues to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, voters say their top priorities are elsewhere _ on
education, mostly, but also on jobs, crime, and health care. They
aren't looking for budget cuts, they're looking for government to
use its extra cash to tackle some longstanding problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'd like to see the tax rate cut a percent. Sure. But I
can't get too excited about that,'' said Ed Kasok, leaning against
his new red sports utility vehicle as he watched his daughter's
softball practice in Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the government could do is help with health insurance,''
said the toy store owner. ``These are things you think about as you
get older _ my town taxes are going to go up, and my health
insurance is going to go up.''
</P>
<P>
   If then-governor William F. Weld lost to US Senator John Kerry
in 1996 because he sounded the wrong mantra of crime, welfare, and
taxes, voters suggest that candidates who make tax cuts the crux of
their campaign messages this year may be following suit.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, polls often show that voters favor tax cuts. And
every candidate running for governor this year has a plan to roll
back the state income tax over time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in conversations with dozens of people in shopping malls and
on street corners around Massachusetts, only one person even raised
the issue of taxes when asked to discuss the state's most pressing
problems. When specifically questioned about a tax cut, many said
they had higher priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Even pollsters are detecting such a sentiment this year. Lou
DiNatale, who oversees the regular University of Massachusetts
poll, says he has run four polls on the budget surplus and found
that a consistent 50 percent favor spending the money on things
like social programs or capital projects, rather than giving it
back to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely this lack of public enthusiasm for lower taxes
that has led the state's leading tax-cut group, Citizens for
Limited Taxation &AMP; Government, to consider closing its doors. For
the first time in two decades the group couldn't gather enough
signatures this year to put a tax-cut question on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't seem to care,'' said Barbara Anderson, the
executive director. ``If they don't care, how can we ask our
membership to organize?''
</P>
<P>
   Where people do talk taxes, it is local property taxes they
mention and fret about. Many people wanted Beacon Hill to spend
more to help pay for local schools, roads, and other services _
which, in turn, could ease the burden on property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to rebuild roads, we need to improve our schools. All
of these are important, and all of them are draining town
budgets,'' said Tom McCrumm, as he delivered maple syrup from his
farm in the tiny western Massachusetts town of Ashfield to a diner
in nearby Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Of Taxes, McCrumm, who has voted Republican in recent years,
offered: ``Oh, I just bite the bullet and pay 'em and hope I get
something out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Batts of Marshfield, shopping at the Natick Mall with
her grandchildren, said she didn't feel like she was paying too
much in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think they're too bad,'' she said. ``The most
important issue is education and those teachers failing the test.
Do you know it was on the Jay Leno show?''
</P>
<P>
   What voters are most concerned about appeared to depend,
generally, on what corner of the state they call home.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs around Boston, where crime has fallen to record
lows and an electric economy has pushed employment to record highs,
almost everyone who was approached demanded that the state focus
more attention on education.
</P>
<P>
   In pockets of western and central Massachusetts, where the
economy has yet to recover from the loss of manufacturing jobs,
residents sought economic incentives to draw industry. In interview
after interview, they complained that Beacon Hill ignores them and
their region's very serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get us some industry. Get us some jobs,'' said Joanne Maloney,
who works the cash register at a liquor store in Pittsfield.
</P>
<P>
   In middle-sized cities, such as Worcester and Springfield,
resident after resident complained that crime remains a stubborn,
demoralizing problem, and ought to be government's top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a real serious drug problem,'' said Bishop Timothy
Baymon of the Praise and Glory Ministries in Springfield, which
recently opened a drug rehabilitation program there. ``I really
believe this election should be about economics in our communities.
We should be talking about economic literacy and crime in western
Massachusetts. Is anyone listening?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scot Lehigh of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
