<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VANMORRISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNRELEASED VAN MORRISON EMERGES FROM THE TWILIGHT ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In late 1974, Van Morrison played the Anaheim Convention Center
in California, one of many shows that year before he retreated for
two years from performing and recording. Besides songs from the
then-recent ``Veedon Fleece'' album, Morrison did a strange number
called ``Twilight Zone.'' He sang in a falsetto voice and finished
the song memorably _ lying on his back on top of a grand piano.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, I never heard the song again, but remembered it
well: ``It's not the Twilight Zone/It's just a party
phone/Honeycomb, honeycomb, honeycomb.'' Then, a couple of years
ago, a friend from England tucked into my hand an old bootleg
audience-made tape from another 1974 Morrison show.
</P>
<P>
   There it was.
</P>
<P>
   That enigmatic, rather haunting love song is one of 30
previously unreleased Van Morrison works, mostly his own
compositions, on a new double-CD set, ``The Philosopher's Stone.''
For anyone, it's good listening, but for many who appreciate the
poet from Northern Ireland as one of the most necessary and gifted
of the pop musicians who came of age in the 1960s, this set is more
than just that.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing these 30 songs recorded from 1971 through 1988 _ remixed
and with quality sound _ is a little like going to a place where
you suspect, but aren't quite sure, you've been before.
</P>
<P>
   Five are alternate versions of _ and in each case improvements
upon _ earlier recordings: ``Wonderful Remark,'' heard first in the
Martin Scorsese movie ``King of Comedy'' and less commercially
treated here; ``Joyous Sound'' from 1977, this a fuller, happier
version; ``Flamingoes Fly''; a more energetic ``Bright Side of the
Road''; and a reggae, ``Real Real Gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The real surprises, however, are two dozen blues, ballads, and
love songs that would have been hailed when they were originally
recorded but, in most cases, just didn't physically fit on the
albums Morrison released annually. Most of them have circulated
among obsessive Morrison fans for years.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Polydor Ltd. even put out a tentative 30-song CD
set, but it was pulled back, and the content of the two discs
tweaked to make it even richer.
</P>
<P>
   Three somewhat monotonous inclusions were eliminated, and three
superior pieces from the enormous Morrison vault were substituted.
One of them is ``The Street Only Knew Your Name,'' a moving 1975
recording that already had the reflective songwriter looking back
nostalgically: ``That was long before fortune and fame/No such
thing as a star when you've played that game.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the favorites of Van collectors are ``Not Supposed to
Break Down,'' an introspective song with lyrics typical of the
searching '60s period; ``Laughing in the Wind,'' with Morrison
joined by Jackie DeShannon; ``Madame Joy,'' an upbeat cousin to the
dark masterpiece ``Madame George,'' from the 1968 album ``Astral
Weeks''; ``Contemplation Rose,'' an urban diary you'd swear could
have been written for ``West Side Story''; and the rocking ``Naked
in the Jungle,'' covered by Morrison's San Francisco-based
singer-daughter, Shana, when she visited Boston last year.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison never hid his contempt for the commercial end of the
record industry, and ``Drumshanbo Hustle'' is an explicit
expression from 1973, early in his career: ``You were puking up
your guts/When you read the standard contract you just signed.''
</P>
<P>
   The musicians Morrison gathers always have been creative
choices, and these _ from sessions ranging from Sausalito, Calif.,
to Hilversum, the Netherlands _ include the late jazz drummer
Connie Kay, from ``Astral Weeks,'' and the always remarkable
pianist Jeff Labes. Morrison himself plays a weepy saxophone on ``I
Have Finally Come to Realize,'' as well as some guitar and
harmonica.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the reworked songs are more assured, less
commercial, somewhat stripped-down _ more in keeping with the
artist's folk or jazz roots. Morrison, like Dylan, has a knack for
turning his songs inside out, reshaping them. Morrison actually
improves his.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Mr. Thomas,'' a tribute to poet Dylan Thomas by Robin
Williamson, is on a level with the many literary paeans Morrison
has written and sung over the years. ``Crazy Jane on God,'' a W.B.
Yeats poem set to music by William Mathieu and sensuously
harmonized by the voices of Ireland's Moving Hearts, could be the
most interesting song of all he's left on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   It was pulled at the last minute from the ``A Sense of Wonder''
album in the 1980s because of objections from the Yeats estate _
and would have helped save that album from mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the assortment that makes up these two CDs, fans clearly
have even more to anticipate. The original studio tapes with
extended versions of the songs on ``Astral Weeks'' are rumored to
survive in a basement somewhere, perhaps even in Boston, where
Morrison lived in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The set released this month, after all, is subtitled: ``The
Unreleased Tapes _ Volume One.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
