<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCAIFE SCHISMS; FEAR OF `CREAMING';   RESILIENT YELLOWSTONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until Hillary Rodham Clinton unveiled her right-wing conspiracy
theory earlier this year, Richard Mellon Scaife was an obscure
Western Pennsylvania newspaper publisher. But in the reflected
glare of ``Monicagate,'' Scaife _ whose foundations have earmarked
hundreds of millions to conservative causes _ has emerged as the
camera--shy sugardaddy of the New Right.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get a handle on Scaife, a semirecluse who eschews
interviews, is a frustrating task at best. (He is best known in
media circles for an obscenity-laced tirade he unleashed at a
reporter for the Columbia Journalism Review.) The latest writer to
take a crack _ and trying a unique tack _ is Joe Conason, in the
July issue of Boston magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Fish Out of Water,'' Conason _ the political editor at the
New York Observer _ portrays Scaife as philosophically out of sync
with his fellow Nantucket summer-home dwellers. One of Scaife's
neighbors is Teresa Heinz, who is married to Senator John Kerry and
the widow of Pennsylvania Senator John Heinz. Both Heinzes were too
liberal for Scaife and his Pittsburgh Tribune-Review paper. Another
Nantucket denizen is Heinz's successor, former Pennsylvania Senator
Harris Wofford, whose Republican opponent was the recipient of
serious Scaife largesse. Then there's Clinton's private snoop,
Terry Lenzner, who lives a few miles from Scaife and for all we
know, may have a fat dossier on the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Conason's approach is clever and readable. But he can't surmount
the same old dilemma. The real Richard Mellon Scaife remains as
elusive as sasquatch. ``Nobody knows him,'' one longtime Nantucket
resident tells Conason. ``I don't think I've ever met him,''
confesses Wofford. ``Scaife is here?'' says a laughing Lenzner. ``I
didn't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next profile of Scaife, I nominate the ``X-Files'' duo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the search for solutions to the education crisis, charter
schools have emerged as the panacea of the moment. Writing in the
July/August issue of the liberal American Prospect, Richard
Rothstein, an adjunct professor of public policy at Occidental
College in Los Angeles, is clearly out to puncture some charter
school myths. ``What we hear about charter schools today is little
more than anecdotal puffery and phony statistics,'' he insists.
</P>
<P>
   The author makes persuasive arguments that it's too early to
accurately measure charter school performance and raises worthy
suspicions about ``creaming,'' the fear that charters will
ultimately attract the cream of the crop and leave the needier
students to the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Where Rothstein's analysis veers from academic to polemic is his
conclusion that charter schools won't ``seriously harm the cause of
public education,'' largely because ``there will be too few
charters to have much of an impact.'' That seems to verge on open
rooting for the failure of this intriguing experiment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever since a buffalo showed up next door to my Yellowstone Lake
cabin a few summers ago, I've been hooked on the Disneyland of
national parks. Now, the August issue of Audubon magazine offers
some reassuring news. A decade after raging wildfires burned for
six months, affected almost 800,000 acres in the 2.2 million acre
park, and ``redistribute(d) biological wealth'' (nice turn of
phrase), the winners outnumber the losers. Owls, bluebirds, and
woodpeckers have thrived. Wildflowers have exploded and the food
chain has been strengthened by increases in insects and algae. The
one big victim has been the park's moose population, which lost a
major food source when the fire burned forests.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up the verdict a decade later, the park's chief
scientist says that ecologically, Yellowstone survived the fires
``as if they were a summer thundershower passing through.`` Now
that's resilience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The news is considerably more ominous in the July issue of
Outside magazine, which examines the impact of this year's Amazon
rainforest fires on the ``world's largest Stone Age tribe,'' the
Yanomami Indians of Brazil. (Remember them from Anthropology 101
class?) While blaming the fires, which destroyed 5,400 square miles
of forest, on ``rampant tree-clearing and homesteading,'' the
article paints a grim portrait of ``a bewildered people in
transition.'' Their home scarred by the fires, the Yanomami
encountered by writer Tad Friend were starving, stunned, and in
social retreat. (The saddest image is of them lugging around empty
two-liter Coke bottles, apparently in the belief that they held
some commercial value.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Yanomami viewed the smoke from the fires as a sign of the
apocalypse,'' Friend writes. It's hard to argue with them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Fire is also a theme, actually more of a metaphor, in David
Grann's New Republic story on Jasper, Texas. That's the town where
Black Panthers and Muslims faced off against the KKK in the days
following the brutal race murder of James Byrd Jr., whose body was
dragged three miles by a pickup truck. (Locals say that raging
fires, clearly some kind of omen, began breaking out right about
the time when Byrd was killed.)
</P>
<P>
   Grann's story is another parable of a media age in which
journalists and outsiders descend on a place in the news and
distort its natural rhythms. As racial tensions mounted, Jasper
residents actually fled their town, hoping to escape the flames of
hate being fanned by strangers in need of a cause and a story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
