<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5483 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-TURNABOUT-2ND &LR;  &UR;      07-08 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TURNABOUT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WASHINGTON: ... enough products.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This ``demand'' problem is often stated another way. Japan has
an ``export-led'' economy that relies more on foreign customers
than on Japanese consumers to make their profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what needs to be done: shift Japan from a producer
economy to one based on domestic demand,'' said Chalmers Johnson,
president of the California-based Japan Policy Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high prices and high profits of so many Japanese
companies, not enough of the wealth is passed to workers, some
economists say. Katz estimates that companies, instead of raising
wages or paying interest and dividends to investors, retain cash
beyond their business needs equal to 3 percent to 4 percent of
Japan's annual gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that money has gone to poor investments, such as excess
factory space and overpriced real estate. Flush with cash, Japanese
companies paid high prices for such US properties as New York's
Rockefeller Center in 1989 and Pebble Beach in California in 1990.
The Rockefeller Center owner wound up in bankruptcy, while the
Pebble Beach owner sold out at a reportedly steep loss.
</P>
<P>
   With businesses failing to pass much of their wealth to workers
and investors, Japanese consumers do not have enough money to buy a
large share of Japanese goods. And the rest of the world can buy
only so much from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government has acknowledged this problem for years.
In 1985, then-Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone charged a high-level
panel with developing a plan to change the country from an export
economy to a consumer economy.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Maekawa Commission for its leader, a former Bank of
Japan governor, the panel proposed cutting back the export-heavy
industries and spurring consumer demand by giving the Japanese more
tax breaks, more vacations, and shorter work weeks. But even the
commission acknowledged, one year after its report, that the
government had not acted on those proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Japan has even exacerbated its demand problem.
The government raised the sales tax last year, a move that crimped
consumer spending even more. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bank debacle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is one other major problem in Japan: the banks. And nobody
knows how bad that problem is.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks, unlike their American counterparts, can buy
stock and count it as part of their assets. Now, the stock market
has dropped by half since its 1989 high, cutting the value of bank
assets. At the same time, property values have fallen by 70
percent, hurting banks that hold loans backed by inflated real
estate values.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, the government of Japan claimed that the banking
system had about $200 billion in nonperforming loans,'' said
Senator Chuck Hagel, Republican of Nebraska, at a recent Senate
hearing. ``Earlier this year, the government increased that
estimate to $600 billion. Private estimates of bad loans range from
$770 billion to as high as $1 trillion, or about one-fifth of total
bank assets. And this does not count the billions more that are off
the books.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter the size, Japan's problem is far larger than the $150
billion in direct costs that the United States spent to clean up
the savings and loan crisis, and they come in an economy just over
half the size of the United States economy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Necessary measures
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Japan is still the world's second-largest economy, with a huge
industrial base, a skilled work force, and many other resources.
Many Western analysts say the nation can revive itself, though the
process will likely raise unemployment and stifle growth for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the measures often suggested:
</P>
<P>
   _End protectionist trade rules so that Japanese industries face
competition and become more efficient;
</P>
<P>
   _Dismantle the cartels, which have been officially abandoned for
a decade but continue in practice, so that poorly run companies
cannot be propped up;
</P>
<P>
   _Cut taxes so that consumers have more money to buy goods, which
might stimulate the economy;
</P>
<P>
   _Change accounting standards, so that the extent of the bad bank
and corporate debts are known;
</P>
<P>
   _End the system by which companies own large chunks of their
business partners, so that the stock market becomes an efficient
vehicle for allocating capital to the best firms rather than a way
to cement business ties; and
</P>
<P>
   _Write off the bad bank debts.
</P>
<P>
   The government has promised to take some of these steps. Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto last week announced a new plan to close
insolvent banks and turn credit-worthy clients over to
government-run ``bridge banks'' that will continue to provide them
capital. The government also proposed a $115 billion tax cut to
spur consumer demand, and has spent $600 billion on public works
over five years to spur the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Many people are reserving judgment until after next month's
parliamentary election. If Japanese leaders do not follow through
on a comprehensive plan by then, currency and stock traders could
batter Japanese markets even harder than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pivotal moment for Asia and the global economy,''
warned Lawrence Summers, the number two US Treasury official, at a
Senate hearing last month. ``The weakness in Japan is now having a
clear impact on the other troubled economies in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are goods reasons for Japan to hesitate: Cleaning
up the economy would force businesses to close and cause huge
layoffs, which are unheard of in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   This contract was Japan's social safety net, the system that
stood between order and panic. Now, some economists say, Japan must
create a new safety net, some kind of equivalent to US
unemployment, Medicaid, and bank-deposit insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have these social safety net devices, it is
impossible to do the reforms they need to do. Which is why they
don't do it,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese leaders may not yet be ready to impose pain on their
country, said Johnson of the Japan Policy Research Institute. ``The
Japanese do not yet feel that the old system has to be abandoned,''
he said. ``They say, `We are like people sitting comfortably in a
hot bath. We know the water is cooling off, but we don't yet feel
the need to get out.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5484 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-RADIO09-COX     07-08 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-RADIO09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RADIO TALKS WITH STUDENTS SCRUBBED FROM GLENN SHUTTLE FLIGHT
 &HT;    280&AMP;add
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A popular education program has been scratched from
the October space shuttle flight of Sen. John Glenn because the
astronauts are booked solid with a vast array of science
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   One school in Japan and five in the United States _ including
John Glenn High School in the senator's home town of New Concord,
Ohio _ were scheduled to connect via amateur radio with the shuttle
Discovery for 10-minute conversations between students and
astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   NASA schedulers decided last week that the process of setting up
and then stowing the radio equipment makes the classroom program
too time-consuming for a mission that already has more than 80
experiments aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time-liners have come to the conclusion that it doesn't
all fit,'' said Doug Ward, head of public information at Johnson
Space Center in Houston. ``That's not one we like to give up, but
it also has a lower priority than the science.''
</P>
<P>
   Now NASA's education division is looking for a replacement
project that will fit the schedule of the nine-day, science-laden
flight that also has great education potential because of its high
public profile with Glenn aboard.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the oldest person in space (he'll be 77 by
launch day), Glenn is returning to space for the first time since
his pioneering flight as the first American to orbit the earth in
1962.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Robertson, who heads the education and information
services division of the Johnson Center, said she's been given a
short window in the astronauts' schedule to fill with an education
project and she said Glenn will be at the center of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 30 minutes open for some kind of education event,''
she said. ``And right now, we don't know what that's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Shuttle Amateur Radio Experiment (SAREX) began in 1983
aboard the ninth shuttle mission and spent its first few years as a
secondary project that astronauts did only in their leisure time.
Although it now is a scheduled shuttle program like any other, it's
not uncommon for a SAREX project to be scotched when a shuttle
schedule gets too full.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we call it an experiment,'' said Rosalie White,
manager of educational activities for the American Radio Relay
League. ``Schools know that when they apply.''
</P>
<P>
   The Radio League, a non-profit organization of amateur radio
operators, has a contract with NASA to manage the SAREX program by
selecting the schools that participate from hundreds that apply.
The league also arranges for radio equipment to be set up in
schools that are chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're looking at applications from schools that
applied in 1996, just to give you an idea of how backed up we
are,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   In the program, students learn about radio waves and space
travel in anticipation of the radio contact. As the shuttle passes
overhead, students ask questions and take answers from the
astronauts. White said schools typically practice the event to get
the most out of their 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Space shuttles are equipped with air-to-ground radios, but the
SAREX program involves adding a separate radio that transmits on a
public frequency. Robertson said it's likely that the official
shuttle radio will be used in the replacement project, which means
it will be transmitted through NASA television.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the SAREX program had gotten the ax apparently hadn't
reached Glenn, who on Tuesday touted it as one of the
``intangible'' benefits of the space program. During debate on the
Senate floor over an amendment to kill the International Space
Station, Glenn's defense of the station included mention of the
radio talks he'd be giving to students while aboard the Discovery
in October.
</P>
<P>
   A staff member for the Ohio Democrat said the senator wouldn't
comment on the loss of SAREX from his mission because he doesn't
want to overstep his role as a regular member of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Since being named to shuttle crew in January, Glenn has taken
pains to point out how ``research-rich'' the flight would be, and
two weeks ago his flight commander, Air Force Lt. Col. Curt Brown,
said in Houston that the flight was so rich in experiments that
NASA schedulers were considering cutting some projects.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a multitude of experiments, the crew also will
use the heavy mechanical arm in the shuttle's cargo bay to deploy
and then retrieve a sun-measuring device called the Spartan. Glenn
himself will be the subject of two experiments in which scientists
are searching for links between the human body's reaction to
extended periods of weightlessness and old age, which cause similar
debilitating effects.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
