<HEADER>
A5485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CARPENTER-BOS &LR;      07-08 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CARPENTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARY-CHAPIN CARPENTER HAS COME OUT TO PLAY, NOT TO PROMOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Touring, for some musicians, is a necessary evil. It's a way to
promote a new album or ``prod-uct,'' a way to keep their record
label happy. So it's refreshing to see artists hit the road when
they're not hyping something. The Grateful Dead often toured
without a new album. And Billy Joel once even played Boston Garden
for the sheer fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, it's Mary-Chapin Carpenter's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to tour,'' she says. ``I didn't have a new
rec-ord out. I just wanted to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, the folk-country star by way of Brown University,
actually took a chance by touring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unfortunate fact that because it's so expensive to
tour, you tend to do it only if you have something new to
promote,'' says Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did she want to alienate the concert promoters who have
supported her. ``The last thing I want to do is blow a promoter's
wad or do bad business. You don't want to be stupid about it,'' she
says. ``But hopefully, the tour we set up is done smart enough so
that no one is gonna lose their shirt and we can still just go out
there and play. And it's been really gratifying, because I haven't
really gotten any airplay to support this tour, but we're still
seeing people come out.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour's success is also due to Carpenter's personality. She's
an effervescent, charismatic performer who not only has a deep
cache of hits (``Passionate Kisses,'' ``Down at the Twist and
Shout,'' and ``Shut Up and Kiss Me''), but can pull out many
crowd-pleasing cover songs, from Van Morrison's ``Real Real Gone''
to Johnny Cash's ``I Still Miss Someone.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the cover song of choice is John Gorka's ``Flying
Horse,'' which opens her show. ``It's a wonderful song about how
the Texaco horse _ you know, the red horse with wings _ decides to
just blow off her job.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Carpenter, 40, is a revered songwriter, she loves doing
other people's songs so much that, like Shawn Colvin and Dwight
Yoakam in recent years, she'd consider releasing an album of
covers. ``I'd love to do that someday,'' she says. ``It would be a
challenge because I'd want to put all my favorite songs on the
album, but it would be excruciating to whittle them down.''
</P>
<P>
   After Carpenter played Harborlights last year, she talked about
taking a long vacation. But she hit the trail again last winter for
a tour of Bosnia sponsored by the United Service Organizations, at
the request of US Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a whirlwind,'' she recalls. ``And it came up very
quickly. It was, like, do you want to go to Bosnia? Do you want to
play for the troops on Christmas Eve? And it was: Yeah, I do. I
just thought it would be a meaningful experience. And I find it
hard to describe how meaningful it was. Just to be there with
people who are doing a really important thing _ and to see all the
(Bosnian) orphans that I met. I had never really experienced
anything that like that before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went by myself and slung my guitar over my shoulder,''
she says. ``I did three gigs in one day, from Italy to Macedonia to
Bosnia. Your head is spinning and you are emotional. But I found it
to be a real gift.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Carpenter also performed an ``Evening at the Pops''
concert at Boston's Symphony Hall, invited by conductor Keith
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the best time,'' she says of the Pops. ``Maestro
Lockhart and everybody were so great and really made you feel at
home. They just said, `Do whatever you want to do and it's going to
be fine.' The only time I had ever played with an orchestra before
was a couple of years ago at the Fourth of July `Down at the Mall'
concert in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear your songs scored for an orchestra, it's like
being in your own movie. It's very cool,'' she adds. ``And it was
really fun to be in Symphony Hall, which is one of the great
buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   As for future recordings, Carpenter doesn't have a studio album
in the works, though she's doing a couple of new songs in her show.
She will likely release a hits-oriented disc this fall, including a
couple of new tracks and a couple of covers. One would be ``Party
Doll,'' a Mick Jagger tune from his ``Primitive Cool'' album.
``I've loved that song for years,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And don't ask her what she thinks of the current Nashville
scene, because she's too busy doing her own thing. ``I don't really
know what's going on,'' she says of Nashville. ``That's not an
abdication, but I'm just out here having fun right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And part of that fun is having Boston-based guitarist Duke
Levine in her band. ``He's a truly amazing player,'' she says. ``He
has a gift for the interiors of songs. And he's very modest. He
turns beet red when you tell him how great he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
