<HEADER>
A5488 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRAWBERRIES-COMEBACK     07-08 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAWBERRIES-COMEBACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBORN STRAWBERRIES GETTING BACK IN THE GROOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out of bankruptcy and under new ownership, the Strawberries
record store chain looks to make a comeback worthy of Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberries ``could do nearly $100 million in sales this
year,'' said chief executive Robert J. Higgins of Trans World
Entertainment Corp., which bought 90 Strawberries stores last fall
for $21 million _ nearly half of what the chain reportedly sold for
a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   With too many stores and too few hit records, the mid-1990s were
a nightmare for many record chains including Strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   But after a burst of intense consolidation, the mood today is
more upbeat. Soundtracks from movies such as ``Titanic'' and ``City
of Angels'' are luring consumers back into stores. And hits from
Garth Brooks and Dave Matthews along with CD singles could help
boost music retail sales by 8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   With many of its stores now remodeled, Strawberries hopes to
cash in on this rebound as part of Trans World's music empire,
which includes such other chains as Coconuts Music &AMP; Movies, Record
Town, and Saturday Matinee.
</P>
<P>
   The Strawberries stores, Higgins said, fit well with his
distribution network, and there was an opportunity for savings by
closing Strawberries' home office in Milford, Mass. and moving many
operations to Trans World's headquarters in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   For Strawberries, a change of ownership is simply another
chapter in a colorful three-decade history.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by the late Morris Levy, who managed the Birdland jazz
club in New York before going on to produce such rock-and-roll hits
as ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?,'' Strawberries was once a dominant
record chain in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   If it was the 1970s, and a local disco lover wanted a copy of
``Saturday Night Fever,'' Strawberries was the place to go.
</P>
<P>
   And in the '80s when many Beatles fans were replacing worn-out
vinyl albums with cassettes or CDs, Strawberries was where many
local music lovers went to buy new copies of old favorites.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, Strawberries operated 160 stores. In 1989, the
chain claimed sales of $75 million. It was about that time that
out-of-state retailers began invading the Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, chains such as Tower Records, HMV, and
Circuit City moved in and, suddenly, everyone from the local Star
Market to the local Kmart was also selling music.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, a chain such as Circuit City would use music as a
loss leader, further squeezing traditional record store chains.
</P>
<P>
   If all this new competition wasn't enough, the music of the
mid-1990s was a disaster. Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish, REM, and Pearl Jam
all released CDs that disappointed retailers.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, this shortage of hits occurred just as
many baby boomers had finished replacing their vinyl record
collections with CDs, something that had driven music sales for
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``1996 was one of the worst years the music business ever had,''
Higgins recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the double whammy of stiff competition and bad music,
Strawberries had issues of its own to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, founder Levy was convicted of racketeering. A
short time later, the new owner of Strawberries, Jose Menendez, and
his wife were found shot to death. Their sons, Lyle and Erik, were
later convicted of the California murders.
</P>
<P>
   Following this turmoil, Strawberries was bought by its
management team through a leveraged buyout.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, though, the entire music business was struggling,
including the industry's biggest player, Musicland Stores Corp.,
the $1.8 billion Minnesota-based company that operates the Sam
Goody chain.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, Strawberries filed for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was rapid consolidation in the $12.2 billion music
industry. Analysts estimate that in about a two-year period, more
than 1,000 record stores closed.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to store closings, Trans World was especially
aggressive. Instead of operating a large number of small stores,
the company believed it would have greater success with a smaller
number of large stores. At the end of fiscal 1994, it operated 684
stores; at the end of 1997, it operated 539 stores.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike some of its rivals, Trans World has managed to become
mean and lean without loading on a lot of debt.
</P>
<P>
   All this consolidation has improved the industry's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overcapacity has been absorbed,'' said analyst Thomas
Tashjian at NationsBanc Montgomery Securities, which recently
helped Trans World underwrite a secondary stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Something else has improved the industry's health and its profit
margins: Record companies have had success in persuading giant
retailers such as Wal-Mart Stores Inc. to stop selling CDs below
cost and using them as loss leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In such an ideal climate, Trans World has been thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business keeps coming in over plan,'' said Tashjian, who
projects Trans World's earnings per share for this fiscal year at
$1.50, up from 99 cents a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Trans World uses two retail formats: one for freestanding stores
such as Strawberries, and another for stores in malls. Part of
Trans World's turnaround strategy has been to negotiate leases that
allow it to be the only record store in a particular mall. Trans
World is also experimenting with a much larger store concept called
``For Your Entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the shortage of hits in the mid-'90s, Trans World has
taken steps to be less dependent on the vagaries of new releases.
To that end, it has signed licensing agreements that allow it to
package its own exclusive CD boxed sets, such as anthologies by
Yanni, Andrew Lloyd Webber, and Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike other music retailers, Trans World does the majority of
its business outside the top 50 category,'' wrote Beth A. Richard,
an analyst for Everen Securities Inc., which also helped underwrite
Trans World's recent stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   All these moves have yielded results. Last year, Trans World
reported sales of $571 million, up from $482 million the previous
year. Profits grew from $7.1 million to $20.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Trans World's share price has also exploded. Less than a year
ago, shares traded at 20. Now, even after a two-for-one stock
split, shares are trading above 40. On Nasdaq Tuesday, Trans World
shares were up 3/4 to close at 43 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Other chains are also enjoying better days. In early 1997,
shares of Musicland traded at under a dollar; now they're near 13.
</P>
<P>
   But challenges lie ahead for the industry and for Strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Some day fans could buy more music on the Internet, and national
chains Target and Best Buy are set to soon open their first stores
in Greater Boston, the latest outsiders to challenge Strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   But after almost 40 years in the business, Higgins doesn't seem
worried. He remembers when the Kingston Trio was popular and when
disco was king. As he scouts other possible acquisitions, he sees
good times ahead for the music business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do over $700 million in sales this year,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
