<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5490 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATINO-URBAN-SCENE-NY     07-08 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-URBAN-SCENE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE WOMAN, TWO CULTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By SILVANA PATERNOSTRO  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   I live in New York City, the capital of English-speaking
culture. But I can go entire days without ever speaking English.
Today was one of those days. This morning, I didn't have exact
change for the bus ride so I went into a Korean deli and asked the
Ecuadorian behind the register for it.
</P>
<P>
   On the bus, coming down Seventh Avenue, I tried reading a few
pages of ``Three Trapped Tigers,'' by the Cuban writer Guillermo
Cabrera Infante. But I was distracted by the stories of a Dominican
