<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-TURNABOUT-2TAKE     07-08 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TURNABOUT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE IN TOKYO 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was a time, only 10 years ago, when Americans
wondered if they would soon lose their claim to living in the
world's largest economy. Japan was growing rich on auto and
electronics exports, and Japanese companies were buying such
trophies as Rockefeller Center, the Pebble Beach golf course, and
CBS Records. As Americans watched the Soviet Union crumble, many
saw a new threat in the economic power of ``Japan Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   But today, in a turnabout few predicted, the business tactics
that made Japan so fearsome have led to its undoing, causing one of
the sharpest economic reversals in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial cartels, clubby lending practices, rules that barred
US firms from reaching Japanese customers _ all this helped build
Japan into one of the world's top makers of autos, computer chips,
and consumer electronics. But as it turns out, the same practices
created a set of bloated, inefficient industries in Japan that are
now largely responsible for rising unemployment, plummeting stock
prices, and a banking crisis that could turn Japan's current
recession into something far worse.
</P>
<P>
   It is a remarkable setback for the nation that inspired Michael
Crichton's 1992 novel ``Rising Sun'' and Pat Chaote's political
study ``Agents of Influence,'' which portrayed Japanese businessmen
as secretly buying their way into American politics and society to
steal US jobs and wealth. Today, Japan is again being cast as an
economic threat. But in a twist worthy of any thriller, Americans
are now frightened of Japan's economic weakness, which might allow
the Asian financial crisis to spread to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What strikes me is how angry, how unalloyed the anger is in
the US toward Japan right now,'' said Richard J. Samuels, who heads
the Japan program at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
``There's this unified front of frustration with the Japanese.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it proves to be a short-term problem or the start of a
major collapse, Japan's downturn holds lessons for the United
States, economists say. They say it shows the need for flexibility
and ``creative destruction'' in an economy, values that Japan has
rejected as a threat to its long tradition of social stability.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some economists say, Japan's story shows that
to survive this kind of economic turbulence, a country must spread
the wealth to workers, or at least extend them a safety net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The supply problem
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Japan is facing two problems at once: a supply problem and a
demand problem.
</P>
<P>
   On the supply side _ the part of the economy that produces goods
and services _ Japan is suffering from an industrial policy suited
for a fast-growing economy, not the mature nation that it has
become. ``It was a marvelous system for catching up to the West,''
said Richard Katz, senior editor of The Oriental Economist Report
and author of a new book, ``Japan: The System That Soured.''
</P>
<P>
   After the second World War, Japan turned itself from a farming
nation into a manufacturing powerhouse by channeling its money into
factories. Its government allowed banks to lend freely to
manufacturers and fostered industrial cartels in which members
assisted one another instead of competing. At the same time, it
protected those cartels with trade rules that kept foreign
competitors out of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, Toyota and Honda autos had become world standards,
and Sony electronics flooded Western markets. By the mid-1980s,
Japanese computer chip makers outsold US rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a good economic model,'' said Gary Hufbauer, research
director at the Council on Foreign Relations in New York. ``But all
this shows that no model lasts forever, or that every model has its
weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   In Japan's case, a key weakness was that the economic system
protected not only world-class exporters but inefficient
industries, including steel, aviation, glass, and cement.
</P>
<P>
   These industries charged inflated prices to their domestic
consumers, and their cartels punished any company that tried to
undercut those prices. For example, Katz writes in the September
issue of The American Prospect magazine, the construction industry
promised not to buy cement from any firm that sold it at prices
below those set by the cement cartel. When one construction firm
bought low-cost Korean cement, Katz writes, the cartel persuaded
Japanese longshoremen not to unload it.
</P>
<P>
   Practices like these allowed Japanese producers to charge their
domestic customers prices 60 percent higher than world prices for
steel, 70 percent more for cement, and 64 percent more for
petrochemicals, Katz writes in the Prospect. They allowed the food
processing industry to survive with one-third the productivity of
US companies.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to Japan's protectionist trade rules, these
industries never faced the foreign competitors who might have
forced them to cut prices or become more efficient, Katz said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toyota, Honda, Sony _ they are not the problem,'' said C. Fred
Bergsten, president of the Institute for International Economics in
Washington. ``The problem is with the 80 percent of companies that
are not global or flexible, that are inefficient and dragging down
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems became worse in recent years as South Korea,
Thailand, and other ``Asian Tiger'' economies developed their own
manufacturing sectors. Faced with new competition and the high
costs that cartels imposed within Japan, some of the best Japanese
companies began shifting production overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``VCRs and refrigerators _ Japan makes more of those outside
Japan than inside Japan,'' Katz said. ``Glass, steel, cement _
that's what's left at home.'' The trend is so significant that the
Japanese have a word for it: ``kudoka,'' or the ``hollowing out''
of the economy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The demand problem
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While many of its manufacturers are in trouble, Japan has also
developed a problem that seems unimaginable in the United States:
Its citizens do not buy enough products.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
