<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUARTER-RUSSIA-BOS &LR;      07-08 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUARTER-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME STILL HAVE FAITH IN RUSSIAN MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A once-popular Soviet song about prerevolutionary Russia
describes a servant's response to the mistress of the mansion when
she calls home one night. The stable has caught fire. In fact, the
entire estate has burned. The aristocrat's husband has died. And
the peasants have revolted.
</P>
<P>
   But not to worry, the servant reassures her _ &UR;  &LR; everything else
is fine.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the song could just as easily be about Russia's
stock market, in shambles after two years of heady gains.
</P>
<P>
   Among those reciting a litany of disasters but still insisting
things will turn out all right are the managers of the Lexington
Troika Dialog Russia fund, the worst-performing equity mutual fund
in the quarter ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The $50 million fund, which invests solely in Russian stocks, is
not for the faint of heart: It lost 55 percent of its value in the
second quarter and 60 percent in the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several very real and severe problems going on in
Russia right now,'' said Richard Hiser, one of the fund's managers,
from Saddle Brook, N.J., headquarters of Lexington Management, the
fund's adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's stock market _ only last year the world's
best-performing emerging market for the second year in a row _ has
collapsed in the wake of &UR;  &LR; the Asian economic turmoil that has
infected Russian debt markets, where Korean banks were players. The
reformist government is broke. Tax evasion is rampant. Hard
currency and gold reserves are dwindling. The communist-dominated
parliament is dragging its feet on tax reform.
</P>
<P>
   But everything else is fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of progress has been made,'' Hiser said, citing ersatz
blue-chip enterprises, newly privatized, that are becoming more
responsive to shareholder concerns and Kremlin anticrisis measures
aimed at reviving the ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, huge uncertainty remains for Lexington Troika Dialog
Russia, which last year was among the world's highest-returning
mutual funds but has since seen steep redemptions.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow is now begging the International Monetary Fund for a
supplement to its $10 billion bailout. There are signs that Russia
may be forced to devalue the national currency, the ruble _ a move
that would spark inflation and social and political unrest as well
as slash equity values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors as a whole have not found Russia to their liking
yet,'' conceded Gavin N. Rankin, Lexington Troika Dialog Russia's
lead manager, from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The open-end fund, one of a handful invested solely in Russia,
treated investors to a 67.4 percent return in 1997. Most of the
gains came last summer, when economists mistakenly predicted Russia
would undergo its first growth in productivity since the 1991
collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's stock market, barely four years old, soared 97.7
percent in 1997 after rising 141.8 percent in 1996, both in dollar
terms. Since then, the outlook for this wild emerging market, now
in decline for nine straight months, has soured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next six months are make or break,'' said John Paul Smith,
a Russia equity strategist at Morgan Stanley International in
London. ``It all depends on whether or not they devalue.'' He said
Russia's stock market could take at least two years to recover from
a currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   About one-quarter of Lexington Troika Dialog Russia's holdings
are in Russia's oil and gas sectors, which have been hit hard by
low world energy prices. Shares in utilities and telecommunications
firms account for the fund's next biggest &UR;  &LR; holdings, at 19 percent
each. With a total of 40 stocks, the fund also hold shares in
breweries, retailers, and autoworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valuations have become extremely attractive, but there's a
great deal of short-term volatility,'' Hiser said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has 22 percent of its holdings in cash _ a sign that
its managers do not view stocks as the best place for investors'
money.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has some potentially world-class companies, with oil
giant LUKoil, &UR;  &LR; gas behemoth Gazprom, and national utility Unified
Energy Systems among investors' favorites. The country is endowed
with huge untapped energy and metals reserves, and, in some cases,
major Russian companies have lucrative alliances with Western
partners.
</P>
<P>
   But eight years after Russia jettisoned its planned economy,
privatized enterprises have done little to remake themselves.
Productivity has fallen and companies are mired in a vicious cycle
of nonpayments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; John F. Cogan, president of Pioneer Group Inc., a Boston-based
asset management firm with Russia operations, recently described
Russia as ``a country with 14,000 failed IPOs,'' or initial public
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   But high-risk spills as well as high returns are the hallmarks
of most emerging market funds.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rankin: ``Russia is used to taking its knocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
