<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS &LR;      07-08 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER HUGE GAINS, BLUE CHIPS DISAPPOINT INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking safety in the stock market's high but choppy waters,
most investors set their moorings last quarter in the biggest
mutual funds with the largest blue-chip companies.
</P>
<P>
   But they found little solace in their chosen haven.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds invested in US stocks lost an average 0.3 percent
in the three months ended &UR;  &LR; June 30, slipping into the red after
giant gains of 12 percent in the first quarter. Among general
equity funds, only those with the biggest household-name stocks
made any significant money _ and those gains were far below those
of earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three months of 1998, an investor could not lose
money in most US equity funds, as the market crested to new highs.
In the second quarter he could barely make any, as Wall Street,
more conscious of earnings warnings amid worries about Asia,
joltily slowed down. It was the third time in the past six quarters
that the average stock fund lost money, and a strong sign that the
double-digit gains of previous quarters simply cannot be sustained
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few exceptions. Mutual funds that invest solely in
technology stocks staged a rally at the end of June to gain 3.3
percent in the second quarter, becoming the best performing of the
so-called sector funds, which invest in a particular industry,
according to Lipper Analytical Services, the New York fund tracking
firm.
</P>
<P>
   But in a major shift from the recent past, when US stocks
dominated headlines, the best action was not even stateside.
European stock funds, buoyed by Europe's economic and financial
transformation, rose 6.3 percent, more than any other kind of fund.
Nine out of the 25 top-returning funds were invested in Europe,
with Belgian and German stocks doing especially well. Funds
invested in international small companies also gained, rising 3.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Funds invested in Asia and natural resources continued to
perform abysmally, with gold funds down 16 percent, China funds
losing 28.3 percent, and those invested in Asia but not in Japan
dropping 26.9 percent. Lexington Troika Dialog Russia, a Russia
fund that was once a highflier, was the worst performer of the last
quarter, losing 55 percent on Moscow's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the second-quarter slowdown, US stock funds are still up
a very strong 11.8 percent so far this year. That is a typical
year's total gains, and some analysts think the US market may yet
pull off an unprecedented fourth straight year of returns over 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Individual and institutional investors in mutual funds have done
much to fuel Wall Street's huge rise this decade. The investing
revolution that began in earnest in the mid-1980s has transformed
the way Americans plan for their futures, with funds replacing
savings accounts and insurance policies as the favored investment
vehicle. At just $135 billion in 1980 and $1 trillion in 1990, the
total assets in mutual funds of all types has mushroomed to more
than $5 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   But many investors appear to have unrealistic expectations of
what they will earn.
</P>
<P>
   And the newly intensified focus on size may have reshaped the US
bull market into a beast that is trying to run on one leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market got narrower,'' said James M. Weiss, deputy chief
investment officer at State Street Research &AMP; Management Co.
``There was a focusing of the market onto very large companies. The
theme was `very few, very large.'''
</P>
<P>
   With their market dominance and traditionally stronger earnings
growth, large companies are historically more insulated from
economic downturns. Eager to own the outsize ``Steady Eddy'' stocks
that can better weather the effects of Asian or interest rate
turmoil, investors retreated to funds tracking the big-name
well-established companies, such as General Electric and Coca-Cola,
that make up the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 &UR;  &LR; stock index.
</P>
<P>
   While the S&AMP;P 500 gained only 3.3 percent last quarter, after
13.5 percent in the first quarter, it is still in record territory.
But the percentage of S&AMP;P 500 companies that outperformed the index
dropped to 36 _ one of the lowest rates in 10 years, and a sign
that only a small number of the biggest companies are generating
Wall Street's returns.
</P>
<P>
   Swelled by new investments, funds that track the S&AMP;P 500 gained
3.2 percent in the just-ended quarter, and were the period's best
performing general equity funds. Such funds slightly underperformed
the index when their managers could not invest a flood of new cash
fast enough, thus missing some of the S&AMP;P's upturns late last
month. Index funds are able to attract more new money than funds
that actively pick stocks because they charge lower fees for
passively tracking a benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, given the focus on size, growth funds invested
in large companies with the potential to increase earnings also
nudged up, gaining 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 19 of the nation's 25 largest mutual funds _ all of
which invest mostly in large companies _ rose last quarter, with
American Century 20th Ultra fund &UR;  &LR; leading the pack with gains of
6.1 percent. And it was a good quarter for Boston's Fidelity
Investments, the nation's largest fund company, whose Magellan, the
country's biggest fund, rose 3.4 percent. Fidelity's Contrafund
returned 4.5 percent, while its Blue Chip Growth increased 4.2
percent. Bringing up the rear of the largest funds was Vanguard
Windsor, which lost 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, investors' predilection for large-company stocks locked
funds invested in smaller companies out of the action. After gains
earlier this year, most small-cap and mid-cap funds lost money.
</P>
<P>
   But the US market still hands some good stockpicker gains, even
if they are invested against the fashion. The best-performing fund
last quarter was the IAI Value fund, which gained 24.8 percent; the
tiny fund, closed to new investors in May, seeks out undervalued
stocks in smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some observers see danger behind the mutual fund
industry's intensified gravitation toward a narrow group of
large-company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a phenomenon you begin to see at the beginning of
every economic slowdown,'' said Michael Stolper, publisher of the
Mutual Fund Monthly newsletter in San Diego, describing the flight
to quality and safety and away from the small and midsize companies
that are more open to downswings in fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these blue chips are selling at price-earnings
multiples that defy history,'' said Lawrence Wachtel, a market
analyst at Prudential Securities. ``Valuations are at record highs.
But you could have made this argument for the past year and a half
and you would have been locked out of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   In another portent that Wall Street may be preparing to head
south, bond funds _ until recently the staid, fail-safe cousin to
more glamorous, high-flying stock funds _ did well last quarter,
rising 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are other signs that the domestic stock market may return
to the more moderate 12 percent annual gains returns that are the
historical norm. Many companies have revised downward their
forecasts for quarterly earnings growth. But they are still 2
percentage points above the 4 percent range that many economists
think is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Narrowly focused markets, for whatever reasons, tend to
eventually have to broaden out and take a correction at some
point,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Japan. Severe troubles with the Asian country's
battered economy risk spilling over to China, causing currency
devaluations and further regional weakness _ a process that would
jolt US companies that sell into Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, US fund investors &UR;  &LR; will stay put through a
downturn. Much of the new money has gone into long-term retirement
plans, such as 401(k)s, and investors are not likely to trash their
retirement savings by panicking and yanking out cash in the short
term.
</P>
<P>
   But most economists and analysts think the recently ended
quarter provided a preview of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going ahead, you're going to have a mixed market,'' said John
W. Ballen, chief equity officer at Massachusetts Financial
Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock picking and selecting (vs. tracking indexes) is going to
be more important,'' he said. ``I would think that in the more
normal return environment that we're heading into, those S&AMP;P gains
will reverse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
