<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5502 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESTATE-TAXES-HNS &LR;      07-08 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTATE TAXES NOW PINCH MORE THAN JUST THE RICH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Once thought to be a problem only for the rich,
estate taxes are now challenging middle Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Work for a few decades, pay off a mortgage, buy some life
insurance and invest your savings, and boom, you could have a more
sizable estate than you had ever imagined.
</P>
<P>
   It's startling for clients to realize that ``maybe estate taxes
do reach down to people other than the Kennedys,'' said financial
planner Jeffrey Sullivan, who works on estate plans for clients of
the Albany law firm Burke &AMP; Casserly.
</P>
<P>
   Having a decent job, a retirement plan that performed well in
the stock market and a paid-off house puts many people in line for
estate planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're definitely in the middle of middle-income America,''
agreed Stewart Welch III, author of the forthcoming ``J.K. Lasser's
Estate Planning for Baby Boomers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People of my generation are accumulating a fair amount of
wealth in their own right, as well as the amount of wealth they
will inherit from their parents,'' Welch, 47, said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why consumers are seeing so many seminars from financial
consultants and lawyers on ways to protect the value of estates,
and why politicians at both state and federal levels have created
more protection from estate taxes for middle-income consumers and
their heirs, Welch said. Estate taxes generally have to be filed
and paid within six to nine months after a person's death, Sullivan
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the federal government that imposes a tax burden.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, current state law exempts from taxes estates of up
to $115,000, plus up to $250,000 value in a principal home.
(Separate credits apply to businesses.) But changes that will give
new relief on estate taxes go into effect later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The first step will come in October when estates of up to
$300,000 will be exempt from New York estate tax, and taxes will be
cut even further after Feb. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The new changes will eliminate state taxes for about 85 percent
of estates that would have been taxed previously, and cut taxes for
many of the rest, according to the state Department of Taxation and
Finance.
</P>
<P>
   New York estate taxes range from 2 percent to 21 percent,
depending on the size of the estate.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, federal estate taxes range from 18 percent to 55
percent and can create the major financial burden on an estate,
Sullivan said. Heirs often have to sell an asset to satisfy the
taxes, and it's common for estates to be taxed at 35 percent to 40
percent, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law now exempts $625,000 from estate tax, and the amount
exempted gradually increases to $1 million in the year 2006. But
some people are seeing their net worth grow at such a fast pace
that they may have a tax burden even under the new rules, Sullivan
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, careful planning is more important than ever, and
consumers should consider options such as giving some assets to
their heirs while they are still alive or creating trusts, Sullivan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Every case is individual and complex, yet planning can be
worthwhile for people whose estates might be taxed by 35 percent to
40 percent, and who realize ``for every dollar I can protect, I'm
saving my heirs 35 to 40 cents. That's a staggering amount,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
