<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   FLAG _ WASHINGTON _ As a constitutional amendment to allow
Congress to outlaw flag descretation nears a showdown in the
Senate, witnesses ranging from former Dodger manager Tommy Lasorda
to former Dukes of Hazzard star John Schneider to a disabled Green
Beret veteran testified Tuesday on the emotional issue at a hearing
of the Senate Judiciary Committee. With the popular amendment
already overwhelmingly approved by the House and 49 state
legislatures demanding a chance to vote on it, the decision will
likely come down to whether opponents can muster a one-third
minority to block it. (Dart, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES _ WASHINGTON _ Francis Renee Mullin, the oldest
daughter of James Byrd, victim of a racial killing in Jasper,
Texas, broke down at an emotional news conference Wednesday as she
urged passage of a bill to enhance federal enforcement of hate
crimes. Mullin and others, including representative of ethnic and
homosexual groups, testified later at a Senate Judicary Committee
hearing. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HDTV _ WASHINGTON _ The first high-definition television
broadcasts are just months away, but a number of difficult issues
remain unresolved for consumers, broadcasters, cable companies and
content providers, a Senate hearing was told Wednesday. (Glass, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-RADIO _ WASHINGTON _ A popular education program has
been scratched from the October space shuttle flight of Sen. John
Glenn because the astronauts are booked solid with a vast array of
science experiments. One school in Japan and five in the United
States _ including John Glenn High School in in the senator's home
town of New Concord, Ohio _ were scheduled to connect via amateur
radio with the shuttle Discovery for 10-minute conversations
between students and astronauts. But NASA schedulers decided last
week that the process of setting up and then stowing the radio
equipment makes the classroom program too time-consuming for a
mission that already has more than 80 experiments aboard.
(Montgomery, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-WAR _ WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton launches a $2
billion public relations offensive against illegal drugs Thursday,
new government studies are pointing to mismanagement and stalemate
on other fronts in the war against drugs. In recent weeks, the
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress, has
issued reports showing a disjointed effort by 20 separate federal
agencies to gather intelligence on illicit drugs, a failure to stop
smuggling at the Mexican border, and widespread drug-related
corruptions in major cities. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRIP _ Advance on President Clinton's visit to Atlanta
Thursday to attend youth anti-drug rally and luncheon fundraiser
for the Democratic U.S. Senate candidate Michael Coles. More
details on itinerarly.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Why Bill Clinton is spending so much time on the
road. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CNN-ARNETT _ Ferreting out status of Peter Arnett following his
additional meetings with CNN CEO Tom Johnson over the news
network's Tailwind story retraction. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-ANIMALS _ BUNNELL, Fla. _ The trauma isn't over for the
pets, livestock and wild animals routed by Florida fires. Some are
still out in the smoking woods, cut off from their homes, hiding in
culverts, drainage ditches, under cars or in garbage cans,
disoriented and traumatized. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TX-INSTITUTIONS _ AUSTIN _ In the past three weeks, three Texas
institutions have had their federal money frozen because of serious
health and safety problems. The three sanctions may signal growing
trouble with Texas' ability to keep free from harm the 5,300
mentally retarded people living in state institutions. (Gamino,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
