<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5524 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGE-DISCRIMINATION-HN     07-08 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGE-DISCRIMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES PRESSURE CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR ON AGE-BIAS BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Pete Wilson must choose between
protecting middle-aged workers and helping California's corporate
interests in a bill that would significantly strengthen
anti-discrimination laws for workers older than 40.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups are pressuring Wilson to veto the bill, which
would prevent companies from firing older workers just to profit
from hiring younger, lower-paid employees. The measure also would
put age in the same protected class as race, religion, ancestry and
gender within the state's Labor Code.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Sen. Quentin Kopp, an Independent, the bill is
supported by every lobbying group for senior citizens. Members of
those powerful political forces, including the California Congress
of Seniors and the American Association of Retired Persons, have
sent scores of letters to the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the most significant anti-discrimination bills to
reach Wilson, who turns 65 next month. He has until Monday to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp's measure comes as the nation's work force is growing
older, and the number of age-discrimination lawsuits is increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a court weakened California's 35-year-old age
discrimination when it ruled that companies had a free-market right
to fire employees if they were paid too much.
</P>
<P>
   Age discrimination laws generally apply to workers over 40.
Lawyers who specialize in age discrimination say they are noticing
a younger class of workers being fired and replaced with even
younger and less-expensive employees, despite the seemingly robust
economy and an ample supply of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, half of the working population in California is
expected to be over 40. The number of age discrimination complaints
filed with the California Department of Fair Employment and Housing
rose from 2,705 in 1992 to 3,297 last year. About 15,000 claims
were filed in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to see an increase in business,'' said Mark
Rudy, a San Francisco lawyer who specializes in age discrimination
cases. ``Maybe this is a prelude to some kind of recessionary
cycle, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean more people are successfully suing their
former bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate interests in California received a boost last summer
when a state Court of Appeal said they could choose workers ``even
though this may result in choosing younger employees.'' The ruling
allowed juries to be instructed that ``if the choice is based on
salary, there is no age discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted many attorneys to recommend against suing
companies for age discrimination. Instead, workers are advised to
take whatever bailout package or severance pay is offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That instruction to a jury is a killer,'' said Kopp, who
recently advised a group of airline employees against suing for age
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it put a stranglehold on a lot of the age claims that
had been brought and were pending,'' Rudy said. ``It gives
employers broad discretion in relying on cost in deciding who to
let go and who to keep.''
</P>
<P>
   A divided state Supreme Court let the jury instructions and
ruling stand. That's when Kopp and two other lawmakers proposed
three bills to rewrite the law. Kopp's bill, which was approved by
the Legislature mostly with Democratic support, is the first to
reach Wilson, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The California Manufacturers Association and the California
Chamber of Commerce contend that just because someone with a high
salary is fired doesn't mean the firing occurred because of age.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kopp's bill, a business owner would have to prove they
fired an employee out of a ``business necessity,'' not just to make
a profit. In addition, a worker would no longer have to prove
intentional discrimination, only that a framework allowed
discrimination to exist at the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it removes the ability of employers to make basic
decisions as to the cost of running their businesses,'' said Fred
L. Main, a lobbyist for the Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
