<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5576 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOLESTER-SUICIDE-HNS &LR;      07-08 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLESTER-SUICIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CON KILLS HIMSELF AFTER SEX-OFFENDER NOTIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for MOLESTER.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Michael Allen Patton's young adult years
were characterized by violent sexual perversity, but those who knew
him say he had lived a straight-arrow life since his parole three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was here every day. He was a very steady, consistent
worker,'' said his boss, Craig Miller, president of Kresky Signs
Inc. of Petaluma, where Patton worked as a large-format silk-screen
printer.
</P>
<P>
   No matter.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently depressed by being identified in a notice distributed
to his neighbors as a high-risk sexual predator, Patton hanged
himself Sunday in a redwood grove on Santa Rosa Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The ``community alert'' flier, which included a color photo of
the 5-foot-5-inch, 220-pound Patton and a list of the crimes of
which he had been convicted _ forcible rape, assault to commit
rape, sodomy and forced oral copulation with children under 14 _
was distributed June 30 to all homes within two blocks of the
College Avenue apartment where he lived.
</P>
<P>
   Under Megan's Law, named after a New Jersey girl murdered in
1994 by a paroled sex offender who lived in her neighborhood, the
police are allowed to notify neighbors about convicted sex
offenders living nearby if they believe the offenders pose a danger
to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea he was under stress,'' Miller said of Patton.
``We were as shocked as anybody'' to learn of the suicide.
</P>
<P>
   An acquaintance who lived in Patton's apartment house, who
flashed a Chicago police badge but declined to give his name, said,
``They should turn the page. They do that for auto thieves and
murderers.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors interviewed for this story said they were surprised to
receive the flier, but did not object to the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any idea,'' said next-door neighbor Kendra
Levitin.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Rosa police took an antiseptic view of Patton's death.
The department was simply following state law on neighborhood
notification, said Sgt. Ernesto Olivares. He said that Patton had
not seemed upset when informed of the planned distribution last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But a neighbor who had known Patton for about three years said
the notices had bothered Patton a great deal. When the notices
arrived, ``I could see the social pressure stressing him,'' said
the neighbor, who declined to give his name. ``It was a knife
through the heart. ... He said, `I just can't get away from it. I
did my time, but society still has the ability to crush you.' He
just felt he couldn't get away from underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Rosa police, using eight officers and an equal number
of volunteers, distributed community alert fliers about six such
offenders, including Patton.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma County Deputy Coroner Steve Rapp said Patton had not
mentioned the flier or its effect on him in the suicide note he had
left for his family.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patton had been out of Atascadero State Hospital for the
Criminally Insane for less than a year when he kidnapped and raped
a 17-year-old Rohnert Park high school girl in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1982, Patton pleaded guilty to charges of rape, oral
copulation, sodomy and kidnapping and was sentenced to 25 years in
prison in prison.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in six years that Patton had committed a
violent sex offense. He had been sent to Atascadero as a mentally
disordered sex offender in 1977 for the kidnap-rape of a
23-year-old female hitchhiker.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Patton had been placed on probation and given a 90-day
sentence for kidnapping four female hitchhikers, ages 14 to 16, and
trying to molest them.
</P>
<P>
   Patton would have completed his parole in a little more than one
week, when he committed suicide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
