   &UR; TINA BROWN RESIGNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times plans a package of stories on the resignation of
Tina Brown as editor of The New Yorker:
</P>
<P>
   BROWN-RESIGN (New York) _ A ledeall on the resignation and what
we know of its circumstances. She is leaving to go to develop a new
magazine for Walt Disney's Miramax. By Geraldine Fabrikant and
Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   In addition we are considering other angles to the story,
including a look at the changing relationship between Hollywood and
the magazine industry and a focus on the New Yorkere and S.I.
Newhouse, chairman of Advance, which owns Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other financial &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-BRITISH-AIRWAYS (Undated) _ American Airlines and
British Airways must give up 267 weekly takeoff and landing slots
at London airports, enough for 15 daily roundtrip flights, and
reduce flight frequencies to three American cities before they may
proceed with their planned alliance, the European Commission says.
By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-BREAST-IMPLANTS (Undated) _ Dow Corning and negotiators for
women with silicone breast implants have tentatively agreed to a
$3.2 billion bankruptcy-reorganization plan for the company that
would compensate thousands of women and bring to a close most of
the bitterly contested litigation that has spanned nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Detroit) _ Developments in the GM-UAW talks. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-STOCKS (Undated) _ Looking at the latest runup in
Internet stocks, including Yahoo, which will post after the close.
By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-AIRPORT (Hong Kong) _ The troubles at Hong Kong's new
airport continue, affecting both cargo and passengers. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was up 38 points at midday. By David Barboza.
</P>
