<HEADER>
A5642 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERB-KAFFIRLIME-TEX     07-08 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERB-KAFFIRLIME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAGRANT, CITRUSY LEAVES GO WELL IN CURRIES AND SOUPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: Kaffir lime is called ``makrut, makrood, bai makrut'' or
``bai makroot'' in Thailand, where it is prized for its fragrant,
citrusy leaves as well as for its fruit. It can reach 8 to 10 feet
in height.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Must be overwintered indoors, so container
planting is a good idea. Use rich, well-draining soil. Add bone
meal. Stake if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Curries, soups such as lemony hot-and-sour shrimp
soup.
</P>
<P>
   Caveats: Beware the 1 1/4-inch-long thorns.
</P>
<P>
   STIR-FRIED PORK WITH RED CURRY PASTE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2 to 4
</P>
<P>
   13 ounces lean diced pork
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon purchased or homemade red curry paste; for
purchased paste, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 kaffir lime leaves, finely shredded, see Note, OR 1 teaspoon
grated lime zest, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 small zucchini, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fish sauce, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon rich chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons shredded fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   Remove any fat from pork. Heat oil in wok or large frying pan,
add pork and stir-fry until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Add curry paste, lime leaves, zucchini, fish sauce and stock.
Stir-fry until pork is just cooked through. Stir in basil and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Red curry paste
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped lemon grass, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   8 red chiles, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons galangal powder, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon shrimp paste, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in food processor and grind to a paste.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 3/4 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Available at Asian groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 298 calories, 21 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, 24 grams protein, 83 milligrams cholesterol,
102 milligrams sodium, 62 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Taste of Indochina/ by Jan Castorina and Dimitra Stais
(Barron's, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BEANS IN COCONUT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds green beans
</P>
<P>
   1 fresh long, hot red chile
</P>
<P>
   1 fresh long, hot green chile
</P>
<P>
   1 scallion
</P>
<P>
   1 stick fresh lemon grass OR 1/2 teaspoon powdered lemon grass,
see Note, OR 2 teaspoons grated lemon rind
</P>
<P>
   6 shallots OR 2 medium-size onions, peeled and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2-inch piece fresh ginger, peeled and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh or dried kaffir lime leaves, see Note, OR 2 strips lime
or lemon rind
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned coconut milk, see Note, stirred thoroughly and
combined with 1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Keeping each ingredient separate, cut green beans, red and green
chiles and scallion into 1 1/2-inch lengths, preferably at a slight
diagonal.
</P>
<P>
   Discard top part of lemon grass, leaving approximately 6 inches.
Crush bulbous bottom lightly with a heavy object. Cut the stick
into 2 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Put shallots and ginger into container of an electric blender
with approximately 2 tablespoons water. Blend to a paste.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large, nonstick frying pan over medium-high heat.
Add paste, lemon grass and lime leaves. (If using powdered lemon
grass or lemon rind, add it later, with the green beans.) Stir and
fry for about 5 minutes, or until paste is lightly browned. Add
chiles and scallion. Fry for another minute, stirring. Add green
beans, coconut milk and salt. Mix and bring to a simmer. Cover and
cook gently about 20 minutes, or until beans are tender.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Available at Asian groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 224 calories, 20 grams fat, 12
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 0 milligrams cholesterol, 509
milligrams sodium, 79 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Madhur Jaffrey's a Taste of the Far East'' by Madhur Jaffrey
(Carol Southern Books, $35)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
