<HEADER>
A5675 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURREALGOURMET-TEX     07-08 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURREALGOURMET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET `PRETEND CHEF' BOB _ HE'S THE SURREAL THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that many members of Generation X are past the slacker phase
and are living life rather than searching for its meaning, they
need a domestic role model, someone they can relate to more than
Martha Stewart or Julia Child.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Bob Blumer, aka The Surreal Gourmet. His sense of
domesticity _ and fabulous hair _ ought to suit
almost-thirtysomethings. The basic life philosophy: Work,
experiment, play and stay healthy. And that goes double for food.
</P>
<P>
   An artist at heart _ his pieces use such bizarre juxtapositions
as a head of broccoli in chef's attire or an ear of corn on the
grille of a Buick (grilled corn, get it?) _ Blumer is also a
cookbook author who came to the field indirectly. In between
bartending jobs and managing musical artists such as ethereal
Canadian singer Jane Siberry, Blumer dabbled with food.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't learn entirely by watching cooking shows or rummaging
through cookbooks, but by mix-matching ingredients and developing
ideas according to whatever struck his fancy. His first mission: to
perfect the Caesar salad. ``It's really not a complicated thing,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Caesar, new ideas emerged: cream of broccoli soup with
white wine, shrimp sauteed with fennel and Pernod, salmon grilled
between romaine lettuce leaves. He even simmered whole cloves,
cinnamon sticks, anise, orange slices and honey with a cup of
orange juice, a cup of Calvados or Southern Comfort and two bottles
of cabernet sauvignon to make a nice, hot comfort drink.
</P>
<P>
   With all those ideas running through his head, there was only
one logical thing for him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, I just decided to write a book,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``The Surreal Gourmet: Real Food for Pretend
Chefs,'' (Chronicle Books, $14.95), and it's not your
run-of-the-mill church-ladies cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think of it as more than just a cookbook,'' he said.
``I like to think of it as a guide to better living.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Blumer explores ideas other than how to make easy
meals that are aesthetically pleasing. He explains how to stock
your kitchen with the essential utensils and spices (fresh ginger
root and garlic are ``Reasons to Live'') and how to make your
kitchen environmentally friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Since his first book, he has made occasional guest appearances
on the Food Network and various TV shows, and he continues to do
his art. He created 18 surreal martini glasses for an auction
benefit for the Salvador Dali Museum's endowment fund.
</P>
<P>
   His second book, ``The Surreal Gourmet Entertains: High-Fun,
Low-Stress Dinner Parties for 6-12,'' was published in '95, and he
is working on a third. ``Champagne Tastes on a Spaghetti-O Budget:
How to Get a Lot Out of Life, Regardless of What Your Lot in Life
Is,'' is tentatively scheduled for fall 1999.
</P>
<P>
   To Blumer, dining is more than just food, so he covers such
aspects as playing mood-setting music when cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyle Lovett has a lot of good food songs,'' he said,
explaining why the Texas singer-songwriter is one of his favorite
artists. That can also be assumed from Blumer's hair, a cross
between that of Lovett and The Cure's Robert Smith.
</P>
<P>
   His suggestions range from Gipsy Kings to Tom Waits to the
Bulgarian State Female Vocal Choir. Often, the music complements
the cuisine: blues for barbecue, Dylan's ``Highway 61 Revisited''
for making flavored olive oil (because it's a ``pick-me-up''), k.d.
lang for grilling asparagus, yams and Japanese eggplant.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you won't get from the Surreal Gourmet is an
extravagant dessert. ``Baking is about alchemy,'' he says.
``There's too much involved, and I usually don't want to mess with
it.'' Under the dessert section of his first book, you'll find ``10
Ways to Avoid Making Dessert,'' some of which are asking the dinner
guest to swing by a bakery and pick something up, or serving a
dessert port.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with all his philosophies about the art of dining, he
emphasizes that the only real way to learn how to cook is to
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use me as a guide if you want to,'' he said, adding that he is
by no means a chef.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you say, Bob. Whatever you say.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
