A5703 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     07-08 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEONE'S IN THE KITCHEN WITH DINAH'S COOKBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lou Ann Morey of Burleson, Texas, wrote a couple of weeks ago
looking for two recipes that had been, ahem, chewed up by a new
family member _ a puppy named Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The first was Dinah Shore's recipe for cioppino, that wonderful
San Francisco fish stew. Apparently, lots of readers have Dinah's
cookbook in their kitchen. Wanda McNeely sent in the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   The second recipe Lou Ann had ``lost'' was from our microwave
column from a few years back. Here they both are, and good luck
with the obedience classes.
</P>
<P>
   CIOPPINO
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1 leek, trimmed, well-washed, and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 to 4 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 green bell peppers, cored, seeded and cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   4 cups canned tomatoes (preferably imported, chopped)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   Red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fish stock PLUS 1 cup bottled clam juice OR 3 cups fresh
clam juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 pound firm-fleshed fish such as striped bass, red snapper,
rock cod, or sea bass, cut into bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 pound shrimp, shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   1 dozen well-washed clams in the shell
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup shucked oysters with their liquor
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound fresh scallops (preferably bay scallops)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound lobster tail, cooked in shell (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 hard-shell crab, cooked in shell and cracked (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil and butter in kettle and add onions, leek and garlic.
Cook, stirring often, until vegetables are lightly browned. Add
green peppers and continue cooking, stirring until peppers wilt.
</P>
<P>
   Add tomatoes, tomato sauce, salt and pepper to taste, bay leaf,
oregano, thyme, basil and about 1/4 teaspoon red pepper flakes. Add
fish stock or clam juice and cook slowly about 2 hours, stirring
often to prevent burning. More fish stock may be added if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Add wine and continue cooking about 10 minutes. The soup may be
made in advance to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes or so before serving, remove bay leaf, return
soup to boil, and add striped bass or other fish. Cook about 3
minutes and add shrimp. Cook 2 minutes more and add clams. Cover
and simmer about 6 minutes. Uncover, add oysters, scallops, lobster
tail and crab.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, stirring, about 5 minutes or until clams open. Serve in
warmed soup bowls with red pepper flakes on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 270 calories, 8 grams fat, 15
grams carbohydrates, 33 grams protein, 139 milligrams cholesterol,
733 milligrams sodium, 27 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE RIBBON COCONUT PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces semisweet chocolate squares OR 2/3 cup chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons low-fat milk
</P>
<P>
   9-inch prepared graham cracker pie crust (6 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups low-fat milk
</P>
<P>
   1 package (6-serving size) vanilla pudding and pie filling mix
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup flaked coconut, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 cups thawed, frozen nondairy whipped topping or whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Place chocolate and 2 tablespoons milk in a small microwavable
bowl. Microwave on high 2 minutes. Stir until chocolate is melted
and spread on bottom of crust; refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Combine milk and pudding mix in a 4-cup glass measure. Stirring
after every two minutes, microwave on high 6 to 8 minutes, or until
thickened. Cool to room temperature, stirring every few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir 1/2 cup coconut into pudding and pour over chocolate bottom
in pie. Refrigerate several hours. Toast remaining 1/4 cup coconut.
Top pie with whipped topping and garnish with toasted coconut.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 362 calories, 22 grams fat, 39
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 6 milligrams cholesterol, 131
milligrams sodium, 55 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Peacock Fogle of Fort Worth would like a recipe for an
angel food cake that is torn apart and layered in a springform pan
with a chocolate mousse made with dark or unsweetened chocolate and
peach brandy and then refrigerated overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Dean of North Richland Hills, Texas, would like a recipe
for a plum sauce like that served at the old Jimmy Dip's restaurant
in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Hooper of Joshua, Texas, would like a recipe for peach
butter.
</P>
<P>
   A reader would like the recipe for the black-bottom pie that was
served in the coffee shop and at the buffet at the
now-closed-but-soon-to-reopen Blackstone Hotel in downtown Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
