<HEADER>
A5721 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-BRAIN-$     07-08 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-BRAIN-$ADV12-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AND OUT OF A MIND THOUGHT TO BE DOOMED 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 12) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(jt) 
 By VINCENT CANBY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Brain,'' William Finn's latest chamber opera, is the
composer-lyricist's attempt to deal with what was obviously a
doomy, seriously traumatic experience: the preliminary diagnosis of
an inoperable brain tumor, which he received in 1992 just two weeks
after winning Tonys for his book and score for ``Falsettos.''
</P>
<P>
   In the program for ``A New Brain,'' which is now at the Mitzi E.
Newhouse Theater in Lincoln Center, he reports that all he could
think about in the days before the diagnosis was revised ``were the
songs I had planned to write but hadn't finally written.'' The show
we're now seeing, he says, is not meant to be a medical drama since
what eventually happened was ``much worse than anything that's on
the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``A New Brain'' means to recall what it's like to spend
five weeks thinking you're going to die, and then living. A
Dostoyevskian experience full of dread, anger and hopelessness?
Possibly, but in Finn's hindsight it also seems to have been
therapeutic: a time to recognize priorities, the ephemeral nature
of existence and the alternately sustaining and lacerating effects
of the artist's merciless vision.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the show that has come out of all this is a major
anticlimax. ``A New Brain'' is a peculiarly random collection of
pale characters and unrevealing incidents that seem more like an
exercise in composition than an urgent expression of the creative
impulse restored.
</P>
<P>
   The new show is especially wan after the exuberant wit,
originality and technical virtuosity of ``Falsettos,'' in which
Finn explores the awakening of one of the musical theater's most
charming heels. He is Marvin, an aggressively feckless fellow who's
thunderstruck to realize that he can't put together a household of
his ex-wife, his troubled adolescent son, his male lover and his
shrink (who has fallen in love with and married the ex-wife).
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Michael Schwinn, the central character in ``A New
Brain,'' could use a little of Marvin's redeeming chutzpah. Instead
he's a passive character whose grand aspirations would seem quite
unrealistic. Like Finn early in his career, Gordon is a composer
and lyricist who dreams of writing great songs while turning out
ditties for children's television programs, in this case for a
loathsome man-size frog named Bungee.
</P>
<P>
   During most of the 100-minute ``New Brain,'' which is played
without an intermission, we move in and out of Gordon's woozy mind
as he deals with his mother, his agent, his lover, Bungee and
assorted doctors, nurses and other types found in hospital
corridors. Hovering on the fringes of his awareness is a mysterious
woman who wears rags and has a smudged face, identified in the
program as Lisa, ``a homeless lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Finn's principal associates are Graciela Daniele, the show's
director and choreographer, and James Lapine, who collaborated with
him on the book. ( Lapine earlier worked with Finn on ``March of
the Falsettos'' and ``Falsettoland,'' which, combined, became the
material for the Broadway production of ``Falsettos.'') Both Ms.
Daniele and Lapine appear to have worked overtime to give this new
project some sense of cohesion and energy, but it never takes off
on its own. ``A New Brain'' seems always to be on artificial life
support.
</P>
<P>
   Quite early in the show, not long after Gordon has been
hospitalized, Ms. Daniele stages a big, energetic song-and-dance
number (''Ya gotta have heart and music/Heart and music make a
song''), enthusiastically performed by all the principal
characters, including the dreaming Gordon. Yet because the number
comes so early in the show, before the audience is aware of what
the stakes are, it seems to have no point, either as a genuine
anthem or as a send-up.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, the number reflects the weaknesses of Finn's entire
score, which is never as evocative, pointed or disarmingly cheeky
as ``Falsettos.'' So much attention is devoted to subsidiary
characters that Gordon remains no more than a puzzled ego. It's as
if he sees everything through a squint, so that the show becomes as
out-of-focus as he is.
</P>
<P>
   Especially disappointing are some of the lyrics, whose banality
can't be excused as intentional. I think of the number (``I'd
Rather Be Sailing'') sung by Gordon's lover, Roger, who, as
imagined by Gordon, describes his joy at being on the sea by
rhyming ``sailing'' with ``railing,'' which is the thing he leans
against as he's ``inhaling'' the fresh salt air.
</P>
<P>
   One of the show's better songs is sung by a robustly gay male
nurse, who rues his fate in ``Poor, Unsuccessful and Fat.''
Meanwhile, the mysterious homeless lady pops up from time to time
as a kind of tough, streetwise psychiatrist prone to enigmatic
pronouncements in song. As the show pushes doggedly on, Gordon
himself becomes even more of a cipher than he was at the beginning.
Perhaps Finn should have spent more time on the real horrors of
Gordon's craniotomy and hospitalization rather than attempting to
compose a half-heartedly upbeat musical testament to his survival.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Daniele's production looks great and is well sung,
especially by Malcolm Gets (Gordon), Penny Fuller (Gordon's
mother), Liz Larsen (his agent), Michael Mandell (the nurse), Chip
Zien ( Bungee) and Mary Testa (the homeless lady).
</P>
<P>
   `THE SKIN OF OUR TEETH'
</P>
<P>
   Thornton Wilder's cosmic comedy, ``The Skin of Our Teeth,''
which triumphed on Broadway in 1942 under the direction of Elia
Kazan, is still some kind of great play, but it's not easily
revived today. That's clear in the earnest, jokey, sometimes
colorful Joseph Papp Public Theater production that closes Sunday
at the Delacorte Theater in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   When you read it, ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' is a free-form
delight: the history of the world as experienced by and Mrs. George
Antrobus, an average American couple from Excelsior, N.J. During
their 5,000-year marriage, he invents the wheel and the alphabet,
among other things, and she keeps the family together while he
periodically threatens to run off with other women, all played by
the Antrobus maid, Sabina. Plucky optimists that they are, the
Antrobuses survive the Ice Age, the Flood, various depressions
large and small, and World War II, which America was just getting
into when Wilder wrote the play.
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiography, ``A Life,'' Kazan describes the form of
the play ``as novel and constantly surprising,'' but says that
``the author's values'' are ``conventional and finally stuffy.'' He
adds: ``Other plays I've liked were conceived out of the life
experience of the dramatist; this play seemed to have been hatched
in the library of a financially secure college campus.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a devastating though not inaccurate assessment. Wilder
was a cerebral artist for whom the mind was the only logical locale
for his Grand Tours. Part philosopher, part professor, part yarn
spinner, he created tales that depended less on particular
experience than on his imagination. He was a fantasist of the
ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its conception, ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' is full of
irresistible moments that are especially difficult to recreate in
today's theater, which is far less bound by conventions than was
the Broadway theater of 1942. In Wilder's script, the actress
playing Sabina is constantly interrupting the performance, as if
ad-libbing, to say she hasn't a clue as to what the play's about,
to remember other, better roles, or to refuse to say a particular
line of dialogue she finds distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   This was pretty lively stuff in 1942, especially when Tallulah
Bankhead, at her most grandly volcanic, was playing the outspoken
actress who plays Sabina.
</P>
<P>
   Today's audiences have grown up watching television comics step
in and out of character, break up at their own jokes and make rude
remarks about their material. Such badinage has become an accepted
form of contemporary humor, almost obligatory. This may be why the
Delacorte audience with which I saw the play accepted these
interruptions as comic. It wasn't because the interruptions really
were funny (which they weren't, at least not as played by these
actors), but because it was recognized they were supposed to be
funny. Television has taught us that intentions are enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' is showing its age these days, but
there's nothing wrong with that unless, as sometimes happens in
this staging, you have the feeling that the actors are patronizing
their material, patting it on the head. What is more difficult to
accept is Wilder's conviction that man will somehow muddle through.
</P>
<P>
   In this time of the Bomb, environmental pollution and global
warming, such optimism seems utterly mad, until you understand
that, in 1942, optimism was a patriotic duty.
</P>
<P>
   The Delacourt production, directed by Irene Lewis, has the great
good fortune to have John Goodman playing Antrobus, which may be
the best role he's had since his early years on ``Roseanne.''
Goodman is a fine, big stage performer, disciplined, commanding and
unfussy. His George Antrobus pats no one on the head. He's a
salesman, traveling through the ages, meeting the eye of each
person he's talking to. Frances Conroy is also stalwart as Mrs.
Antrobus, not an easy assignment since it's almost entirely
humorless.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Johnston, of television's ``Third Rock From the Sun,''
looks stunning as Sabina, with a voluptuous figure that seems to
have been sewn into her saucy maid's costume. She also has the
seductively husky voice required of a siren still operating at peak
efficiency after 5,000 years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   What she lacks, however, is an apparent willingness to be the
bitchy opportunist who might alienate the audience. She tries too
hard to please, which is the manner of the entire production. This
``Skin of Our Teeth'' seems geared to convince the audience that
it's a warm, cuddly teddy bear of a show.
</P>
<P>
   It was to guard against such interpretations that Wilder mocked
his own highfalutin aims in Sabina's asides to the audience. If
anyone was going to wink at the audience, Wilder would do the
winking. The members of the cast were expected to play it straight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
