<SLUG> BC-TOMATOES-RECIPES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`YOU SAY TOMATO' BEARS A CROP OF LUSCIOUS RECIPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ahhh, finally.
</P>
<P>
   No more ersatz tomatoes from the supermarket. No more pretending
you're biting into summer when you know full well that the only
right thing about winter tomatoes is the color of the exterior.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to revel in tomatoes: those from your garden, those
from your friends' gardens, those from the farmers markets. Still
warm from the sun and aromatic with their flavor, local tomatoes
are the culinary highlight of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Say Tomato'' by Joanne Weir (Broadway, $15) agrees. If
you're lucky enough to have your own crop of lovelies, Weir tells
you how to peel, seed, core, roast, oven-dry, freeze, can or make
them into tomato paste. If you're limited to the bounty from the
market, Weir gives recipes for fried green tomato ``sandwiches''
and Cheddar-crusted tomato flan.
</P>
<P>
   Not limited to this season's fresh offerings, the book offers
plenty of recipes using canned tomatoes _ arguably the best canned
fruit or vegetable going. ``You Say Tomato'' is a book for all
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   PORTUGUESE TOMATO PILAF
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons bacon drippings, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups peeled, seeded and chopped fresh or canned tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you don't have bacon drippings, use four tablespoons of
olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Heat bacon drippings and olive oil in large saucepan over medium
heat. Add onion and garlic and cook, stirring, until lightly
golden, 12-15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomatoes and stock and bring to a boil over high heat.
Add rice and salt and pepper to taste, reduce heat to low, and
simmer, covered, until rice is tender and liquid is absorbed, 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fluff rice with a fork and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 353 calories, 11 grams fat, 56
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 5 milligrams cholesterol, 34
milligrams sodium, 28 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIAN MARINATED TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 tablespoons coriander seeds, coarsely cracked
</P>
<P>
   12 small ripe red tomatoes, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 head romaine lettuce, cut crosswise into 1/2-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh cilantro sprigs
</P>
<P>
   In deep bowl, whisk together vinegar, sugar, salt, pepper,
ketchup, 3 tablespoons water, Worcestershire sauce, lemon juice,
olive oil and coriander seeds. Prick each tomato with a fork in 3
or 4 places. Submerge tomatoes in vinaigrette and marinate
overnight in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, layer half the lettuce, cilantro and drained tomatoes
in a serving bowl, then repeat layers.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 176 calories, 15 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 13 milligrams cholesterol,
535 milligrams sodium, 75 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN CREOLE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 stalks celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 medium green bell pepper, cored, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley, plus whole leaves for
garnish
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peeled, seeded and chopped fresh or canned tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot pepper sauce, such as Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in large heavy casserole over medium
heat. Add onion, celery, bell pepper and parsley and cook for 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add garlic and cook for 2 minutes until almost soft. Add chicken
stock, red wine vinegar, tomatoes, tomato paste, brown sugar, hot
pepper sauce, 1/2 teaspoon salt and pepper to taste. Bring to a
boil over high heat, reduce heat to low and simmer for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat remaining 1 tablespoon olive oil in large frying pan over
medium-high heat. Add chicken breasts and cook until golden on both
sides, 5 minutes total.
</P>
<P>
   Add white wine and tomato sauce to the chicken and simmer until
chicken is cooked through, about 10 minutes. Season to taste with
salt and pepper. If sauce is too thin, remove chicken and keep
warm. Reduce sauce over medium-high heat until it thickens
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place chicken on a platter, spoon sauce over it, and
garnish with parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 277 calories, 9 grams fat, 10
grams carbohydrates, 37 grams protein, 96 milligrams cholesterol,
152 milligrams sodium, 30 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
