<SLUG> BC-CIR-FISHCAM-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC SNOOPING ON FISH CAUSES CRY OF FOUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (Circuits) 
(bl) 
 By CARLA BARANAUCKAS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALKER, Minn. _ A video camera that reveals the secrets below
the surface of lakes in far more detail than other electronic fish
finders has renewed an intense debate about the use of technology
in the pursuit of game fish.
</P>
<P>
   The patented device, called the Aqua-Vu, can show a detailed
picture of a lake's water, bottom and inhabitants, using a video
camera small enough to fit inside a coffee mug. It is the invention
of Jeff Zernov of Brainerd, Minn., a 45-year-old lifelong fisherman
and entrepreneur. The setup, which costs $1,495 gives ``people such
enlightenment to know what was happening down there,'' Zernov said.
</P>
<P>
   But sentiments on the use of the fishcam differ sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Department of Natural Resources opposes the
camera, and it is setting up a committee to study all high-tech
devices for fishing and hunting. State Sen. Bob Lessard of
International Falls introduced a bill this spring to ban the
underwater video camera for fishing in Minnesota. The bill was
passed by the state Senate but never came to a vote in the state
House of Representatives, so it is dead unless it is reintroduced
in the next legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is fair chase and how far do we want to go before we do
away with sportsmanship and skill?'' Lessard, who has made his
living as a fishing guide since he was 13, said in a telephone
interview from his fly-in fishing resort in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Zernov said he had invented the Aqua-Vu after spending years
learning about fish and their habitats. He took up scuba diving and
founded and later sold Zercom Marine, a producer of sonar devices
that indicate whether fish might _ with an emphasis on the
``might'' _ be below the surface of the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we know what sonar is telling us about fish, but we
don't know for sure,'' Zernov said. With a sonar device, blips on a
screen indicate that fish _ or other objects suspended in the water
_ are there.
</P>
<P>
   When Zernov was diving, he said, his presence and the noise of
the scuba equipment disturbed the fish so much that he could not
observe their normal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Then an idea came to him last summer: what if a video camera
could be put below the surface of the water with a monitor in the
fishing boat?
</P>
<P>
   In six weeks, Zernov said, he had a prototype ready. By January,
just in time for ice fishing, Zernov was selling the Aqua-Vu
underwater viewing system, with a 1{-pound black-and-white camera
(with a detachable fin and ballast weights), a 200-pound
tensile-strength power cable and a 5{-inch black-and-white monitor,
for $1,495.
</P>
<P>
   Lessard contends that technology is affecting the sport in a
fundamental way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have right now GPS,'' he said, referring to Global
Positioning System receivers, ``and we have faster boats. Our lakes
are charted and then we have state-of-the-art depth finders, which
I use, by the way. But even with those, you don't actually see the
fish. There's an element of judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Zernov, who said he fished every day from a dock in his
backyard, said the camera did not take the sportsmanship out of
fishing. ``The right lure and the right presentation still hold
true,'' Zernov said. ``It doesn't force the fish to bite.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a recent demonstration on Leech Lake here in northwestern
Minnesota, the camera showed details of the lake bottom. It was
easy to differentiate among walleye, perch, weeds and the mayflies
hatching in the sandy bottom. Fish swam nonchalantly past the
camera lens, occasionally staring directly into it for an eerie
eye-to-fisheye view. The camera is maneuvered by pulling and
twisting the cable, requiring hand-eye coordination similar to that
needed for using a computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mariners Classic fishing tournament on the lake, opinion
on the Aqua-Vu was sharply divided. The Leech Lake Area Chamber of
Commerce, the sponsor, does not permit the use of underwater video
cameras in its competitions, although sonar and GPS receivers are
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Zubke of Walker said he had used the camera forice fishing.
``You've got an advantage with it,'' Zubke said. ``You're looking
at the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he might use a camera to examine the bottom of a lake.
``But I would never use one for fishing,'' he said. ``That would
just take the fun of it away for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Olson of Andover, Minn., said he saw no reason to ban the
device.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be fun to use it to see the structure that the fish are
sitting on and even what they're eating,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Michael, added, ``Sometimes the fish just won't bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Whittington of Bemidji, Minn., questioned whether a fishcam
would actually help a good angler. ``You've got some of the best
fishermen who ever wet a hook here,'' Whittington said. ``It
wouldn't have helped them.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough people are interested in the Aqua-Vu for sales to exceed
Zernov's initial expectations. Zernov said he had expected to sell
500 cameras in the first year. ``We sold that many in the first
three months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Arnold, owner of Reed's Sporting Goods in Walker, said he
had sold hundreds of the cameras. He said that some customers had
questioned whether he should sell the Aqua-Vu but that he responded
by saying, ``No one puts fish hooks on the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't catch them,'' he said. ``They only give us more
knowledge.'' If Arnold thought that the camera would help deplete
fish stocks, he would not sell it, he said. ``Fishing is all we
breathe and do here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the divide are the Minnesota Department of
Natural Resources and the billionaire financier Irwin L. Jacobs,
whose Genmar Holdings owns boat manufacturing companies and
professional fishing tournaments, which have purses of up to $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no bones about it,'' said the department's deputy
commissioner, Ron Nargang, ``we are opposed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nargang said the department was concerned about sportsmanship,
the potential depletion of fish stocks and the issue of keeping
fishing equally accessible to people who couldn't afford such
expensive devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visual contact thing with the fish really takes us to
another level,'' Nargang said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big business,'' said Jacobs, whose Wal-Mart FLW Tour is
televised on ESPN2, ``and if you create the legality of this, it
really takes the sportsmanship out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful from a nature and natural standpoint if you
take people out and just show the environment,'' he said, but he
said he thought the camera could easily be abused by fishermen. ``I
want to preserve as much of the sport as I can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the debate goes on, Zernov has kept working. In August,
he plans to introduce Aqua-Vu II, which will have a smaller camera
and thinner cable and a monitor with a built-in sunscreen. He said
he expected the retail price to be less than $700.
</P>
<P>
   Nargang said, ``I'd be surprised if this did not come back to
the Legislature.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
