<P>
   &UR; TINA BROWN RESIGNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times plans a package of stories on the resignation of
Tina Brown as editor of The New Yorker:
</P>
<P>
   BROWN-RESIGN (New York) _ A ledeall on the resignation and what
we know of its circumstances. She is leaving to develop a new
magazine for Walt Disney's Miramax. By Geraldine Fabrikant and
Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   In addition we are considering other angles to the story,
including a look at the changing relationship between Hollywood and
the magazine industry and a focus on the New Yorker and S.I.
Newhouse, chairman of Advance, which owns Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RESEARCH-PRIORITY (Washington) _ Patients and the public
should be given a bigger, more formal role in setting priorities
for biomedical research financed by the federal government, a
blue-ribbon panel says in a report criticizing the National
Institutes of Health. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HUT-ARCHITECTRE (Undated) _ If summer is the season for
celebrating simple things, ``A Hut of One's Own: Life Outside the
Circle of Architecture'' (MIT Press), by Ann Cline, is well-timed.
Its small subject _ the hut _ defines the field of architecture
like a cricket in the grass. Hand-built and homemade, usually
wooden, scraped together with pieces of scrap or engineered with
standard lumber, the hut is barely design. It is as ordinary as a
structure can be. But the hut has an extraordinary ability. It
understands what to bring in, and what to leave out, to craft the
wonder of being.
</P>
<P>
   HANNAH-HOME (Oxford, Miss.) _ It's not easy to imagine what sort
of house Barry Hannah might live in. His characters, who saunter
and stumble and soliloquize through his heavily autobiographical
fiction seem to have no home: they are drunk at the controls of a
jet or bargaining with God atop a horse or roaring down the road in
a Lincoln with beer cans rattling around the floorboard. So it is
strange to step out of Mr. Hannah's Jeep Cherokee, with a basket of
bright new tennis balls in the back seat, and onto the driveway of
his modest, Eisenhower-era house in this pretty, antebellum town.
</P>
<P>
   REFRIGERATORS (Undated) _ Of all America's migratory species,
perhaps the strangest is the refrigerator. This summer, when the
fridge is crammed with watermelon and seems to heave like an
overweight jogger, it may be worth pondering the increasingly
nomadic nature of this once-monumental appliance. The magnet-laden
stalwart of the kitchen has started to appear in the weirdest
places, popping up in closets and dresser drawers where sweaters
and mothballs used to be.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPER (Livingston, Texas) _ For years, whenever vacation time
rolled around, LaVere and Ginny Keller would roll out of Salt Lake
City in their camper truck and explore the West. ``It was pretty
tight quarters, especially when our three daughters were with us,''
he recalled. ``But we loved it. We'd get home, and we'd say,
`Wouldn't it be great if we could just keep going?''' In 1994 they
did just that. The Kellers retired, sold their house, bought a
trailer and a truck to tow it, and took to the road full time. At
Rainbow's End, a camp for up to 400 recreational vehicles here in
the piney woods of East Texas, they joyously described the changes
in their lives _ the 17 states they have toured, the new friends
they have made at RV camps along the way and most of all, the new
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-DESIGN (Undated) _ Some modern kitchens may be geared up
with enough equipment to retool the Mir space station, yet they
manage to invoke the well-bred charm of Jane Austen's parlor. Tea
anyone? It can be steamed up on the Aga or zapped in the microwave
oven, then served in a room newly commodious with a kitchen sofa,
pillows, even an armchair. The designer has arrived in the kitchen,
bringing an eye for creature comforts and materials once reserved
for more showy parts of the house. The last barrier between rooms
has finally come down. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   DESERT-MOTEL (Desert Hot Springs, Calif.) _ For 15 years Miracle
Manor, a divey 40s motel 10 miles northeast of Palm Springs, seemed
scripted more than operated by Lois Blackhill, a sometimes topless
facialist noted for chanelling a spirit named Omra. Ms. Blackhill
attracted an unusual cast of characters to this Southern California
Lourdes, which sits atop a geyser reputed to gush the most
``balanced'' mineral water in America into its spa and pool. When
she died of cancer in 1996, her ashes were sprinkled under the
fronds in the garden. It seemed she would be a hard act to follow.
Could there ever be a sequel to Lois? Today, the rusty neon sign is
lighted again. The modest stucco establishment, with zoomy roofs
lifting off toward a long desert view, now belongs to a Los Angeles
designer, April Greiman, and an architect, Michael Rotondi, both
regulars at the motel since the 1980s. By Joseph Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   FROGDESIGN (New York) _ ``It's industrial Wheatena,'' Michael
McDonough, a New York architect, said. He is talking about a
product made from the stumps of wheat left after a harvest, a
caramel-colored material he fashioned into pipes that hide
electronic cables in the new 6,000 square foot office of Frogdesign
in Manhattan. Frogdesign, an industrial design company, wanted the
finished space to follow two concepts: waste not, want not, and
make sure everything can be disassembled. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
