<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5744 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SONDHEIM-REVIEW-     07-08 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SONDHEIM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LIFE OF MUSICAL THEATER'S MODERN GENIUS EXPLORED IN NEW
BIOGRAPHY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  `STEPHEN SONDHEIM: A LIFE' by Meryle Secrest; (Knopf, $30) 
 
By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following well-received biographies of several key 20th-century
artists (painter Salvador Dali, architect Frank Lloyd Wright,
composer Leonard Bernstein), Meryle Secrest has turned her
attention to Stephen Sondheim, indisputably the most important
composer and lyricist in contemporary musical theater.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim's bold and incredibly varied output encompasses many
stage milestones of the past 40 years _ from his Broadway
beginnings as lyricist of ``West Side Story'' and ``Gypsy,''
through his staggering early 1970s burst of creativity that
produced ``Company,'' ``Follies'' and ``A Little Night Music`` and
established him as his generation's pre-eminent composer/lyricist,
through such masterpieces of his maturity as ''Sweeney Todd,``
''Sunday in the Park With George,`` ''Into the Woods`` and
''Passion.``
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim continues the American musical's development as an art
form, taking up the mantle of composer Richard Rodgers and
librettist Oscar Hammerstein II _ the latter not only mentor to
Sondheim but virtually a surrogate father. No other Broadway talent
has consistently tackled such big, meaningful and challenging
subjects, always pushing the musical into new territory, both in
theme and structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pacific Overtures,'' for instance, depicts the forced opening
of Japan to trade with the West after centuries of isolationism and
the subsequent effect on Japanese society _ a musical about the
price of progress. ``Sunday in the Park With George'' uses Georges
Seurat's creation of his landmark pointillist painting ``A Sunday
Afternoon on the Island of La Grande Jatte'' to explore the process
of creating art, what it costs its creator and how its meaning
reverberates beyond his lifetime. Two typically ``Sondheim''
musicals _ and who else would have had the nerve to attempt them,
much less the genius to realize them so brilliantly?
</P>
<P>
   While there have been other books on Sondheim, the most crucial
being Craig Zadan's pioneering work ``Sondheim &AMP; Co.'' (first
published in the mid-1970s but revised and expanded in recent
years), Secrest's is the first to combine discussion of Sondheim's
public career with an in-depth look at his private life, heretofore
largely unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   As such, Secrest's capably written and painstakingly researched
volume boasts inherent interest and will be widely read and
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   True, much behind-the-scenes show-biz lore reiterates material
from earlier sources. Secrest relies heavily on excerpts from
contemporary reviews of each Sondheim work, keeping her own
analysis of his music and lyrics minimal and fairly standard,
seldom supplying the depth and insight one might expect. But then,
virtually every one of Sondheim's rich and complex works could do
with a full-length study.
</P>
<P>
   In exploring Sondheim's personal life, Secrest describes his
privileged upbringing as the son of a successful dress manufacturer
and his upwardly striving wife. Parental affection seems to have
been in short supply for the child, who was ``institutionalized''
in the best schools and summer camps.
</P>
<P>
   His parents' divorce, when he was 10, became the pivotal crisis
of Sondheim's early life, while his thorny relationship with mother
Janet Fox Sondheim, a bright, aggressive and maddeningly difficult
woman aptly nicknamed ``Foxy,'' would go on bewildering them both
until her death in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age Sondheim's friendship with Hammerstein and wife
Dorothy gave needed emotional support while guiding Sondheim toward
his career in the theater. Secrest delves into Sondheim's
apprentice works written in college and under Hammerstein's
tutelage, finding early signs of blossoming talent as well as the
emotional ambivalence that would characterize much of his mature
work.
</P>
<P>
   Secrest shows how alliances formed by the unusually
well-connected Sondheim led to early career opportunities _ and
helped overcome such setbacks as the cancellation of his first
Broadway-bound show (``Saturday Night,'' for which he penned both
music and lyrics) when its producer, Lemuel Ayers, died of leukemia
in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Yet early triumphs with ``West Side Story'' and ``A Funny Thing
Happened on the Way to the Forum'' remained shadowed by Sondheim's
own highly self-critical nature and the reluctance of some key
theater figures to acknowledge his gifts as a composer.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, this biography abounds in colorful glimpses of the
fascinating, infuriating production process. Secrest details the
crucial impact of longtime Sondheim collaborators like
producer/director Hal Prince, librettist Arthur Laurents and
director/librettist James Lapine. Brilliant figures like Jerome
Robbins reveal their tempestuous and difficult side but also come
to the rescue at crucial moments _ as when Robbins, after dithering
over whether he would direct ``Forum,'' finally oversees a new
opening that saves the show.
</P>
<P>
   Secrest's book is the first to deal with Sondheim's
homosexuality _ handled with a welcome logic and lack of
sensationalism but also a discretion bordering on reticence. In his
entire adult life, only two or three relationships merit fleeting
mention. The only one treated at length is Sondheim's recent, rocky
but apparently continuing relationship with young composer Peter
Jones, whom he met in 1991; their love story clearly influenced the
course of Sondheim's emotionally charged ``Passion.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief virtue of Secrest's biography is that it relates
Sondheim's personal life to his much-admired creative output. In
``Sunday in the Park'' the artist's mantra is, ``Connect, George.
Connect.'' Secrest has connected Sondheim the human being with
Sondheim the genius.
</P>
<P>
   One can consider Secrest's work to be definitive for the time
being, though it is equally clear that the last word has not been
written on Sondheim's life and career.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
