<HEADLINE>
LICORICE-FLAVORED VEGETABLE TAKES ROOT IN SOPHISTICATED COOKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED: (Workman, $18.95)
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN BREASTS WITH FENNEL IN BECHAMEL SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 medium fennel bulb, coarsely chopped, heart discarded
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 large skinless and boneless chicken breast halves
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups very hot whole milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of ground nutmeg, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups shredded Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fennel tops, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   In steamer pot, steam chopped fennel bulb for 10 minutes.
Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In large skillet over medium heat,
heat oil and saute chicken 10 minutes on each side. In medium
saucepan over medium-low heat, melt butter and stir in flour. Whisk
in milk and cook, stirring, until sauce thickens, about 5 minutes.
Season with salt and pepper and nutmeg. Pour a third of sauce into
square 10-inch baking pan. Lay chicken breasts bottom-down in the
sauce, and top with steamed fennel and remaining sauce. Sprinkled
with Parmesan and bake 25 minutes. Garnish with fennel top and
serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 530 calories, 23 grams fat, 12
grams carbohydrates, 65 grams protein, 182 milligrams cholesterol,
597 milligrams sodium, 39 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Italian Dinners 1, 2, 3,'' by Jacqueline Heriteau with Holly
Brown Hunter (Potter, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CURED SALMON WITH THINLY SLICED FENNEL
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 as appetizer
</P>
<P>
   2 medium fennel bulbs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds thinly sliced smoked salmon
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons capers, drained
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons snipped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 4 lemons
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, for drizzling
</P>
<P>
   Salt and cracked black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   To prepare fennel, pull outer leaf off the bulb. Wash bulb and
cut off the very bottom. Thinly slice bulb into paper-thin slivers.
Cut out and discard round heart in center. You should be left with
half-moons of fennel.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange fennel and salmon, alternating the two, on individual
plates. Sprinkle capers and chives over salmon and fennel, squeeze
lemon juice over the top, and drizzle with olive oil. Season with
salt and cracked pepper, to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 195 calories, 7 grams fat, 9
grams carbohydrates, 22 grams protein, 26 milligrams cholesterol,
1,122 milligrams sodium, 34 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Intimate Gatherings'' by Ellen Rose and Jessica Strand
(Chronicle Books, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
