<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5764 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHY-WEAGE-TEX     07-08 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHY-WE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING OLD? BLAME IT ON YOUR CELLS
</HEADLINE>
 AGE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If Mother Nature doesn't get you, Father Time will.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows the cause of death in people older that 85, says
the scientist who discovered in 1961 that human cells can divide
only a finite number of times before they age and die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has cardiovascular disease at that age _ or any age _
and there are very few older people you can open up on autopsy and
not find cancer,'' says Leonard Hayflick, Ph.D. ``Doctors put down
some socially acceptable reason as the cause of death, but
ultimately in many cases, time has simply run out. The normal
process of aging has reached its limits.''
</P>
<P>
   The clocks that govern our lives are not all on our walls or on
our wrists. The clocks that age us are in our cells, and they
ultimately determine how many seconds, minutes, hours, days, weeks,
months, seasons and years add up to one life, Hayflick says.
</P>
<P>
   He and other researchers in the young science of biogerontology
are trying to find out how our cellular clocks work and what they
can tell us about our biological destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Hayflick was in Fort Worth recently on a public education
campaign to promote
</P>
<P>
   early diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease. The visit was sponsored
by the makers of Aricept, the new Alzheimer's drug.
</P>
<P>
   Hayflick's book, ``How and Why We Age'' (Ballantine Books, $14),
is based on more than 30 years of pioneering research in biological
aging.
</P>
<P>
   Building on the concept of ``The Hayflick Limit,'' researchers
reported in the journal ``Science'' this year that for the first
time, healthy human cells growing in a dish have been made
immortal.
</P>
<P>
   The new research is based on the finding that the innate
potential for cells to divide and reproduce is controlled by a
chemical sequence called telomeres, found at the tips of
chromosomes. Each time a cell divides, its telomeres grow shorter
until they eventually become unstable, stop dividing and die.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists broke the cellular aging process by replenishing the
enzyme called ``telomerase,'' which telomeres need to continue
dividing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our understanding of telomeres, we now have the capacity
to immortalize a living cell with a finite capacity to replicate on
its own,'' Hayflick says. ``As our understanding of cell biology
increases and we understand the process of how cells age and die,
we will be able to develop means of interventions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayflick says that aging is not a disease, but it is terminal _
unless scientists find a way to give cells in the body an endless
supply of telomerase.
</P>
<P>
   Even if medical science were to find cures for all diseases and
all injuries, he says, people would die of cellular aging. Even
accidents are often caused by aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The normal process of aging increases your vulnerability to
the causes of death listed on death certificates, even if you are
hit by a truck _ you might not see it in time or react in time to
jump out of the way'' because of aging senses, Hayflick points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is why an old cell is more susceptible to
pathology than a young cell. That will explain Alzheimer's,
arthritis, cancer, cardiovascular disease _ heart attacks, strokes
_ and all the rest. Why don't 20-year-olds get those diseases in
most cases? There's something different about their cells,''
Hayflick says.
</P>
<P>
   Few question the goal of resolving all the causes of death
listed on death certificates, Hayflick allows. But most older
people would rather add life to their remaining years than
unlimited years to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living longer with a very important caveat: Life
expectancy and life span are not the same thing,'' he says. ``Life
span has not increased in 100,000 years; life expectancy has
increased more than 25 years in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy _ the average length of life for a just-born
person _ has increased from 45 years in 1900 to 75 years today. But
the ultimate life span _ the upper limit on human life _ has
remained about 120 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few serious scientists are directing their research to
extending human longevity or achieving immortality,'' Hayflick
says. ``The goal should be for all human beings to reach the
maximum life span, still in possession of full mental and physical
abilities, with death occurring quickly as we approach, say, our
115th birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
