r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-INFERNO-TEX     07-08 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-INFERNO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW IS THE SUMMER OF OUR MALCONTENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ I moved to Texas in the spring of 1982,
after a winter on the western plains of North Dakota, where the
temperature did not rise above 30 degrees below zero for three
weeks straight. That's without wind chill. I'm not making this up.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the days during that singular stretch were sunny and
windless, yet cross-country travel was discouraged because at that
temperature, a breakdown on a country road could be fatal within
minutes. Coaxing dead car batteries back to life with jumper cables
was part of the daily morning ritual. The teeniest piece of skin
exposed to those temperatures felt pricked by a thousand tiny
needles. The cold literally took your breath away.
</P>
<P>
   Which, right now, all sounds kind of nice. I have just come from
a noontime jog along the Trinity River. The sign at the downtown
YMCA says it's 104 degrees outside, and Have A Nice Day.
</P>
<P>
   I decide to hit the public library to see whether any references
to North Texas pop up in Dante's ``Inferno.'' On the two-block walk
there, my legs perspire heavily and stick to the inside of my
jeans. The air feels like engine sludge as it enters my lungs.
Blanketlike.MDNM/ humidity saps my spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Please, give me a bracing gust of Canadian January wind. Hand me
a snow shovel _ and some snow. Compared with.MDNM/ this, a
Midwestern winter is frolic, or if not exactly fun, certainly the
lesser of two evils.
</P>
<P>
   Up there, for instance, you could always add another layer. In
Texas, .MDNM/you can take off only so many clothes. In a Midwestern
winter, the ice-fishing antidote was available to cure cabin fever.
In Texas, there only alternatives are shopping malls and the
increasingly tepid waters of outdoor pools.
</P>
<P>
   I hate this weather. Have I said that? It makes me grumpy. One
recent night, my wife and I saw a TV news report that said domestic
abuse cases generally rise during the hottest weather. Something
about irritability, combined with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I ever glad you don't drink,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She, by the way, is one of those unfortunate souls whose
personal thermostat is hopelessly out of whack. When
it.MDBU/'.MDNM/s 95 degrees, she thinks it's 75. She must wear
sweaters and thermal underwear to movies. She LIKES this heat.
Worst of all, she has forbidden me to whine about it.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I think that whining about the heat is more than
appropriate. It's almost obligatory. But she is firm. So whenever
the two of us leave air conditioning together and step outside, I
take several appreciative gulps of 100-degree air and stretch my
arms wide, like Julie Andrews on the mountaintop in the ``Sound of
Music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My,'' I say. ``Isn't this invigorating?''
</P>
<P>
   I think she picks up on my sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   THE CRAPE MYRTLE THEORY.MDBU/
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/I am pleased to learn that Dr. Bob Lanier, the local TV
personality, is a kindred spirit. I call him to ask why heat makes
the human body feel so lousy. Instead, for most of our
conversation, the two of us take turns whining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dread this time every year,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, too,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier has a couple of theories about the heat, neither of which
has anything to do with medicine. One is that the really terrible
weather begins when the crape myrtles bloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see those darn crape myrtles coming out, I said, `Oh,
% &LR; !. Here it comes,' '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The other is his theory of five seasons. Autumn in Texas lasts
four or five days, Lanier says, followed by a day or two of winter.
``From December through the end of May, we have spring, and this is
a fabulous place to be. From the end of May until the second week
of June, we have summer.'' Then, from the end of the NBA playoffs
to the Dallas Cowboys first home game is the fifth season, he says,
``the season from hell.''
</P>
<P>
   His theory holds up most years, but not this. This year, the
temperature hit 100 degrees for the first time on May 6 _ 38 days
before Michael Jordan launched his historic,
NBA-championship-winning jump shot. Five other days in May, the
temperature rose to 95 or worse; 23 more times in June, a month
when the average high temperature is supposed to be 92.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of heat rightfully belongs in the last week in July or
the first week in August. Not June. Certainly not May. No wonder
I'm grumpy. As oppressiveness goes, this year promises to be a
doozy. I'm no scientist, but I know exactly where to point the
finger of blame. Two words.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   UNLIKELY SUSPECTS.MDBU/
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/Not so, says Dave Martin, a meteorologist for the National
Weather Service. El Nino has pretty much played out. He has another
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's summer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder immediately whether this guy has been talking to my
wife. To describe the heat we've all been withstanding, he uses
irritating words like, ``slightly above normal.'' He insists on
comparing everything with the summer of 1980, when it was 113
degrees on June 26 and 27, 112 on the 28th, 108 on the 29th. I want
to say that I don't care how hot it was in 1980. But I bite my
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   No. Not El Nino. Instead, this torment is due to the massive
high pressure systems that tend to linger around the region in the
summer, Martin says. High pressure means that the air in the upper
reaches of the atmosphere is forced downward toward Earth. When air
is forced down, its molecules are scrunched together, and they heat
up.
</P>
<P>
   All that plus the fact that the sun shines about 13 hours a day
this time of year, giving it plenty of time to make us miserable.
And the wonderful westerly winds that bring us cold fronts and rain
at other times of the year all move farther.MDNM/ north in the
summertime, vacationing in the Hamptons, as it were.
</P>
<P>
   Just one more thing to be ticked off at. Those darn westerlies.
</P>
<P>
   So now my wife won't let me watch the weather on television,
because she knows it will only tempt me to grouse, which I'm
forbidden to do. Me, I don't know why the weather forecasters don't
just take the season off. ``Here's your five-day forecast,'' they
say. ``High 101, low 82; high 100, low 81; high 102, low 82,''
blah, blah, blah, etc. etc. etc. I mean, why bother?
</P>
<P>
   So now, I whine about the weather whenever I'm not at home. I
dream of January in North Dakota, and 30 below. Did you know that a
frozen earlobe feels as heavy as a ball bearing when it starts to
thaw, or that eyelashes crust over with ice in about two minutes?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, heaven.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
