<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5816 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-BITS-ART     07-08 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-BITS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIT BY BIT: A GUIDE TO HOW COMPUTERS CRUNCH NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One common measure of computer function is the way the central
processing unit handles information. The terms 8-bit, 16-bit,
32-bit, 64-bit and, occasionally, 128-bit are tossed around by
people who may be trying to impress others with the horsepower of
their machines.
</P>
<P>
   This statistic has some value, but as with most numbers used by
computer marketing divisions, its real value is complex, nuanced
and not necessarily the same for all people. The number of bits
measures the capacity that a chip has for moving data around. A
16-bit computer and an operating system tailored to run on it can
perform better than some 32-bit computers in much the same way that
a four-cylinder Porsche 944 can blow the doors off some
eight-cylinder cars.
</P>
<P>
   The measurement refers to the number of pieces of data that are
pushed around by the computer at a time. An 8-bit computer handles
data in chunks of 8 bits, that is, in binary numbers eight digits
long. Because they are binary, each place is either 0 or 1.
</P>
<P>
   In binary numbers, the place values are based on 2, not 10. So
moving from right to left for the number 01100111, the place values
are 20, 21, 22, 23 and so on. That means that for the number
01100111, the values, from right to left, are 1 plus 2 plus 4 plus
0 plus 0 plus 32 plus 64 plus 0, for a total of 103.
</P>
<P>
   The number of possible combinations of eight 0's and 1's is 256,
so any 8-bit chunk of data can have only 256 different values.
Numbers with 16 bits can have 65,536 possible values, and numbers
with 32 bits can have 4,294,967,296 possible values.
</P>
<P>
   A common joke is that the world must move to 64-bit computers
because 32-bit machines aren't big enough to hold the number that
represents Bill Gates' personal wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of 32-bit computers also run into this problem
because that capacity is not enough to count each byte in a hard
drive that holds 4.3 gigabytes or more.
</P>
<P>
   Computer designers must choose one common size for data _ a
standard number of bits _ and use it throughout each machine.
</P>
<P>
   A good way to understand the problem is to think about buying
eggs. While eggs can be bought in packages of 6, 12, 24 or 100 or
more, the most efficient package size depends upon consumption
patterns. People who eat only six eggs every two weeks don't need
to buy a dozen at a time. But short-order chefs might go nuts
opening a new box every 12 eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest microprocessors were 4-bit machines and were more
curiosities than useful tools. They were limited to 4 bits because
manufacturers could build only simple circuits efficiently. Now
chip designers are able to build more complex chips, increasing the
number of bits that can be handled at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Using more bits to store each number is a great feature, but it
chews up resources. Doubling the number of bits, from 16 to 32, for
example, in the standard number means that the circuits used to
handle these values must be doubled. That rule holds for most other
parts of the chip, including the temporary storage locations and
the lines used to carry the values around the chip. Some problems
take up even more resources.
</P>
<P>
   So computer manufacturers try to find one size that fits most
users. That is not easy, so the designers try to ease problems and
prevent incompatibilities by finding ways for machines to operate
in different modes. Sixteen-bit machines can act like 32-bit
machines by treating the data as two 16-bit values, then gluing
them together. And 32-bit machines can act like 16-bit machines by
padding the values with 16 extra 0's. In fact, 32-bit machines can
also act like 64-bit machines, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, computer architects are like egg marketers trying to
decide on the right size for packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Any solution that forces a machine to move information in a
nonstandard size makes a computer work more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Intel and Microsoft did not perfectly
synchronize the transition from 16-bit to 32-bit machines. For a
time, Intel's hottest chips were 32-bit, while Microsoft's main
operating system was designed for 16-bit machines. That led to
slower performance on newer, supposedly faster machines because the
chip spent more time converting 16-bit numbers to 32-bit numbers
and back. That anomaly is largely gone, but it may return when
Intel starts adopting 64-bit chips in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics cards used in computers and popular console video
games also measure their capabilities in bits. In that case, the
value refers to the size of the data moved around in the process of
updating, or refreshing, the screen. For larger values, like 64 or
128 bits, larger chunks are moved in each step and the refreshing
process is accomplished faster. Faster means smoother animation and
more time to add slime and green objects to the faces of aliens.
</P>
<P>
   If 64-bit machines are on the horizon, can 128-bit machines be
far behind? Is there anyone who can count that high? Will Bill
Gates ever be that rich? Astronomers might need numbers that high.
There are 1057 atoms in Earth's Sun, and 185 bits would be needed
to count each of them.
</P>
<P>
   But even average humans could need larger numbers if current
trends in the computer industry continue. The number of megabytes
you can get per dollar continues to double every 12 to 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two bits is already not enough to count all the bytes in
the standard-issue 4.3-gigabyte drive. Since each additional bit
doubles the maximum value, it should be about 32 years until 64-bit
machines cannot handle the number of bits in the addresses used for
data by hard disks. Of course, 64 bits should suffice for that
period only if present trends continue, and if Bill Gates doesn't
get much wealthier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
