<HEADER>
A5834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     07-08 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERING THE ART OF FRENCH POLISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: How-to drawing has been sent to NYT graphic and NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (JT)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   French polishing is a classic finishing technique developed by
French furniture makers in the early 19th century. It's a shellac
finish that's applied by rubbing the shellac onto the wood by hand.
The technique is laborious and takes time and practice to master.
Nevertheless it is an essential technique for anyone who wants to
recreate the look of authentic period furniture.
</P>
<P>
   French polishing is done in three stages: filling the wood pores
with paste, applying and polishing the finish and removing residue
oils. While this technique can be applied to any furniture surface,
the beginner should first practice on flat horizontal surfaces,
like table tops, before working on more complex surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve a perfectly smooth surface, it is essential that you
fill the pores of the wood. Traditionally furniture finishers made
their own filler paste by adding pumice to a thick cut of shellac.
</P>
<P>
   To make your own paste filler, dissolve four ounces of shellac
flakes ( available from mail order suppliers) in four ounces of
denatured alcohol. This amounts to an eight-pound cut and it is not
sold in stores, you must mix your own. Add about three ounces of
pumice (available at paint stores) to the shellac solution and stir
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   You will need a stiff-bristled brush, a rubber squeegee and a
few clean cotton cloths for filling. First vacuum the surface to
remove all dust and dirt, then brush on the filler and work it into
wood pores. When the entire surface is covered, scrape across the
grain with a rubber squeegee to remove excess filler. Work quickly
because the shellac has a brief set-up time. For the final cleanup,
dampen a clean cotton cloth with alcohol and wipe the surface using
a circular motion. As the cloth becomes loaded , discard it and use
a fresh cloth.
</P>
<P>
   If making your own pumice/shellac filler sounds too difficult
you can use a commercial wood filler (available at paint stores and
home centers), but the final finish may not be as clear as with the
shellac filler.
</P>
<P>
   After the surface has been allowed to dry (allow at least 24
hours for this), scuff-sand it with 600-grit wet/dry sandpaper. Put
down a few drops of mineral oil as a lubricant and use your hand to
back up the paper. The purpose of the sanding is to remove any
bumps or imperfections in the filler coat and not abrade the
shellac film.
</P>
<P>
   You are now ready to apply the finish. For this you will need a
plastic squeeze bottle filled with shellac (purchase a can of white
shellac in a paint or hardware store), another squeeze bottle
filled with denatured alcohol and a polishing pad.
</P>
<P>
   The polishing pad consists of two parts: an inner core and a
covering. The core is a small wad, about the size of a golf ball,
of cloth. You can use cotton, cheesecloth or flannel for it. Use a
piece of lint-free cloth about 10 inches square for the covering.
Linen or muslin are suitable but avoid using cotton because it will
leave lint.
</P>
<P>
   Place the core in the center of the cover and dampen it with
alcohol. Then squeeze about a thimbleful of shellac into it. Fold
the sides and corners of the cover back over the core and twist
them so the cover tightens around the core. The pad should look
like a soft ball with a twisted handle. The face of the pad should
be smooth with no seams or wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze a little more shellac onto the face of the pad, then
squeeze an equal amount of alcohol. Rub over the entire surface
with small circular stokes. If the pad starts to dry out, squeeze
on more shellac. Sometimes the pad may stick to the surface. If
this happens, apply a few drops of mineral oil and continue
rubbing. Keep rubbing with the pad until the entire surface is
coated with an even film of shellac.
</P>
<P>
   Allow the surface to dry overnight, then repeat the procedure
with a new pad. Only this time, as the pad begins to dry out, do
not recharge it. Use the dry pad to buff the finish. You may use a
few drops of mineral oil if the pad begins to stick. When you have
polished the entire surface, allow it to dry for at least three
days.
</P>
<P>
   The final stage is to remove the any oil deposited in the
polishing stage. Make a round pad of clean cheesecloth and dampen
it with alcohol. Wipe across the surface with light pressure. Keep
the pad moving and do not stop or it may stick to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
