<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM OF MARRIAGE ENDS WITH SHOOTING FOR FIANCEE OF SLAIN AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NATHALIE TREPANIER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Melissa Barela should be planning her wedding
instead of making funeral arrangements for her finace, who was one
of two U.S. Border Patrol agents shot dead Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Salinas, 24, and fellow agent Susan Lynn Rodriguez were
killed helping the police hunt for a man wanted in an earlier
shooting that left a 53-year-old woman and her 31-year-old daughter
dead in the South Texas town of Rio Hondo.
</P>
<P>
   Barela, 23, had known Salinas since she was 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would ever have thought that last night was the last time
I would tell him that I love him,'' Barela said Tuesday night from
the San Antonio-area home of Salinas' parents. ``It just shows you
need to live life to its fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   As visitors gathered at the gray brick home that the Salinas
family has lived in for nine years, Ricardo Salinas Sr. recalled
that his son always had wanted a career in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my pride and joy,'' Salinas said. ``He never got into
any trouble. He was a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Salinas Jr. graduated from Judson High School in 1992.
In 1996, he received a degree in criminal justice from the
University of Texas at San Antonio. While he was happy in the six
months he had been with the Border Patrol, his ultimate goal was to
join the FBI, according to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Barela was concerned the FBI might be too dangerous, but she
knew better than to stand between her fiance and his dream, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Brown arrived at the Salinas family home. As he was
greeted by Ricardo Salinas Sr., the two embraced, tears welling in
their eyes. Brown, 24, was to be the best man at the Salinas-Barela
wedding. The two had known each other since childhood, and Salinas
had even convinced his friend to join the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you still going to do it?'' the slain agent's father asked
Brown. ``Are you still going to join the patrol?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Brown said. ``I'm doing it for him as well as for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas and Barela were planning to marry next year. Both were
children of military officers. They had met as children while their
parents were posted in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Barela sat in the Salinas home on Tuesday, surrounded by family,
friends and two Border Patrol agents. Cradled in her arms was one
of the few pictures ever taken of the two. ``Ricardo hated having
his picture taken,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The man identified as the gunman, Ernest Moore, 24, died in a
Harlingen hospital late Tuesday following surgery for multiple
gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The two women killed in Rio Hondo, a small community northeast
of Harlingen, were identified as Dalia Morin, 31, and her mother,
Margarita Flores, 52. Her son, Danny Morin, 22, was wounded, as was
Cameron County Deputy Sheriff Raul Rodriguez, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 28, was the first woman Border Patrol agent killed on
active duty. Since its founding 74 years ago, 81 agents have been
killed while on duty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1639EDT &QL; 
