<SLUG> BC-CIR-SURF-MONKEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MONKEY BUSINESS IN BROWSER FOR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (Editors: in the 11th graf, the substituted symbols are four
telephone pound signs)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when the phrase ``kid friendly'' actually
referred to something that was fun for kids instead of good for
them. In my own childhood, for instance, I once created what I
considered a kid-friendly ant farm by sprinkling several teaspoons
of sugar onto the front steps.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on that definition, I was excited to hear about a new
software program called Surf Monkey, described as a kid-friendly
browser. I figured that it could teach my daughters to build an ant
farm online.
</P>
<P>
   Surf Monkey is not, in truth, a stand-alone browser; it runs on
top of Microsoft's Internet Explorer, replacing the toolbar and
on-screen window with the image of a rocket ship hurtling through
deep space in search of Web sites. As stars and asteroids whiz by,
my daughters Zoe, 9, and Ella, 7, would be able to click on the
ship's instrument panel to navigate, activating commands like Back
or Forward or Help.
</P>
<P>
   Surf Monkey also has a tour guide, an animated monkey whose job
is to hop around on the bottom of the screen and narrate the
mission. Though no Jane Goodall myself, I respect the fact that
some people think monkeys are charming and so was willing to give
this one the benefit of the doubt. After all, the monkey was able
to perform such useful tricks as reading aloud the text of any
e-mail message, a feature that could alert my kids to any spelling
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Before inviting my daughters to test Surf Monkey, I decided to
install it on my own because software installation has never been
my idea of a kid-friendly activity. Nor was it adult-friendly. The
first time I tried to run Surf Monkey, the program clashed with
Windows 98, prompting my computer to crash after announcing
tragically that ``Surf Monkey caused an invalid page fault in
module KERNEL32.DLL,'' a core chunk of code in the operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   After I restarted the computer, Surf Monkey behaved for a while,
but I was unable to register my review copy. That would have been
fine with me, but the instructions warned that if I skipped that
step, Zoe and Ella could not send e-mail. Getting impatient, I
phoned David Smith, chief executive of Media Live, the company that
makes Surf Monkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is working fine at our end,'' Smith reported.
``Let's try it again.''
</P>
<P>
   After he showed me how to get Surf Monkey on line without
registering, Smith offered to demonstrate the program's finer
points. He guided me to a button on the control panel that would
explode the on-screen image of a Web page and another that would
hurl a blob of green slime across the page. ``Kids like that sort
of thing,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   So do I. In fact, I was just about to summon my daughters for
some family slime hurling when Surf Monkey's dark side surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Smith mentioned that Surf Monkey had licensed the Surf Watch
filter to block what Media Live calls ``unsuitable'' content. He
said that category included pornography, profanity, sexually
explicit language and many other topics. ``Go ahead, try to go to
the Playboy site on line and see what happens,'' he said. Yes, Surf
Monkey blocked me, with an on-screen suggestion to try visiting
someplace else.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Surf Monkey's filter _ unlike the typical
censor-your-child program that some parents buy in a retail store
and load onto the computer _ was unique because it was constantly
updated. Every time a child tries to visit a Web site, the request
is processed through Surf Monkey's computers, which check to see if
the destination is on Surf Watch's blacklist, updated daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The filter works with e-mail, too,'' Smith said. ``Type an
e-mail message with an obvious profanity and then ask the monkey to
read it aloud.'' Sure enough, the monkey refused to speak the
four-letter word I had typed. In fact, the program changed the
letters of the word on-screen as well, substituting
``(NU)(NU)(NU)(NU),'' which the monkey pronounced soberly as
``number-number-number-number.''
</P>
<P>
   I worried that this feature might upset my daughters if they
happened to type a forbidden word. Could fear of displeasing the
monkey prompt ``Planet of the Apes'' nightmares?
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you decide what to censor?'' I asked. ``How many words
are on the list?''
</P>
<P>
   Smith explained that his company had reviewed 2,700 words
blacklisted by Surf Watch and winnowed the list to 1,300 that Media
Live deemed truly objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. As a test, I typed, ``My name is Michelle, and I am gay.''
</P>
<P>
   The monkey said, ``My name is Michelle and I am
number-number-number.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why won't the monkey say `gay'?'' I asked. ``There is nothing
wrong with being gay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ouch,'' Smith said. ```Gay' is not supposed to be blocked.
`Gay' is not a bad word.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll say. In fact, just the previous week I had addressed this
same topic with Zoe and Ella, who had been troubled by a third
grader on the school bus who shrieked ``gay'' as an insult. The
last thing we needed was a painful follow-up discussion about how
some adults can be as bigoted as third-grade bullies. Or monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Smith assured me that the ``gay'' gaffe was a glitch in the
program. But then I learned that Surf Monkey also blocked the word
``breast,'' as in, ``My name is Michelle and I am eating a chicken
number-number-number-number-number-number.'' Who knows how many
other perfectly suitable words are blocked as well?
</P>
<P>
   Surf Monkey illustrates the problem with filters: they transform
``kid friendly'' into ``ignorant.'' Under the guise of protecting
children, filter makers seek to impose their values on my
offspring. I would rather do the child-rearing myself, thanks.
</P>
<P>
   After I got off the phone with Smith, I realized that my only
choice was to censor the censor. I barely had time to remove Surf
Monkey before my daughters came bounding up the staircase.
``Where's the monkey?'' Ella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you're old enough to be exposed to him,'' I
said, shielding the CD-ROM from view. ``He wasn't kid-friendly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
