<SLUG> BC-CREMATION-COMPLAINTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSED CREMATORY CAN'T DISPOSE OF ALL ITS BODIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Stymied at first by the fire department and then
by a state investigation into consumer complaints, the Hidden
Valley Memorial Park crematory is struggling to dispose of its
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, state Department of Consumer Affairs officials said
17 bodies _ some which had been there for more than three weeks _
were cremated at other facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Laurel Rogers, an owner of the Martinez crematory and two other
funeral homes, said the state investigation and newspaper reports
last week had slowed processing of the remaining bodies. She would
not say how many bodies remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several steps for transferring bodies from one place
to another,'' Rogers said. ``And the state wants to see the bodies
and the paperwork, which takes a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to delays is that other crematories in the area are now
reluctant to process the body backlog, said Nancy Luke, a lawyer
representing Rogers and her husband Chris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (others) are understandably worried and reticent because
they don't want to get involved in a scandal that's been in the
papers,'' Luke said. ``Other crematoriums have said they would help
out and then backed out and left (the Rogerses) in the lurch.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Affairs inspectors believe they have seen discrepancies
between the Rogerses' operations and state codes on at least two
occasions, spokeswoman Nancy Hardaker said. Hardaker said that she
could not reveal the nature of the code violations or complaints
until the investigation was completed, and could not estimate when
that might be.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, the Contra Costa County Fire Protection District
temporarily closed Hidden Valley because of a malfunctioning
smokestack. Once repairs were made in late June, fire inspectors
gave the crematory permission to resume business. On June 27,
however, the state asked the Rogerses to keep the business closed
while it conducted a separate investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am doing everything I can to resolve this,'' Laurel Rogers
said. ``The bottom line is that we are good people who have helped
thousands of families and have had thousands of cases and never had
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A Better Business Bureau complaint was lodged against the couple
in February.
</P>
<P>
   California law sets no time frame for the disposition of bodies,
as long as they are stored properly. But Ernest Landauer, spokesman
for the San Francisco Bay Area Funeral Society, said the cremation
process usually takes about seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Landauer said delays not only were difficult on families
emotionally, but also interfered with the administration of bank
accounts, insurance, investments and trusts of the deceased.
</P>
<P>
   If the state investigation reveals code violations, the case
will be filed with the State Justice Department, which in turn
could present the case to an administrative law judge, Hardaker
said. The judge could then impose a range of penalties on the
Rogerses, including suspending or revoking their license, placing
the crematorium on probation or fining them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
