<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SPICE-GIRLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPICE WORLD, LAND OF MISSED OPPORTUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of Ginger Spice's departure from the Spice Girls,
Sony is trotting out Spice World, an interactive piece of
Spice-iana designed for the preadolescent girls who are buying
Spice albums, T-shirts, lip gloss and plastic dolls. At minute 13{
of the fab five's fame, it's now or never.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Spice World (Psygnosis; $29.95; to be released July
28; Playstation) is a make-your-own-music-video project starring
the Spice Girls as cartoon characters with oversize shoes, tiny
bodies and huge heads (this is not a stretch).
</P>
<P>
   In stage one, the Mixing Room, you splice together bits and
pieces of the Spice Girls oeuvre, stringing sound samples into
Cubist versions of their songs. If you're dying to hear a phrase
from ``Wannabe'' (``I'll tell you what I want, what I really really
want!'') 20 times in a row, that's also an option. Somewhere there
is a special hell for parents where this sequence is looped ad
infinitum.
</P>
<P>
   From the Mixing Room you move into Dance Practice, a
choreography tutorial, and hit button combinations as they appear
on the screen to see the full repertory of shimmies, sashays and
shoulder rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have mastered the Spice Girls' moves, it's time to
record their routines by programming their dance steps one by one,
Spice by Spice. Then on to the TV Studio, where you choose camera
angles, zooms and close-ups to show them off. It's a customized
Spice Girls experience, MySpiceGirls, if you will, followed by a
20-minute popumentary _ video footage of the Spice Girls being
interviewed in the South of France _ that is completely
nonparticipatory.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, Spice World is the latest in a series of
interactive music videos and enhanced CDs produced on a variety of
platforms in the last 10 years _ music titles for the Sega CD,
David Bowie's Jump CD-ROM, Devo's Adventures of the Smart Patrol,
interactive offerings from Bob Dylan and Sting, and the list goes
on. All of them combine recycled content with the illusion of
choice, the fake empowerment of mixing your own version of someone
else's music with a keyboard or a joystick.
</P>
<P>
   With the notable exception of Peter Gabriel's Real World CD-ROM,
all these products have fallen flat because they cannot compete
with the albums and music videos they supposedly enhance. What
shows up on your computer monitor is not the beautifully produced
entertainment you see on television, and it doesn't offer the
full-throttle interactivity of a genuine video game. It's a sterile
hybrid that compromises both media. Interactive music videos are
the mules of digital entertainment. To add insult to injury, they
are generally overpriced. At 12 bucks, the Spice Girls game is
cute. But $30? Come on.
</P>
<P>
   It's irksome that Psygnosis should take this bone-headed
approach with Spice World because the company is one of the top
video game developers on the planet. These are the people who gave
us Wipeout XL and Colony Wars. ``The guys had been working on
Porsche Challenge and Total NBA '97,'' said Peter Eley, who managed
the Spice World project at Sony Computer Entertainment Europe in
London. ``At first a lot of them weren't that keen. Some of them
viewed it as a bit of a ludicrous prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   One can almost picture them gazing longingly at their co-workers
play-testing space shooters, then casting a plaintive glance at
their boss. (``No. You cannot work on the new driving game until
you finish Spice World.'') Judging from the final product, it is
obvious that these lads were not applying their talents
wholeheartedly to the joy and wonder that is Spice.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a shame because they have deprived the world of the
Spice Girls interactive experience it really deserves. Think of the
missed opportunities: A Lara Croft adventure game with five pinups
on the screen instead of one. An interactive version of MTV's Spice
Girls vs. Hanson Celebrity Death Match. The Spice Girls can't stop
screaming about Girl Power. Where are the weapons? Sporty Spice
behind the barrel of a semiautomatic machine gun _ that's Girl
Power.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't these designers even bother to rip off Barbie Fashion
Designer? A Spice Girls video game where you can't change their
clothes? Five Spice Girls videos and no costume changes? What were
they thinking?
</P>
<P>
   The video shows them chatting up Nelson Mandela and other world
leaders. ``Meeting Prince Charles and having the opportunity to
squeeze his bum. That is what you remember,'' quoth Ginger Spice.
If Spice World were a role-playing game, that could be her
signature move: bum-squeezing the famous for bonus points. Sporty
could turn back flips. Baby could foil enemies by rapidly batting
her eyelashes. And Posh could suck in her cheeks, unleashing the
Glare of Death. The Spice Girls are comic book characters anyway.
Why not have them act like comic book characters?
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, half of this game's title is ``world.'' There is no
world in this game. There is nothing to explore. This band is
supposedly on an international tour, and backdrops are no big trick
in a video game. But do we get to see the Spice Girls perform in
front of the Forbidden City, in Red Square, along the Amazon, on
the African veldt, against the foothills of the Himalayas? No. And
where is the warren of backstage areas? Where is the inside of the
Spice Girls' bus? Even the movie gave them a more engaging place to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, most girls prefer PC games to console games. And they
prefer the Internet to video games, period. So where is the Spice
Girls 3-D virtual community on the World Wide Web, with all those
preteen-age girls joining little guilds _ the Sporty Zone, the
Scary Zone, Posh.com.
</P>
<P>
   The music is derivative and shallow. The game didn't have to be.
And if it succeeds commercially, it's only because its audience is
all but neglected by digital media. The pickings are anorexically
slim. So much for Girl Power.
</P>
<P>
   Bad job, boys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
