<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-POLLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE POLLING IS MORE BUSINESS THAN SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (JT)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCI issued a press release last week declaring America's
Internet literacy on the upswing. Touting the results of a survey,
MCI heralded baby boomers, Generation X-ers and residents of
Delaware as among the most Net-savvy segments of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the catch: The survey did not test the population at
large, but only regular Web surfers and visitors to the MCI site,
who were presumably already fairly Internet-literate. MCI did not
claim otherwise, but it used a bit of sleight of hand to overstate
the survey as a basis for ``the American public to gauge their `Net
know-how,''' prompting several news outlets to report the findings.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it did not mean for people to misinterpret the
findings as comprehensive. ``The survey is not scientific in any
way,'' conceded an MCI spokeswoman, Mary Matalobos.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberspace is filling up with surveys and polls. In fact, news
junkies can participate in dozens of polls posted on line on any
given day.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, for instance, ABC News polled visitors to its site
on whether they worried about online privacy. CNN's online quick
poll asked if Netizens supported an anti-flag-burning amendment to
the Constitution (as opposed to the ``in-depth'' CNN poll, which
asked about China and democracy).
</P>
<P>
   ESPN queried visitors about who would make it to the finals of
the World Cup; a daily survey by the search engine Excite asked,
``What's gone wrong in fighting Florida's fires?'' and Time
magazine's Web page posed a question about trust and the news
media: ``Whom can you believe anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   All of which raises another question: Which, if any, of these
polls can be taken seriously?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to that is not many, some polling experts say,
because for the most part, the polls are marketing ploys designed
to attract traffic. Getting more poll participants means more page
views and that, in turn, can produce advertising revenue, said Dan
Murphy, director of research and analysis for Relevant Knowledge, a
market research company in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they create polls, they create page views,'' Murphy said,
referring to the number of Web pages that visitors call up. ``It's
methodical. It's a business model.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the sites do not present their polls as anything more
than an unscientific sampling of opinion. The CNN site, for
instance, plainly states that its ``poll is not scientific and
reflects the opinion of those Internet visitors who have chosen to
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the polls' creators say, the polls are meant to be fun.
Scott Woelfel, editor in chief of CNN Interactive, said CNN's polls
gave people the opportunity to express themselves and to see where
other people stand. Tens of thousands participate in CNN's more
popular polls, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woelfel also said that CNN had taken steps to prevent virtual
ballot-box stuffing by making it possible for each individual to
vote only once. That effort took on new importance after an
advocate of nuclear testing by India overwhelmed a CNN poll on the
subject and made it seem as if testing had widespread support.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of skewed results followed an effort by the
radio broadcaster Howard Stern, who urged visitors to the People
Magazine site to vote for ``Hank the Angry Drunken Dwarf'' as the
most beautiful person of the year. Hank crushed Leonardo DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's one person, one vote,'' Woelfel said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Internet presents significant challenges to
prospective pollsters, it offers certain advantages, too. Indeed,
some scientists and polling organizations are seeking to capitalize
on some of the inherent advantages of conducting surveys in
cyberspace, like the medium's wide reach and affordability.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Black International in Rochester, N.Y., the publisher of
the Harris telephone polls, says that online polling, if done
correctly, can be statistically valid.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months, Harris has begun using the Internet to
conduct popular-opinion polls. Leonard Bayer, chief scientist for
Harris, said the company believes that understands the population
on the Net well enough to find samples that are representative of
the population at large. The company is creating a sampling pool of
five million e-mail respondents, which Bayer said would be far
larger than most off-line pools.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was easier to find rare subsets of the population
using the Net because there were so many people to draw from. ``If
we need to reach 10,000 people with a particular medical condition,
say multiple sclerosis, we can do so virtually overnight,'' Bayer
said. Previously, he added, ``it was unaffordable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bayer and others emphasize that there was a major difference
between a study that sought to survey a representative sample and a
mere popular opinion poll. ``You can't just hang out a couple of
questions, say, about which university has the best fight song and
expect it to be representative,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
