<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Hidden Thing''
</P>
<P>
   By Athol Dickson
</P>
<P>
   Zondervan, $12.99
</P>
<P>
   Dallas writer Athol Dickson likes his theology front-and-center;
``Every Hidden Thing'' is a Christian mystery _ no doubt about it.
But that forthrightness doesn't mean that this author/architect
won't sneak up and whack you upside the head with his plot when you
aren't looking.
</P>
<P>
   When gunfire at an East Texas hospital leaves an abortionist
wounded and a Roman Catholic priest dead, the devout wife of
contractor Garrison Reed is the prime suspect. Worse, Mary Jo
disappears while out on bail, leaving her new-believer husband to
wrestle with a grotesque and violent web of circumstances, as well
as doubts about his faith and marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Hidden Thing,'' a sequel to 1996's ``Whom Shall I
Fear?,'' gathers elements as disparate as abortion, religious
fanaticism, cancer and voodoo (yes, voodoo) and melds them into a
darkly effective tale. And don't think that the revelation of who
shot Melvin Milo and Michael McKay is the biggest surprise in
Dickson's repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jesus Record''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Mullins &AMP; a Ragamuffin Band
</P>
<P>
   Myrrh Records
</P>
<P>
   Nine days before he died in a car accident, Rich Mullins sat
down in an old, abandoned church and, accompanied only by an
acoustic guitar and piano, sang nine songs into a cheap
battery-powered cassette recorder.
</P>
<P>
   For that, we can be thankful.
</P>
<P>
   The nine songs were part of a 10-song project Mullins was
calling ``The Jesus Record.'' The plan was to go into the studio
later and record them with a full band.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he never made it into the studio is tragic for
Christian music fans. When we lost Mullins, we lost the pre-eminent
songwriter of our time. Nobody matched him for the depth and
intensity of feeling of his lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   But at least we have this two-disc album.
</P>
<P>
   The first disc consists of the demos Mullins recorded in the
church. The second features the same songs recorded by his group,
the Ragamuffin Band, with guest vocalists including Michael W.
Smith, Ashley Cleveland, Phil Keaggy and Amy Grant.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to listen to this CD without feeling a tug of
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain sense of melancholy in hearing the rough
recording of Mullins singing in the church, knowing that these are
his last songs. And also in listening to the finished songs.
Although the guest vocalists are uniformly excellent _ especially
Cleveland on Jesus _ there is a feeling of regret that it's not
Mullins himself.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, the emotions come from the lyrics themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Mullins will be missed. But we can be thankful he left us
this parting gift.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
