<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-KEYBOARDS-2TAKES-     07-08 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KEYBOARDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT STRANGE KEYBOARD ISN'T BROKEN, JUST REDESIGNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (editors: sidebar at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH QUILTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who experience wrist or forearm pain from using computers
often welcome the idea of so-called ergonomic keyboards, which are
supposed to reduce the risk of injury and increase comfort. But do
they really help prevent repetitive stress injury, known as RSI?
And if so, which ones are best?
</P>
<P>
   With the widespread use of personal computers, the incidence of
repetitive stress injuries has greatly increased, and the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration calls RSI one of the
fastest-growing workplace injuries.
</P>
<P>
   RSI is an umbrella term for many injuries caused by overuse of
the nerves, muscles and tendons; the ailments include carpal tunnel
syndrome, tendinitis and trigger finger, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the risk factors for RSI _ including typing speed,
repetition, poor posture, sedentary behavior, poor technique, too
much force and awkward positioning _ is informative. Changing the
angle of the keyboard will help with awkward positioning, but it
won't solve any of the other problems, and therefore can be of only
limited use in preventing injuries.
</P>
<P>
   And as problematic as the keyboard is, many ergonomists consider
its alternative, the mouse, to be far more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that better engineering won't vastly improve
the standard keyboard, which has many faults. It forces users to
put their wrists into a palms-down position (the medical term is
pronation). It encourages the user to make a sideways twist of the
wrist to reach the Enter key (called ulnar deviation) and to take
the bent-wrist position of a police officer halting traffic (called
dorsiflexion).
</P>
<P>
   The standard keyboard also has a right-hand bias: the number pad
and important keys are placed on that side, forcing overuse in what
for most people is the dominant hand. In addition, many frequently
used keys, like Enter, Shift, Backspace and Control, are placed
near the weakest finger, the pinkie. The space bar taxes the thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Certain keyboards billed as ergonomic address some of these
problems, but many merely place the keys in two angled banks with
few other improvements. Labeling an input device ``ergonomic'' can
be a lot like calling a food loaded with sugar, salt and fat
``natural.'' Some accessories bearing this term are in fact not
useful in preventing injuries and can actually promote problems.
</P>
<P>
   When choosing a keyboard, here are features to look for:
</P>
<P>
   _ True split. Some keyboards _ like the Microsoft Natural
Keyboard, Kinesis Maxim, Kinesis Ergonomic, and Pace _ separate
keys into two banks with space in between, but they are fixed in
place. This arrangement may work if your dimensions happen to fit
that keyboard, but may not split widely enough apart if you are
broad-shouldered. When the keyboard is actually split into two
separate pieces, as with the IBM Options keyboard, you can position
the banks where you want them. Sometimes, professional assistance
from a doctor or therapist may help in the positioning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Angle rotation. The shallow V-shaped angle on some ergonomic
keyboards is intended to help users avoid twisting their wrists to
the side. On some keyboards, the angle is fixed; others allow
infinite adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tilt. The upward tilt toward the middle keys helps to move the
hand out of an extreme palms-down position and into a less
stressful, near-handshake posture. Touch-typists will have an
easier time using this feature than those who hunt and peck.
</P>
<P>
   _ Layout of keys, especially function and edit keys.
</P>
<P>
   _ Springy ``end feel.'' A great deal of cumulative force runs
through your fingers, especially if you pound the keyboard. Keys
that give slightly as you press them help soften the landing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Feedback, meaning that the user feels the key give or click to
the touch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Detachable number pad. Lefties (and righties who want to
distribute hand work more evenly between two hands) can move the
number pad to the left side. Or if you rarely use these keys, you
may exclude it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Streamlined design. Many of the newer ergonomic keyboard
designs are quite large or are mounted on platforms, which may make
them awkwardly high. Before making any purchase, consider whether
your current platform is wide enough to accommodate both the
keyboard and the mouse at a comfortable height.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good hand-to-key fit. Hands, like feet, come in all shapes and
widths. Key design varies subtly from maker to maker; notice
whether one keyboard allows more comfortable spacing for your hand
span than another.
</P>
<P>
   _ System compatibility. Some keyboards work only with PCs, not
with Macs.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting again that keyboards are only one aspect of
an ergonomically sound workplace. Adjustable keyboard holders,
light sources and chairs are also elements of a well-thought-out
computer set-up.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some keyboards that offer useful ergonomic
features:
</P>
<P>
   IBM OPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   This keyboard, which was formerly known as the Lexmark and is no
longer manufactured, had an intelligent design. The right and left
key banks were separated in two distinct pieces, and feet on the
midsection allowed upward tilt. Keys were arranged so that work was
more evenly distributed between both hands: the left space bar
could be used either as Delete key or for spacing, and there were
cursor keys on both banks. The Options keyboard had a detachable
number pad so you could use either hand for this function.
</P>
<P>
   If you were using the number pad exclusively, as an accountant
might, you could move the keyboard out of the way and place it
directly under your hand. (Depending on the software, this may not
be applicable.) More important, if you rarely used the number pad,
you could remove it entirely, freeing up valuable space. Word
Perfect users were often annoyed to find the F7 key on the
left-hand side of the board, but users quickly became accustomed to
it. The keyboard was simple to install _ you just plugged it in.
</P>
<P>
   A similar keyboard with some new features will be available in
September from Goldtouch Technologies. (Goldtouch Keyboard, for PC
only, $99; www.goldtouch. com; (800) 593-2453.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a keyboard is akin to buying a pair shoes _ to insure
the right fit, you need to try it out first. To get a better sense
of a new keyboard, sit down and position yourself properly as you
type. If possible, buy from a vendor that accepts returns. That
way, you can try the keyboard out on your own desk.
</P>
<P>
   Take your time as you test. Different angles and key locations
may take getting used to; avoid buying or using a new keyboard
under time pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Trust your instincts. If a keyboard causes pain or strain the
moment you try it, don't buy it thinking you'll adjust to it later.
</P>
<P>
   Don't try to solve a medical problem with an ergonomic gadget.
If you are experiencing soreness, fatigue, tingling, clumsiness or
other signs of RSI, see a good doctor immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
