<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUCLEAR STORAGE SITE IN WEST TEXAS `VERY MUCH ALIVE,' AGENCY HEAD
SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Maine and Vt.) 
(See optional trim) 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The head of the state agency charged with
disposing of low-level nuclear waste predicted Wednesday that a
storage site near Sierra Blanca will eventually be approved,
despite an unexpected setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this thing is very much alive,'' said Lawrence Jacobi
Jr., general manager of the Texas Low-level Radioactive Waste
Disposal Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think yesterday's ruling was just a bump in the road to
success.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, two administrative law judges who had conducted 10
weeks of technical hearings recommended against issuing an
operating license for the project in the West Texas desert.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobi said his agency, which would operate the facility, will
appeal the recommendation to the three-member Texas Natural
Resource Conservation Commission, which can accept or reject the
judges' findings. TNRCC is expected to rule by this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The administrative judges cited two factors in their opposition
to the facility. They said the waste disposal authority hadn't
adequately determined whether a geological fault at the proposed
site posed an environmental risk.
</P>
<P>
   They also said the agency hadn't adequately answered questions
about the socio-economic impact on Sierra Blanca, a small, isolated
town about 90 miles southeast of El Paso. Sierra Blanca already
disposes of sewage sludge from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobi said evidence presented to the judges had proved
``conclusively that the fault is not a problem.'' He noted that the
judges had ruled in the agency's favor on 15 other issues
considered in the application.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the evidence is sufficient to support the
application,'' said Bill Dugat III, a private attorney representing
the waste disposal agency.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear disposal facility is backed by utilities and medical
centers that generate radioactive waste. Texas also has plans to
accept waste from Maine and Vermont, which are decommissioning
nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal has drawn opposition from some Sierra Blanca
residents, environmentalists and some Mexican officials. The site
is about 16 miles north of the Rio Grande River.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC staff has issued an environmental assessment that
concluded that the license should be granted. All three members of
the TNRCC are appointees of Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he doesn't want to proceed with the project if it
is determined to be unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the TNRCC to ``thoroughly review this recommendation
and the facts and to make their decision based on sound science and
the health and safety of Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Democratic challenger Garry Mauro, who opposes the
disposal site, called on Bush to urge his appointees to the panel
to vote against the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two independent hearing examiners have confirmed what a lot of
us have been saying. You don't put a radioactive waste disposal
site near a geological fault with strong earthquake potential,''
Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the $34 million Sierra Blanca site to begin
accepting waste in 2000 for disposal in concrete canisters that are
to be placed in deep trenches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
