<HEADER>
A5943 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ONLINE-MUSIC-2TAK     07-08 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-MUSIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARIETY AND PRICES DRAW MUSIC FANS TO WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Auman has stopped wolfing down his lunch. He used to spend
his meal break in the music marts of Raleigh, N.C., hunting for
hard-to-find compact disks by Yes and the other progressive-rock
bands he enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of scarfing a sandwich on the run, Auman, a
28-year-old network administrator, munches in front of his computer
while shopping at CDnow, a huge music boutique located solely on
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blockbuster Musics and Wal-Marts have billions of copies
of whatever is in the Top 40, but I'm usually going for the more
obscure stuff,'' said Auman, who figures that 10 percent of the 500
CD's in his collection have been ordered from CDnow.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone in turning to the Internet to satisfy his
musical needs. While music sales nationwide through online
retailers will reach only $81 million this year, according to
Jupiter Communications, a new-media research company in New York,
they are expected to grow to $1.1 billion in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   On-line music retailers are essentially mail-order vendors who
post interactive catalogs on the Web. Those catalogs are searchable
databases attached to distribution and credit-card billing systems;
orders may also be placed by phone. Auman occasionally pays extra
for overnight delivery so a hot new release can be delivered to his
desk before Raleigh's stores open.
</P>
<P>
   On-line music stores can offer a vast selection, long lists of
CD's that would dwarf most real-world inventories. The entries are
often supplemented with song titles and cover art. Even ardent fans
may be surprised by the availability of imported recordings and
other rarities by their favorite performers.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit can be price: the time spent waiting for music
to arrive in the mail is often offset by attractive Web prices. An
informal survey of eight music retailers, four on line and four off
line, showed that a trio of chart-topping disks bought from CDnow,
Music Boulevard or Amazon.com was as much as 4 percent cheaper than
the same albums purchased at the lowest-cost chain store, once
shipping charges and sales taxes were factored in.
</P>
<P>
   But every music vendor's prices fluctuate regularly, especially
with sales on current hits. It pays to shop around: choose several
sites and open a browser window for each site, then register at
each, pick identical items and choose the store with the lowest
price. The options include Sound Stone  &UR; (www.soundstone.com) &LR; ,
Tower Records  &UR; (www.towerrecords. &LR;   &UR; com) &LR; , Total E of Columbia
House  &UR; (www.totale.com) &LR;  and Tunes.com  &UR; (www.tunes.com) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Virtual merchants also capitalize on the Web's multimedia
capabilities by offering hundreds of thousands of 30-second song
snippets that encourage you to sample before you buy. Auman said he
had been inspired to buy a John Wetton album _ a disk he would
never have found at a Tower Records listening station _ after
sampling its tracks on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In online music catalogs, as in any database, accuracy is
critical for conducting searches. An errant keystroke can alter
results _ is that band's name Figdish or Fig Dish? (It is the
latter.) Nor should the data necessarily be trusted; two sites list
``Some Girls,'' a 1978 Rolling Stones album, as having been
released in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a database by itself is valuable, as is the case with
the Global Electronic Music Marketplace  &UR; (www.gemm.com) &LR; , a
clearinghouse for used, out-of-print and esoteric recordings that
is little more than an enormous text-based registry. Other online
retailers routinely decorate their shops by adding digital bells
and whistles, typically including album recommendations meant to
spur further buying.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers truly seeking guidance should turn to specialty
retailers like Descarga, a Latin-music purveyor in Brooklyn that
opened its Web site  &UR; (www.descarga.com)  &LR; in June.
</P>
<P>
   Or they might consider returning to the real world. Chicago
Compact Disc in Evanston, Ill., had the highest prices of the eight
sites participating in the informal survey. But its owner, Michael
Bernard, has been selling used CD's to this collector for nearly a
decade. Asked to suggest a new disk he thought I might like, he
immediately volunteered a recently reissued Miles Davis title. ``I
don't even have to think about it,'' Bernard said. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   WWW.CDNOW.COM
</P>
<P>
   What led to the start of CDnow was the passion of Jason Olim,
the company's co-founder and chief executive, for the music of
Miles Davis. After hearing the trumpeter's ``Kind of Blue'' in
1988, he went to a nearby music store. ``I asked them, `What can
you recommend?''' Olim recalled, ``and the answer I got was, `Oh,
Miles Davis is in the jazz section.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Olim and his twin brother, Matthew, now 29, opened CDnow on
the Web in October 1994, their goal was to build a music store
where the virtual staff was well prepared for that sort of inquiry.
Like its rivals, CDnow maintains an editorial team to write
articles and reviews (invariably positive) and to compile buyer's
guides on genres like Celtic music. And more content is coming from
sources like the archives of Rolling Stone magazine.
</P>
<P>
   A central feature of the site is the Audio Advisor, which
recommends other titles based on the preferences of like-minded
listeners. For fans of ``Kind of Blue,'' CDnow's somewhat odd
suggestions include albums by Eric Clapton, Bob Dylan and
Radiohead, as well as an apt tip for Thelonious Monk.
</P>
<P>
   CDnow has a workmanlike interface, and registering at the site
is a snap (as it was for all the services reviewed here). Shipping
costs $2.99 for the first CD, plus 99 cents for each additional CD;
the maximum fee is $4.97. Sales tax is collected for California,
Florida, New Jersey and Pennsylvania, where the company is based.
</P>
<P>
   CDnow says it offers 250,00 titles and 315,000 audio clips. Like
Music Boulevard, it sells a few exclusives, like a limited-edition
disk of remixed tunes by David Byrne, former leader of the Talking
Heads.
</P>
<P>
   While sample sound clips are offered for some albums on CDnow,
many albums have none. That is particularly true for classical
music; half-minute clips rarely do justice to an hourlong concerto.
Also, none of the sites have a search engine that works well for
classical titles, an impression confirmed when a quest for Bartok's
``Music for Strings, Percussion and Celesta'' confounded the CDnow
software.
</P>
<P>
   CDnow's customer-service area invites visitors to e-mail
inquiries to its staff of experts. After three days, a question
about a Charlie Palmieri-arranged album by Cal Tjader, a cool-jazz
vibraphonist, drew this response: ``I have not yet had the
opportunity to listen to `Primo,' so I am unable to tell you if you
will like it or not. Also, I think that only you can be the true
judge of what music you will like.'' Compare that with the response
from a specialty site, Descarga. Bruce Polin, Descarga's founder,
sent this message: `` `Primo' is not a typical Tjader release. . .
. It's a classic that smokes from beginning to end. `Mama Guela' is
worth the price alone.'' Polin's expertise comes at a premium:
Descarga charges $15.98 for the disk; at CDnow, it's $11.49.
</P>
<P>
   WWW.MUSICBLVD.COM
</P>
<P>
   Music Boulevard is a nice ride if you are willing to tolerate
the speed limit. With its colorful graphics and glossy black
backdrops, the site creates a visually appealing environment, a
Barneys among two Bloomingdale's and a Kmart. The trade-off is the
wait while the graphics-rich pages load.
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1996, Music Boulevard carries 260,000 titles and
provides 350,000 audio clips. On-screen annotation comes from the
All-Music Guide, among other sources, but large amounts of original
content can be found by following the links to Classical Insites,
Jazz Central Station and Rocktropolis, genre-specific sites also
operated by N2K, Music Boulevard's parent, based in Manhattan. One
oddity: despite the company's attention to classical music, the
search function does not permit hunting for compositions by name.
</P>
<P>
   Music Boulevard offered a few more sound samples and
consistently lower prices _ this week, anyway _ on an offbeat array
of 10 titles, like NRBQ's ``Tapdancin' Bats.'' Shipping is $2.49
for the first item and 49 cents for the next, but a total of only
99 cents for three or more. Taxes are assessed in Pennsylvania,
California and New York. Repeat customers are rewarded with a free
CD after buying 10.
</P>
<P>
   Good customer service is essential for online retailers. When a
CD arrived with a cracked case, I wrote to Music Boulevard via
e-mail. Just as when I placed my order, my message was immediately
acknowledged. Four days later, the company informed me that a
replacement had been shipped; three days after that, it was
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   I also got an explanatory note intended for another customer.
Wild, I hope your problem was solved, too.
</P>
<P>
   WWW.AMAZON.COM
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com has been selling books on the Web since 1995, but its
music site is the new kid on the block, appearing just last month.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its well-developed literary counterpart, the music area
remains very much a work in progress. The look is simple, the
recommendation system is in its early stages, and plans for a
classical section are still being drafted. At the moment, the site
also has the dinkiest selection, a mere 125,000 titles and 225,000
clips. Shipping is $2 per order, plus 95 cents per item, and taxes
are levied on residents of Washington State (the company is based
in Seattle).
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com deserves praise for its search engine, which yielded
a recording by the Three Baritone Saxophone Band that other sites
did not when queried with the word ``baritone.'' Similarly, the
site's song-title search is also the most effective, a useful
feature for those who are unable to identify a tune heard on the
radio _ you know, the one with the chorus that goes ``something,
something, mmm, hmm . . . baby!'' Only on the Amazon.com site did a
search on ``corner'' lead to Creedence Clearwater Revival's ``Down
on the Corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing review excerpts from about a dozen
publications, Amazon.com allows visitors to sound off about
recordings. While these comments are rarely illuminating, they can
be entertaining, as in this analysis of a new release by Master P:
``Could've been better, but could've been much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   WWW.GEMM.COM
</P>
<P>
   When a friend's romantic relationship ended recently, she lost
more than a beau. A treasured CD by Timbuk 3 also vanished from her
life. The disk was not available at several music sites on line,
but rather than scour the used-CD bins, she searched the Global
Electronic Music Marketplace's listings. Six entries popped up,
ranging in price from $7.95 to $35.66.
</P>
<P>
   The credit goes to Roger Raffee's mom. When Raffee decided to
unload his vinyl LP's in 1994, his mother suggested that he meet
with Jim Hall, a programmer, about cataloguing the collection on a
PC. Over dinner, the pair hatched a plan for an open marketplace on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Born as a bulletin board system, GEMM hit the Web that fall. It
has become a huge online flea market with 1,500 retailers selling
everything from old 45's and posters to new-release CD's and
concert videos.
</P>
<P>
   The GEMM database has an astounding 2.7 million items, although
entries from different merchants for the same title do pad that
count. ``I'm pretty sure we've got everything CDnow, Amazon and all
the other music sites combined have _ and a heck of a lot more,''
Raffee said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its unrefined appearance, GEMM's functions are quite
polished, enabling users to customize their searches by filtering
out, say, older disks, imports or any item that costs more than
$12. Buyers can order through the site, operated from San Diego, or
get in contact with the seller directly, possibly avoiding a
commission of up to 15 percent that GEMM sometimes collects. GEMM's
site is devoid of news, commentary and audio clips, although there
are easy-to-follow links to noisier locales, and the text-heavy
look derives too clearly from the site's bulletin-board roots. Hall
promised a graphics update soon.
</P>
<P>
   But the blend of used CD's, vintage vinyl and unusual
memorabilia is a collector's dream. Raffee said he regularly
received e-mail messages of thanks for fulfilling decades-old
desires, like an unused ticket from a Beatles concert at Shea
Stadium. Because GEMM is not the actual retailer, it monitors
sellers to make sure that transactions actually take place. Raffee
said only five vendors had been banned from the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seduced by Money,'' a power-pop CD by the Thieves, has long
been on this writer's wish list, but GEMM did not have it. Ever
mindful of the vagaries of data entry, I tried again after
reversing the middle vowels in ``Thieves.'' The out-of-print disk
was delivered Monday, a week after it was ordered.
</P>
<P>
   On a lark, I also tried the site's ``best price'' filter to look
for the same three chart-topping titles I had used to test the
other sites. GEMM directed me to a site that beat all the others
 &UR; (www.cdcellar.com) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
