r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEDOPHILE-PRIEST-LAIC     07-08 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEDOPHILE-PRIEST-LAICIZED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN LAICIZES PRIEST CONVICTED OF SEXUAL ABUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rudolph ``Rudy'' Kos is no longer a priest, and the convicted
pedophile can no longer be involved in Catholic Church ministry of
any kind, the Vatican has decided.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a request from the Catholic Diocese of Dallas, the
Vatican has taken the rare step of returning Kos to lay status. The
action cannot be reversed, and Kos has no course of appeal, canon
law experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Kos' ordination was not nullified, which is a more extreme
measure, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it happened,'' said the Rev. Robert Williams, who
served with Kos at a church in Ennis, Texas. ``He was an affront to
everything the priesthood is about. He violated the priesthood in
every way he could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican's action prohibits Kos from being called ``father''
or ``reverend,'' although he can remain a Catholic, officials said.
It also relieves the Dallas Diocese of financial responsibility for
Kos if he is ever released from prison, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this action will bring some closure for the victims and
their families as well as for all of us,'' Bishop Charles V.
Grahmann of Dallas said in a written statement Tuesday. ``This
forced laicization sends a definitive signal that the Diocese of
Dallas will make every effort to see that this abuse does not occur
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Kos is serving a life sentence at a prison in Huntsville, Texas.
He was convicted of molesting four boys more than 1,350 times
between 1987 and 1992, while he was assigned to St. Luke's Catholic
Church in Irving and St. John's Catholic Church in Ennis.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old inmate apparently does not know of the Vatican's
decision, friends said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In an April interview after his criminal trial, Kos said of his
priesthood, ``They can't ever take that away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kos was suspended from priestly functions and benefits in 1993,
shortly after accusations surfaced that he had molested altar boys
at three area churches between 1981 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the boys sued. In July 1997, a civil jury awarded
$119.6 million in damages to 10 former altar boys and the parents
of an 11th who committed suicide. The amount of the damages was the
largest ever against a diocese. Three plaintiffs have settled for
$7.5 million, and the remaining eight are close to reaching a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the diocese filed a petition seeking to nullify
Kos' ordination. Nullification, which is rarely used in
disciplining priests, would have meant that Kos was never a validly
ordained priest.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the Vatican told diocese officials that a
unilateral laicization was a faster course to remove Kos from the
priesthood, and the diocese resubmitted the required paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``The civil and criminal trials made it clear how much he
deceived and defrauded the diocese about his lifestyle,'' Monsignor
John Bell, the diocese's chancellor and judicial vicar, wrote in
the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The action was taken June 26 while Grahmann was in Rome to
report on the Dallas Diocese.
</P>
<P>
   Unilateral laicization means that Kos is returned to the status
of a lay person and cannot administer the sacraments, Williams
said. Priests can request laicization, but it is unusual for a
bishop to seek it for another priest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kos' removal is the second of its kind in a month in the
United States. A 62-year-old retired Boston priest was laicized in
June. He was accused of sexual abuse, an official with a Catholic
publication said. No criminal charges were pursued, but a
settlement was reached, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Genny Carder of Irving, a friend of Kos' who testified on his
behalf at his criminal trial, voiced her anger at his removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's quite right. I think he is a priest, and
I think he always will be,'' Carder said. ``He has my total support
and, yes, he still is my priest.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
