<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-CRIMES09-COX     07-08 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEARFUL DAUGHTER OF JASPER VICTIM BACKS NEW HATE CRIMES LAW
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just a month after the racially motivated murder of
her father in Jasper, Texas, a tearful Renee Mullins urged the U.S.
Senate on Wednesday to strengthen federal enforcement of hate
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Her delicate voice and compassionate words brought several
people in the hearing room to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all citizens to pray for these individuals who have
such low self-esteem and who are so full of fear and hatred that
they are cut out from the happiness of life,'' Mullins said,
referring to the three white men who allegedly chained her father
to the back of a pickup truck and dragged him more than two miles
until his head and one arm were ripped from his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brutal murder of my father, James Byrd, Jr. is for us a
tragedy that we have only begun to experience. I cannot get over
the horrid and deeply felt hatred of how he died,'' she said.
Mullins then began to cry softly and apologized for her emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins, 27, and other witnesses testified before the Senate
Judiciary Committee in favor of a measure that would broaden the
federal statute against hate crimes to include those based on
gender, sexual orientation or disability. It would also make it
easier to prosecute hate crimes federally, by relaxing the rules on
which cases qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passing this bill into law would give some mercy for my family
and for the families of future victims of such horrible crimes,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The new measure was introduced by Sens. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,
Ron Wyden, D-Ore., and Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal law covers hate crimes based on race, religion
or national origin, and includes restrictions, such as the crime
must occur while a victim is exercising a federally protected
right.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the current laws are so restrictive that federal
prosecutors have had to decline prosecution in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bill does not undermine the role of states in
investigating and prosecuting hate crimes. It simply closes the
loops in the federal law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Byrd's death may not qualify for federal
prosecution because he was just walking down the street and not
exercising a federally protected right, Widen said.
</P>
<P>
   Several racial minority groups _ including the National Council
of La Raza and the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People _ submitted statements Wednesday strongly supporting
the changes in the statute.
</P>
<P>
   Although the House has scheduled a hearing on a similar measure
for July 22, the bill could have problems passing because of the
provision to add crimes based on hatred of someone's sexual
preference.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian groups are aggressively lobbying in favor of the
measure, and conservative groups are reacting accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement distributed outside the hearing room, the
Traditional Values Coalition said that ``President Clinton and his
leftist cronies'' are ``capitalizing on the recent atrocities in
Jasper, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Sheldon, executive director of the group, said that the
homosexual community, which has failed to gain society's acceptance
for their chosen behavior, is trying to gain acceptance through the
force of law.
</P>
<P>
   Wyden said the bill should not be a referendum on homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is about deterring criminal violence,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Mullins thanked the nation for all the prayers
being delivered to her family and said she will overcome the tragic
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot to live for and many more accomplishments to
achieve, to continue to be _ in spirit _ the sparkle in my father's
eyes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a Jasper County grand jury indicted the three men
accused of kidnapping and killing Byrd. The three men could be
executed if convicted of capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   John William King, 23, of Jasper; Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31,
of Sulphur Springs; and Shawn Allen Berry, 23, of Jasper are being
held without bond in what authorities say was a racially motivated
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles said the earliest possible
trial date is January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
