<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5994 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-SURF09-COX     07-08 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-SURF09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE ENDLESS WAIT
 &HT;    By PAUL REID
 &HT;    c. 1998 Palm Beach Post/Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meet Don French _ retailer, world traveler, homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   Surfer.
</P>
<P>
   He's been surfing Florida beaches for 28 years. That means he
knows what it's like to be a Chicago Cubs fan, knows how an
astronomer feels after a lifetime of looking for alien life forms.
</P>
<P>
   It means French knows how to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred miles of sandy beach from Jacksonville to
Hollywood sings a siren song for surfers. Azure waves lap every
inch of that beach. But that's the problem for Don French, surfer.
</P>
<P>
   Florida waves lap.
</P>
<P>
   They don't roll too often, are not swell swells, do not crash
with the power and grace of a Pacific monster wave upon the north
shore of Oahu, where French just spent two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   They lap. That's why our beaches are crowded with happy
swimmers, sunbathers, treasure hunters wielding metal detectors.
And surfers, many surfers. Frustrated surfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go to the beach to enjoy the breeze, the clouds,
the sand underfoot. It's all there and it's beautiful,'' says
French, owner of Ocean Magic surf shop in Jupiter. ``You have to
appreciate the whole show, because if you go only to surf, you'll
be disappointed more often than not.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida surfing means shelving any dream of the perfect wave.
Any wave will do. During the high season of Florida surfing _
October through April _ French and his surfing buddies feel lucky
if they get 10 great surfing days. Last year they got two.
</P>
<P>
   Florida hosts the endless beach, the endless summer and, for
surfers, the endless wait. That's because the sandbar we call
Florida slopes so gently under the Atlantic that a 3-foot drop in
the sea level would extend our coastline out for miles, to where it
was 11,000 years ago, before the glaciers melted. The gentle slope
of our shore knocks down big ocean waves. That and a paucity of
good coves makes for inconsistent surfing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Volcanic regions, like Hawaii, stick right up out of the open
ocean and capture passing swells. That's perfection. But what
Florida lacks in geological necessities it makes up for _ on
occasion _ with meteorological fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   An offshore storm can kick up good rollers, French says, but if
the storm is too far offshore and the winds from the south or
southeast, the Bahamas will knock the waves down.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes are a surfer's friend, but only if the eye of the
storm is just far enough away and comes up the coast just far
enough offshore to send breakers our way without sending a wicked
storm surge. A 12-foot storm surge sounds good on paper but will
more than likely be the last ride a surfer takes.
</P>
<P>
   Nor'easters make for more chop than swells, but they sure can
kick up the surf, making for wild rides and broken boards, to say
nothing of bones. Trouble is, nor'easters are a winter phenomenon.
Summer offers little or no relief for the waiting surfer.
</P>
<P>
   The best waves come when autumn and winter Canadian cold fronts
push cool air from the west and ocean rollers from the north.
That's when Reef Road in Palm Beach becomes as good a surfing beach
as any in Fiji, Barbados or Costa Rica, says French.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part during surfing season it's wait, wait,
wait for waves that rarely come. During the summer it's an endless
wait, like in war and baseball where long periods of immense
boredom are punctuated by moments of sheer terror or exhilaration _
except Florida's summer surfers experience long periods of boredom
punctuated by brief periods of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes the wait is rewarded by brief shock waves of
adrenalin when surfers spy far offshore the quivering crest of an
incoming gently curved, perfectly glassy roller.
</P>
<P>
   Good things sometimes come to surfers who wait, especially if
they wait at the Sebastian inlet, about 40 miles south of
Melbourne. That's surfing central for Florida surfers. National
champions Kelly Slater and Lisa Anderson hail from the Cocoa
Beach-Melbourne-Sebastian area.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Jon surf shop in Cocoa Beach draws surfers from all over the
Southeast. Melbourne is home to numerous surfing boutiques: Find a
dedicated surfer in the waves off Sebastian and there's a good
chance he made his own board in his own store.
</P>
<P>
   And when the wind is out of the west and the waves out of the
northeast, you'll find all those Sebastian denizens at Reef Road. A
natural cove augmented by two jetties, Reef Road beach offers
incoming waves the perfect venue for rolling in with perfect form.
You don't want to see white caps on the horizon, says French. You
want to see breakers waiting until they reach the beach to break.
That's what you'll see at Reef Road on a good day.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also see Palm Beach police ticketing surfers' cars
because there's no parking hard by Reef Road. Good waves mean a
boost in local enforcement revenues.
</P>
<P>
   And a boost in morale for Don French. And for all the surfers up
and down the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Guys such as Palm Beach architect Harry Gilbert, who has surfed
the world for 30 years and is not above rolling up the blueprints
and locking up the shop when the waves are right. And Bryon Rivers,
a writer for this newspaper who can smell good waves from his
windowless cubicle. And Danny Beaudoin, a Lake Worth native and
acoustic ceiling installer who has been known to be late for work
because the ocean has called.
</P>
<P>
   Beaudoin bought his custom-made board from Dave Freidank,
another Lake Worth lad for whom life does not exist west of the
mean high tide line. Freidank builds his boards at his shop, Blue
Earth Surfboards. His motto: Pray for surf.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing's still mostly a guy sport, 8 to 1 ratio, says French.
But it's a good way to meet girls, and other new friends, for the
simple reason that people on the beach have to talk about something
when faced with indeterminate waits.
</P>
<P>
   For those who elect not to socialize while they wait for the
perfect wave, French suggests some beach reading. Something long.
Such as ``Moby Dick.'' It's a good lesson in patience and
determination, says French.
</P>
<P>
   Just like waiting for the perfect Florida wave.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-08-98 1118E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
