A6000 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLIONAIRE09-COX     07-08 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The guy next door might be a millionaire
 &HT;    By Scott Shepard and David Gulliver
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ He drives a Mercury Sable wagon, with three
hubcaps and probably some junk in the back. His designer label is
more likely to be Levi than Armani, and for lunch, the $5 salad,
thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Burton R. Saidel, the millionaire next door.
</P>
<P>
   Saidel is a dentist, not a stockbroker or a lawyer or a
high-tech whiz. He's not big on trappings of success. But through
hard work and smart investing the Dayton, Ohio, resident has built
a small fortune, and probably given one away as well.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the thousands of Americans who see themselves not
as tycoons, but as ordinary working folks who have gained financial
security through frugality and prudent investing.
</P>
<P>
   And he is part of a group that has economists, sociologists and
demographers scrambling for new definitions of what it means to be
wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   In their recent best-seller, ``The Millionaire Next Door,''
co-authors William Danko and Thomas Stanley found that many
millionaires in America today live rather quiet lives without
ostentation. Instead of splurging on expensive houses and cars,
they save and invest their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were walking down the street, you wouldn't be able to
pick them out,'' said Carrie Coghill, executive vice president of
D.B. Root &AMP; Co. in Pittsburgh. ``They're just average people, only
they have saved and invested to the point that they have achieved
financial independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Saidel's income _ near $225,000 in peak years, now lower as he
limits his office time _ is high but neither spectacular nor
unheard of. Where he has made is wealth is through investments, for
which he credits his real estate partners and investment advisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been interested in the stock market,'' he said.
What he does know is the investment basic of compound interest that
bankers and brokers preach: Buy a stock, hold it, and reinvest the
proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Saidel has reinvested in real estate, and is currently a partner
in a Holiday Inn, a shopping center and, until recently, an
apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Tony, an engineer from Pittsburgh who asked that his name not be
used, has an even simpler strategy. Tony has been saving and
investing, largely through his employer's 401(k) tax-deferred
retirement savings plan, for about 20 years. Only recently did he
realize that _ largely thanks to the roaring financial markets of
the past decade _ he had accumulated more than $1 million in
assets, 60 percent of it in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It is the so-called ``401(k) millionaires'' like Tony who
confound the experts on income and wealth in America as they debate
who is truly rich.
</P>
<P>
   Not many years ago, a millionaire was a person whose net worth
was $1 million. As recently as 1971, there were fewer than 100,000
of them in America, according to Internal Revenue Service
estimates. But by 1995, the number had reached 1.48 million _ one
in each 178 Americans, according to the most recent IRS estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But although much may separate savvy investors like Tony and
someone like Disney CEO Michael Eisner, who earns more than $1
million a day, the U.S. Census Bureau essentially treats them the
same. The Bureau, the primary source for wealth and poverty data on
Americans, statistically lumps everyone together above $100,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, ``we really don't know that much about the rich,''
said Dimitri Papadimitriou, executive director and chief economist
of the Jerome Levy Economics Institute at Bard College in
Annandale-on-Hudson, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there is only sketchy statistical data on ``401(k)
millionaires,'' most of it coming from investment firms. For
example, T. Rowe Price of Baltimore, in a survey of its clients
last year, found 774 millionaires among the 1.4 million accounts it
services.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 million Americans have such accounts. But only 10
percent have balances of more than $100,000, according to Access
Research, a Connecticut-based consulting firm. The average balance
is $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some question whether any money saved for retirement should be
considered wealth. ``I wouldn't call it wealth,'' said Ted Benna,
president of the 401(k) Association, a national retirement account
advocacy group based in Cross Forks, Pa. ``It has to last you the
rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
