<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6002 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGLEY-MILLIONS09-CO     07-08 1809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGLEY-MILLIONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``This isn't a family that just hands you money''
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Chances are, her mom's maiden name is in your
purse. Or in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Every time you duck into a 7-Eleven, it's there. Glance at a
vending machine, same thing. Pause in a Publix checkout line,
voila!
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley.
</P>
<P>
   As in Doublemint (or U.S. Mint, considering the company is worth
$3.1 billion).
</P>
<P>
   Helen Rosburg, great-granddaughter of chewing gum magnate
William Wrigley Jr., is a very rich woman. But to meet her _ away
from her Bentley and her Arabian stallions and her Palm Beach
estate, at least _ you'd never know.
</P>
<P>
   Because Rosburg is an heiress without an attitude. An heiress,
you might say, for Everyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our family believes in normalcy,'' says Rosburg, wearing a
sleeveless floral frock from a Spiegel sale catalog (``I did get it
on sale, right Laury?'' she hollers to her secretary. ``Good!'')
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to public schools _ not all the time but most _ and it
was a given that we'd grow up and work. This isn't a family that
just hands you money.''
</P>
<P>
   And she means it. After high school, Rosburg studied to be a
secretary and even scrubbed kennels for a vet.
</P>
<P>
   These days, though, her work is her passion: writing. In fact,
Rosburg's first novel, ``Call of the Trumpet,'' just hit
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   She and James Rosburg _ a sculptor she married 10 months ago _
sit closely on a couch in their living room, which overlooks the
Intracoastal. Outside on the dock is a bright yellow Jet Ski
(``that's Juicy Fruit,'' she says). And the big red Bentley with
the CHEW GUM license plate? That's Big Red.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more to Big Red, by the way, than a clever license
plate. Details to come.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the heiress/author even more real is that she sees
the humor here. A discount dress. A day job. Yet enough stock to
buy a whole town. (The Wrigleys, after all, already own an island _
Catalina Island _ 25 miles off the coast of L.A.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting dropped off by a chauffeur in first and second grade
was a little demoralizing,'' she says with a smile. ``I took a lot
of heat.''
</P>
<P>
   She also took some heat finding an agent for her book, a period
piece based on the Bedouin culture (as in desert nomads) of the
early 1800s. Seems some folks thought, you guessed it,
another-bored-socialite-spews-a-love-story. Yawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to use my connections, but I did finally pull a
string to get a good agent because it's a Catch-22. You can't get
an agent without being published, and you can't get published
without an agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I asked a friend of mine _ a broker in New York who had a
lot of high-powered clients _ if any of them were agents. I knew at
least one would be. And I said, `He doesn't have to take me on,
just have him read it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (He read it. He took her on.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The broker, by the way, was my own friend,'' she emphasizes.
``He wasn't a Wrigley connection.''
</P>
<P>
   The literal Wrigley connection, meanwhile, goes like this: In
1891, William Wrigley Jr. started a soap company in Chicago with
$32. (As a kid, he'd helped his dad peddle soap in Philadelphia.)
To lure merchants, Wrigley gave out free baking powder. The powder
became more popular than the soap, to his surprise, so he switched
to selling that.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, he offered gum as an incentive: two packs per
can of powder. Again, the freebie took off _ really took off _ and
Wrigley was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   He and wife, Ada, had two children, including Philip K. Wrigley.
Philip K. went on to have three kids with wife, Helen, among them a
daughter named Deedie.
</P>
<P>
   Deedie married George Rich _ a jack-of-all-trades, Rosburg says
_ and they had three children: Helen Rosburg; Misdee Milligan, a
horse breeder in Ocala; and George T. Rich, who died of cancer
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (Deedie and George Rich eventually split up, but don't even try
to crack the ex-spouse code. Rosburg, when asked what marriage
she's on, turns to James and jokes, ``It's up there.'' Immediate
past prior is construction wheeler-dealer Willie DeGray, whom she
divorced in 1997 after nearly 11 years.)
</P>
<P>
   Rosburg recalls how she and her cousins teased grandpa Phil
during summers at the family estate in Lake Geneva, Wis. (There are
also homes in Chicago, Phoenix and on Catalina Island.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very, very quiet, even when he laughed,'' she says.
``We'd take the silver sugar thing and dump it out and put in
foaming sugar from the novelty shops. He'd put some into his coffee
and then very quietly say, `Replace my coffee, please.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This went on all summer. We did fake dog doo, fake everything,
and he finally got us back by inviting us into his office for some
chocolate. And, of course, it was rubber.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoic grandfather. Mischievous youngsters. Fake doo. Maybe the
rich aren't so different after all.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of pranks, a nearby table holds several real-looking
glass cocktail sculptures. James, with a straight face, points to
them and tells unsuspecting guests to help themselves to a
highball. Gotcha!
</P>
<P>
   Still newlyweds, he and Rosburg remain all a-bliss _ almost
always touching, often finishing each other's sentences, constantly
joking around. They ride Harleys together, too. Biker types.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him through the art world,'' she recalls. ``I'm the past
president of the Ann Norton Sculpture Gardens, and I went to a lot
of openings and stuff like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Cross Ball was coming up, and I'm always the wine
chairman or the reception chairman or something, so I needed an
escort. I called up this friend and said, `Help me get a date,' and
she said, `Why not Jim?' And I said, `That stud would never want to
take me out.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She literally dragged me to his Delray studio to renew old
acquaintances. When I walked in and we looked at each other, it was
like in the movies _ the drumroll, the orchestra . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Same here,'' says James, 41, in jeans and boots. ``When you
remember what they smell like _ their perfume _ and exactly what
they were wearing . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   That was Jan. 11, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The following year we were a scandal at the Red Cross Ball,''
says Rosburg, 49, with a grin. ``We were at that stage in our love
affair where we couldn't keep our hands off each other. We were
really naughty _ and we were sitting right in front of Barbara
Wainscott Berger!''
</P>
<P>
   (Wife of New York attorney David Berger and a former social
secretary for President Nixon.)
</P>
<P>
   Rosburg says her relationship with James (``now I can write
about real romance''), fueled her to finish Call of the Trumpet, a
novel she started in the early '80s. She's already on her second,
another historic romance with horses and a heroine.
</P>
<P>
   Rosburg recalls always wanting to be a writer, although her mom
wasn't so keen on the idea. Said she wouldn't make any money.
</P>
<P>
   So she went to Stephens College _ a small, private girls school
in Columbia, Mo. _ to study nursing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, I figured, I could work four days a week and then
write. But when I took a literature course, the professor took me
aside and said, `Why are you taking all this psychiatric nurse
nonsense? You're a brilliant writer.' So I quit school after a year
and wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Book of Arabesque,'' a poetry collection she co-authored
with Christine Penfield, was published in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Rosburg had two more kids _ Will DeGray, 11, and Ali
DeGray, 9. Her first child, Erik Wood, 29, lives in Australia and
is med-school bound.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Australia, Sydney is home to one of 13 Wrigley gum
factories worldwide. (The 14th is under construction in Russia.)
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1915, the down-under site was William Wrigley Jr.'s
second plant abroad _ the first was in Toronto _ so the young
entrepreneur was prospering. So much so, in fact, that he bought
the Chicago Cubs that same year. (That's how Wrigley Field got its
name.) The baseball team stayed in the family until 1981, when it
was sold to the Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   The gum giant went public in 1919, but the majority of stock
still remains Wrigley-owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have reunions, we plot about how to keep it in the
family,'' Rosburg jokes. ``Things happen, you know. There are a lot
of ex-spouses out there.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd think there'd be packs of gum waist-high at Rosburg's
house, but au contraire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I buy it just like everybody else,'' she says, confessing that
a cousin keeps her supplied with P. K, a peppermint brand not sold
in the States. P. K, you see, comes in ``pellets,'' not sticks.
Americans, for whatever reason, dig sticks. Plus, Chiclet has the
U.S. pellet market nailed shut. ``And we hate that about them,''
Rosburg jokes, feigning dispair.
</P>
<P>
   The Wrigley Co., meanwhile, dominates the world gum market.
First quarter earnings this year were $76 million, up 12 cents a
share from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   So how does it work? Do Rosburg and kin get a check every time
someone buys Spearmint? Or Winterfresh. Or Freedent. Or Hubba Bubba
. . .
</P>
<P>
   She hoots at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, in a way, that is how it happens. Not literally, of
course. But when you buy gum, the stock stays up. It's
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosburg, she'll tell you, is in a good place right now. But just
a few years ago, this wasn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a really bad time. First, I was in a car accident, and
it took me a year to recover. Then, I had massive abdominal
surgery. Then, they discovered I had breast cancer, and during all
of this I was in a disgusting marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   A certain red automobile, she says, put her on the road to
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do something for myself that would get me up and
out of bed, so before the surgery (she's now cancer free), I went
car shopping. I drove the BMWs and the Mercedes _ the fast cars,
the hot cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said, `While you're at it, why not try a Bentley?' I
said, `That is absolutely not my style.' But then they said, `It's
turbo.' So I drove it, and let me tell you, they could not get me
out of that car.''
</P>
<P>
   James nods his head in agreement, chuckling at the memory (``we
needed a crowbar'').
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got back to the dealership, the salesman _ a
distinguished elderly English fellow _ got out of the car, turned
around and in a very clipped British way, said, `Well! I have never
had a lady client burn rubber in a Bentley!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Rosburg, lead-foot heiress.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had predicted six weeks of bed rest, but Rosburg was up
in 10 days ``thanks to that car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that car, and I drive the hell out of it,'' she says.
``So now that you know the story behind it, you realize I don't
drive a Bentley for the same reason that other people in Palm Beach
drive Bentleys.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Helen, we knew that already.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
