<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 9, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday, 2.5 inches of rain fell at McGrath,
Alaska, accounting for 15 percent of the town's annual average.
Downpours came as a low pressure system stalled over interior
Alaska, its progress blocked by unyielding high pressure over the
Arctic Ocean. More showers are possible Thursday over Alaska's
interior.
</P>
<P>
   Steering winds on the eastern flank of the blocking high will
direct a cool Canadian air mass toward western New England
Thursday. Scattered showers and a few thunderstorms will develop
along and ahead of the leading edge of the cool air mass from the
Adirondacks of upstate New York to northern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of fog will reduce visibility over the northern Middle
Atlantic and southeast New England States Thursday morning, a
legacy of the rains of late Tuesday and Wednesday. After the fog
dissipates, a few showers and thunderstorms will blossom over the
central Appalachians as moist air in contact with the warming
ground rises into cold air aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Hot and humid weather will persist over the Gulf Coast States,
with hit-or-miss showers and storms developing along and ahead of a
very weak front stretching across the region. Heavy rain is
possible in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon thunderstorms will again develop over the southern and
central Rockies as invading tropical moisture combines with the
uneven heating of mountains to produce roiling cumulus clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, isolated clusters of thunderstorms will patrol the
western high Plains from the Texas panhandle northward into the
western Dakotas and eastern Montana.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hollywood Hail &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hailstones with a diameter of three-fourths of an inch pelted
Hollywood, Florida, to the north of Miami on Tuesday. Hail is
unusual in Florida in July because hailstones typically melt
completely during their descent through the thick layer of warm air
above the ground. However, when updrafts in thunderstorms are
exceptionally strong, hailstones can be suspended longer in the
cold upper atmosphere, allowing them to grow larger as they collect
ice crystals and water drops. If hailstones grow sufficiently large
while suspended, they can avoid melting completely once they
plummet toward the ground.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
