<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Need a wrench? It's a snap for a man with an inventory on
wheels.
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You stand in the back of Chris Holme's
white, 13-ton Snap-on tool truck and look up at the ceiling where
silver wrenches and screwdrivers and sockets and pliers hang on
little hooks and glow in the soft light and you think of Carl Sagan
looking up at the heavens saying billions and billions of . . .
</P>
<P>
   Holme is a few wrenches shy of billions, but he's got thousands
hanging in his truck _ tons upon tons of tools, $300,000 worth at
any time, from a 1-inch-long 4mm socket to a 3-pound, 18-inch-long
double open-end bolt remover.
</P>
<P>
   Tools? He's got 'em all.
</P>
<P>
   Holme is one of a dozen Snap-on franchise owners who work
territories in Palm Beach and Martin counties in Florida, one of
3,400 nationwide. They own their business, own their inventory, own
their trucks. They're some of the last true American road salesmen,
drummers on a mission to those who use tools _ just about all of us
nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   But their main clients are automotive mechanics. Holme's Stuart
territory is just large enough for him to know every customer by
name, and more. He knows what cars they specialize in, how old
their kids are, whether their wives are displeased when their
mechanic husband comes home with an $8,000 toolbox. He knows their
credit ratings, domestic status and football team preference.
</P>
<P>
   And they know that Holme has the tools they need. All the tools,
all the time.
</P>
<P>
   And they know something else. ``Chris Holme's tools are the
best, but his word is better,'' says Marty Lyke, a Stuart auto body
man.
</P>
<P>
   Lyke owns $30,000 worth of Snap-on tools. He uses them to turn
three wrecked cars into one functioning car. He keeps his tools in
a $10,000 bright red toolbox that measures about 4-by-6 feet. It's
the Snap-on model known as The Intimidator.
</P>
<P>
   Lyke's young sons, Marty and Matthew, have their own tools.
Snap-on. Lyke bought them tiny wrenches when they were born instead
of the usual silver bauble from Tiffany's.
</P>
<P>
   If Lyke needs a few hundred dollars worth of tools, Holme will
sell on easy terms _ no interest, pay when you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple equation,'' says Holme. ``An auto mechanic's
livelihood depends on having tools right now. No tools, no work. If
he doesn't work, I don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Holme, 37, with a ready smile and Tab Hunter all-American good
looks, has been selling Snap-on since 1987. Paid his $5,000
franchise fee. Bought his truck for $80,000, filled it with
inventory, went on the road. Hasn't been off the road since. Tools
are hot items.
</P>
<P>
   So isn't a tool a tool like a rose is a rose?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what Americans spend on automotive repairs each
year,'' he says, ``but I know that auto mechanics spend about $3
billion on tools _ $3 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto makers use different standards, measures, fittings, screws,
gauges, meters, plugs, nuts, bolts and computer diagnostic
monitors. More
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
