 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE THURSDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, July 9, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BLUECROSS _ Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia has agreed to
settle a lawsuit by consumer groups who challenged its 1996
conversion to a for-profit company. The agreement creates a
nonprofit health-care foundation and endows it with stock and
warrants that amount to 20 percent of the shares of Cerulean, Blue
Cross's parent company. (Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   EQUIFAX _ Pursuing details on acquisition Equifax is to announce
Thursday. (McNaughton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PAYROLL _ A Speedway SuperAmerica in Dayton is the first
Speedway in the country to have the Mr. Payroll Check Cashing
Machine. The machine allows people, even ones with no bank account,
to cash any type of check any time of the day with no ID required.
All you need is a SSN. (Townsend, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WRIGLEY-MILLIONS _ Helen Rosburg, great-granddaughter of chewing
gum magnate William Wrigley Jr., is a very rich woman. But to meet
her _ away from her Bentley and her Arabian stallions and her Palm
Beach estate, at least _ you'd never know. Because Rosburg is an
heiress without an attitude. An heiress, you might say, for
Everyman. (Grantham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FRUGAL-MILLIONAIRE _ In their recent best-seller, ``The
Millionaire Next Door,'' co-authors William Danko and Thomas
Stanley found that many millionaires in America today live rather
quiet lives without ostentation. Instead of splurging on expensive
houses and cars, they save and invest their money.
(Shepard/Gulliver, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TOOL-GUY _ Tools? He's got 'em all. Holme is one of a dozen
Snap-on franchise owners who work territories in Palm Beach and
Martin counties in Florida, one of 3,400 nationwide. They own their
business, own their inventory, own their trucks. They're some of
the last true American road salesmen, drummers on a mission to
those who use tools _ just about all of us nowadays. (Reid, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLBIZ-ADVICE _ AUSTIN _Flexibility is a business strategy
that many companies rely on _ in Austin and across the nation.
(Tyson, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
