<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6020 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-BOOKREVIEW10-CO     07-08 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-BOOKREVIEW10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diamonds are a fan's best friend
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A GREAT AND GLORIOUS GAME: The Baseball Writings of A. Bartlett
Giamatti. Algonquin; 121 pages; $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   Reading this lovely, if brief collection of Bart Giamatti's work
made me realize it's been downhill for baseball since Giamatti had
the misfortune to die in 1989 after only five months as
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Giamatti was a fluke to begin with. He wasn't a
hack, a flunky, or a political appointee. He was a high-line
academic who knew baseball, loved baseball and carried a moral
authority because everyone knew that his primary allegiance wasn't
to the owners or the players, but to the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   Since Giamatti, we have had to endure Commissioner for Life Bud
Selig, an owner himself, a lackey to his peers, completely bereft
of credibility to the players or to any other sentient observer.
</P>
<P>
   It was Selig who meekly presided over the catastrophic strike
that washed out a World Series for the first time in history and
provided the game with its greatest crisis since the Black Sox
scandal. Bring back Ford Frick.
</P>
<P>
   Giamatti would probably not have been able to do anything about
some of the perils that have wounded the game. Wayne Huizenga would
still have broken up a World Championship team, expansion would
still water down the available talent, Michael Jordan would still
have electrified a generation of young fans, and Rupert Murdoch,
the Prince of Media Darkness, would still buy the Dodgers. Outside
the stadiums, the Balkanization of the culture that has affected
all other aspects of American life would have still worked to
decrease baseball's purchase on our emotional lives.
</P>
<P>
   But I suspect Giamatti would have mediated that strike because
he had one eye on the past and the other eye on the future, and he
knew that the strike endangered the passion the fans have for
bygone times, and the interest they hold for days to come.
</P>
<P>
   And there can be little doubt Giamatti would have put his job on
the line had someone suggested scrubbing the Series. Listen to
this, written on the occasion of the 1981 strike, a modest
fireworks display compared to the bloody Verdun of the '94 strike:
</P>
<P>
   ``Call this baseball strike an example of deny-side economics,
which says you withhold from the consumer what he most desires so
that you may substitute discipline for satisfaction; call it a
symptom of the plague of distrust and divisiveness that afflicts
our land; call it the triumph of greed over the spirit of the
garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call it what you will, the strike is utter foolishness. It is
an act of defiance against the American people, and the only summer
God made for 1981. . . . There is no general sympathy for either of
your sides. Nor will there be.''
</P>
<P>
   Giamatti was president of Yale when he was named National League
president, after which he ascended to the Commissioner's office. He
was a classicist in all things, and a fervent, small d democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Since Giamatti spent little of his life in baseball, he didn't
spend all that much time writing about it. This collection is
therefore a miscellany of pieces; here an essay for the Yale Alumni
Journal, there an op-ed piece from the Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the book falls under the heading of the
Elysian-fields-green-garden-of-our-lost-youth category of baseball
prose, to which I have a congenital resistance.
</P>
<P>
   But you can forgive a lot for writing like this: ``It breaks
your heart. It is designed to break your heart. The game begins in
the spring, when everything else begins again, and it blossoms in
the summer, filling the afternoons and evenings, and then as soon
as the chill rains come, it stops and leaves you to face the fall
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Giamatti hammers home one continual theme _ that baseball is
quintessentially American in the way it simultaneously puts a
premium on the team and the individual, in the way it tells us that
no matter how far you go, the ultimate object is always the return
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is counterpoint,'' he writes. ``Stability vying with
volatility, tradition with the quest for a new edge, ancient
rhythms and ever-new blood.''
</P>
<P>
   For Giamatti, baseball wasn't a metaphor for his country, it was
his country, innately pertinent to the moral and intellectual
bounty of our culture:
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually all our other sports reflect the time clock, either
in their formal structure or their definition of a winner. Baseball
views time as if it were an endlessly available resource; it may
put a premium on speed . . . but it is unhurried. Time, like the
water and forests, like the land itself, is supposedly
ever-available.''
</P>
<P>
   Giamatti knew that time has a way of running out, although he
probably wasn't aware of how little he really had. This book
suggests that Giamatti would have become the poet laureate of our
beleaguered national sport.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
