<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6025 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HIGH-END-AUDIO-AR     07-08 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HIGH-END-AUDIO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOW FOR HIGH-END HI-FI 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The high end is in a funk.
</P>
<P>
   These ought to be glory days for that peculiarly American
obsession with the ultimate in stereo equipment. The numbers of the
Wall Street and Silicon Valley wealthy multiply daily, seemingly
increasing the potential customer base for monaural tube amplifiers
at $34,000 a pair, an electrostatic speaker system at $70,000 or a
CD player with no integrated circuits for $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the high end isn't crowing; instead, it is experiencing a
kind of existential angst, beset by demographic and economic issues
beyond its control and technological trends that threaten its very
relevance.
</P>
<P>
   The best audio equipment is largely handmade, and therefore
expensive, and the high end has always been a bit of a cult with
its own language and customs, something that has scared away new
participants. What makes it special is the tireless devotion of its
practitioners to innovation and to a level of excellence that is as
much art as engineering.
</P>
<P>
   But high-end audio may be the only electronic product whose
price has steadily risen in the past two decades, narrowing its
potential market to software millionaires and magnates of the Asian
tigers, now in eclipse, who made up as much as a third of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high end has been preaching to the converted for years and
hasn't branched out,'' said Wayne Garcia, editor-in-chief of Fi, a
three-year old magazine devoted to high-end audio. ``The
traditional two-channel music lover is either aging, burned out or
has enough gear and doesn't need to upgrade all the time, or has
other priorities,'' he said. ``At the same time, the high end
hasn't done a good job getting its message across to younger
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in the hobbyist days of what was then called hi-fidelity,
high-end audio blossomed in the late 1970s and '80s. Even as stereo
equipment became the domain of mass-market consumer-electronics
manufacturers, most of them Japanese, scores of small companies
sprang up in the United States and Europe to pursue the elusive
goal of nearly perfect sound.
</P>
<P>
   Though they remained small businesses, brands like
Conrad-Johnson, Martin-Logan and Spectral gained international
followings for their exquisite amplifiers and speakers. Spurred on
by magazines like Stereophile, The Absolute Sound and Fi, the
auteurs of audio aimed to recreate the sound of live music.
</P>
<P>
   While that goal may be forever elusive, a properly set up
high-end audio system, using only two channels, can produce a
musical experience that is startling real, a sound of a completely
different order than that offered by mass-market equipment, albeit
for a very few consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association
estimated total U.S. factory sales for the high-end audio industry
in 1997 at about $1.1 billion, out of a total market of about $75.6
billion. But the association did not differentiate between home
theater and high-end audio. Many manufacturers say they believe
that the industry is far smaller, not more than $500 million, and
even that total is spread among literally hundreds of companies.
Although sales grew in 1997, many companies have reported declines
in 1998, which they attribute primarily to the Asian economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Defining the high end is problematic. It's not just a matter of
expense because a music lover can easily spend thousands of dollars
on flashy gear that no self-respecting audiophile would condescend
to listen to. The entry point for a high-end system today is about
$10,000 for a CD player, preamplifier, amplifier, speakers and
cables, more if the system includes a turntable, tuner or tape
deck, less with savvy purchases of used equipment or with equipment
built from kits. For an all-out assault on the state of the art,
figure some multiple of six figures.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the high end's woes reflect the same kind of
changes that led to the decline of classical music radio stations.
Not so long ago, listening to a broadcast of a symphony was a
popular evening's entertainment; now most radio listening is done
in cars. Similarly, the audio hobbyist who used to spend hours
``tweaking'' his system, playing record after record, may now be
surfing the Web, even if it is to check in on rec.audio.high-end, a
Usenet newsgroup devoted to his old hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to how people spend their leisure time,'' said
Wendell Diller, president of Magnepan in White Bear Lake, Minn., a
maker of large flat-panel speakers that are much praised in
high-end circles. ``They can play with a computer, watch a movie,
but to sit and listen to music? C'mon, only the die-hard music
lovers continue to entertain themselves this way. Although the
economy is booming, I hear all my friends in the business saying,
`What's going on here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Labovitz, who manages technology transfer for the
University of California at San Francisco, has a roomful of
high-end gear, but he has not set foot in an audio store in a few
years. ``I still have all the equipment, and I listen to it all the
time, but I don't read audiophile magazines any more, and I don't
hang out at the Audible Difference,'' he said, referring to a Palo
Alto store that has outfitted many Silicon Valley luminaries.
Noting the huge cost increase for an incremental improvement in
sound, he said, ``You reach a certain level and you stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually the seeming paradox of a healthy economy and a flat
high end reflects a long-standing dichotomy in the industry, which
has only been exaggerated by three or four decades of rising
prices. Just as Porsche designs cars for race drivers but reaps
most of its revenues from the merely wealthy, so, too, the high end
may be driven by hobbyists and critics, but it survives on sales to
successful entrepreneurs and professionals whose level of interest
may not match their ability to spend. One does not need to be
obsessed to spend $100,000 on a music system, only well-to-do.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the wealthy have grown less enamored of huge speakers placed
well away from walls for the best sound, racks of glowing
amplifiers and yards of garden-hose-size interconnect cables. Today
the demand is for custom installations that hide all the gear in
walls or bespoke cabinetry and, above all, for home theater.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers are benefiting from this trend, devoting more of
their store space to theater systems and reaping good margins from
installation work. But the purists find it almost offensive. ``It
is the middle class, low to middle, who are fascinated with this,''
said Michael Kay, owner of Lyric Hi-Fi, Manhattan's temple to audio
excess. ``These people were never high end. They abandon the high
end for today's fad, that I can't consider really musical
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   With five speakers instead of two and an emphasis on video
projection, home theater systems attempt to make viewings
comparable to attending screenings at the best cinema, a far
different calling than recreating Carnegie Hall or the Village
Vanguard in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a huge increase in personal wealth, and one of
the ways people advertise their wealth to friends and neighbors is
putting in a big home theater,'' said Larry Archibald, publisher of
Stereophile, the leading audiophile magazine, which was acquired in
May by Petersen Cos. ``Our Guide to Home Theater is seeing big
advertising growth, and Stereophile is seeing flatness, and that is
what's happening in the stores as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While home theater is primarily the domain of big consumer
electronics companies like Sony and Pioneer, a number of high-end
manufacturers have developed products for this market. These
companies say they can apply some of the values of the high end to
home theater devices, like using the best components money can buy
and building equipment that can be updated rather than replaced as
technology improves and standards change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly an opportunity,'' said John Herron, manager for
new product development at Madrigal Audio Laboratories in
Middleton, Conn., which produces the ultra-high-end Mark Levinson
line. Madrigal, a unit of Harman International, has introduced
multichannel amplifiers and a digital surround-sound decoder in its
more moderate Proceed line, with prices in the mid-to-high four
figures. Some in the high-end industry say music reproduction and
home theater are completely different goals. But Herron said the
incompatibility was ``not really the nature of the beast, it's the
nature of the presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree, on both esthetic and technical grounds. While
home theater stresses dynamic range, the ability to play very
loudly and have deep bass, to reproduce all those explosions in
``Terminator 2,'' high-end audio systems are all about high
resolution, the ability to recreate the most subtle tonal and
spatial details of a musical performance.
</P>
<P>
   High-end advocates also note that both Dolby Digital and Digital
Theater Systems, or DTS, the two technologies battling for
allegiance in home theater sound, employ compression technology
that effectively eliminates phase information. Without that
information, which delineates the precise timing of musical events,
a music system cannot reproduce a three-dimensional sound stage.
That is fine for theater systems, which rely on multiple speakers
around the room to generate a 3-D effect, but anathema to the
reproduction of live music.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an absolute all-out audio system, you never want to use
compression,'' said Rick Frier, president of Spectral Inc. a maker
of high-end amplifiers, preamps and compact disk players in San
Jose, Calif. ``That has cleaved the high end and home theater
apart.'' Still, he added, the high end has to find a way to make
itself relevant in this market. ``Some can do it _ some swallow
their pride and make a stab at it _ some say, Over my dead body,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some high-end manufacturers who have introduced home
theater products have reservations about them.
</P>
<P>
   The five channels of audio used in home theater ``are going to
lead customers to spend much less per channel, and that doesn't
bode well for our part of the business,'' said Lew Johnson,
president of Conrad-Johnson, a maker of high-end amplifiers and
preamps in Fairfax, Va., that plans to offer a five-channel
amplifier in the fall. ``If you've got a $25,000 home entertainment
budget and you spend $10,000 to $15,000 on a video projection
system and spread the rest over five channels instead of two, your
budget per channel for amplifiers and speakers is very limited,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that the high end may thrive again.
Johnson is part of a work group meeting to promote an advanced
audio disk based on DVD, which would take advantage of that
medium's higher data capacity to offer better sound quality than do
current CD's. But that effort comes just as CD sound, driven
largely by a technology called HDCD, for high definition compatible
digital, is finally approaching audiophile quality. HDCD,
commonplace in high-end CD players, is now beginning to appear in
mass market machines as well.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, sales of turntables have taken off this year,
mirroring a simultaneous rebirth of the vinyl LP. ``There is a
resurgence,'' said Kay, of Lyric. ``The small CD's that people buy
are convenient, but the fanatic knows better. The analog is still
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more surprising, The Absolute Sound, which went out of
business in March 1997 after all but coining the term high end, is
back, with a new publisher and new financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not share this gloomy vision that the high end is dead;
there's too much new and lively happening,'' said Harry Pearson,
Absolute Sound's founder and editor. ``They're confused, they're
worried about surround sound and home theater, but I think the
field is hopping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
