<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAG09-COX     07-08 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLAG PROTECTION AMENDMENT UP TO SENATE
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a showdown vote looming on a constitutional
amendment to let Congress protect the American flag, senators
summoned a revered baseball manager, legal scholars, war heroes and
a TV star to Capitol Hill on Wednesday for an emotional debate on
the divisive issue.
</P>
<P>
   After passionate testimony from both supporters and opponents,
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, predicted
the Senate would vote on the measure by this fall. It would let
state legislatures essentially override a 1989 Supreme Court
decision that flag desecration is a form of political speech
guaranteed by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   While detractors have argued that flag desecrations are rare and
Congress has more important matters to attend, the overflow crowd
at the hearing illustrated the intense interest of many veterans
and civil libertarians.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the proposed amendment sponsored by Hatch and Sen. Max
Cleland, D-Ga., a wheelchair-bound Vietnam veteran, goes to the
essence of national community and patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American flag is the one symbol that unites a very diverse
people in a way nothing else can, in peace and in war,'' said
Hatch. ``Despite our differences, the American flag forms a unique,
common bond between us. Failure to protect the flag inevitably
loosens this bond, no matter how much some may claim to the
contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This country was built on more than symbols,'' countered Sen.
Russ Feingold, D-Wis. ``No laws or amendments that we can pass will
make anyone love or revere the flag, but we can and ought to
protect the principles of freedom, opportunity and democracy in the
Bill of Rights by opposing this amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses reflected creative casting by leaders of both
sides. Former Los Angeles Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda and former
``Dukes of Hazzard'' star John Schneider led the charge for flag
protection, while a disabled Green Beret veteran and a conservative
legal activist warned against infringing on the right to free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard law professor who boasted of his liberal Democratic
roots argued in favor of the amendment, as did a Medal of Honor
winner from Wisconsin, the home state of a committee opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can accuse me of opposing this proposed constitutional
amendment for political reasons,'' conceded Feingold. ``Indeed, it
may be the most politically unpopular position I could take.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates claim support from 80 percent of the populace for the
amendment, which says simply: ``The Congress shall have the power
to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed the House last year by a vote of 310-114,
more than the required two-thirds majority. The legislatures of 49
states _ more than the three-fourths needed for ratification _ have
passed resolutions calling for Congress to send them the proposed
amendment. So the fate of the issue likely rests on whether Senate
opponents can muster the margin needed to block the measure _
one-third of those voting plus one vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate vote is likely to be close. Hatch said the amendment
has 60 co-sponsors, but the final seven or eight votes may be hard
to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are serious about protecting the American flag, it is up
to this body, at this time, to take action and send this proposed
amendment to the states,'' said Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the witnesses urged the senators to pass the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, because of the Supreme Court's decision, the flag is
just another piece of cloth that can be burned and soiled with
impunity,'' lamented Lasorda. He recalled an incident in which Rick
Monday, then the Dodger center fielder, grabbed a burning flag from
two protesters who had jumped onto the field. The crowd stood and
spontaneously sang ``God Bless America'' after Monday rescued the
flag, Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that the amendment would ``somehow harm the First
Amendment'' is ``absolute, unadulterated hogwash,'' said Schneider,
an actor and singer who has recorded a song titled ``I Love Old
Glory'' that was written by Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court said that those who would defecate on the flag of
the United States _ theirs or another's _ are merely exercising
their First Amendment rights,'' said Gary Wetzel, who won the Medal
of Honor during the Vietnam War and now lives in Oak Creek, Wis.
``With decisions like this one, I sometimes wonder if our judges
have fallen out of step with the citizens of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   But other witnesses warned against ``amending the First
Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, the flag is really just a symbol of that sacrifice
and, more importantly, our American ideals,'' said Marvin
Stenhammar, a disabled veteran of the Army Green Berets. ``This
flag amendment will place a higher value on an inanimate object, a
symbol, than on the rights of the people living under it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clint Bolick, a former intern in Hatch's office and director of
litigation for the Institute of Justice, said his former boss is
wrong on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we draw the line here?'' he asked. ``On what principle
can we punish someone who burns a flag, but not someone who burns a
cross?''
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard University law professor Richard Parker, who
described himself as a lifelong Democrat whose heroes include the
late Robert Kennedy, said flag protection was allowed under the
Constitution for the 200 years before the 5-4 decision in the 1989
case of Texas v. Johnson. The amendment would restore the First
Amendment to its longstanding meaning and the ``tampering'' was
done by five justices, he testified.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
