<HEADLINE>
NEWS WATCH: NEW KEYBOARDS FROM IBM;   SYNCING ON THE WEB;   PALM
PILOT UPDATE;   SWAPPING ON THE WEB;   MAC TYPES WANT ADSL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (mk)  
 By STEVEN E. BRIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM has made life easier for those who find it too much trouble
to click on those pesky desktop icons or move a mouse around. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company has two new lines of keyboards, one with buttons
allowing ready access to popular functions and another with a
pointing device like those in the company's laptop line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rapid Access Keyboard includes four buttons to start up
favorite applications, one of which is programmed to start a Web
browser and connect to the Net. Three other programmable buttons
can be set based on a user's needs, whether opening time sheets for
an office worker or starting a child's favorite program at home.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other buttons on the otherwise standard 104-key model control
audio CDs and speaker volume, put computers into a power-saving
mode and open Windows Help programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rapid Access Keyboard costs about $50 and comes in computer
beige. The company plans to release a black model soon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IBM's other new line uses the latest iteration of the
Trackpoint, an eraser-head pointing device that replaces a mouse.
This keyboard, called the Trackpoint, is popular with laptop users
who like consistency and for those with limited desk space. It
costs about $110 and will be available later this month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My People, Your People: Contact Managers Go Online
</P>
<P>
   The Web is normally associated with surfing, not syncing, but
Puma Technology has teamed up with Planet All to change that. The
beneficiaries are those people who use personal information
database software, commonly known as contact manager programs.
</P>
<P>
   Planet All is a contact manager that, unlike others, is
Web-based and self-updating. That means that the user's information
is linked with that of his or her regular contacts, and users are
automatically notified of any changes in one another's contact
information.
</P>
<P>
   Puma, one of the market leaders in synchronization software, has
a new package that synchronizes a customer's existing contact
database with the Planet All database, allowing users to have
access to their contact lists from any Web browser. That allows
people to use their contact managers from borrowed computers
without having to copy a particular application and database to the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Rowe, president of Puma Technology, said that synchronizing
a database to the Web and sharing selected parts of it was a good
way to keep people who talk to each other up to date. ``This uses
the Internet as a tool to stay in touch without much effort,'' Rowe
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another version from Puma uses Orchestrate, a Web-based
universal in-box for faxes, e-mail and voice mail. That version
allows a user to retrieve messages from Orchestrate and respond to
them using their computer.
</P>
<P>
   A Pager to Lighten the Load
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Pilot from 3Com has been wildly successful, capturing
more than 60 percent of the personal digital-assistant market. But
the Pilot's highly mobile adherents have needed to carry along
cellular phones and pagers to stay in touch. Now Palm Pilot people
can leave at least the pager behind with the help of Motorola, Page
Mart and 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   For older Palm Pilots, Motorola has developed a memory card that
has most of the features of the new Palm III and also a pager chip.
The card, available through Page Mart, a paging and wireless
services company based in Dallas, allows Page Mart subscribers to
receive pages on a Pilot. The card is priced at $169, and the
nationwide paging service is $19.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The pager software has been integrated into Pilot applications,
providing more than just paging. Incoming numeric messages will be
checked against the Pilot address book. If a phone number matches,
the corresponding entry will be opened so a user knows who sent the
page. Messages are also numbered, allowing the user to know about
out-of-sequence or missing messages. Like most pagers, the Palm
Pilot will only receive messages, but Bridget Cavanaugh, a
spokeswoman for Page Mart, said that the company was looking at
two-way options as it expanded its other services.
</P>
<P>
   To install the card, users need to remove the memory door and
memory card and insert the new card and door. Since many users put
copies of the character recognition help file on the memory door,
Page Mart will include a new copy. People taking advantage of the
vCard electronic business card and scheduling tool can also have
their schedules updated remotely. Motorola also has a software
developer's kit, so corporate developers can create and tailor
applications to their business.
</P>
<P>
   A caveat: The pager will not work with the newer Palm III, only
with older Palm units. In addition to the pager function, the card
brings two megabytes of memory and Palm OS3 to the older units.
</P>
<P>
   Users of the Pilot, of course, have a not undeserved reputation
for brandishing the unit a little too publicly. But the cachet of
older units suffered when the Palm III, with its redesigned shell,
was released. Some of that cachet may be recovered with the
pager-memory card. Ms. Cavanaugh, the Page Mart spokeswoman, said
11.6 million older Pilots were in use.
</P>
<P>
   New Barter Site on the Internet
</P>
<P>
   Auctions successfully moved from the auto lot to the Internet,
and now the barter system is going to give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   Ubarter.com is scheduled to start July 20, giving consumers a
chance to trade unneeded items for something they deem a bit more
important. (There were already barter sites for corporations.)
``Our guess is that people have things around the yard or business
that they don't need,'' said Steven White, president of
International Barter, Ubarter's parent company. Ubarter will take a
2 percent to 3 percent fee for helping set up the transaction.
Since it is a barter, the fee is determined by the value listed on
the item listed.
</P>
<P>
   Ubarter will have 10 categories, focusing on things like
electronics, vehicles, vacations and home furnishings as well as
several business-related groups. Users will be able to post an
item, along with its value, in a category. They also will list what
they would like in return. (``Exercise bike. Never used. $450 new.
Will trade for concave mirror or convertible.'').
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other people can look at the list and see if there is a match
for a trade. (``Sideshow sell-off. Closing House of Mirrors,
opening health club.'') Ubarter also opens up the opportunity for
cross-trading, in which a series of swaps are used to get people
the items they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an auction, the highest price gets the item,'' White said.
``With us, the right product gets it.''
</P>
<P>
   The site will recommend that traders use an online escrow
service or a local lawyer to insure that products will be as
advertised. White expects that his company will be paid by credit
card, although in the spirit of the enterprise, ``Ubarter dollars''
are on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth ADSL to Include Mac Users
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth plans to tap into the evangelism of the Apple market
as the phone company speeds up its rollout of the ADSL high-speed
Internet connection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the company, which provides local phone service in the
southeastern United States, first announced its rollout of ADSL
(asymmetric digital subscriber line) technology in May, it focused
on Windows computers. But the company then received what it called
a huge demand for the service from Macintosh devotees, something
that caught its attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``By working directly with Apple, we are bringing the Mac
version of BellSouth.net Fast Access ADSL service to market much
more quickly,'' said Andrew Dietz, director of product marketing
for BellSouth.net Services.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By focusing on Mac users, BellSouth hopes not only to increase
market penetration but also to promote its service to the wider
online community. ``We also are extending BellSouth's
lightning-fast capabilities to an important group of computer
users, who we believe are highly likely to have Internet access and
be evangelists for new Internet services,'' Dietz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
