u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      07-08 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DORA GALITZKI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Nasturtiums &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In May, I planted Creamsicle nasturtiums (Tropaeolum majus)
from seed in a large pot on my windowsill, which faces east and
gets lots of morning sun. They came up quickly, but now I have very
few flowers and a great tangle of leaves and stems. I have cut back
the greenery, but it simply returns. How can I encourage the growth
of flowers? I fertilize with Miracle-Gro every two weeks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your nasturtiums would like to be left alone for a while,
preferably on the outside of that windowsill, to recover from all
your kindnesses. Nasturtiums like a lean life: not much fertilizer,
a porous, well-drained potting mixture like Pro-Mix BX, and plenty
of sun. Overfeed them, and they'll just grow lots of foliage. Shear
the foliage back, and they'll do their best to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, soilless mixtures like Pro-Mix contain very few
nutrients on their own, so some fertilizing is necessary. Soluble
liquid fertilizer at one-quarter to one-half strength every three
weeks is plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Give them what they want and they will flower, but not until
they reach a certain size. Many nasturtium cultivars can sprawl or
mound, reaching 12 or more inches. If that is too large for your
space, try a more compact growing nasturtium, like the Tip Top
hybrids, which grow to about seven inches and hold their flowers
above the foliage for a showier display.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dwindling Peaches &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last year, my five-year-old peach tree produced scads of
peaches only to lose them all. I blamed the squirrels at the time.
This spring, the tree again produced scads of baby peaches, and
when I saw some of them on the ground I placed netting around the
tree. I am now left with about four or five peaches that still seem
to be growing. What is going on here? Am I lacking something, like
fertilizers? Or is this the nature of the beast? I would like a few
suggestions on how I can raise my peach production.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I hope you have apologized to the squirrels. This is the
nature of the beast, although your harvest can be improved.
</P>
<P>
   A mature tree will produce about 500 peaches from its 30,000
blossoms, a ratio of about 1 to 60. That sounds as if there is a
natural conspiracy, and there is, sort of. Fruit may fail to mature
for several reasons. If pollination isn't complete, the seed inside
may not be viable, and the fruit is aborted early.
</P>
<P>
   Win Cowgill, an agricultural agent with Rutgers Cooperative
Extension in Hunterdon County, N.J., said cloudy weather like this
spring's forces fruit trees to make a choice: use the limited
sunlight to produce more leaves for photosynthesis, or produce
fruit. Leaves win. And finally, there's the phenomenon called June
drop. For about two months after bloom begins, roughly from late
May into early July, fruit trees self-thin, dropping enough fruit
that the tree can support the rest, both nutritionally and
literally. Overloaded branches can break.
</P>
<P>
   To get the most from your tree, don't overfeed it (nitrogen
promotes foliage growth, not fruit), keep the ground below the tree
free of weeds, thin the small peaches so there is six to eight
inches between fruit, and prune every March or early April, while
the tree is still dormant. Prune a few older branches to promote
new growth, since peaches fruit on wood that is a year old. Of
course, the easiest way to increase your production is to buy more
trees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
