<HEADER>
A6056 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAG-BURNING-HNS &LR;      07-08 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-BURNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCH SAYS SENATE WILL VOTE ON FLAG AMENDMENT THIS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee, said Wednesday that the full Senate would vote
this fall on a proposed constitutional amendment that would empower
Congress to ban flag desecration.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he has 60 other Senate co-sponsors for the amendment,
including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. The flag
amendment needs 67 votes or two-thirds of the senators present to
pass. The Citizens Flag Alliance, a group pushing the amendment,
says it can count 64 senators for the amendment as of now.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, a Republican from Utah, predicted the Senate vote would
come in September or October.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendment, which would carve out an exception to
the First Amendment by giving Congress the power to enact laws
against flag desecration, has already won House approval. If it
passes the Senate, the amendment would require ratification by
three-fourths of the states. Polls indicate a majority of voters
favor the flag amendment and 49 states have passed resolutions
asking Congress to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   The flag amendment would overturn U.S. Supreme Court rulings in
1989 and 1990 that struck down state and federal flag desecration
laws as unconstitutional violations of freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said in an interview that the issue has personal
significance for him because he lost his older brother in World War
II, a fact that makes him empathize with veterans who want to
protect the symbol they fought for.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most prized possessions I have in my life was the
flag that draped his coffin,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch also said he thinks the 310-114 House vote in favor of the
amendment in June 1997 gave the issue enough momentum to win Senate
approval this session.
</P>
<P>
   However, after a flag protection amendment passed the House in
1995 by a 312-120 vote, it fell three votes short in the Senate.
That amendment would have allowed state legislatures as well as
Congress to enact flag protection laws.
</P>
<P>
   To drum up support for the amendment, supporters enlisted Tommy
Lasorda, general manager of the Los Angeles Dodgers, to testify
before the Senate Judiciary Committee. He told the lawmakers
Wednesday that flag burning was an act of ``violence and
intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda recalled an incident during a 1976 baseball game at
Dodger Stadium against the Chicago Cubs in which two protesters ran
onto the field, soaked the American flag with lighter fluid and
ignited it.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Rick Monday ran at the protesters, grabbed the
burning flag and fled with it into the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who saw the incident then, and now, knows that the
protesters were doing something terrible, offensive and wrong,''
Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, who favors the amendment, told
the hearing that ``desecrating the flag is like spitting on the
memories of these brave men and women ... who made the ultimate
sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., said he strongly opposes the
amendment because it would limit Americans' First Amendment right
to freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``America stands today as the leader of the free world because
it tolerates varying forms of dissent,'' Feingold told the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said the United States should not align itself with
``oppressive, tyrannical'' governments like Cuba, Iran and Haiti,
which imprison people who desecrate the country's flag.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said those totalitarian countries protect their flags
out of fear ``that their citizens will gain free speech rights and
stand up in opposition to their oppressive regimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Flag Alliance, a coalition of civic, fraternal and
veterans groups, says there have been 20 acts of physical
desecration against the American flag in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill, a foe of the flag amendment, said
the nation has seen an increase in flag burning because Congress
keeps talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``By engaging in this discussion, we encourage copycats,''
Durbin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
