<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUT-ARCHITECTURE-ART-     07-08 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUT-ARCHITECTURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME CAN BE HAPPY LIVING IN A HUT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If summer is the season for celebrating simple things, ``A Hut
of One's Own: Life Outside the Circle of Architecture'' (M.I.T.
Press), by Ann Cline, is well timed. Its small subject _ the hut _
defines the field of architecture like a cricket in the grass. It
makes a song of the air around it.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-built and homemade, usually wooden, scraped together from
pieces of scrap or engineered with standard lumber, the hut is
barely design. It is as ordinary as a structure can be. But the hut
has an extraordinary gift.
</P>
<P>
   From Tang dynasty Chinese poets' pavilions secluded in the
mountains to present-day Puerto Rican casitas sunning themselves in
the Bronx, the hut is a shelter for the imagination. Marie
Antoinette had her hameau of huts. George Bernard Shaw wrote in a
shack at the foot of his garden. Seated outside civilization, the
hut, like Shaw, has had a good view of it.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston Bachelard, in his 1969 book, ``The Poetics of Space,''
called the dream of life in a hut ``the taproot of inhabiting.''
Nothing goes straighter to the source of the delight that springs
from dwelling. Second homes take a stab at it. There are now an
estimated five million in the United States _ indication enough
that informality is looking for a frontier upon which to reinvent
the house itself. Recreation homes reintroduce the necessary
connection between people and the rudiments of place. But huts
recreate the echo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cline, a professor of architecture at Miami University in
Oxford, Ohio, is one of many calling for a return to first
principles to re-engage her profession with its public. The
architects Frank Gehry and Cesar Pelli are among those who agree
that a study of basic structures could inform richer human sympathy
in the design of houses. Though Ms. Cline is not advocating life in
huts, they hold the power of illustration for a new generation of
architects and their audience.
</P>
<P>
   No one has to be talked into the satisfactions of the hut. It is
architecture's inner child. Many people who wouldn't know or
couldn't care where a design began or ended have built a fort from
a box, or put a house in a tree, created a workshop in a garage or
covered a porch to make a room. As the subtitle of Ms. Cline's book
makes clear, life goes on outside architecture's charmed circle.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cline likes huts, as a kind of quick example of what a
building can do, and of what can be done with a building. She has
built two herself, with off-the-shelf materials from a suburban Ace
hardware store and the help of a hired laborer. They stand in the
yard outside her Civil War-era house in Oxford. She plotted them
out as she put them up. Ms. Cline uses the smaller of the two,
which lives like an owl in a tree at the back of her property, as a
teahouse. The larger hut is an exhibition space for a rotating
collection of favorite objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my way of tiptoeing out of architecture,'' she said
recently, serving mugs of coffee and local strawberries in the
gallery of the large hut, built in 1995. A morning rain hit the
plywood roof three feet above like fingers lightly drumming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take much,'' she explained. ``If you have a corner
somewhere that's visually private, that corner could be developed
with one of these huts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cline maintains that huts have much to teach. As pieces of
pure construction, they translate the natural world into sensory
experience. It is a different kind of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could be in a wilderness,'' she said, pausing to let the
pattering above make its presence heard in the acoustically close
space. ``Because you really can't tell. It's the rain on the roof
that's the signal. When you go inside a house, you don't have
that.''
</P>
<P>
   If houses are interventions in the landscape, huts are
interpreters. They are like musical instruments or box cameras. A
window goes up and the outside comes in, like wind entering a
flute. A door opens and the inside walks out. One sees by the light
of its picture.
</P>
<P>
   Though her interest in huts is something of a hermit's pose, Ms.
Cline, 56, is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much in the air in schools,'' said Jaan Holt,
director of the Washington-Alexandria Architecture Consortium at
Virginia Polytechnic Institute in Alexandria, Va., which invites
architectural professors and students from Europe and Asia to work
together. ``There is a desire to have an architecture based on
materiality and discreet experience. I think it's a hunger for
architecture that's not programmatic _ that a building can exist
because one finds one's way into it, like a forest.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Frampton, a professor of architecture at Columbia
University, concurred that there is an interest in ``grounding the
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reduction of architecture to imagery and style has
consumed architectural practice and discourse for two decades,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To Frank Gehry, one-room structures have been the sparks that
ignite inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you strip a building down to its essence,'' he said,
``you're left with what it actually is: a shelter. A room that
engenders emotion. I think a lot of architecture hides behind
functionality and technology _ as architects, we have tremendous
excuses and denial mechanisms to make something special. How to get
around that?''
</P>
<P>
   Gehry recalled watching friends who were artists begin to paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you make the first mark? The one-room building _ the
hut, if you like _ is the closest you get in architecture to that
moment of truth. I think it's powerful _ I would urge young
architects to play with that. It gets you to the point a lot
quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cadwell, a professor of architecture at Ohio State
University, used the idea of hutlike construction as the kind of
sketching exercise an artist might employ. In the 1980s, Cadwell
built four structures based on the seasons, which he called ``a
pastoral quartet'' in a pamphlet, ``Small Buildings,'' published by
Princeton Architectural Press in 1996. Sited in open country at a
colleague's vacation home in Vermont, they are essays on
insideness. ``Drum-Barge,'' the summer building, floats on a lake.
One enters it by diving below it and hoisting oneself by rope
through its chamber to an observation deck at the top. The scene
drifts with the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Though a fascination to architecture, the hut remains outside
its circle. It belongs to lay builders, a bit of fire that the gods
would wish to steal. As well as a sensual life and a life of the
mind, it has its association with the soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``The construction of huts is associated with metaphysical
thought,'' said Cesar Pelli, who teaches architecture at Yale
University, speaking of nomadic structures like the black tents
built by Middle Eastern and North African cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are low-slung huts, built by women,'' he said. ``Air
passes through the skins of the walls, but not water.''
</P>
<P>
   When teaching, Pelli began lectures with huts. ``They are
dwellings in the most important metaphysical sense,'' he said.
``They carry with them the center of the cosmos. Once established,
they connect you with the earth, but put you at the center. It is
the world around that changes.''
</P>
<P>
   As a metaphor, the hut has taken one of its most remarkable
stands in New York. In the last 10 years, it has created an
architecture of exile for immigrants, in particular Puerto Ricans,
who have built casitas on vacant lots throughout the city, as
public meeting places within community gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Casitas are based on the ``casita de madera,'' or ``little
wooden house,'' that appears in the vernacular architecture of the
Taino Indians in Puerto Rico. For immigrants in New York, the
casitas are emblems of home, if home is how you hug the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are powerful memories, '' said Daniel Winterbottom, a
landscape architect who has been documenting New York's casitas for
four years with photographer Ejlat Feuer. ``They were summer
residences that were reminiscent of the Jibaro _ real but mythic
figures in Puerto Rico who made a life of their own in the
mountains. This myth of independence is what you see represented in
the casitas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Museo del Barrio in New York is organizing a show on casitas
in November, based on the work of Winterbottom and Feuer. Feuer
estimated that there are 500 casitas in New York, concentrated on
the Lower East Side of Manhattan and in the Melrose section of the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``These casitas are a metaphor for the old land,'' Winterbottom
said, ``but they are also a cultural healing: by creating a new
place, of respect and dignity, they are a declaration of control.
They have pretty tough neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Milagros Rodriguez stood on the porch of a casita
that she and Enrique Diaz initiated and preside over on Manhattan's
Lower East Side, at Fourth Street between Avenues C and D.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house is a celebration,'' she said. Friends walked in and
walked out. A family played cards beneath a tree. The red and white
hut was built on in 1992 by Diaz from abandoned lumber he hauled
there in his pickup truck. A kitchen and veranda were added last
year. ``The good thing about it, everybody pitches in,'' Ms.
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Built and furnished with donations, the casita has a latrine
behind it and an outdoor shower. Inside, there are a Persian-style
rug on the floor, paintings on the walls, two chairs in plastic
slipcovers and a sofa, a brass coffee table and a veneered
Blaupunkt stereo console from the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Because they sit on vacant lots, which are subject to
development, the casitas teach another lesson that one learns well
from huts. Many that have been built are gone; more are sure to go.
Ms. Rodriguez and Diaz's casita is built on a lot that is privately
owned. No one in the neighborhood who uses the casita knows whom
the lot belongs to. The house and its garden are living on prayers
for borrowed time.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Bohio'' on South Second Street in the Williamsburg section
of Brooklyn, a garden with a casita and a wooden hut, or ``bohio,''
organized and built by Harry LeBlon and his community, has not been
as lucky. City-owned, the lot is being developed in three months as
a day care center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where will it all go?'' asked LeBlon, pointing to the open
hut, whose roof is strung with artifacts of Puerto Rico, and a pine
tree, now 20 feet tall, that grew from a sapling on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Life, like huts, is temporary. That isn't stopping Ms.
Rodriguez, who has started over once before. She looked through the
front door of her casita.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need is a beach,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
