<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Making a Mac's Files Speak a PC's Language &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to transfer important files from my old Mac to my
new PC. What are my options?
</P>
<P>
   A. Incompatible floppy-disk formats have kept Mac and PC users
from freely transferring information on disks, but times have
changed.
</P>
<P>
   There are several programs available, like Dataviz's Mac Opener
and Pacific Micro's Mac-in-DOS, that will let your PC read a Mac
disk. And Apple Computer began including its PC Exchange software
in its operating system years ago to allow Mac users to read a
PC-formatted disk if you ever need to go the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Word-processing programs used in both worlds, like Microsoft
Word, can often open files on either platform with minimal
difficulty. If you don't have one of those programs but the files
you want to transfer are word-processing documents, you can open
them in your Mac's word-processing program and save them as ``plain
text'' files onto a floppy. Most word-processing programs on any
computer platform can open one of these basic text files, although
any special formatting or type styling will be stripped out. Move
the floppy to the PC and open (and save) your files with the PC's
word-processing programs. Or if you have Internet access on both
machines, try e-mailing text files to the new computer.
</P>
<P>
   If you have graphics files, spreadsheets, databases or specially
formatted documents like manuscripts, you can buy file-translation
software, like Dataviz's Conversions Plus for Windows, that will
convert them in their Mac applications to the nearest PC
equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com or postal mail to Questions, Circuits,
The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959.
This column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
