<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6068 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COPS-SPOOF-NYT &LR;      07-08 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COPS-SPOOF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREEN GRAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (JT)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the creator of ``Star Wars,'' George Lucas, has been
toiling on a new megamillion-dollar installment of the science
fiction saga, a weekend filmmaker with a home video camera, a
personal computer and some well-placed friends is discovering fame
and opportunity with a $1,500 vision of the ``Star Wars'' universe.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker, Kevin Rubio, said he had been inspired to create
``Troops'' by last year's special edition release of the ``Star
Wars'' trilogy. Rubio, 30, a cartoon animation worker in Los
Angeles, took six months to write the script and complete his
10-minute movie, which has lots of ``Star Wars'' technology and
dazzling special effects. It also offers what Rubio describes as a
comical, sympathetic take on the faceless, bad-guy minions of
``Star Wars,'' the imperial storm troopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troops'' has become immensely popular this year as an
underground film distributed at no cost on the Internet
 &UR; (www.TheForce.net) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Rubio said the film, which he also directed and co-produced, was
less a ``Star Wars'' pretender than a parody recast in the guise of
an episode of the syndicated television show ``Cops,'' which
follows real police officers on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just guys with jobs and happen to be on the Empire's
side,'' Rubio said of his storm troopers, whose head-to-toe body
armor uniforms, a dead-on imitation of the real ones, help give the
production a striking aura of authenticity. His troopers also
deliver their darkly comedic lines in a quirky ``Fargo'' accent as
they trudge and rocket over a barren, desert planet (a dry lake bed
in Southern California).
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, storm troopers gun down desert-scavenging Jawas
when they try to flee. A trooper says dryly, ``Well, what we had
here was that these Jawas had stolen some imperial property and it
unfortunately turned violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the film's popularity and near-cult following, Rubio
said, he is now shopping around ideas for feature film projects,
has a development deal with MTV and is represented by the William
Morris Agency _ though he hasn't quit his day job.
</P>
<P>
   All the attention that Rubio is receiving does not surprise
Chris Gore, publisher of Film Threat Weekly, a magazine that covers
underground filmmaking and that picked ``Troops'' as the best
underground film of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was especially impressed with the movie's special
effects and their implications for the film industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this film means is that basically anyone with a home
computer can do the same kinds of fantastic special effects we see
at the movie theaters,'' he said, though he said it also took
talent like Rubio's to use the technology artistically.
</P>
<P>
   The special effects _ including sand-skimming speeders and
low-flying imperial attack ships _ were created in three days by
Shant Jordan, 30, and Patrick Perez, 29. Both work for Netter
Digital Entertainment of North Hollywood, Calif., where they
supervise the making of special effects for the television space
series ``Babylon 5.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Perez, co-producers of ``Troops,'' said they used
off-the-shelf software, Lightwave 3-D, and a 600-megahertz Digital
Equipment Corporation computer to crank out the effects shortly
before the film's debut last July at the San Diego Comic Con
International. ``It was pretty scary,'' Perez said with a chuckle,
``but we wanted to have a crack at it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
