<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-CAMPERS-2TAKES-N     07-08 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CAMPERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED RV'ERS RIDE OFF INTO THE SUNRISE, TO KEEP THE SUNSET AT
BAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT W. STOCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON, Texas _ For years, whenever vacation time rolled
around, LaVere and Ginny Keller would roll out of Salt Lake City in
their camper truck and explore the West. ``It was pretty tight
quarters, especially when our three daughters were with us,''
Keller recalled. ``But we loved it. We'd get home, and we'd say,
`Wouldn't it be great if we could just keep going?'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, both at age 59, they did just that. The Kellers
retired, sold their house, bought a trailer and a truck to tow it,
and took to the road full time. At Rainbow's End, a camp for up to
400 recreational vehicles here in the piney woods of East Texas,
they joyously described the changes in their lives _ the 17 states
they have toured, the new friends they have made at RV camps along
the way and most of all, the new freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 30 years of working and raising a family, we get to go
wherever we want, do whatever we want,'' Mrs. Keller said. ``I
still feel it's like a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kellers are not alone on the road. Some 8.6 million families
in the United States own recreational vehicles, most dedicated to
occasional family trips or annual winter flights to the Sun Belt.
The Recreational Vehicle Industry Association says that more than a
million of those families are ``full-timers,'' houseless nomads
like the Kellers, who set out on their greatest adventure at an age
when most people traditionally are looking forward to a rocking
chair. Experts say their ranks are growing, with baby boomers
taking early retirement and an older generation holding higher
expectations and an energy level to match.
</P>
<P>
   Full-timers typically traverse a bittersweet life cycle. They
start out as nonstop sightseers in a motor home or pulling a big
trailer. Sooner or later, aches and pains make driving difficult;
they trade down to a smaller rig and spend more time at favorite
camper sites. Eventually, they and their rig reach full rest in one
of those camps _ or in a driveway, connected by electric and water
life-support lines to the house of a son or daughter. Some sell
their rigs and enter nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   But now, when it comes time for them to hang up their keys, as
they put it, some full-timers have a new option. At Rainbow's End,
the site of the national headquarters of a recreational vehicle
club called the Escapees, ailing members can get the help they need
while remaining in their motor homes and continuing the RV life.
The program is called CARE, for Continuing Assistance for Retired
Escapees, and those in this peripatetic world say it is the first
of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, life in a recreational vehicle is not for everyone.
Even in a luxurious, $180,000, 36-foot-long motor home, as my wife
and I discovered during a four-night stay, privacy is nonexistent _
you can't get out of each other's way _ and claustrophobia is high.
Every experienced full-timer has a story to tell about a couple
whose marriage broke up after six months of nonstop intimacy.
Wives, in particular, complain about the shortage of space _ for
clothing, for family heirlooms, for the paintings and furniture
that helped give structure and warmth to their old stationary
homes. But most of all, they miss their children and grandchildren.
The occasional letter, phone call or once-a-year visit turns out
not to be enough for some full-timers, who either quit the life or
markedly cut back their road time.
</P>
<P>
   Family weighs on the minds of Barton and Martha Anderson. In
February 1996, a week after the last of their three daughters
married, the couple _ he was 70; she, 68 _ set out from southern
Connecticut as full-timers. They have traveled 29,000 miles since,
and they have no intention of stopping. But they do miss their
grandchildren. ``Martha wants to spend the summer back in
Connecticut,'' he said. ``I want to go for a few weeks.'' He
shrugged and added, ``We'll probably stay the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Full-timers have their own special customs and ethos, including
nonstop sociability and an eager readiness to help a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   In the mornings, the lawn chairs go out under the vehicle
awnings, the dog walkers parade and everybody gets acquainted. Some
full-timers go sightseeing. Some attend camp classes in crafts or
line dancing or count their laps in the swimming pool. Others
putter, repairing or polishing their rigs or reading maps or
history books for the next leg of their journey. After an early
supper in the rig, or an occasional campwide potluck dinner, there
is more strolling and chatting. By day's end, new friendships have
been formed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Having given up their old communities, these nomads consciously
set about creating new ones based on their identity as full-timers,
say David R. and Dorothy A. Counts, a Canadian husband-and-wife
team of anthropologists who wrote ``Over the Next Hill: An
Ethnography of RVing Seniors in North America'' (Broadview Press,
1996). The full-timers join together in clubs, design their
itineraries around meetings of club chapters and seek each other
out at campsites. Friendships develop rapidly, because full-timers
know they will be moving on.
</P>
<P>
   For LaVere Keller, that took some getting used to. ``You meet
wonderful people, you get so close and then they leave and you know
you may never see them again,'' he said. ``I'm a real sentimental
kind of person. I still cry when they leave, but I've learned to
let go.''
</P>
<P>
   For many full-timers who must retire from the road, the prospect
of losing their adopted community is devastating. Dorothy Jackson
felt that way when her eyesight worsened and forced her off the
road, but she learned about the CARE program at Rainbow's End and
in 1995 became one of the first participants.
</P>
<P>
   D.J., as she is known, is tiny, spirited and 84. After her
husband died, she raised their four children alone, working as a
psychiatric nurse in Gallup, N.M. In the 1970s, she set off on her
own in a recreational vehicle. ``I learned how to do it the hard
way,'' she said. ``When things broke down, I read repair books.''
She was primarily a boondocker, a full-timer who spends most nights
not in organized camps but in church or school parking lots or
highway rest areas. Boondockers can be footloose and spontaneous in
their travel and in saving camp fees _ a consideration, because
many live on a shoestring.
</P>
<P>
   At CARE, she is one of 28 participants; the center and the
parking area are being expanded to accommodate 14 more. The
participants pay a basic fee of $450 a month, which covers parking
and hookup for their rigs, housekeeping and laundry services, and
exercise and crafts classes at the center, where a nurse is on duty
to monitor their blood pressure and general health. Breakfast and
lunch are available at extra cost.
</P>
<P>
   Half the participants, like D.J. Jackson, stop in for meals or
exercise classes but go their own way most of the day. The other
half receive full-time care during the center's hours, which costs
$100 a month more. The staff bathes them, changes their dressings
and gives them their medicines. Nurses are on call nights and
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The Countses, the Canadian anthropologists, say they would like
to see the CARE concept spread to other sites around the continent.
``Full-timers need to be able to maintain their personal
independence,'' David Counts said. ``CARE does that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the communal breakfast table one day, a husband sat patiently
feeding his wife. The husband, Ray Gearing, is a retired
Presbyterian minister from Little Rock, Ark., a film-star-handsome
man of 72 who lives in his recreational vehicle in the CARE parking
lot. His wife, Ruth, 71, has Alzheimer's disease and lives with him
but spends eight hours a day at the center. ``When she got angry
once in a while, I could deal with that,'' her husband said. ``But
when it would go on for hours or a whole day, I just needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gearings had dreamed of being full-timers for 15 years, ever
since the night they heard mysterious music while camping out in
sleeping bags on a deserted beach on the Texas coast. ``I thought
my teeth were receiving radio waves,'' Gearing recalled, but in the
morning they discovered a motor home, occupied by a concert harpist
and her husband, parked nearby. ``They were our first
full-timers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, he retired, and they sold their house in Little Rock
and set forth in a 32-foot motor home. When his wife's health began
to fail, he took over more responsibilities and they drove on,
visiting 49 states. But after a final trip, to Alaska in the summer
of 1996, he guided their vehicle to its resting place at Rainbow's
End.
</P>
<P>
   Gearing takes his wife along to camp events, when her health
permits. ``She's a happy person at the center most of the time,''
he said. ``She has a life, and I have a life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
