<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CLEMENS ALL OVER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ I hate contract stories more than you do. Like most
sports fans, I'd rather just hear about it when it's over.
</P>
<P>
   I also loathe today's agents and ballplayers for their greedy
practice of scorekeeping. If you're offered $37 million over four
years, what more will you be able to buy if you can jack the price
up to $42 million? This is what ballplayers really mean when they
say it's not about the money. ``Not about the money'' is code for
(itals)``Nine million a year? You mean you don't even think I'm as
good as Roy Hobbs, who's making $9.5 million?''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, I hate when the word ``insult'' appears in the same
paragraph with a $20 million offer to play baseball. Have we all
lost our minds? Market value is market value, but it's offensive to
talk about ``insulting'' million-dollar offers to ballplayers when
there are millions of people working two jobs trying to keep food
on the table.
</P>
<P>
   There. Now that I've addressed all that, let me blast the Red
Sox for getting themselves into this silly situation with their
heart-and-soul, blood-and-thunder first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox said this would not happen. They said there would be
no repeat of the Roger Clemens fiasco. They said they would never
again put themselves in position to lose a franchise player in
exchange for a mere draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   But if you've just turned on your radios, ladies and gentlemen,
it's happened again.
</P>
<P>
   Contract talks were held when the Sox brass convened with Mo
Vaughn's people at the All-Star festival in Denver. The Sox
reportedly added two years to their offer, going from $20.4 million
over two years to $37 million over four. Vaughn's people turned it
down. Sox general manager Dan Duquette says trading Mo is not an
option. The All-Star break is over, play resumes in Baltimore
Thursday night, and both sides agree there will be no more
negotiations until the completion of the season.
</P>
<P>
   This means Mo will have the option to walk just like Clemens
did. The Sox will lose their exclusive right to negotiate with
Vaughn about six weeks after the World Series ends. And if Mo
chooses to accept an offer from the Orioles, Blue Jays, Yankees, or
Mets, there is nothing Boston can do.
</P>
<P>
   We can argue the merits of the offer. Thirty-seven million
sounds pretty good to most of us, and the offer would put Mo in the
same category with the estimable Mark McGwire, who took the
``hometown discount'' to stay in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   It is a legitimate offer, one that any player would have to
consider if he (itals)were(unitals) serious about staying here.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the Sox' other contract offers has been the
``insulting'' aspect for Mo. A two-year offer to a 30-year-old
player with Vaughn's resume was, in fact, a message to Vaughn that
he was not wanted. But now the Sox have gone to four years. That's
a big step for an organization which has expressed concerns about
Vaughn's lifetsyle and future fitness.
</P>
<P>
   A four-year offer should be negotiable for the Vaughn camp. If
it's not we can only assume that either Mo is totally annoyed with
the ``joint chiefs of staff'' (his expression) in the front office,
or he's already made up his mind that he'd look better in Blue Jay
feathers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox are left with the egg on their faces because
management had a chance to deal with this earlier and chose to let
Vaughn twist in the wind while the Reggie Jefferssons, Scott
Fletchers, and Troy O'Learys were rewarded with multi-year pacts.
</P>
<P>
   It's always been a melodrama when contract talks concern Vaughn,
and I always wonder if it's because he's not a Duquette ``find.''
</P>
<P>
   From the ground crew to the starting lineup, folks at Fenway
know that people who were here before Duquette have been held to a
different standard than those brought in by the Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette is having a sensational season. It looks as if the Red
Sox are bound for the playoffs and it's not a stretch to see them
upsetting one or two giants (Indians, Yankees?) in a short series.
Life should be good on Yawkey Way, but the cloud of Mo hangs over
the local nine and the Sox should never have gotten themselves back
in this position.
</P>
<P>
   They should have learned their lesson from Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
