<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUT STILL FEELING EFFECTS OF LONG STAY ABOARD MIR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A month after his return to Earth from a visit to
Russia's Mir space station, U.S. astronaut Andy Thomas said
Wednesday that he's regaining the physical strength drained by 141
days of weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old, Australian-born engineer returned to Earth on
June 12 aboard the shuttle Discovery, the seventh and final
American to live and work aboard Mir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been having a wonderful time,'' said Thomas, who looked
tanned and rested during a succession of interviews at NASA's
Johnson Space Center in far south Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas blasted off for Mir in January. His return signaled the
start of a lengthy rehabilitation effort to rebuild his bones and
muscles as well as retune his nervous system to gravity.
</P>
<P>
   The initial wave of nausea and disorientation that followed his
landing has subsided. The muscles in his neck and shoulders still
respond with pain, though he's graduated from the initial
low-impact exercise regime of the swimming pool at NASA to aerobic
workouts, jogging and lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I have professional commitments,'' Thomas said,
``I have a lot more freedom than I've enjoyed for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, NASA assigned Thomas to the months of Russian
language training and demanding technical preparations for a
mission to Mir as a backup. However, the near disastrous collision
in June 1997 between Mir and a rogue Progress cargo capsule changed
the physical requirements for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   An astronaut of smaller stature who could not wear a Russian
space suit was pulled from the original lineup of U.S. visitors,
creating a flight opportunity for Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These (long) missions are very difficult, perhaps the hardest
thing I've ever attempted in my professional career,'' he said.
``It takes a lot of determination and a lot of soul searching. The
personal reward is that I was able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Mir is staffed by cosmonauts Talgat Musabayev and
Nikolai Budarin, with whom Thomas served.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians plan to replace the cosmonauts in August with
another crew.
</P>
<P>
   Mir is nearing its scheduled demise, and NASA has no plans to
send another space shuttle to the aging orbital outpost unless some
sort of emergency required it, said Jim Van Laak, the deputy
manager of the agency's cooperative human spaceflight program with
the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   If NASA and Russia begin the orbital assembly of the U.S.-led
international space station in late November as scheduled, the
Russians plan to propel the more than 200,000-pound outpost into
the ocean in mid-1999. Agreed to by the United States and Russia
last spring, the scheme was re-verified by the Russians earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans, which could be derailed by Russia's financial
problems, would place a final three-man crew aboard Mir in
February. They would be joined by a new larger version of the
Progress supply ship configured with the propulsion needed to
provide the the push that would send Mir into the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
