<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-SLOWDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND NUMBERS INDICATE ECONOMIC SLOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An index of business activity in New England fell in April and
stayed low in May, adding new evidence that a recession sweeping
through Southeast Asia and Japan is causing a slowdown in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   The economic index, prepared by BankBoston Corp., was below the
crucial 50-mark for two consecutive months, its worst reading since
the 1991-1992 recession. The index measures shipments, profits, new
orders, and employment of companies in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Economists are watching indicators such as these closely for red
flags. There is a widespread belief that the US economy will shift
into low gear later this year as Asia's crisis hits home.
</P>
<P>
   The US economy is nowhere near a recession. The economy is still
growing, albeit more slowly, and unemployment has held at record
lows both nationally and in Massachusetts for months. The state's
jobless rate was 3.6 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
   But BankBoston's index shows that the Asia effect is ``showing
up earlier in New England,'' said Wayne Ayers, the bank's chief
economist.
</P>
<P>
   During the long-running economic expansion of recent years, New
England has ``moved in sync with the rest of the country,'' Ayers
said. ``It's curious we've seen this weakness showing up in the
region and it seems to be more severe. What I'm saying is this may
be a leading indicator for the US as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Turmoil in Asian economies can affect US firms in many ways. The
most obvious is that exports fall as Asia's recession reduces sales
by Asian companies both internally and to trading partners in the
troubled region.
</P>
<P>
   A second reason is that US companies find it is more difficult
to compete in global markets against Asian products that are
dropping in price due to the plunging value of their currencies.
</P>
<P>
   There is mounting anecdotal evidence of Asia fallout in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Parametric Technology Inc., one of the Boston
area's hottest companies, watched its stock plunge by more than a
third due to concerns Asia's troubles were choking demand for its
software. Sales by companies that make semiconductor equipment and
products for the Japanese chip industry have been hard hit. More
evidence is expected when companies begin reporting second-quarter
sales later this month.
</P>
<P>
   These companies are part of a national trend, according to a
bellwether index of US growth derived from a survey of American
purchasing managers. The purchasing managers' index also dropped
below the 50 mark _ to 49.6 in June _ for the first time since the
plunge in the Mexican peso and Latin American currencies rocked the
US economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact in this country of Asia's crisis is expected to
last far longer than did the crisis in South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the difficulties about 1998 is that the areas that are
affected are far larger, if you include Japan,'' said Fred
Breimyer, chief econmist for State Street Bank &AMP; Trust Co. in
Boston. ``It is not contained. We're looking for the Japanese to
contain it not only for themselves but for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Troubles are most acute in the high-technology sector but are
not limited to that sector, economists said. BankBoston's index is
derived from surveys of 1,100 chief executives of manufacturing and
non-manufacturing companies in the six New England states.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's index fell from 52.8 in March to 47.0 in April and
remained virtually flat at 47.1 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been below 50 for three of the past five months.
That is the index's worst showing since the 1991-92 recession, New
England's worst economic slump in the post-war period. When the
index is above 50, the economy is expanding; below 50, the economy
is contracting, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Although the unemployment rate remains low in Massachusetts,
the pace of job growth is slowing. The jobless rate increased to
3.6 percent in May, from 2.9 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   The US jobless rate also rose, by 0.2 percentage points, to 4.5
percent in June, and labor force grew by 83,000, an indication of
less demand for new workers.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic slowdown has a silver lining: It calms fears
that inflation is starting to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Asian situation were not hitting, the Federal Reserve
would be raising rates,'' Breimyer said. ``Even bad news translates
to good news in this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
