<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6121 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-CABARET-COX     07-08 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-CABARET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Come to this `Cabaret' for a bawdy '90s bash
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not Liza Minnelli's ``Cabaret.'' Forget the shimmer.
Forget the shine. This is a decadent ``Cabaret'' for the '90s,
deliciously delivered to disc by Tony Award winners Alan Cumming
and Natasha Richardson. It's a sexy, raw, in-your-face ``Cabaret,''
one that makes the 32-year-old musical seem brand-new. Every inch
of its bawdy veneer _ the desperation of those living on a
shoestring, the chin-up fortitude of an old maid pondering her
future, the sex-with-a-shrug nature of its bruised and
needle-marked dancing girls _ comes through, chillingly.
</P>
<P>
   If the goal of a cast album is to re-create the theater
experience, and it should be, ``Cabaret'' succeeds mightily. The
listener almost expects to see Cumming's likable, lascivious Emcee
come slinking around a corner or Richardson's needy Sally Bowles
smoking on the divan.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Cabaret'' has jettisoned several songs from the original
(``Meeskite,'' ``Why Should I Wake Up?'') and added several from
the 1972 movie (``The Money Song,'' ``Mein Herr,'' ``Maybe This
Time'' and ``I Don't Care Much''). The changes make this album
essential listening for any lover of ``Cabaret'' or its musical
team, composer John Kander and lyricist Fred Ebb. It may also be
the only way fans can experience Richardson's Bowles. ``Cabaret''
is one of Broadway's toughest tickets, and she finishes her run
Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   One challenge of her performance, Richardson has said more than
once, is being ``not Liza.'' She needn't worry. Her Sally is worlds
away from Minnelli's, and in this time, at this place, worlds
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabaret''
</P>
<P>
   The new Broadway cast.
</P>
<P>
   RCA Victor. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A perfectly marvelous cast album.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-HARDING-COX     07-08 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HARDING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florence Harding _ confined to obscurity because of her
husband's scandals _ gets her due
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 12: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If first ladies were judged on their own deeds, Florence Harding
would rank among the achievers, writes historian Carl Sferrazza
Anthony. ``Instead she was doomed to be known as the wife of the
greatest failure in the presidency.'' Volumes have been written on
Jacqueline Kennedy and Eleanor Roosevelt, but Mrs. Warren G.
Harding has dwelt in footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony restores her to history and presents a strong case for
her importance as a prototypical 20th-century first lady. His
research seems meticulous, but excessive documentation often makes
for tortuous reading. Florence's portrait, reconstructed from
shards after she burned many of her papers, emerges as distantly
seen, almost as if she lived in the 18th century instead of our
own. Still, the fascinating book makes the adventures of Hill and
Bill seem tame.
</P>
<P>
   The 29th president left a sordid trail: scandals, affairs,
alleged illegitimate children and blackmail funds. Florence herself
was no Victorian. She became pregnant out of wedlock, relied on
astrology, was rumored to have poisoned the president and destroyed
official documents after his death. But she was a force in the
first election in which millions of women could vote, and her
legacy is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   Flossie Kling, born in 1860 in Marion, Ohio, was the daughter of
a domineering father who developed her head for business. At 19 she
became pregnant, probably by Henry De Wolfe, whom Anthony says she
never married. Henry left her and son Marshall, and after
struggling financially she gave up the child to her father, and
``essentially ended her obligations of motherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Florence admired the ``stalwart physique'' of Warren G. Harding,
owner and editor of the Marion Star, even if his moral fiber was
less resolute. He enjoyed drinking and playing poker and had a
``ravenous appetite for sexual adventure with women.'' Florence
courted the younger Warren, enraging her father, who furthered
rumors that the Hardings had African blood.
</P>
<P>
   After marrying in 1891, Florence took over the newspaper's
business dealings, but her main profession was Warren Harding. One
wonders at her faith in his potential. Three years into their
marriage, Harding had an affair and a child with Florence's
childhood neighbor, Anthony writes. Florence developed the
philosophy that the happy wife makes ``the best of what she has
got.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1899, Warren was elected to the Ohio Senate, in 1903 to the
lieutenant governorship. He was maneuvering toward the
gubernatorial nomination in 1905 when Florence became ill with the
nephritis that plagued her for years and finally killed her. During
her hospitalization, he began a long affair with her best friend,
Carrie Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   When the Duchess (Warren's nickname for Florence) discovered the
betrayal, she threatened divorce, but backed off. ``She had
invested everything she had into the very idea of `Harding' as her
career,'' Anthony writes. She channeled her energy toward getting
him elected to the U.S. Senate in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Alice Roosevelt Longworth introduced Florence to
Evalyn McLean and they became unlikely lifelong friends. Flamboyant
Evalyn was married to the Washington Post heir and owned the Hope
diamond. Some presumed she and Florence were lesbians, but Anthony
concludes theirs might have been a ``romantic friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren had passions of his own, carrying on simultaneous affairs
with Phillips; Nan Britton, who claimed they begot a daughter in
his Senate office; and Grace Cross, one of his staffers. Still, he
was mentioned as a presidential hopeful, although Florence was
uncharacteristically leery of his candidacy. Madame Marcia, her
favorite astrologer, had predicted that Warren would be elected
only to die in office. But politics was in Florence's blood, and
when it seemed her husband would lose, she ordered him to stay in
the 1920 race. After he was nominated, Florence wrote socialist
Norman Thomas that she ``was very much afraid.'' She had reason.
Several women used Warren's love letters as blackmail and some
Republicans set up a payoff fund.
</P>
<P>
   During the Hardings' 2 1/2 years in office, Florence was loved
by the public. She supported veterans' causes, initiated press
conferences for women reporters, flew in an airplane, spoke up for
women's equality and physical fitness and opposed vivisection. She
opened the White House to the public, helped immigrant children and
fostered the first federal prison for women.
</P>
<P>
   Just as scandals loomed, the president died, most likely of a
heart attack, 75 years ago in San Francisco. Anthony finds no
evidence of foul play but concludes there was a cover-up to protect
a family doctor who may have misdiagnosed the illness.
</P>
<P>
   After her husband's death, Florence took on the task of
salvaging his memory, burning everything that could be
``misconstrued'' _ about half his papers. Ultimately, her efforts
came to naught: Warren's reputation soon unraveled with the Teapot
Dome scandal. Her own stature slipped months after her 1924 death.
Florence's astrologer peddled her revelations to magazines, her
destruction of presidential papers made headlines and a 1930 book
charged that she had conspired with the family doctor to kill the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Florence Harding!'' a Senate wife recalled. ``If only she
had married differently, or if she could have dared for herself, as
in some other day she might!'' Yet, 75 years after her reign,
little has changed. Hillary Rodham Clinton's reputation still will
largely rise and fall according to her husband's. And no woman has
yet dared for herself to the highest office in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
