<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE12-COX     07-08 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Plato apologist raises postmodernists' ire
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 12: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anonymous mail is the sign you've struck the right nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Grabar had the temerity to write an essay for the opinion
page of The Atlanta Constitution recently, only to find herself the
target of cowards in hoods. She shouldn't have been surprised. You
can say things that most intelligent people would think
commonsensical. But graduate students in the humanities aren't most
people.
</P>
<P>
   Grabar is herself a graduate student _ in English, no less _ and
that is what made her opinion-page piece unusual. It was the kind
of heresy not tolerated in the faculty lounge. The trendinistas
took over the place in the '80s, and only a fool asks about free
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In universities today, free inquiry is a relic of the
``hegemonic'' past, when ``power relations'' were not yet fully
understood and the gospels of Jacques Derrida, Jacques Lacan and
Michel Foucault were not yet nailed to every classroom door.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they are, no one dares question them _ not if she
expects to get tenure.
</P>
<P>
   What Grabar said was obvious enough, even if it failed by the
standards of a good manifesto. Her tone was too reasonable. But
then, she was proposing that a liberal education restore reason and
logic, twin pillars of the Western tradition, to their former
place. Specifically, she suggested that students had more to learn
from Plato than from the postmodernists whose drivel is dogma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alarmingly,'' she wrote, ``Plato, even in graduate seminars,
is popularly referred to as totalitarian, fascist and sexist _
without a respectable and close investigation of his works and
arguments. That the Western philosophical aspiration to use logic
and reason can be traced back to him is rarely acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead ... Foucault is popularly accepted as the high priest
of postmodernists, the group that espouses the ideals of relativism
and multiculturalism and disdains Western institutions and ideas.
With such a point of view in vogue, we cannot expect that history,
literature or philosophy will be taught evenhandedly or
impartially. Sad to say, politics has replaced philosophy in our
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate injustice
</P>
<P>
   I cheered that paragraph, even as I disputed the implication
that Plato was liberal in his premises and conclusions. It's a
complicated subject, long debated by scholars. The important point,
as Grabar made in a telephone conversation, is that Plato, in ``The
Republic,'' asked the important questions _ above all, What is
Justice? _ and let readers wrestle not only with competing ideas
but with their own.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find students wrestling with them these days. For one
thing, they're out of shape (``Most freshman I teach at the
University of Georgia, the state's flagship institution of higher
learning, know little or nothing about Plato''). For another, their
masters on the faculty don't want that kind of intellectual
exercise. They want to dispense their dogmas, imported from Paris,
potted like so many petunias, without dissent.
</P>
<P>
   One is that the Western intellectual tradition, from Plato on,
is a sham. Remember that songfest at Stanford back in the '80s when
the Rev. Jesse Jackson led the boys and girls in chanting, ``Hey,
hey, ho, ho, Western culture's got to go''? Some of the chanters
turned out to be not puerile, impressionable students, but
assistant professors _ who can be just as puerile, just as
impressionable as any sophomore. They called to mind Bazarov in
Turgenev's ``Fathers and Sons,'' the nihilist who would destroy for
the sake of destroying.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as Grabar implies but doesn't quite say, the Western
intellectual tradition is anything but a closed church. Aristotle
parted with Plato on important points. Aquinas was indebted to
Aristotle. Machiavelli, misunderstood by most who utter his name,
anticipated the power theorists of Realpolitik. Kant and Hegel were
on opposite sides of a fence from Locke and Hume. Marx understood
freedom in terms of social class, John Stuart Mill in terms of the
individual.
</P>
<P>
   Tolerance gets short shrift
</P>
<P>
   You cannot very well understand the conflicts that divide the
world without understanding the competing ideas that gave rise to
Western philosophy and literature. One of the byproducts of those
conflicts and those ideas is tolerance, a value that thinkers who
disagreed on everything else have held in common.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a value held in much regard in the humanities
departments. Mary Grabar's unsigned mail from people whose
convictions exceeded their courage was proof of that. One letter
writer accused her of being part of the hegemonic, Eurocentric
something or other _ one of the all-purpose cliches that
substitutes for thought.
</P>
<P>
   If Grabar was irritated, she had to be amused as well. ``I was
born in Slovenia, which didn't even gain its independence until
1991,'' she says. ``Yet here I am lumped in with the oppressors.''
</P>
<P>
   But how do you respond to the nameless? What, in any case, can
you say to people who wouldn't know Plato from Pluto?
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
