</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGS-SHAVING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A little sugar goes long way to smooth legs
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 12: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, a sweet solution to shaving your legs.
</P>
<P>
   Sugaring, one of the newest salon methods for removing unwanted
hair, is also one of the oldest. The syruplike recipe _ sugar,
lemon juice and herbs _ has been used by Middle Eastern and
Mediterranean women for centuries, often before their wedding
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's similar to waxing but gentle on the skin,'' says
Katherine Volkmann, owner of Atlanta's Salon Oxygen, which
``sugars'' 15 to 20 clients a week.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanette Hart, 19, usually waxes her legs but wanted to try
something less painful.
</P>
<P>
   First, Volkmann washed and dried the college student's leg, then
dusted on powder to remove all moisture. With a metal spatula, she
carefully applied the sugar mixture from a heated pot, using long
smooth strokes. On the leg, it looked like a sheer strip of
cellophane. ``It feels a little warm,'' said Hart. ``But not as hot
as wax.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, Volkmann applied a muslin strip to the leg, making certain
the sugar mixture adhered. Then she quickly pulled the strip off _
in the opposite direction of the hair growth _ removing the hair by
the root. When each leg was finished, she spritzed on toner to
remove any sugar residue, then applied a soothing lotion. Volkmann
recommended Hart not go swimming or put any lotions on her legs for
the next 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   And did the process hurt? ``There was a little bit of a sting
when Katherine pulled off the strip,'' says Hart. ``But it didn't
hurt nearly as much as a wax treatment and my legs are super soft.
I'm a convert.''
</P>
<P>
   Sugaring legs takes about half an hour and costs $25 to do from
ankles to knees; a full leg sugaring (ankle to thigh) is $45; a
full leg and bikini sugaring is $60. For best results, you should
have 1/4-inch hair growth on your legs. Treatments generally last
four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While there are sugaring kits on the market _ Sweet Simplicity,
Surgi-Sweet and Body Sugar _ Volkmann urges caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pulling the muslin strips off improperly can cause bruising,''
she says. ``Better to go to a licensed esthetician who has been
trained in sugaring.''
</P>
<P>
   The high and low ends of new hair removers
</P>
<P>
   High tech: Laser
</P>
<P>
   By targeting the hair follicle, lasers slow hair growth. Some
patients have permanent hair removal; others will have ``peach
fuzz'' or a combination. No guarantee that hair won't grow back.
</P>
<P>
   Procedure: Legs must be shaved first before being scanned with a
laser. Treatment can take minutes or hours, depending on size of
target area.
</P>
<P>
   How it feels: Like the snap of a small rubber band or static
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Works best on: Dark-haired people with pale skin; not
recommended for African-Americans, Hispanics or Asians because it
can damage surrounding skin.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance: After initial treatment, touch-ups needed every six
to eight weeks; then every eight to 10 weeks until hair is gone;
time differs with patient.
</P>
<P>
   Fees: Lower legs from $400 to $700 per treatment; legs and
thighs from $750 to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Dr. David H. McDaniel, director, Laser Center of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Laser info: 1-800-441-2737.
</P>
<P>
   Low-tech: Hair Off Mitten
</P>
<P>
   Hoping you'll ``get smitten with the Mitten,'' CCA Industries
touts the ease and safety of this buffing glove.
</P>
<P>
   Procedure: Rub hair off dry skin a circle at a time. Easy
enough, but requires a little elbow grease.
</P>
<P>
   How it feels: Like fine-grade sandpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Works best on: Those who fear the razor or want to work the
upper arm.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eileen Drennen, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
