<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sheers, pastels key to cool, polished look in the summer heat
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 12: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question of which _ if any _ hosiery to wear in the
summertime qualifies as a ``Darned if you do, darned if you don't''
predicament.
</P>
<P>
   Thin though it is, hosiery's still one extra layer that many
women would rather leave home when the temperature climbs. But many
don't have a choice: Due to social or professional dictates, they
simply can't go bare-legged.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have a meeting or presentations to make, I make mad
dashes from the apartment to the car and from the car to the office
because wearing stockings in 90-degree heat for more than five
minutes makes you feel sticky and uncomfortable,'' said Cherry
Banez, a 32-year-old who works for the Atlanta Hawks' special
events division.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all that, there's the difficulty of finding hosiery
that goes with summer styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just go for the nudes,'' said Banez, ``because they work
with summertime clothes, they're sexy and they're professional.''
</P>
<P>
   The pros agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out in the heat, sheers are probably the most
comfortable thing to wear,'' said Felicia Leyva, hosiery and
accessories manager for Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Nordstrom's Lynn Clune recommends stockings and thigh-highs,
``because then you don't have the panty top to deal with.'' Both
Leyva and Don Purcell, manager at Bob Ellis Shoes at Phipps Plaza
in Atlanta, tout Donna Karan's new seven-shade ``Nudes'' collection
as their customers' preferred choice. The seven shades span the
gamut of skin tones and look just as refined as the sheer black
hosiery worn during the cooler months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're ultra-sheer,'' said Purcell. ``They look like you have
nothing on your legs at all, but they give a nice finished look.
They're great with open-toed shoes, and they're woven loosely to
let a little more air in.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cool looks this season include hosiery in pale pastel
shades of pink, lavender, yellow and green to be worn as
alternatives to the traditional summer off-whites, and styles woven
from ultra-thin nylon fibers to make them feel lighter.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least to let you look like the heat's not beating you.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's important,'' said Banez. ``You know how it is with us
women sometimes; it's as much about appearance as it is about
comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
