</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tillis bumped, bruised and better than ever
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul McCartney once said that his best work came out of times of
greatest pain. Two decades later, here's country singer Pam Tillis
proving that theory. This material, recorded during the breakup of
her long-term marriage, is perhaps the most creative and richest
work she's ever done.
</P>
<P>
   Tillis has turned her personal trauma into a musical strength
never heard during her hit-driven career. She's abandoned her
perky, cowgirl style for a more mature sound, not unlike Trisha
Yearwood's best country outings. But don't think slick. Tillis
hasn't turned into a VH1 diva. As in a comfy old farmhouse, the
country foundations are all still here: crying pedal steel,
acoustic guitar, mandolin and searing fiddle. And despite the
personal bumps driving the music, Tillis hasn't taken the morose
route.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she has concentrated on finding tunes that are fresh
without being contrived, and as hard-hitting as a whiskey chaser:
``Ain't tried cigarettes; / There's always alcohol. / I could stay
up all night long. / I've got credit cards; / I could run 'em up. /
If I really want to hurt myself, / I know where to find you.''
``Not Me'' is an I'm-not-gonna-take-it-anymore anthem in which she
declares, ``I won't go through that again, no, not me.'' She's
closing down the bar in ``After Hours,'' getting up and ``going
through the motions of my life'' in ``A Great Disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of country album that makes the repeat button
worth having. There simply isn't a bad track on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Time''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Tillis. Arista. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: She transcends the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS09-COX     07-08 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio reviews of the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Susan Elliott, Doug Hamilton, Shane Harrison, Sonia Murray,
and Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- FOLK-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Mermaid Avenue''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Bragg and Wilco.
</P>
<P>
   Elektra. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Folk music eminence Woody Guthrie left behind more than a
powerful influence on Bob Dylan and Bruce Springsteen. There are
more than 1,000 complete Guthrie lyrics in the archives. His
daughter Nora approached Billy Bragg _ like her father a
left-leaning, politically charged songsmith _ with the offer of
putting tunes to the words. As a result, and enlisting the help of
talented Americana poster boys Wilco, Bragg has been inspired to
make some of the best music of his career. It swings and tugs at
the emotions in equal measure. The ``In the Midnight Hour'' bass
line, singsong organ figure and nonsense lyrics of ``Hoodoo
Voodoo'' make for one of the most joyous pieces of music so far
this year. Guthrie should rest easy with his words in such capable
and respectful hands.
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Stunt''
</P>
<P>
   Barenaked Ladies. Reprise. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Already adored in their native Canada, these often amusing
pop-rockers are primed for superstar status stateside. ``Stunt,''
the Ladies' fifth full-length album, is garnering major airplay,
and they'll co-headline this summer's H.O.R.D.E. tour. As with
previous efforts, the new release is a mishmash of styles and
influences. ``One Week'' sends a hilarious, tongue-tripping rap
skittering over a solid frat-rock riff. ``Leave,'' an
end-of-the-romance lament, recalls Crosby, Stills and Nash at their
most countrified. Perfect pop tunes such as ``I'll Be That Girl''
suggest that the band has a brilliant album in them. ``Stunt''
isn't it _ too many slow tempos drag it down _ but it's an
agreeably imperfect diversion.
</P>
<P>
   -- CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``Dedication: Lieder of
</P>
<P>
   Beethoven, R. Strauss,
</P>
<P>
   Schumann, Liszt''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Heppner. BMG Classics.
</P>
<P>
   16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Among the hottest tenor sensations in classical music, Ben
Heppner raises the bar here on an already high standard of
musicianship and interpretation. Having earned his stripes singing
such burly Wagnerian repertoire as ``Die Meistersinger,'' he delves
into the more intimate turf of German lieder. Heppner shows an
impressively wide tonal and emotional range, as adept at essaying a
folk-like Beethoven phrase as a lyrical Schumann melody. Liszt's
operatic ``Three Sonnets of Petrarch'' thrusts him over the top at
times, but taking chances is among Heppner's most admirable
attributes.
</P>
<P>
   -- RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Poly Sci''
</P>
<P>
   John Forte. Ruffhouse/Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   John Forte made his bow on the biggest-selling rap album by a
group, the Fugees' ``The Score,'' then lit up the remix of Fugee
Wyclef Jean's ``Gone Til November.'' So, in the words of Forte's
own single, ``All You Gotta Do,'' all he had to do was make a
record and this debut should have been a hit by affiliation.
Instead, it suffers from his affiliations. Too often Forte's mild
delivery is too much like Jean's, whose real strength, by the way,
is production. So even with Jean's assistance on the production
boards, what Forte comes up with is a second-tier Wyclef record.
</P>
<P>
   -- SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Columbia. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Space rock, heavy on buzz-and-crunch impact. That's what you'd
expect to find on this soundtrack of the doomsday-asteroid thriller
``Armageddon.'' And you'd be wrong. Instead, Columbia has assembled
a surprisingly lightweight collection of pop-rock, little of it
new. There's a generous helping from the ever-feisty Aerosmith,
including two new songs: the gleefully boisterous ``What Kind of
Love Are You On?'' and the ballad ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing.''
Folk-rocker Shawn Colvin adds a bubbly cover of World Party's
``When the Rainbow Comes.'' But the rest is strictly fluff and
filler, with lackluster efforts from Journey, Bob Seger, Bon Jovi
and former Yes guitarist Trevor Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-FINALVINYL-COX     07-08 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FINALVINYL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For McCorkle, charm goes only so far
 &HT;    FREELANCE STORY. TO BE USED BY COX PAPERS ONLY. NOT TO BE USED
BY NY TIMES WIRE.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 12: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Greg Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, almost every Southern fiction writer has faced
a common problem when publishing a book. If the author is male, he
will be compared to Faulkner; if female, to Eudora Welty or
Flannery O'Connor. The reviewer will complain either that the
author is derivative of these illustrious forebears or is guilty of
New South trendiness, ignoring the richness of Southern literary
tradition. Either way, it often seems the contemporary writer can't
win.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Cormac McCarthy must grind his teeth each time he
encounters the adjective ``Faulknerian,'' and few reviews of Mary
Hood's work fail to mention O'Connor. So it isn't surprising that
Jill McCorkle, author of five novels and two collections of
stories, recently has been called ``our contemporary Eudora
Welty.'' Like the great Mississippi writer, McCorkle has a deft
comic touch and is a keen observer of Southern manners, in all
their complexity and frequent absurdity; her vision is also
similarly humane, revealing the foibles of her characters but
withholding harsh judgments or violent epiphanies.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, McCorkle's new collection lacks the penetrating
insight into human nature and the storytelling artistry that mark
the work of her most talented contemporaries, let alone Welty.
While notable for their headlong energy and surface charm, most of
McCorkle's new stories are merely clever rather than memorable.
</P>
<P>
   This cleverness is plainly visible in some of her titles. In
``Your Husband Is Cheating on Us,'' a mistress addresses her
lover's wife, suggesting they join forces and poison their mutual
friend. ``It's a Funeral! RSVP!'' is narrated by a woman who throws
parties for terminally ill people.
</P>
<P>
   A line from the latter story illustrates a problem that hobbles
many of these tales: ``I know I'm rambling,'' the woman admits,
``but it's important that I lead you to the moment of
realization.'' Rather than tell a story, McCorkle's obtrusive
narrators merely harangue the reader, and though their monologues
are sometimes entertaining, they seldom achieve much narrative
coherence or dramatic impact.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the characters particularly likable: In ``Life
Prerecorded,'' a pregnant woman finds it amusing that she cannot
stop smoking cigarettes; in ``Last Request,'' an even more callous
narrator observes that her dying mother ``struggled up a little
from her pillow and squeezed my wrist. I didn't trust her as far as
she could spit, which at that moment was no further than her bottom
lip.''
</P>
<P>
   The best story, ``Paradise,'' actually has a plot, dialogue and
a satisfying resolution. A northern Jew named Adam meets a Southern
girl named Eve at a wedding; after enduring predictable jokes about
their names, they embark on a touching, beautifully observed
romance. McCorkle's descriptive gifts are at their best here. When
the couple goes to a motel for their first tryst, Eve's dress lies
``crumpled in the corner, like some ghost of the Victorian era that
had pulled up a chair to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   If most of the stories in ``Final Vinyl Days'' strain to be
clever and amusing, it must be acknowledged they often achieve this
aim. One can't help feeling, however, that this talented author is
settling for too little, cheating not only her readers but herself.
</P>
<P>
   Final Vinyl Days and Other Stories. By Jill McCorkle. Algonquin.
$18.95. 212 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Clever and amusing, but not quite memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Johnson's most recent books include ``Pagan Babies,'' a
novel, and ``I Am Dangerous,'' his third collection of stories. He
teaches in the graduate writing program at Kennesaw State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
