<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEA-FUTURE-COX     07-08 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEA-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEA head Ivey pledges to forge new ties, move beyond past gaffes
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 12: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speaking in his Capitol Hill office earlier this year, Rep. Cass
Ballenger (R-N.C.) described himself as ``a conservative who thinks
the National Endowment for the Arts has done some good things but
has got to stop doing dumb things.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaned forward, thumped his forearms on his desk for emphasis
and added, ``The NEA has to prove that it matters to more than 5 or
10 percent of the voters, not just Barbra Streisand and that
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to swing congressmen such as Ballenger _ a hearty
plastics manufacturer who plans to vote for maintaining the NEA's
budget at $98 million for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 _ the
loved-and-loathed agency is enjoying its most encouraging prospects
in several summers. Thanks to a recent Supreme Court ruling against
Karen Finley, the so-called ``chocolate-smeared woman,'' the NEA
can continue to follow an 8-year-old law mandating ``general
standards of decency'' in its grants and therefore avoid the ``dumb
things'' in its past _ controversial grants that had remained
targets of anger and ridicule long after they occurred, during the
Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to last month's swearing-in of NEA Chairman William
Ivey _ a presidential choice so popular that he required no
confirmation hearings _ the 33-year-old agency appears to be on the
populist road Ballenger recommends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NEA has turned a corner,'' says Adrian King, a former
agency staffer who now heads arts and education programs for the
Coca-Cola Foundation. ``That old rag has been wrung out,'' he says
of the immorality charge. ``The question now is not so much `Will
the NEA survive?' but `How will it adapt to the demands of the
future?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey is already offering clues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to form stronger partnerships with the business
community, rethink those relationships'' says Ivey, 53, who as the
former head of Nashville's Country Music Foundation enjoys close
ties with music industry executives. ``And the concern I'm hearing
from leaders in the arts as well as politics is: getting outside
the major cities, widening the circle for what constitutes artistic
excellence,'' Ivey adds from his Washington office. ``I believe in
what Vice President (Al) Gore says about a government of `customer
service' for the taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rep. Pete Hoekstra (R-Mich.) is now angrier that ``My
district doesn't get a penny from the NEA!'' than about the issues
of decency that have consumed him in years past. In a recent
telephone interview, he offered no complaints about specific grants
for fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Populist style, substance
</P>
<P>
   The process of shaking off the NEA's bicoastal, ``elitist''
image actually accelerated from 1993 to 1997 under the leadership
of actress Jane Alexander, who as agency chairman not only visited
all 50 states but championed such community-based events as Navajo
silversmithing in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Under Alexander, working with tighter grant guidelines and only
about 60 percent of her predecessors' budget, money often shifted
away from such big-city flagships as the Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra, which in spite of continued excellence could no longer
expect general support in the hundreds of thousands of dollars per
year.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, with arts education for young people emerging
as one of the few NEA missions that appeals to conservatives as
much as liberals, ``education'' has become a magical buzzword,
changing old patterns of grant distribution. That may explain why
the Atlanta Ballet, snubbed in the past for general support, this
year landed a $50,000 grant for an educational program.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander was no elitist, but _ as a forthright female with a
Boston accent and many show business friends _ she sometimes
appeared to be. By contrast, Ivey, after 27 years in Nashville, has
the down-home style to go with the populist substance. Said
Ballenger, the Streisand nonfan, of Ivey on the eve of his
confirmation: ``I hear he's a good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Support in the Senate
</P>
<P>
   Two of the NEA's most powerful opponents, evangelist Pat
Robertson and House Speaker Newt Gingrich, declined to comment for
this story. Robertson was among the conservative leaders who
inspired Gingrich in May to form a ``Values Action Team,'' with the
elimination of the NEA among its goals.
</P>
<P>
   But even NEA critic Hoekstra concedes that the agency probably
will survive the perennial summer wrangling in Congress, largely
because of bipartisan Senate support. As Gingrich wrote in his 1997
book, ``Lessons Learned the Hard Way'': ``The social pressure of
(arts-loving) elites has always been felt more strongly in the
Senate than in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the support of President Clinton, who proposed
boosting the NEA's budget to $136 million, and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who made a passionate statement in defense of the
NEA at Ivey's swearing-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clintons clearly want the arts to be an important part of
their legacy,'' Ivey says.
</P>
<P>
   A gun-shy agency?
</P>
<P>
   Though heartened by Ivey's popularity, many arts leaders are
dismayed that the social value of public grants to the arts _ which
are far higher, per capita, in many European countries _ is still
questioned in America. And they are troubled by what they see as a
timid, gun-shy NEA that has abandoned direct gifts to individual
artists in all categories but literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw out the baby with the bath water, took away money
from the very source of spontaneity and creativity,'' declares Rick
Hutto, chairman of the Georgia Council for the Arts, which
continues to receive hefty NEA grants but is prevented by both NEA
rules and the state from channeling money to individual artists.
</P>
<P>
   It may be no coincidence that Atlanta's Nexus Contemporary Art
Center recently received a $40,000 grant for the exhibition ``Home
and Place ... Traditional Southern Vernacular Arts and Crafts,''
which on the basis of the NEA announcement sounds surprisingly safe
by that intown museum's edgy standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find ourselves pre-editing grant applications,'' says Nexus
curator Teresa Bramlette. When asked whether she could mention
deserving projects that don't dare apply for grants now, she
replied with a rueful laugh, ``Yes, but I won't! We have to live
with this perception of whininess.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Vernell Marshall is a prime example of a painter who could
contribute to Atlanta's artistic life with an NEA grant. Without
one, she can no longer afford to maintain her studio-home here.
Marshall, who makes about $25,000 a year from her art, was packing
up, preparing to move in with her sister in Washington, when she
said by telephone, ``Artists are at the bottom of the food chain;
we get little respect. We're commentators on life, and the
marketplace doesn't always want to hear the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   John McFall, artistic director of the Atlanta Ballet, says the
future of the arts is imperiled when ``a choreographer in his 20s,
with a vision and a passion, can't get the kind of NEA grant that
got me on my feet in the '60s. And yet there's nothing to replace
the NEA for giving an artist presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Charles ``Pete'' McTier, president of the Woodruff
Foundation, says the NEA's stamp of approval remains as
indispensable as ever in leveraging grants from other sources, in
``an environment where the arts are in competition with other
social needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Reclaiming territory
</P>
<P>
   Despite his belief in ``partnering'' between the arts and
business, and in spreading the wealth around the map _ beliefs that
happen to have broad political appeal right now _ Ivey says he
won't retreat on the issue of funding individual artists. In fact,
he'll try to reclaim some of the territory of risk lost over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden is on us to go to Congress and argue our case about
getting back into the business of funding artists,'' Ivey says.
``Artists are at the foundation of our cultural life, and we must
find a way to support them.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes, McFall says, are high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NEA has been falling away from a core value: free
expression. And isn't that what our whole country is founded on?''
</P>
<P>
   NEA BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   1990 $171 million
</P>
<P>
   1996 $99.5 million
</P>
<P>
   1997 $99.5 million
</P>
<P>
   1998 $98 million
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
