<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams, Damon lend heft to touchy-feely `Good Will'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Good Will Hunting'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   A superior After School Special for adults (with oral sex jokes,
no less), this Oscar-winning charmer, written by boyhood pals Matt
Damon and Ben Affleck, isn't the masterpiece the Academy Award
voters would have you believe. But what it is _ a literate,
beautifully acted, character-driven movie _ has become so rare at
the multiplex that it seemed revolutionary when it hit screens last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Damon plays Will Hunting, a Boston Southie who gets by as a
janitor at M.I.T. The truth is, though, that he's a mathematical
genius, emotionally hindered by a series of foster homes and bad
breaks. That's where Robin Williams steps in, as a court-appointed
shrink who spars with Damon in their sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics are familiar, whether it's Damon's faux father-son
relationship with Williams or the boy-meets-girl-loses-girl
subplot, with Minnie Driver as a brainy British college babe who
falls for Will. But thanks to Gus Van Sant's textured direction and
the smart performances (including a genuinely Oscar-worthy turn by
Williams), the flick is a shaggy charmer. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Other movies with Matt Damon: ``The Rainmaker,'' ``Courage Under
Fire,'' ``Chasing Amy'' (with Affleck), ``School Ties.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
