A6137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAMPERS-COX     07-08 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAMPERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Plus' diapers let toddlers extend freedom of infancy
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's here and it's huge: the first plus-size disposable diaper
for full-figured babies and toddlers who run from the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pampers' diaper for children 35 pounds and larger hit
store-- this summer, the company's customer service line has been
jammed with parents calling to find out where the diapers can be
bought.
</P>
<P>
   Pampers developed the line because children are larger and
potty-train later.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sara O'Heron, who runs the Maternal Child Health Center at
the Emory Clinic in Fayetteville, Ga., can relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful. I know from my own daughter, kids are
bigger. We had to go to the adult Attends and she was just 2,''
O'Heron said, referring to disposable briefs for incontinence.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the largest disposable diaper was for children over
30 pounds. Diaper manufacturers assumed that children would be
toilet-trained by the time they outgrew that size. But the
convenience of disposables, coupled with more relaxed attitudes
from parents and pediatricians, has stretched a child's
diaper-wearing years well into toddlerhood.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, just 22 percent of children were potty-trained by age 2
1/2, compared with 90 percent in 1961, according to the American
Academy of Pediatrics. Although 60 percent had given up diapers by
age 3, about 2 percent still were not trained at age 4. The new
Size 6 diapers are aimed at children older than 2 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Leila Denmark of Alpharetta, Ga., who at 100 is the country's
oldest practicing physician, said her children were going to the
toilet at 6 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd squat them down and say, `Grunt, sister, grunt,''' Denmark
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But she knows that some children cling to their diapers like a
security blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a child in here 4 years old who sits on his heels to
keep from going to the bathroom,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
