<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arnett not to be further reprimanded
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--CNN decided Wednesday not to take any further action
against correspondent Peter Arnett for his role in the Operation
Tailwind story.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett met with CNN chairman Tom Johnson, CNN International
president Eason Jordan and others Wednesday and defended his
involvement in the Tailwind story. Arnett has said he was only
reading from a script prepared by producers and was not responsible
for the story, which CNN was forced to retract July 30.
</P>
<P>
   CNN had announced a reprimand for Arnett, best known as the
network's correspondent in Baghdad during the Persian Gulf War, as
part of its retraction and apology. But it also had announced that
two producers had been fired, and Pam Hill, the senior executive
producer of ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of conference calls between Johnson and CNN
employees Monday and Tuesday, staffers raised questions as to
whether Arnett had been given more lenient treatment than the
producers because of his status at the network.
</P>
<P>
   After executives talked to Arnett and deliberated for most of
the day Wednesday, CNN released a statement that read: ``Peter
Arnett's reprimand stands. No further personnel actions are
planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett was called back from his vacation in Oregon on Tuesday to
confer with Johnson. Before the meeting, Arnett had defended his
role in the Tailwind story, saying he had only conducted three of
the interviews, and then was reading questions prepared by the
report's producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was part of the team, but I didn't have surpervising
authority ... I was the face,'' Arnett told The New York Times
before Wednesday's meeting. ``There was nothing I could do to halt
the onward rush of this story.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, which aired June 7 on the debut of ``NewsStand,''
alleged that U.S. military forces in Laos used sarin nerve gas in
1970. An independent investigation found that there was
insufficient evidence to support the charge, and CNN apologized to
viewers and military personnel involved.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
