<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF DEAD NIGERIAN LEADER ACCUSES MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As experts from three countries flew to Nigeria to perform an
autopsy on Moshood Abiola, who had been Nigeria's most prominent
political prisoner, Abiola's relatives accused the military regime
of murder.
</P>
<P>
   The government of General Abdulsalam Abubakar insisted again
Wednesday that Abiola _ widely seen as the winner of the country's
1993 presidential election _ had died of natural causes on Tuesday.
He collapsed during a meeting in a &UR;  &LR; government villa with visiting
US officials and was rushed to a hospital with US Under Secretary
of State Thomas Pickering at his side. Doctors could not revive him
and said the 60-year-old businessman had suffered cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   After initially accepting the Abubakar regime's explanation that
there was no foul play, American officials were cautious Wednesday
not to concur with the military government. ``Up to this point, we
have seen no evidence that Chief Abiola died of anything other than
natural causes,'' State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said
Wednesday. Acknowledging the Abiola family's doubts, though, he
expressed hope that a team of American, Canadian and British
pathologists would be allowed to perform an autopsy ``that is as
independently and credibly conducted as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The military anulled the 1993 election, which Abiola won by a
large margin. A year later the military imprisoned Abiola, a
millionaire from the Yoruba-speaking southwest region of Nigeria,
for declaring himself the country's elected president.
</P>
<P>
   After four years in solitary confinement _ with almost no
contact with friends, relatives, lawyers or doctors _ Abiola was
supposed to be released this week. The American delegation had been
negotiating a transition to democracy with the military regime.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the coronors decide, Rubin said, Nigeria's
military ultimately bears the blame for the death. ``We made very
clear that we think that he should never had been in prison, and
therefore any consequence of him being in prison is the
responsibility of the government that wrongly put him in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of Abiola's 18 children gathered in their apartment in
suburban Maryland Wednesday, accepting the calls of well-wishers
and democracy activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chief Abiola's children do not believe that he died from
natural causes,'' said Randall Echols, the Abiola family's
representative in Washington. ``What is incredible is that the
military government did this in front of the Americans. You
couldn't even imagine that in a James Bond movie _ the elected
president of a country would be poisoned in front of American
diplomats.''
</P>
<P>
   The Abiola children had spoken with US officials and heard
first-hand accounts of their father's death, but they continue to
believe that he had been poisoned shortly before Tuesday's meeting,
Echols said. ``The circumstances scream foul play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Abubakar regime agreed to the Abiola family's request for an
independent autopsy. The United States sent two military
pathologists, Britain sent one and Candada sent the chief coroner
of the province of Ontario. In addition, Physicians for Human
Rights, a non-profit group, dispatched John Pless, head of the
National Association of Medical Examiners.
</P>
<P>
   The experts will probably conduct the autopsy today, said
Leonard Rubenstein, executive director for the human rights group,
which is based in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Hafsat Abiola, 23, the daughter who has become the family's
spokeswomen, said on Tuesday that she was considering a trip to her
homeland for the funeral, which is scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Because she has been so outspoken in her criticisms of Abubakar
and his predecessor, General Sani Abacha, Abiola has been warned
not to travel to Nigeria. She was unable to go to the funeral of
her mother, Kudirat, who was shot and killed a day before Hafsat
was to graduate from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Many relatives still blame the military government for that
killing, which was never investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family is devastated _ they are complete orphans now
because their mother was murdered and now their father has been
taken out,'' Echols said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
