<HEADER>
A6162 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-CHILE-NAT     07-08 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CHILE-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      GORE SWEARS IN MAINER FOR CHILEAN POST
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 8 -- With his left hand on the Bible and his
right hand raised before Vice President Al Gore, Maine lawyer John
O'Leary swore to uphold the Constitution of the United States in
his newest job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations, Mr. Ambassador,'' Gore said Wednesday,
welcoming O'Leary into the diplomatic world as U.S. ambassador to
Chile.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's tickets to Santiago have already been purchased, and
he'll arrive in Chile at the end of the month. His diplomatic
abilities will be tested quickly, as he deals with the aftermath of
a dispute between the Maine and Chilean salmon industries and the
continuing controversy surrounding the White House decision to
promote the sale of F-16 fighter jets to the newly democratic
Chile.
</P>
<P>
   After the 30-minute ceremony, O'Leary said his role was to
continue to promote the growth between the United States and Chile.
While Maine's salmon industry may claim that Chilean salmon fishers
are dumping their product at below-market prices in America,
O'Leary said that is only one element to a broad relationship that
covers $4.5 billion in U.S. exports and $2.5 billion in Chilean
imports to America.
</P>
<P>
   ``From time to time, there will be disputes,'' he said. The
salmon dispute, however, could be settled before O'Leary arrives in
Santiago, as the International Trade Commission is expected to
issue a final ruling on the dispute next week.
</P>
<P>
   A former city councilor and mayor of Portland, now a partner at
Maine's largest firm, Pierce Atwood in Portland, O'Leary was sworn
in in the White House Roosovelt Room, in front of such luminaries
as former Maine Gov. Joe Brennan and former Federal Communications
Commissioner Reed Hundt -- who was O'Leary's roommate at Yale
University.
</P>
<P>
   His years of work in the Democratic Party, and his connection to
Hundt, a close friend of Gore's, led to the Clinton administration
picking O'Leary to lead a 1993 U.S. delegation in helping Bolivia
craft new environmental laws. That pro bono work led to other
assignments in South America, and eventually to the nomination as
Chilean ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   With bipartisan support from Reps. Tom Allen, D-Portland, and
John Baldacci, D-Bangor, and Maine's Republican senators, Olympia
Snowe and Susan Collins, O'Leary's nomination sailed through the
Senate for his confirmation and a swearing-in ceremony in two
months.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
