<SLUG> BC-WEBSITE-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY PHOTO ALBUM FOR THE NATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's like opening a scrapbook on America.
</P>
<P>
   But it's no ordinary scrapbook. This book of memories has more
than 500,000 items in it. Imagine the binding.
</P>
<P>
   The Library of Congress recently unveiled its American Memory
project, memory.loc.gov/ammem, at its Web site as part of the
five-year, $60 million National Digital Library Program, which is
due for completion by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the project has indexed 36 collections of maps, plans,
drawings and other images as well as thousands of photographs from
some of the great names of 20th-century photography, including
Walker Evans and Dorothea Lange.
</P>
<P>
   Early items in the collection detail the effects of the
Depression on farms. Then the emphasis shifts to the mobilization
effort for World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Users can navigate into specific titles or topics through search
functions. Plug-in audio (RealAudio) and video (QuickTime) software
will be needed to view the hundreds of multimedia features.
</P>
<P>
   Images can be copied if they are credited under specific
copyright mandates listed on the site.
</P>
<P>
   To print images at near-photolike quality, you need one of the
newer color ink-jet printers. You will want fairly high resolution:
at least 600 dpi. You can also buy glossy photo-style computer
paper.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
