<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6175 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FRANCE-CROATIA-BO     07-08 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRANCE-CROATIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE IN THE FINALS AFTER DEFEATING CROATIA, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Les Bleus finally devised a way to solve
their scoring problems. They left the scoring to Lilian Thuram, a
Guadeloupe-born, Italy-based defender, to take a 2-1 victory over
Croatia in the World Cup semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The result set up the tournament organizers' dream final -- the
host nation against Brazil at Stade de France Sunday. The French
appear capable of defending against the Brazilians, even without
Laurent Blanc, suspended after being ejected against Croatia, but
their offense remains extremely questionable.
</P>
<P>
   France's strikers have converted only five of the team's 12
goals in six games, so coach Aimee Jacquet started this game with
one forward. Predictably, the French produced little offensive
cohesiveness, even after striker Thierry Henry entered in the first
half Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But, after Davor Suker's first-minute goal in the second half,
Thuram's forward forays caught the Croats off guard and produced
the tying score in the second minute and the winner 22 minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to play against Croatia,'' Jacquet said. ``They
put you off stride and they have some extremely good individuals.
That is why it was hard for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have prepared for this qualification and we deserve it.
Obviously, Brazil are the masters of world football and it is an
exciting prosepct to play against them. They are the greatest team
in this World Cup, as they showed against a Holland team which
played extremely well (Tuesday). They have dominated and beaten
teams at will.''
</P>
<P>
   Croatia has also been in a defensive posture in this tournament,
but the Croats seemed more dangerous than the French, at least
until Zvonimir Boban departed with an injury 20 minutes into the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   France did not have even a semblance of an attacking formation
-- it began with three defensive midfielders in an ostensible 4-5-1
alignment which has been described as an 8-2 -- until Henry
replaced Christian Karembeu in the 31st minute.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's strategy of patiently waiting to capitalize on
opponents' mistakes nearly paid off in the final minute of the
first half. Robert Jarni, who scored the first goal in injury time
in the first half of a 3-0 win over Germany, advanced on the left
side and earned a free kick on the edge of the penalty area. Fabian
Barthez easily handled the free kick, and attempted to launch a
counterattack, but found only lone striker Stephane Guivarc'h
surrounded by two defenders with goalkeeper Drazen Ladic
approaching.
</P>
<P>
   The Croats seemed anything but underdogs. They attacked and
defended confidently, even arrogantly. In the 11th minute, Suker
forced a corner after penetrating to the edge of the goal area
against Blanc and Marcel Desailly. Suker then calmly walked into
the goal and drank from one of Barthez's water bottles, spitting
out much of the contents in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing for Germany's aerial attack, Croatia coach Miroslav
Blazevic had used a war analogy, noting that how Rommel's tanks had
been vanquished by the English against the odds. Whatever Blazevic
used to motivate the team this time was equally effective.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia struck 25 seconds into the second half, as Aljosa
Asanovic skillfully dribbled through two opponents, and chipped a
pass against the flow to Suker. France retaliated desperately, as
Thuram moved into attack. Thuram took the ball off Boban, then took
a return pass from Youri Djorkaeff and slotted the shot to tie the
score in the second minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``As so often happens, you score and the opponent scores
immediately after, they draw a lot of strength from that,''
Blazevic said.
</P>
<P>
   Thuram put France ahead, working a combination with Henry, and
taking advantage of some leniency by Spanish referee Jose Garcia
Aranda by knocking Jarni off the ball inside the penalty area.
Thuram's left-footed finish into the far side of the net caught
Ladic flat-footed.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, Lizarazu was felled by Mario Stanic, who was
cautioned. Blanc advanced for the free kick, and tangled with
Slaven Bilic, who went down, embellishing the effect of a hard,
open-handed strike by Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Thuram, the top-rated foreigner in Italy's Serie A with Parma
last season, has been making threatening runs on the right side for
the entire tournament, but seldom created scoring chances -- until
last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the organization of the team, our defenders are
more attacking wing backs,'' Jacquet said. ``It's good for the team
that he scored and, in any case, great reward for how France
played. It's not really his position, but it is one he likes
playing, and it's good for the team to have him there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6178 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HDTV-1stLEDE-COX     07-08 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV-1st </SLUG>
 LEDE-COX 
 Fixes spelling of Brian Lamb 
 &HT;    DIGITAL TV WOES PERSIST AS ROLLOUT NEARS, SENATE TOLD
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first high-definition telecasts are only months
away, but the problems posed for consumers, broadcasters, cable
operators and programmers by the new technology are as razor-sharp
as the images that will soon go on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has ordered the industry to relinquish its current VHF
and UHF channels by 2006, the date when nearly all Americans will
supposedly be watching sets equipped for digital television (DTV).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to put their feet to the fire in keeping that
commitment,'' Senate Commerce Committee Chairman John McCain,
R-Ariz., said Wednesday after holding a hearing on a host of
unresolved DTV issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``But frankly,'' McCain added, ``meeting that deadline was a
joke from the very beginning. We wrote that law because the auction
(of the current TV channels) was supposed to bring in $20 billion
and balance the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the imminent promise of much higher quality wide-screen
images and sound resulting from the first basic change in U.S.
television standards in 60 years, McCain often focused on the dark
side of the picture. He put skeptical questions to a panel of
industry witnesses who, often as not, found themselves at odds with
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``All cable subscribers face the possibility of losing valued
channels of cable programming as the price of their systems' having
to accommodate all their local broadcasters' new digital
channels,'' the senator noted.
</P>
<P>
   Full-scale DTV transmissions will require cable outlets to use
at least double the number of current channels to accommodate the
same amount of programming.
</P>
<P>
   New TV sets arriving in the stores before Christmas can handle
all 18 DTV formats approved by the Federal Communications
Commission. But if station owners decide to ``multiplex'' their
signals, adopting a lower-definition format, as many as eight cable
channels may be required for each one that is in use today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody is going to get squeezed out,'' McCain predicted.
</P>
<P>
   That was the prime concern of Brian Lamb, C-SPAN's founder,
chairman and frequent on-air host, who saw the coming conversion to
DTV as ``a large train wreck in the making.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If 'must carry' status is granted to (local) digital broadcast
signals, the C-SPAN networks, and, most important, the American
people who watch the Senate and the House on television, will be
harmed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Elizabeth Murphy Burns, who heads a family-owned
broadcasting firm with four stations in Washington state and
Wisconsin, claimed an industry smashup would occur if the FCC fails
to adopt ``must carry'' rules.
</P>
<P>
   If initial buyers of DTV sets ``cannot get their local DTV
stations over cable, and if they lack assurance that expensive DTV
sets will operate with their cable systems and other digital
devices, the transition to DTV will falter and ultimately fail no
matter how many signals we put on the air or how we program them,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first DTV sets will go on sale in November and cost about
$7,000, said Alan McCollough, president of Circuit City Stores, a
major electronic retailer.
</P>
<P>
   McCollough said that ``what will entice our customers is a
dramatic breakthrough in picture performance'' for the new
wide-screen format.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Collins, chairman of Time Warner Cable, noted that
the 18 approved DTV formats offer a range of improved picture
quality. While all are sharper than today's pictures, some formats
sacrifice a degree of picture quality in exchange for the ability
to transmit other information.
</P>
<P>
   ``If consumers cannot notice the difference between competing
formats, using the most efficient format will best serve consumer
interests,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up the fuzzy scene for the broadcasters, Gregory Schmidt
of Lin Television Corp. said: ``We are full speed ahead towards
DTV, although cable carriage is uncertain at best and consumers'
buying DTV sets will be frustrated by uncertainty about these sets
working with cable and about reception of DTV signals, both via
cable and over the air.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, a potential consumer voiced his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to run out and buy one of these sets,'' Sen.
Conrad Burns, R-Mont., told the panelists. ``I don't have enough
money. I think I'll wait until you make a set that Joe Six-Pack can
afford.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANNAH-HOME-ART-NYT &LR;      07-08 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANNAH-HOME-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME WITH: BARRY HANNAH, MELLOWING OUT BUT UNBOWED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Barry Hannah is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Miss. _ It's not easy to imagine what sort of house
Barry Hannah might live in.
</P>
<P>
   The characters who saunter and stumble and soliloquize through
his heavily autobiographical fiction seem to have no home: They are
drunk at the controls of a jet or bargaining with God atop a horse
or roaring down the road in a Lincoln with beer cans rattling
around the floorboard.
</P>
<P>
   When they end up in places more domestic, they often lament what
one character in his latest collection of short stories, ``High
Lonesome'' (Atlantic Monthly Press, 1996), calls the ``farce of
playing house.'' They wrestle heroically, but not successfully,
with their lust. They get bored and turn to whisky or hashish or
guns. Sometimes they just wander out in the morning streets playing
a French horn and wearing an Indian headdress.
</P>
<P>
   So it is strange to step out of Hannah's Cherokee, with a basket
of bright new tennis balls in the back seat, and onto the driveway
of his modest, Eisenhower-era house in this pretty, antebellum
town.
</P>
<P>
   Susan, his wife, is the only one wrestling heroically, with the
front door, to keep their six dogs from running out. But a black
and white feist named Jill shoots across the street, where she
rousts the squirrels from the neighbors' yards. When she charges
back, Hannah squats down to her, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves for you to bow down to her when she comes back,'' he
says. ``Feists are squirrel dogs. She thinks it's her job. She
wants a little recognition.'' Then he herds her inside, where she
stretches herself out on the beige pile carpet near the big-screen
television.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Barry Hannah, the Deep South's answer to Charles
Bukowski and the man whom Truman Capote once called ``the maddest
writer in the U.S.A.,'' has mellowed.
</P>
<P>
   After a rambling life as a writer and teacher that has taken him
from South Carolina to Vermont to Alabama to Hollywood to Iowa _
and often to the depths of alcoholism and self-destruction _ Hannah
has called Oxford and the University of Mississippi, where he
teaches creative writing, home for 16 years now.
</P>
<P>
   He is nearing completion of his 12th book, a novel. He has not
had a drink in more than seven years, though he still speaks
glowingly of the insights he has gained while drinking. He says it
feels good, mostly, to be so rooted and comfortable after so many
years ``living out of a suitcase and on a motorcycle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be out at the reservoir to fish in 10 minutes,'' he
says. ``There's not a hell of a lot of things to do, but I like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long, lazy Saturday, and as the conversation wanders
easily from Elvis to Beckett to Southern women to Southern
Baptists, Hannah also seems more settled with his place as a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   His first novel, ``Geronimo Rex,'' about his raucous Mississippi
youth, was nominated for the National Book Award when Hannah was
only 30. His first collection of short stories, ``Airships,'' now
considered a modern classic, prompted Larry McMurtry to call him
``the best young fiction writer to appear in the South since
Flannery O'Connor.''
</P>
<P>
   But while all of his books except one remain in print and he is
always mentioned on the short list of the South's best writers, he
endured a long period in which critics and even fans complained
that his frenetic, high-comic fiction had become strained. As much
as anything, it was a complaint that Hannah had fallen short of the
impossibly high mark he set for himself with his first books.
</P>
<P>
   But with his last two collections of short stories, ``Bats Out
of Hell,'' and ``High Lonesome,'' he seems to have worked himself
back to the searing, jump-cut electricity of his earlier work. At
56, Hannah says he is less bothered by bad reviews and now sees his
writing, always intensely personal, as even more of an exercise in
self-exploration. Of his new novel, tentatively titled ``Yonder
Stands Your Orphan With His Gun,'' he will say only that it is
about ``zombies of the new South.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why I like writing: it's just jumping into a
pool,'' he says later in the day, smoking another of his
ever-present Marlboro reds on the balcony of Square Books, the
Oxford bookstore that has become a gathering place for Southern
writers. ``I get myself into a kind of trance. I engage the world,
but it's also wonderful to just escape. I try to find the purities
out of the confusion. It's pretty old-fashioned, but it's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In what could be considered one of America's literary hometowns,
he says he works equably in the large shadow of Oxford's most
famous writer, William Faulkner, who immortalized the town's
residents as the Compsons and McCaslins, Sartorises and Snopeses.
(Hannah's father, William, who died recently, was an Ole Miss
student when Faulkner was university postmaster, and like many
townspeople then, he derisively referred to the grandiloquent
writer as ``Count No 'Count.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me to be writing in the place where he
wrote,'' Hannah says. ``I like the ghosts.'' In a piece to
commemorate Oxford's 150th anniversary, he wrote of Faulkner:
``Salute him or go away. You can't walk through a statue.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannah often describes his role in Oxford as a kind of lonely
bulwark against a creeping homogenization in American fiction that
has rendered it irrelevant or simply a servant of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blandness has taken over everywhere, or just idiot low
sensation,'' he complains, admitting that he would rather read good
journalism than most modern fiction. ``Because at least you've got
the truth to hang on to, whereas with fiction you just get
information with a little fancy.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teacher (he recently returned to Mississippi from Iowa,
where he taught at the Iowa Writers' Workshop), he also bemoans a
generation of young writers afraid to take risks. ``It's a problem
even with the talented students at Iowa, who come from
everywhere,'' he says. ``They're actually better than they used to
be, because they are older. But there is not a drunk among them.
Nobody takes drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up,'' he says, ``when people seemed actually to be
hurting themselves for their art. Of course, some of it was
phony.''
</P>
<P>
   The wounds Hannah inflicted on himself for his writing were very
real. Unlike Hunter S. Thompson, he didn't cultivate a public
persona as a wild man of letters. But for years Hannah's reputation
for drinking and entertaining himself with guns was just as
legendary among writers. In an incident recounted in Esquire
magazine in 1988, he pulled out an unloaded pistol in a classroom
at the University of Alabama when students tried to walk out on his
impromptu soulful trumpet solo. According to the article, he waved
the gun, told the students, ``Now this is some bad soul _ you guys
had better learn the difference,'' and began to play again.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Hannah says, when he needed to make holes in the
walls of an apartment for stereo wires, he would use a shotgun.
When his car once filled with water during a rainstorm, he riddled
the floorboard with bullets to drain it. ``A lot of that stuff was
not a good idea, but it gets turned around by middle-class minds
into a cowboy thing,'' he says. ``It wasn't. It was just a need to
find something real, to do something that was real.''
</P>
<P>
   Of drinking, which eventually landed him in the hospital, he
stands by his comments in an interview several years ago. ``I'm not
going to come down on booze, because it's done a great deal for me,
frankly,'' he said then. ``It's like scolding an old friend now
that you don't need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Fisketjon, vice president and editor at large at Alfred A.
Knopf, who has known Hannah since the early 1980's, said that he
seemed remarkably content about ``hanging up his cup'' for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of high-wire act that goes with the
profession,'' he said. ``But I think it was closing in on him.'' He
compared Hannah's writing during that period to the playing of a
talented jazz musician that is still beautiful ``except there's no
tune there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hannah sticks mostly to a regimen of tennis, cigarettes,
coffee and iced tea. When he and his wife can, they go to Paris (a
map of the city hangs in his living room). When he is home, he sits
on the sunny porch just off the small room where he writes and
worries about the developers encroaching on his view of trees and
rolling hills.
</P>
<P>
   He spends as much time as he can with his two sons and his
daughter, all of whom are now grown up and living elsewhere. He
sometimes sees his literary pals Thomas McGuane or Richard Ford, or
he talks to Robert Altman, for whom he briefly worked as a
screenwriter. And he exults in new interest in his work _ he has a
devoted following in France and recently read that members of the
rock band Pavement said he was their favorite writer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other writers he knows, Hannah does not keep regular work
hours, but when bursts of inspiration hit, he writes like a man
possessed. ``You can't expect them to come all the time,'' he says.
``You're lucky when they come.''
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, he simply settles into his living room with his
wife and their dogs to watch the Belmont Stakes on television. As
Real Quiet, the doomed favorite, rounds the home stretch with a
contender on his heels, Hannah smiles broadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the noise they make when they come around that last
turn, man,'' he says. ``It sounds like the end of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
