<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-HARVEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTHEW J. HARVEY, 73; FORMER ADMINISTRATOR OF US AID AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matthew Joseph Harvey, a former Boston teacher who was assistant
administrator of the US Agency for International Development during
the Nixon and Ford administrations, died at his Dennis home on the
Fourth of July. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Harvey graduated from Milton (Mass.) High School and served
in the Navy before graduating in 1947 from Harvard College, where
he was a member of the Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``After graduating from Harvard I taught algebra and geometry in
a Boston high school for a year and then decided to do something
about following a more active role in the world of politics,'' he
wrote in the 25th annual report of his Harvard class.
</P>
<P>
   He worked in the stock and bond business for several years while
devoting his free time to politics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, he was active in the Eisenhower campaign in
Massachusetts. This led to his employment as a member of the staff
of US Senator Leverett Saltonstall. He also served as an
administrative assistant to US Representative William Mailliard of
California for eight years before becoming a civil service employee
at the State Department, where he rose to assistant administrator
for US AID. He handled legislative affairs for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the Harvard annual report, he wrote that his work allowed him
to ``see firsthand the problems of the world through travel and
study'' and provided him with an opportunity to play a ``role in
trying to work out ways to alleviate the plight of people in the
less-developed countries.''
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement from the State Department in 1975, he was a
consultant on international and legislative affairs and taught
political science at Cape Cod Community College.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves two sons, Mark of Dennis and John of Yarmouth, Mass.;
a daughter, Margaret Raunela of Dennis, Mass.; a sister, Rose
Garpestad of Staten Island, N.Y.; and a grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
