<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEROUAC-ESTATE-ART-1     07-08 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEROUAC-ESTATE-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLARS AND SURVIVORS TATTER KEROUAC'S SELF-PORTRAIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.M.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The only people for me are the mad ones, the ones who are mad
to live, mad to talk, desirous of everything at the same time,''
Jack Kerouac wrote in ``On the Road.'' The words could have been
his epitaph.
</P>
<P>
   Kerouac portrayed himself as a free spirit and a wanderer,
boasting of having made love to more than 300 women. He died in
1969 at the age of 47 from the effects of alcoholism, leaving what
is believed to be one of the most valuable, and litigious, literary
estates in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a new generation is discovering Kerouac and the Beats,
seeing them as agents of rebellion against middle-class
constraints. Since 1991, sales of ``On the Road'' have quadrupled,
with more than 3 million copies purchased since the novel was
published in 1957. Lines from the book are featured in ads for
Volvo, and Kerouac is pictured in his khakis in Gap ads.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the actor Johnny Depp purchased the author's old blue
raincoat from his estate for $15,000. Today, the entire Kerouac
estate _ including the royalties from his books and the sale value
of his manuscripts and belongings _ is believed to be worth close
to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kerouac willed his estate to his mother, Gabrielle, who in turn
left it to Kerouac's third wife, Stella Sampas. When she died, she
left the estate to relatives who appointed her brother, John
Sampas, as executor. But in 1994, Kerouac's daughter from another
marriage, Jan Kerouac, whom her father had barely acknowledged in
his life, sued the estate, saying her grandmother's will had been
forged.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kerouac died in 1996. Now the fight over Kerouac's legacy
has been renewed. And it has become so bitter that a discussion
group on the Internet devoted to Kerouac and other Beat writers was
shut down in March because of accusations of threats and
harassment. Two new biographies, both claiming to unravel the myth
of Kerouac, say Kerouac created an image of himself through his
semi-autobiographical writings that was far from the truth, an
image that has lingered and has now captured the imagination of a
new generation of readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subterranean Kerouac,'' by Ellis Amburn, who edited the
author's last two books, will be published next month by St.
Martin's Press. Another book, to be released by Henry Holt in
November, ``Jack Kerouac: King of the Beats,'' is by Barry Miles, a
biographer of Allen Ginsberg and Paul McCartney.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a disparity between the image and the actual man,''
Miles said. ``He didn't live the actual Beat lifestyle. He really
lived in the suburbs with his mother,'' a fiercely overprotective
figure who was also a vocal anti-Semite.
</P>
<P>
   Miles depicts Kerouac himself both as a racist who said in ``On
the Road'' that he wished he were black and as an anti-Semite whose
best friend, Ginsberg, was a Jew. Kerouac banned Ginsberg from the
house because of his mother's bias. And as Kerouac grew older,
Miles said, ``he became more and more racist and anti-Semitic''
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Hiding Behind a Playboy Image
</P>
<P>
   Miles said there was also a dissonance between Kerouac's image
as a Don Juan, and his true self. ``His sexual image is early
Playboy,'' he said. ``But in reality, he had a lot of boyfriends,''
and in his writings, Miles said, Kerouac skipped over his
homosexual encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pretended to be honest, which gave rise to whole idea of
spontaneous writing,'' almost free association, said Miles. ``He
was a tremendous influence on the new journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Amburn, who edited Kerouac's novels ``Desolation Angels'' and
``Vanity of Duluoz,'' based his biography on new material from the
Kerouac archives in Lowell, Mass., the author's hometown. While
other biographies have mentioned Kerouac's sexual relationships
with men, Amburn portrays his subject as a tormented figure, a
misogynist and a homophobe, torn between homosexual and
heterosexual desires and drowning his conflicts in alcohol. He said
that taking into account Kerouac's homoerotic feelings provides a
key to understanding his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most biographies say fame killed him,'' Amburn said. ``It was
alcohol that killed him because he couldn't accept his sexuality.
All the hateful streams in him are part of the same disease, of not
admitting who you are, and living your life truthfully.''
</P>
<P>
   He traces Kerouac's life from what Amburn termed a crucial early
infatuation with Stella's other brother, Sammy Sampas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fell in love with Sammy Sampas, who drew him into the
Scribbler's Club at Bartlett Junior High School,'' in Lowell, said
Amburn. ``Kerouac said every Rimbaud needs a Verlaine. He said,
`Sammy was my Verlaine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Amburn said Sammy was Kerouac's true love, and he married
Sammy's sister as a substitute. ``In denying that love, he went on
to lead what Henry James called `an unlived life,''' he said. ``If
you live a lie, you're going to drink and drug yourself to death.''
</P>
<P>
   When Amburn was editing ``Vanity of Duluoz,'' he said, ``Kerouac
would call me up and read me these cryptic passages. I would say,
`Would you clarify or decode these?' He would sometimes refuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerouac's ambivalence, said Amburn, explains certain passages in
``On the Road,'' which was based on Kerouac's journey across
America with the charismatic drifter Neal Cassady. Kerouac's love
for Cassady, Amburn said, explains the devastation that the Kerouac
character, Sal Paradise, feels when Dean Moriarty, the surrogate
for Cassady, leaves him.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that Kerouac was fighting his sexual impulses,
said Amburn, he was desperately searching for transcendence in
Buddhism, struggling between its spiritual teachings and attempts
to drown his conflicts in drugs and alcohol. Amburn traces
Kerouac's prose style, the flow of words that Ginsberg called his
``spontaneous bop prosody,'' to Kerouac's Buddhist beliefs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Road'' was written in three weeks on one long stream of
Teletype paper. Using Kerouac's letters and his writings on
Buddhism (published last year by Viking Press in ``Some of the
Dharma,'' edited by John Sampas and David Stanford of Viking),
Amburn said he was able to depict Kerouac's style as an outgrowth
of his Buddhism. ``He would say, `You're not supposed to edit
sentences because our mind is God,''' Amburn said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Kerouac never found transcendence, Amburn said.
And he left a legacy as messy as the life he led.
</P>
<P>
   `A Gold Mine of Information'
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Kerouac's estate is embroiled in two lawsuits,
one involving the heirs of his daughter, the other with Gerald
Nicosia, author of ``Memory Babe,'' a Kerouac biography published
in 1983 by the University of California Press. Nicosia, who is Jan
Kerouac's literary executor, has charged that Jack Kerouac's
executor, John Sampas, is selling off the author's archives in
violation of his wishes that his manuscripts be given to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Kerouac said in a letter to his friend the novelist John Clellon
Holmes in 1962 ``that he wanted to create a gold mine of
information for scholars,'' with his papers, said Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
   But Jan Kerouac's heirs _ her ex-husband John Lash, who is the
general executor of her estate, and her half brother, David Bowers
_ have parted company with Nicosia. They want to settle the will,
and they are challenging Nicosia's right to block the settlement
with the Sampas family in court. A decision by a probate court in
Albuquerque, N.M., where Jan Kerouac died, is expected this summer,
paving the way for a resolution of her original lawsuit, which was
brought in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   John Sampas, who lives in Lowell, denied selling off the
archive. ``No doubt, I did sell some letters,'' he said, ``but 99
percent of the archive is intact.'' He said the material would be
``going to the public,'' after the completion, expected in 2001, of
an authorized Kerouac biography by Douglas Brinkley, a professor at
the University of New Orleans who has also written a biography of
Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Nicosia said his opponents had threatened his life. ``Within the
last eight months, there has been major harassment and death
threats,'' he said. He pointed to a message on the Web site of The
Kerouac Quarterly, a literary magazine, from Paul Maher, editor of
the quarterly, who Nicosia said was allied with Sampas. The message
ended with these words: ``The Beat Generation where words still
carry the ammunition of guns. Gerry, I think they have an open
teaching post for you over at that Arkansas school.'' Nicosia said
that was an ominous reference to the recent shooting of a teacher
in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Nicosia said, ``I was sent an anonymous envelope
filled with ashes and obscenities.'' He said he did not know who
had sent it.
</P>
<P>
   Maher denied ever threatening Nicosia's life. Sampas denied any
involvement, saying, ``It's all baloney,'' and adding that he had
never participated in the Internet discussion group.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Sampas has accused Nicosia of ``stalking'' him.
``He was all over the place, yelling at me,'' said Sampas. Nicosia
called the accusation ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the various charges and accusations made their way
onto Beat-L, a Web site devoted to the Beats. ``The discussion got
so totally out of hand, it got really vile, that I closed it
down,'' said William Gargan, a librarian with the Brooklyn Public
Library, who set it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerouac's estate,'' Amburn said, ``is a divided and conflicted
issue, just as Kerouac was a divided and conflicted man: between
lies and truth, between men and women, between the drive for
instant gratification and the quest for a true and lasting
spiritual experience that would give him peace of mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6187 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-REFORM-BOS &LR;      07-08 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-REFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE LEADER OFFERS TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ As support for Japan's government plummets and polls
show the ruling party slipping in the run-up to Sunday's
parliamentary elections, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto made a
late bid Wednesday to win votes and instill confidence in markets:
He promised to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Vowing to cut taxes is a time-honored crowd-pleaser. But what
makes Hashimoto's 11th-hour gambit so unusual is that it's his
third statement on taxes since last Friday _ and the second time
since then he's flip-flopped.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto's waffling on taxes is understandable given that
Japan's deficit is one of the largest in the industrialized world;
the country needs revenue to meet the worst budget shortfall since
1981. Moreover, Japan has one of the world's oldest populations; by
2020, one in four Japanese will be on social security _ an argument
against cutting taxes now.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan also needs a cash injection into an economy suffering
its worst recession since World War II, and Hashimoto is under
intense pressure from investors and the United States to cut taxes
to jump-start consumption. The problem is that historically,
Japanese increase their savings, not their spending, when taxes are
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are running scared, and I think this is the last
big piece of ammo they're going to pull out and fire at the
opposition,'' said John Neuffer, a political analyst at Matsui
Marine Research Institute. ``Hashimoto sees the specter of his
demise, and this is part of his strategy to stay on as prime
minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto's back-and-forth on tax cuts has exasperated and
disillusioned many here, but it is emblematic of the larger
confusion and disarray over how to revive Japan's long-suffering
economy. The economy has become the sole issue in the upcoming
elections, and the elections, in turn, have become a referendum on
the ruling party's competence.
</P>
<P>
   How well the parties sell their reform packages in these last
days of the campaign will determine who is able to form a
government to preside over Japan's long-overdue restructuring. &UR;  &LR; But
even the ruling Liberal Democratic Party, it seems, has not yet
decided what form restructuring should take.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Hashimoto said he wanted ``permanent tax reform,''
a statement widely understood to mean permanent, rather than
one-time, tax cuts. The next day, Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi
said permanent tax cuts were part of the government's platform. By
Sunday, however, Hashimoto insisted he had never promised a
permanent tax cut, and the next day a spokesman for Obuchi said the
foreign minister had issued a retraction.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Wednesday, after one newspaper survey showed support for
Hashimoto's government had dropped to 28.5 percent, and other polls
suggested his party might lose seats in the upcoming election _ a
failure that could force him to resign _ the prime minister said
again that he supported tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes these guys look like the Keystone Cops running around
with everyone saying something different, leaving people wondering
who is running the show. It further undermines the already
questionable credibility of the ruling party,'' Neuffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are confused too. A poll by Asahi Shimbun newspaper
published Wednesday said that 59 percent of voters are not
affiliated with a party, and most of them have not decided who they
will vote for on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Yasuhiro Okudaira, professor emeritus at the University of
Tokyo's Institute of Social Sciences, said the government's
behavior has disillusioned voters: ``When the government hasn't
succeeded in improving the situation, people get tremendously
pessimistic and that doesn't necessarily'' inspire them to vote.
Okudaira called Hashimoto's latest statement on taxes ``too little,
too late.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Hashimoto did not give many specifics Wednesday, saying
merely that he would not now raise the minimum taxable income to
pay for a tax cut for the rich, and that he wanted a decision on
corporate taxes by the end of the year. The tax rate for businesses
can now run as high as 46 percent, while the income tax rate for
the wealthiest individuals is 65 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
