   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINE (Jerusalem) -- The Israeli government downplays
the nearly unanimous UN vote giving Palestinians a voice in the
world body for the first time. By Charles M. Sennott. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   ABIOLA-FAMILY (Washington) -- As experts from three countries go
to Nigeria to perform an autopsy on Moshood Abiola, Nigeria's most
prominent political prisoner, Abiola's relatives accuse the
military regime of murder. By David L. Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-IRS (Washington) -- Senate approves conference version of
IRS overhaul and sends it to the president for his signature. By
Chris Black. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RACE (Washington) _ President does a conversation on
race with pundits from the Lehrer Newshour. By Ann Scales. 1200
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CNN-ARNETT (Undated) -- CNN correspondent Peter Arnett,
reprimanded for a retracted report that the US military used nerve
gas during the Vietnam War, will face no further punishment. By Don
Aucoin. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   MA-RABIES (Undated) -- Incidence of rabies is way up over last
year and 1996 as raccoon population recovers from last rabies
epidemic. By Maraie Sanchez. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY-SLOWDOWN (Undated) -- An index of business activity in
New England fell in April and stayed low in May, adding new
evidence that a recession sweeping through southeast Asia and Japan
is causing a slowdown in this country. By Kimberly Blanton. 750
words.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-REFORM (Tokyo) _ With polls showing the ruling party
slipping in Sunday's parliamentary elections, an increasingly
desperate Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto offers to cut taxes. By
Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 750 words. (f and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-MCI (Undated) -- Worldcom clears a major antitrust
hurdle in its effort to merge with MCI, as European Union
regulators approve the $46 billion deal. US regulators, who had
worked with their European counterparts, are expected to follow
suit soon. By Joann Muller. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   MIRAMAX-BROWN (Undated) -- After six splashy years at the helm
of The New Yorker, Tina Brown resigns to head a film, TV and
publishing venture with Miramax Films. By Mark Feeney. 1300 words.
(f and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-FRANCE-CROATIA (Saint-Denis, France) _ By defeating Croatia
2-1, France finally gets to play for the championship of the
tournament it invented. By Frank Dell'Apa.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-COMMENT (Paris) -- By John Powers.
</P>
<P>
   SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN (Baltimore) _ The Red Sox have said there
would be no repeat of the Roger Clemens contract fiasco. But it's
happened again. By Dan Shaughnessy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
