<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER VICTIM'S DAUGHTER ASKS CONGRESS TO STOP HATE CRIMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With tears streaming down her face, the daughter of
a black man who was dragged to his death in East Texas called the
killing ``a wake-up call for America'' as she urged Congress to
crack down on hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men who murdered my father had a choice that morning, and
they chose violence,'' Renee Mullins, 27, the eldest daughter of
James Byrd Jr., told members of the Senate Judiciary Committee on
Wednesday. ``Therefore, the laws of the land should punish them.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, 49, was beaten, chained to the back of a pickup and
dragged along a rural road June 7 near Jasper. Three white men with
links to racist groups have been indicted on capital murder charges
and are being held.
</P>
<P>
   John William King, 23; Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31; and Shawn
Allen Berry, 23, could face the death penalty id convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects in Byrd's death were charged under Texas law, but
legislation in Congress would make it easier for federal
prosecutors to take over similar cases. The bill, sponsored by
Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., would also
expand federal jurisdiction to include hate crimes motivated by
gender, sexual orientation or physical disability.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that the proposal seeks an unnecessary and
unconstitutional expansion of federal power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would do little to prevent tragedies like the one in
Jasper, Texas,'' William Stunts, a University of Virginia law
professor, told the Senate panel. ``In short, I think this bill
would do no good and may do real harm.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mullins argued that hate crimes are so heinous that they
deserve special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here today to prevent any other acts of violence of this
nature from occurring in America,'' she said. ``I think there
should be federal jurisdiction over crimes so hateful. It is a pity
to die because of your race, handicap or sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullins also urged Americans to pray for the three men accused
of her father's killing, saying that the jailed suspects ``are so
full of fear and hatred that they are cut out from the happiness of
life.'' She struggled to maintain her composure as she delivered an
emotional appeal for racial tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to talk peace and harmony at my most difficult times, so
that no sparks will ignite more hatred and retribution,'' Mullins
said. ``People should be judged by the content of their character,
and not by the color of their skin. I've learned from living 27
years _ it takes more energy to hate than to love.''
</P>
<P>
   The young woman ended her emotional testimony by thanking the
senators and adding, ``God bless America.'' Her comments hushed the
cavernous hearing room and left lawmakers struggling for an
appropriate response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really, really feel badly about what happened. I think
everyone in America does,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the panel's
chairman, said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy added: ``You're very special to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could be strong,'' Mullins replied, embarrassed by
her tears. ``But thank you, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who is skeptical about Kennedy's bill, assured Mullins
that Congress will find some way to encourage the prosecution of
hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you should presume we're going to do something here,''
he said. ``We have too many hate crimes, and something needs to be
done about it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
