A6212 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMP-ART-AZR &LR;      07-08 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMP-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECO-CHIC HEMPENTWINES INDUSTRY, ECOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYTNS photo clients)  
 By ANNE M. SPITZA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Hemp is eco-chic.
</P>
<P>
   If you have not yet consumed, bathed with or worn something made
from the hearty plant, you are seriously out of the loop _
ecologically speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Hemp _ seeds, oil and fiber _ are now the Earth-friendly raw
materials of choice among the environmentally correct.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, hemp's worldwide sales have exploded
from $5 million in 1993 to more than $75 million in 1997, according
to industry trackers at Hemptech in California. By 2001, they
predict that hemp sales will reach $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Byproducts of the fibrous plant are popping up in everything
from bath soaps and sunscreens to backpacks and bedding.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz is using hemp as soundproofing in some of its
cars. Calvin Klein and Ralph Lauren have included hemp fabric in
their luxury home collections. Adidas and Vans make sneakers with
hemp-fabric uppers. And, the Patagonia catalog offers several hemp
garments, including a wrap-around skirt for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Finneran is founder of Crucial Creations, a 7-year-old
Tucson, Ariz. -based hemp garment company that sells its goods as
far away as Japan, the Netherlands and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's absolutely crucial the work we are doing for the
planet,'' said Finneran during a telephone interview. ``Eventually,
we're not going to be able to sustain ourselves using
petrochemicals that are a limited resource. (Hemp) is a sustainable
plant resource that can be regenerated every year to produce over
25,000 different products _ everything from paint to building
materials and (organic) plastics.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran is hardly alone in his dedication to ``hemp for a
healthier environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Body Shop is the latest voice to join the chorus of
advocates singing hemp's praises. The British-based bath and
body-care company introduced a line of hemp-oil products worldwide
this spring. ``Hemp Is Hope, Not Dope'' is the message embossed
beneath the waxy contents of its Hemp Elbow Grease ($10) skin
moisturizer.
</P>
<P>
   Not too surprisingly, hemp has met with controversy and
confusion. The grass-roots movement to bring this ``premier
renewable resource for the 21st century'' back into the public eye
began in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, commercial hemp is a variety of Cannabis sativa.
Although it is a cousin of the plant that produces marijuana,
experts say industrial hemp contains no significant traces of the
psychoactive drug THC (tetrahydrocannabinol).
</P>
<P>
   Environmentally, the appeal of hemp is that it grows without
insecticides, clears fields of weeds and replenishes nutrients in
the soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the magic about hemp,'' said John W. Roulac, president
of Hemptech. ``It helps regenerate the soil.''
</P>
<P>
   One acre of hemp can produce four times more paper than can 1
acre of trees. And, unlike timber, hemp grows back the following
season.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of hemp revolves around the gradual illegalization
of Cannabis sativa in the United States between 1937 and the
mid-1950s. The public outcry against marijuana ensnared hemp, too.
It's been pointed out that innovative plastics, cotton and
wood-pulp paper were making hemp obsolete anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Hemp advocates, however, argue that the powerful timber and
petrochemical industries had a hand in the anti-hemp legislation.
The absence of a hemp crop, they contend, eliminated competition
for wood- and petroleum-based products.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, hemp was used in the production of fuel, paper,
fabric, rope, food, birdseed, livestock fodder and paints.
</P>
<P>
   Hemp cultivation remains illegal in America. Movements in
several states _ backed by environmental, agricultural, academic
and industrial interests _ are working to repeal the law.
</P>
<P>
   Importing hemp as a raw material _ sterilized seeds, oil, fiber
or fabric _ is legal. The bulk of the world's industrial hemp is
grown in China, India and Europe. Canada expects to harvest 45,000
acres of hemp this year, according to Roulac.
</P>
<P>
   Eye-popping price tags have put a damper on the current hemp
scenario. Import duties and limited supply of sterilized hemp
seeds, oil, fiber and fabric have made hemp-based products an
expensive option.
</P>
<P>
   A yard of hemp fabric costs between $18 and $40 retail. A pair
of Ecolution jeans sell for $73.50 on the Internet. Adidas' hemp
and recycled-rubber sneakers go for about $80 a pair. A queen-size
hemp duvet cover by Calvin Klein will cost a whopping $725.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, it (hemp) is a non-toxic alternative to our
toxic world,'' said Bill Gobus, owner of the Flagstaff Hemp Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see in my own store is that almost everybody is into
hemp _ contrary to the media vision that the people who like hemp
are a small minority. I get doctors and lawyers and teachers and
judges and even probation officers _ people you would think would
be against it, but are not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1849EDT &QL; 
