<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-LAW-HNS &LR;      07-08 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER OF JASPER VICTIM URGES PASSAGE OF HATE-CRIMES LEGISLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The eldest daughter of James Byrd Jr. on Wednesday
urged Americans to pray for the three white men indicted in the
racially motivated slaying of her father in Jasper, Texas. Renee
Mullins also pressed Congress to pass legislation that would
increase the federal government's authority to investigate and
prosecute hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all citizens to pray for these individuals who have
such low self-esteem and who are so full of fear and hatred that
they are cut out from the happiness of life,'' Mullins told the
Senate Judiciary Committee, which is considering the proposed 1998
Hate Crimes Prevention Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as Americans, and human beings in general, we have choices
in life: to hate or not to hate; to kill or not to kill; to be a
leader or a follower,'' Mullins said in tearful testimony. ``The
men who murdered my father had a choice ... and they chose
violence. Therefore, the laws of the land should punish them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullins' testimony followed the capital murder indictment of the
three men Monday in Jasper County.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper residents Bill King, 23, and Shawn Berry, 23, as well as
Russell Brewer Jr., 31 of Sulphur Springs, could face the death
penalty if convicted in the June 7 dragging death of Byrd, 49, who
was black. He was pulled behind a vehicle until his head and right
arm were wrenched from his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brutal murder of my father, James Byrd Jr., is for us in
my family a tragedy that we have only begun to experience,'' said
Mullins, who had to stop her testimony briefly to regain her
composure. ``I cannot get over the horrid and deeply felt hatred of
how he died. I want to thank the nation for all the prayers being
delivered to us and we _ my mother, brother, sister and I _ want to
express our immense gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation before the Senate, and a similar bill before the
House, would extend the U.S. hate crime statute to enable the
federal government to prosecute violent attacks on women, gays and
disabled people, as well as blacks and religious minorities, as
current law permits. The bipartisan proposal, which President
Clinton supports, also would remove a provision in the hate-crime
law that limits federal jurisdiction to instances when the violent
act interfered with the victim's exercise of a federally protected
activity, such as voting.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, however, must cite a power it has under the
Constitution to take the broad step of making a state offense a
federal crime. The bill, therefore, cites Congress' authority to
regulate interstate commerce as the basis for allowing U.S.
lawmakers to federalize hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Byrd case, for example, the requirement could be met if
prosecutors could show the pickup used to drag the victim to his
death had parts that came from a state other than Texas. However,
the measure, if enacted, would not apply to Byrd's case because it
was not law at the time of the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passing this bill into law would give some mercy for my family
and for the families of future victims of such horrible crimes,''
said the 27-year-old Mullins of Lufkin. ``To not pass this bill is
unfair to the American people and to police officers and Justice
Department officials who work hard to keep people safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr., citing two Texas cases,
told senators that the bill would remedy two ``deficiencies'' in
the current law: the limitation to race- and religion-based hatred
and the requirement that a federally protected activity be
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Holder noted the brutal 1996 stabbing death of a gay man in
Houston, allegedly by two men who belonged to a white supremacist
group in Montana. Federal charges could not be brought because U.S.
law did not protect people from violent acts based on their sexual
orientation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holder also cited the 1994 acquittal by a federal jury in Fort
Worth of three white supremacists who were charged with assaulting
black people because of their race. The jury concluded the victims
were not engaged in a federally protected activity when they were
attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal would permit the federal government to work in
partnership with state and local officials in the investigation and
prosecution of cases that implicate the significant federal
interest in eradicating hate-based violence,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   However, University of San Diego law professor Larry Alexander
criticized the proposal as an unconstitutional exercise of
Congress' limited authority to regulate activities that
substantially affect interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means is that to comply with its constitutional
responsibilities, Congress ... must actually believe that hate
crimes have a substantial effect on interstate commerce,'' he told
the committee. ``You will forgive me for believing, based on the
speeches in support of this bill, that the motivation for this bill
has little to do with its overall effects on interstate commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Arcara of western New York objected
to the bill as the latest example of Congress turning into federal
offenses those crimes, such as murder, historically enforced by the
states. Such congressional steps have flooded overworked federal
courts with cases best left to state judges, said Arcara, who
testified on behalf of the Judicial Conference of the United
States, which represents federal judges. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
