<SLUG> BC-TV-WITNESS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`48 HOURS': FOR CRIME WITNESSES, SHOULD SEEING BE BELIEVING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(bl) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't trust your eyes. That is the main message of Thursday
night's cautionary ``48 Hours.'' Experts, examples and exhortations
are arrayed against witness testimony, whether in a rape case or a
robbery or the assassination of John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's report begins with the rape conviction of two
Alabama brothers who were picked out of a photo lineup by the
victim. They were freed after serving 14 years, when Peter Neufeld,
a lawyer and DNA specialist, showed that the semen on the accuser's
clothes did not match that of the brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The case remains unsettled: the victim now says that the semen
was a boyfriend's but that she was raped later by the two suspects.
So a retrial is promised. Whatever the outcome, the episode draws
attention to other cases in which belated inspection of DNA
evidence has cleared convicted men of rape charges despite witness
testimony of their guilt.
</P>
<P>
   In another incident, a defendant in a convenience store robbery
was acquitted after a psychologist explained to the jury why the
storekeeper's memory could not be trusted. But can the expert
witness' theory be trusted? Soon after acquittal, the suspect was
arrested in another convenience store robbery. (Do these stores owe
their titles to their convenience for robbers?)
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists and others explain how memory can be a fooler. In
a punchy demonstration, a quick grab-and-run theft is staged in
front of a class at Brooklyn Law School. In photo lineups soon
afterward, most of the students choose an innocent man as the
culprit. Whether this is a comment on the power of suggestion or on
the people who become lawyers invites further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the program returns to the conflicts in witnesses'
recollections of the Kennedy assassination. But let's not get into
that.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``48 HOURS''
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Thursday night at 10
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Susan Zirinsky, executive producer; Steve Glauber and Gavin
Boyle, senior producers; Linda Martin, producer. A production of
CBS News. Wyatt Andrews and Harold Dow, correspondents; Dan Rather,
anchor.
</P>
</TEXT>
