<SLUG> BC-DENVER-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DENVER, PRIDE AND PROSPERITY TAKE CENTER STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ELIZABETH HEILMAN BROOKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ This year the city has been in an everlasting state of
Rocky Mountain high.
</P>
<P>
   January brought a stunning Super Bowl victory, and the champion
Broncos were honored by the president. This week sports fans were
focused on the baseball All-Star Game at Coors Field.
Tele-Communications Inc., based here, was recently scooped up by
AT&AMP;T, earning local entrepreneurs head-spinning billions.
</P>
<P>
   And last month the Denver Center Theater Company received a Tony
Award, named for Antoinette Perry, an actress and director who grew
up here a century ago. The award citation said that this regional
company has shown ``a continuous level of artistic achievement and
contributed to the growth of theater nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan Marley, the company's artistic director, and Donald
Seawell, founder of the Denver Center for the Performing Arts,
delivered the award to the steel-and-glass theater complex, where
the medallion was passed hand to hand from one company member to
the next, up the front steps and down the galleria to the soaring
lobby of the Helen G. Bonfils Theater Complex.
</P>
<P>
   The theater company, founded two decades ago, is a dream turned
remarkable reality of Seawell, a former Broadway producer. He took
a nearly abandoned sports arena, a city jail, police headquarters
and numerous parking lots, and made an arts center of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the city's emergence on the national theater scene,
members of the American Theater Critics Association saw the theater
company's current repertory in May when they held their conference
in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The company, part of the largest arts center between Chicago and
Los Angeles, includes as many as 230 professionals _ actors,
managers, technicians, artisans and publicists. Its annual $6.9
million budget is reserved solely for producing theater. Box office
services, development costs and rent are all paid by the performing
arts center.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Seawell's stewardship of a foundation, now worth $110
million, that supports the arts center, the troupe has four
different theaters in the arts complex available for an average of
15 productions a year: the Stage, a 700-seat hall with a thrust
stage; the Space, a 450-seat theater in the round; the Ricketson, a
250-seat proscenium house, and the Source, with 200 seats and a
thrust stage.
</P>
<P>
   Across Arapahoe Street, the company has a wealth of downtown
space rare in international theater. There is a vast old tramway
building, built in 1911, which houses rehearsal rooms; workshops
for sets, props, wigs and costumes, and the classrooms for the
company's two schools, the Denver Center Theater Academy and the
National Theater Conservatory. The Theater Conservatory, chartered
by Congress and established in 1984, has a master's program in
acting. During their third year, conservatory students apprentice
with the Denver Center Theater Company.
</P>
<P>
   Marley said the mingling of students and professionals was
vital. ``The theater is a very brutal world,'' he said. ``I want to
create a healing relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years as producing director of the Pacific Conservatory
of the Performing Arts, in Santa Maria and Solvang, Calif., Marley
came here in 1984, bringing several Pacific Conservatory members,
including Denver's current producing director, Barbara Sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Nagle Jackson, who has served as artistic director of the
Milwaukee Repertory Theater and the McCarter Theater in Princeton,
N.J., recently directed his poignant play ``Taking Leave'' here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing about the Denver company is that it
maintains what we all started out to do in the 1960s,'' he said.
``It is still a resident company in a community, creating good
theater. So many companies have moved in favor of more glamorous
pursuits in hopes of moving them on to Broadway. But then you might
just as well be a booking house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver is just one of two or three companies that are very
well endowed and have been well managed over the years, so are able
to maintain a large company and do big works,'' he continued.
``Denver has kept the flame alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The company produces musicals as well as classic and
contemporary plays in its annual season, October through June.
Audiences come from all over Colorado and the neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Elk Speaks,'' which had its premiere in Denver in 1993,
was later staged by Marley in Hong Kong with Cantonese-speaking
actors, then went to the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles in 1995.
``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' which originated in Denver in
1995, went to Cleveland for the opening of the Rock-and-Roll Hall
of Fame and later to the Arena Stage in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This past season, the company staged new versions of Carlos
Goldoni's ``Servant of Two Masters'' and Pedro Calderon de la
Barca's ``Life is a Dream.'' It also presented the world premiere
of Jackson's ``Taking Leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's forthcoming season features another world
premiere, Jackson's ``Elevation of Thieves,'' for which he won a
1997 Onassis Foundation International Playwriting Award, and a
fresh production of Derek Walcott's ``Dream on Monkey Mountain,''
with pulsing new choreography by Cleo Parker Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the company's Tony Award was announced, a theater
critic at The Rocky Mountain News accused the troupe of being too
complacent, considering the size of its endowment. But audiences
don't seem to agree. Attendance is rising despite the draw of
Denver's four major-league sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   The actors keep coming, too. ``Denver has a war chest that
cannot be matched,'' said Robert Westenberg, who came here last
August from the Broadway production of ``1776.'' ``The costumes,
the sets and lights are all first-rate. The work is tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Church, who joined the Denver troupe in 1988 after 28 years
with the Royal Shakespeare Company, has found ``a huge artistic
family where the technical crew and the actors are all treated with
an equal respect that I have never seen in England,'' he said.
``The range of material is extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Shay, who has been a member of the Negro Ensemble
Company and received a Tony nomination for her performance in
August Wilson's ``Seven Guitars,'' said: ``The menu of things that
are being offered to people is really wonderful. I call Denver
actor-friendly. It feels like an oasis where you can relax and
work. It's holistic in a sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sellers said: ``We are able to reach a little farther
because we have been able to assemble a group in one place, in one
community and have a sense of security. It is a family kind of
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   And the family felt proud to bring home Antoinette Perry's
award.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1855EDT &QL; 
