<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6227 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS &LR;      07-08 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIC GROUPS URGE CONGRESS TO PASS BILL BARRING HATE CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hate crime victims and dozens of civic, church and
civil rights groups urged Congress Wednesday to pass a bill making
it a federal crime to attack someone based on bias against gays,
women, or people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal came at a news conference on Capitol Hill sponsored
by 74 organizations including the Human Rights Campaign, National
Council of Churches, National Education Association, National
Organization for Women and the YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   One speaker, Pat Cramer, who owns the Casa Nova Restaurant and
Lounge, a nightclub for gays in Boswell, Pa., said that on March 9,
1997, someone ``shot into the bar, injuring three of my
customers.'' She added, ``I have received numerous death threats,
and my business has received a bomb scare. My husband and I live
above the Casa Nova, and every day I fear for our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania does not have a law banning violence against gays.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer and the groups attending the news conference praised a
bill offered by Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.; Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., and Ron Wyden, D-Ore. It would amend a federal statute
that currently bans violence against people engaged in a
federally-protected activity _ such as working, voting and going to
school or places of public accommodation _ on the basis of race,
color, religion, or national origin.
</P>
<P>
   The new bill would add hate crimes based on sexual orientation,
gender or disability. It would also allow federal officials to
pursue a case even if the victim was not engaged in a
federally-protected activity _ so long as the violence is not
covered by state law.
</P>
<P>
   Wyden explained, ``If there is no remedy on the (state) books,
our law will be there to back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing a case that could not be prosecuted under current laws,
Kennedy said a woman was raped in a train traveling from Miami to
New York, but ``because the woman couldn't identify which state she
was in, the rapist is still out on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyden said 12 states have no laws against hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Campaign (HRC), the nation's largest gay
political organization, released statistics showing that 61.6
percent of hate crimes are committed for racial reasons, 16 percent
because of religious bias, 11.6 percent because of anti-gay
sentiments and 10.7 percent for reasons relating to national
origin.
</P>
<P>
   Wyden said that the torture-murder of James Byrd, Jr., of
Jasper, Texas, last month was not covered by federal law because he
was not engaged in any federally protected activity when he was
attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a disabled 49-year-old black man, was walking on a Jasper
street in the early morning of June 7. He apparently accepted a
ride from three white men who allegedly beat him and chained him to
their pickup truck, dragging him down a country road. Dismembered
body parts were discovered in various places over a two-mile
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects were indicted Tuesday by a Jasper County grand jury
on charges a kidnapping and murder, a capital crime.
</P>
<P>
   One of Byrd's children, Renee Mullins, said at the news
conference, ``Nothing that Congress does will bring my father
back.'' But she added that the bill would make ``hate crimes like
the terrible act that took my father a federal crime and (would)
ensure that anyone who commits a hate crime will pay a price.''
</P>
<P>
   Later at a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing on the subject,
HRC Executive Director Elizabeth Birch testified that the
hate-crime bill would help homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally have stacks of newspaper clippings describing
gruesome hate crimes where lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgendered
Americans are beaten, assaulted and murdered, solely because of who
they are,'' she said. ``This bill is vitally needed. It is
constitutional, and it will provide a sense of safety to the
millions of Americans who are gay, lesbian, bisexual, or
transgendered.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee has not set a date for a vote on the measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
