<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMPTRIVIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEMP THROUGH HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (WITH HEMP-ART)  
 By ANNE M. SPITZA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Hemp is a plant that has up to 25,000 reported uses,
ranging from fuel to fabric, paper to paint, and cosmetics to
comestibles. It can even be used in explosives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tiny hemp seeds taste something like sunflower seeds and are
high in fiber and protein. Soy is its only organic nutritional
rival.
</P>
<P>
   _Man's earliest known fabric _ dating back to 7,000 B.C. _ was
apparently made of hemp.
</P>
<P>
   _ The word ``canvas'' is derived from the Greek word
``kannabis.''
</P>
<P>
   _Confucius' writings (550 B.C.) were transcribed on hemp paper.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Gutenberg Bible (15th century) was put down on hemp paper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Christopher Columbus' ships had hemp canvas sails.
</P>
<P>
   _ The paintings of Rembrandt, Van Gogh and others were primarily
painted on hemp canvases.
</P>
<P>
   _``Make the most of the hemp seed and sow it everywhere,''
proclaimed George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hemp was a mandatory crop in the American Colonies until the
mid-1700s. Thomas Jefferson and George Washington grew hemp on
their estates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Benjamin Franklin founded one of America's first paper mills
using hemp fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _Old Glory, sewn by Betsy Ross, was constructed with hemp
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   _ The first drafts of the Declaration of Independence were
written on Dutch (hemp) paper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Settlers of the West traveled in wagons covered by hemp
tarpaulins.
</P>
<P>
   _Levi Strauss' original jeans were reportedly made from sturdy
hemp sailcloth and worn by prospectors during the California gold
rush.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1941, Henry Ford unveiled an automobile fueled and
fabricated by hemp products. The auto that he ``grew from the
soil'' was never mass-produced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sources include ``The Emperor Wears No Clothes,'' by Jack Herer,
and ``Hemp: Lifeline to the Future,'' by Chris Conrad. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
