<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arnett won't face further job action
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- CNN decided Wednesday not to take any further action
against correspondent Peter Arnett for his role in the Operation
Tailwind story.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett met with CNN Chairman Tom Johnson, CNN International
President Eason Jordan and others Wednesday to defend his
involvement in the Tailwind story. Arnett, who won a Pulitzer Prize
for his coverage of Vietnam for The Associated Press, has said he
was only reading from a script prepared by producers and was not
responsible for the story, which CNN was forced to retract last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   CNN had announced a reprimand for Arnett, best known as the
network's correspondent in Baghdad, Iraq, during the Persian Gulf
War, as part of its retraction and apology. But it also had
announced that two producers had been fired and that Pam Hill, the
senior executive producer of ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' the program
on which the retracted story was run, had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of conference calls between Johnson and CNN
employees Monday and Tuesday, staffers raised questions as to
whether Arnett had been given more lenient treatment than the
producers because of his status at the network.
</P>
<P>
   After executives talked to Arnett and deliberated for most of
Wednesday, CNN released a statement that read: ``Peter Arnett's
reprimand stands. No further personnel actions are planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett was called back Tuesday from his vacation in Oregon to
confer with Johnson. Before the meeting, Arnett had defended his
role in the Tailwind story, saying he had conducted only three of
the interviews and then was reading questions prepared by the
producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was part of the team, but I didn't have supervising
authority. ... I was the face,'' Arnett told The New York Times
before Wednesday's meeting. ``There was nothing I could do to halt
the onward rush of this story.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, which aired June 7 on the debut of ``NewsStand,''
alleged that U.S. military forces in Laos used sarin nerve gas in
1970. An independent investigation found insufficient evidence to
support the charge, and CNN apologized to viewers and military
personnel involved.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
