<SLUG> BC-CNNCX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV newsmagazines have similar heirarchies
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Executive producer. Senior producer. This producer.
That producer.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's Tailwind story retraction has brought to the forefront the
myriad of personnel deep inside the broadcast and cable networks
who work on stories for TV's newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   Although every newsmagazine _ from ``Dateline NBC'' to CBS' ``60
Minutes'' _ functions somewhat differently, they have developed an
editorial heirarchy with very distinct roles:
</P>
<P>
   Executive Producer _ EPs, as they are usually called, are
responsible for the entire show. They are involved in hiring and
firing personnel, budgeting, the program's format, and approving
the final edits of the stories that are scheduled to appear on the
show. They rarely get involved in the reporting stage, unless the
story is sensitive or controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Producers _ They function as traffic cops and are
responsible for sifting through story proposals from segment
producers. They green-light story ideas they deem newsworthy, and
reject those that don't make the grade. Once a story has been
approved, they keep tabs on its progress as its being reported, and
screen rough edits of subjects being interviewed for the story.
</P>
<P>
   Producers _ Responsible for generating story ideas, doing
legwork, lining up interviews, conducting pre-interviews, writing
scripts, and supervising the editing of the story. Producers are
considered the ground troops who must have a clear idea of where a
story is going, and make the necessary adjustments when it changes
course. At a newspaper, the producer would perform many of the same
functions as a newspaper reporter whose byline ultimately appears
on a story.
</P>
<P>
   Associate Producers and Researchers _ Perform adminstrative and
journalstic grunt work such as fact-checking and scheduling for
upper-level producers. May also be involved in some of the
preliminary reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Correspondents _ Some act as traditional reporters who are
involved in every level of the story from inception to editing.
Some are merely celebrity journalists who ``parachute'' in when
most of the work has already been done to conduct interviews that
will be seen on-air, provide narration, and tape opening and
closing segments. And in some cases, they are glorified script
readers who are merely ``fronting'' stories that have been prepared
in advance by production staffers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys _will ``vet'' the story, especially controversial ones
to make sure they are not slanderous and unnecessarily expose the
network to lawsuits. Depending on the nature of the story, the
attorney will view everything from the rough-cuts to the network's
on-air promotions for the story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
