<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-IVY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WET SUMMER BRINGS POISON IVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JAY COOPER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Summer brings with it an onslaught of poison
ivy cases. This season many gardeners, landscapers and weekend
hikers already have had to coat their skin with goopy anti-itch
lotion more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Pereira, a horticultural education assistant at the
University Outreach and Extension, Jackson County, said weather has
been the main cause of the rampant poison ivy this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a lot of moisture has contributed to more poison ivy
(because) it promotes germination,'' Pereira said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that poison ivy has rooted itself across Missouri, the main
question is how to avoid it _ or get rid of it. The maxim ``leaves
of three, let them be,'' applies, but poison ivy isn't the only
three-leaf plant.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically poison ivy leaves are shiny and pointed. Poison ivy
also grows small, white or greenish-white berries at certain times
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   If you suspect poison ivy, get away from it or dispose of it,
but do not burn it. When inhaled, fumes of burning poison ivy may
cause dangerous swelling in the throat or lungs. Herbicides are the
best way to fight the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Pereira said the best time to spray is in the spring or fall
because as the plant grows, it will absorb the herbicide more
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   To dispose of the plant in midsummer, the university extension
recommended cutting it, forcing a grow cycle and then spraying it.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ashby, a dermatologist in North Kansas City, Mo., said
that if you're going to be around poison ivy, it's best to use a
barrier cream like Stokoguard or Ivy Block beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   If you do come in contact with the plant, Ashby said, try
over-the-counter antihistamine creams or anti-itch lotions. For
more severe cases, see a doctor for a prescription medicine or
cream.
</P>
<P>
   But who wants to spend a summer covered with rashes and lotions?
Identification and prevention are really the keys to avoid
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby also said that if you come in contact with the plant,
shower right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get rid of the resin in five to 10 minutes, you may not
break out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
