<SLUG> BC-CULINARY-CENTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY CULINARY CENTER IS REALITY NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ It has been a horse-and-buggy shop, the
butcher shop of a Thriftway store, a storage barn for Kansas City
Power &AMP; Light and a warehouse for junk.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest incarnation, co-owners Laura O'Rourke and Betsy
Titterington have transformed the 4,300-square-foot warehouse space
into the Culinary Center of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   They hope their culinary center, in downtown Overland Park, will
become to Kansas City cooks what the James Beard House is to the
nation's leading chefs.
</P>
<P>
   The home of the late culinarian, Beard's brick town house in New
York City has become in recent years a mecca for culinary education
and stylish entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there was a need for a place for the average person,
as well as the professional chef, to learn about the culinary
arts,'' O'Rourke says of their own endeavor. ``We want it to be
interactive, and we want people to have an opportunity to get their
hands dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   The center features a commercial//residential teaching kitchen
with state-of-the-art equipment, a comfortable dining area
featuring a 1,800-pound solid walnut table, a culinary resource
center with stone hearth and a large event space.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a ``breakout'' kitchen for pastry work, a
cooking//work station accessible for cooks in wheelchairs and an
herb garden outside the front door.
</P>
<P>
   The center will offer a variety of hands-on culinary classes
taught by area cooking professionals, but its founders plan to draw
on the skills of home cooks as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is `Mi casa es su casa.' There is no intimidation
here,'' O'Rourke says.
</P>
<P>
   Forthcoming classes include such subjects as cooking with two
ripe tomatoes, basic knife usage and maintenance, recipes from
Under the Tuscan Sky, pairing beer with food, Chinese peasant
cooking, cooking with produce from the farmers market and a pizza
class for kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful facility,'' says Karen Adler, owner of Pig
Out Publications and an accomplished gourmet cook who is scheduled
to teach at the culinary center. ``They have a broad view of what
their culinary center can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Before jumping off the career track to follow their culinary
dreams, O'Rourke worked as a lawyer and Titterington organized
running events. Although neither has a professional culinary
background, Titterington has taken classes at the Culinary
Institute of America in Napa Valley, and O'Rourke has taught
culinary classes at local community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very experienced in organizing events and
entertaining,'' O'Rourke says. ``It is a natural extension of who
we are.''
</P>
<P>
   They envision providing the cooking space for the community to
learn about food and wine while sharing the joys of the table. The
center will not have regular business hours.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to provide a space for culinary events and
affordable catering services. They also see it as a venue for
private dinner parties, bridal showers, corporate team-building,
cooking-show video production and even food-themed art shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are helping us evolve by letting us know what they
want. It's a canvas, and we're painting as we go,'' O'Rourke says.
``The biggest marketing challenge is helping people understand what
we're about.''
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of the center's current offering of classes write the
Culinary Center of Kansas City, 7917 Foster, Overland Park, Kan.
66204, or call (913) 341-4455.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
