A6243 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SILVA-KAN &LR;      07-08 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SILVA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEARLY EVERY CULTURE HAS ITS OWN VERSION OF SHISH KEBAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Shish kebabs are undeniably one of the most popular
foods cooked on a stick or skewer, and nearly every culture has its
own version.
</P>
<P>
   The word shish kebab comes from the Turkish, shish meaning to
skewer and kebab meaning chunk of meat. Culinary anthropologist
Elisabeth Rozin writes her book The Universal Kitchen that the same
word is shashlik in Russian and souvlakia in Greek.
</P>
<P>
   In India spit-grilled foods are called tandoori. The Persians
used pounded meat to form balls, croquettes and sausage-shaped
kebabs known as kofta. Satay is the Malay term for meat skewered
and cooked on bamboo skewers. The term is used throughout Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, skewer cookery became all the rage in the
'50s thanks to Russian immigrants who settled on both coasts after
World War I, leading New York Times food critic Craig Claiborne to
claim the ``shish kebab craze'' was second only to the national
rage for pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually anything that could be strung on a skewer was
barbecued in the Fifties,'' author Sylvia Lovegren confirms in
Fashionable Food: Seven Decades of Food Fads (Macmillan).
</P>
<P>
   Word play
</P>
<P>
   Rozin notes the words grill and skewer are ``unabashedly
aggressive metaphors.'' To ``grill'' someone means to question them
relentlessly. To ``skewer'' someone means to puncture, defeat or
pin them to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Bamboo or metal?
</P>
<P>
   Metal skewers are thought to be derived from the swords of
ancient Asian horsemen. But in Southeast Asia skewers usually are
made from bamboo. If you're using bamboo, don't forget to soak them
in water at least 30 minutes before holding them over the flames.
</P>
<P>
   Unskewering advice
</P>
<P>
   In his impressive new book, The Barbecue Bible (Workman), Steven
Raichlen gives this bit of advice for those who have ``tried to
unskewer too vigorously and sent cubes of meat sailing across the
dining room.''
</P>
<P>
   On his global barbecue jaunts, Raichlen noticed cooks in the
Near East and Central Asia employed this method to the madness:
``They hold the end of the skewer in one hand and grab the meat in
the other, using a piece of pita bread or a sheet of lavash as a
potholder. They pull the meat toward them a tiny bit to loosen it
from the skewer, then slide it off the skewer onto the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternative skewers
</P>
<P>
   Not sure what to thread on your skewer? A few suggestions you
might not have thought about from The Complete Book of Outdoor
Cookery by James Beard and Helen Evans Brown:
</P>
<P>
   - Alternate cubes of turkey with oysters wrapped in bacon.
</P>
<P>
   - Wrap squares of veal and Swiss cheese in bacon.
</P>
<P>
   - Skewer cubes of cooked duck and green olives, then brush with
orange juice and butter.
</P>
<P>
   - Marinate raw shrimp in equal parts of soy and sherry, then
roll in sesame seeds.
</P>
<P>
   - Dip pineapple chunks in the juice of preserved ginger. Serve
with grated coconut.
</P>
<P>
   Fish sticks
</P>
<P>
   Too fancy-smancy for you tastes?
</P>
<P>
   As any seasoned camper will tell you, the best of campfire
cuisine is based on stick or spit cooking. In Roughing It Easy (The
Dian Thomas Company) you'll find methods for cooking eggs, fish,
meat loaf and apple pie on a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't forget the marshmallows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
