<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR HAS LOST TOUCH WITH ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: As America's labor movement struggles to revitalize
itself, its leadership should ponder the implications of the
National Education Association's rejection of a proposed merger
with the American Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The bid to create the country's largest union apparently
foundered because many of the NEA delegates considered the AFT too
militant. Those who voted no also were concerned about the merger
bringing the association into the AFL-CIO's fold. One Iowa teacher
said members feared losing the independence that has been a proud
part of the association's heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The merger needed a two-thirds majority for approval but
received only 42 percent support. This was a stunning shortfall
considering the challenges facing those involved in traditional
public education. The voucher movement seeking wider freedom of
school choice is gaining momentum, as are other crusades to allow
public money to be used to subsidize private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the huge margin of disapproval, the NEA's leadership
vowed to continue pursuit of the merger, albeit in a form more
acceptable to members. Bob Chase, NEA president, said he believed
most delegates favored unification with the American Federation of
Teachers, ``but didn't think this plan was the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but Chase may be suffering from the same inability to
read the public mood as other labor leaders. The anomaly of
organized labor is that while it continues to exert considerable
political power, it continues to lose membership. This is happening
both in terms of absolute numbers and as a percentage of the work
force.
</P>
<P>
   Although aggressive recruiting campaigns mounted by the AFL-CIO
last year added 400,000 union members to its rolls, this still
wasn't enough to produce a net gain for organized labor. What makes
this lack of progress all the more remarkable is that it's
happening during a job-creation boom that should be producing
substantial employment growth in unionized businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind organized labor's declining appeal were
brought into sharper focus by the NEA vote. The leadership's agenda
seems too far out of step with the workplace hopes, dreams and
aspirations of ordinary workers.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas organized labor's membership was once overwhelmingly
blue-collar Democratic, for instance, the political lines haveshifted. Many union members now are as likely to vote Republican as
Democrat and consider themselves moderates, if not outright
conservatives. To some degree this reflects the success labor has
had helping workers achieve prosperity through higher wages and
wealth accumulation.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, union executives act as if they were leading a mass of
undereducated working folk as economically and politically
oppressed as they were 50 or 100 years ago. As a result they fail
to connect often enough with today's worker, which makes recruiting
all the more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   And when a few thousand General Motors workers in Michigan
strike and force huge layoffs of their brethren, it makes non-union
types all the more skeptical of the promised rewards of union
membership.
</P>
<P>
   When those representing the members of the NEA overwhelmingly
rejected a relationship with the harder-line leadership of
organized labor, their message was that they didn't think the
traditionalists could meet the challenges of a changing society,
workplace and economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
