<HEADER>
A6248 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOGUS-LIENS-KAN &LR;      07-08 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOGUS-LIENS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REVERSES CONVICTION OF `FREEMEN' CHARGED WITH FILING BOGUS
LIEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: In the first test of the state's new get-tough policy
on ``freemen'' and their common-law courts, a Missouri appeals
court on Tuesday reversed the convictions of 13 persons charged
with filing a $10.8 million bogus lien against a judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Court of Appeals in St. Louis ruled that though the
judge ``took great care in the trial of this matter and performed
admirably under the circumstances,'' he should have disqualified
himself at the defendants' request.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri legislators passed a law in 1996 banning the filing of
common-law court liens, with Secretary of State Rebecca Cook
calling it the toughest law in the country in fighting such actions
designed to vex public officials.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants who filed the multimillion-dollar lien against
the judge, nicknamed ``The Missouri 20'' by their sympathizers,
were the first prisoners in Attorney General Jay Nixon's war
against the so-called common-law courts.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, they were elated at the news of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm blessed,'' said Donald Ray Schaefer, a Montgomery County
man who was released in November after serving 11 months of a
two-year sentence. ``We're quite pleased with finally maybe getting
some justice in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, we did nothing wrong. They convicted us of a crime
that we did not commit because the judge was biased. We're not
against the government; we're against the people who are trying to
overthrow and run the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Those in the attorney general's office were not happy with the
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very unusual,'' said Mary Still, Nixon's spokeswoman.
``With all due respect for the judges, we fear that their leniency
with this group would set a dangerous precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   In their 17-page ruling, the justices said that the right of a
defendant to disqualify a judge in criminal and civil cases ``is
one of the keystones of our legal administrative edifice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No system of justice can function at its best or maintain
broad public confidence if a litigant can be compelled to submit
his case in a court where he sincerely believes the judge is
incompetent or prejudiced,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, statutes and rules are liberally construed in favor of
the right to disqualify....Therefore, if a request for trial judge
disqualification is in proper order, the trial judge's duty is to
sustain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri law allows just one change of judge under those
circumstances, however.
</P>
<P>
   Still said the attorney general will ask for a rehearing at the
appellate court level ``so hopefully we will not have to go back
and have a new trial.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the defendants _ who represented themselves in court _
did not provide appropriate notice of their request for a new
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that standard rules of order in the court should be
followed and upheld, regardless of whether the defendant is pro se
or represented,'' she said. ``Had they followed appropriate rules
and provided notice that they were requesting a new judge, we would
not have objected to their request for a new judge. The fact is
they did not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The convictions stemmed from the case of Amanda Lenk, a
17-year-old from Silex, Mo., who was stopped by the Missouri
Highway Patrol in February 1996 and cited for driving 78 mph in a
55 mph zone, failing to wear a seat belt and failing to drive
within a single lane.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, Lenk filed a ``Declaration of Quiet Title,''
designating herself a ``sovereign citizen.'' When she appeared
before Lincoln County Associate Judge Patrick S. Flynn the
following month, her father, Melvin Lenk, warned the judge to drop
the charges. The judge refused and, two weeks later, received an
``Order to Appear'' in ``our one supreme court.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, 1996, a 20-member ``common-law grand jury''
convened in Bowling Green, Mo., and found the judge guilty of
violating Amanda Lenk's rights. The ``jury'' ordered that a $10.8
million lien be placed on the judge's property. The lien was filed
by Amanda Lenk's father and grandfather on April 1, 1996, with the
Lincoln County recorder's office.
</P>
<P>
   Following an investigation by the Missouri Highway Patrol, Nixon
ordered the arrests of those who had participated in the ``grand
jury'' for tampering with a judicial official _ a class C felony.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen of the defendants were tried in Lincoln County, with
Nixon sending his own special prosecutors to handle the case.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn testified that he felt threatened by the lien and said he
saw two of the defendants in the courthouse after the charges were
filed against them. One of them, Flynn said, told the other that
the judge ``ought to be shot.''
</P>
<P>
   At their trial, the defendants requested a new judge, claiming,
among other things, that Circuit Court Judge Fred Rush was biased.
Rush denied their request, and all of the defendants were
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Patrick Logan of St. Peters and Clifford Keith Hobbs of
Auxvasse, the self-appointed leaders of ``our one supreme court,''
were sentenced to seven years. Most of the remaining defendants,
including Ima Deana Conklin of Oak Grove, received two-year
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs is still in prison. Still said she did not know yet
whether he would be released as a result of Tuesday's appeals court
action.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer, who lives near Hermann in Montgomery County, said he
and the others now plan to sue the state for wrongfully convicting
them. And again, he said, they'll represent themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never once had an attorney, wouldn't have an attorney,
because they're all part of the American Bar Association, whose
headquarters are in London, England,'' he said. ``They're all
taking this country over for England.''
</P>
<P>
   He said though he hasn't sat on a common-law grand jury
recently, ``I'm still teaching people about the constitution and
their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Still said Tuesday's court ruling would not discourage the
attorney general from prosecuting similar cases in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue of procedure in court,'' she said. ``It
really doesn't have to do with the new law. Clearly, we feel that
no one has the right to threaten law enforcement and attempt to
sabotage the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sent a strong message, and we haven't had that much
activity ever since this case. I think that message still stands. I
think we'll get this straightened out in court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
