<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAIN BOY'S MOTHER, CLINTON CALL FOR TIGHTER GUN CONTROLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Spelling of Suzann and Brittheny are cq) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and a woman whose daughter was
killed in a schoolyard shooting urged states and Congress on
Wednesday to tighten restrictions on children's access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the series of recent campus killings ``seared the heart
of America,'' the president called for new laws similar to one
passed in Texas three years ago penalizing adults who fail to keep
guns away from minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still too easy for deadly weapons to wind up in the
hands of children, by intent or by accident, and then, to lead to
tragedy,'' Clinton said. ``No matter how you analyze this, it is
clear that the combination of children and firearms is deadly.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also announced new federal regulations requiring
gun dealers to post warnings about laws barring the sale of
handguns to anyone under 18 and federal support for a Maryland
program designed to trace the sales and ownership of every gun
seized by police.
</P>
<P>
   The president's announcement followed emotional remarks from
Suzann Wilson, the mother of 11-year-old Brittheny Varner, one of
four students shot to death when two classmates opened fire at
Westside Middle School in Jonesboro, Ark. A teacher also was killed
while trying to shield her students. Two boys _ ages 11 and 13 _
were arrested and charged in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in Jonesboro could have been prevented,'' Wilson
said in a halting voice as she choked back tears. ``Two children
who should never have had unsupervised access to firearms were able
to put together a small arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``To every gun owner in America I want to say please, please,
for the sake of the children, lock up your guns,'' Wilson said.
``Don't let what happened in Jonesboro happen to your town.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about gun rights, it's about gun safety,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the most recent school year, armed students opened fire
on classmates in Pearl, Miss.; Jonesboro; West Paducah, Ky.;
Edinboro, Pa.; and, seven weeks ago, in Springfield, Ore. Sixteen
students and teachers were killed in the incidents; 43 were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen states have passed so-called ``safe-storage laws'' that
provide criminal penalties for adults who allow children
unsupervised access to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged other states to follow suit. He also endorsed a
proposal by Sens. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., and John Chafee, R-R.I.,
designed to encourage the use of so-called ``trigger locks'' or
other security mechanisms when storing guns.
</P>
<P>
   The Durbin-Chafee proposal also would impose penalties on gun
owners who fail to safely store their guns or use trigger locks if
a firearm falls into the hands of a minor who uses it against
against another person, shows it in a public place, or takes it to
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This recent series of killings in our schools has seared the
heart of America about as much as anything I can remember,''
Clinton said. ``We can't shrug our shoulders and say, `well,
accidents happen,' or `some kids are beyond hope.' That's a copout.
Every one of us must step up to our responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the White House has drawn criticism for brokering a
deal that would limit damage awards against small businesses _
including gun makers _ in product liability cases. The product
liability reform, which awaits action by the Senate, is a priority
of congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, part of a tort-reform effort worked out during the
past 18 months by the White House and Senate Republicans, would put
a $250,000 cap on the amount small businesses must pay in punitive
damages for marketing defective products. Exempted from that cap _
which essentially means there are no limits to damages that be
awarded by the courts _ are makers of tobacco products and silicone
implants.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sens. Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer of
California, and Robert Torricelli of New Jersey announced plans
Tuesday to try to amend the legislation to allow unrestricted
damage awards against gun makers. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
said he was ``not inclined'' to allow the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned that if this bill passes in its present
form, it would limit product liability suits against gun makers and
sellers at the very time we are seeing such efforts that proved so
successful in the battle against smoking tobacco,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Without the amendment, Boxer said, ``this bill is a travesty, a
complete travesty.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
