<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6256 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-ART-800(2     07-08 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BASEBALL'S SECOND-HALF BEGINS, MARK MCGWIRE LEADS THE MARIS
CHASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Mark McGwire leads the major leagues in home runs
and in blank stares. Visualization, he calls it: Before each at-bat
McGwire will imagine the pitcher throwing the baseball, he'll
imagine how the ball will move, maybe a fastball or curveball, and
he'll imagine smashing the ball with his Paul Bunyan swing.
</P>
<P>
   But McGwire stops there. In his mind's eye, the St. Louis
Cardinals slugger does not visualize home runs, which separates him
from just about everybody who follows baseball, fans and fellow
players alike.
</P>
<P>
   The fans are visualizing many home runs from McGwire, and Ken
Griffey, Jr., Sammy Sosa and others, as the second half of the
major league season starts. What they envision down the road is a
general siege on the single-season record for home runs _ 61,
established by the Yankees' Roger Maris in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest record out there,'' said Tony Gwynn of the
San Diego Padres, the eight-time batting champion. ``It's bigger
than hitting .400. Breaking Maris' record is the biggest thing that
can be done in baseball today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, the right fielder for the Chicago Cubs, has 33 home runs,
Seattle's Griffey has 35, and there are other sluggers who, with a
flurry of home runs, could join the pursuit. McGwire, however,
leads them all with 37 home runs, and he is considered the most
likely to scale the Maris mountain because of his extraordinary
power, and because of the refinements he's made as a hitter. Only
the pitchers' fear of him and their reluctance to throw him strikes
will prevent him from hitting 62 or more homers, most believe, so
long as he remains injury-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they pitch to him,'' said David Howard, the Cardinals'
veteran infielder, ``he'll hit 70 home runs. I have no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit 52 homers in 1996, 58 last year. He's on a pace to
hit 70 home runs this season, averaging 1 for every 7.2 at-bats.
He's batting .310, .349 when there are runners on base, when
pitchers are more compelled to pitch to him. After Gwynn reached
first base against the Cardinals earlier this year, he turned to
McGwire and said, ``Everybody talks about your home runs, but
people don't realize what a good hitter you've become.''
</P>
<P>
   His home runs are titanic, their distances measured as far as
545 feet. His batting practice is a sideshow everywhere, fans
gathering in all decks of left field of whatever park he visits.
Opposing players stand and gawk like everybody else, their heads
turning with each blow, as if they're watching a space shuttle
launching.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in St. Louis, Glendon Rusch of the Kansas City Royals
made sure he was on the field to see McGwire's batting practice.
Two hours later, Rusch was on the mound, as the starting pitcher
for Kansas City, and in the seventh inning, he surrendered
McGwire's 37th home run, a shot of 472 feet. ``I'm going to do
everything I can to get him out,'' Rusch said the next day. ``But
once he hit it, I was going to watch it like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when opponents pitched to McGwire more without
such fear, and fearlessly. Though a dangerous slugger, McGwire had
a hole in his swing, and everybody knew you could get him out by
throwing fastballs inside _ even with average fastballs. Sure, if
you made a mistake, he'd crush the ball, but if you pitched him
correctly he had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire might be 6-foot-5 and 250 pounds, his biceps and
quadriceps straining the fabric of his uniform, but the mechanics
of his swing were such that he couldn't get his bat around quickly
enough to hit the inside fastball. That's why McGwire had such a
terrible time against a hard thrower like Roger Clemens, with only
4 hits in 47 at-bats. Aim fastballs at McGwire's hands was the
conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Early this season, Brad Ausmus, the catcher for the Houston
Astros, read in the team's scouting report that pitchers shouldn't
pitch inside to McGwire. Ausmus dismissed the intelligence, for he
played against McGwire in the American League two years ago and
knew that you could beat him with inside fastballs. ``When the
scouting report differs from my own experience,'' Ausmus said,
``I'll always rely on my experience.''
</P>
<P>
   With the left-hander Pete Schourek pitching to McGwire, Ausmus
called for a fastball inside. Schourek threw ``a good fastball,
89-90 mph, inside,'' Ausmus recalls. McGwire launched it into the
third deck, but just foul.
</P>
<P>
   Ausmus wondered if McGwire's blast was a fluke, and later in the
series, with the right-hander Jose Lima on the mound, Ausmus called
for another fastball. ``Lima's fastball probably gets up to 92 mph,
and he put one right on McGwire's hands,'' Ausmus remembered. ``He
hit a missile over the fence that was never more than 25 feet off
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for conventional wisdom, so much for the holes in
McGwire's swing. He now has ``a perfect approach'' at the plate,
according to one of his former hitting coaches, after years of
evolution. Hitting, McGwire maintained last week, is the hardest
thing to do in sports. ``If it was easy, a lot more people would be
doing it,'' he said. ``You have half a second to realize whether
it's a slider, forkball, split-finger, or a 90-mph fastball. You've
got to be balanced at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have good hand-eye coordination. I guarantee, you
can get any athlete in any other sport, they wouldn't want to get
in that box to face the pitcher, but we do.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nobody visualized McGwire as a great hitter when he was in high
school. The University of Southern California figured him for a
pitcher when he enrolled there in the fall of 1981, but after that
first year, Ron Vaughn, an assistant coach with the Trojans, took
McGwire with him to play first base in an Alaska summer league.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn had seen McGwire playing for Damien High in Claremont,
Calif., and thought his swing was too long _ that it took McGwire a
long time to get the head of the bat through the strike zone _ and
that he lacked balance. But McGwire was willing to work, and he had
power. Vaughn can remember McGwire that summer in Alaska, driving a
ball all the way to the 30-yard line of a football field beyond the
left field fence.
</P>
<P>
   In time, and with work, McGwire became a star hitter and was
drafted 10th over all by Oakland in 1984. Three years later he hit
49 home runs in his rookie season for the Athletics. ``He was more
of a reactive hitter,'' recalled Merv Rettenmund, the hitting coach
for Oakland at the time. ``He just saw the ball and hit it. He
wasn't a student of the game, like he is now.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire continued to hit home runs, but his average plummeted
from year to year, from .289 to .260 to .231, and in 1991, he
batted .201. He had that big hole in his swing, at his hands, and
he struck out about once in every three times at bat. Rettenmund is
convinced that McGwire's biggest problem was his eyesight. ``He was
squinting all the time,'' said Rettenmund. ``He just looked like he
had no clue where the ball was.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, McGwire first learned about his poor eyesight while
playing Little League. His father had replaced him as the pitcher,
sending him to shortstop, and when the boy stopped crying, he
realized he couldn't see home plate. McGwire now has 20/500 vision,
which he corrects with contact lenses.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he addressed his vision trouble, McGwire started
suffering injuries, primarily to his left heel; he played a total
of 74 games during the 1993-94 seasons. He considered quitting and
becoming a policeman, but he thought about his father, John, a
dentist, who contracted polio at age seven. ``He never had a chance
to play sports when he was a kid,'' McGwire once explained. ``When
I think of my father, it makes my injuries seem so miniscule.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire kept playing, improved his physical fitness, and he
learned more about hitting. Slowly, McGwire plugged the hole in his
swing, where pitchers had thrown fastballs past him.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, McGwire has streamlined his access to the news
media. But in several group interviews as well as interviews from
previous years, he has provided cursory descriptions of the
adjustments he's made in his swing. Former coaches and peers have
provided the more telling details.
</P>
<P>
   Among the improvements were his ability to reduce the movement
in his hands. Rather than draw them back slightly, as the pitch was
being thrown, McGwire taught himself to lock them in place and
bring them forward. Before, McGwire had to cock and fire his swing
as the pitch was being delivered. With the adjustment, he
effectively cocked his swing before the pitch was delivered, and
then fired his bat. He had shortened his long swing, made it
quicker, and began hitting inside fastballs that once overwhelmed
him.
</P>
<P>
   He changed the positioning of his feet, too. Early in his
career, he had turned his toes inward as he prepared to hit. Now
his feet are turned outward slightly, and he takes one small stride
toward the pitcher of approximately eight inches.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball lingo, McGwire has quiet feet and quiet hands _
quiet, because there's so little wasted motion, and the reduced
movement allows him to keep his head in place, Rettenmund says, and
see the pitches better. ``He couldn't identify a breaking ball
before,'' said Rettenmund. ``Now he sees everything and he's much
more patient and better at not chasing pitches out of the strike
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Quiet hands, quiet feet, loud bat. Robert Adair, a professor of
physics at Yale University, says that while most hitters generate
bat speed of 65 mph, McGwire's is ``at least 75 mph,'' maybe more.
If you slow down videotape of all the great hitters, Adair noted,
you'll see that at the point of contact, their bodies have stopped
their movement, the front leg is stiff, and all the energy
generated has been funneled into the head of the bat. ``That's the
beautiful part of the swing,'' said Adair.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire generates around 30 percent more energy than most
hitters, according to Adair, swinging a 34 1/2-inch, 33-ounce bat _
his is different than most power hitters, because he uses a bat of
regular proportions, rather than one with a tapered handle and a
wide barrel.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' Rick Reed allowed McGwire's 400th career homer earlier
this year at Shea Stadium. ``He hit it, like a mile high, and it
looked like a pop-up, but it kept going,'' Reed said. ``It was 800
feet in the air and it landed in the first row of the seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed acknowledged the fear of pitching to McGwire _ a physical
fear, of the possibility he might hit the ball through the middle.
``If he hit it back at you, it might go through you,'' said Reed.
``He hits a nubber in front of the plate and you just about jump
out of your shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he hits a home run or strikes out, McGwire's demeanor
rarely varies. ``I've never seen anybody that intense,'' said
Howard, ``or someone that can concentrate like that. He hit a grand
slam once and when he got to home plate, he seemed a little
surprised all these guys were waiting for him. He got back to the
dugout and asked, `How many guys were on base?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He stands there with his eyes closed, and he's already
envisioning what he's going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire begins to visualize as he goes to the bat rack, staring
straight ahead. Two batters removed from his at-bat, McGwire will
stand at the base of the dugout steps, resting the bat flatly
across his shoulder, watching the pitcher work. When the pitcher
goes into his delivery, McGwire draws the bat down, as if to cock
it.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire repeats this throughout his teammate's at-bat, and
continues the practice when he reaches the on-deck circle, watching
the pitcher, cocking his bat, then resting it on his shoulder,
staring downward between pitches, visualizing. In his mind's eye,
he's seeing the pitch perfectly, hitting it squarely; when hit
properly, a baseball is compressed to one-half of its original
diameter at the moment of contact.
</P>
<P>
   Now his name is being called, it's his turn to bat, and McGwire
slowly circles behind the catcher, bat on his shoulder, staring
downward, never looking at the pitcher. He steps into the box,
holding the bat in his right hand, and with his right foot, he
violently digs a hole, breastworks for his swing. His right foot is
like a pick ax. His biceps, 20 inches around, are only partly
concealed by his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   He steps back, glances at his bat, steps back in, settles into
his stance, feet turned out slightly. Only then does he look at the
pitcher, a stare. McGwire is very large. The ballpark seems
smaller. His bat is drawn back.
</P>
<P>
   By then the pitcher probably is visualizing, too, along with
everybody else. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
