<HEADLINE>
BROWN QUITS THE NEW YORKER FOR MIRAMAX JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's highest-profile magazine no longer has America's
highest-profile editor. In a move no less shocking for having been
speculated about for several months, Tina Brown resigned as editor
of The New Yorker Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is leaving the magazine after six years to start a joint
venture with Miramax Films. The New York-based firm will publish a
new monthly magazine, as well as produce films, generate television
programming, and publish books.
</P>
<P>
   ``This partnership with Miramax is a unique creative and
business opportunity _ to own what we create and to expand our
vision into other media,'' Brown said in a statement issued by
Miramax, an autonomous division of the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 44, will serve as chairman. The firm's president will be
Ron Galotti, who resigned Wednesday as publisher of Vogue. Vogue,
like The New Yorker, is part of Conde Nast Publications. Other
magazines Conde Nast publishes include Glamour, GQ, and Vanity
Fair, where Brown and Galotti previously worked together.
</P>
<P>
   No successor has been named at either The New Yorker or Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tina Brown is the best editor in the world, with taste and
talent that is second to none,'' said Harvey Weinstein, cochairman
of Miramax, in a prepared statement. ``I couldn't be more thrilled
to be forming a business that will allow her to take that genius
and apply it to film, television, and books.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised it took this long,'' said Esquire film critic
David Thomson of Brown's move into new media. ``The possibility of
her involvement in films has long been there. Especially when she
was at Vanity Fair, there were overtures made,'' said Thomson, who
wrote for Brown when she was editor of Vanity Fair. ``Her father
was a film producer, and she's never made a secret of her interest
in the business. She certainly has no enemies in Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   As editor of Vanity Fair from 1984 to 1992, the English-born
Brown established her reputation on this side of the Atlantic for
big-ticket, high-gloss editing. She made the magazine an emblem of
'80s excess _ and the antithesis of the sedate, reflective style of
The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective clash of magazine cultures made for front-page
news when Brown was named editor of The New Yorker in 1992. While
largely retaining the magazine's intellectual cachet, Brown
enlivened The New Yorker's graphics, made it consistently topical,
and jettisoned the magazine's long-held reputation for propriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she added to The New Yorker was getting people to read it
and talk about it in a way they had not in a long, long time,''
said Arthur Cooper, editor-in-chief of GQ.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's success came at a price. The New Yorker increased its
circulation from 450,000 to 800,000 but has never been profitable
under Brown. Last year, it lost an estimated $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about Brown's departure began to circulate last spring.
Fueling the speculation had been reported unhappiness at The New
Yorker, which had been a separate business entity, over its being
consolidated into Conde Nast operations. In May, David Carey was
named president of the magazine without Brown's being consulted.
Her contract was reportedly up for renewal this month, although a
senior Conde Nast editor said Wednesday, ``I'd take the contract
issue with a grain of salt. Contracts aren't regarded all that
seriously around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown will stay at The New Yorker through the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about her successor began as soon as news of her
resignation began to spread through the media world. Among many
names bruited about have been those of Graydon Carter, who
succeeded her at Vanity Fair, GQ's Cooper, Conde Nast editorial
director James Truman, House &AMP; Garden editor Dominique Browning,
New Yorker fiction editor Bill Buford, New Yorker staff writer
David Remnick, and New York Times Magazine editor Adam Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's resignation is this month's second major magazine
shake-up. It follows the departure last week of US News &AMP; World
Report editor James Fallows, who was fired by that publication's
editorial director, Harold Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Evans is married to Tina Brown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
