<P>
   &UR; Y2K BUG COULD HAVE BENEFITS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID GRIMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It is not too early to begin breaking out in nervous hives over
the ``millennium bug,'' that minor computer glitch that, come Jan.
1, 2000, will simultaneously detonate every nuclear warhead on the
planet, crash the world's stock markets and, perhaps most alarming
of all, make it impossible to buy a lottery ticket at your
neighborhood convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   Or not, depending on whom you talk to.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what's so unsettling about the millennium bug, also
known as ``Y2K'' for reasons that are altogether clear: You do not
know whether you should be stockpiling your underground compound in
Wyoming with emergency rations and automatic weapons or popping
another cold one and watching ``Ren and Stimpy'' cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium bug refers to what might or might not happen in
the first few seconds of 2000 when all the world's computers
advance the date from 99 to 00. Although computers are incredibly
clever to the point that they can run power plants and create the
special effects for movies like ``Armageddon'' (is there a
connection here?), they are also incredibly stupid in that they
cannot figure out that the year after 1999 is 2000, not 1900.
Apparently, once a computer decides that the year is 1900, it goes
crazy with grief, which is understandable considering that
computers hadn't been invented yet in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   What this means to us is unclear or perfectly clear, depending
on whom you wish to believe. There are Internet forums where
``doomsayers'' debate ``Pollyannas'' over the severity of the
millennium bug's impact.
</P>
<P>
   Candace Turner (whom it would be safe to label a doomsayer) of
Cartersville, Mo., manufactures ``Y2K survival domes'' and markets
them on the Internet for $7,000 apiece. Other alarmists have begun
storing survival food, building fortified hideouts in the
countryside and stockpiling guns and ammo to protect their turf.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, it does not take a great deal of incentive for a
certain percentage of the American population to build fortified
hideouts in the countryside or stockpile guns and ammo. A
penny-a-gallon rise in the price of gasoline might do the trick, as
might a tabloid news story reporting that the House of
Representatives is controlled by aliens.)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its severity, the millennium bug is certainly bad news
for people like myself whose feelings about computers range from
vague mistrust to outright terror. Anyone who writes on a computer
has experienced a ``crash'' where days, weeks or even years of work
is suddenly beamed into a parallel universe from where it can never
be retrieved.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of crashes, airline passengers are unlikely to take
much comfort from the millennium bug, particularly if they were
nervous to begin with. What fun it would be to be flying at 35,000
feet over the Rocky Mountains at midnight, Jan. 31, 1999, and have
the onboard computer suddenly reprogram itself so that it is no
longer flying the airplane but is, instead, colorizing the movie
``Casablanca'' or ordering one of Candace Turner's survival domes
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be interesting to go to the supermarket for a
half-gallon of milk and a loaf of bread and have the check-out
scanner tell you that you owe $35,000
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is also possible, I suppose, that the millennium
bug will cause all the world's automatic teller machines to
suddenly shoot out a stream of $20 bills and all the slot machines
in Las Vegas to hit ``jackpot.''
</P>
<P>
   So you might want to plan on being in a big casino when the
clock strikes midnight Jan. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   I just wouldn't advise taking an airplane to get there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How to Write More Better &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. Avoid alliteration. Always.
</P>
<P>
   2. Never use a long word when a diminutive one will do.
</P>
<P>
   3. Employ the vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   4. Eschew ampersands &AMP; abbreviations, etc.
</P>
<P>
   5. Parenthetical remarks (however relevant) are unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   6. Remember to never split an infinitive.
</P>
<P>
   7. Contractions aren't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   8. Foreign words and phrases are not apropos.
</P>
<P>
   9. One should never generalize.
</P>
<P>
   10. Eliminate quotations. As Ralph Waldo Emerson said, `I hate
quotations. Tell me what you know.`
</P>
<P>
   11. Comparisons are as bad as cliches.
</P>
<P>
   12. Don't be redundant; don't use more words than necessary;
it's highly superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   13. Be more or less specific.
</P>
<P>
   14. Understatement is always best.
</P>
<P>
   15. One-word sentences? Eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   16. Analogies in writing are like feathers on a snake.
</P>
<P>
   17. The passive voice is to be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   18. Go around the barn at high noon to avoid colloquialisms.
</P>
<P>
   19. Even if a mixed metaphor sings, it should be derailed.
</P>
<P>
   20. Who needs rhetorical questions?
</P>
<P>
   21. Exaggeration is a billion times worse than understatement.
</P>
<P>
   22. Don't never use a double negation.
</P>
<P>
   23. capitalize every sentence and remember always end it with
point
</P>
<P>
   24. Do not put statements in the negative form.
</P>
<P>
   25. Verbs have to agree with their subjects.
</P>
<P>
   26. Proofread carefully to see if you words out.
</P>
<P>
   27. If you reread your work, you can find on rereading a great
deal of repetition can be avoided by rereading and editing.
</P>
<P>
   28. A writer must not shift your point of view.
</P>
<P>
   29. And don't start a sentence with a conjunction. (Remember,
too, a preposition is a terrible word to end a sentence with.)
</P>
<P>
   30. Don't overuse exclamation marks!!!
</P>
<P>
   31. Place pronouns as close as possible, especially in long
sentences, as of 10 or more words, to their antecedents.
</P>
<P>
   32. Writing carefully, dangling participles must be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   33. If any word is improper at the end of a sentence, a linking
verb is.
</P>
<P>
   34. Take the bull by the hand and avoid mixing metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   35. Avoid trendy locutions that sound flaky.
</P>
<P>
   36. Everyone should be careful to use a singular pronoun with
singular nouns in their writing.
</P>
<P>
   37. Always pick on the correct idiom.
</P>
<P>
   38. The adverb always follows the verb.
</P>
<P>
   39. Last but not least, avoid cliches like the plague; They're
old hat; seek viable alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   _Passed on by staff writer Amy Vernon at the Arizona Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
