<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-JURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY BEGINS WEIGHING BRAWLEY CASE EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. -- After seven months of courtroom testimony
and tirades, the jury in the Tawana Brawley defamation trial
finally started deliberations Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the plaintiff, Steven Pagones, it has been a longer wait
still _ 10 years, in fact, since he filed his lawsuit against the
Rev. Al Sharpton and two other civil-rights activists, who had
publicly accused Pagones and five other white men of abducting and
raping Brawley, a 15-year-old black girl.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the accusations set off a storm of racial tensions
not only in this sleepy town, 80 miles north of New York City, but
across the entire country.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones was exonerated of all charges in 1988 by a grand jury,
which also concluded that Brawley had probably concocted the entire
tale. However, Sharpton and his two co-defendants _ Alton H. Maddox
and C. Vernon Mason _ kept up their campaign against Pagones, who
responded by suing them for defamation of character.
</P>
<P>
   He is asking $400 million in damages, though it is unlikely the
three could raise even a tiny fraction of that sum.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which began last December, has been interrupted
repeatedly by loud and lengthy outbursts from all sides of the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the case, Sharpton _ who, over the years, has
fashioned an increasingly respectable political career for himself
_ has tried to sidestep the question of whether a rape took place
or whether Pagones did it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his lawyer, Michael Hardy, has argued that Sharpton was
simply acting as Brawley's advocate and believed what she said.
Since the law holds that Pagones must prove the defendants acted
with malice and ``reckless disregard for the truth,'' Sharpton, by
this argument, cannot be said to have defamed Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   However, Maddox and Mason have taken a different tack _
continuing to maintain that Pagones raped Brawley and used his
position as a Dutchess County assistant district attorney to cover
up the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones' lawyer, William Stanton, has meanwhile argued that all
the defendants knew they were lying and that they have not produced
a single shred of evidence against his client.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing statement Tuesday, Stanton went further and
called the three defendants ``evil,'' likening their ``big lies''
to those of Hitler's propaganda minister, Josef Goebbels.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton lashed out against Stanton for this comparison after
Wednesday's session, saying, ``We never asked for Mr. Pagones to be
put in an oven. We only asked him to be put in a courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton also defended his own actions of a decade ago more
outspokenly than usual these days. ``I believe that what we did,
history dictated that we do,'' he told reporters. ``What we did,
history will vindicate.''
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom was packed Wednesday, mainly with supporters of
Sharpton and Maddox, who have been coming up here regularly, from
Brooklyn and New Jersey, since the trial began.
</P>
<P>
   It took all morning for Justice S. Barrett Hickman to read the
jury his legal instructions _ the precise wording of which he had
hammered out, over four days' of negotiations last week, with the
four lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant instruction was that the jurors may
infer from Brawley's absence as a witness that she would not have
supported the contention that she was abducted and raped.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the jury out of the room, the defense lawyers raised
a few final legal objections. Finally, at 2:50 pm, Hickman ordered
the six jurors _ four white, two black _ to begin deliberating.
</P>
<P>
   By state law, the jury does not need to reach a unanimous
verdict. Agreement by five of the six jurors is sufficient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
