<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6271 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-ARLEN-NAT     07-08 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-ARLEN-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      SPECTER BACK TO WORK
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 8 -- U.S. Sen. Arlen Specter settled into
familiar territory Wednesday, back in his Senate office after
nearly a six-week recuperation from heart surgery, cracking jokes
about his restless approach to lawmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctor told me to take it easy. I asked him how to spell it,''
Specter, R-Pa., quipped. He said the doctor couldn't spell ``easy''
-- so he won't be taking it easy, at least not as easy as doctors
would like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors have given me the green light to proceed with
caution,'' he said, slightly more serious, in a 45-minute briefing
with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Specter returned to the Senate floor Tuesday night, receiving a
round of applause from his colleagues, and had his first full day
at work Wednesday. He checked into Thomas Jefferson Hospital in
Philadelphia May 30 with chest pains, which led to a double bypass
surgery. Within a week he was back in the hospital with aspiration
pneumonia, a complication that Specter said was ``not unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel very lucky to have weathered the storm,'' he said,
admitting to being heavily sedated during the first few days after
the surgery and unable to recall much of what occurred.
</P>
<P>
   He was released June 15, and has spent the past three weeks
recuperating at his home in Philadelphia. Three times a day Specter
took 500-yard walks, followed by hand and leg exercises.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not been allowed to play his favorite pastime,
squash, and will not be allowed to play until probably next month.
</P>
<P>
   Specter, 68, said he conferred with his doctors on a plan to
ease his way back into his duties as a senator. He'll spend most of
his day in his private hideaway, just off the Senate floor, so that
he will have an easy walk to Senate votes, as opposed to the quick
trots most senators must make from their office building to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He will not attend many Senate hearings, which usually number
about four a day. This timetable will also keep Specter off the
campaign trail in his bid to win a fourth six-year term to the
senate.
</P>
<P>
   Specter and his aides do not expect health to be an issue in the
campaign against state Sen. Bill Lloyd, D-Somerset, and Specter
said he would be ``full tilt before Labor Day'' -- leaving him
plenty of time to campaign against the vastly underfunded Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   Turning philosophical, Specter admitted that his doctors would
prefer him to slow down his schedule but that it was ``very
difficult'' for him ``to maintain a slower pace,'' something that
was ``not doable'' until after the election -- probably never. ``I
don't anticipate any slowing down.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart surgery comes fives year after Specter had surgery for
a benign brain tumor. ``I've been able to take both of them in
stride,'' said Specter, who is thinner but would not say how much
weight he lost after the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he has not given any thought to retiring. In the
short run, he said, ``If at any time I'm not up to it, I'll go home
and go to bed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
