<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL DOWNPLAYS PALESTINE'S UN ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli government went out of its way Wednesday
to downplay the nearly unanimous vote in the United Nations Tuesday
giving Palestinians a voice in the world body for the first time.
Even Israeli newspapers treated the action lightly.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts throughout the Middle East said that the 124-4 vote
upgrading the Palestine Liberation Organization's status at the
United Nations was a startling example of the increased isolation
of the United States and Israel in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Key US allies such as Britain, Germany, and France voted against
the United States and Israel Tuesday, apparently frustrated by the
Clinton administration's reluctance to push Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu into the next phase of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The UN vote also highlights the dividing line between domestic
Israeli politics and its international relations.
</P>
<P>
   David Makovsky, the veteran diplomatic correspondent for
Israel's leading daily newspaper, Haaretz, said, ``Israel's
isolation is very real internationally. But domestically for the
Likud it is almost a vindication of their core belief that the
whole world is against us. The fact is Israel gets much more worked
up about what the US says than what the UN does.'' If US Secretary
of State Madeline Albright ``sneezes, the place worries. But the
UN? Oh well, we expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The looming question a lot of people want to avoid is, could
it have an effect on the Americans' thinking, the allegations in
the Arab world and the greater world of a double standard?'' asked
Makovsky. ``America can't go it alone forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Alpher, Jerusalem representative for the American Jewish
Committee, said that while the UN vote is in itself only a ``blip
on the screen,'' the growing isolation of Israel over its policies
toward peace is a more profound matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel's international profile is suffering,'' he said. ``It's
economy is suffering. Both of these had improved dramatically since
Oslo ... Now they are backtracking. The damage thus far is not
extensive, but the direction concerns me.''
</P>
<P>
   The UN measure, which granted Palestinians the right to
introduce resolutions and participate in debates in the General
Assembly, also reflected Palestinian momentum toward international
recognition of the Palestinian Authority's right to declare itself
an independent state _ a possibility that could eventualy erupt in
bloodshed and permanently wreck the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a senior adviser to Netanyahu, David Bar-Illan,
dismissed the idea that the UN vote would have any impact on the
domestic politics that surround the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have a shelf life of two days at best. It means
nothing,'' Bar-Illan said. ``It's not the only time we've been left
out in a UN vote with only the US and Micronesia.''
</P>
<P>
   Bar-Illan added that the resolution, as adopted, was a diluted
version of the original Palestinian proposal which sought to grant
the PLO full representation in the United Nations. He said that
Netanyahu had successfully lobbied against that draft in recent
months with European leaders.
</P>
<P>
   While a broad political spectrum of Israelis believe that the
United Nations is reflexively anti-Israel, Netanyahu's rightist
Likud party in particular is convinced of this alleged
partisanship. Bar-Illan, citing the controversial 1975 UN vote that
equated Zionism with racism, said, ``You can't take the UN
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Netanyahu government thus far has resisted US pressure to
accept a further 13 percent withdrawal from the West Bank _ a
proposal that Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority has accepted.
Netanyahu's fragile coalition has frayed during the debate on
whether to accept this idea or the 9 percent alternative that Ariel
Sharon, the legendary hawk and current infrastructure minister,
insists is critical to ensure Israel's security over water
resources, settlements, and military installations.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by delays, Arafat has vowed to declare the creation
of a Palestinian state on May 4, 1999. May 4 marks the end of the
five-year transitional period stipulated in the Oslo accords, which
began when Israel and the PLO signed the agreement in Cairo on May
4, 1994. Under the agreement, final status talks were to have begun
in May 1996 and were to be concluded no later than May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has blasted Arafat's statements as a violation of the
peace accords, which deny either party the right unilaterally to
alter issues to be negotiated during final status. But Netanyahu
has been criticized internationally for doing precisely that when
he recently announced plans to expand Jerusalem's municipal
boundaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
