<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACIAL-HATE-BOS &LR;      07-08 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-HATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER OF HATE CRIME VICTIM URGES BEEFED-UP FEDERAL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The daughter of a disabled Texas man who was
dragged to death last month allegedly by white supremacists issued
a tearful plea Wednesday for Congress to beef up the federal law
against hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Amid criticism of the initiative, Renee Mullins, the oldest
daughter of James Byrd Jr., wept as she argued before a hearing of
the Senate Judiciary Committee that lawmakers could help prevent
other atrocities like her father's slaying by passing the Hate
Crimes Prevention Act of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, co-sponsored by Senator Edward M. Kennedy and
backed by President Clinton, would strengthen the current law and
broaden the statute to cover crimes motivated by hatred for women,
people with disabilities, and homosexuals. The law now is aimed at
hate crimes based on race, color, religion, and national origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passing this bill into law would give some mercy for my family
and for the families of future victims of such horrible crimes,''
said the 27-year-old Mullins. ``Mercy is like a glove that fits the
hand, and passing this bill surely will fit right into place.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including a coalition of federal judges, described the
proposal as an unwarranted, wasteful, and possibly unconstitutional
federal intervention into the jurisdictions of state and local law
enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also is expected to rankle Republican congressional
leaders who oppose expanding laws to protect homosexual rights. The
House Judiciary Committee has scheduled a hearing for July 22, but
the bill's prospects for passage this year are far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican who chairs the Judiciary
Committee, backed the bill's goal of curbing crimes motivated by
hatred for particular groups of citizens. But he raised concerns
about the measure's potential impact on the overburdened federal
courts and indicated he may favor a scaled-back proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for anybody to be treated hatefully in our
country today,'' Hatch said. ``The committee's going to move on a
hate crimes bill.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 8,750 hate crimes occurred in the United States in
1996, yet only a handful were prosecuted under the federal law,
according to the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   In Byrd's case, county prosecutors obtained capital murder
indictments this week against three suspects charged with beating
the 49-year-old musician, chaining him by his ankles to the back of
a pickup truck and draggging him nearly three miles to his death on
a country road in Jasper, Texas. Police said the alleged ringleader
uttered racially laced vulgarities throughout the attack.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas prosecutors had failed to vigorously pursue the case,
as has happened in other racially motivated slayings, federal
authorities may have been unable to bring hate-crime charges
against Byrd's alleged killers because of restrictions in the
current law, according to supporters of Kennedy's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Current law requires prosecutors to prove the victim was
participating in a federally protected activity, such as voting or
serving on a jury. ``The gaps in the current law mean that
prosecutors are fighting these despicable crimes with one hand tied
behind their backs,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric H. Holder Jr., testifying for the
Clinton administration, agreed. Holder also supported expanding the
law to cover attacks on women, people with disabilities, and
homosexuals that are based on hatred for those groups. ``It makes
no sense that violent, hateful people can be prosecuted for attacks
on African-Americans based on race but not for assaults on gays
based on sexual orientation,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal judges expressed no official position on
the plan, their representative, US District Judge Richard J. Arcara
of Buffalo, N.Y., described the measure as ``the latest proposal in
a trend that seeks _ unwisely in our view _ to expand the criminal
jurisdiction of the federal courts into matters previously
prosecuted exclusively in the state courts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
