<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-AIRPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAOS REIGNS AT HONG KONG'S NEW AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Three days after its much-trumpeted opening, Hong
Kong's $20 billion airport is lurching from crisis to crisis. Just
as the airport seems to be reducing the chaos in the passenger
terminal, computer glitches have all but paralyzed its air-cargo
operations.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Hong Kong International Airport's main cargo
handler said it would extend until Saturday an embargo on all
exports and imports carried on passenger jets. Hong Kong Air Cargo
Terminals Ltd. first imposed an embargo on Tuesday, after it began
to lose track of shipments, causing containers to pile up next to
its giant terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The company handles 82 percent of the more than 4,000 tons of
air cargo that flows through Hong Kong every day. And the embargo,
which applies to all shipments except medical supplies, newspapers,
food and livestock, promises to ripple through this city's
trade-dependent economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can probably suffer through a couple of weeks of this,''
said Ian Perkin, an economist at the Hong Kong General Chamber of
Commerce. ``But exporters are going to be hit, and they're facing
tough times already.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkin said the airport's messy opening was inflicting serious
damage on Hong Kong's image. After relentlessly promoting the
airport as a symbol of its Swiss-watch efficiency, Hong Kong has
had to endure horror stories about passengers waiting two hours to
get off planes, lost luggage, dirty restrooms, blank flight
information boards and crates of seafood rotting on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger terminal settled into a semblance of normalcy
Wednesday, though some weary travelers said they had waited an hour
for bags or had been sent to the wrong baggage carousels by faulty
overhead screens. Still, compared with the air-cargo terminal
across the runway, it was poetry in motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolute chaos,'' said Ross Allen, the operations
director of DHL Worldwide Express in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Containers were strewn across the tarmac, as freight handlers
tried in vain to match containers with planes. Allen said he spent
the day plotting how to route DHL's Asian cargo around Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are teething problems with any large project,'' he said,
``but we're very surprised by the level of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Asia's other lavish new airport, Kuala Lumpur International in
Malaysia, has also suffered a trouble-prone opening. As in Hong
Kong, the airport uses modern technology to control functions like
gate assignments and baggage handling. But last week, software
glitches forced passenger delays.
</P>
<P>
   Kuala Lumpur's cargo operation has also bogged down badly _ with
seafood, vegetables and other perishable goods left sitting for
days. According to The Sun, a daily newspaper in Kuala Lumpur,
garbage trucks are transporting rotten cargo to a nearby dump
several times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals built a $1 billion complex, called
Super Terminal 1, to sort and store cargo. But after a software
glitch erased the company's inventory list, it was forced to
transport most of the cargo 19 miles west to its old terminal at
Kai Tak Airport, which was closed on Sunday after 73 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even after it lifts the embargo, Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals
said it would continue to process most imported cargo at Kai Tak.
Only food, medical supplies, newspapers and other perishables will
be handled at the Super Terminal. In the meantime, it said, it will
try to fix its computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These temporary arrangements are designed to provide the best
level of service we can to customers,'' the company said Wednesday.
Anthony Charter, managing director of Hong Kong Air Cargo
Terminals, did not return telephone calls seeking further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the airport's travails have prompted a flurry
of finger-pointing. In interviews with several local papers on
Tuesday, Charter said his company had to meet an unrealistic
timetable to have its terminal up and running by opening day.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the Hong Kong Airport Authority, Christopher
Donnolley, said: ``We've had an agreement with them for some time
now. The agreement was to have 75 percent of capacity on the day
the airport opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong officials have also come under pressure. The city's
two top civil servants, Anson Chan and Sir Donald Tsang, visited
the airport on Tuesday to assess the problems. ``It's hard getting
a turkey to fly,'' said the headline on an editorial in The Hong
Kong Standard.
</P>
<P>
   Among passengers, though, a more tolerant attitude prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Sogo, a businessman arriving from Tokyo, said he waited
more than an hour for his baggage. ``It's only the first week,'' he
said. ``It will be fine in six months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
