<HEADER>
A6291 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-08 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 COMMENTARY: WAITING FOR THE D.A.  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's an outrage either way.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a foul-up in the office of Brooklyn District Attorney
Charles Hynes, a man who may be wanted in South Carolina, or who
may be totally innocent, was dumped for the better part of a month
in the limbo of Rikers Island.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Johnson, a city employee and part-time musician, was
arrested in Brooklyn on June 13 for carrying an open beer can in
public. The 41-year-old father of two was not released from jail
until last Monday. Should he have gone to Rikers at all? Should he
still be in custody? Thanks to the D.A.'s office, we have no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was on his way to his mother's apartment in Coney Island
when two police officers spotted the can of beer, which he was
carrying in a brown paper bag. They arrested him. A computer check
turned up a fugitive warrant from Florence County, S.C. It said
Johnson was wanted for illegal possession of a controlled
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he had only been in South Carolina once, when he
took a bus that passed through the state on its way to Birmingham,
Ala. He said he never got off the bus, was not arrested and could
not be the man that the authorities in Florence were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Now this would seem to be a pretty easy case. Clouseau could
have solved it in a minute. Johnson was in custody in Brooklyn and
his fingerprints and mug shot had been taken. All investigators had
to do was compare his prints to those of the man being sought. In
this age of computers and fax machines, that should have taken
approximately no time at all.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, it still hadn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   The charge of carrying an open beer can was almost immediately
adjourned in contemplation of dismissal, but because of the
outstanding warrant Johnson was ordered held without bail. He was
taken to Rikers and left there.
</P>
<P>
   Legal Aid lawyers representing Johnson pleaded for a comparison
of fingerprints. Nothing doing.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Moletteri, supervising attorney for the Legal Aid Society
in Brooklyn, said her office was told that the D.A. was waiting for
a ``governor's warrant'' to be sent up from South Carolina. A
governor's warrant is issued when a suspect refuses to waive
extradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually comes with fingerprints,'' said Ms. Moletteri,
``which is what you want.'' If the prints match, the suspect can be
extradited. If not, you know you have the wrong man.
</P>
<P>
   No governor's warrant was sent. Weeks went by. Johnson remained
at Rikers. Last week, at the urging of Legal Aid and over the
objections of the D.A.'s office, a judge finally agreed to release
Johnson on $1,000 bail. He left Rikers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday I called Hynes' office to ask why a fingerprint
comparison had not been made. An aide said, ``We still don't have
the prints on him from South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked why it was taking so long. The aide said, ``That's
something I can't answer for you.''
</P>
<P>
   I called the sheriff's office in Florence County. It turns out
that Hynes' office did not ask for a copy of the fingerprints until
Tuesday _ the day I began inquiring about the story and one day
after Johnson was released. How long would he have stayed at Rikers
if the judge had sided with the D.A. last week and refused to grant
bail? Forever?
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday a spokesman for Hynes acknowledged the foul-up. ``What
happened is attributable to a filing error,'' he said. ``It's a
human mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a separate file ``on the extradition aspect of the
case'' should have been opened when Johnson was arraigned on the
beer charge. That didn't happen. He said a copy of Johnson's prints
will now be faxed to South Carolina, where, presumably, a
comparison will be made.
</P>
<P>
   No one explained why the requests by Legal Aid to have the
prints matched weeks ago were rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   It should have been so easy. Fax the prints and make the
comparison. Case closed. Instead, because of the bumbling by the
D.A.'s investigators, the South Carolina warrant is still
outstanding and Johnson doesn't yet know what will happen to him.
If this is how they handle the easy cases, what in the world would
they do with a real mystery?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
