<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-08 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT BOOK IS THE HARDEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Often for a writer, it's the book after the last one that seems
impossible to start because the very notion of what that next book
should be seems beyond the grasp. The author rolls the idea up the
hill of imagination, only to have it roll back down just before it
reaches the top. Daily, like Sisyphus.
</P>
<P>
   This is a bit different from writers' block _ the inability of a
writer simply to write _ and it strikes even, or maybe
particularly, the most successful authors. Excepting perhaps genre
writers, like mystery or thriller authors, who in some ways tell
nearly the same tale time and again.
</P>
<P>
   Authors who are commercially and critically successful get
distracted by celebrity and publicity, by magazine offers, by
people simply wanting to talk to them about the writing life. But
mostly, it's the pressure of people saying, ``Let's see you do it
again,'' and the writer wondering if it CAN be done again.
</P>
<P>
   Rosellen Brown, a literary novelist and poet, said: ``So-called
success trammels you in a way you didn't think of. The stakes get
higher with each book. There are more readers you are afraid to
disappoint.'' Ms. Brown's last novel, her fourth, ``Before and
After,'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux) was published in 1992 to
critical acclaim and made the best-seller lists. Six years later,
she has nearly completed a new novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second book is much harder than the first because if you
are doing serious fiction, with every book, you keep closing doors
you don't want to walk through again,'' she said. ``You closed off
certain possibilities.'' And so it goes, book after book, using up
one's experiences story by story. ``I had some good ideas for this
book,'' Ms. Brown said. ``But I said to myself, `I did that
already.'''
</P>
<P>
   There surely is such a thing as pure writer's block when
fecundity not only fails but the author's ability actually to sit
and write seems gone forever.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous case in modern American fiction was that of
Henry Roth. His first novel, ``Call It Sleep,'' was published to
mixed reviews in 1934. He was immediately contracted for a second
by the mythic editor Maxwell Perkins, only to develop a case of
writer's block that lasted more than 40 years, until 1979, when he
was finally able to put to paper the first words of his four-volume
autobiographical novel, ``Mercy of a Rude Stream.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the '60s, that first novel, ``Call It Sleep,'' a
portrait of Jewish immigrant life on the Lower East Side, was
rediscovered and hailed as a masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have speculated that the cause of Roth's profound
literary malady was Jewish self-hatred, low self-esteem beaten into
him by his violent father, and the apparent likelihood that the
writer had incestuous relationships with his sister and a cousin.
All the stuff of great novels, if the writer can just get it down
on the pages. Which could be particularly difficult for a writer of
autobiographical novels.
</P>
<P>
   Doing it again, or simply starting up a second time, can at
times appear to be nearly impossible for a young writer who has had
a great critical success with a first book. In 1996, Junot Diaz,
then 27, bewitched the publishing world with his first book,
``Drown,'' a hard-to-forget collection of 10 short stories that
eight publishing houses wanted but that Riverhead got after giving
him a six-figure advance for the collection and a second book, to
be a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz declined to be interviewed. He needed to write rather than
talk, he said through his agent, Nicole Aragi. But in an article
about him in the July-August issue of Poets and Writers, a literary
magazine, he said that his instant success had turned him from
``someone who wrote'' into ``a writer,'' and that the acclaim he
received had so unsettled him that he did little writing in 1997,
not a ``worthy word.``
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was writer's block, self-doubt or simply the
distraction of celebrity, or a combination of all, his distress was
clear. He was quoted in the article as saying that it made no sense
that ``anyone should pay any attention to someone who has published
a short-story collection _ one.'' He went on to say, ``It
infuriates me, you know?'' and to refer to himself as ``passe'' and
``two-bit.'' The feeling one gets of his anguish is palpable. Ms.
Aragi said that, happily, he was now starting to write.
</P>
<P>
   Even enormous success can have a downside for a writer. Finding
the idea for the second book can be a slippery slope indeed. John
Berendt, author of ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil''
(Random House), has done hardly any writing in the four years that
his book has been a nonfiction best seller. He researched an idea
about Venice, and now thinks it might work better as a magazine
piece than as a book, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he has spent the four years mostly promoting his book;
recently he was in a warehouse signing 2,000 copies. Clearly,
Berendt is not entirely over his ``Midnight'' experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say: `Do you feel the pressure? How can you top the
first book?''' he said. ``I don't have to, and I wouldn't try.''
</P>
<P>
   His problem is not the writing, but ``to find something as
seductive and as enticing as the last story,'' he said. ``The
characters in that book set a high standard. I had a lot of luck
stumbling into that setting.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``I have a few stories on the prowl, have been
considering two of them for a book.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all his bravado, he does feel the pressure of his
readers lurking behind him. ``A lot of them might be looking for
the same thing, expecting another `Midnight,' and then be
disappointed,'' he said. ``I might be disappointed also, but if I
did another `Midnight,' I'd feel trapped. I need something very
different that works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writing is not a problem, as soon as the story presents
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has a luxury that fiction writers don't, and that is
the adrenaline of the chase. ``I love getting into that.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Berendt may not worry about the writing part of
producing his next work, but one hopes the pursuit of the story is
full of joy, since it took the author seven years to write
``Midnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6295 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-UNH-GIFT-BOS &LR;      07-08 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-UNH-GIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNH RECEIVES LARGEST-EVER SINGLE GIFT, $10 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. -- The University of New Hampshire has received
the biggest gift in its 105-year history -- and the largest ever
received by any state university in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million gift from 94-year-old Leslie S. Hubbard of
Walpole, a 1927 graduate of UNH who made his fortune breeding
poultry, will be used to expand the school's marine sciences
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marine program here has been traditionally very strong,''
said UNH president Joan Leitzel. ``This lets us move in some new
areas and add faculty at the senior level and put an endowment
under the program which speaks to its future -- and for that we are
extremely grateful to Leslie Hubbard.''
</P>
<P>
   The next largest gift the university has ever received was $6.2
million in fiscal year 1993-94. The recent gift may pale in
comparison to the largest gifts donated to UNH's Ivy League
neighbors. Dartmouth College in Hanover, for example, received a
$25 million gift from one donor in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But $10 million is big money for a public university in a state
not known for its munificence in funding public education.
University officials predicted the gift will help transform the
university's marine program into one of the leading undergraduate
marine science programs in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hubbard award should allow us to assume a leadership role
in the Northeast for undergraduate education in marine science,''
said Ann Bucklin, the director of the UNH Sea Grant program and a
professor of zoology.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bucklin said the $10 million windfall will ``basically double
our capacity in marine education, research and outreach.'' It may
also allow the university to move into pathbreaking areas of
research. For example, Roy Torbert, dean of the College of
Engineering and Physical Sciences, said the school has plans for a
program in hydrography, the mapping of the ocean, that he believes
will be the only instructional program in that field in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Leitzel said the school is looking increasingly toward the
private sector for funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not so we can let the state off of its obligation,''
Leitzel said. ``I think a research university must move these days
to more dependance on fundraising. UNH is a little later than some
of the other public instuitutions...in challenging graduates and
friends to assist in the funding of the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Hubbard was unavailable for comment. But Hubbard family
attorney and spokesman Charles DeGrandpre said Hubbard and his
family are ``devoted to making New Hampshire better and being very
concerned about those who are left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hubbard family, which founded the Hubbard Farms poultry
breeding operation, made $70 million in 1974 when it sold its
poultry operation and became a division of Merck &AMP; Co., the
pharmaceutical giant.
</P>
<P>
   DeGrandpre said the Hubbard family has given a total of $20
million-$25 million to UNH. The family is known for giving money to
charity, and the UNH gifts, he said, were in keeping with that
family's philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many members of the family have told me that they don't think
they're taxed enough -- that the New Hampshire system (of taxation)
is not a good system,'' said DeGrandpre. ``It's an extraodinary
perspective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
