broadcasts are just months away, but a number of difficult issues
remain unresolved for consumers, broadcasters, cable companies and
content providers, a Senate hearing was told Wednesday. (Glass, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-RADIO _ WASHINGTON _ A popular education program has
been scratched from the October space shuttle flight of Sen. John
Glenn because the astronauts are booked solid with a vast array of
science experiments. One school in Japan and five in the United
States _ including John Glenn High School in in the senator's home
town of New Concord, Ohio _ were scheduled to connect via amateur
radio with the shuttle Discovery for 10-minute conversations
between students and astronauts. But NASA schedulers decided last
week that the process of setting up and then stowing the radio
equipment makes the classroom program too time-consuming for a
mission that already has more than 80 experiments aboard.
(Montgomery, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-WAR _ WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton launches a $2
billion public relations offensive against illegal drugs Thursday,
new government studies are pointing to mismanagement and stalemate
on other fronts in the war against drugs. In recent weeks, the
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress, has
issued reports showing a disjointed effort by 20 separate federal
agencies to gather intelligence on illicit drugs, a failure to stop
smuggling at the Mexican border, and widespread drug-related
corruptions in major cities. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
