<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-RABIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABIES CASES IN MASSACHUSETTS BEGINNING TO CLIMB AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rabies is back.
</P>
<P>
   Though nowhere near as common as it was during a major outbreak
earlier this decade, after two years of decline the number of new
cases in Massachusetts has almost doubled in each of the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   State officials Wednesday attributed the increase to the rapid
growth of the raccoon population after its decimation during the
1993 epidemic, and said July and August are peak months for new
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a second wave,'' said Dr. Michael McGuill,
the chief veterinarian for the state Department of Public Health.
``So many raccoons got killed by this strain that the population
took some time to rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   From January through June 1998, health officials found 214
animals testing positive for rabies, up from 114 during the same
period in 1997. There were altogether 282 positive tests in 1997;
115 in 1996; 401 in 1995; 735 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest worry is that pets . . . serve as a bridge between
wild animals and humans,'' McGuill said.
</P>
<P>
   While widespread vaccination of dogs has kept the incidence of
the disease among them very low, in the last two years the increase
in new cases of infected cats has outpaced the growth of the diease
in total animals, 33 percent to 25 percent. The number of infected
cats has grown to 60 from 45. ``We're fortunate that we've
diagnosed cats and people have had treatment,'' McGuill said.
</P>
<P>
   Pets that fight with wild rabid animals can bring the disease
into homes. To prevent this, McGuill advised pet owners to get
their dogs, cats, and ferrets vaccinated as required by law. If a
pet appears to have been attacked by a rabid animal, McGuill
recommends wearing gloves to prevent contact with saliva, washing
the wound with soap and water, and taking the animal to the vet.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to a rabid animal can have severe consequences. One
infected kitten in New Hampshire, McGuill said, led to
post-exposure treatment of 665 people in 1994 at an estimated cost
of $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   A person bitten by a wild animal should wash the wound with soap
and water and call a physician immediately. At the height of the
epidemic in 1995, almost 2,700 people across the country underwent
vaccination after exposure at a cost to patients and insurers of up
to $6.5 million, according to a report by the US Bureau of
Communicable Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   The disease traveled into Massachusetts along the Atlantic
Seaboard in 1992. But the current wave has spread almost uniformly
throughout the state. Of the 351 towns and cities in the
commonwealth, 308 have reported cases.
</P>
<P>
   The only ones that haven't, McGuill said, are those on Cape Cod,
Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard where a 5-year-program to vaccinate
raccoons in the wild has succeeded in keeping the area rabies-free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
