<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE PANEL TACKLES SCHOOL DIVERSITY DURING DEBATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a session that was long on talk but short on
solutions, President Clinton on Wednesday joined in another
discussion on race _ this one focusing heavily on school diversity.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an initiative on race that he launched last year, the
president participated in a panel discussion that will be aired on
public television and moderated by ``The News Hour's'' Jim Lehrer.
</P>
<P>
   The participants immediately plunged into a debate on whether
certain ethnic or minority groups should gain admission into
schools to the exclusion of others.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Chao, a fellow at the conservative Heritage Foundation,
recalled the story of an Asian-American student in San Francisco
who she said could not gain entry into a certain school even though
he had high test scores because of a quota on Chinese Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different standards in that school system for
different students of different colors,'' she said. ``If you are
white you have one standard. If you are Asian American you have the
toughest standard to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, however, defended schools and universities that seek
varied student bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our society has a vested interest in having people
from diverse backgrounds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also suggested that ``test scores and all these
other so-called objective measurements are somewhat ambiguous and
they are not perfect measures of people's capacity to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he may have even benefited from such
policies when he applied to Georgetown University, which he said
sought students from every state.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know maybe I got in because there weren't too many people
from Arkansas who applied, for all I know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the president conceded there is not a ``perfect
solution'' to the issue of how to ensure racial balance in schools
without hurting the opportunities of some qualified students.
</P>
<P>
   The televised discussion follows a forum on race and sports that
was sponsored by the cable sports networkl ESPN and held in Houston
with the president in April.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest session, Clinton also sought to mollify critics
who claimed the race initiative has not included some critics of
affirmative action as well as spokesmen from minorities other than
African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   One panelist, Richard Rodriguez, an editor at Pacific News
Service, said he turned down jobs he suspected were offered to him
because he was Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the job offers came to him ``when I was middle
class Mexican American perfectly capable of dealing with the
competition for jobs, and the jobs came to me because I was their
brown man.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel also included a Native American, Sherman Alexie, a
Seattle-based writer, who argued that, to get ahead, Indians must
recognize that education is as important as many of their tribal
customs.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie, who wrote a new film called ``Smoke Signals,'' noted
that race creeps up in most conversations although it is usually in
code language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well nobody says that's a black person, let's talk about being
black. What they will do is come up to me and tell me they're
Cherokee,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reference may have been an allusion to the fact that earlier
in the discussion Clinton mentioned that his grandmother was
one-quarter Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   The one-hour discussion will be nationally televised beginning
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
