<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S PREMIER VOWS TAX CUTS NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on Wednesday promised
long-term tax cuts beginning next year, but gave no details about
how much the move might fatten pocketbooks or lift the sagging
Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and other countries have put enormous pressure
on Japan to make permanent tax cuts to stimulate the economy and
reduce the risk of a global downturn. Hashimoto's promise seemed
aimed at winning support from Washington and from Japanese voters,
who go to the polls on Sunday to choose members of the upper house
of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concerning tax-system reform, starting next year we would like
to implement tax cuts that will be supported by the public,''
Hashimoto said Wednesday while campaigning in the central city of
Nagoya.
</P>
<P>
   His remark seemed to be an attempt to end days of confusion
brought about by his public waffling.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday he suggested he would consider introducing permanent
income tax cuts. Two days later he seemed to backtrack, saying that
overall tax reform might not bring about a broad reduction in
income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto has been reluctant to lower the minimum level of
taxable income, currently at nearly $24,000. Such a step would
bring in more tax revenues but it would be politically risky
because it would hurt the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's remark, which seemed more forceful, still left many
people wondering whether the size of the cuts would be enough to
prompt consumers to spend more money. The yen, which had fallen
against the dollar throughout the day, weakened slightly, to 139.60
yen, from 138.85 yen, just as Hashimoto was making his comments.
</P>
<P>
   In April Hashimoto said the government would tackle reform of
the entire tax system, which many economists say drains a great
deal of incentive from employees and businesses to make more money.
Economists say they expect to see top rates slide to 50 percent,
from 65 percent, on individuals and to 40 percent, from 46 percent,
on corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge that Hashimoto faces, however, is that any tax
cuts would have to be financed somehow by a government that has
just declared fiscal austerity to be its medium-term goal. Last
fall Hashimoto pushed through a policy of fiscal austerity, and
though he has since stepped back a bit, that principle seems to
have kept the government from spending its way too freely out of
the recession.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the government made $14 billion in income tax
rebates, and it plans to make a similar rebate beginning in late
summer. It has also said that next year, it will cut income taxes
by another $14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and economists have not been entirely pleased with
those cuts, however, because they are one-time reductions that will
not necessarily encourage people to spend more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax reduction through tax rebates is nothing but giving liquor
to an alcoholic,'' said Teizo Taya, an economist at Daiwa Institute
of Research. ``That is not going to change the motives of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
