<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ECON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVE TOWARD EURO SPARKING BOOM IN SMALLER COUNTRIES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID _ When Jose Antonio Santamaria and his family moved into
their new condominium in February, they got satellite television
along with access to enclosed gardens and a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   But they also got a euro-break. Largely because Spain has been
accepted into the group of European nations that will adopt the
euro as a single currency in January, interest rates here have
plunged almost as low as those in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   For Santamaria, that translates into monthly payments that are
about $140 lower than he had calculated when construction started
three years ago. ``It is much cheaper than we had expected,'' he
said. ``And with the swimming pool and enclosed garden, the quality
of life is better, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Santamaria, Spain has not had it this good in years. As
much of Europe adopts the euro as a single currency, poorer
countries like Spain, Portugal and Ireland are growing much faster
than bigger and wealthier ones like France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, interest rates in Spain and Portugal have plunged to
less than 6 percent from 11 percent, largely because interest rates
across the ``euro zone'' are converging down to the levels in
Germany. Ireland, with a well-educated work force and relatively
flexible work rules, has become an important manufacturing base for
American companies exporting to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The effect within these fast-growing countries has been
profound. While Germany and France invest heavily outside their
borders, the smaller and poorer countries have become magnets for
foreign money. While job creation continues to be stagnant in much
of continental Europe, it is speeding up rapidly in places like
Spain. And while consumers in Germany anxiously refrain from
spending, demand is surging in the poorer countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us is going to be the same five years from now _ not
us, not France, not Germany,'' said Rodrigo Rato, Spain's Economics
Minister. ``We are all moving toward a new era of more
competitiveness and more openness.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland, one of the poorest countries in Western Europe in 1990,
is rapidly catching up with the rest of Europe in terms of per
capita income. Its economy is growing by more than 8 percent this
year _ compared with about 3 percent for the European Union as a
whole. Indeed, with real estate prices soaring and labor shortages
cropping up in some areas, the biggest worry among economists is
that Ireland is headed toward an overheated economy.
</P>
<P>
   Spain and Portugal are growing at about 4 percent this year _
faster than almost anywhere else on continental Europe. Their stock
markets have been among the best performers in Europe as investors
bet that interest rates will remain low and stable for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a gift, essentially, a gift from abroad,'' said Miguel
Sebastian, chief economist at Banco Bilbao Vizcaya in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, part of the current boom is simply catch-up as
countries bounce back from past problems, in particular Spain's
severe recession in the mid-1990's. Though Spain has generated
about 400,000 new jobs since the start of 1997, its official
unemployment rate is still 19 percent _ one of the highest in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are living through now is the rapid correction of past
imbalances,'' said Ignacio Gomez-Montejo, Merrill Lynch's chief
equity analyst in Madrid. ``We are being rewarded for correcting
our mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs of new affluence are visible here. On the outskirts of
Madrid, the Las Rosas condominium development is building 10,000
apartments with an average price of about $120,000. Beckoning young
families with signs that boast ``We are building your dream
house,'' the condominiums are selling quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the center-right government of President Jose Maria
Aznar has pushed through several reforms aimed at bolstering
employment and investment. It has promoted fierce competition in
banking and privatized about $25 billion worth of state-owned
companies. And soon after taking power in 1996, the Aznar
government drastically cut the tax on capital gains, reducing the
top rate to about 20 percent from more than 60 percent. Now, the
government is pushing through a much broader tax reform that would
reduce income tax rates by closing loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   The government, under Aznar and his predecessor, Felipe
Gonzalez, has also made it easier for companies to hire workers on
temporary contract. Though full-time jobs are still relatively
scarce, temporary jobs have soared. But perhaps the biggest change
in Spain is one of outlook: a new willingness of domestic companies
to look abroad for opportunities. Since joining the European Union
in 1986, the country has steadily increased its volume of trade
with the rest of Europe. As recently as 1990, Spanish exports and
imports added up to about 40 percent of the country's gross
domestic product. Today, foreign trade in both directions adds up
to about 70 percent, the lion's share with other European
countries.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6322 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIMINATE-CNN-ARNETT-     07-08 0029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIMINATE-CNN-ARNETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spot budget story CNN-ARNETT (e) will not move in tonight's
Boston Globe file.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6323 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-ECON-2NDTAKE-N     07-08 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ECON-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: European countries. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new confidence is apparent in Elche, a city on Spain's
southern coast that is the heart of its shoe industry. Bolstered by
low interest rates and cheap money, nearly 50 companies are
building factories and office buildings at the city's newest
industrial park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financial costs used to account for about 5 percent of a
company's expenses,'' said Jose Pertusa Romero, a partner in Gesem,
a consulting firm in Elche. ``But in the last year, interest rates
have declined, and those costs have been cut in half.''
</P>
<P>
   And though shoes are still the mainstay of the local economy,
the business itself has changed. Instead of competing strictly on
price, traditional shoemakers are reinventing themselves as
designers and marketers of brand names. And they are exporting
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a revolution, a real shock for the local industry,''
said Felipe Gonzalez, export manager for Panama Jack Group
Internacional S.A., which produces hiking boots and leather casual
shoes and began developing its own brand nearly nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Peran, the founder of Pikolinos S.A., made a particularly
striking odyssey. A small, wiry craftsman who started his company
from scratch in the mid-1970s, Peran spent years stamping out cheap
plastic shoes. But five years ago, he began designing and marketing
his own line of high-fashion shoes for the export market.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has worked. Pikolinos has more than tripled its
sales volume since 1992, to 1.1 million pairs of shoes from about
300,000, and the profit for each pair has increased significantly.
About 80 percent of the companies sales are to other European
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Peran recently moved the company into a gleaming glass-covered
building at the industrial park. Shoe designers work out their
ideas by creating three-dimensional models on computers, and
robotic cutting machines transfer those ideas into precise strips
of leather that are then sewn into prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still a shoemaker, but this is the way we create about 80
percent of our designs,'' Peran said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest differences between countries like Spain and
Portugal and Europe's wealthier but slower-growing nations is the
pace of job creation. Even though Germany's economy is expanding at
one of its fastest rates in years, nearly 3 percent, the number of
new jobs has increased only marginally. Over the last several
years, the number of jobs in Germany has remained almost flat while
the number of unemployed job seekers has steadily increased. Though
German job growth has finally picked up in the last few months,
unemployment is expected to stay above 10 percent throughout the
year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, economic growth is bolstering job gains in Spain,
Portugal and Ireland. Though Spain's unemployment rate remains
high, economists and government agencies calculate that about
400,000 new jobs have been added since the start of 1997, nearly 3
percent, and many others have probably been absorbed in the
underground economy.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal has had even greater success. Its unemployment rate has
declined to about 6.3 percent from 7.3 percent in 1996 _ about half
the level in Germany and France. And Ireland, with employment of
1.3 million, has added 50,000 jobs since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Though the evidence is mixed, many economists say the penchant
toward hiring people in ``periphery'' countries stems partly from
lower wages but perhaps more from greater flexibility, even though
labor laws are often just as strict.
</P>
<P>
   In Ireland, economists say the quality of workers is at least as
important as the cost of wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the new jobs are coming from knowledge-intensive
industries, not labor-intensive industries,'' said Terry Baker, an
economist at the Economic and Social Research Institute in Dublin.
Fifty percent of people entering the work force have college
educations, and their educations have often been tailored toward
technical areas. Ireland's biggest growth areas have been in
computer and software companies, from Microsoft to Dell Computer to
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irish labor is a good value,'' said Peter Jarrett, an
economist at the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development in Paris, who has studied Ireland closely. ``The
quality of the educational system is as good as anywhere, and they
have really geared it to the needs of the labor market.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain has worked to loosen its work rules. Although full-time
permanent workers have some of the strongest job-protection laws of
any nation, new laws allow companies to hire workers on temporary
contracts _ often for years at a time. About one-third of all
workers in Spain work on temporary contracts, one of the highest
levels in the world and most of the new jobs are being created in
the temporary labor market.
</P>
<P>
   But as Europe's previously poor countries become richer, they
may well become more like their wealthier neighbors. Even though
Ireland has long boasted a devotion to ``Anglo-Saxon'' principles
of light regulation, the country has followed Germany's tradition
in reaching broad wage agreements in negotiations between unions,
manufacturers and industry. In the most recent one the government
pledged last year to reduce income tax rates while unions agreed to
modest wage increases of about 3 percent a year through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much on the old German or Scandinavian model, but it
seems to have worked very well,'' Baker said,
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, the Aznar government has become a staunch defender of
social programs even as it tries to support business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem is how you keep social cohesion and at the
same time stay ahead of the competition,'' said Rato, Spain's
Economics Minister. ``I don't think Europe is contemplating the
American model on social issues. We do look to the American model
on questions of competition and promoting capital markets. But on
social issues, European society does not envy the Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
