<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6329 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-ART-2T     07-08 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE OF 2 BROTHERS ILLUSTRATES FLAWS IN JAPAN'S POLITICAL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927. This was budgeted earlier as JAPAN-HASHIMOTOS
on the BC-GRAPHICS-BUDGET-NYT.) 
(bl) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOCHI, Japan _ It is more of a compliment than it might sound
when people say that Daijiro Hashimoto is the best politician in
his family. His brother, after all, is Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Daijiro, the governor of Kochi Prefecture here on the
forest-covered southern Japanese island of Shikoku, who is widely
hailed as an example of the kind of dynamic leadership that Japan
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Shikoku is one of the poorest and most backward parts of Japan,
but Hashimoto has shaken up the prefecture and made it a testing
ground for the nation. More to the point for a politician, opinion
polls show Daijiro drawing public approval ratings of more than 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ryutaro, though, has slumped below 30 percent, and he could even
be forced to resign if his Liberal Democratic Party loses ground in
elections for the upper house of Parliament on Sunday. Polls show
the party struggling, in part because Ryutaro seems to be
emblematic of the old-style politicians who have led Japan into its
present economic mess and cannot lead it out.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of the two brothers underscores the weaknesses of
Japan's political system. While Daijiro is widely praised by
Japanese commentators and his own constituents, under the rigid
seniority system in the Liberal Democratic Party, he and others
like him stand almost no chance of ever playing a major role in
national politics.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he is pessimistic about the prospects of fundamental
change in Japan in the coming years, in large part because he
thinks the public does not want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are, Japan won't really change very much,''
Daijiro, a compact man with a touch of gray in his neatly coiffed
hair, mused in a long interview the other day. ``Even if an
opposition party took over, it'd be hard to take steps toward
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need very dramatic changes in our system,'' he added,
sitting forward in his chair and speaking in rapid-fire Japanese.
``If public sentiment does not change in Japan, then Japan will be
in a very dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Daijiro discourages any contrasts between his popularity and
that of his brother, and the two remain close. Indeed, Ryutaro was
also regarded as a talented maverick until he became prime minister
in 1996 and seemed to become overwhelmed by the forces of
stagnation around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power of a prime minister in Japan is very limited, even
compared with that of a British prime minister,'' Daijiro noted.
``So my big brother may be feeling tight restrictions right now on
his ability to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Daijiro and Ryutaro share similar good looks, charm and quick
wit, as well as the legacy of their father, who was a Cabinet
minister and longtime member of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Ryutaro, 60, inherited his father's seat in Parliament and has
spent his entire career as a politician, while Daijiro, 51, went
into journalism and became nationally famous as the lead television
reporter covering the dying Emperor Hirohito in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Then a couple of years later, friends persuaded Hashimoto to run
for governor here in Kochi. He had no connection to Kochi and no
power base here, but he ran as an independent against a deputy
governor backed by the governing Liberal Democratic Party. In the
end Hashimoto won in a landslide, and at age 44 he became the
youngest governor in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Governors in Japan normally do not do much, even less than prime
ministers, but Hashimoto made remote Kochi a whirlwind of activity.
</P>
<P>
   He started a technical college and an optical fiber data
network, hoping to nurture a miniature version of Silicon Valley.
He began dismissing any government employee caught drinking and
driving. He emphasized openness in government and publicly
disclosed official entertainment expenses, and he offended
hard-line nationalists by criticizing the national anthem, which
has strong militarist connotations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a great stimulus to this prefecture,'' said Eiichiro
Mizobuchi, the managing director of the Kochi Chamber of Commerce.
``He stresses that we must change our way of thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiroyuki Morishita, a prefectural assemblyman, says that ``he
was a big culture shock for Kochi Prefecture'' and notes that some
people complained about spending money on starting a technical
college at a time of tight budgets. But Morishita says these
measures are changing Kochi and adds, ``He's been a key governor
for all of Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   A good measure of Hashimoto's popularity _ he won re-election in
1995 with 85 percent of the vote _ is a matter less of policy than
of his style. In contrast to the bland bureaucrats who preceded
him, Hashimoto is outspoken and charming, with a natural political
feel for cultivating his image.
</P>
<P>
   And he is popular among women in part because in a nation of
absentee husbands, he comes across as particularly devoted to his
wife, Takako, who was a widow with two children when he married
her.
</P>
<P>
   The gossip magazines are full of stories about the ``women
problems'' of Prime Minister Hashimoto, questions have been raised
in Parliament about a supposed affair with a Chinese woman who by
some accounts was a spy. In contrast, the magazines report that
Daijiro faithfully shares a bath with his wife in the evenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``His style is very different from his predecessors, and people
feel that Kochi is now changing,'' said Hitoshi Toyama, a political
columnist for the Kochi Shimbun, a local daily. ``There's a feeling
here that people in Tokyo used to know nothing about Kochi but that
now the governor is putting Kochi on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all his popularity in Kochi and even around the
country, Daijiro has almost no chance of becoming a leader on the
national stage. It is not just that he is an independent rather
than a member of the Liberal Democratic Party, but also that
national politics operates by a rigid seniority system.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that was why Hashimoto decided not to go into national
politics like his brother, and it is a disincentive to many other
mavericks in Japan: even the most qualified Liberal Democrat can
dream of a Cabinet position only after serving 10 or 15 years in
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   When Hashimoto first ran for office, he calculated that since he
was in his mid-40s he was too old to go into national politics, and
now that he is in his 50s the same logic applies with even greater
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Japan had a presidential system,'' he mused, ``then I might
think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the puzzles of Japanese politics is who actually does
wield power, for there is general agreement that the prime minister
is weak and that individual members of Parliament have much less
influence than any member of the U.S. Congress. Certainly the
answer is not the governors, for local leaders like Hashimoto have
far less autonomy than do the governors of American states.
</P>
<P>
   One of the answers to that riddle is that the bureaucracy holds
a good deal of power that in other countries is controlled by
politicians, and Hashimoto seethes with frustration that 90 percent
of the funds for Kochi are controlled by bureaucrats in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   These days the Transportation Ministry is building an expensive
railroad in Kochi, even though Hashimoto says that Kochi does not
need it and that the railroad will be sure to lose money once it is
built.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto would like to use the money for other purposes, but
the Transportation Ministry will not allow him to do so. It will
not even let him use some of the money for roads, because roads
belong to the turf of a different bureaucracy, the Construction
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto is passionate about the need for fundamental change,
but he is skeptical that it is coming any time soon. The underlying
problem, he says, is that ordinary Japanese are content with life
as it is, and they want to preserve the regulations that protect
them even if they also stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dramatic change might come about in only two ways,'' he
argues. ``The first is if the Japanese economy were to get very
bad. I don't want to see that, and it would be a problem for the
whole world. But then Japanese might realize that they are facing a
dead end and thus accept the need to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other way is that if an entirely new political party were
to arise as a major force with a new agenda, then maybe there could
be dramatic change. But otherwise I think it's hard to see major
changes in the next 5 or 10 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
