<SLUG> BC-REIT-PRUDENTIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REIT PAYS $867M FOR REAL ESTATE PROPERTIES, LEASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.J.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston Properties Inc. announced Wednesday it had
completed the purchase of $867 million worth of real estate
properties and leases _ including The Prudential Center complex, a
venerable signature of Boston's skyline.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate investment trust has doubled its holdings since
going public in June 1997, positioning itself to reap the benefits
of a booming economy, low interest rates, and rising office and
occupancy rates.
</P>
<P>
   The $4 billion REIT _ whose chairman is New York publishing
magnate Mortimer Zuckerman, owner of The New York Daily News and
U.S. News &AMP; World Report _ purchased the 2.2 million-square-feet
office tower and retail complex for $546 million in securities,
cash and debt from Prudential Insurance Co. of America, which has
agressively sought to unload many of its real estate holdings.
</P>
<P>
   For $37 million in cash, Boston Properties also purchased the
longterm lease to the University Place office building in
Cambridge; and for $284 million in cash, securities, and debt
assumption, bought eight buildings in Princeton, New Jersey's
Carnegie Center and an office tower in East Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Prudential deal, Boston Properties also acquired
a 50 percent controlling partnership interest in the development of
an additional 1.75 million square feet of property adjacent to
Prudential Center. The city has already granted preliminary
approvals for use of the parcels as residential and office space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston obviously is a major market for us and we see the
Prudential as one of the most significant pieces of real estate in
the northeast and certainly in Boston,'' said William J. Wedge,
senior vice president for Boston Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the acquisitions will strengthen Boston
Properties's position as one of the largest 10 REITS in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rents in place (at the Prudential Center) are
significantly below market, and market rents continue to rise so
there is tremendous cash flow and development opportunity,'' said
Christopher C. George, an analyst in New York with Bear, Stearns.
``It was a great acquisition for the company and it improves the
longterm growth potential for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   One immediate result of the new ownership, said George, is that
some office and retail rents in the Prudential complex are likely
to rise over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Boston Properties has been assembling a portfolio
that includes more than 100 commercial and office properties in
urban centers such as New York, Washington, D.C., Baltimore, and
Richmond. The firm recently signed a letter of intent to acquire
another trophy property: San Francisco's enormous Embarcadero
Center office and retail complex, dubbed the Rockefeller Center of
the West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6334 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-N     07-08 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE STANDOUT SCORES TWO GOALS FOR FRANCE, PUTTING HOST TEAM
IN CUP FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. DENIS, France _ After a tedious first half, something
awakened in the French World Cup team Wednesday night, something
exciting and desperate, and the team that could not score goals
suddenly got two from the unlikeliest of places.
</P>
<P>
   After producing no goals in his first 37 appearances with
France's soccer team, the exquisite defender Lilian Thuram
delivered a pair Wednesday night, providing a 2-1 victory over
Croatia and propelling France into the World Cup final for the
first time before 80,000 delirious fans at Stade de France.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes into the second half, after he made a rare mistake
that led to Croatia's goal, Thuram stole a pass to tie the game and
energized a lethargic team that had not scored during regulation in
two previous matches. He scored again in the 69th minute after
another alert disruption and sent his team into Sunday's
championship game against Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Stunningly, the semifinal match changed from a dull,
interminable first half to a wild, gripping conclusion. France was
fatigued and frantic to avoid a third consecutive overtime game.
But five minutes into extra time, it was still not out of trouble.
Not until goalkeeper Fabien Barthez punched away a shot from Goran
Vlaovic did tiny Croatia finally succumb in its first trip to the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   France played shorthanded for the final 20 minutes, after its
previous savior, Laurent Blanc, received a red card for a stiff-arm
to the face of a Croat defender. He is ineligible for Sunday's
final, which could be crippling. It was Blanc who scored the goal
in sudden-death overtime to France past Paraguay in the second
round, and it was Blanc's penalty kick that made the difference in
the quarterfinals against Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But Blanc's absence will be considered in a more sober,
reflective moment. Wednesday night was a night for exuberant
release as France finally made it to the World Cup final after
failing in the semifinals in 1958, 1982 and 1986. A previously
indifferent nation has become fanatical about its ascendant soccer
team. In Paris, the Champs Elysee was jammed with exultant fans
Wednesday night from the Louvre to the Arc de Triomphe.
</P>
<P>
   Both French President Jacque Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin attended Wednesday night's match and applauded
appreciatively at the accomplishments of Thuram, the splendid
defender turned scorer and rescuer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream to have the World Cup in France with us in the
final,'' Jospin said. ``The second dream is to win on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Thuram was placed on the shoulders of reserve goalie Bernard
Lama and paraded about after the game. Forwards usually receive
these adulatory rides on their teammates' shoulders, but France
hasn't had a forward score since its second game of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Thuram's normal duty is as a central defender for Parma in Serie
A, the Italian premier league, where he was voted defender of the
year this season and foreign player of the year in 1997. But France
has Blanc and Marcel Desailly at central defender, so the
26-year-old Thuram, who was born in Guadeloupe and came to France
at age 9, reluctantly agreed to play right back in the World Cup.
He is part of a virtually impenetrable defensive wall that has
surrendered only two goals in six matches. And Wednesday night he
assertively filled the vacuum in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an excellent reward for all the effort he has put in,''
Aime Jacquet, the French coach, said of Thuram. ``Especially the
mental discipline he has been able to instill into this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacquet started three defensive midfielders Wednesday night and
only one forward as France's tepid offense consisted of setting up
playmaker Zinedine Zidane 30 yards from the goal. The scoreless
first half was the kind of game that people who dislike soccer use
as prime evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But, 25 seconds into the second half, the game exploded into a
captivating fight to the finish. France attempted an offsides trap,
seeking to catch Croatia's Davor Suker beyond the last defender and
thus ineligible to receive a pass. But Thuram failed to scramble
upfield, keeping Suker onsides, and Suker deftly trapped a pass
from teammate Aljosa Asanovic and pushed a left-footed shot past
Barthez for a 1-0 Croatia lead.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, Thuram redeemed himself. He stole the ball from
Zvonimir Boban, the Croat captain, and played give-and-go with
teammate Youri Djorkaeff to tie the match at 1-1. He had never
scored for France before, but on this play Thuram's instincts
seemed as natural as Ronaldo's had in the previous semifinal for
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``France was lacking strength, but as so often happens, when you
score and the opponent scores right after, it gives them the
strength to come back and do better,'' said Miroslav Blazevic, the
Croatian coach.
</P>
<P>
   In the 69th minute, Thuram stole the ball off the foot of
Croatia's Robert Jarni and hooked a shot inside the far post from
20 yards out, giving France a 2-1 lead that it would not
relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally when I'm near the goal, I black out,'' Thuram said,
explaining his previous futility. ``I'm not a hero. I just scored
two goals. It's 11 players on the team who made France make the
finals.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard, tough game that turned potentially disastrous for
France in the 74th minute when Blanc shoved Croatia's Slaven Bilic
in the face and was given a red card. Blanc claimed that Bilic had
been goading him all night, but this was an awful time to lose
one's cool and one's eligibility for the final. But at least the
French will have the advantage of playing Brazil at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 22 players here who are poets, who play with their
feet and their hearts,'' Djorkaeff said.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, one who can put the ball into the goal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
