u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-H     07-08 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-BRAZIL-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Brazil handles tension like true champions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ At some point, perhaps the world will realize that it might
be more than mere Brazilian mystique.
</P>
<P>
   Like the parquet floor at old Boston Garden, the Brazilian
mystique makes for a nice excuse, but it might be something else
that actually has made this marvelous team four-time world
champions.
</P>
<P>
   It might be practice, persistence and an unflappable nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest players in the world can crack during a penalty
shootout,'' said Brazilian captain Dunga. ``You have to be prepared
for anything in this game, including the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the Brazilians were prepared. The Dutch seemingly
were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our players before (the shootout) that it was time for
all or nothing,'' Brazil coach Mario Zagallo said. ``The stakes
were high. But just as in 1994, we had to make the penalties bring
us the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   For 120 minutes before Tuesday night's World Cup semifinal went
into nerve-bending shootout penalty kicks, the Netherlands was
playing Brazil to a dead draw.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed the Brazilians finally would be outdone.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch had the momentum of the game swaying their way, having
scored a dramatic game-tying goal in the 87th minute. The Dutch had
the offense in gear and Brazilian goalkeeper Taffarel making
spectacular save after spectacular save.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately the Dutch didn't have the Samba Swagger.
</P>
<P>
   Once the game went into shootout penalty kicks it was as if all
the confidence that the Netherlands exhibited during the game
suddenly vanished and the Brazilian swagger stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   While Taffarel continued to star in goal for Brazil, the
Brazilian shooters confidently smashed penalty kicks past helpless
Dutch keeper Edwin van der Sar.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dutch coach Guus Hiddink was unsure about which
players to send up to the penalty shootout. Hiddink conferred with
coaches and players, switched shootout lineups and finally sent
five players out.
</P>
<P>
   In the moments before the first shot, the Dutch looked nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Philip Cocu smacked a shot to the left of Taffarel that
Taffarel confidently blocked away. And moments later, Ronald de
Boer hit a meek, soft shot to Taffarel's right that he easily
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   And the difference between these teams became clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this kind of exercise you have to stay lucid and keep your
concentration,'' Dunga said. ``It is not easy, but we've had that
(shootout) experience. We've lived in the pressure. I think it
helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the Brazilians won the World Cup in a penalty
shootout over Italy. In that game, like on Tuesday, the Italians
had one shot blocked by Taffarel and another one meekly sailed high
on a poor shot _ by Italy's Roberto Baggio.
</P>
<P>
   Some have called the Brazilians lucky for squeaking out of the
near-miss situations in consecutive World Cups. But perhaps it's
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Dutch) didn't hit their shots real strong, but it also
was good plays by Taffarel,'' Dunga said. ``Of course, you have to
have good luck. But you have to make the shots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
