A6336 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER09-COLUMN-COX     07-08 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER09-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton roadshow may be smart path
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Today, Atlanta and fire-ravaged Florida. Fresh back
from his China tour, President Clinton has lost little time getting
back out on the road and away from his troubles, to the chagrin of
his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Along with frequent domestic jaunts, Clinton plans a lot more
foreign travel this year: Ireland and Russia, and later in the
fall, Malaysia and possibly India and Pakistan, if they simmer
down.
</P>
<P>
   A ``roadshow,'' conservative columnist Rowland Evans called it
on television the other day, complaining that Clinton has
``trivialized'' the presidency by staying out of Washington so
much, avoiding Cabinet meetings and national security sessions for
the pursuit of the perpetual campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Staged events like this morning's kickoff for an anti-drug ad
campaign at the World Congress Center probably are more trivial
than Cabinet meetings, at least most of them. But in the post-Cold
War, post-Big Government world of image, consensus and personal
politics, the more trivial pursuit may also be the wiser form of
governance. Especially, it goes without saying, if we're speaking
of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth, the Virgin Queen, had a similar knack. She sapped the
dissenting energies of her lords by trooping about 16th century
England, perpetually drawing on their hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   A modern president travels with a broader agenda. On this day
trip, which will put Clinton back in Washington sometime after
midnight, he'll pack in two fund-raisers and a tour of the Florida
burn zone on top of the drug message.
</P>
<P>
   But an Elizabethan motive lurks behind the short-term
objectives. By hitting the road so often, Clinton is not, strictly
speaking, fleeing the Monica Lewinsky scandal. That would imply his
pursuers have the better of him, which is not the case.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Clinton has used Air Force One to demonstrate the
considerable power of a president to change the subject. And he has
exhausted his anchormen, his pundits and prosecutors, much as
Elizabeth wore out her lords.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has been away, special prosecutor Kenneth Starr's
investigation has droned along in one-step forward, three-steps
back fashion. It seems less and less a threat to this particular
president, and more and more a menace, in the uncomfortable
precedents it would set, for presidents in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been taking a pounding from his colleagues on the
federal bench, particularly in last week's dismissal of the case
against Webster Hubbell, his wife and lawyer. A stung punditry has
largely abandoned him.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr's tumble from favor really pales beside the
misfortunes of the media that provide the morning footage of the
cheery prosecutor finishing his coffee in his carport.
</P>
<P>
   Since the media seized on the Lewinsky story as a Gen-X
Watergate back in February, they have been subjected to a string of
bad press about themselves, culminating in CNN's retraction of its
nerve gas story last week. The stories of columnists who made up
stuff and networks that went off half-cocked have nothing directly
to do with the handling of the Lewinsky story, but they give more
kick to Steven Brill's excoriation of the Washington media's
alleged complicity with Starr than it would have otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much the context can change, if you stay out on the
road long enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
