<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUECROSS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blue Cross to endow foundation
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia has agreed to
create a multimillion-dollar nonprofit foundation to settle a
lawsuit by consumer groups, who challenged the insurer's 1996
conversion to a for-profit company.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, filed Wednesday in Fulton County Superior
Court, Blue Cross would endow a health care foundation with stock
and warrants _ a total amounting to 20 percent of the shares of
Cerulean, Blue Cross's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the dollar value of that endowment can't be
determined. But based on valuations of the company at the time of
its conversion, made by Blue Cross and later by the plaintiffs, the
endowment stock could be worth $40 million to $120 million, or
more.
</P>
<P>
   The deal must be approved by the court, after a fairness hearing
August 20. When the settlement gets final approval, the endowment
also would receive $1 million in cash. Blue Cross, in the
agreement, denied all allegations of wrongdoing and liability made
in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Harman, a Blue Cross vice president, said that while the
company believes the suit had no legal merit, ``the settlement is a
business decision made in order to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lynn Thogersen of Let's Get Together, a plaintiff
organization that's an advocate for people with disabilities,
called the deal ``a victory for the people of our state.''
</P>
<P>
   Thogersen said she hoped the foundation would make grants
available for projects ``to look at needed changes in the health
care system, such as monitoring managed care.''
</P>
<P>
   Grants also could establish medical clinics in underserved areas
of the state, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of the foundation will be to improve the delivery of
health care services to medically underserved Georgians,'' Harman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal culminates three years of controversy over the Blue
Cross transaction, which was approved by Insurance Commissioner
John Oxendine in December 1995. Legislation allowing the conversion
passed the Georgia General Assembly earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Blue's conversion was criticized by consumer groups
nationwide, who noted that Blue Cross plans have gained years of
tax breaks as nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, legislative and regulatory actions have caused
billions to be set aside or designated for charity. For example,
all assets of Blue Cross of California, about $3.2 billion, have
been transferred to two health care foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Bell of Consumers Union in California, who tracks Blue
Cross conversions, said the Georgia for-profit transaction was the
only one nationally that had not awarded funds to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said the settlement ``is better than it was, but it could
have been more money, and could have been done three years ago.
Georgia legislators and regulators could have taken action, and 100
percent of the company could have been preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, eight consumer groups, had argued that the
General Assembly law to allow the conversion was unconstitutional.
They argued that an entity considered a public asset must create a
public trust or foundation if it seeks to switch to a for-profit
company.
</P>
<P>
   According to the settlement agreement, the foundation, to be
called Healthcare Georgia, will have as its goal ``the advancement
of health care for all Georgians.''
</P>
<P>
   It will have a nine-member board, which would approve grants for
nonprofit health care purposes. Three of the directors will be
named by the plaintiffs, three by Cerulean, one by the Carter
Center and the other two by separate foundations in Atlanta and
Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   The endowment will include 9.5 percent of the stock ownership of
the company, plus warrants that entitle the foundation to acquire
another 10.5 percent of Blue Cross over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross valued itself at about $200 million at the time of
conversion, but experts for the plaintiffs said it was worth $400
million to $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' law firm, Carr, Tabb &AMP; Pope, will receive a fee
of no more than 10 percent of the value of the endowment. The final
sum will be determined by the court.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also could clear the path for an acquisition of
Blue Cross. Speculation of such a deal has centered on
California-based WellPoint Health Networks, a huge, highly
profitable insurer with Blue Cross roots.
</P>
<P>
   Its managed care business in California is operated as Blue
Cross of California. WellPoint's health plans in Georgia are
offered under the UniCare label, and cover about 100,000 in a
preferred provider organization in the state. WellPoint has 6.7
million managed care members overall.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the California charitable foundations involved
WellPoint, which was formed in 1992 to operate Blue Cross of
California's managed care business. In 1996, WellPoint and Blue
Cross of California merged into a stockholder-owned company. As a
result, the foundations were created.
</P>
<P>
   Harman of Blue Cross declined to comment on possible discussions
with another company.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the settlement of the consumer groups' suit was a
vital hurdle that needed to be cleared before a merger agreement
could be concluded.
</P>
<P>
   If an acquisition occurs, Consumers Union's Bell says, ``It
would provide a windfall to the private investors in the
conversion.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight consumer groups, besides Let's Get Together, are:
Statewide Independent Living Council of Georgia; Living
Independence for Everyone; AIDS Survival Project; Disability
Connections; The Middle Georgia Center for Independent Living;
Physicians for a National Health Program; Campaign for a Prosperous
Georgia; and Friends and Survivors Standing Together.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
