<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Equifax buys customer loyalty consulting company
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Equifax will announce today an acquisition that will
broaden its base and sophistication in helping retailers, banks and
other businesses target and retain customers.
</P>
<P>
   Decisioneering Group, the company Equifax has bought for an
undisclosed price, specializes in helping businesses ''engineer
loyalty among customers,'' said Thomas J. Blischok.
</P>
<P>
   Blischok, formerly managing partner of Coopers &AMP; Lybrand's
retail consulting practice, is chairman and chief executive officer
of Phoenix-based Decisioneering Group. The firm has a number of
competitors, but has a ``two- to three-year head start'' on others
in the field, Blischok said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is help people understand their
customers, products and channels,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas F. Chapman, president and chief executive officer of
Equifax, said the acquisition of the privately held Decisioneering
Group is in line with Equifax's transition. The Atlanta-based
company best known as a keeper of consumer credit reports has been
adding analytical services to the data it sells, rather than to
just sell the raw information.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said the deal will not lead to a merger of the databases
Equifax maintains with those of Decisioneering Group. Data from
Equifax might be used by Decisioneering Group, but the privacy
rights of individuals will be protected, Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   Decisioneering Group, with 25 employees, will be part of what
Equifax calls its knowledge engineering unit and will have Equifax
in its name, Chapman added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
