<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-COMPANY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Energy trading deal in Illinois goes sour on Southern Co.
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The city-operated utility of Springfield, Ill., has
defaulted on a $10 million contract to sell electricity to Southern
Co., the Atlanta-based utility holding company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   City Water Light &AMP; Power, which has entered the wholesale energy
trading business, broke contracts with Southern and a number of
other leading investor-owned utilities when the energy trading
company it was buying power from defaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Southern said it is assessing its options, but that the default
would not have a significant impact on profits. David Mould, a
spokesman for Southern, said the company diversifies its trading
transactions to hedge against such risks. Overall financial results
for the period Springfield defaulted are expected to be positive,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mould also said recent volatility in wholesale electricity
prices ``will have no impact'' on second-quarter financial results
Southern reports July 20.
</P>
<P>
   City Water Light &AMP; Power's supplier, Federal Energy Sales Inc.
of Cleveland, found itself unable to purchase enough electricity to
meet its obligations during the week of June 23. Record
temperatures increased demand for electricity and made energy
prices volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Towner, president of Federal Energy, said prices
skyrocketed from $30 per megawatt hour to $5,000 in two days, and
that his company was unable to supply electricity to the
Springfield utility.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield then reportedly broke contracts to sell power to
Southern, LG&AMP;E Energy Trading Corp. of Louisville, El Paso Energy
Corp. of Texas and PECO Energy Co. of Philadelphia. El Paso Energy
has filed suit in Harris County, Texas, against the Springfield
utility, seeking at least $7.4 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   City Water Light &AMP; Power officials did not return calls seeking
comment. The Wall Street Journal said a spokesman confirmed the
broken contracts, but denied liability in the El Paso case.
</P>
<P>
   Southern has been involved in wholesale electricity sales for
years. The company started a separate trading subsidiary in 1996
that last year became a joint venture with Vastar Resources, a
Houston-based natural gas company, for sales of both electricity
and natural gas. It was that unit, which operates trading floors in
Atlanta and Houston, that had contracted to purchase electricity
from Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Southern reported that energy trading contributed almost $2
billion of the company's $12.6 billion in revenues last year. It
did not separately report profits from the trading business, known
as Southern Company Energy Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing unit Tuesday announced an agreement to sell
electricity produced by four upstate New York power plants operated
by New York-based Sithe Energies.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Southern subsidiary announced a five-year
agreement with Houston-based Kinder Morgan Energy Partners to
jointly market coal storage and transportation services. The two
companies will jointly market coal transloading, blending and
storage services at Kinder Morgan's coal terminals near St. Louis
and in western Kentucky. Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
