<HEADER>
A6343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIRE-IMPACT-NYT     07-08 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRE-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROUGHT AND FIRES RAVAGING REGIONAL ECONOMIES
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ While hurricanes and tornadoes sweep through with swaths
of utter devastation, the wildfires that have struck Florida since
May labor erratically _ one acre here and a few more there.
</P>
<P>
   But with the passage of time, the fires and the drought that
sparked them have wiped out crops and cattle herds and sent up
choking clouds of smoke that have emptied beaches and hotels,
disrupting the economic pulse of whole communities.
</P>
<P>
   With lightning starting 50 new fires on Wednesday, the onslaught
is far from over. As firefighters spend their seventh week taming
the worst fires in memory in Florida, state officials have only
begun to tally the financial damage and assess long-term effects.
</P>
<P>
   As uncertain as the damage is, the one certainty is that Florida
is not alone in being hurt. Severe drought has been ruining crops
since March from Texas eastward through Arkansas, Mississippi and
Georgia. At the same time the Midwest, middle Appalachia and New
England have been awash in rain, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency says it has spent more
than $520 million in grants, loans and other assistance so far this
year on states affected by fires, drought, winter storms, flooding
and tornadoes. For agriculture, drought has been a worse problem
than flooding, said Albert Peterlin, chief meteorologist with the
U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flooding is localized,'' Peterlin said. ``Water is a
thousand small threats. Drought is a big, terrible one.''
</P>
<P>
   It hit hard in states like Texas, where farmers say they have
lost track of the days with temperatures over 100 and some are even
hoping for a hurricane. State officials estimate the loss to crops
this year at $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers said losses from drought in previous years have
made them barely able to hold on to their businesses now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to laugh or cry,'' said Lynn Bartlett, 32, who grows
cotton and peanuts on a 500-acre farm his grandfather started in
the 1930s along the northeastern border with Oklahoma. ``The
dry-land cotton needs rain exactly right now, or it's close to
being over.''
</P>
<P>
   In northern Florida, two inches or less of rain fell in May and
June compared with 10 to 12 inches normally. Although only about
$175 million of the state's annual $6.2 billion farm revenue has
been lost so far to the record-breaking heat and drought, the
weather has all but destroyed crops like corn and hay and has
inflicted major losses to about 12,000 growers in the Panhandle and
north-central region, Florida Department of Agriculture officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Livestock hungry from dry pastures are subsisting on hay, which
is not expected to last through the winter when it is normally
needed. As a result demand is great.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're desperately short of hay,'' said Terence McElroy, a
spokesman for the agriculture department, which is seeking hay
suppliers outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst losses in Florida have come from wildfires that
have burned about 485,000 acres, more than half of those commercial
timberland. About $300 million in timber has been lost, along with
at least $2.6 million from the destruction or damage to about 324
homes. The price tag for firefighting efforts is now $104 million,
state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 260,000 of the state's 14 million acres in timber
land have burned, but affected landowners are now turning to
salvage efforts. The pine trees used for paper and building
materials take 15 to 25 years to reach maturity, said Jeff Doran,
executive vice president of the Florida Forestry Association, which
represents the timber industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just go back and plant the trees all over again,'' said
Jim Kauffman, land manager of the Jefferson Smurfit Corp. in
Fernandina Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The fires that began burning out of control on Memorial Day have
caused no deaths and only a few dozen injuries, mostly to
firefighters, because they were concentrated in forest lands.
Compared with the tornadoes in Central Florida in February that
killed more than 40 people, or Hurricane Andrew in 1992, which
killed at least 32 people in Florida and the Bahamas and caused $30
billion in damages and still ranks as the nation's most expensive
disaster, the fires have seemed relatively benign.
</P>
<P>
   But the potential for the fires to reach that same scale as the
flames moved toward towns and coastal communities last week
prompted evacuations that displaced more than 100,000 people,
closed major highways and led to cancellation of Fourth of July
events.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism in most of the state remains unaffected by fires,
drought and summer heat, state officials said, but smoke has cast
an acrid pall over beaches, keeping visitors away from coastal
cities like Daytona Beach and Ormond Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally have a 90 to 95 percent occupancy this time of
year,'' said John Connors, president of the Ormond Beach Chamber of
Commerce. ``There was one hotel I talked to that had only 13 of its
150 rooms occupied.''.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of small businesses, from restaurants to fireworks
stores, suffered from mandatory evacuations that emptied out whole
communities, including all of Flagler County last week, or from
state health warnings that kept residents indoors.
</P>
<P>
   In Ormond Beach, where the city's 35,000 residents were under
evacuation orders for four days, Paul LaRusso, manager of the
Bicycle Company, said business is still down 30 percent. Many of
his customers are avid bicycle racers, who because of the smoke,
left the area to train in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally get 50 to 60 people a day through here,'' he said.
``One day I counted seven people in nine hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, when dislocated communities are returning to a
semblance of normalcy, city officials say it is hardly business as
usual. Judy Sloane, an Ormond Beach city engineer, said routine
maintenance is not being performed because the smoke makes work
outside difficult. The city has also imposed strict limitations on
water use, asking residents to water lawns or gardens only two days
a week, to conserve water for firefighters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
