<HEADER>
A6347 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TEACHER-BONUSES-BO     07-08 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHER-BONUSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRMINGHAM SAYS BONUSES WOULD CREATE TEACHING ELITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Responding to criticism that his proposal to lure new
teachers with $20,000 signing bonuses was ``stealing money from the
taxpayers,'' Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham refined his idea
Wednesday to include high qualifications, ones that he said would
create an ``elite'' teaching corps.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, Birmingham said, would make Massachusetts the nation's
top contender in the looming competition to replace 40 percent of
the country's teaching force during the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   While the idea of attracting better teachers drew favor,
Birmingham's proposal also drew fire from legislators and interest
groups as well as from Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci, who said it would
be misusing the state's newly-realized surplus _ money that would
be better spent, they said, on tax cuts than good teachers.
</P>
<P>
   And some remained skeptical that the same kind of bonuses
baseball teams use to entice big-name players would score better
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going to have, free agents next?'' asked Rep.
Harold M. Lane, the Holden Democrat who co-chairs the Legislature's
Education Committee, and a former high school principal. ``I think
the rejuvenation of the profession is long overdue, but I'm not
terribly enthusiastic about this kind of approach.''
</P>
<P>
   But Birmingham said he would limit the bonuses to the best
students, in the same way that top law schools or medical schools
screen out their candidates, using grade point averages or test
scores, and possibly having colleges nominate their best students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to be elitist, and unapologetically so,'' the
Senate president said. ``This is not just a check to people who
would already go into teaching. The purpose of this initiative is
to attract a population that has not traditionally gone into
teaching. That's one reason why we are aggressive in terms of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   And whatever the criticism, Birmingham's proposal sparked a
conversation _ or at least lots of talk _ about how to improve the
state's teaching force. In a political year, it triggered a race
among candidates, all rushing to insist that they have the best
plan to attract the best and brightest to teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci pitched scholarships to top-flight high school
students. Attorney General and gubernatorial candidate Scott
Harshbarger offered $5,000 bonuses to teachers who promise to work
in the worst schools. And consultants to Sen. John Kerry, testing
the waters for a presidential race, insisted he had been first to
address the problem with a plan to attract talent from other
professions into teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham's plan was by far the most dramatic initiative to get
better teachers, a need that has seemed more acute in the weeks
since the state announced that 59 percent of prospective teachers
could not pass a test of literacy and basic skills.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of that came the state's announcement this week of
a $1 billion surplus. Birmingham Tuesday suggested using $100
million to create _ subject to legislative approval _ a trust fund
that would pay $20,000 signing bonuses to 250 teachers. Over the
years, the money would come from interest on the fund, which he
suggested the state invest in treasury notes.
</P>
<P>
   The bonuses would rival what employers offer Ivy League business
school graduates, and dwarf much smaller bonuses offered in a small
number of other school systems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham said Wednesday he would limit the awards to only the
most top performing candidates. While existing plans to, say, pay
off college loans to teachers, go to students in the top quarter of
their class, Birmingham said he wanted it to be even more
exclusive, though he did not specify a cut-off.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that money is not the only way to improve
teachers, but also said it was a key ingredient, to make the
profession seem more attractive. The state is competing not only
with other states, but with other professions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect there are many top-notch college students who flirt
with the idea of teaching, then they see the entry-level salaries
that are dwarfed by other offers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham's counterpart in the House, Speaker Thomas M.
Finneran, would be a key to getting the plan approved. Finneran
refused to comment on it Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But other key policy makers criticized it as the wrong use of
the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should take this unexpected surplus and turn
it into a feeding frenzy,'' said Cellucci. ``I don't like taking
$100 million that is scheduled to go back to the taxpayers and
applying it to some other use. If you're trying to steal money from
the taxpayers, I am not going to look favorably on it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the signing bonuses are such a good idea, Cellucci said, they
should be paid for in the regular budget, and subject to the
Legislature's approval each year.
</P>
<P>
   The acting governor also said he preferred his plan, which would
pay scholarships to high school students on the honor roll or in
the top quarter of their classes to attend the University of
Massachusetts or a state college, in exchange for a promise to
teach for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Others said they agreed that higher salaries are part of the
equation to better teachers, especially in the early years, when
new teachers often have student loans to pay off. Starting teachers
make an average of $26,000 the first year, compared with $35,000 in
other professions, according to the state Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   But critics questioned whether Birmingham's plan would sustain a
good teaching force after the first year, when those elite teachers
would crash back to the starting salary level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would that one-time inducement be enough?'' asked Michael
Widmer, president of the Massachusetts Taxpayers Foundation. But
Widmer, like Cellucci, also questioned whether the money should
come from the surplus, and stressed that the first priority should
be a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Yet James St. George, director of the Tax Equity Alliance for
Massachusetts, said the public was starting to value issues like
education more than tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I believe people are coming to see when it comes to
education in particular, you can't get something for nothing,'' he
said. ``If teaching is not a valued profession, you won't get the
good people at it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Frank Phillips of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
