<SLUG> BC-FUTURENET-CHANGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURENET NAMES INTERIM PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALENCIA, Calif. _ Three weeks after its president resigned,
multilevel marketing firm FutureNet Inc. said it has named a new
top executive.
</P>
<P>
   The news Wednesday appeared to give FutureNet shares a slight
boost. The issue rose 3.12 cents from its 52-week low Tuesday, to
close at 53.12 cents Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Menning, who joined FutureNet as a consultant just before
the departure of then-President Chris Lobato, will serve as acting
president of the company. Menning said he will work with newly
appointed Senior Vice President Charles Perkins to reposition the
company in the multilevel marketing sector.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Federal Trade Commission accused
FutureNet of operating a Ponzi scheme that depended on initiation
fees paid by the company's independent dealers to survive. To
settle the suit, Chairman Alan Setlin established a $1 million fund
to refund membership fees to disgruntled dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not blind to some of the policies advocated by previous
management,'' Menning said. ``That's not the modern world of
network marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Menning said that among other changes, he will work to increase
FutureNet's role in Internet services. Currently dealers for the
company sell WebTV, a device that allows users to access the
Internet through a television. Menning said the company is
considering becoming an Internet service provider that would also
offer Web design services.
</P>
<P>
   Menning likened the challenge he faces in repositioning
FutureNet to those faced by Amway and Herbalife, two multilevel
marketing firms that overcame bad publicity arising from their own
run-ins with government regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
