<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-NIGHT-840&AMP;AD     07-08 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-NIGHT-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYS PASS NORMALLY IN ULSTER, BUT NIGHTS ARE VIOLENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ In the daylight hours life follows
its usual rhythms in Northern Ireland. In a spell of surprisingly
sunny weather, people go to work, shop or sip $3 cups of Viennese
cappuccino at cafes like Roscoff on Fountain Street. Shops and
department stores have plenty of customers. Buses crowd the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   But at nightfall the towns of this predominantly Protestant
British province, especially Belfast, become urban war zones.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants vent their anger over a parade by the Protestant
Orange Order that was blocked on Sunday by the police and the
British Army from marching through a Roman Catholic area along
Garvaghy Road, Drumcree, in Portadown, west of here.
</P>
<P>
   For four nights gangs of Protestants have thrown blazing
gasoline bombs at police officers, who respond by firing plastic
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, mostly young men, hijack and burn cars, block
roads with burning barricades and have caused cancellations and
interruptions of buses and trains.
</P>
<P>
   Official police summaries from Tuesday night and early this
morning were terse and grim:
</P>
<P>
   ``0100 hours. A car was driven through the outer gates of Holy
Cross Girls' Primary School at Ardoyne Road, driven against the
front-door shutters and set alight. Scorch damage and structural
damage was caused to the doorway. A number of windows were broken
and petrol poured into a broken window though not ignited.
</P>
<P>
   ``2159 hours. A mob attacked a hostel in Castlereagh Street with
stones, breaking up to 14 windows. The occupants were evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   ``2350 hours. A police patrol was attacked with four petrol
bombs in the Ballycraigy estate, Antrim. Minutes later they foiled
a hijacking and arrested one male. Approximately 20 minutes later
two blast bombs were thrown at police in the estate. There were no
injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders and security officials said they expected at
least several more nights of violence, raising fears that the
turmoil will damage or destroy the peace settlement, approved in
the spring, that is supposed to end sectarian killing between
Catholics and Protestants in the province.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night the vicious mood of many in the province was
reflected at a meeting in Portadown. A prominent moderate Catholic,
Seamus Mallon, a member of the British Parliament and Deputy First
Minister of the new Northern Ireland Assembly, went to Garvaghy
Road to discuss solutions with Catholics opposed to the march.
About 100 of the 6,000 Catholic residents of the area shouted
insults at him, saying he was selling out his own kind and forcing
him to enter his car and leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-win situation,'' John Taylor said Wednesday. Taylor
is a member of the British Parliament and deputy leader of the
Ulster Unionist Party of David Trimble, who is the First Minister
of the new Assembly that is to work out the peace agreement
approved in referendums in May in the Irish republic and in the
North.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you let the parade go down the Garvaghy Road,'' Taylor
added, ``there will be violence. If you try to reroute, it there
will be violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Trimble, an Orangeman who is now committed to cooperating
with Catholics in the Assembly: ``We cannot afford this situation
to continue indefinitely. The longer the present situation
continues, the greater the dangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Slight progress had been made toward a compromise, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The office of Prime Minister Tony Blair said in London he would
meet on Thursday with leaders of the Protestant Orange Order, whose
parade was blocked, to try to work out something. Britain announced
that it would send 800 additional troops here by the end of the
week. They will join the 17,000 troops in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians, including Blair, have been urging people to stay
calm, saying there has been some progress toward ending the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   But for four nights pleas for calm have been ignored. The police
reported Wednesday that there had been 350 gasoline bomb incidents
in five days and 437 attacks on security forces, injuring 44. There
have been 92 arrests. In addition, 156 vehicles have been hijacked,
about half burned. About 135 private homes have been attacked, as
have 92 commercial buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But television stations repeatedly showed a fight between a
Protestant and a Catholic, in which one man swung a long piece of
wood at the other, who ducked. The two rolled in the street before
the police separated them. For the viewer it was impossible to tell
which one was the Catholic and which the Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said in London on Tuesday, in a statement repeated
Wednesday on television: ``I think it's important in a situation
like this, when we've come so far in Northern Ireland, we've got
over the hurdle of the referendum. We've got over the hurdle of an
Assembly. We now have the possibility of a tremendous future in
Northern Ireland. So if we can talk and work with people, too, then
I hope the good will exists to change.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   People watch the mayhem and the politicians on television, but
in interviews in downtown Belfast in recent days, many indicated
that there was at least as much interest in less violent events
like the World Cup soccer matches in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crisis Deepens,'' said a sign in front of newsstand that was
advertising The Belfast Telegraph. But at sidewalk tables of the
Roscoff cafe, people enjoyed the hazy sunlight and ate
cheddar-and-scallion soup.
</P>
<P>
   David McCabe, 40, a Protestant graphics designer, said of the
violence and politics: ``There's an entertainment value. The only
effect is the nuisance of roadblocks. The wanton damage is
something we're used to. The whole thing's politically driven.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend John Lunn, 25, a Protestant computer programmer,
said, ``I think the government created the problem, got themselves
into a stalemate.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the government decision to try to mollify
Protestants by allowing them to march through a different Catholic
area in Belfast next Monday, he added: ``They have to parade in
silence, no traditional music, before 8:30 in the morning. It's not
a parade at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner on Chapel Lane, a Catholic busker, Mike Doyle,
strummed his six-string guitar and sang his own songs and those of
Simon and Garfunkel, his instrument case open at his feet for
donations. ``I'm losing about 40 percent of my income,'' Doyle
said. ``People go home earlier. It's just that they're wary.''
</P>
<P>
   A uniformed security guard at the Castlecourt shopping complex
said there were no plans to resume checking bags of arriving
customers for guns or bombs, as was the case until the peace effort
began making progress three years ago. ``I don't think it really
bothers anyone,'' he said of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   At the Northern Ireland government tourist office on North
Street, a woman at the information counter said there had been no
noticeable drop in tourism this week. A few people a day telephone
to ask whether it is safe to visit the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them the whole of Northern Ireland is not in
uprising,'' the woman said. ``Life is continuing in Northern
Ireland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
