<SLUG> BC-MISSING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS TO CHICAGO BEATING IS MISSING, FEARED DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER AND HEATHER RATCLIFFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (SCOTTSDALE, Ariz.) A 13-year-old Chicago boy who lay in a coma
for days might never recall the day police said three White teens
pummeled him for being Black.
</P>
<P>
   So prosecutors must rely on eyewitnesses to tell his tale.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, one key witness is dead. And the other, a Scottsdale
teen, is nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Richard DeSantis, 19, vanished from the Valley in April.
Authorities, who have focused a nationwide manhunt in Arizona, fear
he might be dead because the defendants he is to testify against
reportedly have ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just would like to see Mr. DeSantis alive and well and in
court,'' said Bob Benjamin, spokesman for the Cook County State's
Attorney's Office in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say DeSantis saw three Chicago teens attack
13-year-old Lenard (cq) Clark in March 1997. Police said the young
Black teen was savagely beaten after wandering into a predominantly
White neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The racially charged case sparked national outrage, drawing the
attention of Black leaders and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is recovering from the attack but has no memory of it,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness in the case was fatally shot in May, in what
police call a gang-related shooting. Chicago Police Department
spokesman Patrick Camden said police believe the cases are
unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it left prosecutors in the beating case with one
eyewitness, DeSantis, and little time. The case is set to go to
trial July 20.
</P>
<P>
   The teens, Frank Caruso, Victor Jasas and Michael Kwidzinski,
are charged with several counts including attempted murder,
aggravated battery and hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago officials have said Caru so's father is tied to an
organized crime crew, which Chicago media also have linked to
Richard DeSantis's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' located DeSantis' father Wednesday at a
north Scottsdale post office box and asked him to explain his side
of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a side,'' Richard DeSantis Sr. told a reporter,
declining to say whether he knew his son's location.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   A relative, who lives in Scottsdale and asked to remain
anonymous, told ``The Republic'' he fears the younger DeSantis
might be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   The relative said family members suspect Richard DeSantis Sr.
might be helping his son evade authorities. If that is the case,
the relative said, he should turn his son over to authorities as
part of a witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   The DeSantis family moved to Scottsdale several years ago to get
away from the old Chicago neighborhood, the relative said. Local
records indicate Richard DeSantis started a cleaning business,
Amerimex All Kleen Systems, in 1997, but the relative said it is
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   The DeSantis family, including the younger DeSantis, lived with
relatives in a sprawling north Scottsdale home until just before
last Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   They then moved to another home after a family feud over money,
said the relative. Before his disappearance, young Richard DeSantis
traveled between Scottsdale, where he worked occasionally at a
local video store, and Chicago, said relatives and a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the family abruptly moved out of that home, and
Richard DeSantis' mother and sister returned to Chicago, the
relative said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard DeSantis Sr. stayed behind and is living in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Cook County authorites sent a letter to Maricopa County Attorney
Richard Romley in April asking for help locating DeSantis. A
Maricopa County judge issued a warrant April 29 for his arrest,
declaring him a federal fugitive for flight from testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chicago prosecutors said they will continue to
prepare for the trial and will not rule out the possibility that
their key witness might be dead, said Benjamin, of the state's
Attorneys Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to consider anything as being possible,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
