u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-NYT &LR;      07-08 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATED BY KOSOVO STALEMATE, THE WEST CRITICIZES ALL SIDES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The United States, Russia and European countries
monitoring fighting between ethnic Albanian and Serbian forces in
Kosovo turned their attention to the rebels Wednesday, condemning
outside support for the fighters and urging all countries to
prevent exiles from financing arms for the insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   While the diplomats of the six countries, known as the contact
group, acknowledge that the primary responsibility for the
bloodshed in Kosovo lies with Serbia, their statement Wednesday was
almost as critical of the insurgents. The diplomats also said for
the first time that negotiations should include ethnic Albanian
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Warning that chances of a peaceful settlement had deteriorated
over the last month, the diplomats, meeting near Bonn, called on
Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic to live up to commitments
he made in Moscow on June 16 to stop the Serbian attacks and resume
talks with Kosovo's ethnic Albanian political leader, Ibrahim
Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a province in Serbia; Montenegro and Serbia are the
two remaining republics in the Yugoslav federation, with Serbia by
far the dominant partner.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rebels, Rugova has called for independence for the
province, a goal the contact group countries _ the United States,
Russia, Germany, Italy, Britain and France _ do not endorse. Some
ethnic Albanian fighters have complained recently that Rugova, who
advocates a peaceful approach, does not speak for them.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomats said they had agreed to suggest elements of a
political settlement in an effort to speed negotiations, but they
did not elaborate. They have said that any settlement would have to
restore the autonomy that Kosovo had before Milosevic revoked it in
1989, when he was president of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the province's 2 million people are ethnic
Albanians, and the diplomats in Bonn also expressed concern
Wednesday that the conflict could draw in Albania and Macedonia, a
former Yugoslav republic that also has a sizable Albanian minority.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Wednesday in Brussels that military
contingency plans could be put into effect within hours if the
allies were called upon to act in Kosovo, and the contact group
states threatened again Wednesday to consider military steps if the
two sides ignored demands to stop the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The six countries also said they would seek a United Nations
Security Council resolution calling on both sides to stop fighting,
requiring Milosevic to keep his promises to resume a dialogue and
requiring both the Serbian authorities and the rebels to ensure the
safety of international observers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The statement from Bonn Wednesday reflected the frustration that
the American special emissary to the Balkans, Richard Holbrooke,
said he and other diplomats had experienced last weekend with
disunity between the Albanian political leadership in Pristina, the
capital of Kosovo, and the fighters of the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army.
</P>
<P>
   As the statement put it: ``It is clear that the Kosovo Albanian
team for all these talks must be fully representative of their
community in order to speak authoritatively. Although the primary
responsibility for the situation in Kosovo rests with Belgrade, the
contact group acknowledges that armed Kosovo Albanian groups also
have a responsibility to avoid violence and all armed activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gelbard, the Clinton administration's principal
troubleshooter in the area, said in Bonn Wednesday that the Kosovo
Liberation Army controlled more than 30 percent of the province.
But if the militias did not agree to seek a peaceful settlement, he
added, ``we will try to interrupt their ability to sustain
themselves through the full chain of supply.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAG-BURNING-NYT     07-08 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-BURNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAG AMENDMENT FLIES PROUDLY IN SENATE HEARING
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In one sense, a hearing before the Senate Judiciary
Committee on Wednesday to consider a proposed constitutional
amendment to allow Congress to ban flag-burning was just so much
rhetorical icing on the cake.
</P>
<P>
   The committee approved the measure two weeks ago and hardly
needed the inspiration provided by witnesses like the longtime
baseball manager Tommy Lasorda, who denounced the Supreme Court for
treating the flag as ``just another piece of cloth'' when it ruled
in 1989 that burning an American flag in political protest was a
form of constitutionally protected expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom of speech is when you talk,'' Lasorda growled
dismissively of the nuances of the court's First Amendment
doctrines.
</P>
<P>
   But in another sense, this after-the-fact hearing, organized by
the amendment's supporters to get a few last words on record in
preparation for a vote by the full Senate this fall, was a preview
of things to come. After several false starts, and with little
public notice this time, supporters of a flag-protection amendment
appear closer to victory than at any other time since the effort
began to overturn the court's 1989 decision in Texas vs. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The current proposal, differing slightly from the version
offered in 1989, 1990 and 1995, passed the House of Representatives
a year ago by a 310-114 vote, with nearly half the Democratic
members voting in favor. It has 61 sponsors in the Senate, 6 short
of the two-thirds needed for passage, but with time remaining for
supporters to turn on the election-year pressure. The last time a
flag amendment came to a vote, three years ago, it fell three votes
short.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would amend the Constitution by ``authorizing
Congress to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the
United States.'' Earlier versions gave similar authority to the
states as well as to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Once an amendment clears both houses of Congress, it goes
directly to the states, where final adoption requires approval by
three-quarters of the legislatures; there is no role for the
president in the process. Over the last three years, 49 state
legislatures, all except Vermont's, have adopted resolutions urging
Congress to approve the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Those state resolutions, spurred by a coalition of veterans'
groups, carry no formal weight but add to the political climate.
There have also been other recent developments calling renewed
attention to what earlier appeared a quiescent issue. On June 25,
the Wisconsin Supreme Court, ruling in the case of a 17-year-old
self-described anarchist who had stolen an American flag from a
country club and defecated on it, unanimously held Wisconsin's
flag-desecration law unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin court, writing with obvious reluctance, said it
was bound by U.S. Supreme Court precedent but noted pointedly that
Congress had the power to begin the amendment process ``to protect
our nation's symbol.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is thus firmly in our court here in Congress,'' said
Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who heads the Judiciary Committee and
presided over Wednesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who strongly favors the amendment, appeared particularly
moved by Lasorda's account of a flag-burning incident during a game
at Dodger Stadium in Los Angeles in 1976. Lasorda, then the
Dodgers' third-base coach and now their general manager, said that
two men suddenly ran onto the field and tried to burn a flag they
had soaked with lighter fluid. One of the players, Rick Monday of
the Chicago Cubs, rescued the flag, Lasorda said, and the fans in
the stadium stood and sang ``God Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda described Monday's intervention as ``one of the most
heroic acts ever to take place on the field during a major league
baseball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch commended Lasorda for ``as powerful a statement as I have
heard'' on the issue. Other witnesses who spoke in support of the
amendment were John Schneider, a star of the 1980s television
series ``The Dukes of Hazzard''; Gary Wetzel, a Medal of Honor
winner from Wisconsin; Sean Stephenson, a 19-year-old student at
DePaul University, and Richard Parker, a Harvard Law School
professor.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider, who recently recorded a song written by Hatch called
``I Love Old Glory,'' testified that the ``shock tore at my heart''
when he first learned of the Supreme Court's decision on
flag-burning, ``and it is still tearing at my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said that the court's 5-4 decision had been a mistake and
that the ``legal elite'' were mistaken in continuing to support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court and the Constitution are not the same thing,'' he
said, adding, ``The flag represents not the freedom to burn it, but
an ideal and aspiration for national community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee's Republican majority allowed the
amendment's opponents to present two witnesses. Along with two
Democratic senators, Russell Feingold of Wisconsin and Richard
Durbin of Illinois, they said that amending the Bill of Rights for
the first time in the country's history would be a drastic and
unnecessary step. Feingold said adopting the amendment would
``align the United States with totalitarian governments like China,
Cuba and Iran,'' where flag desecration is a crime.
</P>
<P>
   One witness opposed to the amendment, Marvin Virgil Stenhammar,
a disabled Army Special Forces veteran from Asheville, N.C., said
the proposal would ``place a higher value on an inanimate object, a
symbol, than the rights of the people living under it.''
</P>
<P>
   The other, Clint Bolick, vice president of the Institute for
Justice, a public interest law firm here with a libertarian
orientation, asked the senators to oppose the amendment in order to
make the ``powerful symbolic statement'' that the country has
nothing to fear from ``such pathetic displays of contempt for our
system'' as flag-burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That principle,'' Bolick said, ``seems to have worked awfully
well for all of these years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
