</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-LIABILITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT'S LIABILITY PLAN WOULD AID BIG EMPLOYER IN HIS HOME STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Ill., W.Va.)  (bl) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the final push for a bill setting a nationwide
product liability standard began this week, Senate Republican
Majority Leader Trent Lott urged his colleagues not to burden the
measure with amendments. But Wednesday, a new hand-written
amendment sponsored by Lott suddenly appeared in the bill, one that
would significantly benefit a major company in his home state of
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has angered Democrats by blocking their efforts to add a
variety of amendments to the bill, which is designed to set the
first-ever nationwide limits on court awards for injuries caused by
faulty products as diverse as toaster-ovens and tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Lott told his fellow senators they should restrain
themselves from tinkering with the measure.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday morning, the new version of the measure had the
amendment offered by Lott, scrawled with a pen in the margins, and
it seemed aimed at helping Baxter Healthcare Corp., one of
Mississippi's largest employers.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sought by the business community for nearly two
decades, contains two sections. The main section would limit
litigation against retailers and wholesalers unless they altered a
product.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill limits punitive damages, that is the large
amounts awarded by juries to punish especially irresponsible
corporate behavior. The limits on punitive damages would apply only
to companies with fewer than 25 employees or with annual revenues
of less than $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lott amendment is part of the second section that deals
with biomaterials. Sponsors of this section have argued that unless
there is some kind of immunity for companies that provide raw
materials used in medical devices, the supply will dry up.
</P>
<P>
   The original bill provided protection against lawsuits for
materials and components used only in implants. Lott's amendment
would extend that protection to materials and components used in
``containers and their related products to be used to collect
fluids or tissue from the body or to infuse or to otherwise
introduce fluids or tissue into the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Baxter's subsidiary in Cleveland, Miss., is one of the world's
largest manufacturers of products that precisely fit that
definition: medical kits used in intravenous injections as well as
special catheters used in kidney dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Spak, a spokeswoman for Baxter International Inc., the
parent company which is based in Deerfield, Ill., said that her
organization sought the change only to assure its raw material
suppliers that they would be immune from lawsuits. She said that
Baxter, a global medical products and services corporation which
did $6.1 billion in sales in 1997, did not believe that the
amendment would affect it directly. Rather, she said, Baxter would
only benefit by being able to have a reliable supply of raw
materials from suppliers no longer afraid of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But Joan Claybrook, the president of Public Citizen, a
Washington-based consumer group which has lobbied against the bill,
said that the measure explicitly provides immunity not only for the
raw material suppliers but also for ``component parts'' which
Baxter itself manufactures.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Baxter lost a lawsuit in Illinois state court
in which it was ordered to pay $18 million to the family of a woman
who suffered severe brain damage because of a faulty intravenous
unit. Baxter supplied the faulty tube used in the intravenous unit
which allowed air to enter the woman's bloodstream which could fit
the definition of a ``component part'' in the bill making the
company immune from a similar lawsuit in the future. Baxter is
appealing the judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Lott's latest move to sneak into the bill a special
amendment for a major Mississippi corporation, adds to the pile of
special interests contained in this bill,'' Ms. Claybrook said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott spokesman John Czwartacki said, ``Protecting small
business from lawsuit abuse is what this bill is all about.'' He
said ``this provision allows the continued supply of raw materials
to those who manufacture critical health care devices by providing
some protection from out-of-control trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure was scheduled to be voted Thursday afternoon, but it
has become embroiled in all manner of extraneous politics. Sen.
John D. Rockefeller IV, W-Va., who has been its staunchest
supporter, Wednesday suggested the vote be postponed, an
acknowledgment that it would probably fail to win the 60 votes
needed to cut off a a filibuster or extended debate by its
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The current version of the bill is the product of a fragile
compromise between Senate Republicans, the White House and
Rockefeller who commands a crucial handful of Democratic votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
