<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-BRITISH-AIRW     07-08 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-BRITISH-AIRWAYS-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS PROPOSE LIMITS ON BRITISH AIRWAYS-AMERICAN PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than two years after American Airlines and British Airways
PLC announced an alliance that would dominate air traffic across
the Atlantic, European regulators proposed preliminary conditions
Wednesday that appeared to clear the the way for its approval.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the European Commission, which represents 15
countries, angered UAL Corp.'s United Airlines, Lufthansa and
Scandinavian Air System by proposing retroactive restrictions on
their alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's moves sharpened simmering tensions between the
European Commission and the Clinton administration as well as
between the commission and its own member states concerning
international aviation competition at a time when an increasing
number of the world's airlines have entered into cross-border
alliances that have received exemptions from U.S. antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The partnerships are seen as the only way for international
airlines to provide global service because of regulations that
limit the rights of carriers to operate outside their home
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's proposed conditions would require American, a
unit of the AMR Corp., and British Airways to give up rights to 267
weekly landings and takeoffs at London's two principal airports,
Heathrow and Gatwick, without receiving any compensation. They
would also require United, Lufthansa and SAS to give up 108 of
these so-called slots at airports in Frankfurt and Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the commission would also force the carriers to
reduce their flights for six months on certain routes that they now
dominate in order to give competitors a chance to establish
themselves. That proposal is directly at odds with the approach
taken by American regulators, who have already approved three
international alliances since 1993, including the
United-Lufthansa-SAS link.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at American and British Airways raised objections to
the commission proposals but said they were generally encouraged
because they were now convinced that their partnership, which has
been suspended in regulatory limbo since June 1996, would finally
move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very positive news,'' said Robert Ayling, the British
Airways chief executive. ``I am now more hopeful than I was before
that we will get a deal on acceptable terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at United reacted more harshly, accusing the
commission of using international airlines as pawns in a turf
battle with its member states. United filed a complaint with the
U.S. Transportation Department on Wednesday contending that the
commission's recommendations violated bilateral aviation treaties
between the United States and various European countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the commission is proposing to do is inject itself into a
bilateral process between sovereign nations,'' said Cyril Murphy,
United's vice president for international and regulatory affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The commission stressed that its recommendations were
preliminary. It will make a final decision following a month of
public comment on the proposals. After that, the antitrust
authorities in each European country will make the final
determinations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though it is not clear whether these competition officials are
obliged to accept the commission's recommendations, it appears
likely that they will. Karel van Miert, who announced Wednesday's
proposals and is head of the commission's competition directorate,
said that he was cooperating very closely with British regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Beckett, Britain's Secretary of State for Trade and
Industry, said Wednesday that she expected to approve the
American-British Airways alliance in the fall, but she also said
she would require the airlines to give up landing rights at
London's two airports.
</P>
<P>
   Several other hurdles remain. The alliance must also receive
approval from the U.S. Transportation Department, which has said it
will not give its blessing until a new, liberalized aviation treaty
is signed between the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and London now have one of the most restrictive
aviation treaties in the world. Only two American carriers _ United
and American _ are allowed to fly into Heathrow, which is the
busiest airport in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For years, British officials have stubbornly refused to
negotiate a more liberal, so-called open skies agreement. The
American-British Airways alliance has apparently given Washington
the leverage it needed to bring London to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   But as eager as other American carriers like Delta Air Lines,
Continental Airlines, U S Airways, and Trans World Airlines are to
get into Heathrow, they are also worried about being able to
compete with the American-British Airways alliance. Together, the
two airlines would control 58 percent of the flights between the
United States and London and 42 percent of the slots at Heathrow.
</P>
<P>
   In May, an advisory opinion presented to the Transportation
Department by the Justice Department's antitrust division
recommended that American and British Airways be forced to give up
336 weekly slots. Even then, the Justice Department study
concluded, there were still serious concerns that the alliance
would do more harm than good to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Several airlines, including Delta, Continental and the Virgin
Group P.L.C.'s Virgin Atlantic, criticized the commission's
proposals as being too weak. ``The proposed remedy will do little
to stop A.A. and B.A. from dominating trans-Atlantic service to
Heathrow,'' Scott Yohe, Delta's senior vice president for
government affairs, said.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines said they would lobby Washington strongly to
extract more concessions from American and British Airways. But
analysts said it was unlikely that the Transportation Department
would scuttle the alliance, because of its eagerness to reach an
open-skies accord with London.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has already reached open-skies agreements with 12
countries in Europe. The agreements upset van Miert because they
allow American carriers to fly freely to individual European
countries but do not allow European carriers to compete with each
other across the Atlantic. But European Union member states like
Britain and Germany have declined to give the commission the
authority to negotiate a Europe-wide aviation pact with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Van Miert said Wednesday that later this year the commission
would release proposed conditions on three other airline alliances
between Northwest Airlines and KLM Royal Dutch Airlines; Delta,
Swissair A.G., Sabena S.A., and Austrian Airlines, and Air France
and Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy of United said that the commission was deliberately
violating Washington's open-skies treaties in order to force
European governments to give it the negotiating authority it seeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
