</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIANS VISIT U.S. SEEKING HELP WITH DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Indonesia economy worsens, government
officials embarked Wednesday on a campaign aimed at persuading
international lenders to repackage up to $9 billion of debt.
</P>
<P>
   An International Monetary Fund official said he was confident
that the fund would release about $1 billion in aid to the country
next week, but it is uncertain whether other lenders and investors
will display the same faith in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is in worse condition than it was in April,'' said
Finance Minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita, after meeting with bankers
in New York on Wednesday. ``Our main concern now is to stabilize
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginandjar said Indonesia planned to keep interest rates high to
combat inflation and would allow the country's weakest banks to
fail as resources were concentrated on a handful of strong banks.
He said Indonesia would also continue to liberalize its social
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesia has been portrayed as an outcast country because of
our legal system and human rights issues,'' Ginandjar said. ``We
are embarking on a new era that we hope will cause the Western
people and the Western media to look more favorably on us.''
</P>
<P>
   These are dire times for Indonesia. The damage wrought by the
collapse of Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, has been so severe
that a senior World Bank official said Tuesday that Indonesia faced
an economic crisis unparalleled in the post-World War II era.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia expects its economy to contract about 13 percent this
year _ the first time the economy has shrunk since 1963.
Automobile, electronics and construction output slid in the first
half of the year, all of Indonesia's airlines are bankrupt and
roughly 80 percent of flights to the country have been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   In starker, more human terms, the World Bank forecasts that 50
million of Indonesia's 200 million people could fall below the
poverty line by the end of the year. Government officials
acknowledged a widespread concern about people dying from
starvation. A severe drought is causing added pain in various parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Although the World Bank said riots had disrupted food
distribution networks, Ginandjar said the government had a
``distribution system that is independent'' of routes disrupted by
riots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not the supply but the buying power,''
Ginandjar said, adding that the country had a program akin to food
stamps that it would use to support those unable to purchase food.
</P>
<P>
   Ginandjar was at Chase Manhattan Bank in New York to lobby
international lenders to reschedule a portion of about $64 billion
to $66 billion in debt owed by Indonesian corporations. The
lobbying effort will continue to Washington, and on to Frankfurt,
Paris, Tokyo, Seoul and Singapore, in the next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian government also has $54 billion to $55 billion in
debt, but that is not a subject of the current negotiations.
Ginandjar said there were ``no problems'' with the government debt
but that Indonesia remained open to various ways of restructuring
the debt by renegotiating the interest rate or other terms.
</P>
<P>
   While Indonesian ministers and advisers were upbeat about
repackaging the private-sector debt, they face a tough challenge
convincing lenders and investors that the country can overcome its
economic challenges. Investors have cooled to a similar debt
repackaging recently undertaken by South Korea, where the economy,
while troubled, is considered to have stronger prospects than
Indonesia's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wishes that things were better, but people are
realistic,'' said Mark Walker, a lawyer with the New York firm of
Cleary, Gottlieb, Steen &AMP; Hamilton, who is advising the Indonesian
government. ``I sense that people understand why this program and
why this proposal make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginandjar said Indonesia ``has a fair chance'' of getting the
battered rupiah, which has been trading recently in a range of
14,000 to 14,500 to the dollar, down to about 10,000 to the dollar
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   He also was optimistic that free elections would be held by
December 1999 and offered praise for the new government of
President B.J. Habibie, who has been struggling to assert his
authority despite calls for an early election.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ginandjar is considered an ambitious man with his own
designs on the Indonesian presidency, he said Habibie had ``done
quite a bit in eight weeks,'' citing Habibie's acceptance of labor
unions and the freeing of political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Ginandjar said elections should not be held any sooner than the
end of next year. ``To be fair to the new parties, we need to give
them time to organize,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
