</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGENTS-SLAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODIES OF SLAIN BORDER AGENTS HEAD HOME AFTER MELEE IN TEXAS TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ As the Rio Grande Valley grappled with a
killing spree that left five people dead, the body of a rookie U.S.
Border Patrol agent was escorted home to San Antonio Wednesday by a
motorcade of fellow law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   With emergency lights flashing and American flags flapping, a
procession of six patrol vehicles closed ranks around a hearse
carrying the body of Ricardo Salinas for the 220-mile journey to
San Antonio, where he is to be buried Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At a funeral home here, 15 uniformed Border Patrol agents
snapped to attention as six others loaded a blue-steel coffin into
the hearse.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas's body was dressed the same dress uniform the young man
wore when he graduated from the Border Patrol academy in January.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas, 24, and fellow agent Susan Rodriguez, 28, were killed
in a hail of automatic weapon fire Tuesday as they helped sheriff's
deputies track a suspect in a double murder near San Benito, south
of here.
</P>
<P>
   The fallen agents had responded to a call for help from the
Cameron County Sheriff's Department, said John Brinning, head of
the patrol's Harlingen station.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we accepted our badge, we agreed to not just protect our
borders, but back up other law enforcement agencies,'' Brinning
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may have thought this was a mundane job. This may
cause some people to choose a new vocation,'' said Brinning, who
estimated 50 percent of his officers have been on the job less than
a year.
</P>
<P>
   In the Border Patrol's 74 years, 81 agents have been killed in
the line of duty. Rodriguez was the first women agent slain in
action.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors were on hand at the patrol headquarters here
Wednesday, and many agents wore strips of black tape over their
badges in memory of the fallen officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real hard time for all of us; we've got to deal with
this in our own way,'' supervisor Douglas Spelman told agents at a
muster before sunrise. ``We must go on. They'd insist we go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas and Rodriguez, who was a training officer, had requested
that if they died in the line of duty that they be buried in their
dress uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Reed, regional director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service, which oversees the Border Patrol, said the
attack had prompted the agency to re-evaluate safety procedures at
the national level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to look at this from a training point of view. We
have to be vigilant about this. We cannot become complacent,'' Reed
said in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   There were no indications the agents had violated safety
regulations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Both agents died with their guns in their holsters, but
officials said they stood no chance when Ernest Moore, 25, walked
out of a cornfield and fired as many as 100 rounds from an
automatic weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Other deputies and agents returned fire, hitting Moore as many
as a dozen times. Moore, who was the son of a Harlingen police
officer and brother of a San Benito officer, later died of his
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron County Sheriff Omar Lucio has said Moore first killed
Margarita Flores, 52, and her daughter, Dalia Morin, 31, at their
home in Rio Hondo around 5 a.m. Tuesday. The sheriff said Moore was
in a jealous rage and hunting for his ex-girlfriend, who was
staying there but who hid during the shooting and was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Also wounded was Flores's son, Dan Morin, 22, who remained in
critical condition Wednesday at a hospital here.
</P>
<P>
   Moore fled the scene and was pursued by the police to a rural
area of San Benito. The Border Patrol agents responded to calls for
assistance from the officers who had chased Moore.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that Moore ambushed Susan Rodriguez and Salinas,
the sheriff and others said.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas was shot in the head and died instantly. Rodriguez was
hit in the neck and was airlifted to a local hospital where she
died.
</P>
<P>
   The two were working an 11 p.m. to 7 a.m. shift and could have
headed home instead of responding to the call for assistance,
officials said. Instead, they joined in the hunt for Moore and were
shot at 7:19 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Officers described a chaotic situation in which Moore was
mortally wounded and in which officers _ who thought at least two
other gunmen were with him _ tried to keep their heads down while
attempting to reach the two Border Patrol agents, Moore and Cameron
County Deputy Sheriff Raul Rodriguez, 32, who was critically
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they had no other suspects in the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Services will be held Friday in San Antonio for Salinas. A
funeral mass for Rodriguez will be here at Queen of Peace Catholic
Church, and burial will be in her native Tennessee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
