<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-DREAMWORKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEN DEAL MAY MAKE INVESTOR DREAMWORKS' TOP SHAREHOLDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ High-tech investor Paul Allen disclosed he has
boosted his investment in DreamWorks SKG in a deal that could make
him the biggest shareholder in the fledgling studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``DreamWorks has been a good investment to date,'' said Susan
Pierson, a spokeswoman for Allen's Vulcan Ventures who declined
Wednesday to offer specifics of the deal. ``This demonstrates his
faith in the company, the partners and the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks, founded by Hollywood moguls Steven Spielberg,
Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen in 1994, has achieved modest
returns so far from its movies, TV shows and music. Its best
results have come from co-financing ``Deep Impact'' with Paramount
and prospects look solid for its upcoming movies: ``Small
Soldiers,'' ``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Antz'' and ``Prince of
Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   The move by Allen, a co-founder of Microsoft Corp., is a major
vote of confidence for DreamWorks, according to analyst Kevin
Skislock of L.H. Friend, Weinress, Presson &AMP; Frankson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great opportunity for a long-term investment,''
he said. ``There's no question in my mind that DreamWorks will make
it and become one of the most successful studios early in the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Skislock cited Spielberg's track record (``Jaws,'' ``Raiders of
the Lost Ark,'' ``E.T.,'' ``Jurassic Park,'' ``Schindler's List'')
and Katzenberg's (``Beauty and the Beast,'' ``Aladdin,'' ``The Lion
King'') as the key reasons why DreamWorks will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that Steven has a phenomenal record in live-action
and Jeffrey is the main reason why Disney's formula for animation
worked so well,'' Skislock said.
</P>
<P>
   Pierson confirmed that Allen has increased his stake above the
original 18 percent, purchased in 1995 for $500 million, but gave
no details. However, South Korean conglomerate Cheil Jedang Corp.
has been widely reported as being willing to sell part of its 11
percent ownership, obtained in 1995 for $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, owner of the Portland Trailblazers basketball team and
backer of a variety of high-tech ventures, has been active in
DreamWorks and had said previously he wanted to boost his stake.
``If they'd sell me more, I'd buy it in an instant,'' he told
Business Week recently.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal, citing unnamed people familiar with the
deal, reported Wednesday that the deal calls for Allen to buy more
than half of Cheil's stake for $160 million, giving him a stake of
24 percent. The three founders continue to hold 22 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks, Hollywood's first new studio in 65 years, is
estimated to have spent about half of the $2.7 billion it raised in
debt and equity. It currently employs about 1,600 people and
recently opened an animation studio in suburban Glendale, modeled
after an Italian village. But its plans to build a studio campus in
Marina del Rey are several years behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks, in a move to take away thunder from Disney-Pixar's
computer-animated ``A Bug's Life,'' recently moved up the opening
date of ``Antz'' five months to Oct. 2. ``A Bug's Life'' arrives
seven weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very impressed that DreamWorks has that much confidence
and it shows that we're entering a new golden age of animation with
Disney and DreamWorks going toe-to-toe,'' Skislock said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
