<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-U.S.-305&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AWAITS NIGERIAN'S AUTOPSY RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NIGERIA.) 
(bl) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States said Wednesday that it would
await the results of the autopsy of the body of Nigeria's most
prominent political prisoner, Moshood K.O. Abiola, before it
considers resuming its high-level diplomatic efforts to bring
democracy to the country.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden death of Abiola, who was imprisoned in 1994 after
apparently winning the democratic presidential election the year
before, threw U.S. policy toward Nigeria into confusion and
generated debates among critics of the policy.
</P>
<P>
   It also overshadowed what State Department officials described
as an otherwise successful mission to Nigeria this week by a
delegation of senior U.S. diplomats who pressed the Nigerian junta
for democratic reforms and for the release of political prisoners,
especially Abiola.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that continued and high-level contacts can take
place, but I think we all need to wait and see how this autopsy
comes out,'' said Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering, who was
meeting with Abiola in a government guest house in Abuja, the
Nigerian capital, when he fell ill Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering, in a telephone interview from London, where he
stopped en route home to Washington, said Wednesday that he found
Nigeria's new leader, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, to be receptive to
U.S. demands for movement toward democratic civilian rule there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were receptive, particularly the head of state,''
Pickering said, referring to the general. ``He committed himself to
professionalize the military and get it back to its professional
role in Nigeria _ clear and direct code words for getting the
military out of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect they are going to release political prisoners,'' said
Pickering, a former ambassador to Nigeria. ``It was very clear to
me that they were prepared to release Abiola.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week the Nigerian government told Kofi Annan, secretary
general of the United Nations, that all political prisoners,
including Abiola, would be released.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said that he had been impressed by the willingness of
Nigerian officials to conduct an autopsy with outside doctors
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Nigerian government doctor in attendance who said
that everybody must insist on an autopsy,'' he said. ``I think this
autopsy will be done in a way that clearly protects the integrity
of the scientific process.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said that while the timing of the death was
extraordinary _ the U.S. diplomat traveled with Abiola to a nearby
hospital and watched as doctors tried to revive him _ the
60-year-old multimillionare businessman was known to be in poor
health after four years' of often brutal imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some record of hypertension,'' Pickering said. ``Both
of his legs were swollen and he showed them to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden death of Abiola prompted calls Wednesday from human
rights organizations, African scholars and others with an interest
in Nigeria for a reappraisal of U.S. policy toward the Nigerian
junta.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Carrington, who served as the U.S. ambassador to Nigeria
from 1993 until last fall, said in an interview that he believed
the Clinton administration ``has been generally tiptoeing around
too much'' and should have been tougher in threatening to impose
economic sanctions against the country's military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He said that while serving in Nigeria, he was repeatedly
rebuffed by the State Department when he recommended that the
United States consider freezing the assets of corrupt leaders of
the Nigerian army, who are believed to have stashed millions of
dollars in U.S. banks.
</P>
<P>
   He said the State Department's reluctance to offend the junta
had less to do with oil _ Nigeria is fifth-largest supplier of
petroleum to the United States _ than with an institutional mindset
in the State Department that ``we should try to get along with the
established leadership in Nigeria and everywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the default position for the State Department,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington, a lawyer who is now on a fellowship at Harvard
University, said that during his four years in Nigeria he had been
frustrated by the reluctance of the State Department to throw its
full support behind Abiola during his imprisonment, in part because
of long-standing rumors that Abiola was corrupt and somehow
involved in the narcotics trade.
</P>
<P>
   The department's attitude towards Abiola, he said, was
shortsighted because it failed to recognize how his years in prison
had changed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Abiola is that he underwent an epiphany once
he went into prison,'' he said. ``Nobody expected that he would
last more than a few months in prison. But he had opportunities to
come out and he turned them down. I think he grew substantially as
a real leader of the democratic movement.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, the civil rights leader who is President
Clinton's special envoy to Africa, said he was ``stunned and
saddened'' by the news of Abiola's death, and that the United
States needed to demand the presence of independent medical experts
at the autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he died arouses real suspicion,'' Jackson said.
``There are questions about whether his death was induced or
whether he was simply allowed to rot in prison. These questions are
unavoidable and should be addressed directly and frankly by the
Nigerian government. They subjected him to circumstances that were
increasingly inhumane.''
</P>
<P>
   While condemning the Nigerian junta for its treatment of Abiola
and other dissidents, Jackson said the United States would now have
to step up its campaign to bring democracy to Nigeria, or risk the
violent fragmentation of a nation of 110 million people that is
torn by tribal and regional rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we cannot take a hands-off policy and a wait-and-see
policy,'' he said. ``The sheer size of Nigeria is such that we
should not move too slowly right now. If the tension exploded
there, it could be even more devastating than Rwanda. This is a
very, very delicate moment for Nigeria, perhaps the most tense
moment since its independence.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Clinton, who pointedly did not stop in Nigeria
during a recent African tour, should now seriously consider a visit
to Nigeria to encourage democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, the president should visit Nigeria for the same
reasons he visited China _ visit not because it is democratic or
observes human rights, but because it doesn't,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
