<SLUG> BC-SEMTECH-LOSS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMTECH PROFITS TO PLUMMET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWBURY PARK, Calif. _ Semtech Corp. shares lost 28 percent of
their value Wednesday after the chip maker warned quarterly profits
will fall well below Wall Street's forecasts because of slack
demand.
</P>
<P>
   The stock fell 4 1/16 (one-sixteenth) to $10 3/8 (three-eights)
for its lowest close in more than 15 months. It has lost nearly
two-thirds of its value since Feb. 13, when it closed at $29 3/4
(three-fourths).
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Arun Veerappan at BancAmerica Robertson Stephens cut his
rating to ``long-term attractive'' from ``buy'' but C.B. Lee of
Sutro &AMP; Co. issued a ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Semtech, of Newbury Park in Ventura County northwest of Los
Angeles, announced late Tuesday that profit for its second quarter
ending Aug. 2 would fall 40 to 50 percent from first quarter
earnings of $4.7 million, or 30 cents a diluted share, due to slow
sales to personal-computer makers and to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Newbury Park-based company forecasted quarterly sales will
fall 15 percent from $29.5 million in the first quarter and plans
to take a $2.5 million pretax charge to reduce capacity and write
off assets.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with weak Asian demand have hurt most chip makers,
including leaders Intel and Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Semtech makes analog and mixed-signal chips used in the
communications, computer and test-equipment markets. It has not
disclosed if it will cut its worldwide work force of 540 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
