<HEADER>
A6417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT &LR;      07-08 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' MURAL IS PAINTED IN DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Yankees produced a handful of full-color snapshots for
history as they matched a 20th-century record by winning 61 of
their first 81 games. There was David Wells bounding off the mound
while watching the final out of his perfect game, Bernie Williams
launching an eighth-inning home run against Baltimore two days
later to cap a wild comeback, and the frightening fight that
erupted subsequently, the result of an ugly beanball incident.
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of the '98 Yankees, who will open the second half
of their season Thursday night in Tampa Bay, can be found in the
shadows of their mural, in moments often meaningless to victories
and defeats, moments that nonetheless have essential meaning and
illuminate the character of the team.
</P>
<P>
   On June 28, in the final game of their three-game interleague
series, the Yankees and the Mets were tied at 1-1 in the bottom of
the ninth inning. The Mets had runners at first and third and one
out and the pinch-hitter Luis Lopez at the plate, and the Yankees
were playing their infielders and outfielders far in, in an effort
to cut off the potential tying run. Lopez drove a high fly to
right-center; off the bat, it was apparent it would be deep enough
for the runner at third, Carlos Baerga, to tag up and score, too
deep for Paul O'Neill, the right fielder, to throw out Baerga at
home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielders in this situation routinely ignore the ball and
begin jogging back to the dugout, an accepted practice. O'Neill
charged back, tracking the fly. ``You don't want to take anything
for granted,'' he said later. ``You never know what might happen.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill caught the ball, whirled and fired back toward the
infield _ and it happened that the runner at first, Brian McRae,
hadn't bothered to tag up. Suddenly the relay went to first and the
umpires were saying it was a double play and that Baerga's run
didn't count and there would be a 10th inning. You never know what
might happen.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the umpires conferred and ruled correctly that
Baerga's run counted and the Mets had won. But O'Neill, at the end
of a brutal two-week schedule of tough opponents and travel, having
gone nearly two months without a day off, had thrown the game into
temporary chaos with his determination. O'Neill's attitude,
teammate David Cone said, is pervasive throughout the Yankees'
clubhouse: Don't concede anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all of us in here,'' said the reliever Mike Stanton,
``have played on winning teams at one time or another, and we know
what it takes. This is a team of a lot of good professionals, but
it's also a team with guys who love to play. O'Neill going back for
that ball, that's called playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball players will have days of diminished concentration, and
in this way they are no different than bakers or farmers or
warehouse workers. Some nights they overlook details; they might
not be fully focused on an at-bat or a pitch. But the Yankees are
rabid in their attention to detail, in their concentration, and
they have developed the best sort of peer pressure: all of them
must keep up with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's competition not just with the opponent, but in this
clubhouse, too,'' Stanton said. ``Nobody wants to make the last
out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez, the defector from Cuba who ascended to the
major leagues last month, is extremely well-liked and respected in
the clubhouse, where he blends in easily. On the mound, he is a
dictator, going so far as to tell Jorge Posada, his catcher, what
fingers to use to signal pitches _ a trivial matter to most, but
not to El Duque. ``He knows exactly what he wants to do,'' Posada
said, ``and he's going to do it his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has disagreed about pitch selection with Posada
numerous times, vehemently shaking his head at the signs, stepping
off the rubber, stepping back on, shaking his head some more.
Posada sometimes slams his glove down into the dirt, out of
frustration _ and Hernandez will explain to him later, Hey, I'll
pitch the way I want to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a crucial situation against Baltimore last Saturday,
Hernandez stepped behind the mound, ripped a few blades of grass
from the ground and lofted them into the air; he wanted to know
which way the wind was blowing. Details. You never know what might
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball-sized bruises dot Chuck Knoblauch's left side, from his
shoulder to his thigh. These are the places he has been hit by
pitches, 11 times this year, most in the American League. He crowds
home plate and won't step back, merely bowing when a fastball nears
his head. Even in a relatively poor offensive season for him,
Knoblauch is averaging 4.22 pitches per at-bat, second most in the
American League, according to STATS Inc.
</P>
<P>
   On May 3, the Yankees were putting the finishing touches on a
three-game sweep of Kansas City. Jeff Montgomery hit Scott Brosius
with a pitch leading off the ninth inning. When Homer Bush bounced
a grounder to second baseman Jose Offerman, a possible double-play
ball, Brosius torpedoed into second base to break up the double
play, obliterating shortstop Felix Martinez as Martinez tried
throwing to first. The Yankees led by 10-1 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The catchers, Posada and Joe Girardi, block balls in the dirt
even when there are not runners on base, to keep the play
instinctual, and practice the play daily. ``I've never seen that on
any team I've ever played on,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Some players mentioned outfielder Chad Curtis as possibly the
most intense Yankee, his signature play being his full somersault
as he throws home. ``He just goes into battle when the game
starts,'' Brosius said. Curtis has company. Cone is bright and
well-read and gregarious, and is utterly possessed when he pitches,
his face turning tomato red. Girardi will step out from behind home
plate sometimes to remind Cone of a flaw in his pitching mechanics,
and Cone will snap, ``I know,'' adding words and phrases Girardi
does not care to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Girardi said, ``he's so intense you're not sure
if your words are penetrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the Yankees came back from a three-run deficit in
the ninth inning, two outs and nobody on base, to beat
Philadelphia. Down to their final out, their at-bats were precise
in their purpose, Brosius noted. The Yankees are running away with
the division, they were playing a game that likely will have no
bearing on the standings, and they concentrated like it was
October. Derek Jeter lined a double, O'Neill patiently waited
through a walk, Martinez pounced on a mistake, for a game-tying
three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have a lot of guys who play the game the right way,''
Brosius said. ``Play hard, never assume anything. I don't think
there will be a letdown, because everybody on this team has a goal,
and we're not going to let up until we reach that goal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
