u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DISNEY-HNS &LR;      07-08 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DISNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS EDUCATION BOARD SET TO DUMP $43 MILLION IN DISNEY STOCK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trim, optional ending) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Denouncing some Disney movies as ``garbage,''
the State Board of Education is expected to vote Thursday and
Friday to dump the 406,000 shares that Texas public schools own in
Walt Disney Co. stock.
</P>
<P>
   Despite financial analysts' predictions that earnings per share
will continue to grow 18 percent annually over the next three to
five years, board Chairman Jack Christie, a Houston Republican,
said he think it's time to sell. And he thinks the votes are there
to require fund managers to sell off the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be a good investment in the future because of the
ownership of some of the films they have,'' he said, ``and ... I
think as the public sees that type of garbage, (the stock) will
lose some of its luster.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he cited ``Pulp Fiction,'' an Oscar-winning black
comedy that featured murder for hire, explicit drug use and
sadomasochism. The film was produced by Miramax Films, a Disney
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching that, I cannot be any part of investing children's
money into that type of promotion,'' Christie said.
</P>
<P>
   A vote to sell the stock, worth about $43 million earlier this
week, is seen by some as a win for social conservatives, who have
been waging a battle for more than a year to force the state to
sell Disney stock in protest of violent and sexually explicit
movies and records produced by Disney subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Any vote Thursday would be preliminary only, since the issue is
being raised first in committee. If approved there, it will come
before the entire 15-member board Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney stock represents a small portion of the $17.65
billion in the Permanent School Fund, but the Teacher Retirement
System and Texas Employee Retirement System own nearly 4 million
shares of Disney stock, worth an estimated $289 million. Action by
the Education Board would have no impact on any other state
investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   Christie said that a board vote to sell Disney holdings should
not hold any political repercussions for Gov. George W. Bush. Bush
was a paid director of Silver Screen Management Inc. for about 10
years. Silver Screen raised more than $1 billion to finance Disney
movies, including 21 R-rated movies, 32 PG and PG-13 flicks and 9
G-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Wednesday that the governor
continues to believe that investment decisions should be based on
sound investment principles and not on political ideology.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative American Family Association tried
unsuccessfully a year ago to get the state board to sell off Disney
holdings, citing violent and sexually explicit lyrics in some of
the songs produced by Disney subsidiaries. The group also has
boycotted Disney, though the boycotts seem to have had little if
any financial impact on the company.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Freedom Network, meanwhile, denounced Wednesday any
move to succumb to American Family Association pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic example of a special interest group trying
to make a political point at the expense of taxpayers,'' said Rick
Levy, a spokesman for the group, which was organized to fight the
influence of religious or social conservatives. ``It has nothing to
do with what's best for the schoolchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   The Permanent School Fund, the constitutionally created vehicle
for investment of public school money, has been investing in Disney
stock since July 1996. In the past two years, according to a Texas
Education Agency report, earnings and dividends have grown at
annualized rates of 12 percent and 21 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Christie said a vote to sell off holdings should not be viewed
as a boycott of the company that built its reputation on family
entertainment, adding that he will continue to take his children to
Disney World in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that when films desensitize life by people
blowing away people and explicitness and just senseless killing of
individuals, it's got to somehow encourage school-age children to
blow away each other,'' he said. ``And in good conscience, we can't
do that, and I hope that Disney realizes this also.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christie, who had resisted earlier attempts to force school
portfolio managers to sell off Disney holdings, said he changed his
mind two or three months ago after the conservative AFA provided
him a film clip with scenes from various R-rated films produced by
Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the movie clips Christie viewed were scenes from
``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking film excerpts I could not finish watching,''
Christie said. ``Let's just say the mildest of the film clips I saw
was `Pulp Fiction.' And it got worse from there. I didn't even
catch the titles of the others because there's no way on earth I
could sit through these films.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disney representatives did not return a call from the Houston
Chronicle, but a spokesman told The Associated Press he knew of no
other state investment fund considering divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   John Dreyer, Disney spokesman, added that Miramax is ``a
highbrow film label'' that has returned great value to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board member Randy Stevenson, a Republican and part of the
social conservative faction, said Texas should take the leadership
in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   He said that while a decision to divest the Permanent School
Fund of Disney stock ``may not have a direct financial impact upon
the Disney corporation itself, it is my hope that a strong, clear
message will be sent to Disney ... that we are concerned about the
way they are handling the public trust that this nation has in
their organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents and schools across this nation entrust their
children's eyes, ears and minds to Disney and perhaps such trust is
no longer deserved,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson said there is more to investing than financial
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``By investing in a company, we are indirectly supporting their
impact upon society,'' he said. ``I do not believe that we should
prostitute ourselves by investing only for monetary gain. We should
invest for the overall good of the schoolchildren of this state and
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie said he would have preferred to handle the decision to
sell the stock ``without much fanfare,'' but social conservatives
on the board insisted that it be brought to a public vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we could have worked out of these stocks very
easily without fanfare,'' he said. ``I'm hoping that even with the
fanfare it doesn't set a precedent, it doesn't set a trend (toward)
social investing or that we are screening NBC or ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want it to turn into that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
