<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves develop Wohlers Worry
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Bobby Cox's pen put down a steady rhythm as he tapped
it against the glass top, counting the days on the Atlanta Braves
schedule that covers his desk. Suddenly, the tapping stopped, just
when the reality began.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can't be right. It's been three weeks?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and Friday marks Week No. 4, since Mark Wohlers demoted
himself and made a bigger problem of the bullpen than the Braves
manager has faced in years, or at least since Juan Berenguer lived
here. The Braves resume the season's second half tonight with the
first of four games with the Florida Marlins and for all the things
that made the first half so exceptional _ at 59-29 the best start
ever, the 110-win pace _ Cox and his club are well familiar with
the qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   It's the bullpen. It needs some work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming Wohlers comes back, I like our bullpen because he
settles everybody down,'' said Tom Glavine. ``Even with that, I
think you can tweak it to improve it, probably by adding a veteran
lefty.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if Wohlers doesn't come back, you've got to do something.
And I don't know how long you wait to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves hadn't thought it would take this long. Said Cox,
``We told (Wohlers) 19 days, because then you don't lose your
pension time.'' But Wohlers just signed off this week for a longer
assignment. With the major league trading deadline approaching on
July 31, management has just over three weeks to assess their needs
along with Wohlers' future. Down in the clubhouse, the players wait
for the other shoe to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, everyone in the bullpen would like to know if there
is Plan B,'' said Kerry Ligtenberg. ``We're apparently not going to
get that information.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he was dealt from Cincinnati to Los Angeles last weekend,
some on the Braves staff were certain closer Jeff Shaw would be
coming to Atlanta. Reds GM Jim Bowden had the Dodgers' offer on his
desk for a week while continuing to leverage other clubs before
closing the deal, indicating the current demand for a quality
closer.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves would like to avoid that, if Wolhers can be salvaged
for the second half. Braves GM John Schuerholz, who said he has
been ``sort of non-plussed'' by Wohlers' early performances in
Richmond, has already run 11 relievers through the bullpen and
discarded four, not counting Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret to anyone that our closer's role is not being
filled by Mark Wohlers,'' Schuerholz said. ``We've got a bullpen
full of younger, inexperienced pitchers. We've got to look at that
area if we're keeping an eye on the total strength of the club. And
we have and we will.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no accounting for it but since Wohlers' last appearance
June 12, the bullpen has rebounded well, accumulating a 2.83 ERA in
41 1/3 innings with the veteran closer gone. But while it has rung
up 42 strikeouts in that period, the team has also blown two of
five save opportunities at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging as a new entity is right-hander Rudy Seanez, whose 12
strikeouts and 1.29 ERA are bullpen bests in Wohlers' absense.
Called up May 30 when the team designated (and subsequently lost)
Brian Edmondson, Seanez made just two appearances in his first 20
days with the Braves before settling into steady work in late June,
a situation ``that would have made me go nuts,'' if he did not have
previous major league experience in Cleveland and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves don't need another right-hander. They need
another left-hander in addition to John Rocker, preferably a
seasoned player Cox can use for late-inning match-ups. These
pitchers are in the shortest supply in the majors but here are two
candidates:
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Orosco, 41, Baltimore (1-1, 3.38): At $800,000, he's
affordable and even at his age, he is still a handful for
left-handed hitters. Lefties are hitting .233 against him. The
Orioles are evaluating who can be dispensed with as their wild card
hopes fade, which can make Orosco available.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Christiansen, 28, Pittsburgh (1-1, 1.69): Fully recovered
from 1996 shoulder surgery, he has arrived as a reliever with 40
strikeouts in 37 1/3 innings. Left-handers have nine hits against
him in 51 at-bats (.176) and he has allowed just five of 26
inherited runners to score. The emergence of Ricardo Rincon also
makes him expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring another closer, if necessary, is more ticklish and
will cost the club a prime prospect, as Denny Neagle did when the
Braves shipped Jason Schmidt to Piitsburgh for him. It could cost
the Braves a Kevin McGlinchy or Bruce Chen to acquire a quality
closer like Tampa Bay's Roberto Hernandez or Baltimore's Randy
Myers. If the Braves are feeling lucky, Cleveland's Jose Mesa just
lost the closer job to Mike Johnson and is waiting to be dealt or
released.
</P>
<P>
   But all debate returns to Wohlers. Closers are born, not made,
and it took him seven years just to make the Braves' opening day
roster. Maddux has watched Wohlers struggle with the role for going
on two seasons now and what has transpired on the mound is just as
difficult as what has transpired off it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're set up to fail,'' Greg Maddux said of the closer's job.
``You're pitching late in the game with a lead. If he gets them
out, well, he's supposed to. He's got no room for error. Any time
he gives up a run, it usually results in a loss or a blown save.
That's something that's hard to deal with. I know I wouldn't want
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
