<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: Florida Marlins
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight, Friday and Saturday at 7:05 p.m., Sunday at 4:35
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: TBS and 750-AM will broadcast all four games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight -- RHP John Smoltz (5-2,
3.84; 5-2 3.43 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. RHP Livan Hernandez (7-4,
4.20; 0-0, 2.16 lifetime vs. Braves). Friday -- LHP Denny Neagle
(9-6, 3.41; 4-4, 2.89 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. LHP Jesus Sanchez
(3-6, 4.67; 0-1, 6.75 lifetime vs. Braves). Saturday -- RHP Greg
Maddux (12-2, 1.54; 7-1, 2.07 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. RHP Ryan
Dempster (1-3, 6.43; 0-0, 3.00 lifetime vs. Braves). Sunday -- LHP
Tom Glavine (12-2, 2.63; 5-7, 3.57 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. RHP
Brian Meadows (6-6, 4.39; first appearance vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: The Braves lead the all-time series 37-28 but
have lost 16 of the last 28 games between the two clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Marlins lost two of three games in Atlanta on
June 16-18. The Braves out-hit Florida 23-18 in that series,
out-scored them 15-5 but could not pull off the sweep, as the
Marlins beat Glavine 3-2 in the third game.
</P>
<P>
   Marlins leaders: Avg. -- Edgar Renteria (.302); HR _ Cliff Floyd
(14); RBIs _ Floyd (57); SB _ Renteria (28). W _ Livan Hernandez
(7); ERA _ Matt Mantei (2.31). Strikeouts _ Hernandez (93). Saves _
Antonio Alfonseca (5).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Marlins have played some of their best baseball in
the last two weeks with five victories in their last seven games
and a 15-11 record dating back to June 8. They have won seven of
their last 11 home games and have gone 9-10 against the Eastern
Division. . . . Florida pitchers have yielded a 4.98 ERA and given
up 381 walks, or 4.4 per game, the most in the majors. That rate
last year was 2.5. Of the 21 pitchers who appeared for the Marlins
during their championship season, just four are currently on the
active roster (Livan Hernandez, Antonio Alfonseca, Felix Heredia
and Kirt Ojala). Rookies already have accounted for 64 Florida
starts this year. . . . Despite 12 errors, SS Edgar Renteria has
improved his play since winning the series, hitting a team-high
.302 with a team-high 33 multi-hit games. His 28 stolen bases are
third in the NL, but he has been caught a league-high 13 times. . .
. Tonight is a rematch of Game 3 of October's NLCS, when Hernandez
beat John Smoltz, 5-2. This season, Hernandez has given up 146 hits
(second in the league) and 17 home runs, tied for fourth in the NL.
But the Marlins get their money's worth from him. He has worked
past the seventh inning nine times in his 18 starts, and with some
staggering pitch-counts. He has thrown more than 130 pitches five
times already, including a 152-pitch complete game against Tampa
Bay on June 25 (a 5-1 victory)
</P>
<P>
   On the DL: INF Kevin Millar (broken left hamate), RHP Alex
Fernandez (rotator cuff surgery), EHP Eric Ludwig (broken right
arm) and RHP Rafael Medina (sore right shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: 3B Todd Zeile is hitting .301 with runners in scoring
position. Renteria has reached base in 44 of his last 48 games.
Todd Dunwoody is hitting .368 in his last 38 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
