</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-REPORTCARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' midseason report card
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How the Braves rank after a half-season .
</P>
<P>
   INFIELD: With three All-Stars, this may be the best infield the
Braves have put on the field. 3B Chipper Jones and 1B Andres
Galarraga comprise the strongest corners in the league, and SS Walt
Weiss is having a career year. 2B platoon of Keith Lockhart and
Tony Graffanino has hit a combined .234 since May 1. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   OUTFIELD: The defense, with four outfield errors, has been
superb, but offense has been inconsistent. CF Andruw Jones has hit
.291 since an awful April. RF Michael Tucker followed a .323 May
with a .256 June. Ryan Klesko, who has improved defensively, may
post career numbers. And Gerald Williams has been better than
advertised. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   STARTING ROTATION: Even by Braves standards, the first half
(49-20, 3.06 ERA) was something special. And that's with John
Smoltz working part-time. Greg Maddux is the Cy Young front-runner,
and Tom Glavine is right behind him. The league hit .246 against
them and struck out 460 times, once every 4.8 at-bats. Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   BULLPEN: It is a major vulnerability on a team that has few. The
struggles of Mark Wohlers have disrupted what was a thin relief
staff. While nine blown saves is tolerable (the 1995 championship
Braves blew 14 saves), the bullpen has allowed a whopping 271 base
runners in 198 2/3 innings. They'll need some help before they're
through.Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   BENCH: Braves' pinch-hitters batted .260 in the first half. The
additions of Gerald Williams and Ozzie Guillen provide depth for a
roster that appeared a little thin when spring camp broke. But the
bench doesn't have a weapon like Mike Devereaux proved to be in
1995, and Curtis Pride, the No. 1 left-handed bat in reserve, was
5-for-29 (.172). Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   MANAGER: Bobby Cox lost two of his favorite players (Mark Lemke,
Jeff Blauser), has watched his closer self-destruct and seen one of
his Cy Young guys' work-load cut in half. His DL includes an
appendectomy and a couple of torn shoulders. His roster includes
nine players who weren't here a year ago. For all that, his team is
on a pace to win 120 games. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
