<SLUG> BC-NICKLAUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nicklaus'major streak ends `on my own terms'
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Jack Nicklaus always has cringed at the thought of
being a ceremonial golfer. If he can't be competitive, he would
rather be elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to shoot a pair of 80s and wave to the crowd,''
Nicklaus once said.
</P>
<P>
   With his hip and groin hurting and his pride still intact,
Nicklaus, 58, officially pulled out of next week's British Open at
Royal Birkdale, ending at 154 his streak of professional majors for
which he had been eligible. Nicklaus also said he would not play in
the PGA Championship next month.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the incredible streak was the 1957 U.S. Open.
The end becomes the U.S. Open two weeks ago at the Olympic Club,
where Nicklaus, playing on a special exemption, made the cut and
tied for 43rd. In April, in an astounding performance, he tied for
sixth at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to end the streak by having it said that Jack
Nicklaus could no longer play the game,'' the winner of 18
professional majors and two U.S. Amateurs said in a statement
released Wednesday through his North Palm Beach, Fla., office.
``Instead, I wanted to step back with the feeling that the
competitive spirit and ability still thrived within me. I wanted to
end the streak on my own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus also said, ``After 42 years of playing major
championship golf, I feel that my ability to compete at the highest
level is marginal at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally regarded as the best ever to play the game, Nicklaus
won six Masters, four U.S. Opens, three British Opens and five
PGAs. He made the cut in 130 of the 154 pro majors, including 10 of
his last 12, and was a runner-up 19 times.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
