<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-HOLLYWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCH MADE IN HOLLYWOOD AS RAZZLE MEETS DAZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BROWN-RESIGN, BROWN-NEWHOUSE.) 
(jt) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Has Tina Brown finally gone Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   After years as the top editor of Vanity Fair and then The New
Yorker, during which both magazines paid extraordinary attention to
Hollywood moguls and stars, Ms. Brown has, in some ways, turned the
corner and become part of the world that she helped to create.
</P>
<P>
   In her new job, announced Wednesday by Harvey and Bob Weinstein,
co-chairmen of the Walt Disney Co.'s Miramax Films unit, Ms. Brown
will help form a media venture that will include a monthly magazine
designed to create material for Miramax films and television shows.
Ms. Brown will be joined by Ronald Galotti, vice president of
Advance Publications' Conde Nast unit and the publisher of Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She creates the most interesting magazines, finds the hottest
journalists and has her hand on the cultural Zeitgeist,'' Harvey
Weinstein said. He said that the movie material would be produced
by Miramax and that the television shows would most likely appear
on ABC, which Disney owns.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said details of the new venture remained vague and
that Ms. Brown and Galotti would spend about a year creating it.
Which writers will be hired _ will Ms. Brown raid her stable of
writers at The New Yorker? _ and how they will be paid if articles
turn into films or television programs have not been determined.
Ms. Brown's and Galotti's financial arrangements with Miramax were
undisclosed, though they will profit from a film, television show
or book that emerges out of a magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said that that they would would serve, for example, as
executive producers on any film that emerges out of a magazine and
that they would earn producing fees. ``What this is about is
creating a pipeline for ideas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown has in recent years developed a friendship with
Michael Eisner, the chairman of Disney, among other moguls. The New
Yorker held a conference in October, celebrating a magazine issue
about the future, at the Disney Institute in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a fantastic friendship with Michael _ and that
certainly was a plus,'' said Weinstein, who noted that two years
ago he began discussing with Eisner the notion of Miramax starting
a magazine that would feed into films, television and books.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the last two years, Tina would kid me about the
magazine,'' Weinstein said. It was only when he learned in the last
month that Ms. Brown's contract was up at The New Yorker that he
began having serious discussions with her about working as a
partner in the new venture, Weinstein said. He added that Ms. Brown
had been pursued by multimedia companies but declined to identify
them.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Brown, whose father was a film producer, has been
fascinated with Hollywood since she took over Vanity Fair in 1984,
the movie community has been even more fascinated with her. Unlike
any other magazine or newspaper editor, Ms. Brown has gone out of
her way to establish friendships with some of the most formidable
people in Hollywood: she is friendly with top executives like
Eisner, Barry Diller and Michael Ovitz, as well as the director
Steven Spielberg and Bert Fields, a top Hollywood lawyer. She has
even been fictionalized in ``The Horse Whisperer,'' in which the
actress Kristen Scott Thomas plays an English editor of a sleek
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Why Hollywood is so fascinated with Ms. Brown _ why she's
somehow perceived as a star _ has been attributed to several
factors. She is British and Oxford-educated in a town where a
surprising number of big players have never gone to college and are
dazzled and even intimidated by such credentials. She is powerful
in a town that respects power as much as money. And Ms. Brown
herself has, of course, contributed to her own Hollywood aura.
</P>
<P>
   Upon taking over Vanity Fair, Ms. Brown became the first
magazine editor to make Hollywood executives as celebrated as
stars. She ran often-flattering articles about their lives and
their feuds and published glossy photos of them. ``Tina allowed
herself to be educated by these guys, and they all thought, in
their own bizarre way, that they controlled her,'' said one movie
industry author, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``But the
reality is she controlled them. She had them in the palm of her
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown's power over Hollywood became evident in 1989 when, as
editor of Vanity Fair, she held a fund-raising event at the 20th
Century Fox lot for the Phoenix House, which operates drug
treatment centers nationwide. More than 700 people showed up,
including virtually every mogul and star in town.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Graham, a longtime colleague of Ms. Brown who has
worked for her as West Coast editor of Vanity Fair and now The New
Yorker, acknowledged that ``Tina has a certain magic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is not a Hollywood girl, and she was never going to be,''
Ms. Graham said. ``She's a distinctly English woman, a very smart
and successful Oxford graduate. She has many friends in Los
Angeles, she loves coming here, but what she's really about is
editing magazines and letting writers be extremely creative.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Ms. Brown has no plans to leave New York. She
and her husband, Harold Evans, the editorial director of Mortimer
Zuckerman's publications, recently moved to a new apartment in
Manhattan. The couple have two children, a son, George, and a
daughter, Isabel.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said that, like so many of his counterparts in
Hollywood and New York, he was dazzled by Ms. Brown. ``I've moved
from being a fan to a friend,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
