<SLUG> BC-NBC-DATELINE-JURY-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY FINDS NBC NEGLIGENT IN `DATELINE' REPORT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A jury in Maine on Wednesday found that ``Dateline NBC,'' the
television network's prime-time news program, was negligent in
misrepresenting a 1995 series about the trucking industry and
ordered the network to pay $525,000 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The federal case in Bangor did not center on whether the
two-part report was true. Instead, it focused on whether the NBC
journalists had misrepresented the focus of the story and how the
sources would be portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the lawsuit, Classic Carriers, based in
Waterville, Me., and one of its drivers accused NBC correspondent
Fred Francis and freelance producer Alan Handel of misleading them
about the theme of a segment on the trucking industry.
</P>
<P>
   The company's owners, Raymond and Kelly Veilleux, and the
driver, Peter Kennedy, said Francis and Handel conveyed that they
were working on a positive story. The two-part series instead
focused on safety violations by Kennedy and other truckers.
</P>
<P>
   NBC argued that it had promised only to report accurately as a
film crew joined Kennedy for a cross-country drive.
</P>
<P>
   In the program Kennedy referred to his driving log as a ``joke
book'' and admitted falsifying entries so he could drive for
periods longer than the law allows. At one point Kennedy drove from
Chicago to Boston without sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy argued that the program failed to reflect his views that
he could drive for long periods without impairing his driving
ability.
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating for four and a half hours on Tuesday and five
hours Wednesday, the jury said the network and the show had
committed negligence and misrepresentation and had inflicted
emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   Veilleux was awarded $300,000, Kennedy $175,000 and Ms. Veilleux
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press has no special protection under the laws of the
United States,'' the plaintiffs' lawyer, Bill Robitzek, told the
jury. ``They are not immune. They're not exempt. If they do
something wrong, they can be brought here and held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC, a unit of General Electric Co., stood by the report
Wednesday and tried to distance itself from the other media outlets
that have had public setbacks recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC News believes our story was presented accurately and
regrets that the jury came to a different conclusion,'' the network
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   With Wednesday's ruling, NBC joined the string of high-profile
media outlets that have dealt with professional lapses in the last
two months. Since May, The New Republic magazine, The Boston Globe
(which is owned by The New York Times Co.), The Cincinnati Enquirer
and Cable News Network have either renounced major reports or
discovered fabrications by staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately there will be those that try to lump this with
other stories about media missteps,'' Kassie Canter, an NBC
spokeswoman, said. ``This is very different.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Canter said NBC was weighing whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision was the second time in six years that
``Dateline NBC'' found trouble with trucks. In 1992, as part of a
segment on truck safety, the show broadcast footage of a General
Motors truck bursting into flame supposedly as a result of a
collision. It turned out that the program's producers had rigged
the truck to explode more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in recent years, ``Dateline NBC'' has been a big
success for the network, expanding to four hours a week last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, who runs NBC's entertainment division, said
recently: ``There is no show more important to us than `Dateline.'
I look on `Dateline' as a hit show in the same way I look on `E.R.'
as a hit show.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The jury's ruling raised concern in news media circles, where it
sparked fears that any person who was the subject of a critical
article or program could successfully sue for defamation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It often is the case that a source agrees to tell a story
perceiving somehow that the story will be a positive for them,''
said George Freeman, assistant general counsel of The New York
Times Co. ``But that's a far cry from a contract actually existing
where the deal is that you actually have to write a positive story,
which no self-respecting journalist would agree to.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
