u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-DAVIS-COX     07-08 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-DAVIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons can't wait much longer for Nathan Davis to develop
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Nathan Davis has had more than a year to get in
shape, and he's getting closer.
</P>
<P>
   But in the NFL, close sometimes isn't good enough, and the
Atlanta Falcons might reach a point soon where they can wait no
longer for the big defensive tackle to get his act together.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons selected Davis in the second round of the 1997 draft
with the 32nd overall pick and brought him to Suwanee thinking he
might play as a rookie. But Davis, who constantly battles weight
problems on his 6-foot-5, 300-pound frame, played in only two games
and was on the inactive list for 14.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Atlanta could afford to let Davis work on the
practice squad, because it made sense financially and the team
didn't need him. With starters Travis Hall and Dan Owens and
reserve Shane Dronett, Atlanta had one of the top defensive-tackle
rotations in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But Owens went to Detroit as a free agent, Dronett is expected
to start at right tackle, and the Falcons need help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the pads go on (in training camp, beginning July 23),
it's tough to judge the guys up front,'' said Rich Brooks,
assistant head coach and defensive coordinator. ``We need some guys
to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nate is still a big question. He's in better shape ... but
it's too early to tell much.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis didn't show much last year, arriving in Suwanee with
swelling in his pelvis after tearing a tendon as a senior at
Indiana. He never caught up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I was depressed a lot; I wasn't feeling good about
myself,'' he said. ``I went from being able to do whatever I
wanted, to sometimes not being able to get off the couch. That does
a lot to you mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just slept all the time and watched TV, re-runs of Jerry
Springer and cartoons like Fat Albert and Shazaam.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Davis' weight jumped to 330, 45 pounds more than his
playing weight at Indiana. ``Last year, Nathan had no chance,''
said defensive line coach Bill Kollar, who would like Davis at 295.
</P>
<P>
   Davis weighs 312 pounds and is in better shape, thanks to four
workouts a week in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone through the workouts, and he's been standing up at
the end of most of them,'' strength and conditioning coach Al
Miller said. ``That is winning the battle, though, not the war.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons need Davis, or somebody, if they hope to replicate
the success of last year's defensive front. Owens had 69 tackles
and eight sacks, Hall 107 tackles and 10.5 sacks and Dronett 40
tackles and four sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, seven-year veteran journeyman Esera Tuaolo (6-2, 296),
seventh-round draft choice Henry Slay (6-1, 290) of West Virginia
and free agent Mark Campbell (6-1, 293) are competing for two
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year, Davis won't have the salary cap working to his
benefit, and it will be cheaper for the Falcons to cut him than
keep him.
</P>
<P>
   His salary cap figure in 1997 was $508,700, but if he had been
waived and then claimed by another team, his entire $660,000
signing bonus would have counted against last year's cap.
</P>
<P>
   If he makes the team this summer, his cap number will be
$580,000; if he gets cut and claimed by another team, it will be
$440,000, or the remainder of his pro-rated signing bonus. If he
cleared waivers, the Falcons would have no cap charge.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he'll have to earn his spot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
