<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Free-agent pickup Louchieygunning for tackle spot
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When the Atlanta Falcons begin training camp two
weeks from today, the right-tackle position will draw the most
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Louchiey (pronounced LOU-chee), the Falcons' first
offseason free-agent acquisition, is working as No. 1 at the
position during the current mini-camp. Seventh-round draft choice
Ephraim Salaam is the backup. They're trying to replace Matt
Willig, who signed with Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Louchiey, now working under offensive line coach Art Shell, is
taking nothing for granted. Although he's 6-foot-8, 305 pounds,
he's not talking that way. Despite being drafted in the third round
by the Bills in 1994, Louchiey, a former South Carolina standout,
never got established in Buffalo, starting 13 games in four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just here to play, and contribute in whatever way
possible,'' said Louchiey, who grew up in Greenville, S.C. ``At
this point in my life, in my career, it's in my best interests to
adjust to whatever coach I have. I have to work on all parts of my
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Searching for pearls
</P>
<P>
   One of the undrafted college free agents in Suwanee is former
North Carolina receiver Octavus Barnes. The 6-2, 200-pounder set an
ACC record for freshmen with 609 yards in 1994, and he set a UNC
record with 970 yards on 53 catches as a sophomore. Barnes tore the
anterior cruciate ligament in UNC's final game that year, and his
last two years were solid but not spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I got a bad draw, (not getting drafted) because of
my knee,'' he said. ``Before that, I was one of the best receivers
in the country. I think I came back too soon, playing six months
after surgery. I'll show I can play, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has suffered another setback. When the team was off last
week, he went oyster hunting in North Carolina, and cut his feet on
sharp shells in an oyster bed. He was running gingerly Wednesday.
``I'm never going oyster hunting again,'' he said, ``and after
that, I'm never eating oysters.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-minute drill
</P>
<P>
   There were no notable injuries Wednesday, but defensive end
Chuck Smith is still fighting a strained back, and quarterback
Chris Chandler has a sore knee. ... Falcons general manager Harold
Richardson played the foil Wednesday on AM-790, when sports talk
co-hosts Nick Cellini and Chris Dimino ribbed him about the Falcons
signing 44-year-old quarterback Steve DeBerg. Cellini said it
``borders on the bizarre, borders on being a practical joke.''
Dimino asked Richardson if there was any truth to the rumor former
Falcon linebacker, Tommy Nobis, who retired in '76, was working
out. Richardson responded, ``He's out on the field, but I'm not
sure what that means.'' The GM said 17 years of NFL experience
gives DeBerg a big mental edge, but the preseason will show if he
still has what it takes physically. When Dimino asked if actors
Warren Beatty, who played a QB in ``Heaven Can Wait,'' or Mac
Davis, who played a QB in, ``North Dallas Forty,'' would be taking
snaps, Richardson said, ``We're open to that.'' ... Receiver Todd
Kinchen and reserve linemen Scott Adams and Adam Schreiber were
among the most impressive veterans in Tuesday's conditioning test _
while running the 40-yard dash 10 times, their times remained
consistently fast. Among rookies, linebacker Keith Brooking,
receiver Tim Dwight and cornerback Elijah Williams were tops. ...
Practice today will be at 10 a.m., and the team golf tournament
will be at Chateau Elan at 1:30. The early favorites: Chandler
among players and Dan Reeves and Bill Kollar among coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
