<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons sign German, last of this year's draft picks
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Former University of Miami receiver Jammi German
signed a three-year contract with the Falcons on Wednesday, making
Atlanta the first team in the league to sign all of its 1998 draft
class.
</P>
<P>
   German, a third-round draft choice, signed for $1,001,250, with
a signing bonus of $375,000.
</P>
<P>
   He was All-Big East in 1994 and 1995 but missed the next two
years, the first with injury and 1997 for giving false information
to the NCAA when it investigated Miami.
</P>
<P>
   German, who made all-conference as a return man the first time,
caught 33 passes for 391 yards that year. In 1995, he caught 41
passes for 730 yards (17.8 average) and three touchdowns. The
scouting report says German has inconsistent hands but runs good
routes, has better-than-average speed, is athletic and will fight
for the ball. He also is considered a good downfield blocker.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons remained at the NFL's limit of 80 under contract
after six-year veteran reserve guard/center Matt Elliott, 29,
failed his physical and was waived.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who signed with the Falcons on March 16 after playing
three years in Carolina, has an arthritic knee with bone-on-bone
contact in the joint.
</P>
<P>
   German was ecstatic Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been my motivation all along. Now I can help my mom
(Clare Douglas) get a house; she's still in an apartment,'' said
German, one of seven siblings. ``My brothers can have their own
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely happy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations on German's deal hit a snag last week after
first-round draft choice Keith Brooking signed a six-year, $7.925
million contract, leaving just $292,000 for German in the rookie
salary pool allotted by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   That number, which is the combination of German's first-year
salary and the pro-rated portion of his signing bonus, is a bit
below market value for a player drafted in the middle of the third
round.
</P>
<P>
   So German's agent, Alan Wade, asked for a bigger signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just looking forward,'' German said. ``As far as me not
playing the last two years, just being up here the last month (for
condititioning, passing camp and the current mini-camp), I'm
getting in great shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm back to where I was, and probably beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
