A6433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SELIG-COMMISSIONER-CO     07-08 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELIG-COMMISSIONER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Selig becomes commish today
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Braves player representative Tom Glavine said the
athletes won't stand in the way. Players association director Don
Fehr said it will be business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   When Major League Baseball changes the title of commissioner
from ``interim'' to ``permanent'' for Milwaukee Brewers owner Bud
Selig today, most baseball people think the impact on the game will
be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Selig has served as acting commissioner since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bud has done some good things for baseball,'' Glavine
said. ``Is it ideal for an owner to be a commissioner? No. But I
think Bud loves the game, and I would rather have someone like that
at the top who wants to do the job instead of someone forced in
there to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only major change involves Selig moving out of his office at
County Stadium and turning over the club to his daughter, Wendy.
Selig will commute from Milwaukee to the major-league office in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think him being named commissioner will change the way
we have conducted business the last couple of years,'' Fehr said.
``We now have an office to deal with on a daily basis. That's why
we don't treat this as an item of significant change.''
</P>
<P>
   The union will continue to deal with former Toronto Blue Jays
executive Paul Beeston, baseball's chief operating officer.
Beeston, who acts as a liaison between management and the union,
has developed a workable relationship with Fehr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the relationship now, while I won't say is healthy and
close, is certainly respectful and positive,'' Beeston said.
``Sometimes, people see Don as an omnipotent dictator. But he has
always been responsive to me. I wouldn't use the word 'delight' to
work with, but we certainly can be professional and work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig will continue to do what he does best, which is to bring
the owners to a consensus. The owners, with few exceptions, are
strongly in support of Selig. They were not going to take ``no''
for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes today are clearly higher than they've ever been,''
Selig said. ``You're better off trying to develop an understanding
in people, so when you get to a meeting, they understand the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Former commissioner Peter Ueberroth said Selig has done a good
job of navigating baseball through tough times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be recognized one day by the Hall of Fame for his
efforts,'' Ueberroth said.
</P>
<P>
   And Selig thinks he can get along with Fehr, a must-situation
for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human events tore us apart at times, but we've gotten along
for the most part,'' Selig said. ``We've reduced the acrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
