</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-DEDUCT-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. RULING WILL LIMIT MAJOR TAX DEDUCTIONS FOR CORPORATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to rulings in two cases handed down by U.S. Tax Court
last month, corporations may be about to lose some major tax
deductions.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with almost everything involving taxes, the
issues are complex. But they boil down to this: expenses that each
company considered part of doing business, and therefore
deductible, were ruled to be capital expenditures. That made them
nondeductible.
</P>
<P>
   If the Internal Revenue Service is aggressive in applying the
rulings to other businesses, as several tax specialists expect,
corporate tax bills could swell and corporate profits could shrink.
</P>
<P>
   The losers in tax court were FMR Corp., the Boston parent of the
giant Fidelity mutual fund concern, and PNC Bank Corp., the
Pittsburgh-based bank with $75 billion in assets. FMR and PNC are
each considering whether to appeal the rulings issued by Judge
Robert Ruwe in Washington. Such appeals would go to the U.S. Court
of Appeals in each company's area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both cases are resounding defeats for the taxpayer,'' said
Robert Willens, managing director in tax and accounting at Lehman
Brothers. ``This could be one of the most important things we've
seen in the last few decades. The possibility of disallowing a
whole host of expenses is staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue may be on the IRS radar screen, but at some companies
it has not yet registered. A spokesman for Liberty Financial Cos.,
which is one of the biggest publicly traded fund companies, said
this week that he was unfamiliar with the FMR case and could not
comment on the potential impact for his business.
</P>
<P>
   In the PNC case, the tax court ruled the expenses associated
with making home loans at two small banks that PNC had acquired
were nondeductible. Banks generally deduct these mortgage
origination fees from their tax bills, but the tax court ruled that
because these fees created ``a separate and distinct asset,'' they
should be capitalized or added to the bank's balance sheet in the
form of an asset.
</P>
<P>
   The Fidelity case was a bit different. It involved expenses
associated with starting new mutual funds in tax years 1985 through
1987. These costs included such things as research, legal and
regulatory fees and the preparation of offering documents.
</P>
<P>
   Neither case involved a significant amount of money. At issue
for Fidelity was approximately $750,000 in start-up costs for the
three years. At PNC Bank, the subsidiary's loan origination costs
were about $150,000. Because PNC's loans had a measurable life, it
could amortize the costs.
</P>
<P>
   This has the effect of extending the tax bite over the life of
the loans, reducing the impact a bit. But Fidelity could not
specify the life of its new funds. That means it will be forced to
eat the startup costs in the year they are incurred.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Fidelity and PNC say they fought the issue on
principle, not because of the money at stake. ``The potential,
far-reaching implications of this issue is why we challenged the
IRS on the matter,'' said Jessica Johnson, a Fidelity spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the rulings loom large over corporate America because
the expenses involved in Fidelity's case and PNC's case are not
arcane business costs. They are typical of the costs incurred by
companies to maintain their businesses and to expand their scope
and increase profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Baran, senior tax counsel of the American Bankers
Association in Washington, prepared a court brief in support of
PNC. ``It is unclear to what extent this would effect a bank's
earnings,'' he said in a recent interview. ``But when you can no
longer take a current deduction for making loans, it will have some
type of financial impact on a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the two recent rulings on financial services, the
IRS had begun to disallow deductions in some other industries. For
example, airlines are complaining that they are being told to
capitalize the cost of repairing planes instead of deducting them,
as has been accepted practice. Other areas of dispute involve
certain costs by cellular phone companies to attract new customers
and by other manufacturers to get their products on a retailer's
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   What does it add up to? An effort by the IRS to make companies
capitalize costs that they have historically deducted. The result,
said Irving Salem, a partner at the law firm of Latham &AMP; Watkins in
New York, would be a ``hemorrhage of fashionable, new
capitalization issues with no foreseeable end in sight.'' Salem
knows what he is talking about. In the mid-1960s, he was the
technical assistant to the chief counsel of the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   In distinguishing between expenses that are deductible and those
that must be capitalized, the IRS is relying on a 1992 Supreme
Court decision known as ``Indopco'' in which the court required the
capitalization of the costs of a friendly merger between National
Starch and Chemical Corp., which later changed its name to Indopco
Inc., and Unilever. Because the combination changed the corporate
structure of the entities and promised long-term benefits, the
court ruled that the costs should be capitalized, not expensed.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Supreme Court did not define exactly which costs
must be capitalized, some tax practitioners say the IRS is using
Indopco as an excuse to review many areas. Because it takes so long
for issues to wend through the courts, the six-year-old ruling is
only being played out in a broad way now.
</P>
<P>
   Under section 162 of the tax code, ``ordinary and necessary
business expenses'' are deductible from a company's income tax
bill. What does ordinary mean? Don't think typical or normal, says
the IRS. Citing ``Indopco,'' the IRS says ordinary business
expenses are those not considered capital expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   This fuzzy definition of what is ``ordinary'' leaves room for
interpretation by companies and the IRS. ``It's a `know it when you
see it' kind of concept,'' Salem said.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, companies have felt safe deducting
expenses that they incurred year-in, year-out.
</P>
<P>
   The PNC case changes all that, because loan origination costs
are routine. Adrian Fenton, director of taxes at PNC Bank, said,
``The much broader issue for corporate America is how far will the
IRS go?''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the IRS says that neither the FMR nor the PNC case
is a step in a new direction. A spokesman said that it was not
planning a blanket effort to capitalize every cost in the mutual
fund industry. But he added that if other mutual funds have similar
costs to Fidelity's in creating new funds, they will be examined by
field agents.
</P>
<P>
   Salem countered that the FMR case moves well beyond old law
because the judge ruled that FMR's costs of expanding its business
_ bringing out new funds _ should be capitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were expanding your business, it was an expense,'' said
Salem of past procedures. ``There was recognition of that in the
government's brief in Indopco. Everybody thought that expansion was
golden, but this court didn't buy that.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the IRS find expenses to capitalize beyond those at banks
and mutual funds? You bet. After all, corporations large and small
in all industries incur costs that will produce significant
long-term benefits. The IRS official said that to the extent those
costs were identified by its agents and were found to be related to
significant long-term benefits and/or a separate and distinct
asset, it would take the position that they should be capitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Indopco ruling, the IRS has begun requiring that the
airline industry capitalize aircraft and engine maintenance costs.
Over the last two years, the airlines have tried to resolve the
issue in talks with the IRS and the Treasury Department. So far
they have been unsuccessful. Southwest Airlines asked the tax court
this spring to rule on the issue. The case has not yet been heard.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over what should be capitalized is so large and so
fuzzy that it is almost impossible to assess what is at stake for
corporate America. Some rough estimates can be made for the mutual
fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lipper Analytical Services, 3,300 entirely new
funds have been established over the last five years, at what an
industry consultant estimated was startup costs of $20,000 to
$100,000 each. Taking the midrange, $50,000, the costs that may now
be neither deductible nor amortizable could reach $165 million. Not
backbreaking to a multibillion-dollar industry, but not peanuts
either. Assuming a corporate tax rate of 35 percent, that means a
$58 million increase in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A greater concern to Willens is how the IRS will treat the
expenses of expanding a business. ``The FMR case gives the IRS
carte blanche to go after a whole world of startup costs,'' he
said. This would apply to any company opening new outlets. Think
Starbucks, think McDonald's, think Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   And requiring that cellular phone companies capitalize the
expenses of getting customers on their books has implications for
other industries as well. Why couldn't the IRS ask the same of
Internet providers such as America Online? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
