<HEADLINE>
FOR FRANCE, IT'S THE INCREDIBLE DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There hasn't been a night like this here since the
Liberation. Thousands of cheering, singing, dancing people in front
of the ancient Hotel de Ville. Strangers hugging strangers. Flares
burning, firecrackers popping. The bleu-blanc-rouge tricolor
flapping from car windows, draped around shoulders, painted on
faces, sprayed onto hair. Spontaneous celebrations from Pigalle to
the Pantheon. Horns honking until three in the morning along the
Champs Elysees, the Boul' Mich, the quais along the Seine.
</P>
<P>
   After 68 years, Les Bleus _ France's beloved but ill-starred
soccer team _ will be playing for the World Cup title against
champion Brazil come Sunday. Incroyable, n'est-ce pas?
</P>
<P>
   ``La France en finale,'' teenager Sebastien Duchange exulted
after the host country had come from behind to beat Croatia, 2-1,
at the Stade de France just north of town, finishing the match with
only 10 men on the field. ``C'est top.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, as the sporting daily L'Equipe had proclaimed Wednesday
morning, ``le reve du siecle'' _ the dream of the century. France
has been playing in this quadrennial festival of feet since 1930
and never reached the final. But ever since Laurent ``Lolo'' Blanc
defeated Paraguay with his ``La Delivrance'' goal in overtime a
week ago Sunday, Les Bleus have been touched by stardust.
</P>
<P>
   They play 120 scoreless minutes against Italy and win on penalty
kicks when an Italian shot clangs off the crossbar. They're
resigned to losing to the Germans in the semifinals, as they always
do _ but the Germans lose to the Croats. ``The Germans always
win,'' businessman Irvin Rosenberg was saying. ``Always, always.
But this time, they don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the pessimism that has always enshrouded the national
team lifted. Suddenly, a country that has always taken its soccer
with insouciance developed an amour fou, a mad love, for Les Bleus.
``I never thought I would see people with their faces painted blue,
white, and red in the stadiums,'' said captain Didier Deschamps.
</P>
<P>
   Every brasserie and bistro on either side of the Seine had a
television tuned to last night's match. Le Lutece, on the Boulevard
Saint Michel, was packed from door to door with a bouncer shaking
his head on the sidewalk. And the square in front of the Hotel de
Ville was jammed with thousands of people craning their necks to
watch the match on a huge color screen. Urchins hung from
streetlamps, teenagers wore blue team jerseys with Zinedine
Zidane's name and number 10 on the back, adults sported oversized
tricolored fool's caps with jingling bells.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone chanted ``Allez les Bleus'' _ and gasped when Croatia,
which wasn't even a country the last time France played in the Cup
in 1986, scored a shocking goal less than a minute into the second
half. Then Lilian Thuram drew France even and a roar exploded
simultaneously from sidewalk cafes, from open apartment windows,
from moving cars, from the bridges connecting the Left and Right
banks.
</P>
<P>
   The ``blue hour,'' that enchanted Parisian time between sunset
and darkness, came and went. An enormous full moon appeared over
the Seine and streetlights came on. Thuram scored again and now the
city held its breath and crossed its fingers, especially after
Blanc was ejected for whacking a Croat in the face and Les Bleus
had to play a man short for the rest of the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barthez, Barthez,'' the crowd at the Hotel de Ville kept
chanting, whenever the black-garbed French keeper with the shaved
head and goatee plucked another ball out of the air.
</P>
<P>
   Le reve du siecle was minutes away now. Whenever Spanish referee
Jose Manuel Garcia Aranda looked at his watch and decided to let
play go on, there were impatient groans and derisive whistles. And
then it was done _ and the City of Light rocked with a thunderclap
of joy and relief and disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   The boulevards were immediately jammed with people running
between and around and climbing atop cars. Thousands of flags
appeared from nowhere. Hundreds of celebrants gathered on the Ile
de La Cite, at the Arc de Triomphe, in the Latin Quarter, at the
Opera, at every intersection in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Up in Montparnasse, where the streets outside the train station
were still throbbing after midnight, Irvin Rosenberg and his wife
came down from their apartment and joined the party. ``It is
impossible to sleep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dream had shaken everyone awake. Les Bleus en finale?
Absolument. Down by Notre Dame cathedral, an elderly beggar
approached a foreigner. ``Vive la France,'' he declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
