<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY RULER APPEALS FOR CALM FOLLOWING DEATH OF OPPOSITION
LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Nigeria's military ruler appealed for restraint
on Wednesday after the sudden death of the detained opposition
leader, Moshood K.O. Abiola.
</P>
<P>
   But the country appeared poised on a knife-edge as American and
other Western doctors prepared to travel here to perform an autopsy
on Abiola.
</P>
<P>
   The streets of Lagos were quiet Wednesday night, eerily deserted
as people stayed home out of fear. However, debris and smashed
glass littering several streets testified to the sporadic rioting
here and in other cities that has left at least 19 people dead
since Abiola died and underscored the explosive resonance of his
name.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the nation in a medal-bedecked military uniform, Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar, the country's recently installed leader,
promised a fair autopsy for Abiola and said that his release from
prison had been due to be decided on Wednesday. ``Alas,`' he said,
``God willed otherwise and today we mourn his loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar spoke of the ``restoration of democracy'' in Africa's
most populous nation as an ``imperative,'' but avoided spelling out
any plans as to how this should be achieved. He also dissolved a
military-appointed government _ a gesture that appears unlikely to
have any immediate impact _ as the core of power lies with the
inner circle of military men gathered in the provisional ruling
council.
</P>
<P>
   Although the general's speech was full of compassion for Abiola,
he placed the opposition leader's death on the same level as that a
month ago of the dictator Gen. Sani Abacha, describing both as a
``national tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, who appeared to be poised to win the 1993 presidential
election before the military annulled it, and was imprisoned on
charges of treason in 1994, died Tuesday after falling ill during a
meeting with U.S. and Nigerian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian authorities have attributed his death to ``cardiac
arrest,'' but members of Abiola's family have suggested he may have
been poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said on Wednesday that two American
military physicians will be sent to Nigeria to help perform an
autopsy. The chief coroner of the Canadian province of Ontario, Dr.
James Young, will also be present, along with a British expert. At
the specific request of the Abiola family, Dr. John Pless, a
pathologist at the University of Indiana, is being sent by
Physicians for Human Rights, a Boston-based group.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear when the autopsy would be
performed. The burial of Abiola, who converted to Islam many years
ago, would normally have taken place at once, but a delay of
perhaps as much as two or three more days now seems likely.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said on Wednesday
that the United States had no evidence that Abiola had ``died of
anything other than natural causes.'' But he added that, given the
suspicions of the family, it was ``a good idea to have a
post-mortem conducted in a way that is as independently, reliably,
conducted as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubts are swirling here, prompted by the extraordinary timing
of Abiola's death, and it seems certain that until the results of
the autopsy are known the situation will remain highly volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, with the door now half opened to a democratic
transition and the eventual course of this shift still vague, a
quick return to the calm called for on Wednesday by Abubakar may be
elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You who killed Abiola will pay for what you have done,'' mobs
shouted as they moved through the streets here early on Wednesday,
before being disbanded by police units that fired shots in the air.
By the afternoon, this city of eight million people was largely
calm.
</P>
<P>
   City authorities said at least 10 people had been killed in
Lagos, and some of the violence appeared shaded by old ethnic
rivalries, with Yorubas from Nigeria's southwest attacking Hausas
from the north.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim Hausas and Fulanis constitute a majority in the military
government and the armed forces while a significant part of
Abiola's following came from members of the Yoruba tribe in the
southwestern part of Nigeria. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
