<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI DEFENDS 11-MONTH STEWARDSHIP OF STATE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Has Acting Governor Paul Cellucci finally left the Rose
Garden?
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly frustrated by weeks of bad publicity, Cellucci
Wednesday stoutly defended his 11 months in office, contending that
he has kept the state's economy humming and insisted on high
educational standards.
</P>
<P>
   The animated defense of his administration marked a departure
from a more constrained style, in which Cellucci has tended to
ignore criticism and sidestep controversy while stressing consensus
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his failure to win passage of key initiatives from
the state Legislature, Cellucci insisted that he has done well,
even though most of his agenda remains stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said last July that the principal task in front of me was to
keep the economy of Massachusetts in high gear, and I don't think
anyone can argue, a year later, that the economy of Massachusetts
is not in high gear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed annoyed by campaign criticism from the other
gubernatorial candidates. On many issues, Republican rival Joseph
D. Malone hits Cellucci from the right and the three Democratic
hopefuls attack from the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a political year, I have a bunch of back-seat drivers,
these four candidates for governor, who if I go right, they say,
`He should have gone left,''' Cellucci said. ``I think we ought to
focus on results.''
</P>
<P>
   One result of his leadership, Cellucci said, was that the state
Board of Education last week reversed an earlier decision and voted
to insist on a higher passing standard for prospective teachers on
the state's new certification test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote last week to put those high standards back in place
sent a clear message to every city, every town, and every school
district in this state that we are going to hold the line on
standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he decided to push for higher test standards only after
first accepting the Board of Education's decision to lower the
passing grade, causing some observers to charge that he bungled the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Several political and economic analysts Wednesday cautioned
that, despite Cellucci's claims of success, a governor's ability to
affect his state's economy is quite limited and that the
Massachusetts economy actually has not performed particularly well
compared to other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the budget management and the business climate today
in Massachusetts is better than it was a decade ago, but one should
have some humility about the effect any political figure or
officeholder can have on the state of the economy,'' said Robert
Woodbury, director of the McCormack Institute at the University of
Massachusetts-Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The major variable determining the health of any state economy,
Woodbury said, ``is the state of the national economy and even the
global economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, however, insisted that Massachusetts is outperforming
the national economy and that his efforts had helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought the economy of this state back,'' he said. ``We've
gone from 3 percent above the national unemployment rate back in
1991. We're almost a full point below the national unemployment
rate.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the Economic Policy Institute, a Washington-based
economic think tank, economist Jared Bernstein said the
Massachusetts recovery has not been extraordinary compared to that
in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really isn't that much to crow about in Massachusetts
over the longer run,'' Bernstein said. ``Job growth is flat, family
income at least through 1996 has fallen, and wage growth has been
negative for the typical worker through 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Bernstein said his research showed that
Massachusetts had about 3.1 million jobs in 1997, the same overall
level as 1989, which means the state hasn't experienced real job
growth during that period.
</P>
<P>
   From 1989 through 1996, median income for a family of four
actually declined (in real dollar terms), from $65,542 to $62,385.
Meanwhile, the median hourly wage fell from $13.12 in 1989 to
$12.64 in 1997 (again, in real dollar terms), the economist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy certainly doesn't look like the 1980s, when wages
and income and jobs were growing at a decent clip in
Massachusetts,'' Bernstein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
