u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-RAPE-TRIBUNAL-675&AMP;     07-08 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-RAPE-TRIBUNAL-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECLARING RAPE A WAR CRIME IS STALLED BY SEMANTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ A dispute between women's groups and the Vatican over a
legal term has broadened into a battle of religion and gender
politics that could jeopardize agreement on whether rape will be
declared a war crime by an international criminal court.
</P>
<P>
   There is wide consensus at a U.N. conference that rape is a war
crime that should be prosecuted by an international tribunal.
Women's groups have fought to have a treaty include ``enforced
pregnancy'' as a war crime, for the act of impregnating women and
forcing them to bear children as tools of ethnic reprisal, as in
the case of forcing Croatian women to have Serbian babies.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican agrees that such rapes are war crimes, but is
troubled by the term ``enforced pregnancy,'' fearing it could be
broadly interpreted as an invitation to challenge anti-abortion
laws in many countries.
</P>
<P>
   And that dispute has polarized many of the 159 delegations that
have only days left to negotiate rules for a permanent tribunal to
prosecute war crimes and crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The battle has become one of the most glaring and painful
examples of just how contentious and intractable the process of
negotiating a treaty on war crimes is.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of enforced pregnancy is marginal next to the more
fundamental questions about the court's jurisdiction and authority.
But it is one of many seemingly secondary issues that could thwart
a consensus. ``Everybody is consumed by whether the big five issues
can be resolved,'' said one member of a Western delegation who
asked not to be named. ``But we are forgetting that items 6 through
30 could just as easily throw a wrench into a successful
negotiation of the treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   There is universal support at the conference for the principle
that individuals who commit genocide or other atrocities should be
held accountable. But as they negotiate the details, delegates
remain deeply divided over some of the most fundamental issues of
the court's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Countries as closely allied as Canada and the United States are
battling over how powerful and independent an international
prosecutor should be. The United States, which fears that American
peacekeeping troops could be dragged before international judges on
frivolous charges, wants to limit the prosecutor's power to
initiate cases.
</P>
<P>
   Canada and some 50 other countries known as the ``like-minded
group'' insist that unless the prosecutor has broad authority to
bring charges independently, the court will be toothless. Many
third-world countries worry that their sovereignty could be
undermined by an independent prosecutor _ or one who is called in
on a case by the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, one of the articles that seemed most assured of being
included in the treaty _ making rape and other acts of violence
against women war crimes on the same footing as torture _ is now
under heated debate.
</P>
<P>
   Some delegates worry that the battle over the wording of
``enforced pregnancy'' could deadlock the negotiations and sharply
limit the kinds of crimes against women that the prosecutor could
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``By including this term, you create a mandate for a prosecutor
to investigate this particular crime,'' said Katherine Hall
Martinez, a member of the Women's Caucus for Gender Justice in the
International Criminal Court, a nongovernmental organization
lobbying the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only seven working days left,'' she said, and rape
and the entire list of crimes against women that appeared in the
draft treaty were deleted from a discussion paper submitted to the
delegations on Tuesday and were described as being ``under
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The deletion was meant to jump-start negotiations on the court's
jurisdiction. The draft treaty, which was crafted at a preparatory
meeting, included ``enforced pregnancy'' along with ``rape, sexual
slavery, enforced prostitution, enforced sterilization.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Enforced pregnancy is a slightly confusing term crafted by
rights organizations to describe the act of repeatedly raping women
with the intention of making them pregnant with the seed of their
enemy. Such crimes occurred in Bosnia and Herzegovina, as well as
Rwanda. But the ad hoc tribunals investigating charges of
atrocities in the Balkans and Rwanda have not included enforced
pregnancy among the crimes. Even charges of rape in Bosnia were
formally filed in only one case _ under the insistence of women's
groups and human-rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican, as well as many Islamic countries and American
anti-abortion rights lobby groups, agrees that such kinds of rape
are war crimes, but complain that enforced pregnancy is too general
a term, and that it could be used to challenge countries that have
anti-abortion laws on their books.
</P>
<P>
   No Vatican representative was willing to comment on the debate
Wednesday. One member of the Holy See's delegation, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said, ``We are deeply sensitive to this
issue. We have nuns and brothers who go to these war-torn areas to
heal the victims and end up becoming victims themselves. But we
have a juridical problem with the term.'' He added, ``States which
have legislation protecting right to life could end up being
charged with enforced pregnancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's groups insist that the issue is entirely separate from
the dispute over abortion rights. But it is a measure of how deep
the ideological rift is that each side suspects the other of hidden
motives. ``We are basically reliving the attack on the women's
platform at Beijing,'' said Rhonda Copelon, director of the legal
secretariat of the International Women's Caucus, referring to the
1995 United Nations conference on women.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Copelon and other representatives of nongovernmental
organizations said they detected signs at the conference of
backsliding on a variety of gender issues. Members of the Women's
Caucus said their efforts to have a meeting with the Holy See
delegation were rebuffed. Ms. Copelon said that omitting mention of
enforced pregnancy from the list of war crimes against women was
unacceptable. ``It denies a very grave crime for purely political
reasons,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand is one of several countries that strongly supported
the inclusion of enforced pregnancy as a war crime, and are now
working behind the scenes to seek a compromise to keep it _ and the
entire article _ in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is one we are very concerned about _ with very good
reason if you look at what has happened in Bosnia,'' said Donald
Mackay, a New Zealand delegate to the conference who is Under
Secretary of Foreign Affairs. Noting that the issue had been caught
up in some ``theological aspects,'' Mackay said, ``We have been
engaged in a lot of discussions to find ways to define the term in
a way that will preserve the concept, and not give way on the
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has divided even members of the same delegation. One
lawyer who is a delegate from a Latin American country said her
government had yielded to pressure from the Catholic Church to
oppose the enforced pregnancy article. ``Personally, I strongly
disagree,'' she said. ``But I cannot speak for myself on this
issue. I have to uphold my government's position.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
