<SLUG> BC-DIVESTING-DISNEY-TEX </SLUG>
 
Texas EDUCATION BOARD MAY DUMP DISNEY STOCK 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS SANCHEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The State Board of Education will vote to shed the
Permanent School Fund's 406,000 shares of Walt Disney Co. stock in
response to a growing national protest against the media giant, the
board chairman predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By divesting itself of Disney stock, valued at $43 million at
market close Wednesday, the state board would become the first
governmental entity in the country to divest stock as a result of
the year-old Disney boycott, said David Miller, an official with
American Family Association, one of many religious and conservative
groups pressing for a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   ``For months I've been wanting to divest,'' Board Chairman Jack
Christie said. ``Not as a boycott of Disney, but just as a strong
message: We're not interested in promoting the horrendous films put
out by Miramax,'' a Disney subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Christie, a Republican, has often opposed a minority faction of
social conservatives on the board. By teaming with the
conservatives, Christie is expected to swing Democrats with him to
win the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Disney spokesman John Dreyer told The Associated Press he knows
of no other state investment fund considering divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have returned great value to our shareholders. We continue
to return great value to our shareholders,'' he said. ``I would
hope that the board would be consistent in its entire portfolio for
its criteria for owning stock.''
</P>
<P>
   State board member Will Davis of Austin agreed, saying it is not
a bad idea to make investment decisions based on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do so based on financial merit,'' he said.
``That's the only test.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is the chairman of the Committee on School Finance, which
is scheduled to take up the Disney divestiture issue Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If the finance committee recommends divestiture, the full board
will take a final vote on the issue later in the day. If the motion
to divest is rejected, the full board does not have to take it up.
.MDNM/ One of the primary responsibilities of the 15-member board
is to oversee the investments of the $17 billion Permanent School
Fund, which is projected to earn more than $1.3 billion during the
current two-year budget cycle. The money helps fund public
education.
</P>
<P>
   Board member David Bradley, a social conservative, said that if
Christie supports divestiture, the move to sell Disney stock is
virtually assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's disappointing is that it took Chairman Christie almost
eight months to get this on the agenda for an up or down vote,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Christie said that he had hoped to divest ``quietly'' by having
money managers sell the stock, which is allowable, instead of
raising the issue at a public forum.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Randy Stevenson of Tyler said, ``While divestiture
... may not have a direct financial impact upon the Disney
Corporation itself, it is my hope that a strong, clear message will
be sent to Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen months ago, the Southern Baptist Convention voted
overwhelmingly to boycott Disney, accusing the company of
``promoting immoral ideologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, dozens of conservative and religious groups have
followed suit. The Texas Board of Education began to consider
divestiture in response to a plea from the American Family
Association, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that we do not feel that it's morally
responsible for the state to be investing education dollars into
this kind of product,'' Miller said. He predicted that if a Texas
governmental entity sells Disney stock, other states will take
notice.
</P>
<P>
   His group has produced a video that shows scenes from various
movies made by Miramax. Among Miramax movies are ``Sling Blade,
Pulp Fiction'' and ``Reservoir Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie said that after viewing the video, he was in favor of
selling the Disney stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard in good conscience to invest the children of Texas'
education money in the type of violence and immorality that is
being created by Disney,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christie has tried previously to get the board to sell a
politically unpopular stock. In May 1996, the board rejected his
recommendation to dump $9 million in tobacco investments for
``social, business and moral reasons.'' In that case, board members
urged fund managers to keep the stock if it continued to produce
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Texas Legislature placed a ``gangsta rap'' rider
in the appropriations bill barring state pension funds from being
invested in companies that produce pornographic or extremely
violent lyrics. A state district judge struck down the rider.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Texas Freedom Network, which monitors the
conservative movement, said the move against Disney will hurt
Texans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic example of a special interest group trying
to make a political point at the expense of taxpayers,'' said Rick
Levy, a Freedom Network board member.
</P>
<P>
   Since state officials bought Disney stock in July 1996 at $60.85
a share, earnings have grown 12 percent and dividends have grown 21
percent annually, Texas Education Agency officials said.
</P>
<P>
   TEA staff analysts believe that this growth will continue for
three to five years at a rate of 15 percent to 17 percent annually,
officials said in a report.
</P>
<P>
   But board member Robert H. Offutt of San Antonio isn't
convinced. His personal views of Disney aside, Offutt said, he
believes that the national boycott is beginning to affect the value
of Disney stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney has underperformed the market since the beginning of
the year,'' he said. ``The social issues that others have raised
will affect the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
