<HEADLINE>
4 ANTI-GOVERNMENT MILITANTS CONVICTED OF MORE CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont.)  (bl) 
 By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A federal jury in Montana on Wednesday convicted four
top leaders of the Freemen anti-government movement of a huge
banking conspiracy but declared itself hopelessly deadlocked on
many other charges against the four and eight others.
</P>
<P>
   Those convicted were LeRoy Schweitzer, Daniel Petersen, Dale
Jacobi and Russell Landers. The four and two other Freemen, Rodney
Skurdal and Richard Clark, were convicted of other charges by the
same jury last Thursday, including threatening to kidnap and kill a
federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   But after a week of deliberation, the jury failed to reach a
verdict on charges against half of the 12 Freemen whom the
government brought to trial in late May, two years after they
surrendered at their remote Montana compound.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors failed to convict Ralph Clark, uncle of Richard
Clark and the owner of the ranch; Casey Veldhuizen, a ranch hand;
William Stanton and his wife, Agnes, neighboring ranchers, and John
McGuire, a Freemen from California. The jury also failed to reach a
verdict on charges against Cherlyn Petersen, who was found not
guilty of two firearms charges last week.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the jury reached verdicts on about half of the 126
charges against the 12 defendants.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge John Coughenour declared a mistrial on
the unresolved counts and gave prosecutors 10 days to decide
whether they would seek to retry the defendants. Coughenour said
McGuire and the two women were free to go. The other three men the
jury did not convict are to stay in jail to face state charges.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Sherry Scheel Matteucci said she did not know what
the government would decide about a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the jury also convicted Schweitzer and Landers of one
additional count of bank fraud, Schweitzer of filing a false
federal tax claim and Petersen and Jacobi of five additional counts
of mail fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The jury failed to reach any verdict on armed robbery charges
stemming from two thefts of cameras from network television crews
at gunpoint. Noting that films of the confrontations were shown in
the courtroom, one trial monitor Wednesday read the jury's failure
to convict as an anti-press message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Princess Di factor,'' said Ken Toole, program
director for the Montana Human Rights Network, a group that
monitors hate groups. ``If it had been the local mercantile guy
delivering food, it might have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, the verdicts fueled longstanding complaints that the
federal government had been slow to act against the Freemen.
</P>
<P>
   By the time federal agents moved against the Freemen's compound,
in March 1996, the Freemen had tried to pass 3,432 bogus checks,
with a total face value of $15.5 billion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
