<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton comes to town
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- President Clinton will arrive in Atlanta at 9:05 this
morning for a 4 1/2-hour stay during which he will launch a media
campaign against teen drug use and attend a Democratic fund-raising
effort for Senate candidate Michael Coles.
</P>
<P>
   The president's visit on Air Force One isn't expected to affect
local air traffic, but it could generate some tie-ups for morning
commuters, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coming and going during quiet times of the day. It should
be pretty straightforward, in and out,'' said Paul Meyer,
operations manager at Hartsfield International Airport, where the
president's plane will arrive and depart.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential motorcade is expected to move north along I-85
and the Downtown Connector to the Georgia World Congress Center for
a 10:10 a.m. appearance at the anti-drug event. Authorities will
use a ``rolling roadblock,'' which in essence closes the freeway in
front of and behind the motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to earlier statements issued by public relations
officials associated with the anti-drug campaign, the World
Congress Center program will not be open to the public. Instead,
about 700 invited guests will be permitted to attend, according to
White House official John Salomon.
</P>
<P>
   The political fund-raising effort the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee is holding for Coles will begin with a reception
at 11:30 at the Marriott Marquis Hotel, followed by a $500-a-plate
luncheon. Both events are restricted to political contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to give details of the president's routes due
to security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But Sgt. Phasteus Brooks of the Atlanta police Special
Operations unit said on-street parking won't be allowed along the
International Boulevard corridor from Marietta Street to Piedmont
from 9 a.m. to noon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motorists should avoid that area around those times and people
should expect some traffic backup along the interstate,'' Brooks
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to leave on Air Force One at 1:35 for
Daytona Beach, Fla., where he will meet with firefighters, relief
workers and residents of areas hit by recent wildfires in central
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
