<HEADER>
A6465 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEACHTREE-MASTERS     07-08 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACHTREE-MASTERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peachtree masters winner's competitive desire reborn at age 50
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- For Dick Buerkle, winning the masters division of
this year's Peachtree Road Race shared one similarity with running
in the 1976 Olympics: no prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Buerkle stunned the Peachtree field by finishing first in the
over-40 division with a time of 32:50. At 50, he's a decade older
than the youngest, and usually fastest, runners in that category.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of them didn't show up this July 4 because the Atlanta
Track Club, which organizes the race, didn't offer a purse,
electing instead to put its resources into hosting the elite
runners. For them, the Peachtree served as the $100,000 World
Championship of Road Racing. Most years, the masters prize money is
about $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could've used the bucks,'' said Buerkle (pronounced
``burk-lee''), who teaches Spanish and coaches runners at Dunwoody
High School. He has three children in college and is working as a
temporary worker this summer to make extra money. ``If there was a
race in Macon that day that paid money, I would have gone there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta is his adopted hometown, and he loves the Peachtree,
so he ran, even though he knew no money was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``By accident of history, we didn't have a purse this year, but
we're delighted that we could honor one of our own,'' race director
Julia Emmons said. ``His time was remarkable in any venue. We would
all like to hit our 50s in the style he is accustomed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peachtree victory is the latest incarnation of Buerkle's
running career. Originally from Rochester, N.Y., he competed in the
5,000 meters in the 1976 Olympics, finishing ninth in his
qualifying heat. When he set the indoor record for the mile
(3:59.09) two years later, his picture appeared on the cover of
Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   He qualified for the Olympic team in 1980 but did not compete in
Moscow because of the U.S. boycott. Running at the highest level of
his sport, against the Russians at the height of the Cold War,
placed Buerkle under pressure that brings agony to his voice when
he recalls it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful,'' he said. ``I wanted it to be over. It wasn't
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Atlanta in 1979 to take a job with Coca-Cola, and
finished in the top 10 in the Peachtree that year, his best finish
in the open field. Unlike that year, when he could see winner Craig
Virgin ahead of him, he had no idea how he was doing amid this
year's crush of 55,000 runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I just ran as fast as I could, and everyone who
looked older I would try to pass and beat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The slowest masters winning time before Buerkle's was 30:26, and
he acknowledged that he has to trim a couple minutes to contend in
most masters races. But he termed the Peachtree ``not bad'' for the
training he put in, most of it on cobblestone streets in Spain
during a recent trip there with his students.
</P>
<P>
   The sport occupies a different place in his life now because of
his work. Before teaching, he had a series of jobs, including sales
and sports writing for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. He's also
battled attention deficit disorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember hearing him express disinterest in masters
competition at age 40,'' said his Olympic teammate Don Kardong, now
president of the Road Runners Club of America. ``He was just busy
with other stuff, I guess. I kind of assumed that he was out of the
competitive end of the sport for good. ... Now, he's running so
fast at age 50, it makes me disappointed that he didn't start his
masters career when he turned 40. He's obviously maintained a high
level of talent and ability to run fast with age.''
</P>
<P>
   Buerkle didn't have the time to train or the inclination to
compete. He gained 25 pounds, which he lost two years ago ``after I
got sick of being fat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to run to maintain fitness,'' said Buerkle,
who during the school year commutes by foot and MARTA, ``but I
never thought about competing again. ... When I'm coaching 65 to 70
hours a week, that's not conducive to anything but going home and
going to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peachtree victory has made him reconsider. He may seek out
masters races, perhaps in Mexico, that offer prize money. But he
wants to avoid the high pressure and obsession demanded of the top
runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a fear of getting lost in it _ putting my eggs in one
basket and getting hurt,'' he said. ``There are other things that
keep me from focusing on it too much _ coaching and teaching will
always be it for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to be in shape, and I miss this feeling,'' he added.
``I never thought I'd say this, but I miss the workouts and being
in shape. It's kind of like missing getting hit in the head with a
hammer, but I miss the effort of being in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
