<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frank talk about race
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Fixing the race problem in the United States requires
blunt talk, and that honest discourse must start at the top,
President Clinton was told Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One problem with the race dialogue is I feel you were
reluctant to deal with the question of affirmative action,''
Chicago Tribune columnist Clarence Page said to Clinton during a
discussion on race videotaped Wednesday by the PBS program ``The
NewsHour With Jim Lehrer.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight panelists, most of them prominent media members, discussed
the complexities of race relations in an America that is no longer
just black and white. And they mostly agreed that racism has to be
redefined to keep up with changing conditions and subtle nuances.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Dialogue on Race with President Clinton'' will air
nationally on some PBS stations today. In the Atlanta area, WGTV
will broadcast the program Tuesday at 7 p.m. WPBA does not plan to
air it until at least September.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong discussion with Clinton comes as race relations
pushed to the forefront of the nation's consciousness from several
different quarters:
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the oldest daughter of a Texas black man who was
chained to a truck and dragged to his death last month urged a
Senate committee to strengthen the federal law against hate crimes.
``The men who murdered my father had a choice,'' Renee Mullins, 27,
said Wednesday of the three white men accused in the case. ``And
they chose violence. Therefore, the laws of the land should punish
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Camille O. Cosby, wife of comedian Bill Cosby, blamed racism for
their son's murder last year. ``I believe America taught our son's
killer to hate African Americans,'' Mrs. Cosby wrote in a column
published Wednesday in USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed in Wednesday's discussion when Page
told the president: ``Racism is institutional. We are talking about
history here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's race advisory board suggested that the president
abandon the notion of creating a colorblind society. Stereotypes
remain, board Chairman John Hope Franklin told Clinton, because
Americans persist in believing that it's best to ignore race. ``If
one ignores or eliminates consideration of race,'' Franklin wrote,
``there is no way to deal with the manifestations of racial bias or
prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP opens its 89th annual convention in Atlanta on
Saturday. The oldest civil rights organization in the nation will
hear from Vice President Al Gore, retired Gen. Colin Powell and
Jesse Jackson, among others, during the six-day convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Southern Christian Leadership Conference,
founded by the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. in 1957, will install
his son, Martin Luther King III, as president July 25 in the
opening event of the group's July 26-29 national convention in
Landover, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
