A6469 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-NACCP/BOND-COX     07-08 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-NACCP/BOND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bond backs Cosby's assertion American-bred hate killed her son
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The racism that Camille O. Cosby claims saturates
American history and led to the murder of her son has not
diminished, a prominent civil rights leader said Wednesday, and the
only way to halt its spread is with strong, swift punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond, chairman of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, which convenes here this week for
its national convention, agreed with Cosby's nationally published
column that stated America taught her son's white murderer to hate
him because he was black.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby's son, Ennis, died Jan. 16, 1997 after a young white man
shot him in the head as he changed a tire by the roadside in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A jury on Tuesday convicted Mikail Markhasev, a Ukrainian, of
Cosby's murder. On Wednesday in USA Today, a column by the wife of
actor Bill Cosby appeared in which she wrote, ``I believe America
taught our son's killer to hate African-Americans. ... He said to
his friends, `I shot a nigger. It's all over the news.' ...
Markhasev did not learn to hate black people in his native country,
the Ukraine, where the black population was near zero.''
</P>
<P>
   She continues in the column saying America has honored slave
owners by featuring their faces on its currency, accepts images of
God and holy people as white and permitted scientific experiments
on African-Americans that harmed and killed them, such as a study
at the University of Texas in the late 1950s in which necessary
nutrients were withheld from the formula of black infants.
</P>
<P>
   Bond concurred with Cosby's assessment of the country and said,
``... she is absolutely correct. ... The genius of America is that
it allowed white people to be white.'' In their native countries
people defined themselves by their nationality such as Russian,
German or Irish, not by skin color, he said. ``When they came here
they became white people, and they became white people because
there were people here who were black.
</P>
<P>
   ``They adopted a superior status, either written into law in
past decades or assumed by them in the modern era. ... It was
absorbed by them ... in modern times and by the larger culture _
the media, movies, television which not in their entirety but with
an alarming frequency preached the inferiority of black people and
the superiority of white people.''
</P>
<P>
   The column spawned conversation on talk radio and popular black
radio stations. It was also the topic of CNN's TalkBack Live.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP convention leaders will not address race relations in
America as a separate issue during next week's convention because
of Cosby's column, Bond said, because the civil rights organization
has always focused on that issue throughout its history and is
intrinsic to the reason for its existence.
</P>
<P>
   Bond stressed that he did not want to create the impression that
all white people stand on one side of the racial divide and black
people stand on another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have have always been brave and courageous whites, and
for that matter, Asians and Native Americans, Hispanics, nonblack
people who have joined with us in the struggle for justice,'' he
said. ``That was true in the past and it's true today.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution must consist of more than discontinuing lessons of
hate, Bond said. ``We have to not only stop teaching people this,
we have to punish vigorously and quickly those people whose private
prejudices are acted out in public. Not only does this mean
murderers, but also the people who say, `Oh the apartment was
rented just five minutes ago,' or `I wanted to give you the job but
it was filled by somebody else.'''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Brokaw, spokesman for Cosby, said Wednesday Cosby will not
be giving any interviews at all on her column, explaining that
``She wants the piece to stand on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
