<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAVEN BACK IN WINSTON CUP `LOOP' FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A race car reverberating in the background provided the perfect
mood music to the comeback of Ricky Craven this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world,'' Craven said into the phone, ``we'll win
a race here real soon and things will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven was speaking during a break from a test session at
Greenville-Pickens (S.C.) Speedway, where he was reacquainting
himself with the nuances of turning left. Sidelined by the effects
of post-concussion syndrome and an inner ear weakness since March
9, Craven is scheduled to return to the NASCAR Winston Cup wars for
the Jiffy Lube 300 at New Hampshire International Speedway this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Craven, the 1995 Cup rookie of the year, says he has passed
every medical test of his balance devised by his battery of
doctors. His recent ninth-place finish in a NASCAR Busch Grand
National race on the challenging road course in Watkins Glen, N.Y.,
has fortified his self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Craven says he is glad to be back in the loop.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, Ricky. You've still got the job.
</P>
<P>
   But just how long can you keep it?
</P>
<P>
   That same nasty question has stopped haunting Todd Bodine, who
yesterday was released by ISM Racing after a half-season of
disappointing results. Meanwhile, Cup regulars Mike Skinner and Ted
Musgrave and their respective teams have been swatting out rumors
of their impending dismissals as the season swings into its second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, that also was the tenor of Craven's teleconference
Tuesday. As rival team owner Bill Davis recently noted, Winston Cup
racing is a cutthroat business. Multimillion dollar sponsors demand
immediate results, or a new driver's resume. The pressure
associated with maintaining a high-profile Cup ride has already
claimed former series regulars Hut Stricklin, David Green and Wally
Dallenbach Jr.
</P>
<P>
   For Craven, that means his ensuing performances in the No. 50
Budweiser Chevrolet Monte Carlo fielded by Hendrick Motorsports
will surely be measured against those rung up by replacements Randy
LaJoie and Dallenbach.
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie, the two-time and reigning NASCAR Busch Grand National
Series champion, logged one top five and three top 10s during his
nine-race run in Craven's car.
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach, released this season by Sabates Racing, posted two
top-10 finishes in three recent starts. Craven saw the next
question coming before it was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been told that my job is on the line,'' said
Craven, who is winless in 34 Cup starts for Team Hendrick. ``Toward
the end of the recovery, I had heard some things. There's always
going to be some controversy. It's not comfortable. But my greatest
concern was getting myself back to 100 percent. I do have the
confidence that when I am 100 percent, I can compete at this level
and be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrick Motorsports is home, of course, to reigning Cup
champion and current points leader Jeff Gordon and teammate/former
champion Terry Labonte. They have combined to win 38 races and
three championships for Hendrick Motorsports since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's mostly chemistry,'' said Craven, who has missed
12 points-paying starts since finishing 34th in the Primestar 500
at Atlanta Motor Speedway. ``What Jeff and Ray and the 24 team has
is phenomenal and very difficult to duplicate. (Crew chief) Andy
Graves and Terry and the 5 team are attempting to do that, and it
looks like they're making progress. But this is a better team now
than it's ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   That being so, Craven said the only pressure he feels is
self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't satisfy Hendrick Motorsports, then I certainly
won't satisfy myself,'' Craven said. ``Because I'm wanting the same
thing they're wanting.''
</P>
<P>
   To win a race here real soon. And to keep the job. &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL; 
NASCAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Daytona International Speedway continues as home away from
home for a diverse group affected by the fires that have ravaged
East Central Florida. John Story, director of public relations at
DIS, said approximately 300 firefighters, 100 evacuees and 70
National Guardsmen were living at the track as of Tuesday. ``We've
been providing as many as 2000 meals a day since last Thursday,''
said Story, who was among the inner circle of NASCAR officials who
opted to postpone the Pepsi 400 night race from July 4 until Oct.
17.
</P>
<P>
   Recuperating Cup rookie Steve Park got a little closer to the
heat of the Florida fires than the average motorist. ``I rode my
motorcycle to Florida and was there a few days. I couldn't believe
the devastation,'' said Park, who plans to return to the No. 1
Pennzoil Chevrolet Monte Carlo at the Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis
next month. Meanwhile, the rescheduling of the Pepsi 400 will allow
Park to attempt to qualify for a race he otherwise would have
missed.
</P>
<P>
   Any talk of expanding the Winston Cup schedule automatically is
linked to the toll it takes on team personnel. NASCAR president
Bill France Jr. recently acknowledged that the Cup schedule is
likely to max-out at 36 or 37 races down the road. Add in the seven
test dates NASCAR currently allows each team, and the 52-week
calendar shrinks in a hurry. To combat driver burnout, France has
suggested the novel idea of two-driver teams. Each could feature
specialists on different types of courses who would alternate
behind the wheel and earn points for the team, instead of as
individuals. ``I'm not saying it's unrealistic to have two
drivers,'' France said. ``You have two tire-changers, two truck
drivers, why not two drivers? It would be more of a team-type
championship. That would let (the main driver) have a weekend off.
You wouldn't have to race every race. That would take a little heat
off the driver.'' Now all France has to do is sell the concept to
some of the most self-centered athletes on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Roush Racing star Mark Martin, who shares the Cup series victory
lead with Jeff Gordon at four, is driving in pain. Martin has a
herniated disk that makes it painful to climb into and out of the
No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus. ``I'm fine once I'm sitting in the
car,'' said Martin, who plans to delay surgery until season's end.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the Brickyard 400, Texas-owned Tyler Jet
Motorsports has scheduled a three-day test for Darrell Waltrip in
the No. 17 Chevy at Indianapolis Motor Speedway from July 19-21.
Former Fort Worth resident Kent Johnson, the team's general
manager, said a sponsor has been lined up for the race. But the
sponsor has put an embargo on any announcement until the week of
the race. &QL; 
IRL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 10,000 curious fans saw Pep Boys Indy Racing League
points leader Tony Stewart set an unofficial speed record for a
1.5-mile track during open testing at Atlanta Motor Speedway on
Tuesday night. Stewart turned a hot lap of 228.505 mph in his Team
Menard G Force/Aurora while testing for the inaugural Atlanta 500
Classic Weekend. Stewart had lapped at 226.406 mph Monday night.
Stewart set the official speed record for new formula IRL cars at
228.012 mph (lap 86) during the True Value 500K at Texas Motor
Speedway in Fort Worth last month. ``A lot of people were saying
that we were going to hit 230, but we didn't quite do it,'' Stewart
said. ``I don't think everyone showed everything they had, so it'll
be a little more competitive during qualifying.'' Kelley Racing
teammates Mark Dismore (221.494 mph) and Scott Sharp (221.079 mph)
were second- and third-fastest Tuesday in their Dallara/Auroras.
The race, scheduled Aug. 29, will be the first Indy-style event at
AMS since 1983 and first night race in the track's history. ...
</P>
<P>
   Jim Guthrie made his debut for Cobb Racing during the open test
at AMS. Guthrie, the 1997 IRL rookie of the year, has been
sidelined since a crash at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in May.
Guthrie's top lap was 217.865 mph in the G Force/Aurora owned by
former 24 Hours of LeMans winner Price Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach Jr., who has lost his full-time Winston Cup
ride, has been signed to a one-race deal to drive for
Pennzoil/Panther Racing in the Lone Star 500K at TMS on Sept. 20.
Team manager John Barnes said Dallenbach is scheduled to test
Goodyear tires at TMS on Aug. 4-5. Dallenbach, the Sports Car Club
of America Trans-Am champion in 1985-86, competed in four
Championship Auto Racing Teams events before moving to stock cars.
``Here's a guy that has a tremendous amount of talent and is a
great teammate,'' Barnes said of Dallenbach, who will be paired
with lead driver Scott Goodyear. &QL; 
CART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ground has been broken on the site of Chicago Motor Speedway, a
1-mile oval scheduled to play host to a FedEx Championship Auto
Racing Teams event in the fall of 1999. The speedway, part of a
complex that also will include a seven-furlong track for horse
racing, will be managed by Chip Ganassi, owner of the two-time and
reigning series champion Target/Chip Ganassi Racing. Ganassi said
the track will feature a safety wall system to protect drivers in
the turns.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time series champion Bobby Rahal, who plans to retire at
season's end, continues to field inquiries from possible
replacement drivers. ``We've talked to some guys from Formula One,
some guys from CART, some guys from Formula 3000 and some from Indy
Lights,'' said Rahal, driver of the Miller Lite Reynard/Ford. ``No
one from the Indy Racing League has contacted me about the ride,
though. For all the talk about `people not getting opportunities,'
I bet I'll get 99 percent of my letters and calls from guys in
Europe, South America and other international racing. Americans are
as good as anyone else, but it comes down to desire and if a guy
really wants it. For our team, it doesn't have to be an American.
We want someone who is capable of running up front.'' &QL; 
FAST LAPS &QL; 
DOTY PLANS LAST LAP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost 10 years to the day after a crash at Eldora Speedway
ended his Sprint Car career, Brad Doty plans to make one more lap
around the famed dirt track in Rossburg, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Competing in the annual Kings Royal, Doty was paralyzed from the
waist down in a wreck on the backstretch of the high-banked
half-mile on July 25, 1988. Doty is scheduled to pace the field for
the 40-lap, $50,000 to-win Pennzoil World of Outlaws main event on
July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Doty plans to drive a restored version of the No. 18 Coors Light
Gambler he campaigned during the 1987 Outlaws season. He won four
races and finished second to Steve Kinser in series points in the
car. Restored by Larry Woods, the car is equipped with
hand-operated controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the darkest days of my racing life was at Eldora
Speedway,'' Doty said recently. ``But one of my brightest days in
racing could quite possibly be at Eldora, when I get to make this
lap again.''
</P>
<P>
   Doty, who has remained close to the sport as a color commentator
on TNN's WoO telecasts, said this will be the last time he will get
behind the wheel of a Sprint Car. &QL; 
NUTS AND BOLTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Todd Bodine was released yesterday as driver of the No. 35 Team
Tabasco Pontiac Grand Prix. Bob Hancher, owner of ISM Racing, said
the car will be driven by Gary Bradberry in Loudon, N.H., this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Raybestos rookie of the year contender Kevin Lepage has signed a
contract with Roush Racing that guarantees him a full-time Winston
Cup ride in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Hensley's runner-up finish to Mike Bliss in the DieHard
200 at The Milwaukee Mile on Sunday was the first top-five result
by a Dodge Ram driver in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Top Fuel points leader Cory McClenathan plans to debut a new
Murf McKinney-built McDonald's dragster at the National Hot Rod
Association's Mopar Parts Mile High Nationals in Morrison, Colo.,
July 16-19.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Rahal is the only CART driver to have competed in all 16
previous editions of the Grand Prix of Cleveland. &QL; 
LAST WORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This track definitely has curve appeal. I love Bruton Smith's
tracks, and this one is a masterpiece.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ IRL driver Scott Sharp after testing at Atlanta Motor
Speedway. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
