<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAVEN BACK IN WINSTON CUP `LOOP' FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A race car reverberating in the background provided the perfect
mood music to the comeback of Ricky Craven this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world,'' Craven said into the phone, ``we'll win
a race here real soon and things will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven was speaking during a break from a test session at
Greenville-Pickens (S.C.) Speedway, where he was reacquainting
himself with the nuances of turning left. Sidelined by the effects
of post-concussion syndrome and an inner ear weakness since March
9, Craven is scheduled to return to the NASCAR Winston Cup wars for
the Jiffy Lube 300 at New Hampshire International Speedway this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Craven, the 1995 Cup rookie of the year, says he has passed
every medical test of his balance devised by his battery of
doctors. His recent ninth-place finish in a NASCAR Busch Grand
National race on the challenging road course in Watkins Glen, N.Y.,
has fortified his self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Craven says he is glad to be back in the loop.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, Ricky. You've still got the job.
</P>
<P>
   But just how long can you keep it?
</P>
<P>
   That same nasty question has stopped haunting Todd Bodine, who
yesterday was released by ISM Racing after a half-season of
disappointing results. Meanwhile, Cup regulars Mike Skinner and Ted
Musgrave and their respective teams have been swatting out rumors
of their impending dismissals as the season swings into its second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, that also was the tenor of Craven's teleconference
