<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS UNDERGOES TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Yankee outfielder Bernie Williams underwent a
magnetic resonance imaging examination Wednesday on his balky right
knee and, although the results were not announced, General Manager
Brian Cashman suspected good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must be all right, because I'm sure they would have called
me if he wasn't,'' said Cashman, as he watched the Tampa Yankees
play at Legends Field. Williams, hitting .353 with 10 home runs and
44 runs batted in when he injured the knee June 10 on a slide
against Montreal, aggravated it on a throw from center field in a
Florida League game on Monday against Clearwater.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he felt a sharp pain on the throw and promptly
iced the knee. He left the game in the fifth inning after going 1
for 2 with a walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next morning I felt fine,'' he said, ``and it doesn't hurt
at all right now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6480 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BUDGET-SUB-BOS &LR;      07-08 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (Adding Red Sox-Vaughn slug)  
 For Release THURSDAY AMs, July 9, 1998  
 
