<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINN-HOME-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THIS HELSINKI HOME, BEWARE THE COMPUTER (AND THE DOG) 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ Pity the burglar who breaks into Risto
Linturi's new state-of-the-art computerized home. Scandinavia's
high-tech guru, Linturi has designed a house that takes care of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds after sensors signal his mobile phone that an intruder
is present, Linturi can track the burglar via voice-synthesized
messages and do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   With voice messages to the house's central computer, he can turn
lights on, increase or cut off air circulation, lock doors
automatically, and switch on music or the television at high volume
_ all while the system dials the police, reporting the exact time
of the break-in and the burglar's progress.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Finns, Linturi is very comfortable with cutting-edge
technology. Finns are the world's most intense users of mobile
phones, with three out of four carrying one. Two out of four
navigate the Internet daily.
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years, Linturi, 38, has worked on a ``virtual
reality'' Yellow Pages guide to Finland's capital as technology
manager of the Helsinki Telephone Corporation. With pieces of it
already in place, it will allow residents and visitors to navigate
the streets of Helsinki in a virtual-reality taxi, enter its
theaters in real time, watch its movies for a fee, and listen to
public concerts free.
</P>
<P>
   It's all done with computers operated from homes that are
equipped with a mouse and interactive audiovisual devices and will
be fully operative in 18 months. So it seemed logical for Linturi,
soon after he acquired a prime piece of property on the Baltic Sea
three years ago, to dream up the ultimate computerized home.
</P>
<P>
   When finished some time in September, what Linturi calls ``the
future remote work-home in Finn Bay'' will have cost $3 million to
$4 million. The three-bedroom, four-story house and conference room
is atop a hill with an idyllic view of the serene Helsinki bay and
the city. It has a mooring station for one or two small sailboats.
</P>
<P>
   The house is designed for ultimate comfort and what Linturi
calls passive technology. ``The big emphasis is on economy, safety
and ecology,'' he says. Floor-to-ceiling windows give a spectacular
view of the Baltic. Sensors connected to the computers heat the
stone floors (there is no need for carpets), and regulate lights
and air circulation, controlling the level of gases like carbon
dioxide in the air.
</P>
<P>
   There are few buttons or switches: lights will turn on or off
depending on occupancy. A large electronic screen is affixed to a
wall in the kitchen, where the average Finnish family spends a good
deal of time in the long dark winter days. The screen can display
electronic newspapers and the family can use it to send and receive
e-mail over coffee, snacks or dinner.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 Internet outlets are connected by seven miles of
high-optic fiber wiring that snakes unseen around the house,
allowing portable computers to be plugged in almost anywhere to
communicate or call up music, radio or television.
</P>
<P>
   Built of stone and thick bricks, the place is tightly designed
around Linturi, his wife, Kaija, his two daughters, Henna, 16, and
Anni, 10, and Dino, their 130-pound Irish wolfhound, which has its
own entrance to the house that passes through a tub filled with
water. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
