<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATUS QUO ON VAUGHN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the swirl of Mo Vaughn's rejection of the Red Sox' latest
contract offer _ this one for a guaranteed $37 million over four
years and without a counter-offer by Vaughn's representatives _ the
Red Sox made their way to Baltimore Wednesday night for the start
of the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, rehabilitating a strained right hamstring, did make a
brief Fenway appearance earlier in the afternoon but did not board
the bus that took the rest of his team to Logan Airport for its
trip to Baltimore. However, Red Sox spokesman Kevin Shea said Jimy
Williams expects Vaughn, who has missed the Sox' last eight games,
to be at Camden Yards later Thursday, when the manager will
determine Vaughn's questionable status.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the evening, the Red Sox confirmed in a statement
that they negotiated with Vaughn's representatives during the
All-Star break in Colorado but that there was no agreement despite
making Vaughn ``a substantial offer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' offer nonetheless begins to close the gap between
what Vaughn is seeking and what the club believes he is worth. For
one thing, it is believed to be the first time the Red Sox have
offered Vaughn more than a three-year proposal and doubles the term
of the two-year deal dismissed by Vaughn this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn sustained the hamstring injury while legging out an
infield hit in Miami June 26. He is leading Sox regulars in hitting
with a .327 average and in home runs with 21, and he's tied with
Nomar Garciaparra in RBIs with 56. The Red Sox have a record of 6-2
in Vaughn's absence and twice in the last three games achieved
season highs in runs (15) and hits (20).
</P>
<P>
   In previous rounds of contract discussions, Red Sox general Dan
Duquette has invoked the example of Cardinals first baseman Mark
McGwire as a benchmark against which Vaughn's contract should be
calculated. Last fall, McGwire signed a three-year deal with the
Cardinals for $28.5 million, with an option that can boost it to
$40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, however, has countered that McGwire took a so-called
``hometown discount'' because of special circumstances. McGwire was
bowled over by the reception he received in St. Louis, he was
reunited with manager Tony La Russa, who was his manager in
Oakland, and it allowed him a favorable custody-sharing arrangement
of his son with his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   A better barometer of the market, Vaughn and his agents have
said, are the $10 million deals signed by such sluggers as Sammy
Sosa of the Cubs, Albert Belle of the White Sox, and Gary Sheffield
of the Dodgers, and that market will go even higher when players
such as free agent eligible Mike Piazza, now with the Mets, signs
his next contract.
</P>
<P>
   And a richer contract even closer to home is the one the Red Sox
gave Pedro Martinez last December, a six-year, $75 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gordon Edes reported on this story from Denver; Michael Holley
and Joe Sullivan of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
