<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-ACID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POISONOUS ACID SPILLED AT FOUR ABORTION CLINICS IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By S.K. BARDWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A poisonous, foul-smelling acid that irritates skin,
eyes and nasal passages was left Wednesday morning at four Houston
women's clinics where abortions are provided.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks mirrored five carried out at New Orleans clinics
Monday, and 11 that have occurred in Florida since May.
</P>
<P>
   The four southwest Houston clinics targeted Wednesday were among
nine involved in a Texas Supreme Court ruling Friday that upheld a
$1.2 million damage award against anti-abortion protesters who
staged large demonstrations at the clinics during and after the
1992 Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters were called to the first office building just
before 8 a.m., where workers just arriving were met by a nauseous
stench from the rear entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Fire Department Assistant Chief Rick Flanagan said about
a gallon of butyric acid had been poured on the floor near the
building's rear entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The stench _ similar to rotten eggs _ entered the building's air
system and spread throughout the building. As workers began
experiencing difficulty breathing and nausea, the building was
evacuated and remained closed through the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really too bad that women who need this service have to
put up with this,'' said Dr. Howard Novick, who operates the AAA
Concerned Women's Center on the fifth floor of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Hazardous-materials experts were called from that scene to
another office building, which houses A to Z Women's Health
Services and many other offices.
</P>
<P>
   A woman at that building had slipped and fallen in a pool of
butyric acid, twisting her knee. As in the first case, the stench
from the acid spread quickly through the building and forced
evacuation of all offices there for the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The America's Women Clinic was the third victim. The only
free-standing clinic among the four targeted Wednesday, authorities
said it appeared the chemical had been forced through a hole
drilled in the door.
</P>
<P>
   That clinic, like the others, remained closed through the day as
the noxious chemical was cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   At Aaron Women's Medical Center Clinic, officials said it
appeared someone had poured butyric acid on a mat at the front
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Employees noticed the odor of the acid when they arrived
Wednesday morning, but said it was faint. They cleaned up the area
where the stench came from and remained open.
</P>
<P>
   About 1:30 p.m., hazardous-materials teams had to be called to
the site again, when it appeared people walking over the mat at the
front entrance had tracked the chemical through the building, and
it had begun making people sick.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan said a total of 11 people were treated for nausea and
eye and throat irritation at the four sites and four of those were
taken to local hospitals, where they were treated and released
later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Life Advocates, a local antiabortion group, denied any
association with those who carried out the attacks, but noted that
the incidents may have spared the lives of unborn babies.
</P>
<P>
   Flip Benham, director of Operation Rescue National, went a step
further, releasing a statement Wednesday that claimed ``the tactic
of using butyric acid has been used by the abortionists
themselves'' to turn attention to themselves and away from
``children being slaughtered.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Price, president of Texans United for Life, told The
Associated Press, ``It's an act of lunacy. It does nothing to
further the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Durkin, chief executive officer of Planned Parenthood
in Houston and Southeast Texas, called Wednesday's incidents part
of a ``traveling road show.''
</P>
<P>
   No Planned Parenthood offices were attacked Wednesday, but
Durkin said one of the clinics targeted in New Orleans on Monday
was a Planned Parenthood center.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks stretched the fire department's resources to their
limit, prompting it to institute its ``critical resources dispatch
procedure'' for about an hour Wednesday morning. Some
hazardous-material team members who were off Wednesday had to be
called in.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Floyd Wiltz said his agency is investigating the
incidents, along with the Houston police and fire departments, but
he declined to comment on specifics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
