<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGENTS-DOMESTIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH TEXAS KILLINGS FIT FAMILIAR PATTERN, DOMESTIC VIOLENCE
EXPERTS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Maybe Ernie Moore was driven by love. Maybe by hatred.
But experts on family violence said Wednesday that the actions of
the young Rio Grande Valley gunman who killed four people before
being fatally wounded by police seem to fit a pattern sadly
familiar to those who study domestic abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power and control _ that's what it's all about,'' said Lena
Lungwitz, co-director of the University of Texas Law School
Domestic Violence Clinic in Austin. ``It's not a person losing
control; it's a person trying to gain control.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the details of Moore's final days remained a mystery
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Moore, 24, the son and brother of area
policemen, apparently was enraged by a broken love affair. Armed
with an assault rifle, he invaded the family home of his rival
early Tuesday, demanding that his former sweetheart, who had sought
refuge there, leave with him.
</P>
<P>
   When she refused, Moore critically wounded his rival, Dan Morin,
22, and killed the man's mother and sister. Moore later killed two
U.S. Border Patrol agents and seriously injured a Cameron County
sheriff's deputy in a shootout. Moore sustained mortal wounds in
the exchange of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Cox, Moore's former girlfriend, had planned to move into
an apartment with Morin on Friday, according to Morin's family. Cox
was not injured in the shootings. She could not be reached for
comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While it was unclear whether Moore had previously abused or
threatened the woman, family violence experts concurred that the
point at which a woman leaves a problematic mate can be fraught
with violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that they view the woman not as a partner,
but as their property, like a dog,'' said Sgt. Sandy Kline, a
seven-year veteran of the Houston Police Department's Family
Violence Unit. ``What they can't possess, they kill. `If I can't
have you, no one can.'''
</P>
<P>
   Often, such violence targets the woman's relatives, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely common to threaten everyone, the victim's
parents. I've seen a (pet) held hostage ... . We think of
stranger-on-stranger violence, but the real danger comes from
people they know.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Nickel, an information technician with the Texas Department
of Public Safety's Austin headquarters, said more than 10 percent
of the 1,328 homicides reported in 1997 were the result of violence
between husbands and wives or otherwise romantically linked men and
women.
</P>
<P>
   DPS statistics showed 51 wives were murdered by their husbands;
21 husbands were murdered by their wives. Additionally, 15 women
involved in common-law unions were murdered, 11 common-law husbands
were murdered and 43 people, most of them women, were killed in
``boyfriend-girlfriend'' altercations.
</P>
<P>
   HPD's Kline said such figures likely represented only a fraction
of such killings. Last year, she said, her unit received an average
2,500 family violence reports each month.
</P>
<P>
   Jealousy, she said, often is a factor in some of the most brutal
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Gondlof, who has studied abusive family relationships in
Houston and other Texas cities for the Atlanta-based U.S. Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention, agreed that the termination of
troubled relationships often can send men into a destructive
emotional spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaving is a defiance of authority,'' he said. ``It's a
rejection of control. Oddly, in a perverse way, it's seen as an
attack on him. It throws some men into a tremendous depression _
everything is lost. They are shamed and embarrassed. It's sometimes
a factor in murder-suicides. The man kills and then turns on
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gondlof, who is associate research director at the
Pennsylvania-based Mid-Atlantic Addiction Training Institute,
admitted being only passingly familiar with the Rio Grande Valley
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, Moore's ambush of Border Patrol agents likely
constituted ``almost a death wish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All was lost,'' Gondlof said, ``and he was ready to sacrifice
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox and Moore's family have not been available for interviews,
and the quality of the couple's terminated relationship is not
publicly known. But experts said it is possible that Moore did not
betray his propensity for violence prior to the Tuesday morning
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to predict lethality,'' said UT's Lungwitz.
``Somebody may be a jerk, but you'd not anticipate that they'd kill
someone. Abusive people can be charming. You'd never guess in a
million years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
