<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY RULER APPEALS FOR CALM FOLLOWING SPORADIC RIOTING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for rewriting throughout, adds 400 words at end. No
pickup.)   (sw) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Nigeria's military ruler tried to calm an angry
nation on Wednesday night, after the sudden death of the opposition
leader, Moshood K.O. Abiola, by agreeing to allow outside experts
to take part in the autopsy and speaking, albeit in vague terms, of
moving toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But the country seems poised on a knife-edge despite the appeals
for restraint.
</P>
<P>
   The streets of Lagos were quiet on Wednesday night, eerily
deserted as people stayed home out of fear. But debris and smashed
glass littering several streets testified to the sporadic rioting
that has left at least 19 people dead since Abiola, who was under
government detention, died. The riots underscored the explosive
resonance of his name.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, the country's recently installed
leader, also dissolved the military-appointed government on
Wednesday _ a gesture that appears unlikely to have any immediate
impact because the core of power lies with the inner circle of
military men gathered in the Provisional Ruling Council.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the nation wearing a green medal-bedecked military
uniform, Abubakar promised a fair autopsy for Abiola, who
apparently suffered a heart attack, and said his release from
prison was to have been decided formally on Wednesday. ``Alas,''
the general said, ``God willed otherwise, and today we mourn his
loss.'' It was not immediately clear when the autopsy would be
performed.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar spoke of the ``restoration of democracy'' in Nigeria,
Africa's most populous nation, as an ``imperative,'' but he avoided
spelling out any plans as to how to achieve this or any specific
timetable for elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration appears determined to prod the new
government toward democratic change without appearing to push too
hard or too blatantly. The volatility of the situation here is
evident, and there are major American interests at stake, both
directly in the large oil industry, and strategically in placing a
democratic Nigeria at the heart of a stable West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech the general described the death of the opposition
leader as a ``national tragedy,'' the same terms he used for the
death a month ago of the dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
   This ambivalence suggests the narrow line Nigeria's new ruler is
trying to tread between his own apparent desire to further a
democratic transition in this pivotal African state and those in
the armed forces who remain loyal to Abacha's oppressive and
generally ruinous policies.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, who appeared to be poised to win the 1993 presidential
election before the military annulled it, and was imprisoned on
charges of treason in 1994, died Tuesday after falling ill during a
meeting with U.S. and Nigerian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian authorities have attributed his death to ``cardiac
arrest,'' but members of Abiola's family have suggested he may have
been poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said on Wednesday that two American
military physicians will be sent to Nigeria to help perform an
autopsy. The chief coroner of the Canadian province of Ontario, Dr.
James Young, will also be present, along with a British expert. At
the specific request of the Abiola family, Dr. John Pless, a
pathologist at Indiana University is being sent by Physicians for
Human Rights, a Boston-based group.
</P>
<P>
   The burial of Abiola, who converted to Islam many years ago,
would normally have taken place at once, but a delay of perhaps as
much as two or three more days now seems likely.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said on Wednesday
that United States had no evidence that Abiola had ``died of
anything other than natural causes.'' But he added that, given the
suspicions of the family, it was ``a good idea to have a
post-mortem conducted in a way that is as independently, reliably,
conducted as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubts are inevitably swirling here, prompted by the
extraordinary timing of Abiola's death and it seems certain that
until the results of the autopsy are known the situation will
remain highly volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, with the door now half opened to a democratic
transition and the eventual course of this shift still vague, a
quick return to the calm called for on Wednesday by Abubakar may be
elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You who killed Abiola will pay for what you have done,'' mobs
shouted as they moved through the streets here early on Wednesday,
before being disbanded by police units that fired shots in the air.
By the afternoon, this city of eight million people was largely
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   City authorities said at least 10 people had been killed in
Lagos, and some of the violence appeared shaded by old ethnic
rivalries, with Yorubas from Nigeria's southwest attacking Hausas
from the north.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim Hausas and Fulanis constitute a majority in the military
government and the armed forces, while a significant part of
Abiola's following came from members of the Yoruba tribe in the
southwestern part of Nigeria, the late opposition leader's home
region.
</P>
<P>
   Violence was also reported in at least two other towns,
including Nigeria's second city, Ibadan, where burning tires
blocked streets for several hours, and in Abiola's hometown of
Abeokuta.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I appeal to you to remain calm despite your understandable
grief,'' Abubakar said. ``Our national grief cannot be assuaged by
recourse to lawlessness, threat to life, and wanton destruction of
innocent people's property.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary of state for political
affairs, who led the American delegation here this week, said on
Wednesday he believed that Abubakar was receptive to American
demands that Nigeria move swiftly to democracy. But he added that
the new leader wanted to complete a ``consultative'' process.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the military government should be blamed for Abiola's
death, Rubin said, ``We made very clear that we think he should
never have been in prison, and therefore any consequence of him
being in prison is the responsibility of the government that
wrongfully put him in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar was a prominent member of that government.
</P>
<P>
   He has, however, hinted in recent meetings with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and with Pickering that he wants to
turn the page, ending five years in which Nigeria's economy was
pillaged.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Abubakar conspicuously declined to spell out
the political plans that Nigeria's 105 million inhabitants are now
anxiously awaiting. ``I will address you on the general character
of this administration in due course,'' the general said.
</P>
<P>
   Impatience is, however, running high, and it appears that
Abubakar will have to be more specific about his plans for any move
to democracy soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is trying his best for this country, giving us great
natural wealth, but everything has been wasted,'' said John Iboka,
a businessman. ``Now we are hoping for a new start.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
