<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SQUAW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SQUAW PEAK' KEEPS ITS NAME, ARIZONA BOARD DECIDES 
</HEADLINE>
 PEAK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUBEN NAVARRETTE JR.  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Squaw Peak will remain Squaw Peak, a state board decided
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: A search of historical records showed that it's
never been called by any other name.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Arizona Board of Geographic and Historic
Names was viewed as a rebuke to some Native Americans, who said
they found the name ``squaw'' offensive and wanted to change the
name to Iron Mountain. They said that is the English translation of
the Akimel O'odham word for the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   But the board's assistant and historian, Julie Hoff, said her
analysis of ``one hundred years of Indian literature, poetry and
folklore'' had uncovered virtually no evidence that Squaw Peak was
ever referred to as Iron Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us want to make a change but we couldn't here today
because this is not the right name,'' board member Mervyn Mason
told the handful of people who attended a hearing on the proposed
name change.
</P>
<P>
   The petition to rename the peak, which was unanimously rejected
by the board, was filed in July 1997 by a pair of teenage girls who
claim that the word ``squaw'' is offensive to Native American women
because &UR; , in some Indian languages, it denotes female genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   Several Board members cited Hoff's presentation in explaining
why they voted to reject the name change. Others cited board
regulations requiring that before a change could be made, the
replacement name had to be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Board chairman Tim Norton suggested that the body's mission
leaned more toward preserving names than changing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're required by statute to preserve the historical record of
the state,'' Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, offensiveness is a matter of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say offensive, offensive to whom?'' he asked. ``Where
do you draw the line on political correctness?''
</P>
<P>
   However, Mason said he was ready to consider another proposal at
a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics claimed that the board's research was weak since it
didn't include Native American sources. They say that many Native
American elders refer to the peak as Iron Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Others complained board members h &UR; id behind a technicality to
skirt the main issue of whether ``squaw'' was offensive and should
be erased from public view.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was like splitting a hair,'' &UR; said Michele Curran, a
historian hired by the American Indian Movement.
</P>
<P>
   Curran said she had been assured that those who favor the name
Iron Mountain would have a chance to present their own research.
She said that never happened. &UR; But Norton said that a number of
local tribes did receive copies of the research report for comment
and that none of them responded.
</P>
<P>
   Native American activists vowed to continue efforts to change
the name. One leader said the next step may be to go over the state
board's head to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go national,'' said Vernon Foster, director of
AIM`s Southwest Region.
</P>
<P>
   Foster said that AIM and others opposed to the word ``squaw''
intended to take the issue to the U.S. Board of Geographic Names.
</P>
<P>
   But another supporter of the name-change wanted the Arizona
board to know that it had not heard the last of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna be back,'' said Delena Waddle, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Waddle co-sponsored the name-change proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be back with the same name, Iron Mountain. Just with
more research,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Navarrette, Jr. can be reached at 444-4977 or by way of
email at ruben.navarrette(at)pni.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
