</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RACE-SYMPOSIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VENUE BUT OLD EMPHASIS IN RACE FORUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sat down Wednesday with eight
authors, educators and journalists for an hourlong discussion of
race and class that ranged across questions of stereotyping and
intermarriage but returned repeatedly to the subject of affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   The administration had hoped to play down that topic during the
president's initiative on race. But the participants fell quickly
into the familiar debate, clashing over whether affirmative action
was a necessary redress for discrimination or a system of unfair
preferences that resulted in discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argued for encouraging diversity in schools,
neighborhoods and workplaces but acknowledged the difficulties of
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there is an independent value to having young people
learn in an environment where they're with people of many different
racial and ethnic backgrounds,'' he said. ``And the question is,
How can you balance that with our devotion to merit?''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third and final round-table discussion that the White
House had planned as part of Clinton's initiative on race, which
the president announced in June 1997 as a yearlong effort. It has
now been extended to the end of this year, when Clinton is to issue
a report.
</P>
<P>
   The president taped the discussion Wednesday afternoon for
broadcast Thursday evening on PBS. Moderated by Jim Lehrer of PBS,
the program will be broadcast at 10 p.m. in New York and at
different times in other regions. PBS and the White House provided
transcripts Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion underscored what administration officials
acknowledge is a lingering problem for the race initiative: a lack
of focus. Some panelists complained that the initiative
concentrated too much on black-white relations, while another
objected that it had not taken on affirmative action forthrightly.
</P>
<P>
   And, even though Clinton has been trying to encourage
conversation about race for more than a year now, the talk
Wednesday ultimately turned to the question of how to get other
people talking about race _ though Lehrer had some difficulty
keeping the focus on that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about talking bluntly about race,'' Lehrer said
in trying gently to redirect one panelist headed in a different
direction. The session ended moments later, with the president
objecting, ``We're just getting warmed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks, whites, Hispanic- and Asian-Americans and American
Indians were all represented Wednesday. Given the choice of
writerly panelists and of venue, the White House appeared to be
seeking a more rarefied conversation and audience that at past
events. Last December, Clinton held a town hall meeting with
residents of Akron, Ohio, and in April he appeared with athletes
and sports executives on the cable sports channel ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists Wednesday generally acted as spokesmen for their
racial group, raising issues specific to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A poor Native American faces more hurdles than a poor
anybody,'' said Sherman Alexie, a filmmaker and author. Indian
reservations suffered from ``fourth-world conditions,'' Alexie
said, adding that he did not have running water until he was 7.
``There are no models of any success in any sort of field for
Indians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by the president, who noted that his own grandmother was
``one-quarter Cherokee,'' Sherman said other Americans needed to
appreciate that Indians were independent politically, while Indians
needed to appreciate the value of education.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Asian-Americans a ``much maligned minority,'' Heritage
Foundation fellow Elaine Chao described how a Chinese-American boy
with good test scores was excluded from a San Francisco school
because what she called the ``Chinese quota'' was filled. ``That is
a horrible example of preferential treatment and of unfair
treatment based on race,'' Ms. Chao said.
</P>
<P>
   But The Chicago Tribune columnist Clarence Page said
``desegregation does not come by just good wishes.'' The central
question, Page said, was, ``How much equal opportunity are you
willing to sacrifice in the pursuit of diversity?''
</P>
<P>
   He told Clinton that ``one problem with the race dialogue was
that I think you were reluctant to deal with the question of
affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   The panelists disagreed over the relationship of race and class.
Roberto Suro, a writer and Washington Post reporter, said: ``I'd
say a young black male who lives in an inner city experiences being
black differently than a middle-aged, middle-class female who lives
in a suburb.''
</P>
<P>
   But Page said, ``In my suburb right now, there are numerous
complaints about black youths being stopped by the cops unfairly,
just as they're stopped by the cops in the inner city.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rodriguez, of the Pacific News Service, said he was
sometimes stopped while jogging in San Francisco before dawn. ``The
last time I got stopped was by two black policemen,'' Rodriguez
said, ``and I think to myself, this is a very complicated society
we live in.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
