Sampas, is selling off the author's archives in violation of his
wishes that his manuscripts be given to the public. Kerouac said in
a 1962 letter to his friend, novelist John Clellon Holmes, ``that
he wanted to create a gold mine of information for scholars,'' with
his papers, says Nicosia. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1998 -- BROWN-RESIGN-2-B&AMP;W, 7-8 --
S.I. Newhouse, publisher of The New Yorker, with TIna Brown, the
magazine's editor, at the 70th anniversary party for the New Yorker
in February of 1995. Ms. Brown announced Wednesday that she will
resign as editor of the The New Yorker to start a company
affiliated with Miramax Films that will publish a new monthly
magazine, publish books and produce films and television
programming. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1998 -- BROWN-RESIGN-1, 7-8 -- Tina
Brown in a suite at the Four Seasons hotel in Manhattan. Ms. Brown
announced Wednesday that she will resign as editor of the The New
Yorker to start a company affiliated with Miramax Films that will
publish a new monthly magazine, publish books and produce films and
television programming. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) OXFORD, Ohio -- July 8, 1998 -- HUT-ARCHITECTURE, 7-8 --
Ann Cline's hut, nested like an owl in a tree at the back of her
yard in Oxford, is used as a retreat for tea ceremonies. Hand-built
and homemade, usually wooden, scraped together from pieces of scrap
or engineered with standard lumber, the hut is barely design. It is
as ordinary as a structure can be. But the hut has an extraordinary
gift: it is a shelter for the imagination. (Mark Lyons/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) OXFORD, Miss. -- July 8, 1998 -- HANNAH-HOME-2, 7-8 --
Novelist Barry Hannah with a bike sculpture and one of his six dogs
at his home in Oxford. After a rambling life as a writer and
teacher that often took him to the depths of alcoholism and
self-destruction, Hannah has called Oxford and the University of
Mississippi, where he teaches creative writing, home for 16 years
now. ``There's not a hell of a lot of things to do, but I like
it,'' he says. (Rollin Riggs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) OXFORD, Miss. -- July 8, 1998 -- HANNAH-HOME-1, 7-8 --
Novelist Barry Hannah sees sunny days. After a rambling life as a
writer and teacher that has taken him from South Carolina to
Vermont to Alabama to Hollywood to Iowa Q and often to the depths
