<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONT-ECO-REALTOR-NYT &LR;      07-08 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONT-ECO-REALTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN SPRAWL IS HOME ON THE RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON, Mont. _ All over Montana, in any valley with a decent
road through it, the signs play to an America that is no longer
home on the range, unless it comes with a satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilderness at your door _ just minutes from the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Own a piece of that renowned Montana serenity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A hunting and fishing paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   The enticements come with pictures of elk grazing in backyard
meadows, fly fishermen at sunset and big-chested mountains. But in
the process of subdividing and selling some of the most gorgeous
scenery on earth, Montanans are losing their heritage _ at least
that is the view of Laura Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade ago, Ms. Merrill settled near Hamilton, a
town of about 3,000 people in the Bitterroot Valley and the seat of
Ravalli County in western Montana.
</P>
<P>
   She was determined that she would not let the valley become
another generic suburb built along a strip mall. Now she is an
unlikely crusader against development excess: she makes her living
as a real estate agent in the fastest-growing county in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Merrill is a land broker who will not sell subdivisions, a
real estate agent who encourages people to put conservation
restrictions on their land. And she is outspoken about the
consequences of dividing up ranches to sell pieces to fantasy
cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've turned down lots of listings, and it's cost me a fair
amount of money, I'm sure,'' says Ms. Merrill, an independent
broker in this valley 45 miles south of Missoula. ``I'm interested
in keeping the land intact. Because what I'm afraid we're doing
here is fouling our nest.''
</P>
<P>
   With winter only a snowbound memory, it is high season for
selling real estate in Montana. Ms. Merrill is surrounded by
listings of her fellow agents _ gorgeous pictures of little plots
of paradise with creeks running through them.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound like an oxymoron _ the environmental realtor. She
would rather warn of problems down the road than talk about low
down-payments and ``E-Z terms. But Ms. Merrill is not alone. A
handful of other real estate agents in this state have started to
turn down listings that encourage sprawl or involve tearing up
wildlife habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that any of them are getting rich, but we've actually got
a few eco-realtors making a living in Montana right now,'' said
John Wilson, executive director of the Montana Land Reliance, which
buys development rights to preserve open space.
</P>
<P>
   But at this time of year, when the high mountains hold the sun
until nearly 10 p.m. and the meadows are dense with wildflowers, it
can seem like the entire state is for sale. Places with names like
``Mountain-Vu Estates'' have sprouted in what had been open
country. Since 1974, Montana has lost 3.1 million acres of ranch
and farmland, most of it to urban sprawl, state officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Subdivisions march up the mountainside from Kalispell to Darby,
and from Missoula to Bozeman. They feature big log homes on lots
that vary from one acre to a thousand. Buyers range from
celebrities _ the talk show host David Letterman was here recently,
looking at ranches _ to urban dwellers who have long dreamed of
life under the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   But once the land is carved up, it is generally not open to
wildlife or to agriculture, Wilson said. Sprawl has become the No.
1 threat to the natural world in Montana, many environmental groups
say.
</P>
<P>
   And no valley has seen more development lately than the
Bitterroot. In the last six years, 596 subdivisions have been
approved here in Ravalli County, which has a population of about
34,000. ``The Best of the Last Best Places,'' is the slogan on
relocation guides for the county.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Merrill favors controlling development and trying to keep
farmland intact, positions that she said had not exactly endeared
her to her fellow real estate agents in a state where planning is
anathema. She still sells plenty of property, she added, but it is
land that is intended to stay as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like selling land,'' said Ms. Merrill, a former Forest
Service scientist. ``I like talking to people about property
stewardship, about different trees on the land.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more, clients are asking Ms. Merrill about conservation
easements, which are binding legal agreements that limit
development. Landowners receive estate and income tax benefits by
agreeing to place restrictions on their land. They are paid by
private foundations, or federal, state or local governments, for
these rights. More than 600,000 acres in Montana are now in
protective easements, up from barely 1,000 acres 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Bitterroot Valley and every other scenic hollow
in Montana will be worth more to property owners if pell-mell
development is controlled, Ms. Merrill said. But new subdivisions
continue to go up almost every month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a real range of people in this job, a lot of different
buyers,'' she said. ``All of them are looking for a less congested
place, a less crazy place, a safe place. We have all that. But I'm
afraid if we don't do something, we're going to lose this valley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
