<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-RESEARCH-PRIORITY     07-08 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RESEARCH-PRIORITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AGENCY URGED TO REVIEW SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Institutes of Health, the world's
pre-eminent sponsor of biomedical research, should listen more
carefully to patients and ordinary citizens in deciding how to
spend its $13.6 billion annual budget, a blue-ribbon advisory panel
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it said, the federal health agency should more
systematically consider data on the prevalence, death rates and
costs of different diseases in setting its research agenda and
priorities. The panel found big disparities in the institutes'
spending per person, depending on the disease. For example, data
collected by the NIH for 1996 show that the institutes spent far
more on AIDS research than on heart disease research, even though
heart disease accounted for many more deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Such data, it said, encourage ``the perception of some members
of Congress and the public that NIH spending often follows current
politics and political correctness, or responds to media attention
to certain diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19-member panel was appointed by the Institute of Medicine,
an arm of the National Academy of Sciences, under instructions from
Congress, which requested the study.
</P>
<P>
   It said that the institutes should be ``more responsive'' to the
public, and that ordinary citizens should have ``more opportunities
to present their views regarding research needs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Institutes of Health has helped launch a
revolution in biology over the last half-century,'' by performing
or financing basic research that has led to breakthroughs in the
treatment of cancer, heart disease, diabetes and AIDS, said Dr.
Leon Rosenberg, panel chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenberg, a professor of molecular biology at Princeton
University, added that the NIH, the largest civilian research
agency in the government, ``has fallen short'' in dealing with the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 18 institutes has an advisory council to guide its
work, and one-third of the seats are typically reserved for public
representatives. But the panel found that the institutes were
appointing doctors, lawyers and eminent professors, rather than
ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the panel said that the NIH and its director, Dr.
Harold Varmus, should fill these slots with more ``representatives
of patients and their families, and of populations with special
health problems,'' including blacks, Hispanic Americans and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The director's advisory committee now includes biology
professors from Harvard, Princeton and Columbia, a trustee of the
American Medical Association, a senior vice president of Monsanto
Co. and experts on supercomputers and patent law.
</P>
<P>
   Myrl Weinberg, president of the National Health Council, a
coalition of more than 100 groups, including the American Heart
Association and the American Diabetes Association, said it was
``absolutely appropriate'' for members of such advocacy groups to
sit on NIH committees that help decide how federal money is spent.
Ms. Weinberg was a member of the academy panel.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said it was particularly important for the institutes
to define their priorities more clearly because they are likely to
get a huge infusion of money in the next few years. The agency's
budget has doubled since 1991, and leading lawmakers from both
parties want to double it again in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Advocacy groups have hired lobbyists to seek more money for
research on specific diseases, in an effort to duplicate the
success of advocates for people with AIDS and breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that each institute should create a full-time
office of public liaison, and that Varmus should establish a
``council of public representatives'' so patients and other
citizens could advise the institutes on research priorities.
</P>
<P>
   If the institutes themselves become more responsive to the
public, that could reduce the need, or the temptation, for Congress
to dictate research priorities in detail, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg insisted that these changes need not erode financial
support for basic scientific research that has no immediate or
obvious practical applications. Such research _ in microbiology,
virology and genetics, for example _ has led eventually to
discoveries of immense value to medicine and agriculture and has
stimulated growth of the biotechnology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla., has raised questions about the way
the institutes allocate money. ``Federal spending on disease
research should consider how many people are affected and the costs
of major diseases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NIH officials have tried to compile such information, but
contend that the numbers should not be used as the main criteria in
setting spending priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Data collected by the NIH show that in 1996 the agency spent
$851.6 million for research on heart disease, a disorder
responsible for 733,834 deaths. The agency spent $1.4 billion for
research on the virus that causes AIDS, a disease responsible for
32,655 deaths in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The figures suggest that the institutes spent more than $43,000
for every AIDS death, but $1,160 for each death from heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The report estimates that direct costs to society from heart
disease totaled $70 billion a year, while costs from AIDS were
$10.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allocating dollars for deaths is an overly simplistic way to
approach biomedical research,'' said Daniel Zingale, executive
director of AIDS Action, an advocacy group. ``We also need to
consider which diseases cause the most suffering, the years of life
lost and the chances of scientific breakthroughs.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2218EDT &QL; 
