<HEADLINE>
BRAWLEY DEFAMATION CASE GOES TO JURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Nearly eight months after the trial began,
the six jurors in the Tawana Brawley defamation case began
deliberations Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After Judge Justice S. Barrett Hickman gave the jurors legal
instructions in the morning, the panel deliberated for two hours
and five minutes Wednesday afternoon. They asked to review several
pieces of evidence, including a videotape of the statements that
plaintiff Steven Pagones says defamed him a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, who are not sequestered, went home just after 5 p.m.
and were to resume deliberations on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors' requests occasioned the intense, and usually
inconclusive, courthouse discussion that such notes arouse in many
trials. The notes were not read in public but were described by
some of the trial participants.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought the requests indicated little more than that the
jurors were taking their task seriously. Others said requests for
such evidence showed sympathies with the three defendants, who had
been Ms. Brawley's advisers _ the Rev. Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason
and Alton Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers said Pagones raped and kidnapped Ms. Brawley in
1987, when she was 15. A grand jury later discredited her account
and exonerated Pagones, who filed a suit seeking millions of
dollars in damages in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was far quieter than many of the days since the trial
began on Nov. 18. The judge read the complex legal instructions
that defined the elements Pagones must have proved to establish
that he was defamed. The defendants objected to some of the
instructions. The judge held fast on many points but relented on
several others, calling the jurors back to amend his remarks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sharpton's lawyer, Michael Hardy, objected to the judge's
instruction that the jurors could hold that the defendants acted in
a conspiracy, which could make each responsible for the other's
statements. The judge left intact his instructions on that point.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman also left intact, despite defense objections, his
instruction that since Ms. Brawley did not testify, the jurors
could infer that her testimony would have hurt the defendants'
assertion that she was assaulted. He ruled, however, that the
jurors could only make that inference against Maddox, who, he has
ruled, had legal control over Ms. Brawley and appeared with her at
a Brooklyn rally as recently as December.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, both sides seemed to be positioning
themselves for the end of the case. No matter what the verdict,
Pagones said, he accomplished his goal of forcing the defendants to
appear in court to back up their claims. He said they had failed.
``With that in mind,'' he said, ``I've won. Now, I want to hold
them accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, who has developed a political career, said, ``Whatever
the verdict will be, it will not interfere one iota with the future
and intentions of Al Sharpton.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
