<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-H     07-08 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-FRANCE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Thuram's goals send France into final
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ France coach Aime Jacquet thought it was going to be one of
those nights when nothing went right.
</P>
<P>
   Five great shots had been fired by suspected French hero
Zinedine Zidane. They all barely missed or were knocked away. Two
shots came perilously close from poster-boy French forward Youri
Djorkaeff. Frustration.
</P>
<P>
   A bounce and a dribble went the wrong way inside of France's
area only seconds into the second half _ lucky rolls, really _ and
Croatia forward Davor Suker had a clear shot and goal for a
stunning 1-0 World Cup semifinal lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not having a wonderful time of it,'' Jacquet said.
``It was extremely tenuous. I thought it might be a night when it
was our time to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But it proved to be the rarest of nights at Stade de France, a
memorable 2-1 World Cup semifinal victory over Croatia on a night
when a young man named Lilian Thuram, an unknown splinter of a
player, blasted out of obscurity and into French fable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody thought I would score two goals,'' said
Thuram, 26, a native of Guadeloupe who emigrated with his mother 17
years ago. ``I didn't think I would score one. I don't even score
in practice. This is fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of Thuram's goals proved to be not only vital to French
hopes, but remarkably impressive individual efforts for a player
who had not scored in 37 previous national team appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was an excellent reward for all the work he's put in,
especially the mental discipline he's been able to give this
team,'' Jacquet said. ``A lot of people haven't known the
importance he is to this team. He's had a great World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, until Wednesday Thuram rarely saw the lights of stardom.
His image wasn't painted on the side of buildings, like Djorkaeff
and Zidane. His jersey number _ 15 _ is difficult to find in the
stores.
</P>
<P>
   He was known as a quiet defender with quick reflexes and sharp
clearing passes.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of Wednesday's game, nearly 80,000 deliriously
happy fans at Stade de France broke into wild roars every time
Thuram touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   And by the early-morning hours today in Paris, where an
estimated one million people partied on the streets, they were
toasting Thuram and chanting his name from the Champs Elysees, to
the Arc de Triomphe, the Eiffel Tower and every street, plaza and
cafe in town.
</P>
<P>
   Paris erupted after the emotional victory, which sends the host
team into Sunday's World Cup final against defending champion
Brazil. Croatia, the surprise of the tournament, will face the
Netherlands on Saturday in the Cup's third-place game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wonderful feat to be playing for the Cup, something
France has dreamed about, but never been able to do,'' Jacquet
said. ``Yes, Brazil is the best team in the world. We will be
playing the masters of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will be there. We will be happy to be there. It will be
a festival of football. We have been dreaming of this for so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   It was France, in fact, that gave the world its first World Cup
tournament 68 years ago. The dream finally came alive when things
looked their gloomiest Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go up on them (1-0) and we're in the World Cup final, I
thought,'' Suker said. ``If we had been able to hold on to our lead
for just a few minutes, their fans would have been down, the French
team would have been down. We would have been going.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a span of 22 minutes in the second half, Thuram
consistently bolted upfield from his defensive position, put on a
blurring display of offensive skill and lifted a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Thuram's first goal came only seconds after Suker scored and
gave Croatia the lead.
</P>
<P>
   A collective groan went up at Stade de France in the 46th minute
when, after a scuffle for the ball in front of the French net,
Suker somehow came away with an entry pass and popped the ball past
goalkeeper Fabien Barthez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit that I thought we had them; that we were going
(to the finals) ourselves,'' Croatia coach Miroslav Blazevic said.
``France was failing and lacking strength.''
</P>
<P>
   But before the small and vocal group of Croatia fans had even
stopped celebrating Suker's goal, Thuram was sprinting upfield and
was fighting for possession deep on the Croatia end.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Thuram used his enormous defensive skills to steal the
ball from Croatia's Zvonimir Boban and got a return pass from
Zidane in front of the net. Thuram hammered a low shot easily past
goalie Drazen Ladic and the score was tied.
</P>
<P>
   Only 22 minutes later, after several more length-of-the-field
runs and good chances, Thuram then put on a strong individual
effort as he took the ball at the Croatia net.
</P>
<P>
   He got a pass from Thierry Henry in front of two Croatian
defenders, spun and reared to his left, then fired a bullet from 20
yards on which Ladic had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an excellent goal,'' Thuram said. ``I think it was
200 percent luck.''
</P>
<P>
   It sent this city into an explosion of noise and celebration,
although things got interesting with 16 minutes remaining when
French defender Laurent Blanc was red-carded for pushing Croatia's
Slaven Bilic in the face on a free-kick attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made the end of the game quite interesting,'' Jacquet
said. ``But we showed a lot of heart. We won and we're in the
final. We're at home and we're playing Brazil for the World Cup.
The French people have to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   They were _ well into the night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
