<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN TO KEEP ARNETT AS CORRESPONDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Top executives of the Cable News Network said Wednesday that
they would allow Peter Arnett to keep his job as a correspondent
despite his participation in the network's repudiated report on the
use of nerve gas on a secret 1970 military mission in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Arnett's reprimand stands,'' said a statement issued by
Tom Johnson, chairman and chief executive of CNN News Group. ``No
further personnel actions are planned.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision met with mixed reaction among the network's
journalists, some of whom had felt Arnett, the correspondent who
lent his credibility to the report, was being given a break that
had not been accorded to April Oliver and Jack Smith, the producers
who had done the reporting. Both were dismissed by CNN last week.
Both also say they stand by their report and argue that the network
caved in under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett's defense _ that he was simply doing the bidding of the
producers of the new program ``Newsstand: CNN and Time'' and
reading words written by others _ has proved a particular irritant
to some of the other network correspondents. Christiane Amanpour,
whose reporting from arenas like Bosnia and Iran has given her high
visibility, vehemently denied that when reporting for a
newsmagazine program like ``Impact,'' she narrated reports
developed by others, as Arnett suggested in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, contrary to what Peter Arnett appears to believe,
that a network correspondent should be responsible for what he or
she says on the air,'' she said in a telephone interview. ``I
believe that we have our face, our name, our voices and our
credibility, and therefore we should be responsible for'' such
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, in an interview Wednesday, said, ``Journalists must
assure the accuracy of their reports. It is the obligation of all
journalists to be sure we have the story right.'' Arnett, he added,
has been ``severely reprimanded'' for ``his failure to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Johnson said, ``on this, he did exactly what he was
asked to do. He read the script for air and turned the information
over to producers. Including the interview with the mission's
pilot,'' who denied that he had carried tear gas as part of his
armaments.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions to cut or minimize such denials of the report's
central thesis have come under sharp attack. The network retracted
the report and apologized last week after its internal
investigation, headed by the lawyer Floyd Abrams, determined that
the information gathered by the producers in eight months of
reporting did not substantiate the claim that nerve gas was used.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver and Smith both applauded the network's decision to
retain Arnett. ``This is a victory for reporters everywhere,''
Smith said. ``I am delighted that Peter Arnett's job has been
saved, provided it's unconditional and that CNN management did not
force him to take any positions that Peter felt he was forced to
agree to, to save his job.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arnett did not take the decision as a victory. Speaking from
the network's executive offices, Arnett said, ``Overall this is not
a victory for me at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that this story hurt CNN,'' he said. ``It certainly
hurt me. For those who say I should have been fired with the others
_ my reputation has taken a major hit around the world. As for my
colleagues who are fired _ I know all of them. I'm sorry. I respect
their work and I admire them.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett's byline appeared, along with Ms. Oliver's, on a Time
magazine story about the September 1970 mission in Laos, code-named
Operation Tailwind. The magazine has also retracted the report and
apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has appointed Rick Davis executive vice president for
standards and practices, to build in a mechanism to insure the
accuracy of the network's reporting. ``I am giving Rick Davis the
authority to look carefully into every questionable script,'' he
said. ``He will have the power to pull a program before airing no
matter where it's scheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
