<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BULLETS-ART-260&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC POLICE TO START USING HOLLOW-POINT BULLETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city Police Department is planning to equip its
entire force of almost 40,000 members with hollow-point bullets,
which cause much greater injury to people they strike but are
considered less likely to cut down bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Wednesday that within the
next 60 days the hollow-point bullets would begin replacing the
full-metal-jacket bullets that officers now use. Unlike the old
bullets, the hollow points flatten upon impact and then expand,
helping stop the bullet from passing through its target but causing
a wider wound _ and inflicting more severe internal damage,
forensic experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner first announced his intention to have the
department switch to hollow-point bullets _ which are already used
by federal law enforcement agencies and by dozens of other major
police departments across the country _ in March 1997 after the
Police Department had already spent $500,000 on nine million rounds
of the ammunition. But Safir's announcement came as Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani was running for re-election, and after critics expressed
concerns that the new bullets could prove more lethal, the mayor
halted the plan, saying that the issue needed further study.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after the Civilian Complaint Review Board, the
independent agency charged with monitoring the police, presented
its own report recommending the switch to hollow-point bullets,
Safir said he had already made the decision to use them and that he
expected the first shipments to arrive within 60 days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We are, in fact, going to switch to hollow-point ammunition as
soon as we receive it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are much safer then fully-jacketed bullets, which will go
through a person or tumble through a person's organs and then
continue on and hit innocent victims,'' Safir said. The
commissioner added that the Police Department had conducted its own
tests and decided that the hollow-point bullets would be an
improvement. ``It is the standard around the world in law
enforcement to use hollow points,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other police officials have pushed for the bullets because they
are more effective in stopping dangerous criminals, and they say
that that aspect further protects bystanders because officers have
to fire fewer shots to incapacitate their targets. The public can
also legally buy these bullets.
</P>
<P>
   But some people worried that the Police Department was making
the decision without sufficient public discussion or hard data.
Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union and a frequent critic of the police, said that
while hollow-point bullets would be less likely to ricochet or pass
through objects and strike bystanders, they would cause
significantly more damage to any innocent bystanders who were hit
directly. And he pointed out that since as many as a fifth of
police officers who are shot are hit by police gunfire, the
officers themselves could sustain graver injuries. ``This needs
more discussion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic experts said that the use of hollow points entailed a
trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It increases the wound's capacity to the victim, but it
reduces a risk that the police are always concerned about: the risk
of the bullet perforating the intended target and injuring a
bystander,'' said Dr. Stephen Hargarten, the director of the
Firearm Injury Center in Milwaukee, Wis. ``On the one hand, it
makes shootings safer in public settings. On the other hand, the
impact on the victim is greater.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, police officers in the Transit Bureau and the
Housing Bureau have used hollow-point bullets since 1990, before
they merged with the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to arm officers with hollow-point bullets comes
five years after the Police Department, after much anguished
debate, agreed to allow its officers to upgrade their weapons by
trading in their old .38-caliber service revolvers for 9-mm
semi-automatic pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Critics feared that the added capacity of the 9-mm pistols _
which hold 16 bullets, compared with the old six-shooters _ and the
ease with which they allow officers to fire multiple rounds would
lead to more accidental shootings. And while there were troubling
incidents early on _ including a shootout outside a Chinese
restaurant in Queens in 1995 in which police officers fired 247
rounds and killed a bystander _ the number of shooting incidents
has decreased each year since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster its argument in favor of the hollow bullets, the
Police Department pointed to recent statistics involving gunshots
that hit innocent bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics released by the department, 15 innocent
bystanders were struck by police officers using full-metal-jacket
bullets during 1995 and 1996, police said. Eight were hit directly,
five were hit by bullets that had passed through other people and
two were hit by bullets that had passed through objects. In that
same period, officers in the Transit Bureau, who already used the
hollow points, struck six bystanders. Four of them were hit
directly, one was hit by a bullet that ricocheted and another was
hit by a bullet that passed through an object.
</P>
<P>
   In that same period, 44 police officers were struck by police
gunfire using the old ammunition: 21 were hit directly, 2 were
struck by bullets that ricocheted and 17 were struck by bullets
that passed though other people. Of the four officers struck by
hollow-point bullets, three were hit directly and one was hit by a
bullet that passed through another person. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     07-08 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: KING RETRIAL IS A LESSON IN FUTILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the criminal retrial of Don King dragged on
Wednesday like one of the boxing czar's self-promotional
monologues, a 27-year-old aspiring law student said it sure looked
to him as if the government was about to absorb the second half of
a lethal one-two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their case just wasn't convincing, to me personally,'' said
Courtney Decasseres, a graduate this spring of the Borough of
Manhattan Community College who is moving on to Lincoln University
in the fall. ``If I was on the jury, I would have to acquit.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that Decasseres and about 20 other city
students in the U.S. District courtroom in Manhattan on Wednesday
represented the Our Children Foundation, a privately funded youth
culture group that has been the grateful beneficiary of the man on
trial on charges of wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Brown, the foundation's director, claimed that the
students have been attending the trial not as character props to
make King appear more sympathetic to the jurors but as young
scholars assigned to keep journals on this retrial of a case that
originally ended when a hung jury forced Judge Lawrence McKenna to
declare a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a law club at the foundation,'' said Decasseres.
``We've been to some of the law schools in the city, but this is
the first time we've actually had the chance to be inside the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get a grasp of the justice system. It's true
that Don King has been very helpful to us in the past, but I don't
find it difficult to be objective, though I can only speak for
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it doesn't take a King sympathizer or sycophant to get
the idea that the government, like most old fighters, just didn't
know when to quit. The second time around, this case has generated
all the public interest of a bantamweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting Brown's students, you can find more people in the
ring after most fights than there have been most days in McKenna's
courtroom. In contrast to the first trial, King's worst enemies
have not shown up to gloat, or root. Wednesday, when the previous
day's events with the jury in deliberation created the anticipation
of another mistrial, the news media didn't exactly come with an
O.J.-like swarm.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, this trial has, inexplicably, lasted almost four
months, counting jury selection in mid-March. Mass murder trials
wrap up faster. Entire pro basketball and hockey playoff seasons
have come and gone. If Marcia Clark were the prosecuting attorney,
she would be on her fifth make-over by now. And without trying to
sound ignorant of King's reputation and to the tax evasion charge
that finally nailed Al Capone, the question that gnaws at the core
of this trial is this:
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how King has managed to stay ahead of the posse for
years, why would sensible people believe that a jury would convict
him of defrauding a truly bloodless victim, Lloyd's of London, of
$350,000 seven long years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like there's anyone here that you can feel sorry
for,'' said Decasseres, which is no doubt what half the jurors in
the first trial thought and what at least a couple on this one are
thinking, too.
</P>
<P>
   After the jury forewoman on Tuesday, the third day of
deliberation, wrote a note to the judge complaining of another
juror's intransigence, McKenna spent most of Wednesday interviewing
jurors to determine whether the jury was tainted and, presumably,
whether he should declare another mistrial. The lawyers stood
around watching computer screens scroll up those interviews. The
students did word jumbles and played connect-the-dots and sipped
Snapple drinks through straws.
</P>
<P>
   They came before 9 a.m. and left after 6, and by the end of
another long day, Decasseres and friends were getting the idea that
the practice of law is much more exciting on television. ``Just
waiting for it to end,'' he said. ``Whenever that is.''
</P>
<P>
   If King beats this rap again, then he will be free to make the
only compelling match left in the fight game: him against Mike
Tyson. Thursday, in fact, is the first day that Tyson is eligible
to apply to the Nevada State Commission to have his license
revalidated, a year having passed since he was banished for
munching on Evander Holyfield's ear. Tyson wants to again fight
Holyfield, but he is suing to have his contract voided with King,
his longtime promoter.
</P>
<P>
   King vs. Tyson, now that's must-see-court-TV _ unlike this one,
which has prosecution failure written all over it. If so, at least
the students will have gotten their lesson in judicial law, and
federal waste. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
