 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Are Redbirds dead birds? Next 4 games may tell
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ The St. Louis Cardinals are not dead yet. It just seems
that way by the crater-sized hole they dug for themselves during an
underachieving, injury-filled first half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But St. Louis' life-support machine could be turned off this
weekend during a four-game series with the National League
Central-leading Astros that begins tonight at Busch Stadium. A
series once expected to carry significant weight in determining the
NL Central title has turned into a ``must-win'' set for the
Cardinals, who sit 12{ games behind the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bigger series for them than it is us for us,''
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``If they lose three
of four or get swept, that pretty much puts the last nail in the
coffin. A split really doesn't do much for either team.''
</P>
<P>
   Though little has gone well for the Cardinals in relation to
their record, hardly anyone has bothered _ or cared _ to notice.
The entire country is too busy charting Mark McGwire's assault on
baseball's most sacred record _ Roger Maris' single-season mark of
61 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Alone, McGwire is often enough to keep the fourth-place
Cardinals (40-46) in a game. And with outfielder Brian Jordan, the
NL's top hitter this year at .339, St. Louis was predicted by many
to win the Central division after nose-diving to a fourth-place
finish in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   None of that has seemed to matter, though, as injuries,
particularly to the Cardinals' starting rotation, have taken a
toll. Starting pitchers Alan Benes (shoulder surgery), Matt Morris
(sore right shoulder) and Donovan Osborne (sprained left shoulder)
are on the disabled list _ although Morris is expected to be
activated and start Friday's game _ while shortstop Royce Clayton,
second baseman Delino DeShields and outfielder Ron Gant have also
been bothered by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis entered the All-Star break with 10 losses in its last
13 games, with eight of the defeats coming to lowly Detroit,
Minnesota, Cincinnati and Kansas City _ a combined 43 games under
.500. After being swept in three games last weekend at Cincinnati,
the Cardinals conducted a 55-minute team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the three days off and what we were going to
do after the break to get back (in the race),'' said St. Louis
manager Tony La Russa, whose team has averaged less than three runs
during its last 13 games. ``We also talked about how we played the
last few games. We had a lot to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals suggest it is too early to count them out of the
race. They open a season-long 11-game homestand today against the
Astros, from whom they took two of three games at the Astrodome a
few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a good position right now,'' said McGwire, the
majors' home-run leader at the break with 37. ``Do we have the
potential of catching them? Oh, yeah. The second half is the
weirdest time of the year. Everybody has seen gigantic leads
dwindle down to one or two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played them tough in Houston. If we come out hard and win
four, I think it will send a message to the whole division that
we're for real, that the Cardinals are serious.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals do not gain ground in the division race this
weekend and fall further back in the pack, it's possible they might
consider shopping Jordan and Clayton, both of whom will be free
agents at the end of the season. Boston and San Francisco have been
rumored to be interested in Jordan, while Clayton could be headed
to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are well aware that just because you end the first
half atop the standings doesn't necessarily mean you'll remain
there. The Astros trailed Pittsburgh by one game at last year's
All-Star break before winning the division by five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals find themselves in a much worse predicament.
Before they challenge the Astros, they must find a way to move past
third-place Milwaukee and second-place Chicago. St. Louis is 5-9
against the rest of the Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be extremely difficult for them to come back,''
Hunsicker said. ``It's not just a matter of coming back and
catching us. They still have to catch two other teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
