</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS </SLUG>
 Q&AMP;A-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros in the driver's seat
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ The Astros begin the traditional second half of the
season tonight five games ahead of the closest competitor in the
National League Central and 19 games over .500.
</P>
<P>
   Their first-half start was one for the record books, tying the
1979 club for the best 87-game start in franchise history. But as
the '79 team can attest, a rabbit start combined with a turtle
finish can result in road kill. The 1979 team, which also began the
season with a 53-34 record, played three games under .500 the rest
of the way and stumbled to a second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   The current Astros obviously hope to avoid that fate. With that
in mind, here are 10 questions that could hold the difference
between a major meltdown and consecutive division titles:
</P>
<P>
   1) Does the schedule favor the Astros in the second half?
</P>
<P>
   Because they have a five-game lead, the Astros control their own
destiny. In other words, as long as they take care of their own
business, they don't need to worry about what the rest of the
division is doing. Fortunately for the Astros, the tough part of
their schedule is behind them. Forty of their remaining 75 games
are against teams with losing records, and 38 of their remaining
games will be played at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   2) Which Jose Lima will return from the All-Star break?
</P>
<P>
   Lima was perhaps the Astros' biggest surprise during the first
two months of the season, but things have turned sour for him
lately. The durable righthander was 6-1 with a 2.82 earned run
average in his first eight starts, but he's only 1-4 with a 4.41
ERA in his last 10 starts. Home runs have been his biggest problem.
Lima only allowed five homers in his first eight starts, but he has
surrendered 13 long balls since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Lima has been surfacing,'' general manager Gerry
Hunsicker said. ``He needs to keep his emotions under control and
focus on his game plan and his location.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lima doesn't rebound, the Astros' rotation suddenly loses
some of its sting.
</P>
<P>
   3) Will the arms of Sean Bergman and Pete Schourek hold up for
the remainder of the season?
</P>
<P>
   Bergman is on pace to pitch 173 innings, which would be 38 more
than his career high, and Schourek is on pace to log 104 innings _
something he hasn't done since 1995, when he pitched 190 innings
for the Reds. Both have experienced arm troubles this season, and
Schourek is coming off elbow surgery. Bergman is coming upon
unfamiliar territory, and there has to be at least some concern as
to how he will handle the workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be some concern because of that, but
the more success they have, the more confident they become,''
Hunsicker said. ``People predicted Darryl Kile would fade down the
stretch (last season), and that turned out not to be true. I think
the more (Bergman) pitches, the better he will become. After seeing
what he has done, I've developed a degree of confidence in him.''
</P>
<P>
   4) Is there a turnaround in Mike Magnante's future?
</P>
<P>
   He began the season as the top lefthander out of the bullpen
before closer Billy Wagner, but youngsters C.J. Nitkowski and
Trever Miller have been more dependable. Hunsicker, manager Larry
Dierker and pitching coach Vern Ruhle are in Magnante's corner, and
he needs to support their faith in the coming weeks. The walks must
be reduced significantly.
</P>
<P>
   5) Will the addition of Jay Powell have the desired impact on
the bullpen?
</P>
<P>
   Powell proved himself as a setup man last season, working the
seventh and eighth innings before Marlins manager Jim Leyland
turned the game over to Robb Nen. With Doug Henry on board, Powell
won't have to carry that much of the load with the Astros, but he
will be a key member and should strengthen the relief corps. It
will be interesting to see how Powell's arrival affects Dierker's
usage of Magnante, Nitkowski, Miller and rookie Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   6) Will Jeff Bagwell avoid consecutive second-half tailspins?
</P>
<P>
   That's a safe bet. Bagwell was uncharacteristically cold after
the 1997 All-Star break, batting just .250. History suggests that
was a fluke. Bagwell is a career .306 hitter after the All-Star
break, and _ despite his struggles _ he still managed to hit 19
homers and drive in 57 runs in the second half of the 1997 season.
He ended the first half on a tear, and no one would be surprised if
Bagwell picks up where he left off.
</P>
<P>
   7) How does Richard Hidalgo fit into the mix?
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo will have to accept his new role as a fourth outfielder
when he returns from the disabled list because Carl Everett has
played too well in center field to return to a platoon. If Hidalgo
is smart, he'll accept the role better than Bob Abreu, who found
himself in a similar situation last season and sulked his way back
to the minors and ultimately out of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   8) Will the bench finally pitch in?
</P>
<P>
   This has been the only disappointing area on the team, and it's
a shame, because the bench was supposed to be so much better with
the acquisitions of Dave Clark and Jack Howell. Clark is hitting
just .150, and Howell is likely out for the season with a broken
left wrist. The Astros' .137 pinch-hitting average is the worst in
the National League. They only have two extra-base hits and seven
RBIs off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   9) Will any injured players make a contribution?
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on much help here. Hidalgo notwithstanding, the
Astros can't rely on a significant contribution from their disabled
players. Pitchers Ramon Garcia and Chris Holt are out for the
season, and Howell is probably done, too. Righthanded reliever Jose
Cabrera is on a minor-league rehab assignment, but there may not be
room in the bullpen for him even if he does bounce back from a
shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   10) Is the current team good enough, or is another trade
necessary?
</P>
<P>
   Curt Schilling would be a nice addition, as would be Pete
Harnisch. Hunsicker would love to add a top-notch starting pitcher,
but that's probably not going to happen. Regardless, the Astros are
more than good enough to win the NL Central, and it would be a
disappointment if they don't reach the NL Championship Series. By
most accounts, the Astros are one of the top five teams in the
majors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
