<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-COACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS' COACHING SEARCH DOWN TO 5 CANDIDATES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls have narrowed their search for a coach to five
candidates and expect to name a successor to Phil Jackson in the
next two weeks, a team official said on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa State coach, Tim Floyd, long considered the leading
contender to replace Jackson, is scheduled to be interviewed, along
with four assistant coaches in the National Basketball Association:
the Bulls' Frank Hamblen, the Charlotte Hornets' Paul Silas, the
Indiana Pacers' Rick Carlisle and the Phoenix Suns' Scott Skiles.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, who is scheduled to be the first to meet with General
Manager Jerry Krause, will speak with him on Friday. The interview
process is expected to take between 10 days and two weeks, said the
team official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Several other candidates have been mentioned, among them former
Bulls player Bill Cartwright, now an assistant coach with the team;
Jim Paxson, also a former Chicago Bull, and George Karl, who was
dismissed as the Seattle Sonics' coach soon after his team was
eliminated from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   After having guided the franchise to six championships in the
1990s, Jackson announced soon after the Bulls won their most recent
title that he would not return to coach another season. Given that
he and Bulls' chairman Jerry Reinsdorf mutually agreed last summer
that they would part ways after Jackson completed a one-year deal
worth $5 million, there had been many rumors all season as to who
would take over the the team.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling among many league observers is that Krause, who
could not be reached for comment Wednesday night, will choose
Floyd, whom he has occasionally gone fishing with and considers a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Jordan, who has not decided whether to play next
season, may have veto power. The team official said that Jordan had
been consulted on each candidate and did not appear to have any
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle, 37, ran the offense for Larry Bird last season and is
regarded as one of the best young minds in the game. His system,
predicated on ball movement, helped the Pacers overcome many
quicker, more athletic teams. A former teammate of Bird's on the
Boston Celtics, Carlisle spent five years with the New Jersey Nets
before coaching under P.J. Carlesimo in Portland for three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Silas was edged out by his friend and former teammate Paul
Westphal for the Seattle SuperSonics job last month. He turns 55 on
Sunday, but relates to young players and works well with them. He
has not been a head coach since 1983 when he finished his third
season with the San Diego Clippers before they moved to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming an assistant to Dave Cowens in Charlotte, he
coached under Pat Riley in New York, Chuck Daly in New Jersey and
Cotton Fitzsimmons and Westphal in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Hamblen is a career assistant coach. Hamblen, Jimmy Rodgers, who
recently resigned as a Bulls assistant, and former Bulls assistant
Jim Cleamons were hugely responsible for Chicago's success under
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, a long shot for the position, is the most intriguing
candidate. At 34 years old, he would unseat the New York Knicks'
Jeff Van Gundy as the youngest coach in the league if he were to be
hired. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
