<HEADLINE>
WIFE, BOYFRIEND ARRESTED IN HUSBAND'S KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM WALSH AND JUDI VILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Mesa man obsessed about his affair with his best friend's wife
killed the friend with an ax and stuffed the body in a bathtub,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The body remained in the tub for six days, while the man, the
victim's wife and a 2{-year-old girl lived in the one-bedroom,
one-bath apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're mine, I own you,'' Arthur Osborne, 48, told the
victim's wife, Elizabeth Constance ``Connie'' Terwilliger, 29,
according to a police source who asked to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she was an emotionally abused wife,'' the police
source said. ``She became involved briefly with Osborne. He became
emotionally obsessed with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Connie Terwilliger told police that Osborne killed her husband,
Tom Terwilliger, when she refused to leave him because she still
loved him.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, police believe Tom Terwilliger was
slain about two months ago, on May 10, which was Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne and Terwilliger admitted that they eventually loaded the
body into a cardboard box and into Osborne's pickup truck, and then
took it to a desert area near Maricopa, the records said.
</P>
<P>
   Terwilliger told police Osborne was visiting the apartment May
10 when she went for a 45-minute walk with her daughter, leaving
Osborne and her husband alone, the records said.
</P>
<P>
   Terwilliger said that when she returned, Osborne showed her the
body in the bathtub and threatened to kill her and her daughter if
she told anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Terwilliger told police she never reported her husband's murder
because of Osborne's threat, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne also threatened to frame Terwilliger for the murder, the
police source said, if she ever found another boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell them it was you all along,'' Terwilliger quoted
Osborne as saying, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
   Terwilliger's subsequent relationship with another boyfriend in
her apartment complex prompted Osborne to make good on that threat,
the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne called police to the Terwilliger apartment in the 1900
block of West University Drive on Thursday and told them he may
have disposed of a murder victim's body, the court records said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Osborne, who claimed he was Tom Terwilliger's best
friend, led police to Terwilliger's decomposed body, which was
identified through fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Osborne and Terwilliger were arrested by Mesa
police on suspicion of first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   They came into the Mesa police station together around 5 p.m. to
inquire about Osborne's truck and some other property that had been
impounded, said Sgt. Brian Kozak, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Judge Clayton Hamblen of West Mesa Justice Court
ordered Osborne and Terwilliger held without bond. A preliminary
court appearance is scheduled for July 21.
</P>
<P>
   In court records, both Osborne and Connie Terwilliger denied
killing Tom Terwilliger, 36, and accused each other of the crime.
They both admitted helping to dispose of his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's saying she did it, she's saying he did it,'' the police
source said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time Osborne was accused of lashing out
violently because of a relationship with a woman.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1989, Osborne was arrested in Kingman after an
attack on his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced in February 1990 to two concurrent seven-year
sentences for aggravated assault and attempted kidnapping, after a
sexual assault charge was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne apparently became angry when his girlfriend went out one
night and didn't return home until the following morning, according
to Mohave County Superior Court records.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman returned home, Osborne put a .38-caliber handgun
between her eyes, then hit her on the head with the gun, the
records say. He raped the woman and beat her with a belt before
forcing her to write a suicide note and then threatening to kill
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hurt too many people that I love,'' the note said. ``I can
no longer live with myself. I must kill myself. It's the only way
out. I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The note was signed with the woman's name, Social Security
number and driver's license number, the court records say, but the
woman eventually escaped and called police.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne initially was placed in medium security at the Arizona
State Prison at Florence, but was moved to minimum security in
April 1993, said Michael Arra, a spokesman for the state Department
of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne was paroled in April 1994 and his parole ended that
October, Arra said.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's court appearance, a tearful Terwilliger hugged
relatives before she was led away to a Maricopa County jail.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives declined comment, both in the courtroom and at a south
Phoenix mobile home park where Connie Terwilliger's parents live. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
