u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZ-HNS &LR;      07-08 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Column: All-Star Game still strikes chord
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ This is my favorite leftover note from the 69th
All-Star baseball gala:
</P>
<P>
   David Wells was only the third New York Yankees pitcher to start
in this showcase since 1969, when Mel Stottlemyre took the loss in
Washington. Mel was actually a replacement, pressed into service
when the game was postponed a day because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Denny McLain of Detroit had to miss his scheduled start because
of a previous appointment with his dentist. Either Denny was
suffering from a problem with a really major toothache, or the
incident reestablishes one of two things: the power of dentistry in
America, or the flakiness of the pitchers of another era.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't clear how many All-Star moundsmen wish they had
undergone a root canal Tuesday, as opposed to taking part in a game
that produced 21 runs, 31 hits and a marathon 13-8 win for the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, when you talk to a baseball lifer, and you ask him (or
her) to explain the nuances of a game that had wiped out 16
pitchers, you can expect an answer along the lines of, ``That's
what makes this game so great.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this is the beauty of baseball. It isn't always
greatness that captures our fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we are moved by a story of the heart. Walt Weiss, the
Atlanta shortstop, playing in his first All-Star Game at 34 and
doing it almost out-of-body. A week earlier, his 3-year-old son,
Brody, had a brush with death, then miraculously recovered from an
E-Coli bacteria infection.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss collected two hits, a run and an RBI, but he had eyes only
for his little boy, sitting in the stands, cradled in his mom's
lap. Brody passed a final medical test Tuesday night, eating a hot
dog.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we are grabbed by a story of redemption. This was a
game that made a hero of a player _ Baltimore's Roberto Alomar _
who had been the sport's most maligned man in 1996 after he spat on
an umpire. (At least Roberto never denied it. When a well-known pro
football player did the same to an opponent, he tried to claim it
was a sneeze.)
</P>
<P>
   Alomar led off the AL's sixth-inning rally with an infield
single, stole third and scored on a passed ball. His three hits
included a bases-empty homer and earned him the Most Valuable
Player trophy, a year after the honor was won by his big brother,
Sandy, the Cleveland catcher.
</P>
<P>
   There were four players _ the Alomars, Barry Bonds, and Junior
Griffey _ who were the sons of former players, making the game
suitable for family viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is a game of individuals, really. It is not a team
sport, at least not in the sense football is. A Mark McGwire can
crunch homers at a record clip for a losing St. Louis team, as
Griffey does for Seattle. But Barry Sanders is going to get stuffed
like a cabbage if the Detroit Lions don't block a lick.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this exactly answers the question that was put to
Cal Ripken: Why is baseball's All-Star Game romanticized in a way
that doesn't apply to football or basketball? The Pro Bowl is
played after the season, when hardly anyone cares except the
players and their wives, who get a trip to Hawaii. The NBA All-Star
festival has enjoyed a recent boom, but it is still at bottom a
playground game, with an occasional trapeze act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with baseball,'' said Ripken, ``you begin with all
that history.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you do. Even the casual fan knows Babe Ruth hit the
first home run in an All-Star Game in 1933. Who else? Pick a year,
any year, and you might come up with Carl Hubbell, striking out
consecutively five of the greatest hitters the game has known; Ted
Williams riding Rip Sewell's ``eephus pitch'' over the fence; or
Reggie Jackson lifting one into the light towers at Tiger Stadium,
just like the scene from The Natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my dad was managing in the minors,'' Ripken went on,
``we'd all get together and sit around the TV and watch the
All-Star Game. It made you feel good, something about the middle of
the summer that brings everyone together.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, it was the novelty of seeing the elite of the two
leagues tangle, as they did only three times a year, spring
training and the World Series being the others. It was that rare
chance to see on the same field Joe DiMaggio and Stan Musial, Lefty
Grove and Dizzy Dean, Mantle and Mays, on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that this special character was the trade-off when
the owners adopted interleague play _ which seems to be working, at
a price to be paid later.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell that seeing aliens from the other league is losing
its novelty when the players welcome their return to intramural
combat. McGwire was looking ahead to the Cardinals' four-game
series at home against the first-place Astros. ``I think we're 12{
games out,'' he said correctly. ``I know we play them tough. If we
win four, it sends a message: that the Cardinals are serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the Astros consider the source.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
