<SLUG> BC-FUND-DREYFUS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DREYFUS BEGINS INQUIRY INTO MANAGER'S TRADING ACTIVITIES  (jw) 
 By   EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dreyfus Corp &UR; . &LR;  said Wednesday that it has placed the
former portfolio manager of two of its mutual funds on ``paid
administrative leave'' as part of an inquiry into the manager's
personal trading activities.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Dreyfus comes amid a widening investigation by
federal and state securities regulators into the activities of
Michael Schonberg, who until April was the lead manager of two
Dreyfus funds that have suffered big losses in the last two years
by investing in shares of small companies. The New York state
attorney general's office is conducting an investigation into
whether Schonberg, former manager of the Dreyfus Aggressive Growth
Fund and the Dreyfus Premier Aggressive Growth Fund, personally
benefited from directing the funds to buy shares of companies whose
securities he owned in his personal account, according to a person
involved in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has also begun a
preliminary inquiry into the situation, according to a person close
to the matter. Dreyfus, a subsidiary of Mellon Bank Corp., began
its own investigation last month into the trading activities of the
fund and Schonberg after a well-known short-seller raised questions
about the funds' investment in shares of Chromatics Color
Sciences, &UR;  &LR; a development-stage medical products company.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday announcing that it had placed Schonberg
on paid leave, Dreyfus said, ``Given the thoroughness required by
Dreyfus with respect to its previously reported inquiry and the
interests of all concerned, this initiative is designed to
facilitate the process and to assure that Schonberg's time will
continue to be devoted exclusively to this inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Schonberg did not return a phone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The current uproar over the Dreyfus manager erupted last month,
when Manuel Asensio, a New York investor who specializes in
short-selling _ that is, betting that the price of certain stocks
will fall _ issued a flurry of press releases accusing Dreyfus of
failing to properly supervise Schonberg.
</P>
<P>
   Schonberg owned shares of Chromatics Color Sciences
International in his personal account before joining Dreyfus in
August 1995. Asensio contended that the manager's aggressive buying
of the shares for the Dreyfus funds was ``clear evidence of
wrongful utilization of investors' money.'' .
</P>
<P>
   Schonberg also owned other securities in his own personal
portfolio before buying them for the funds, including shares of
Tidel Technologies, formerly known as American Medical
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   It is not illegal for a portfolio manager to own securities that
are also held in a fund he manages. But federal securities laws
prohibit managers from taking certain actions in the funds they
manage that will benefit their personal accounts, and many fund
companies also have rules about when and how a fund manager can
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has been studying whether to tighten its rules regarding
personal trading. Barry Barbash, the director of the SEC's division
of investment management, which regulates mutual funds, said in an
interview that his staff would soon recommend to the commission
stronger compliance systems for managers' personal trading.
</P>
<P>
   Barbash said among the proposals being considered were measures
that would require a fund manager to disclose his personal
securities holdings upon joining a new company, that would require
a fund company to file its code of ethics with the commission, and
that would tighten the obligations of a fund's independent
directors in reviewing fund managers' personal trading.
</P>
<P>
   The New York attorney general's office is also looking into
whether Dreyfus misled investors in its disclosures about the types
of stocks in which the funds would invest and in its advertising of
the performance of the Aggressive Growth Fund in late 1996,
according to a person close to the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry began in December 1996 after it was learned that few
investors in the fund had enjoyed the phenomenal performance that
was being advertised at the time by Dreyfus, the person said.
</P>
<P>
   In the year ended Sept. 30, 1996, the Aggressive Growth Fund
gained 82 percent. But most of the gains occurred early in that
year, while the fund had only a few million dollars of assets.
After Dreyfus began advertising the fund's red-hot performance and
investors flocked to buy shares, the fund suffered losses, leaving
most shareholders in the red.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while the fund's total return in the 1996 fiscal year
equaled 82 percent, the fund's financial statements showed that it
lost nearly $11 million of investors' money.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
