<HEADER>
A6669 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROWN-RESIGN-2NDLD-WR     07-08 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-RESIGN-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINA BROWN RESIGNS AS EDITOR OF THE NEW YORKER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add several short inserts and for light rewriting 
 throughout)  (Eds: See also BROWN-HOLLYWOOD and BROWN-NEWHOUSE) 
(ART ADV: A graphic and a photo of Tina Brown are being sent to NYT
graphic/photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-1243, 4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JANNY SCOTT AND GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tina Brown, the Oxford-educated and Fleet
Street-trained magazine editor who for better or worse pulled The
New Yorker into the late 20th century, announced Wednesday that she
would resign as editor to start a company affiliated with Miramax
Films that would publish a new monthly magazine, publish books and
produce films and television programming.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown's announcement came after months of rumors of growing
tension between her and Conde Nast Publications, which owns The New
Yorker, over the company's attempts to make the magazine less
unprofitable. Although it won nearly two dozen major awards during
Ms. Brown's six-year tenure and newsstand sales rose 145 percent,
it lost $11 million last year. In total, it has lost more than $100
million in its 13 years of ownership by Conde Nast, which is in
turned owned by Advance Publications.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Harvey Weinstein, a co-chairman of
Miramax, said he approached Ms. Brown about the new venture just
one month ago after reading newspaper reports that her contract
with Conde Nast was expiring. Ms. Brown then introduced Weinstein
to Ronald Galotti, who is the publisher of Vogue magazine and had
worked with Ms. Brown at Vanity Fair, both owned by Conde Nast.
Galotti will leave Vogue, which is also owned by Conde Nast, to be
Ms. Brown's partner in the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   A Conde Nast spokeswoman, Andrea Kaplan, said a successor to Ms.
Brown would be named shortly.
</P>
<P>
   An editor with a flair for show business, Ms. Brown transformed
The New Yorker from a venerated icon that some said was verging on
irrelevance into a kind of news magazine of the power elite. Her
resignation, effective Aug. 1, offers S.I. Newhouse Jr., who is
chairman of Advance Publications, the chance once again to reshape
the identity of The New Yorker, which more than most magazines has
reflected the particular intelligence and idiosyncracies of its top
editors, from Harold Ross and William Shawn to Robert Gottlieb and
Ms. Brown. But it remains unclear whether it will ever be possible
to make The New Yorker a home for the kind of high-quality literary
journalism and humor that made it famous, and, at the same time,
make it profitable for Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine has had only the four editors in its nearly 75-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the staff said they were stunned and upset by the
news, which Ms. Brown delivered shortly after 10 a.m. to a small
group of writers and editors she had summoned to a meeting billed
as a discussion of coming issues.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Brown, she and Galotti will now embark upon the
seemingly risky adventure of trying to create the kind of so-called
synergy that has become a buzz word in media and entertainment
circles _ in this case, inventing a magazine from scratch to dig up
the kind of articles that might then be turned into movies and
television specials that Miramax, which is owned by Walt Disney
Co., would have the capacity to help package, circulate and
promote.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will be the guinea pig of synergy,'' said Peter Kaplan,
editor of The New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old daughter of George Hambley Brown, the British
movie producer who brought out the first Agatha Christie mystery
films, and Bettina Iris Mary Brown, Laurence Olivier's press agent,
who later became a gossip columnist for a magazine for expatriates
in Spain, Ms. Brown made her name in the early 1980s when she
rejuvenated the stodgy British society monthly, the Tatler, making
it slick and trendy and quadrupling its circulation.
</P>
<P>
   She went from there to editor in chief of Vanity Fair in 1984,
where again she nearly quadrupled its circulation in just five
years, putting celebrities on the cover, hiring photographers like
Richard Avedon and doubling or tripling what writers were paid.
Over the last six years, she has introduced many of the same
principles to The New Yorker, raising its circulation from 659,000
in late 1992 to 808,000 in the last half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Ms. Brown revolutionized the image and soul of
the magazine, long known for indulging its writers in articles of
impressive length on subjects inspired by their personal passions
as much as the news of the week. It was a magazine admired for
brilliant foreign reporting and its impeccable taste and sometimes
laughed at for its multipart series on topics like grains.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown shifted its focus to the country's three power centers
_ New York, Washington and Los Angeles. She made it topical in ways
it seemed to have prided itself on never being. Its covers became
willfully provocative, its voice more than occasionally glib.
People talked about it constantly, admirers and detractors alike.
In response to the charge that she vulgarized the magazine, Ms.
Brown said Wednesday, ``I've always believed in lapses of taste.''
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Ms. Brown introduced a new stable of widely
admired writers to The New Yorker, including David Remnick, Louis
Menand, Anthony Lane and Henry Louis Gates. Its coverage of the war
in Rwanda, by Philip Gourevitch, was highly praised. At the same
time, she enlisted Roseanne Barr as a guest editor of a special
issue on women, ran a profile of a dominatrix by Paul Theroux, and
invited Dick Morris to a breakfast with reporters and advertisers
two weeks after a sex scandal forced him to resign as an adviser to
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went too far sometimes,'' said Michael Kinsley, editor of
the online magazine Slate, who formerly edited The New Republic and
who credited Ms. Brown Wednesday with making The New Yorker what he
called the most exciting magazine in America. ``But if you're
afraid of going too far, you don't go far enough. She takes risks.
Sometimes they're embarrassments but they're a price worth
paying.''
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, rumors spread that Ms. Brown and Conde
Nast were increasingly unhappy with each other.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Ms. Brown's husband, Harold Evans, resigned as
president and publisher of Random House's trade group, which is
also owned by Newhouse. Though he said he left in order to become
editorial director and vice chairman of Mortimer Zuckerman's
publications, including The Daily News of New York, many media
executives suspected that Newhouse had at least been willing to go
along with the change because Evans was insufficiently concerned
with the business' bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Brown was said to be displeased by a decision to draw
The New Yorker under the corporate umbrella of Conde Nast and to
sell its advertising pages in packages with pages for other Conde
Nast publications. She had also objected unsuccessfully to a plan
by Conde Nast to move The New Yorker out of its home on West 43rd
Street into a new Conde Nast edifice in Times Square along with all
of the other magazines in the group.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ms. Brown was widely said to be dissatisfied with
the president of The New Yorker, Tom Florio. But when he was
suddenly replaced at the start of Memorial Day weekend, Ms. Brown
was not consulted on his successor. She was given just one day's
advance notice that the job would be filled by David Carey of Conde
Nast House &AMP; Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Ms. Brown and Weinstein, who is 46,
said they first discussed the subject of so-called new media
ventures on the Miramax plane flying back from a New Yorker
conference on the future at the Disney Institute in Orlando, Fla.,
and attended by media moguls like Michael Eisner, Disney's
chairman, and Barry Diller, chief executive of USA Networks. But
Weinstein said he did not formally approach Ms. Brown about the
undertaking announced Wednesday until a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said she then brought in Galotti, 48, who was
publisher of Vanity Fair during the last two years of Ms. Brown's
tenure there. He had left abruptly for a job at Esquire in 1993
amid rumors that Newhouse had forced him out; however, he returned
shortly afterward as publisher of Vogue. Galotti, who is said to
have been the model for the bombastic, sex-machine character called
Big in Candace Bushnell's column and now television series ``Sex
and the City,'' had also been founding publisher of Conde Nast
Traveler when Evans started it.
</P>
<P>
   According to Weinstein, he and Ms. Brown reached an agreement on
the deal at 5 p.m. Tuesday. He said he and Galotti came to terms at
2:30 a.m. Wednesday. Ms. Brown, who had eaten lunch with Newhouse
on Monday without ever discussing her possible plans, said
Wednesday that she had informed Newhouse of her resignation at 9
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ms. Brown and Galotti said that what attracted them most
about the offer, and what made it worth quitting their jobs for,
was the prospect of owning the company they would create. ``It is
the quintessential enticement that Harvey put before us,'' Galotti
said. Without that, they suggested, they would not have chosen to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Neither they nor Weinstein offered many details of the proposed
company, which is to be based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown will be chairman and Galotti will be president.
Weinstein said the company would be separate from Miramax but would
operate like a division, feeding projects to Miramax. The magazine,
which Ms. Brown would describe only with adjectives like ``upscale,
contemporary, sophisticated,'' is to make its debut in the fall of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, Conde Nast announced that Richard Beckman,
publisher of GQ, would replace Galotti at Vogue. Ms. Kaplan, a vice
president for corporate communications at Conde Nast, said Newhouse
would make no statement on Ms. Brown's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Within Conde Nast itself, one conceivable candidate might be
Graydon Carter, Ms. Brown's successor at the highly profitable
Vanity Fair. But staff members said Wednesday that Carter had said
he was not Ms. Brown's replacement. Another rumored possibility
might be Kurt Andersen, who edited New York magazine and currently
writes a column called ``The Culture Industry'' for The New Yorker.
He said Wednesday night that he had not been approached.
</P>
<P>
   Other names being bandied about on the grapevine Wednesday
ranged from Remnick to Kinsley. ``Well, no one's called me,''
Kinsley said cheerfully, when asked if he was in the running. It
seemed at least conceivable, too, that Newhouse might have been
caught by surprise and not yet have a successor or a vision for the
magazine's future in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the staff of The New Yorker insisted Wednesday
that Newhouse had tried hard to convince Ms. Brown to sign a
five-year contract; they speculated that she had finally grown fed
up with dealing with Conde Nast. Admirers of Ms. Brown described
her departure as a terrible loss to the magazine; even those with
more complicated feelings about Ms. Brown were said to have never
wanted her to leave, for fear of getting someone worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
