<HEADLINE>
MEXICO CUTS '98 BUDGET OUTLAYS TO MATCH DROP IN OIL INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico said Wednesday that it would slice an
additional $730 million from federal spending in 1998, taking
bitter fiscal medicine for the third time this year in an effort to
maintain stability despite dropping oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Added to federal budget trims announced in January and March,
the new reductions bring Mexico's cutbacks so far this year to $3.7
billion, closely matching its lost oil revenue. Finance Minister
Angel Gurria said Wednesday that the country would stick to its
original target of a modest federal deficit for 1998, on the order
of 1.25 percent of economic output.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is again seeking to shield itself from the fallout of the
economic turmoil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no deer-in-the-headlights syndrome in Mexico,'' said
Ernest Brown, an economist with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``They
are making a very hard-nosed decision to cut yet again.''
</P>
<P>
   The earlier cuts helped to sustain investor confidence in the
economic leadership of President Ernesto Zedillo. Growth has
continued to surge, reaching 6.6 percent in the first quarter, and
foreign investment continues to flow in.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's cuts showed that Mexico cannot protect itself
entirely against the volatility emanating from Asia. The government
still depends on oil revenue for about a third of its annual
income. Petroleum prices have plunged this year because of flagging
demand in the giant Asian economies, including Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The budget cuts are based on a new downward revision of the
estimated average 1998 price of Mexican petroleum exports that
Energy Minister Luis Tellez announced Wednesday to $11.50 a barrel
from $12.50.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mexico is not a member of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, it has joined a coordinated global effort to
reduce the oil supply by cutting back its production by 200,000
barrels a day. Even so, Mexico's petroleum exports brought an
average of only $10.61 a barrel in the first half of this year,
Tellez said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gurria said that the federal spending cuts would not come out of
budgets for health, education, anti-poverty, police or justice
programs. About $280 million will be taken from exploration and
other programs of Petroleos Mexicanos, or Pemex, the state-owned
oil monopoly. The government also received an unexpected $370
million from increased tax collection and sales of state-owned
railroads and telecommunications services, Gurria said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were relieved that the government decided not to raise
any prices, which might have driven inflation upward.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just said, `We are going to engineer more pain,''' Brown
of Morgan Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors welcomed the new cutbacks. The leading indicator of
the Mexican stock market rose 62.67 points, or 1.39 percent, to
4,573.28 points, its seventh gain in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision is sure to draw fire in Congress, where Gurria
is trying to win approval to transfer $65 billion in debts out of a
federal bank bailout program and include them in the overall
government debt.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the bank bailout, the government will have to ask for
funds to service the interest on bad bank loans it took over from
weak or failed Mexican banks. But many lawmakers, including a
number from the government's own party, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, regard the entire bailout as a political loser
in which Mexican taxpayers are being asked to absorb huge burdens
to pay for the mistakes of wealthy bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The new round of spending cuts is likely to increase skepticism
in the lower house of Congress, which is controlled by the
opposition, about providing funds for the bank bailout, a crucial
piece of a broad package of urgently needed financial reforms the
government has been battling for since March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
