u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STADIUM-REFERENDUM     07-08 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STADIUM-REFERENDUM-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONX OFFICIAL FILES U.S. COMPLAINT OVER STADIUM REFERENDUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's effort to block a public
referendum on the future of Yankee Stadium was the target of
another attack Wednesday, when Bronx Borough President Fernando
Ferrer filed a complaint with the Justice Department, contending
that blocking the referendum would violate the federal Voting
Rights Act of 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer said the referendum _ on whether tax dollars should be
spent to build a new stadium for the New York Yankees _ would
sharply increase voter turnout in New York City, because most
residents firmly believe that the baseball team should not leave
its stadium in the Bronx. He said the referendum would increase
turnout particularly in the Bronx, where most voters are members of
minorities and ardently want the Yankees to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The Voting Rights Act outlaws racially discriminatory voting
laws. It also requires New York City and other regions with a
history of low minority voter turnouts to submit all changes in
election procedures to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This potentially disenfranchises hundreds of thousands of
voters,'' said Ferrer, who held a news conference at Yankee Stadium
on Wednesday to announce that he had asked the Justice Department
to investigate whether Giuliani was violating the voting act.
``Precluding the stadium referendum will not only decrease public
participation on all issues on the November ballot, but it will
suppress minority voter participation.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is trying to block the stadium referendum, proposed in
April by City Council Speaker Peter Vallone, by proposing another
referendum, which would ask voters to approve changes to the City
Charter. Under city law, charter-related questions take precedence
over other questions. The mayor wants to use a business tax to help
build a new stadium, probably in Manhattan, that he has said might
be necessary to dissuade the Yankees from leaving the city
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In attacking Giuliani's charter revision proposal Wednesday,
Ferrer joined a growing group of politicians and private citizens
fighting to keep charter-related questions off the ballot. A
commission named by the mayor to explore changes to the charter has
been assailed in recent weeks for rushing to complete its
recommendations before November.
</P>
<P>
   And in public hearings around the city, dozens of people have
accused the commission of plotting serious changes to the charter
for no reason but to help Giuliani keep the stadium question off
the ballot.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The commission appeared to be responding to the criticism
earlier this week, when its chairman, Peter Powers, announced that
the panel would stop exploring contentious changes in the balance
of power in city government _ like abolishing the office of the
public advocate _ and focus instead on less controversial issues.
But commission members have pressed on with their goal of making
recommendations in time for a November referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Powers and Giuliani have dismissed much of the criticism on the
charter questions as politically motivated, and Wednesday both said
Ferrer's complaint was not valid. ``It doesn't make any sense,''
Powers said. ``A lot of people will come out to vote, because there
is a tremendous amount of debate on this charter.'' He added, ``The
mayor set up a charter commission and this, in my mind, has nothing
to do with a baseball referendum.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive director of the charter commission, Elizabeth St.
Clair, said a charter-related referendum ``absolutely would not''
violate the Voting Rights Act, because it would not affect standard
voting procedures in the city. ``The Justice Department is not in
the business of dictating what a city should put on its ballot in
order to affect voter turnout,'' Ms. St. Clair said. ``We think
Ferrer is absolutely incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer, whose borough stands to lose its most famous and
lucrative landmark if the Yankees depart, also boycotted a public
hearing held by the Charter Revision Commission in the Bronx on
Wednesday night, saying he did not want to participate in ``a
charade.'' But Giuliani said Wednesday that Ferrer's criticism was
only increasing the chance that the Yankees would leave the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a right to make a decision about where they want to
be,'' the mayor said of the baseball team. ``This is a mindless way
to approach trying to keep a private business in your borough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
