<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BK-TEAM </SLUG>
 USA-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Let the no-names begin quest for true-grit team
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ At one end, somebody named Nate Huffman was shooting
15-foot hook shots.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a guy who might be the shortest player in the league
even if the league is the WNBA, 5-5 Earl Boykins, was flinging
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Working on his free throws across the gym at Moody Bible
Institute was Acie Earl, whose bones were dug up by America's best
archaeologists just for this event.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Rudy Tomjanovich, right in the middle of the
action, perhaps feeling like he arrived on vacation only to find
the surroundings looking a whole lot different than they did in the
travel brochure.
</P>
<P>
   Except that this is hardly a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   As one of Tomjanovich's assistant, Del Harris of the Los Angeles
Lakers, said: ``We were suppose to come here, have a little workout
in the morning, then play golf all afternoon. But that's changed a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a little. When you expect Tim Duncan and Tim Hardaway
and get Tim Breaux and Tim Kempton, you know there's a lot of work
ahead when it comes to taking on the world.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what USA Basketball is calling this adventure: Taking
On The World. For Tomjanovich, Harris and Lon Kruger of the
University of Illinois, all they have to do is whip this motley
crew of replacement players into shape in less than three weeks
before the World Championship of Basketball starts in Athens,
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 NBA players who were suppose to be on this U.S. team are
long gone, casualties of the labor dispute between the league and
its players.
</P>
<P>
   So now it's up to Tomjanovich and friends to make chicken salad
out of chicken feathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a bunch of guys working hard,'' Tomjanovich said
Wednesday night after the 29 hopefuls for the U.S. squad went
through their first workout, a two-hour-plus marathon packed with
scrimmage sessions. ``We're going to have five practices to
evaluate them, and then make our first cuts. We want to be as fair
as possible. We want to get the right chemistry. And we're looking
for players who complement each other well and play hard at both
ends.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one other thing that Tomjanovich and his staff are
looking for: an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Without NBA players, the U.S. team will be a long shot to win
the gold medal in Athens. Therefore, Tomjanovich wants a team with
the kind of true grit John Wayne would be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally tough guys,'' he said when asked what he was looking
for out of those trying out for the 12-man roster. ``I think those
teams over there (in Europe) feel they are going to have a cakewalk
with our NBA guys not going. And we've got to have guys who feel
it's us against the world and are really united. Toughness and
sticking together will be important.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said that everybody connected with the U.S. team is well
aware that America's role in the World Championships has changed.
Fans who were promised NBA stars will get no-named replacements.
But the depth of U.S. basketball will be challenged. And it's clear
that the underdog mentality has sunk in already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a different situation,'' Harris said. ``You go
from where you're the obvious overdog to where you're getting
reports from Europe that the teams over there are upset that we're
not sending good players, and that the fans are upset that they
paid money for tickets to see NBA players and are not going to see
a good team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we jump into the role of underdog. At first, it was a bit
of a shock. But then, after you analyze it a little bit, it's
almost a challenge you can't resist. We really feel like this is a
worthwhile challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing a big hurdle. But if we can do it, it's going to
be something that we'll remember. The odds are against us. But on
the other hand, we're going to end up being better than people
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the players showed as much quickly during the first
practice. Tomjanovich did not wish to single out any players, but
it was clear that former Texas Tech star Jason Sasser, former
Washington Wizard Larry Stewart and University of Connecticut
standout Richard Hamilton shined in the inaugural workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very few strangers to us out here, but now these next
four practices are going to be big as far as finding out what we've
got,'' Tomjanovich said. ``The NBA players not being here hasn't
changed how I feel about coaching this team _ that it's a great
honor. And it hasn't changed our goal _ and that's to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is that the team is going to have to work
harder, and the coaches are going to have to work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when you are hoping for Jason Kidd and end
up with Warren Kidd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
