r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-OFFENSE-TEX     07-08 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL REACHING FOR RECORDS, BUT HAS EXPANSION DILUTED
ACHIEVEMENTS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Maris removed Babe Ruth's name from the record books when
he swatted 61 balls over fences in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven years later, baseball statisticians have erasers
poised over Maris' name.
</P>
<P>
   Burly St. Louis Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire has Maris'
single-season home-run record squarely in his sights, with 37, and
Ken Griffey Jr. (35) and Sammy Sosa (33) are also a threat to the
most hallowed record in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   There is a common thread between Maris, McGwire, Griffey and
Sosa, other than their names and the phrase ``home-run record'' in
the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball expanded by two teams in 1961, adding the Los Angeles
Angels and Washington Senators. Baseball expanded by two teams in
1998, adding the Arizona Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Maris hit 61? The popular, off-the-top-of-the-head
response is expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Why are McGwire, Griffey and Sosa challenging Maris? And for
that matter, why is Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez challenging
Hack Wilson's single-season record for runs batted in? Expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Right?
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   And wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers suggest that expansion has an impact, but the
numbers behind the numbers indicate that the impact isn't as great
as generally believed. Yes, great hitters are having monstrous
seasons. However, the league-wide numbers are similar to a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The argument for the expansion effect involves simple
arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stands to reason, it makes mathematical sense, that if you
take 22 pitchers that would be in the minor leagues and put them in
the big leagues, it's diluted,'' said Rangers broadcaster Tom
Grieve, who has seen expansion as a player, general manager and
announcer.
</P>
<P>
   There are some numbers to support the expansion-equals-offense
theory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the National League had a composite .243 batting
average, 2.99 earned-run average and averaged 6.86 runs per game.
The AL hit .230, had a 2.98 ERA and scored 6.81 run per game.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, when two teams were added to each league, the NL jumped
to a .250 average and 3.59 ERA, and scoring soared to 8.11 runs per
game. There was a similar bump in the AL, where the league average
went up to .246, the ERA to 3.62 and scoring to 8.18 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when two teams were added to the NL, scoring jumped by
more than a run per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``With expansion, there's only a couple of shortstops that
weaken the field of shortstops,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``There's only a couple of first basemen that weaken
the field of first basemen. There's probably 30 to 40 pitchers that
weaken the field of pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the numbers behind the numbers suggest there's more to
it than expansion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, the AL bumped the schedule by eight games. Teams played
162 games for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, expansion was accompanied by two significant rule
changes. In response to growing dominance by pitching, the mound
was lowered and the strike zone made smaller.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, one of the new teams was the Colorado Rockies. Baseball
was played for the first time in the thin air of Denver, where
balls carry 7 percent farther than at lower altitudes. The Rockies'
team ERA of 5.41 was the worst in majors.
</P>
<P>
   For further evidence on what that does on scoring, check out the
All-Star Game on Tuesday when a record 21 runners crossed the plate
against the best pitchers in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   This season, players say there's no discernible difference in
the pitching from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much the same,'' Los Angeles Dodgers first baseman
Eric Karros said. ``I'm sure you get the people who played 30, 40
years ago and they'll tell you about how expansion has diluted the
talent and this and that. Actually, if you look at numbers per
capita, the amount of people you're drawing from has increased.
You've got a larger population in the U.S., you're drawing from
people outside the U.S. So you can argue that the talent is
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Perception and reality seem to agree. The statistics don't show
a big bump in offense this season.
</P>
<P>
   The overall batting average in the AL was .271 last year. It's
.272 this year. It was .263 in the NL in '97; it's down a point to
.262 now.
</P>
<P>
   Runs per game in the AL is up a bit from 9.86 to 10.13. It's
down in the NL from 9.35 last year to 9.14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's still as competitive as it was last year,''
Rangers designated hitter Lee Stevens said. ``On any given night,
any starting pitcher can shut you down at this level. And good
hitters are going to get their hits off anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than show a dramatic increase, the statistics show a
continuation of the recent trend toward offense.
</P>
<P>
   There was no expansion in 1994, when Matt Williams was on pace
for 61 homers, Griffey was on pace for 58, Jeff Bagwell was on
target for 55 homers and 163 RBI, and Tony Gwynn was batting .394
when the players went on strike in August.
</P>
<P>
   And there was no expansion last year, when McGwire hit a
combined 58 homers for the Oakland Athletics and the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been coming for the last three or four years,''
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``The hitters are getting bigger
and stronger and more disciplined every year. I think expansion has
something to do with it. This year, you've got 20 pitchers in the
big leagues that wouldn't be here otherwise. Every new ballpark
that's built has at least half of it that's a hitters' paradise.
All of these reasons have to do with the amount of offense we see
today.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one more reason why McGwire, Griffey and Sosa are taking
aim at Maris, and why Gonzalez is stalking Wilson. It's called
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan is a great run producer taking advantage of the
opportunities his teammates provide him and staying healthy,''
Grieve said. ``McGwire, he's been there before. Griffey has been
there before. And Sammy Sosa, that seems to be a function of a
mechanical change he made. My personal opinion is that it's a
disservice to those four guys to attribute it to expansion. I don't
think that's fair. It's not like these guys have just come out of
nowhere. All four of them, they've been there before. They've done
this before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
