<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTARS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ONLY HOME RUNS FIND THE BIG GAPS AT COORS FIELD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Coors Field is a state-of-the-art baseball facility
that makes club owners from New York to San Diego drip with envy.
</P>
<P>
   The home of the Colorado Rockies has four-star accommodations
and amenities for fans, players and the news media. It is Oriole
Park at Camden Yards with the magnificent Rocky Mountains as a
backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Coors Field is perfect, except for one little flaw. It cannot be
defended in the most literal sense. In its four-year existence,
outfielders have not figured out how to approach their defensive
play, and pitchers have not mastered the art of avoiding
embarrassment in the only major league park a mile above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   These aspects, the main reasons for the wacky existence of the
pitching-poor home team, were finally put on full display Tuesday
night when the combination of a ballpark as an offensive weapon and
the best hitters in baseball resulted in the highest-scoring
All-Star Game in history. The television ratings, according to NBC,
were smashing, too: The 13.3 national rating and 25 share were the
highest since 1995, when the game earned a 13.9/25; the estimated
38 million viewers was the highest viewing total since the 1994
game attracted 42 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   The American League, proving once again to be a little bigger
and brawnier despite the defection of Mark McGwire to the other
side, stopped the National League, 13-8. The teams, battering each
other to the delight of a Coors Field record crowd of 51,267,
scored the most runs since 1954 with the American League winning,
11-9. There were a record-tying 31 hits, including 26 singles that
broke the previous record of 26 singles. This mayhem assured
another first _ the longest All-Star Game: 3 hours 38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The thin air of the Rockies and the wide expanses of the Coors
Field outfield deprive players of two of Hall of Famer manager Earl
Weaver's rules for success _ pitching and defense _ leaving only
the three-run home-run portion of his formula in place. And that
makes Coors the most offense-friendly park in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, one of the hitting stars _ the Orioles'
Roberto Alomar _ was named the most valuable player. The second
baseman, inheriting the trophy from his brother, Sandy, the 1997
All-Star MVP, went 3 for 4, ranging from a first-inning bunt to a
seventh-inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar's performance was indicative of the American League's
well-rounded and aggressive attack, which included a two-run double
by Cal Ripken Jr., a bases-empty homer by Alex Rodriguez, a record
five stolen bases and 16 singles, which eclipsed the one-team
All-Star Game mark of 13 singles. Ivan Rodriguez had three hits _
an All-Star record for a catcher. And he played only six innings.
</P>
<P>
   When the elements allowed, defense sparkled, especially when the
Yankees' Paul O'Neill helped preserve what was then a two-run lead
by throwing out Fernando Vina when the Brewers' second baseman
tried to score from second. O'Neill's throw from his uncustomary
position of left field ended a two-run eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the park, not individual plays that left the
All-Stars exhausted and in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coors Field,'' said Rockies outfielder Dante Bichette, ``kept
its reputation, and so it should.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of the 16 All-Stars to pitch only six, including starters Greg
Maddux and David Wells, were unscored upon. Fittingly, the winning
pitcher, Bartolo Colon of the Indians, clung to victory despite
having yielded a three-run homer to the Giants' Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   What the game exposed to the world aside from the Rockies'
eternal plight at this height is that Coors is much more than a
home-run park. Yes, three home runs were hit, but the game was
decided in the gaps, between outfielders and infielders, between
outfielders and outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that makes this ballpark so tough to pitch in is
that the outfield is so big and hitters hit a lot of bloopers and
gappers,'' said Tom Glavine, the exemplary Braves' pitcher made
human when he allowed four runs in an inning and a third of relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people realize, now, it's not the home runs,'' said
Bichette. ``It's been the hits all along, the bloop single, bloop
single, then the home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gwynn: ``I know people came expecting to see six, seven
home runs and they got some, but what they saw more was the grenade
attack. It was not very pretty, but hitters love it when they get
jammed and still find a way to get a hit. And that's what happened
tonight.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
