<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GAIN, NO PAIN WITH BUD LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``So long as the owners and operators refuse to look beyond the
day and the hour; so long as clubs and individuals persist in
gaining personal headlines through public criticism of their
associates; so long as baseball people are unwilling to abide by
the rules they themselves make; so long as expediency is permitted
to replace sound judgment, there can be no satisfactory solution.''
_ Ford Frick, upon his resignation as commissioner of baseball,
1964 _ from Lords of the Realm. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you thought baseball's party reached a rousing crescendo in
Denver this week, wait'll the owners kick it into another gear
today in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   First on their list of things to do: Pop the top on a Bud Light.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the facade officially ends. Today, the owners will crown
one of their own as ``king'' of baseball, and the traditional
concept of a commissioner of the game becomes a footnote in
history.
</P>
<P>
   They're not even going to try to fool us _ or themselves _
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four years after Ford Frick, who never had nearly as much
to say while he was actually serving two terms in the
commissioner's office, became the first and only commissioner to
voluntarily walk away, the only thing that has changed is that the
wizards of Oz have come out from behind the curtain.
</P>
<P>
   They have decided to anoint fellow owner Bud Selig, a car
salesman who owns one of the weakest franchises in the game, as
``baseball commissioner.''
</P>
<P>
   They should make it easy on everybody and call him by his real
title:
</P>
<P>
   Owners' Bobo.
</P>
<P>
   Or houseboy in residence.
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   No more will they try to convince us that the commissioner
represents all of baseball _ the owners, the players, the fans _
which is a pity, because that was always good for a real belly
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Selling Bud as a neutral party, what with him standing there
with his arm elbow deep in the cookie jar, is something even
baseball owners would be hard-pressed to attempt.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a positive to come out of today's meeting, it's that
we can finally put this farce of a commissioner's search behind us,
remove the laughable five-year ``interim'' tag from in front of
Selig's name and move on _ at long last.
</P>
<P>
   That Selig would eventually emerge as the owner's man has been a
foregone conclusion for a long time. He is one of them and they
like that, of course. Plus, Bud is a deal-maker within the context
of discovering which way the wind is blowing and then leading the
charge in that direction. That makes him seem like a leader, even
when reality is that he's simply smart enough to pick the winning
side in every issue.
</P>
<P>
   Please, don't try to use Selig's radical realignment plan as
evidence that he's willing to step out and put his neck on the
line. How much realignment actually got done? One team _ his _
switched leagues and that was exactly what Bud wanted for the
Brewers. One other team, the Tigers, changed divisions. Not exactly
radical, huh? In the end, Bud waffled. It's what he does best.
</P>
<P>
   No, Bud will get the job because he's willing to take it, giving
his fellow owners a chance to focus on what they do best _ making
money. They're happy enough with his leadership by consensus.
</P>
<P>
   That it has taken so long might be a product of allowing the
specter of Selig (looking eerily like an undertaker) calling off
the 1994 World Series, to fade in the minds of fans.
</P>
<P>
   With Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr. chasing Roger
Maris' single-season home-run record, with Juan Gonzalez stalking
Hack Wilson's 67-year-old RBI mark, with youngsters like Ben Grieve
and Kerry Wood coming into the game, baseball is riding a wave of
popularity again.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague play has been a success, despite the grumbling of
prominent players like the Rangers' Will Clark, and the arrival and
success of players from South Korea and Japan have given the game a
colorful international flavor that bodes well for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Selig and CEO Paul Beeston have floated rumors that they might
even ask Paul Molitor, a longtime player rep, to become a deputy
commissioner if he retires after this season, an obvious peace
offering to the Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   They're actually talking a pretty good game. Unfortunately,
that's just business as usual for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, ultimately, is plain and simple: On a day when
we had hoped for Dom Perignon, the best baseball can give us is a
watered-down Bud Light.
</P>
<P>
   Today, for all intents and purposes, the honorable office of
commissioner of baseball officially ceases to exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2330EDT &QL; 
