<SLUG> BC-NY-NURSING-HOMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURSING HOMES HIDE REPORTS OF FLAWS, GREEN CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A five-month investigation of New York City nursing
homes found that they routinely and illegally conceal bad
inspection reports, city Public Advocate Mark Green said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state laws require nursing homes to post inspection
findings by the state Department of Health, Green said, but few do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good law that is ignored,'' he said. ``Almost nobody
knows that the law exists. One hoped-for benefit of the
investigation is that caregivers placing their parents in nursing
homes will ask for these reports and they'll know which nursing
home to best contract with.''
</P>
<P>
   Green blamed the Health Department and Gov. George Pataki for
the lack of compliance. ``Every time we investigate,'' he said,
``we find the Health Department asleep at the switch. The governor
doesn't like business regulations on HMOs, hospitals or nursing
homes. In trying not to appear antibusiness, he has become
anticonsumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Tarlton, a spokeswoman for the state Department of
Health, accused Green of obscuring the facts for political gain.
Green is running for the Democratic nomination for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've cited 28 homes in the last year for failing to
adequately display their inspection results, so it is something we
look for,'' Ms. Tarlton said. ``Mark Green, in an effort to get
publicity for his political ambitions, is continuing to present
very limited information in a dramatic way to unnecessarily alarm
the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said he sent two employees to 37 of the city's 180 nursing
homes. Of the 37, he said, 26 were rated ``deficient,'' meaning
that they had been cited for at least one deficiency in their most
recent available inspection report.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection found that 14 of the 26 homes rated deficient
either failed to post their most recent inspection report, posted
the report where residents would require assistance to review it,
or denied access to the report. Nine posted their inspection
reports legally, Green said, but either posted them so poorly _ for
instance, behind a door _ that it defeated the point of public
display, or obstructed the investigators' review of the reports in
a legal but intimidating manner by, for example, hovering over an
investigator as he read the report.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the 26 homes rated deficient posted their reports
prominently and provided prompt, polite access, according to Green.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, 10 of 11 homes with no deficiencies provided proper
posting and access, Green said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
