<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS AGREE TO TERMS WITH THREE DRAFT PICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys reduced their list of unsigned draft
picks from nine to six yesterday by reaching deals with three
players.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list was defensive lineman Michael Myers, who was
chosen in the fourth round out of Alabama. Myers agreed to a
three-year deal, worth roughly $850,000, including a $245,000
signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the fold are two seventh-round selections _ former
California running back Tarik Smith and former Georgia guard
Antonio Fleming. Both also agreed to three-year deals with
identical base salaries of $144,000 in 1998, $180,000 in '99 and
$216,000 in '00.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys vice president Jerry Jones Jr., who's handling the
Cowboys' end of negotiations for every contract except top pick
Greg Ellis, said things have gone pretty smoothly and expects to
have a few more contracts completed in the next couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he would be surprised if all of the players are not
signed by the start of training camp, July 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone pretty much how you would expect,'' said Jones,
who's gaining a larger role in the Cowboys' front office. Jones
negotiated only three contracts last year.
</P>
<P>
   One reason haggling might be at a minimum this year is the
Cowboys' $3.34 million rookie pool. Most of the rookie money will
go to Ellis, the former North Carolina defensive end who the
Cowboys chose as the eighth overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   With parameters set by last year's No. 8 pick James Farrior of
the New York Jets and this year's No. 9 pick Fred Taylor of the
Jacksonville Jaguars, Ellis is looking at a deal between $1.7
million and $1.8 million per year, including a signing bonus of
around $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Farrior got $8.846 million over five years with a $4 million
signing bonus from the Jets and Taylor received $10.7 million over
six years with a $5 million signing bonus from the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most of the other Cowboys' contracts will be for
league-minimum base salaries, leaving the agents room to negotiate
only on various bonus clauses.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Crawford, Myers' agent, said he is happy they got
everything completed so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, who was suspended for his senior season at Alabama
because of dealings with an agent, will be looked on by the Cowboys
to provide depth on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said Myers is ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a fair deal,'' Crawford said. ``He wasn't penalized for
sitting out. Mike just wants to play. He missed a whole year of
football. He just wants to get started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
