<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING OFF FOR METS NOT PRODUCTIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manager Bobby Valentine says it is an insult to his
players to question the Mets' lack of production from the leadoff
spot.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Steve Phillips points out that there are few
prototypical leadoff hitters around these days, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little question that the team's consistent
inability to score runs in the first half of the season was a major
reason why they hobbled into the All-Star Game break five games out
of the National League wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no question that the offensive weakness begins at
the top of the order, where the Mets rank 15th of 16 in the
National League in batting average (.220) and on-base percentage
(.306) and 14th in runs scored (49).
</P>
<P>
   The leadoff issue is just one of several key problems facing the
Mets as they head into the second half of this season, which begins
Thursday night at Shea Stadium against the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   There is the bullpen, which seems just as thin and unreliable as
it did a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   And there is outfielder Bernard Gilkey, who somehow seems just
as lost at the plate this season as he was last year.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there is the return of Todd Hundley, who is set to
play his first game for the Mets this season on Saturday night in
his new identity as an outfielder. During the nine months Hundley
spent recuperating from elbow surgery, the Mets went out and
acquired another power-hitting All-Star catcher, Mike Piazza, to
take Hundley's place behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Can Hundley quickly pick up where he left off as a hitter and
combine with Piazza to form a formidable one-two punch in the
middle of the Mets' batting order? Will he be sufficiently content
as an outfielder to truly embrace Piazza as the new catcher? Will
Piazza, a free agent after the season, feel comfortable enough with
the whole situation _ and with the Mets' ability to contend for a
playoff spot in coming years _ to sign a long-term deal with the
Mets? And will the Mets ultimately feel comfortable about
committing a fortune to Piazza if other holes on the team are going
to be left neglected?
</P>
<P>
   For all of these reasons, finding someone to do the job at the
top of the lineup does not appear to be the biggest issue at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scheme of things right now, the leadoff spot is a
little bit of a lesser priority,'' Phillips acknowledged just
before the All-Star break. ``The bigger thing is getting the
bullpen settled down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But with such weak numbers at the top, is it any wonder that
Piazza _ who batted third in his first 30 games with the Mets
before hitting cleanup in his last five _ had only 32 official
times at bat in his first 35 games as a Met with runners in scoring
position?
</P>
<P>
   Through their first 83 games, the Mets employed 72 different
batting orders, including 10 leadoff hitters. At the break,
according to figures compiled by the Elias Sports Bureau, the Mets'
leadoff hitters ranked 11th in the National League in extra-base
hits (22); sixth in walks (38); were tied for 10th in stolen bases
(9) and were 12th in slugging percentage (.335). They were,
however, third in runs batted in with 36.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McRae (35 games) and Edgardo Alfonzo (25) did the bulk of
the leadoff work for the Mets in the first half of the season. Even
though he batted only .234 before the break, McRae was productive
in various ways for the Mets, leading the team in extra-base hits
with 29, including a surprising 10 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   But as a leadoff hitter, McRae batted only .210, leaving him
21st out of the 21 players in the league who hit first in a minimum
of 25 games. He was 19th out of 21 in on-base percentage (.305) and
16th of 21 in slugging percentage (.364), all of which suggests
that McRae did a lot better, and hit with more power, when batting
lower in the order.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's numbers as a leadoff hitter weren't all that better.
The third baseman ranked 18th of 21 in batting average (.229); 15th
in on-base percentage (.324) and 18th in slugging percentage
(.344).
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the Mets have yet to replace the Lance Johnson of
1996, who hit .333 for the Mets in the leadoff spot, with an
astounding 227 hits. Last year, Johnson was hampered by shin
splints and missed a significant amount of time before the Mets
traded him to the Cubs last Aug. 8 as part of a deal that brought
McRae and the beleaguered Mel Rojas to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Johnson has been hurt again and has barely played for
the Cubs. Still, Valentine bristles when the leadoff issue _ and
the implication that the Mets miss Johnson _ is brought up. He
recently defended both McRae and Alfonzo as leadoff hitters,
essentially saying that McRae's production speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   As for Alfonzo, Valentine expressed exasperation in the
widespread perception that the third baseman, who batted .315 last
season and is hitting .267 this year, is better suited to hit
second. In fact, Valentine believes Alfonzo has the potential to be
a good leadoff hitter now, even if he has yet to show it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Hundley makes a big impact quickly, the leadoff
problem won't be as troublesome. And if he spends the majority of
his time in left field, he will probably be putting his best friend
on the team _ Gilkey _ on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Gilkey put together a career year, hitting .317
with 30 homers, while driving in 117 runs. Last season, though,
Gilkey hit just .249 with 18 homers and 78 runs batted in, and the
numbers would have been even worse were it not for a surge in the
final weeks of the season. And since April 25, Gilkey is just 27
for 144 (.188) with three homers and 13 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Valentine tried Gilkey in the leadoff spot last
week, perhaps as a way to get him going. But Gilkey went hitless,
doing no better than everyone else who has been batting at the top
for the Mets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
