<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS REMAIN IN RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Anaheim Angels perhaps made one mistake
en route to their place atop the American League West before the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels failed to bury the Rangers when the opportunity
presented itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were probably trying,'' Rangers first baseman Will Clark
said. ``They just couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule makes it so.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who enter the season's second half 11/2 games
behind the Angels, begin a stretch of 25 consecutive games against
the Athletics, Mariners, Orioles, Devil Rays, Royals, Twins, Blue
Jays and White Sox with this afternoon's game in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   All those with the exception of the Blue Jays enter the season's
second half with a sub-.500. record. The Rangers went 26-17 (.605)
against those eight teams before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next three weeks are very important for us,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said, ``because the next three weeks after
that, we've got 17 straight games with Boston, Cleveland and New
York. Those three teams are playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know how well you're going to play against teams,
but the next three weeks we play Oakland, Seattle, Kansas City and
Baltimore. That'll be a stretch where we don't wall to fall behind
with that tough stretch coming in August.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity existed for the Angels to begin shoveling their
first clumps of dirt on the Rangers during June. The Rangers, who
began the season 18-7, won only 17 of 40 games after May 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's baseball,'' Clark said. ``It comes and goes in cycles.
You ride it out. There's no switch you can turn on and off _ not in
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The horrendous stretch included a season-high, six-game losing
streak June 27-July 3. The Angels, though, turned their six-game
deficit into only a meager, 11/2-game advantage before the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a plus,'' Oates said. ``It could be a whole lot worse,
but I don't think there's anyone with enough pitching to run away
and hide _ well, except for the Yankees, which they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   What bodes worse for the Angels might be the manner in which the
Rangers concluded the season's first half. The Rangers enter this
afternoon's game with a modest, two-game winning streak and appear
to be cured of their defensive lapses.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers concluded the first half with a streak of three
consecutive errorless games for the first time since June 18-20
after committing 30 errors during their previous 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got away from playing the type of baseball that we're
accustomed to playing,'' second baseman Mark McLemore said. ``We're
not playing as well now as we were in May, but we can get back to
that level. We can be that good.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule should be beneficial to that cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
