<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT IN TERROR TRIAL IS SAID TO ASSAULT CO-DEFENDANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The trial of two men charged with trying to bomb a
subway station was disrupted Wednesday when, the judge said, one of
the defendants assaulted the other in a cell near the courtroom
during a recess.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators in the courtroom in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn
could not see the assault, but they could hear thumping noises and
a voice crying out, ``They're going to kill me!'' Shortly
afterward, the defendant said to have been assaulted, Lafi Khalil,
23, was returned to the courtroom by federal marshals with blood
streaming down his face.
</P>
<P>
   The jury was still in its room at that point, and was later
reported by court officials not to have been aware of the attack.
The panel was not told about the incident when Judge Reena Raggi
cut short the day's session and dismissed the jurors late Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Khalil was treated for his injuries at Long Island College
Hospital in Brooklyn and was later returned to jail. The trial was
expected to resume Thursday morning, with more bailiffs assigned to
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Raggi warned the defendant she said had committed the
assault, Ghazi Ibrahim Abu Maizar, that he would be removed from
the courtroom, and would have to watch his trial from a courthouse
cell via closed-circuit television, if he caused any disruption in
the courtroom. The judge also said the two men would be kept
separated in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, Palestinian immigrants, are accused of conspiring
to explode a powerful pipe bomb in the city subway in what
prosecutors said was a planned ``act of international terrorism.''
The prosecutors, from the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn, hold
that the men were motivated by a hatred of Israel and opposition to
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Rostal, a lawyer for Abu Maizar, told the jury when
testimony began Monday that her client had not intended to set off
the pipe bomb the police found when they raided his Park Slope,
Brooklyn, apartment last July 31, but rather that he had planned to
use it in a plot to defraud a government antiterrorism program of
money. Khalil's lawyer has not yet addressed the jury, but Khalil
told federal agents after his arrest that he had not known about
the bomb's existence.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after the incident in the cell, another lawyer for
Abu Maizar, Michael Padden, told the judge that his client had
informed him that ``this was not an unprovoked incident'' but that
`` Khalil had made some highly provocative comments'' about Abu
Maizar and his family. Other people familiar with the incident, who
spoke on the condition of anonymity, later said that the reported
remarks were threats to Abu Maizar's family should Khalil be
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Raggi made clear that she held Abu Maizar, 24,
responsible for the incident, adding _ as he sat before her without
expression at a defense table where Khalil was no longer present _
that this was ``only the latest in a string of reckless actions''
by Abu Maizar that included what she termed ``foolhardy escape
attempts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all here biting our nails for what he is going to do
next,'' she said. But she said she was rejecting a suggestion by
marshals that Abu Maizar be made to wear leg irons in court. Raggi
said it could prejudice jurors against Abu Maizar.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials have said that Abu Maizar, who faces a sentence
of up to life in prison if he is convicted, made two short-lived
escape attempts during pretrial hearings last month. In one,
officials said, he jumped onto a courtroom table but marshals
quickly tackled him. In the other, they said, he tore a section of
ceiling panels down in a courthouse cell in an apparent effort to
find a crawl space or air duct to squeeze through, but his effort
quickly ended when a ceiling support collapsed after he grabbed it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, according to Marshal Daniel Byrne, on Monday _ as
Abu Maizar was being led to the discharge area of the Manhattan
jail where he is being held, in preparation for being brought to
court for his trial _ he managed to slip one hand out of his
handcuffs. When asked why he did this ``right before the eyes of
authority,'' the marshal wrote in a letter to Judge Raggi, Abu
Maizar ``replied that nothing could hold him for long.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
