<SLUG> BC-THREE-STRIKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIEF'S LEGAL MOVE BACKFIRES, `STRIKES' COSTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEX ROTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Of all the mistakes Andre Terial Wilks has made in
his young life, perhaps the biggest was refusing to accept a
seven-year prison sentence for stealing a cell phone from a car.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the 19-year-old Los Angeles man man suffered the
consequences in a case that troubled the judge and prosecutors
alike: Instead of seven years for the theft, he'll serve 25 to life
under the ``three strikes, you're out'' law.
</P>
<P>
   The judge imposed the life sentence in April but took the rare
step Wednesday of bringing Wilks back to court to reconsider her
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager apologized to the judge and begged for leniency.
It was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Shari K. Silver in neighborning San
Fernando let the life sentence stand, saying that she couldn't find
mercy _ only ``frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't see the light at the time,'' the judge told Wilks.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the Wilks case is a classic example of a
defendant acting as his own worst enemy. They said he could have
avoided a life sentence had he listened to his lawyer or mother or
uncle or the judge. Even when his attorney _ in a rare move _
allowed the prosecutor to speak with him, Wilks ignored the advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the head of a brick wall,'' Los Angeles County Deputy
District Attorney Jacquelyn Lacey said after the court hearing. ``I
felt that I perhaps could reach this particular defendant. I have a
son who is almost his age.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wilks' attorneys, the fault lies with the criminal justice
system _ not Wilks. They argue, their teen-age client shouldn't
serve a life sentence under the ``three strikes'' law for crimes he
committed as a juvenile. The 1994 law mandates a 25-to-life
sentence for a third serious felony conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad truth is that the criminal justice system has failed
to do the right thing in Mr. Wilks' case,'' said his lawyer, Deputy
Public Defender Richard Petherbridge.
</P>
<P>
   The judge could have reduced the sentence by expunging one of
his two prior convictions for a purse-snatching spree committed a
week after he turned 16. Prosecutors say Wilks and a friend were
armed with a gun during the spree. Wilks' attorney says Wilks'
friend had the gun _ which might have been fake _ and no one was
assaulted or hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Given these facts, the judge refused to drop either conviction.
</P>
<P>
   She also noted that Wilks, a high-school dropout, chose to take
the case to trial even though everyone ``begged'' him to take the
plea bargain. Indeed, during one pre-trial hearing the judge
actually stepped down from the bench to have a personal chat with
the defendant _ another exceptionally rare move.
</P>
<P>
   Wilks' latest brush with the law occurred in September 1997 when
he and a 12-year-old friend were charged with breaking a car window
and taking a cell phone. Wilks' friend testified against him at
trial, saying they'd burglarized a house earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
   While talking with Wilks before the trial, the prosecutor
explained to Wilks that he risked a life sentence if convicted at
trial. She also explained that her case was a solid one.
</P>
<P>
   Her advice fell on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said the District Attorney's Office has since decided that
Wilks deserves a life sentence for reasons including that he showed
no remorse. Worse, he took the witness stand and perjured himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' she said, ``he has earned his life
sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilks' mother said his hard-headed attitude is just another sign
of his immaturity _ evidence that he's too young to understand the
consequence of his self-destructive legal strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people doing attempted murders who don't get that
much time,'' said his mother, Pamela Brown, 41, an unemployed
telemarketer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
