<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKBROKERS-PRICEFIXING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC SAID TO BE ACTING ON POSSIBLE PRICE-FIXING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Securities and Exchange Commission, completing an
extensive investigation into possible price-fixing on the Nasdaq
stock market, is now negotiating settlements with _ and preparing
possible sanctions against _ several stock traders and as many as
two dozen brokerage firms, executives at several Wall Street firms
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The executives, who spoke on condition that neither they nor
their firms would be identified by name, said the commission _
using information culled from trading room audio tapes _ appeared
to be focusing on many of the same 24 brokerage firms that in July
1996 settled a civil antitrust suit that accused them of colluding
to inflate profits from trading shares on the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, according to the executives, is weighing
proposed fines against many individual traders that range from
several thousand dollars up to many million dollars. Their firms
may also be subject to SEC sanctions. The amount of the proposed
fines relates to the amount of evidence found on recorded tapes
that the SEC subpoenaed as part of its investigation, the
executives said. Brokerage firms routinely tape the conversations
of their traders to prevent disputes about transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to have gone through the tapes and have an arbitrary
number of people acting,'' said a senior official at one firm
Wednesday. ``They have some formula of amount per offense.'' The
SEC, this executive said, has listened to tapes and found a
specific number of instances in which, in effect, collusion on
prices took place.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the SEC and for several major brokerage firms,
including Goldman, Sachs, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Paine Webber,
Salomon Smith Barney, Warburg Dillon Read LLC, all declined to
comment on the issue Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been investigating price-fixing on the Nasdaq
stock market since the summer of 1994, when a study by two
professors _ William Christie of Vanderbilt University and Paul
Schulz of Ohio State University _ argued that brokerage firms had
colluded to raise their profit margins from their trading on the
Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC subsequently investigated the National Association of
Securities Dealers, which operates the Nasdaq market. In August
1996, the SEC censured the NASD for its failure to regulate the
market adequately, prompting the NASD to overhaul the way it
regulates the Nasdaq market, and spend tens of millions of dollars
to reorganize its regulation of the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   A class-action lawsuit brought against more than 30 brokerage
firms on behalf of investors who traded shares on the Nasdaq market
has also resulted in a number of settlements with individual
brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   The suit charged collusion and price-fixing. Herzog, Heine &AMP;
Geduld Inc., for example, in June 1997 agreed to pay investors
$30.6 million to its part of that case. The suit contended that the
firms colluded in trading spreads artificially wide in securities
trading on the Nasdaq market in the years between May 1989 and May
1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-98 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980708.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT &LR;      07-08 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CONVICTED OF DOUBLE MURDER MAY FACE EXECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLAUDIA ROWE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Dalkeith McIntosh, an indigent 38-year-old
Jamaican immigrant, was convicted Wednesday of murdering two women,
making it possible that he could be the state's second man awaiting
death.
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating for 14 hours over three days, the jury found
that after a domestic quarrel, McIntosh gunned down his estranged
wife, Francine Williams, 47, and her 23-year-old daughter, Eunice,
in the summer of 1996 as they sat in a car here.
</P>
<P>
   The eight men and four women on the jury also found that he had
shot a 6-year-old boy, Anthony Williams, whom he had raised as a
son, but the child survived and eventually testified against him.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 1995 capital-punishment law provides for death in a
case that meets any of certain criteria, and prosecutors said
McIntosh's case met more than one.
</P>
<P>
   He was accused of multiple first-degree murders, and he was
convicted of killing one person to keep her from being a witness
against him. The law also provides for death in particularly
heinous crimes, and the presence of the child was considered such a
factor, though the prosecution has not emphasized it.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the trial will enter the penalty phase, involving a
decision on either death by lethal injection or life in prison.
McIntosh's lawyer, William Tendy, will begin pleading for his life
by presenting witnesses to testify about his character and
background growing up in Jamaica.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like jurors in the Brooklyn trial of Darrel Harris, who
deliberated for 11 hours over two days before convicting of him of
capital murder, the jury worked with surprising speed, sometimes
deliberating through meals, before delivering their verdict to
Dutchess County Court Judge George Marlow at about 12:30 p.m. One
juror, a young woman, left the courtroom later, visibly distraught.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors had spent the last four weeks listening to often
emotional testimony. Wednesday, the small fourth-floor courtroom
was silent and McIntosh stared straight ahead without registering
emotion as the foreman foreman tolled off guilty verdicts to all 10
counts in the indictment. McIntosh sat motionless, seemingly numb,
as his lawyer tried to comfort him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very, very upset,'' Tendy said of McIntosh later. ``We
will spend a lot of time in the next few days talking to him.
That's really all we can do right now.''
</P>
<P>
   On one count, the jurors found McIntosh guilty of second-degree
murder, not first-degree, because they did not believe the
prosecution had proved that he killed his wife, Francine, to
prevent her from testifying against him in a pending assault case.
They did, however, believe that he had killed Eunice Williams to
eliminate her as a witness to the slaying of his wife.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visibly crushed by the guilty verdict, Tendy said he had let his
client down and doubted whether he would ever undertake another
defense in a capital case. ``I don't think I could ever go through
this again,'' he said. ``If I hadn't let him down then we wouldn't
have the verdict we have right now. This was my responsibility. If
somebody's got to be blamed, it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   During a month of testimony from 52 witnesses, Tendy had pointed
out many reasons that might cause a jury to doubt McIntosh's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   There were no fingerprints on the gun presented as the murder
weapon, and no way to connect it definitively to the defendant or
the shootings. Nor was there a drop of blood on McIntosh's skin or
clothes when he was caught by police, although all three victims
were shot at point blank range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed of the verdict in this case is simply a reflection
of the strength of the evidence,'' said Dutchess County District
Attorney William Grady. ``But I will not say I'm not surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The key, said the district attorney, had been Anthony Williams.
Now 8, the only surviving witness to the slayings had testified for
an hour. He said he had been in the car, watching as ``Keith'' shot
his grandmother, Francine, in the head. The small boy testified
that the man whom he often called ``Daddy'' had then turned the gun
on him, shooting him in the mouth, then shot Anthony's aunt, Eunice
Williams, in the head, and fled.
</P>
<P>
   All these grisly details he recounted with chilling calm to
jurors. Finally the boy pointed at McIntosh when asked who had
committed the murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony Williams is the only eyewitness and he provided the
jury with firsthand testimony,'' Grady said. ``We cannot
overemphasize the significant role that he played.''
</P>
<P>
   In the penalty phase, Tendy would not say which of McIntosh's
relatives would testify. He has two young children and other
relatives still living in Jamaica, as well as a sister in Texas.
Tendy would only say that he would use them to try to show ``what
this man's life was, so that they see him as a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Trial testimony established that McIntosh came to the United
States in the late 1980s, did not have a regular job, and had been
found in possession of marijuana. ``Who cares about a poor, black
Jamaican immigrant,'' Tendy said to the all-white jury in his
closing statement. ``You know what the answer is _ nobody, and
that's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to show that his client was poor, Tendy said, ``He's
buying nickel bags for 40 bucks, he's got $10 in his pocket, he's
riding around on a bicycle, and he's living in a flea-bag with a
mattress on the floor.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
