<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-WOMAN-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY SOCIALITE SIGNED PAPERS BEFORE SHE VANISHED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Several days before socialite Irene Silverman
disappeared on Sunday, she met with a convicted felon who was
renting a room in her lavish town house and signed financial
documents in the presence of a notary public, police investigators
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While police did not have detailed information about the
documents, a law enforcement official who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said the meeting could provide a clue about Ms.
Silverman's disappearance and a possible motive for foul play.
</P>
<P>
   Since the meeting at Ms. Silverman's home on Manhattan's East
Side, her servants saw her arguing with the same tenant, detectives
said, and she threatened to evict the man from the $6,000-a-month
suite he had rented since June 14.
</P>
<P>
   In notes Ms. Silverman kept about the guests in her house, she
wrote extensively about the tenant, who identified himself as Manny
Guerin, but who has been identified by police as Kenneth Kimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust him,'' Ms. Silverman wrote, according to the
investigator who reviewed the papers. ``He seems suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   The notary public who was at the meeting was interviewed
Wednesday but told police that Ms. Silverman did not read the
documents and had no idea what the meeting was about, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting and Ms. Silverman's notes on her tenants were the
focus of a sprawling investigation Wednesday, as a team of 50
detectives searched unsuccessfully for signs of her whereabouts.
Meanwhile, federal agents and Los Angeles investigators began
comparing notes with New York detectives, attempting to solve a
case with possible ties to a mother and son team of convicted
felons and the unsolved murder of a California man.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Kimes, 23, who was arrested with his mother, Sante,
Sunday night on an unrelated fraud charge, was carrying several
pieces of Ms. Silverman's identification, including her passport.
</P>
<P>
   Sante Kimes, 63, has a long criminal history, including
convictions for fraud, using fake credit cards, stealing a mink
coat and enslaving Mexican immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But the pair was arrested by federal agents late Sunday because
they are named in a Utah warrant for allegedly using a bad check to
purchase a $14,000 Lincoln Town Car.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses have refused to answer questions about Ms.
Silverman, leaving the authorities to speculate on why they were
carrying the identification of a woman whose wealth allowed her to
employ a staff of 10 domestic servants.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes is scheduled to appear in court Thursday for a bail
hearing. His lawyer, Matthew Weissman, declined to discuss the
charges against his client.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles detectives, who are scheduled to arrive in New York
on Friday, said they wanted to question the Kimeses about the March
14 murder of a Granada Hills, Calif., man whose financial assets
were stolen after his death.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We're going to meet with the New York detectives to look for
any similarities between the cases,'' Lt. Otis Dobine of the Los
Angeles Police Department said. ``We'd want to compare notes about
these people and go there to look into their possible involvement
in what happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Silverman's case is still classified as a missing
persons investigation, her friends said Wednesday that they were
deeply concerned for her safety. The police found a small trail of
blood on the sidewalk of her home Sunday, but when detectives began
executing a search warrant Wednesday on the Kimeses' green Lincoln
Town Car, they found no evidence to lead them to Ms. Silverman, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives have also searched an assortment of city parks,
vacant lots and garbage dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles detectives and federal agents were still trying
Wednesday to track the Kimeses' trail from their home in Southern
California to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Ms. Kimes and her husband, Kenneth Kimes
Sr., owned a chain of motels and kept homes in La Jolla, Calif.,
Las Vegas, Honolulu and Cancun, Mexico. But in recent years the
family had fallen on hard times, another investigator speaking on
the condition of anonymity said, and FBI officials began searching
for the Kimeses early this year after receiving complaints that
they were involved in a financial swindle in Las Vegas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
