</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSEANNE-TALK-HOST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSEANNE TO TAKE ON DAYTIME TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Roseanne, the one-time queen of blue-collar
comedy, has shed a few dozen pounds, several inches of hair and
some of her trademark trashiness in preparation for her return to
television _ as a daytime talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   The comedian turned star-executive producer of ABC's sitcom hit
``Roseanne'' shared sketchy plans Wednesday for her latest project,
``The Roseanne Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles audiences can expect the syndicated show to debut on
KNBC-TV (Channel 4) on Sept. 14. While no time slot has been set
yet, it likely will air late weekday mornings against established
talkies like ``Live with Regis and Kathie Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roseanne who stepped before the microphones at the
Television Critics Association's biannual press tour at the
Ritz-Carlton Huntington hotel in Pasadena, neighboring Los Angeles,
was a sleeker and quite possibly meeker model of the loudmouthed
housewife television audiences learned to love.
</P>
<P>
   She said she'll no longer micromanage the writers' room as she
did during the run of her sitcom. Her private life will not be
available for public consumption as it had been during much of the
past decade. And bawdy, off-key renditions of the national anthem
seem to be behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of over that,'' Roseanne said. ``A lot of television
shows have shown us how low we can go. I'd like to go the opposite
way and see how high we can go.''
</P>
<P>
   The show that's being co-produced and distributed by King World,
which is also behind Oprah Winfrey's show, has been in conception
for more than a year but has not begun taping at CBS Television
City in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Roseanne will open with a monologue, playing off people in the
studio audience like she did as a standup comic. She'll spend time
during the show discussing important topics such as rearing
children and women's weight issues. And she plans to lighten up by
playing recurring characters in comedy sketches.
</P>
<P>
   The show will be more star-driven than ``Oprah,'' more
controversial than ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show,'' and less
outrageous than ``The Jerry Springer Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do want to reinvent the wheel a little bit,'' said
executive producer Eddie October, ``but we're not deluding
ourselves about the fact that this is a talk show.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is will daytime audiences accustomed to the
softball humor of Regis Philbin and Rosie embrace Roseanne, a woman
better known for crass antics?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people who watch the talk show will be surprised how
learned she is and how well-versed she is in many topics,'' said
comedian-writer Ritch Shydner, who wrote for ``Roseanne'' in 1995
and 1996. ``She has an incredibly agile mind. She could talk to a
street person and have a conversation and talk to a politician and
have a conversation. She is earthy. I don't think she's gonna be a
female Dick Cavett.''
</P>
<P>
   But image consultant Jennifer Maxwell Parkinson of New York's
Look Consulting International says it'll take work to erase
tabloid-generated perceptions _ true or not _ that she is
everything from a schizophrenic to a tyrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can still use her cutting humor, but she has to focus on
sincerity,'' Parkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   There are some simple fixes Roseanne can use to repair her
public image, said Anne Warfield of Impression Management
Professionals in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell her to wear softer suits and wear her hair softer
and not laugh as hard,'' Warfield said. ``She should lean into the
people to look more interested and have a connectiveness so she
would almost be a backdrop. Now she is in the forefront.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Roseanne needs lessons on how to succeed in show
business.
</P>
<P>
   She garnered large TV audiences, well beyond that of the
successful Springer, with her working-class sensibility. Her
self-titled sitcom had a strong run for its nine years on the air,
ranking in the top 10 for seven seasons from 1988 to 1995. It was
especially strong in delivering women viewers, the target of
daytime talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that her name has huge recognition,'' said Carol
Black, the general manager of KNBC. ``I think there's a huge and
diverse viewing audience that will relate to her and a huge
audience interested in tuning in to see what her show is like.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if you want any more details about her latest endeavor,
Roseanne will tell you herself: ``We're gonna do multiple topics
and it's gonna be a lot of comedy. It's kind of a little bit of
everything. We'll have a little bit like `Oprah' and a little like
`Rosie' and we'll have a little bit like blah, blah, blah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
