<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON MAJORS CIRCUIT, NICKLAUS CALLS IT QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending one of the most remarkable streaks in golf history, Jack
Nicklaus announced Wednesday that he would not play in the year's
final two majors, the British Open next week and the PGA
Championship in August.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to 1957, Nicklaus has played in the last 154
consecutive majors for which he was eligible, the longest streak of
that nature. He did not join the PGA Tour until 1962, so he was not
eligible to compete in the PGA Championship until that year, and he
did not play in the British Open until 1962. But Nicklaus has not
missed a major since the 1962 Masters, a streak of 146.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, who turned 58 in January, said a sore left hip,
coupled with a sense that the time was right, contributed to his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to end the streak by having it said that Jack
Nicklaus could no longer play the game,'' Nicklaus said in a
statement issued by his Golden Bear International Inc. ``Instead, I
wanted to step back with the feeling that the competitive spirit
and ability still thrived within me. I wanted to end the streak on
my own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to end that streak at 153 at this year's Masters,
until the USGA kindly gave me an exemption to play in the U.S.
Open. However, I feel the the preparation time and physical demands
which are required to be competitive on a continuous basis are
difficult for me to satisfy at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Nicklaus' decision to end the streak was somewhat
unexpected because of his inspirational performance at this year's
Masters, when he tied for sixth, making him the oldest top-10
finisher in Masters history. Nicklaus also enjoyed a respectable
showing at the U.S. Open last month, when he made the cut and tied
for 43rd.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus has won a record 18 majors: six Masters, five PGA
Championships, four U.S. Opens, and three British Opens. He also
won two U.S. Amateur championships and finished second in majors 19
times.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been better at playing his best golf in the biggest
tournaments. Whether it meant arriving at the site of a major
earlier than everyone else, or taking time off before a major to
rest and work on his game, Nicklaus mastered the art of peaking at
the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his greatest performance came at the 1986 Masters, when,
at age 46, he became the oldest winner of that storied event. But
Nicklaus has not won on the PGA Tour since, and it has become
harder for him to put together four consistent rounds good enough
to beat players 20 and 30 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that my ability to compete at the highest level is
marginal at best,'' Nicklaus said. ``As much as I enjoy playing and
competing in the world's major championships, I feel that it is
time to end my streak.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus will compete on the Senior PGA Tour at this week's Ford
Senior Players Championship, and will also play in the U.S. Senior
Open later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nicklaus will retain lifetime exemptions for the
Masters and the PGA Championship and an exemption into the British
Open until age 65.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
